\key 1.1.1
\title Yoke
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מוֹט, מוֹטָה
\trl mot, motah
\ref H00302601300032 H02305800600022 H02305800600036 H02305800900028 H02402700200018 H02402801000016 H02402801200028 H02402801300022 H02402801300034 H02603001800022 H02603402700054 H03400101300008
\heb עֹל
\trl ‘ol
\ref H00102704000032 H00302601300034 H00401900200056 H00502100300054 H00502804800046 H00900600700034 H01101200400008 H01101200400032 H01101201100012 H01101201100024 H01101201400026 H01101201400036 H01401000400008 H01401000400030 H01401001100012 H01401001100024 H01401001400024 H02300900300006 H02301002700028 H02301002700040 H02301402500028 H02304700600034 H02400202000010 H02400500500040 H02402700800048 H02402701100018 H02402701200038 H02402800200022 H02402800400056 H02402801100034 H02402801400016 H02403000800024 H02500101400004 H02500302700014 H02603402700056 H02801100400026
\grk βοοζύγιον
\trl boozugion
\ref L07102600700002
\grk ἑτεροζυγέω
\trl heterozugeō
\ref G04700601400006
\grk κλοιός
\trl kloios
\ref L07100602400026 L07100602900022
\grk ζυγός
\trl zugos
\ref G04001102900006 G04001103000006 G04401501000016 G04800500100022 G05400600100008 L07102102500020 L07102801900034 L07102802000006 L07102802000010 L07102802500012 L07103302700002 L07104000100014 L07104200400006 L07105102600012 L07700801800010 L07700803100038 L07701304100014 L07900400900022 L08600700900008 L08601703000018
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0021_yokedoxen.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Oxen wearing a yoke|1.0\fig* The yoke was a bar or frame of wood by which two draft animals were joined at the neck so that they could work together effectively in pulling a plow, threshing board, harrow, or wagon. A similar device was used on human beings, but then it was usually a single harness, not the double one used for animals.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The yoke was secured to the necks of the animals by means of a kind of collar made of wood, cane, or rope. The center of the yoke was attached, by means of a rope or a bar, to the object to be drawn. The animals pulled together, side by side. A yoke was sometimes placed on a human being who had been taken captive (\s H02402801000016\s*) or made a slave, to restrict movement or to prevent escape. \fig |WEB-0316_slaves_in_yokes.jpg|col||© Osama Shukir Muhammed Amin FRCP(Glasg) (Wikimedia Commons)|Slaves in yokes|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where the yoking of draft animals is unknown or unfamiliar, in \s H00401900200056\s* (and similarly for \s H00502100300054\s*) translators may follow \a GNT\a*, which renders the literal text “on which a yoke has never been placed” as “which has never been worked.”
\line Always in the New Testament and frequently in the Old Testament, “yoke” appears in figurative contexts. It then becomes a symbol of the subjection and servitude of slaves. In such cases (for example, \s H00302601300034\s*; \s H02301002700028\s*; \s H02402800200022\s*, \s H02402801400016\s*; \s H02403000800024\s*; \s H02603402700056\s*; \s H03400101300012\s*; \s G04401501000016\s*; \s G04800500100022\s*; \s G05400600100008\s*), translators may avoid the literal meaning and translate the figurative sense (\s H00302601300034\s*: “. . . I broke the power that held you down . . .” [\a GNT\a*]). Similarly, in \s L07104000100014\s* \a GNT\a* has “. . . A heavy burden lies on all of us . . . .”
\line For the possible reference to a yoke at \s H02500500500004\s*, see the comments in \i A Handbook on Lamentations\i*, page 134.
\line In \s L07103302700002\s* a yoke is associated with the wearing of a special “harness” or “collar.” This was a device of rope, leather, cane, or wood worn around the neck. The yoke was attached to it. Since it is associated in this verse with control of the animal’s movements, the Italian common language translation (\a ITCL\a*) renders the word as “reins.” The use of \i kloios\i* in \s L07100602400026 L07100602900022\s* is symbolic. In many languages it will be possible to retain the reference to chains and the yoke. However, where a language does not permit such usage, we may say something like “Let all of your actions be ruled by Wisdom” (verse 24) and “If you allow Wisdom to rule you, you will be kept safe, and you will be in control of what happens to you” (verse 29).
\key 1.1.2
\title Goad
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb דָּרְבָן
\trl darvan
\ref H00901302100050 H02101201100010
\heb מַלְמַד
\trl malmad
\ref H00700303100030
\grk κέντρον
\trl kentron
\ref G04402601400048 L07103802500020 L08001401900034 L08601600400008
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0389_goad_oxen_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Goad|1.0\fig* The goad was a stick, sometimes tipped with a metal point (\i darvan\i*), used in driving draft animals or herds of domestic animals, such as sheep. The goad had to be long enough to reach the animal from the driver’s position, thus 1-2 meters (3-6 feet).
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The driver of a cart or other load stuck the point of the goad into the buttocks of an animal that was not pulling hard enough or in the right direction. The pain stimulus caused the animal to move or change direction.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where draft animals are not known, “a goad” in \s H00700303100030\s* may be translated “a pointed stick” or “a rod with a sharp metal point.” \s H02101201100010\s* may be expanded as follows: “The sayings of the wise are like the sharp sticks that shepherds use to guide sheep . . .” (\a GNT\a*; similarly the German common language translation [\a GECL\a*]) or “The words of experienced men are like goads that stimulate the spirit . . .” (French common language translation [\a FRCL\a*]). Another possible rendering is “The words of wise men are sharp and pointed . . .” (Dutch common language translation [\a DUCL\a*]).
\line \s G04402601400048\s*: This is the only place in the New Testament where the word goad occurs. It is in the phrase “to kick against the goads” (\a RSV\a*), meaning to react against authority in such a way as to cause harm or suffering to yourself -- to hurt yourself by reacting against a person or command. An alternative rendering for the last half of this verse is “Saul, why are you persecuting me? You are hurting yourself by your resistance.”
\line In \s L07103802500020\s* the activity of the worker is in focus, so it is unnecessary to find a word to translate this object; for example, \a GNT\a* has “How can a farm hand gain knowledge, when his only ambition is to drive the oxen and make them work . . . ?” Another possibility is “. . . to get the oxen to move when they want to stop pulling . . . ?”
\key 1.1.3
\title Whip, scourge
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שׁוֹט, שֹׁטֵט
\trl shot, shotet
\ref H00602301300056 H01101201100036 H01101201400048 H01401001100036 H01401001400044 H01800502100004 H01800902300004 H02002600300002 H02301002600012 H02302801500026 H02302801800024 H03400300200004
\grk μαστιγόω, μαστίζω, μάστιξ
\trl mastigoō (verb), mastizō (verb), mastix
\ref G04001001700032 G04002001900020 G04002303400042 G04101003400016 G04201803300004 G04301900100018 G04402202400020 G04402202500042 G05801103600010 G05801200600012 L06701301600014 L06800802700036 L07000501100024 L07001202200018 L07001601600020 L07103001400020 L07102300200014 L07102301100024 L07102600600020 L07102801700004 L07103000100014 L07103902800024 L07104000900026 L07102200600012 L07800302600050 L07800303400010 L07800303800024 L07800501800052 L07800603000056 L07900202100042 L07800700100040 L07800703700056 L07800901100030 L08000600300008 L08000600600020 L08000901200010 L08600700900018 L08601000100030 L08601000200010
\grk φραγέλλιον, φραγελλόω
\trl fragellion, fragelloō (verb)
\ref G04002702600018 G04101501500036 G04300201500006
\lat flagellum
\ref V08201602000000 V08201602100000
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0390_whip_man.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man with a whip|1.0\fig* The whip was an instrument consisting of either a single or multiple thongs with or without weighted tips on the ends. The thongs were usually leather, and the weighted tips would normally have been made of metal in order to increase the force of the blow and to inflict more severe punishment.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line When the whip was used on draft animals, it was intended to cause them to move faster. This was done either by striking the animal with the whip or by flicking the whip so that the end of it made a cracking sound, frightening the animal. The whip used on animals was normally without the weighted tips. When the whip was used on human beings, it was for punishment (see \s H00502500201000 H00502500301000\s*).\fig |WEB-0317_soldier_with_whip.jpg|col||© Johnbod|Soldier with a whip|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where the word “whip” or “scourge” is used figuratively, it will usually be possible to preserve the meaning without keeping the figure. For example, for the literal clause “You shall be hid from the scourge of the tongue” (\s H01800502100004\s* in \a RSV\a*), \a GNT\a* has “God will rescue you from slander.”
\line \s H02002600300002\s*: For the literal phrase “A whip for the horse” (\a RSV\a*), it may be better to use a verb to describe the action; for example, \a GNT\a* says “You have to whip a horse.”
\key 1.1.4
\title Muzzle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חסם
\trl chasam (verb)
\ref H00502500400004
\heb מַחְסוֹם
\trl machsom
\ref H01903900200022
\grk φιμός
\trl fimos
\ref L07102002900018
\grk φιμόω
\trl fimoō (verb)
\ref G05400501800016 L07500106000064 L08000103500026
\grk κημόω
\trl kēmoō (verb)
\ref G04600900900016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0318_muzzle.jpg|col||Matson Collection, Library of Congress|Muzzle|1.0\fig* The muzzle was a guard placed over or around the mouth of an animal to prevent it from biting or eating. It was made of rope or leather strips formed into a loose mesh; this allowed the animal to breathe while preventing it from getting anything into its mouth.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The two New Testament references are quotations from \s H00502500400004\s* (where \s G05400501800010\s* follows the Septuagint and \s G04600900900014\s* uses an equivalent verb). In some languages it may be necessary to use some kind of descriptive equivalent of “to muzzle an ox,” for example, “to tie the mouth of an ox so that it cannot eat” or “to cover the mouth of an ox so that it cannot eat.” In \s H01903900200022\s* the literal text “I will guard my mouth with a muzzle” may be rendered “I will keep silent” (compare \a GNT\a* “I will not say anything”).
\key 1.1.5
\title Plow and plowshare
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֵת
\trl ’eth
\ref H00901302000020 H00901302100024 H02300200400030 H02900401000004 H03300400300034
\heb חרשׁ
\trl charash (verb)
\ref H00502201000004 H00701401800060 H00900801200024 H01101901900026 H01800101400022 H01800400800008 H01912900300006 H01912900300008 H02002000400010 H02302802400010 H02302802400014 H02402601800052 H02801001100032 H02801001300002 H03000601200016 H03000901300016 H03300301200012
\grk ἀροτριάω
\trl arotriaō (verb)
\ref G04201700700014 G04600901000030 G04600901000032 L07100601900006 L07100701200004
\grk ἄροτρον
\trl arotron
\ref G04200906200024 L07103802500010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0319_plowing_en.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Egyptian model of a man plowing|1.0\fig*The plow consisted of a flat triangular blade (the “plowshare”) made of hard wood or metal, connected to a handle. In another design the plowshare was a wooden bar covered with a cylindrical, pointed metal sleeve. Ropes or a wooden pole attached to the handle were connected to the yoke and pulled by one or more animals.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The plow was used to cut the soil in preparation for the sowing of seed or the planting of seedlings. (The soil might also be plowed again after the seed was scattered, in order to cover the seed and protect it from the birds and from the sun.) The point of the plowshare cut a shallow furrow in the earth. Plows did not turn over the soil but were used simply to break the surface, seldom to a depth of more than 25 centimeters (10 inches). A man could pull the plow, but more often it was pulled by either oxen or donkeys, while a man walked behind and directed the animals and held the plow in its proper line and depth in the soil.
\line Some have suggested that an \i ’eth\i* was a kind of sharp instrument that was used to cut the soil prior to the actual plowing.\fig |UBS-0005_plow.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Plow|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In most parts of the world at least some type of plow is known. Where a plow is unknown, translators may use the name of a tool used for the same kind of agricultural work, such as “hoe.” This will not be possible where the text refers to plowing with animals (for example, \s H00502201000004\s*; \s H01101901900026\s*). \i ’Eth\i* refers to the physical similarity of the plowshare and the sword in \s H02300200400030 H02900401000004\s*; and \s H03300400300034\s*. Where plows are unknown, in these passages translators may substitute some other farming tool, which could reasonably be formed from a sword or machete or cutlass.
\line The Hebrew verb \i charash\i* is used figuratively in several passages. In \s H02402601800052\s* and \s H03300301200012\s* it speaks of the total destruction of Jerusalem, and in \s H01800400800008\s* and \s H02801001300002\s* it expresses the idea that doing an evil deed will bring an evil result. For the figurative use of plowing in \s H01912900300006\s*, see \i A Handbook on Psalms\i*, page 1080.
\key 1.1.6
\title Sickle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶרְמֵשׁ
\trl chermesh
\ref H00501600900014 H00502302600024
\heb מַגָּל
\trl magal
\ref H02405001600014 H02900401300004
\grk δρέπανον
\trl drepanon
\ref G04100402900090 G06601401400270 G06601401500190 G06601401600090 G06601401700150 G06601401800210 G06601401800280 G06601401900060
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0320_cutting_grain_sickle.jpg|col||The Pictorial New Testament, 1881|Man cutting grain with a sickle|1.0\fig* The sickle was a large, curved knife used for cutting ripe grain. It had a short wooden handle (15-20 centimeters, 6-8 inches).
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The implement was swung in a circular motion close to the ground, cutting off the grass or grain. Using the sickle required bending over in order to cut close to the ground, while the longer handle of the scythe allowed the worker to stand erect (see also \l target="REALIA:2.15.1">2.15.1 Scythe (chariot weapon)\l*).\fig |WEB-0321_sickle.jpg|col||© Juan R. Lascorz|Sickle|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where there is no receptor-language term for “sickle,” translators may often use a descriptive phrase, such as “curved knife for cutting grain,” “reaping hook,” or “machete for reaping.” In \s G06601400000000\s* the word sickle is used in idiomatic expressions that could be confusing to the reader. For example, in \s G06601401500190\s*, rather than the literal “Put in your sickle, and reap” (\a RSV\a*), it may be clearer to say “Use your sickle and reap the harvest” (\a GNT\a*). The long-handled scythe was unknown in ancient Israel. Where a translator must choose between a short-handled implement and a long-handled one, the former will be more accurate.
\key 1.1.7
\title Sheaf
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֲלֻמָּה
\trl ’alumah
\ref H00103700700010 H00103700700026 H00103700700040 H00103700700048 H01912600600028
\heb עָמִיר
\trl ‘amir
\ref H02400902100036 H03000201300026 H03300401200030 H03801200600040
\heb עמר
\trl ‘imer (verb)
\ref H01912900700016
\heb עֹמֶר
\trl ‘omer
\ref H00302301200016 H00302301500024 H00502401900016 H00800200700018 H00800201500030 H01802401000016
\grk δράγμα
\trl dragma
\ref L06800800300014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0100_sheaf.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Sheaves standing in a field|1.0\fig* The sheaf was a bundle made by binding together the stalks and ears of a crop that had been harvested. The binding was most often done with stalks of the grain itself.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Grain was harvested by cutting the stalks low to the ground with a sickle (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.6">1.1.6 Sickle\l*) or even by pulling them up by hand. The stalks were then gathered into bundles and tied together around the middle, making a sheaf. If the sheaves were not collected immediately, they could be left in the field in a standing position to keep the heads of grain off the damp ground. After the sheaves were collected, they were taken to the threshing floor (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.1">1.1.8.1 Threshing floor\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line For the word “sheaf,” translators may use a descriptive phrase, such as “bundle of harvested grain.” In some cultures the practice of tying grain into bundles is unknown. Some languages may have to say something like “bunch of grain you tie together.” In some cases it will be necessary to specify what kind of grain is involved. It may be possible to render “sheaf” in a more general sense as “harvest” (so \a GNT\a* in \s H01912600600028\s*; compare \a GNT\a* in \s H01802401000016\s*, where it has “wheat”) or even “grain” (so \a GNT\a* in \s H03000201300026\s* and \s H03300401200030\s*). Another passage where \a GNT\a* renders “sheaf” in a broader sense is \s L06800800300014\s*. The literal \a RSV\a* text has “as he stood overseeing the men who were binding sheaves in the field,” but \a GNT\a* says “while in the fields supervising the farm workers.”
\line The Hebrew words \i ‘amir\i* and \i ‘omer\i* actually indicate a heap of many sheaves gathered at the edge of the field before being transported to the threshing floor, so the focus of \s H03000201300026\s* is on the collective weight of the grain.
\key 1.1.8
\title Threshing and winnowing
\index \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.1">1.1.8.1 Threshing floor\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.2">1.1.8.2 Threshing board, sledge\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.3">1.1.8.3 Winnowing fork\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.4">1.1.8.4 Sieve, winnowing basket\l*
\cont Threshing was the process of separating the grain from the straw by beating it with flails or having animals trample it or dragging a threshing board (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.2">1.1.8.2 Threshing board, sledge\l*) over it
\line Winnowing consisted of throwing the straw, chaff, grain, and dust into the wind with a wooden winnowing fork (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.3">1.1.8.3 Winnowing fork\l*) or a winnowing basket (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.4">1.1.8.4 Sieve, winnowing basket\l*). The heavier grains would fall back on the threshing floor or into the basket, while the wind would carry away the dust, the chaff, and the straw. The stalks of grain, which had thus been cut and separated from the heads of grain, were used for fodder for the animals.
\line In the land of Israel the wind normally begins to blow about two o’clock in the afternoon and continues through the evening and into the night. It is important that the wind is not too strong or blustery, and this may explain why the evening was regarded as the best time for winnowing.
\line The final stage of winnowing consisted of sifting the remaining foreign bodies out of the grain. This was done with a kind of sieve made of a wooden hoop to the bottom of which was fixed a mesh of crisscrossed strips of cane, leather, tree bark, or straw.
\line Where a technical term for winnowing is lacking, it is sometimes possible to use a descriptive phrase, such as “shaking out the dirt from the grain,” “separating the grain from the chaff,” or “separating the grain from the leaves.”
\key 1.1.8.1
\title Threshing floor
\cont \u References:\u*
\arm אִדְּרֵי
\trl ’idar
\ref A02700203500034
\heb גֹּרֶן
\trl goren
\ref H00401502000016 H00401802700020 H00401803000032 H00501501400016 H00501601300022 H00700603700020 H00800300200030 H00800300300030 H00800300600008 H00800301400054 H00902300100034 H01002401600068 H01002401800040 H01002402100040 H01002402400056 H01102201000030 H01200602700024 H01302101500072 H01302101800040 H01302102100034 H01302102200020 H01302102800026 H01400300100052 H01401800900034 H01803901200018 H02302101000008 H02400202500012 H02405103300022 H02800900100036 H02800900200002 H02801300300032 H02900202400008 H03300401200032
\grk ἅλων
\trl halōn
\ref G04000301200022 G04200301700020
\lat area
\ref V08200403000046 V08200403900016 V08200901700046
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0322_threshing_floor.jpg|col||© Klearchos Kapoutsis|Work on a threshing floor|1.0\fig*The threshing floor was a level, circular area about 7.5 to 12 meters (25-40 feet) in diameter. It was usually located near the fields where the grain was grown, and if possible it was in an elevated area that was exposed to the breeze (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.3">1.1.8.3 Winnowing fork\l*). Where possible, the threshing floor was located near the village so that the grain could be guarded. The floor was either bedrock or earth that was packed down to make it hard. It was often bordered with rocks to hold in the grain.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line After grain has been cut, the individual kernels have to be separated from the stalk and the outer seed covering. The cut grain was laid out on the threshing floor. The process of separating the stalks and seed coverings from the kernels could be done by several methods: 1) dragging a threshing sledge (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.8.2">1.1.8.2 Threshing board, sledge\l*) over the grain, 2) having animals walk back and forth over it, or 3) beating it with some implement.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s H02405103300022\s* and \s H03300401200032\s* the threshing floor symbolizes judgment or punishment. Where threshing is unknown and the meaning would not be clear, it may be made explicit; for example, \a GNT\a* renders \s H03300401200032\s*b as follows: “They do not realize that they have been gathered together to be punished in the same way that grain is brought in to be threshed.” Compare also the alternative suggested by \i A Handbook on The Gospel of Matthew\i* for \s G04000301200022\s*: “He is ready to judge and separate the good people from the bad, like the farmer who is ready to separate the grain from the chaff with his winnowing fork; he will keep safe the good, like the farmer puts wheat into his granary, and just as the farmer clears his threshing floor of the chaff and burns it in a fire, he will cause the bad people to burn in a fire that never goes out” (page 70).
\line In \s G04000301200022\s* and \s G04200301700020\s* the meaning of \i halōn\i* as “threshing floor” forms the basis for the figurative extension of meaning referring to the threshed grain still lying on the threshing floor. This meaning may be made clear by rendering the literal text “he will clear his threshing floor” as “he will thresh out completely all of the grain.” On the other hand, it is possible to interpret \i halōn\i* in both New Testament references in a literal sense and translate “he will clean up his threshing floor,” that is, by gathering up the grain and getting rid of the straw and chaff.
\key 1.1.8.2
\title Threshing board, sledge
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חָרוּץ
\trl charuts
\ref H01804102200010 H02302802700010 H02304101500010 H03000100300032
\heb מוֹרַג
\trl morag
\ref H01002402200052 H01302102300052 H02304101500008
\heb עֲגָלָה
\trl ‘agalah, ‘eglah
\ref H02302802700020 H02302802800024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0323_threshing_board_bottom.jpg|col||© Renyrt|Bottom of a threshing board|1.0\fig*The threshing board was a flat wooden surface made of a single piece of wood or several boards attached side-by-side. It measured roughly 1.5 by 1 meter (5 by 3 feet). On one surface a number of small holes were carved, and into these holes hard, sharp stones (flint or basalt) or metal pieces were tightly wedged.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The threshing board, with the stone side downward, was dragged over the stalks of grain by a draft animal, to which it was attached by ropes. To increase the weight (and the effectiveness) of the implement, the farmer might stand or sit on the board as it was pulled. As the board with its embedded stones passed over the grain, the kernels were separated from the stalks and the seed coverings, while the straw was cut into chaff. See \l target="REALIA:1.1.8">1.1.8 Threshing and winnowing\l* above.\fig |WEB-0325_threshing_board.jpg|col||© CarlosVdeHabsburgo|Iron threshing board|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H02302802700010 H02302802800024\s* uses several terms for instruments that performed basically the same function. The \i ‘agalah\i*/\i ‘eglah\i* was probably a sledge with sharp discs and a seat on top. The point of the agricultural reference in verse 27 is that the seeds mentioned, dill and cumin, are too small to be threshed in the same way as larger grains such as wheat and barley. The Hebrew word \i charuts\i* probably indicates a threshing board with iron spikes instead of stones. The Hebrew word \i ’ofan\i* in verse 27 refers to the wheel of a cart (see \l target="REALIA:8.3">8.3 Wheel\l*).\fig |KNW-0096_threshing.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Man standing on threshing board|1.0\fig*
\line \s H03000100300032\s* speaks of “threshing sledges of iron” (\a RSV\a*). This does not mean that the platform was made of iron but rather that iron spikes were protruding from the wooden platform instead of the usual stones. This language in \s H03000100300032\s* is probably figurative, and where that sense would be lost, the last half of this verse may be expanded to say “because they destroyed the people of Gilead like someone threshes grain with iron-studded sledges.” Or it may be rendered nonfiguratively as in \a GNT\a*, which reads “They treated the people of Gilead with savage cruelty.”
\key 1.1.8.3
\title Winnowing fork
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb זרה
\trl zarah (verb)
\ref H00800300200026 H02002000800012 H02002002600002 H02303002400028 H02304101600002 H02400401100052 H02401500700004 H02405100200014
\heb מִזְרֶה
\trl mizreh
\ref H02303002400042 H02401500700008
\heb רַחַת
\trl rachath
\ref H02303002400034
\grk λικμάω
\trl likmaō (verb)
\ref L07100500900004
\grk πτύον
\trl ptuon
\ref G04000301200006 G04200301700006
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0097_winnowing.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Man using winnowing fork|1.0\fig* The winnowing fork was a wooden fork-like implement, with five to seven prongs, for throwing threshed grain into the air so that the wind might separate the straw and chaff from the grain.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line See \l target="REALIA:1.1.8">1.1.8 Threshing and winnowing\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where there is no receptor-language term for a winnowing fork, translators may choose a descriptive phrase, for example, “a tool for throwing threshed grain into the air in order to let the chaff blow away.”\fig |UBS-0006_winnowing_fork.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Winnowing fork|1.0\fig*
\line The Hebrew verb \i zarah\i* means literally “to scatter.” It refers to a variety of operations in Scripture, including the process of winnowing.
\line The Hebrew word \i rachath\i* appears only once in Scripture at \s H02303002400028\s*, where its meaning is uncertain. It probably refers to a wooden implement with a long, flat blade attached to a long handle, similar to a spade but made of wood. The verse names two objects for performing the different stages of winnowing. The point of the verse is that even the food given to the animals will have been thoroughly prepared. Some translations eliminate the need to translate an implement by following the Septuagint; for example, \a CEV\a* has “Even the oxen and donkeys that plow your fields will be fed the finest grain.”\fig |WEB-0326_winnowing_shovel.jpg|col||National Gallery of Art|Rachath (winnowing shovel)|1.0\fig*
\line In \s L07100500900004\s* the activity of winnowing is used in a proverb. The literal text of the New Revised Standard Version (\a NRSV\a*) says “Do not winnow in every wind, or follow every path,” but \a GNT\a* restructures (and reverses the order of) verses 9 and 10 to give the meaning of the proverb: “Don’t try to please everyone or agree with everything people say.”
\key 1.1.8.4
\title Sieve, winnowing basket
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כְּבָרָה
\trl kvarah
\ref H03000900900038
\heb נָפָה
\trl nafah
\ref H02303002800026
\heb נוף
\trl nuf
\ref H02303002800020
\grk κόσκινον
\trl koskinon
\ref L07102700400006
\grk σινιάζω
\trl siniazō (verb)
\ref G04202203100018
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0327_sieve.jpg|col||© Israel Government Press Office|Sieve, winnowing basket|1.0\fig* The second stage of winnowing was carried out with a shallow, flat circular kind of sieve. This sieve had a mesh bottom made of straw, cord, strips of bark, or reed. The fineness of the mesh varied according to the purpose for which it was intended.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Some languages may have a different word for an instrument that sifts dry things, like grains, and one that allows liquids to pass through but keeps the solids. In all of the references above it is the former instrument that is intended.
\line \s H02303002800026\s*: This verse comes in a context that describes the punishment and destruction of the nations, which is compared to shaking something back and forth in a sieve in the third line of this verse: “to sift the nations with the sieve of destruction” (\a NRSV\a*). \a GECL\a* expands the four Hebrew words in this line to “He shakes the nations in his sieve and throws them out like worthless chaff.” In some languages even such an expansion will not give sufficient understanding, and it may be best to drop the image of the sieve. \a GNT\a* drops both the picture of the sieve and the following one of putting a bit in the mouth of an animal and combines them into “It [the wind] sweeps nations to destruction and puts an end to their evil plans.” Almost all translations consulted attempt to maintain the image of sifting. The Hebrew word \i nafah\i* may indicate a finer sieve, more appropriate for something like flour.
\line \fig |UBS-0007_winnowing_women.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Sieve, winnowing basket|1.0\fig*\s H03000900900038\s*: The Hebrew word for sieve here probably refers to a coarse type of sieve in which stones are kept while the grain passes through. The same type of sieve was also used by bricklayers, who separated the larger stones from the fine sand that they used for mortar. The picture used here could therefore be based on either grain or sand. It does not really matter which picture the translator chooses, since the important point is that not one of the stones gets through the sieve. They will all be caught and then discarded.
\line God is commanding the enemy to treat Israel like this; none of the sinners among the people of Israel will escape punishment, just as no stone gets through the sieve. It may be possible to translate “I will shake/sift the people of Israel like someone shakes sand [or, grain] in a sieve, through which not a single stone falls to the ground. I will shake/sift them to remove the bad people from among them.”
\line While the physical object “sieve” is not mentioned in \s G04202203100018\s*, the act of sifting is. Some languages will find it more natural to speak of the instrument with which the action is performed; compare \a ITCL\a* “. . . to pass you all through a sieve, as is done with grain to separate it.”
\key 1.1.9
\title Iron tools
\index \l target="REALIA:1.1.9.1">1.1.9.1 Hoe\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.1.9.2">1.1.9.2 Fork\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.1.9.3">1.1.9.3 Axe, adze\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.1.9.4">1.1.9.4 Pruning knife\l*
\cont \s H00901302001000 H00901302101000\s* presents a special problem to the translator, with a list of between five and seven different implements, depending on how the somewhat obscure Hebrew is interpreted. The following list is according to the translation order of \a RSV\a*:
\line “Plowshare” (\i macharesheth\i*): Some commentators have suggested that this first word in the list is a general term, meaning “tools for working the soil.” What follow would then be separate instruments, including the \i machareshah\i*, which appears in Hebrew with exactly the same consonants, made different only by the vowel points. This interpretation is, however, far from certain.
\line “Mattock” (\i ’eth\i*): This possibly means “plowshare” (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.5">1.1.5 Plow and plowshare\l*), although ancient mattocks (a kind of hoe) have been found.
\line “Axe” (\i qardom\i*): This is translated also by the Septuagint as “axe” (\i axinē\i* in Greek). More precisely, it was probably an axe-like implement with a blade that was perpendicular to the handle. The implement served as a kind of hoe for loosening the soil or like an adze for shaping wood (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.9.3">1.1.9.3 Axe, adze\l*).
\line “Sickle” (\i machareshah\i*): Here again \a RSV\a* has followed the Septuagint in translating “sickle” (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.6">1.1.6 Sickle\l*). However, another ancient translator renders the word as a kind of small garden hoe used for loosening and weeding the soil, and this interpretation is preferred here (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.9.1">1.1.9.1 Hoe\l*).
\line “The charge was a pim” (\i haptsirah fim\i*): See the discussion on \i pim\i* \l target="REALIA:11.1.3">11.1.3 Pim\l*
\line “A third of a shekel” (\i shlosh qilshon\i*): Here again the meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain. Many translations see this as a second (and lower) price for sharpening two of the smaller implements. This translation assumes that letters have been reversed in the Hebrew text (see Hebrew Old Testament Text Project [\a HOTTP\a*]). A number of commentators and translators prefer to see here another kind of farming implement, a kind of three-pronged rake or fork on a wooden handle. If it was a rake, it was used to scrape together loose cuttings. However, more likely it was a fork, which would need its points sharpened from time to time. Such a fork was used to lift piles of cuttings.
\line “Goad” (\i darvan\i*): See \l target="REALIA:1.1.2">1.1.2 Goad\l*.
\line The general point of this passage is that the Israelites were forced to take their blunt farming implements to the Philistines for sharpening. Where a language lacks equivalent words for several of the implements, a translation may express the idea with a general statement by rendering verses 20-21 as follows: “The Israelites had to go to the Philistines to have their iron farming tools sharpened. The price varied according to the tool.” Another possible model is “. . . to sharpen their iron farming tools which had become blunted. The price varied according to the tool.” See also the comments on this passage in \i A Handbook on the First and Second Books of Samuel\i*, pages 267-269.
\key 1.1.9.1
\title Hoe
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַחֲרֵשָׁה
\trl machareshah
\ref H00901302000022 H00901302000040 H00901302100016
\heb מַעְדֵּר
\trl ma‘der
\ref H02300702500016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0328_hoe.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Man using a hoe|1.0\fig*The hoe was a flat metal blade, 10-20 centimeters (4-8 inches) wide, mounted on a wooden handle with the blade at a right angle to the handle. The illustration to the left shows the blade without a handle.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line This implement was used to loosen the soil, especially for weeding.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line See the note on \s H00901302001000 H00901302101000\s* at \l target="REALIA:1.1.9">1.1.9 Iron tools\l*.\fig |WEB-0329_hoe_blade_roman.jpg|col||© Giovanni Dall'Orto|Hoe blade|1.0\fig*
\key 1.1.9.2
\title Fork
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb שְׁלֹשׁ קִלְּשֹׁון
\trl shlosh qilshon
\ref H00901302100032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0008_fork.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Three-pronged fork heads|1.0\fig* The fork was an iron head consisting of two or three pointed prongs attached to the end of a wooden handle approximately 1-1.3 meters (3-4 feet) in length.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The fork was used by farmers and field workers to lift piles of cuttings.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line See the discussion on \s H00901302001000 H00901302101000\s* above.
\key 1.1.9.3
\title Axe, adze
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בַּרְזֶל
\trl barzel
\ref H00501900500050 H01200600500022 H01200600600044 H02301003400016
\heb גַּרְזֶן
\trl garzen
\ref H00501900500034 H00502001900038 H01100600700028 H02301001500008
\heb מַעֲצָד
\trl ma‘atsad
\ref H02401000300034
\heb קַרְדֹּם
\trl qardom
\ref H00700904800036 H00901302000034 H00901302100040 H01907400500018 H02404602200024
\grk ἀξίνη
\trl axinē
\ref G04000301000008 G04200300900010
\grk πέλεκυς
\trl pelekus
\ref L07300101300014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0330_adze.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Adze with wooden handle|1.0\fig* The axe or adze was an instrument with a metal, sharp-edged head attached to a wooden handle about the length of a man’s arm. The handle was usually wedged tightly into a hole opposite the sharp blade, and it could be held more firmly in place by cords bound around the head and handle. The blade of the axe (\i garzen\i*) was parallel to the handle, while the blade of the adze (\i qardom\i*) was perpendicular to the handle.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line It was used to cut down trees and woody plants as well as to chop them into smaller pieces. It could also serve as a carpenter’s tool for shaping wood.\fig |WEB-0331_axe.jpg|col||© Zereshk|Axe heads|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It is likely that the axe mentioned in \s L07300101300014\s* is a kind of weapon rather than a work tool. While the general form of the implement was the same, some languages may make a distinction between the work tool and the weapon. It is also possible to translate the first half of this verse more generally; for example, “Sometimes they are holding weapons.”
\key 1.1.9.4
\title Pruning knife
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַזְמֵרָה
\trl mazmerah
\ref H02300200400038 H02301800500038 H02900401000012 H03300400300042
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0332_pruning_hook.jpg|col||Lax2|Pruning hook|1.0\fig*The pruning knife was a knife or metal blade, sometimes attached to a long wooden handle.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The pruning process involved cutting away or cutting back unproductive branches so they could produce better.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line All of the references, except \s H02301800500038\s*, are to making spears into pruning knives or vice versa. Where metal plows and pruning knives are not used as agricultural tools, some adjustment in this figure will be necessary. The essential point is that instruments of war and bloodshed will be replaced by instruments of peace and prosperity (or the opposite in \s H02900401001000\s*). If iron instruments are not used in an area, it may not be possible to keep the idea that the weapons themselves are made into agricultural tools. In such a case, a translator can simply say that people will destroy their weapons and make tools for farming instead.
\key 1.1.10
\title Wine press
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גַּת
\trl gath
\ref H00700601100052 H01601301500020 H02306300200020 H02500101500026 H02900401300020
\heb יֶקֶב
\trl yeqev
\ref H00401802700034 H00401803000040 H00501501400022 H00501601300028 H00700702500046 H01200602700032 H01802401100008 H02000301000014 H02300500200030 H02301601000040 H02404803300030 H02800900200006 H02900202400018 H02900401300026 H03700201600026 H03801401000072
\heb פּוּרָה
\trl purah
\ref H02306300300002
\grk ληνός
\trl lēnos
\ref G04002103300036 G06601401900042 G06601402000008 G06601402000026 G06601901500052 L07103301700018
\grk ὑπολήνιον
\trl hupolēnion
\ref G04101200100030
\cont The Greek word \i hupolēnion\i* in \s G04101200100030\s* refers to the wine trough/vat.
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0391_winepress_en.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man in a wine press|1.0\fig* The wine press was a place for pressing out the juice of grapes for the making of wine (see \l target="REALIA:9.1">9.1 Wine\l*), vinegar, and grape honey. Ancient wine presses consisted of large treading floors on which the grapes were trampled in order to extract the juice. Depending on the topography, a wine press floor could be larger and shallower than the one depicted in the illustration below. Beneath the wine press floor was placed (or cut out of the rock) a trough or vat into which flowed the grape juice that had just been pressed out.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i gath\i* usually indicates the treading floor or the entire installation, while \i yeqev\i* is the collecting vat.
\line A descriptive equivalent of “wine press” may be “place where the juice of grapes was squeezed out” or “. . . pressed out” (similarly \i Parole de Vie\i* [\a PV\a*] in \s G04101200100030\s*). The Spanish common language translation (\a SPCL\a*) has “place where wine is made” (\s H00700601100052\s*). For “wine trough,” translators may use a descriptive phrase, such as “place where the juice of the grapes was collected.”
\line The Hebrew word \i purah\i* may refer to a measure of pressed juice or the act of pressing out the juice in a wine press. In \s H02306300300002\s* most translations render it “wine press.” For the first line of this verse the New Jewish Publication Society Version (\a NJPSV\a*) is more accurate with “I trod out a vintage alone.” Good models are \a GNT\a* “I have trampled the nations like grapes” and \a CEV\a* “I alone stomped the grapes!”
\line The Greek word \i lēnos\i* means a depression, hole, trough, or pit. The operation of pressing grapes involved more than one such depression; there was one (in the land of Israel it was a flat surface) in which the grapes were placed and tread, and one or more into which the juice flowed. \i Lēnos\i* can refer to either of these, and it will usually be sufficient to render it something like “pit to crush the grapes in” (\a CEV\a*; \s G04002103300036\s*).
\line \i Lēnos\i* is the word used in \s G04002103300036\s*. In the parallel passage in \s G04101200100030\s* a different Greek word is used (\i hupolēnion\i*), a word that means a pit which lies below the \i lēnos\i*, that is, a “collection pit” into which the juice flowed from the upper surface where the grapes were crushed. translations render both words the same, usually “wine press” or its equivalent. Some translations (\i Traduction œcuménique de la Bible\i* [\a TOB\a*], \a NJB\a*, \a NRSV\a*, New International Version [\a NIV\a*], New American Standard Bible [\a NASB\a*]) use a different word or expression in Mark; for example, \a NASB\a* has “vat under the wine press.”
\key 1.1.11
\title Watchtower
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִגְדָּל
\trl migdal
\ref H00103502100022 H01402601000006 H02300500200020 H03300400800006
\grk πύργος
\trl purgos
\ref G04002103300042 G04101200100036 G04201402800012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0104_watchtower.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Watchtower in a vineyard|1.0\fig* The watchtower was a structure made of stone, sometimes round but more often rectangular. It was normally built on a high place in or near a vineyard. It stood 2-5 meters (6-16 feet) high and was mounted by a ladder or steps. During the grape harvest, it was the custom for the owner of a vineyard or one of his family members or servants to spend the night on the watchtower to guard against animals or thieves who might try to steal the grapes. Similar towers could also be built to watch over other property, such as sheep and goats.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line English uses basically the same expression to describe this structure in a farmer’s field and a lookout point on a city wall (see \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.3">3.13.3.3 Watchtower, tower\l*). In some languages, however, the two structures may have very different terms. In a few verses (for example, \s H01302702500052\s*; \s H01402601000006\s*; \s L07103701400000\s*), it is not entirely clear from the context which type of tower is intended; in \s H00103502100022\s* and \s H03300400800006\s* the reference may be to either one, or it may even be a place name.
\line Some translators may want to use a descriptive phrase for “watchtower,” for example, “tower to keep watch over the vineyard” (\a PV\a*; \s G04002103300042\s*).
\key 1.1.12
\title Irrigation channel, canal
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יְאֹר
\trl y’or
\ref H00200701900040 H00200800100038
\heb נָהָר
\trl nahar
\ref H02301900600006
\grk διῶρυξ
\trl diōrux
\ref L07102403000006 L07102403100032
\grk ὑδραγωγός
\trl udragōgos
\ref L07102403000016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0333_irrigation_channel.jpg|col||© Bukvoed|Irrigation channel|1.0\fig* The irrigation canal was a small channel cut into the rock or dug into the ground to transfer water from a larger source such as a river into a cultivated plot of ground. The reference in \s L07102403000016\s* gives a good description of its function: “an irrigation canal bringing water from a river into a garden” (\a GNT\a*). Gardens could be watered by a system of smaller channels running off a larger channel and feeding into all parts of the garden, using gravity to deliver the water.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i y’or\i* normally refers to the Nile River. However, most translations agree that in \s H00200701900040\s* and \s H00200800500058\s* (1) it means “irrigation canal.” Similarly, the Hebrew word \i nahar\i* normally means “river,” but in \s H02301900600006\s*, where it is plural in Hebrew, most translation render it “canals” (\a RSV\a*) or “channels” (\a NJPSV\a*).
\key 1.2
\title Animal husbandry
\index \l target="REALIA:1.2.1">1.2.1 Sheep pen, sheepfold\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.2.2">1.2.2 Animal pen, stall\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.2.3">1.2.3 Manger, feed trough, feedbox\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.2.4">1.2.4 Rod, club, shepherd’s staff\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.2.5">1.2.5 Shepherd’s bag/pouch\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.2.6">1.2.6 Bit and bridle\l*
\key 1.2.1
\title Sheep pen, sheepfold
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בָּצְרָה
\trl botsrah
\ref H03300201200026
\heb גְּדֵרָה
\trl gidroth, gidroth ts’on
\ref H00403201600012 H00403202400014 H00403203600020 H00902400400008 H02404900300032 H03600200600020
\heb מִכְלָא
\trl mikla’, mikl’oth, mikl’oth ts’on
\ref H01905000900014 H01907807000018 H03500301700042
\heb מִשְׁפְּתַיִם, שְׁפַתַּיִם
\trl mishpthayim, shfatayim
\ref H00104901400014 H00700501600010 H01906801400008
\grk αὐλή
\trl aulē
\ref G04301000100026 G04301001600020
\grk μάνδρα
\trl mandra
\ref L06800202600030 L06800300300044
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0014_sheepfold.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Sheepfold|1.0\fig* The sheep pen was an area enclosed by a stone wall or hedge made of branches and thorns. It had a narrow opening through which the sheep could pass and which could be closed with brush or by the shepherd’s body. Sheep were put in the pen at night to protect them from thieves or wild animals.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Sheep pen” must often be rendered “place for the protection of sheep,” “place for sheep with a wall built around it,” or “enclosure for sheep.” In contrast to the next entry (\l target="REALIA:1.2.2">1.2.2 Animal pen, stall\l*), this enclosure was built out in the areas where the sheep were grazing, and not near the house. It could often be a temporary structure.
\line In \s H02404900300032\s* the Hebrew word \i gderoth\i* is rendered “sheep-pens” by \a NJB\a* and “sheepfolds” by \a NJPSV\a*. Others have “walls” (\a NIV\a*, \a NASB\a*, New Century Version [\a NCV\a*]) or “hedges” (\a RSV\a*, New Living Translation [\a NLT\a*]). Others, however, prefer a small change in the Hebrew, so that it would mean “covered with gashes” as an expression of mourning. Translations that take this approach render the last half of the fourth line in this verse as “lament, and slash yourselves with whips” (\a NRSV\a*) or “and score your bodies with gashes” (Revised English Bible [\a REB\a*]).
\line The Hebrew words \i mishpthayim\i* and \i shfatayim\i* are translated in different ways. In \s H00104901400014\s* \a RSV\a* and \a NJPSV\a* have “sheepfolds,” while \a REB\a* says “cattle pens.” These versions believe these words refer to an enclosure for domestic animals. \a GNT\a* and \a NIV\a* have “saddlebags,” which is preferred by \i A Handbook on Genesis\i*, page 1090.
\key 1.2.2
\title Animal pen, stall
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֻרְוָה
\trl ’awerah, ’urwah, ’uryah
\ref H01100500600014 H01400902500014 H01403202800022
\heb בַּיִת
\trl bayith
\ref H00900600700064 H00900601000044
\heb מַרְבֵּק
\trl marbeq
\ref H00902802400012 H02404602100014 H03000600400038 H03900302000036
\heb רֶפֶת
\trl refeth
\ref H03500301700056
\grk φάτνη
\trl fatnē
\ref G04201301500046
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line This structure was a stall, part of a barn where animals were fed, or it was simply a customary place where animals were fed outside, often in a semi-circular enclosure. Since people normally possessed few cattle, the stalls were often near, or even inside, the house where the family lived.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In contrast to \l target="REALIA:1.2.1">1.2.1 Sheep pen, sheepfold\l*, this enclosure was permanent and built near the dwelling of the owner of the sheep.
\line In \s H00902802400012 H02404602100014\s*; and \s H03000600400038\s*, the Hebrew phrase \i ‘egel marbeq\i* is literally “calf of the stall,” indicating a calf that has been kept in a stall and fed until it is fat. While \i marbeq\i* may usually be left untranslated, it is also possible to follow \a CEV\a*’s translation of the equivalent phrase in \s G04201502301000\s*, where it has “best calf” (compare \a GNT\a* “prize calf”).
\key 1.2.3
\title Manger, feed trough, feedbox
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֵבוּס
\trl ’evus
\ref H01803900900016 H02001400400008 H02300100300012
\grk φάτνη
\trl fatnē
\ref G04200200700030 G04200201200024 G04200201600036
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0334_feed_trough.jpg|col||Feed trough|© Immanuel Giel|1.0\fig*The manger was a trough, made of stone or wood, where animals fed, possibly even an open feeding place under the sky.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It may be important in some languages to distinguish between various alternatives. A “feed trough” or “manger” normally refers to a relatively large box or rack containing hay, where an animal stands when it feeds; a “feedbox” is a much smaller container, usually for grain. There is no way of knowing precisely where the baby Jesus was placed in \s G04200200700030\s*, but it would have been appropriate for the baby to be placed in the feedbox or in the manger.
\key 1.2.4
\title Rod, club, shepherd’s staff
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַטֶּה
\trl mateh
\ref H00103801800030 H00103802500060 H00200400200026 H00200400400042 H00200401700008 H00200402000044 H00200700900032 H00200701000038 H00200701200008 H00200701200022 H00200701200028 H00200701500042 H00200701700030 H00200701900020 H00200702000030 H00200800100026 H00200801200022 H00200801300020 H00200902300010 H00201001300010 H00201401600010 H00201700500036 H00201700900044 H00401701700018 H00401701700020 H00401701700046 H00401701700058 H00401701800014 H00401701800020 H00401702000016 H00401702100024 H00401702100032 H00401702100050 H00401702100054 H00401702100062 H00401702200012 H00401702300030 H00401702400014 H00401702400042 H00401702500016 H00402000800008 H00402000900012 H00402001100024 H00901402700032 H00901404300042 H02300900300014 H02301000500012 H02301001500046 H02301002400038 H02301002600028 H02301400500006 H02302802700034 H02303003200010 H02600701000022 H02600701100010 H02601901100008 H02601901200036 H02601901400010 H02601901400026 H03500301400006
\heb מַקֵּל
\trl maqel
\ref H00103201100034 H00201201100022 H00402202700046 H00901704000006 H00901704300032 H02800401200012 H03801100700030 H03801101000008 H03801101400008
\heb מִשְׁעֶנֶת
\trl mash‘enah, mish‘eneth
\ref H00202101900018 H00402101800022 H00700602100016 H01200402900018 H01200402900054 H01200403100020 H01201802100012 H01902300400030 H02303600600008 H02602900600022 H03800800400030
\heb שֵׁבֶט
\trl shevet
\ref H00202102000024 H00302703200024 H01000701400036 H01002302100042 H01301102300058 H01800903400008 H01802100900014 H01803701300006 H01900200900006 H01902300400026 H01908903300008 H02001001300014 H02001302400004 H02002200800014 H02002201500012 H02002301300020 H02002301400008 H02002600300020 H02002901500002 H02300900300018 H02301000500006 H02301001500034 H02301002400032 H02301100400034 H02301402900014 H02302802700048 H02303003100018 H02500300100014 H02602003700012 H02602101500024 H02602101800014 H03300401400020 H03300701400008
\grk ῥάβδος
\trl rhabdos
\ref G04001001000022 G04100600800022 G04200900300022 G04600402100008 G05800900400042 G05801102100030 G06600202700010 G06601100100012 G06601200500024 G06601901500040 L06700501800038 L07103302500006 L07600102500032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0392_shepherd_staff.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Shepherd holding a staff|1.0\fig* The rod was a straight stick about 1-2 meters (3-6 feet) in length. Its diameter allowed it to fit comfortably in a person’s hand.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The rod was, first of all, just a walking stick, and in some of the references above that is its primary purpose. However, it could serve many other purposes, including herding animals, fighting off wild animals, beating people, or even for divining (\s H02800401200012\s*). In the hands of a shepherd, the rod extended the shepherd’s reach, enabling him to direct stray sheep back to the flock.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Translators must pay special attention to the context when rendering the Hebrew and Greek words listed above. The rod in the hand of the shepherd or traveler could serve multiple purposes. Sometimes it simply helped to maintain balance while walking over rough ground. It could also be wielded as an offensive or defensive weapon. On offense, it is probably best rendered “club” (see also \l target="REALIA:2.7">2.7 Club, war club, mace, shattering weapon\l*). The Hebrew words are similar in meaning, and in several places they are used in poetic parallelism (\i mateh\i* and \i shevet\i* in \s H00302703200024\s*; \s H02301000500004\s*, \s H02301001500034\s*, \s H02301002400032\s*; \s H02302802700048\s*; \s H02303003100018 H02303003200010\s*).
\line Some cultures will have a special word for a staff carried by a shepherd or someone who herds other animals. In other contexts the best rendering will be something like “walking stick” (\a CEV\a* in \s G05801102100030\s*). However, in most passages translators should avoid using a word that gives the impression that the user of the stick was somehow feeble or crippled or injured. Such a staff was carried by men of all ages and states of health.
\line \s H00302703200024\s*: The phrase “every tenth animal of all that pass under the herdsman’s staff” (\a RSV\a*) is probably an allusion to the way in which animals were selected for the tithe. The animals were counted as they passed single file under the staff of the herdsman. Every tenth animal was marked with a red colored stick to show that it had been chosen for the tithe. If this image can be retained in the receptor-language translation while at the same time clearly conveying the idea of counting, then this will probably be better. But the details of the actual procedure are less important than the fact that one of every ten animals was to be designated as belonging to the LORD. One possible model for the whole verse is “When you count your animals, cattle, sheep or goats, every tenth animal must be marked as belonging to the LORD.”
\line \s H01902300400026\s*: The Hebrew words \i shevet\i* and \i mish‘eneth\i* are used together in this verse as if they are distinguishable objects. We may quote from \i A Handbook on Psalms\i*: “The \b rod\b* was a club used to drive away wild animals; the \b staff\b* was a long stick used for support in walking. Kirkpatrick takes the two words to be a poetic description of the shepherd’s crook, using two names for the one instrument. So \a FRCL\a* ‘your shepherd’s rod, that is what reassures me.’ Most translations, however, have two different words. \a TEV\a* [that is, \a GNT\a*] has used the traditional ‘\b rod and staff\b*’; but since there will be many readers who will not know what these are, \a TEV\a* qualifies them with ‘\b Your shepherd’s rod and staff\b*’ ” (page 234).
\line \s G04600402100008\s*: This is the only place where Paul uses the Greek word \i rhabdos\i*, and its meaning must be determined from the context. It is very unlikely that Paul thinks of a literal stick with which he is threatening to beat his converts. It is also very unlikely that he thinks of himself as a ruler. His authority is “in Christ” (verses 15, 17), and he describes it as the authority of a father (verse 15) or a teacher. Both fathers and teachers had the acknowledged right to correct their children or pupils, if necessary, by using force. This idea is difficult to convey in the setting of many modern societies. Paul’s language also seems to have irony in it. Translators have found different ways of explaining or bringing out the meaning of the word \i rhabdos\i*. Some maintain the image of the instrument of punishment (\a REB\a* and \a DUCL\a* “a rod in my hand”; Moffatt [\a Mft\a*] and Barclay [Brc] “rod of discipline”). Others focus on the element of punishment; for example, \a CEV\a* begins the second question of this verse with “Do you want me to be hard on you,” and \a NCV\a* has “that I come to you with punishment.” \a GNT\a* has replaced the rod with a whip by saying “Shall I come to you with a whip.” This has been done presumably because a whip or strap is more familiar in English as an instrument of punishment. Some translators will want to follow this model and substitute an instrument better known in their society.
\line \s G05801102100030\s*: In \s H00104703100028\s* the Hebrew word \i m-t-h\i* can mean either “staff” or “bed,” depending on what vowels are given to the word (see the discussion at \l target="REALIA:5.5">5.5 Bed, sleeping mat\l*). Most translations render it “bed.” \a NIV\a* is an exception with “staff,” and it gives “bed” in the margin. The writer of Hebrews has followed the Septuagint, which has “staff.” The translator of Hebrews must not try to harmonize these verses but should translate the Greek of this verse, which can only mean “staff.”
\line \s G06600202700010 G06601200500024 G06601901500040\s*: The literal phrase “to rule . . . with a rod of iron” appears in these three verses (compare \s H01900200900006\s*). This means to rule completely, ruthlessly, crushing all opposition. The “iron rod” was probably a heavy wooden club capped with iron, not a club made of iron. When translating this expression, some cultural adjustment may have to be made. If there is no local equivalent to “a rod of iron,” the translation may say “to rule with complete authority.”
\line The “staff” is often used in Scripture in a figurative sense, and the figures may not correspond to something known in the receptor language. In such cases it will be preferable to translate the sense.
\line In \s L06700501800038\s* Tobit’s parents speak of him as “the staff of our hand” (\a NRSV\a*), meaning that they are dependent on his help. \a GNT\a* has found a good English idiom to convey the meaning: “He’s our only means of support.”
\key 1.2.5
\title Shepherd’s bag/pouch
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יַלְקוּט
\trl yalqut
\ref H00901704000054
\heb כְּלִי, הָרֹעִים
\trl kli (haro‘im)
\ref H00901704000038 H00901704900016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0393_shepherd_bag.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Shepherd with a bag|1.0\fig* The shepherd’s bag was a pouch hung from the shoulder by a strap or attached to the belt or sash around the waist. It could be made of leather or cloth.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The shepherd used the bag to carry food and small personal items.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00901704000054\s*: This verse uses two words to describe the place where David put the five stones he selected for his upcoming battle with Goliath. Some translations understand the one item to be part of the other: “in the pouch of his shepherd’s bag” (\a NIV\a*; similarly \a NRSV\a*, \a ITCL\a*). Others treat the two terms as referring to one object: “in a shepherd’s bag, which served as his pouch” (\a REB\a*; similarly \a NASB\a*). Most common-language translations that were consulted use only one word to translate the two Hebrew words; for example, \a GNT\a* has “in his bag,” while several others have “in his shepherd’s bag” (\a PV\a*). \a SPCL\a* can serve as a good model: “in the bag which he carried with him.”
\line For the Hebrew word \i kli\i*, see \l target="REALIA:5.18">5.18 Containers, vessels\l*.
\key 1.2.6
\title Bit and bridle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מֶתֶג
\trl metheg
\ref H01201902800030 H01903200900020 H02002600300010 H02303702900030
\heb רֶסֶן
\trl resen
\ref H01804100500014 H01903200900024 H02303002800032
\grk χαλινός
\trl chalinos
\ref G05900300300012 G06601402000032
\grk χρυσοχάλινος
\trl chrusochalinos
\ref L07801002900024 L08100300600028
\grk κόσμος
\trl kosmos
\ref L07800500300044
\grk σαγή
\trl sagē
\ref L07800302500024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0008_fork.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Bit|1.0\fig* The bit was a short bar, usually made of metal, placed in the mouth of a horse. Its ends, which projected from the mouth of the animal, were attached to ropes or leather straps that fitted over the head as the bridle.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line By pulling on the bridle straps to the right or left, the rider or driver of the wagon could control the actions of the horse.\fig |KNW-0394_harness_bridle_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Bridle and bit|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew words \i metheg\i* and \i resen\i* respectively refer to the “bit” and “bridle” (although \a RSV\a* has once rendered \i metheg\i* as “bridle” in \s H02002600300010\s*). The Greek words \i chalinos\i* and \i chrusochalinos\i* refer to both the bit and bridle. Where a bit or bridle as a piece of harness is unknown, translators can use a descriptive phrase, such as “something to guide a horse with” or “something to put in the mouth of a horse to guide it.” \fig |KNW-0031_horse.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Horseman|1.0\fig*
\line The Hebrew word \i mtsilah\i* in \s H03801402000016\s* probably refers to some sort of noise-making decoration on the harness of a horse. The word occurs only here in the Bible.
\line In \s G06601402000032\s* the reference to “a horse’s bridle” (\a RSV\a*) is merely an indication of measurement. It refers to the height of the bridle from the ground, so we may render this measurement as “about a meter and a half” (\a FRCL\a*) or “about five feet” (\a GNT\a*).
\line The Greek word used in \s L07801002900024\s* and \s L08100300600028\s* indicates that the metal parts of the bridle were made of gold.
\key 1.3
\title Fishing
\index \l target="REALIA:1.3.1">1.3.1 Nets\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.3.2">1.3.2 Hook\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.3.3">1.3.3 Fishing spear, harpoon\l*
\line Boat: See \l target="REALIA:8.1">8.1 Boat, ship\l*.
\key 1.3.1
\title Nets
\index \l target="REALIA:1.3.1.1">1.3.1.1 Casting net\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.3.1.2">1.3.1.2 Dragnet, seine\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.3.1.3">1.3.1.3 Net, trammel net\l*
\key 1.3.1.1
\title Casting net
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִכְמָר, מִכְמֶרֶת, מִכְמֹרֶת
\trl mikmor, mikmereth, mikmoreth
\ref H01914101000006 H02301900800030 H03500101500022 H03500101600018
\heb רֶשֶׁת
\trl resheth
\ref H02603200300018
\grk ἀμφιβάλλω, ἀμφίβληστρον
\trl amfiballō (verb), amfiblēstron
\ref G04000401800042 G04100101600030
\grk δίκτυον
\trl diktuon
\ref G04302100600026 G04302100800044 G04302101100016 G04302101100048
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0209_fishermen_net.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Casting a net|1.0\fig* The casting net was a circular net with weights and a draw rope around its edge. It was roughly 6-7.5 meters (20-25 feet) in diameter.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The net was thrown from a boat or the shore in a circular motion so that it landed with the net fully spread out on the water. The weights carried it down, trapping fish underneath. Then the fisherman used the draw rope to close the net and pull it back to himself.\fig |KNW-0210_fishermen_net.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Fish in a net|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It is not necessary to express all the details of the “casting net” in order to render it adequately in another language. What is important is that such a net was thrown rather than dragged. A generic term for “net” may be used in languages that do not have distinct terms for different kinds of nets.
\line The Hebrew word \i resheth\i* normally refers to a hunting net for animals or birds (see \l target="REALIA:1.4.2">1.4.2 Net\l*). In \s H02603200300018\s* it is used in parallel with the Hebrew word \i cherem\i*, which means “dragnet” (see \l target="REALIA:1.3.1.2">1.3.1.2 Dragnet, seine\l*). The Hebrew verb that accompanies \i resheth\i* means “throw” or “spread out,” the action associated with the casting net, and for that reason it is included here. Most translations agree that the context of this verse is fishing and not hunting. However, most translations choose a general word for “net” rather than trying to specify which type of fishing net is intended.
\line \s H03500101500022 H03500101600018\s*: Two different words for net are used in these verses (see \l target="REALIA:1.3.1.2">1.3.1.2 Dragnet, seine\l* for a discussion on the other type of net). If different kinds of fishing nets are familiar in a culture, translators will have no difficulty in speaking about them. If they are not, then it will probably be best to use one generic term for both types of fishing nets here (so \a GNT\a* “nets”).
\line \s G04302100301000\s*: When Peter says “I am going fishing” (\a GNT\a*), some languages will need to make clear what kind of fishing is intended, whether, for example, Peter will be using a hook and line, a trap, or a net. The most normal method of fishing in biblical times was with nets, and this is the meaning here.
\key 1.3.1.2
\title Dragnet, seine
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֵרֶם
\trl cherem
\ref H02602600500004 H02602601400014 H02603200300034 H02604701000028 H03500101500014 H03500101600010 H03500101700010
\grk σαγήνη
\trl sagēnē
\ref G04001304700016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The dragnet was a long net hanging vertically in the water with floats at the upper edge and weights at the lower edge.\fig |WEB-0335_drag_net.jpg|col||George Louis Faber|Men pulling in a dragnet|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The dragnet was drawn in by men working in boats or from shore. As the ends were drawn together to the boat or drawn ashore, fish were trapped in the area enclosed by the net.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line A generic term for “net” may be used in languages that do not require that a distinction be made.
\line In \s G04001304700016\s* the actual form of the net is not so important. What is significant is that the net was sufficiently large to catch a large number of different kinds of fish.
\line \s H03500101500014 H03500101600010 H03500101700010\s*: See the comments at \l target="REALIA:1.3.1.1">1.3.1.1 Casting net\l*.
\key 1.3.1.3
\title Net, trammel net
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מָצוֹד
\trl matsod (see also \l target="REALIA:1.4.2">1.4.2 Net\l*)
\ref H01801900600014 H02100702600024
\heb מְצוֹדָה
\trl mtsodah
\ref H02100901200030
\grk δίκτυον
\trl diktuon
\ref G04000402000012 G04000402100054 G04100101800010 G04100101900042 G04200500200034 G04200500400032 G04200500500038 G04200500600022
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0336_trammel_net.jpg|col||Lindsay G. Thompson, University of Washington|Fish in a trammel net|1.0\fig* The trammel net was actually two or three nets combined in layers, usually a small-mesh inner net sandwiched between two nets of looser mesh.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Similar to the dragnet, the trammel net was set out vertically in the water, held in place by floats on the surface of the water and weighted down by a single weighted rope at the bottom. Fish swam through the outer layer and into the fine-mesh net (1), pushing it through the other layer of loose mesh (2). This caught the fish in a kind of pocket from which they could not return (3). Unlike the dragnet, which was drawn in immediately after it was spread out, the trammel net was left in place for several hours to give time for fish to accumulate in it.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew words \i matsod\i* and \i mtsodah\i* probably refer to “net” in a generic sense, whether for fishing or for hunting.
\line In \s G04000402000012 G04000402100054 G04100101800010 G04100101900042\s*; and \s G04200500200034 G04200500400032 G04200500500038 G04200500600022\s*, it is possible that the Greek word \i diktuon\i* refers to the dragnet (1.3.1.2), although the plural “nets” makes it likely that a trammel net is meant since it alone was made up of multiple nets. A generic term for “net” may be used in languages that do not require that a distinction be made.
\key 1.3.2
\title Hook
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סִירָה, דּוּגָה
\trl sir dugah
\ref H03000400200038
\heb צֵן
\trl tsinah
\ref H03000400200030
\grk ἄγκιστρον
\trl agkistron
\ref G04001702700020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0337_fish_hooks.jpg|col||© Olaf Tausch|Fish hooks|1.0\fig* The fishhook was a small, curved piece of metal or bone or even a strong thorn (in fact, the Hebrew word \i sir\i* in \s H03000400200038\s* means “thorn”). One end of the hook was sharply pointed, usually with a barb just behind the point. The other end had a loop or bend to which a fishing line could be attached.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Some kind of bait was attached to the fishing hook to attract a fish, and the hook, which was attached to a string, was thrown or lowered into the water. When a fish swallowed the bait, it got stuck on the hook.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line A literal rendering of \s G04001702700020\s* could be quite misleading, since it would imply that only the hook was thrown into the water. In some languages it may be necessary to make explicit what is implied in order to avoid misunderstanding by expanding the translation to indicate that what was thrown into the water was a line with a baited hook on the end of it.
\key 1.3.3
\title Fishing spear, harpoon
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חָח, חוֹחַ
\trl chach, choach
\ref H01201902800022 H01403301100038 H01804002600016 H02303702900022 H02601900400024 H02601900900016 H02602900400006 H02603800400010
\heb חַכָּה
\trl chakah
\ref H01804002500008 H02301900800024 H03500101500006
\heb מַסָּע
\trl masa‘
\ref H01804101800012
\heb שֻׂכָּה
\trl sukah
\ref H01804003100008
\heb צִלְצָל
\trl tsiltsal
\ref H01804003100016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0338_fishing_spear.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Point of a harpoon|1.0\fig*The fishing spear/harpoon was a wooden rod about the length of a man. To one end of the spear was attached a metal or bone point with barbs. It is likely that a rope was attached to the other end, so that the spear could be pulled back to the thrower.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The spear was thrown at fish or aquatic animals. The barbs prevented the point from falling out easily. The rope attached to the end opposite the point enabled the thrower to retrieve the spear quickly and easily to prepare for another throw, or to prevent the wounded animal from swimming away with the embedded spear.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \i A Handbook on The Book of Job\i* notes that the Hebrew word \i choach\i* in \s H01804002600016\s* indicates a kind of hook, but one “much larger than the fishhook in the previous verse” (page 752). The word occurs most often in descriptions of the treatment of prisoners, and this is the way it is used of Leviathan in \s H01804002500004 H01804003101000\s*.
\line The meaning of the Hebrew word \i masa‘\i* in \s H01804101800012\s* is uncertain. From the context it is clear that it is some sort of weapon, perhaps a throwing weapon, for hunting a large animal. The Hebrew text has three words at the end of the verse, which \a CEV\a* simply combines as “spear.” The word \i masa‘\i* is most often rendered “dart” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a NASB\a*, \a NCV\a*, \a REB\a*), but also “missile” (\a NJPSV\a*), “javelin” (\a NJB\a*), and “arrow” (\a GNT\a*). The English word “dart,” despite its popularity in modern translations, will only mean one thing to the modern reader unschooled in the English of King James or Shakespeare, that is, the very small pointed, feathered missile thrown at a board in the game of darts.
\key 1.4
\title Hunting
\index \l target="REALIA:1.4.1">1.4.1 Trap, snare\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.4.2">1.4.2 Net\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.4.3">1.4.3 Cage\l*
\key 1.4.1
\title Trap, snare
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶבֶל
\trl chevel
\ref H01801801000010 H01914000600012
\heb יקשׁ
\trl yaqash (verb)
\ref H00500702500034 H01912400700014 H01914100900010 H02000600200002 H02100901200054 H02300801500020 H02302801300060 H02405002400002
\heb יָקוֹשׁ
\trl yaqush
\ref H01909100300012 H02000600500022 H02400502600018 H02800900800014
\heb מוֹקֵשׁ
\trl moqesh
\ref H00201000700024 H00202303300034 H00203401200034 H00500701600044 H00602301300050 H00700200300038 H00700802700056 H00901802100020 H01002200600010 H01803403000012 H01804002400010 H01901800600010 H01906400600016 H01906902300022 H01910603600018 H01914000600024 H01914100900016 H02001201300008 H02001301400016 H02001402700016 H02001800700014 H02002002500002 H02002202500014 H02002900600010 H02002902500008 H02300801400042 H03000300500018
\heb מָזוֹר
\trl mazor
\ref H03100100700030
\heb מַלְכֹּדֶת
\trl malkodeth
\ref H01801801000014
\heb נקשׁ
\trl naqash (verb)
\ref H00501203000008 H00902800900056 H01900901700016 H01903801300004
\heb פַּח
\trl pach
\ref H00602301300044 H01801800900008 H01802201000008 H01906902300012 H01909100300010 H01911911000006 H01912400700012 H01912400700018 H01914000600006 H01914100900008 H01914200400028 H02000702300018 H02002200500004 H02100901200050 H02300801400036 H02302401700010 H02302401800046 H02401802200034 H02404804300010 H02404804400044 H02800500100038 H02800900800012 H03000300500010 H03000300500028
\heb צַמִּים
\trl tsamim
\ref H01801800900014
\heb קושׁ
\trl qosh (verb)
\ref H02302902100024
\heb שְׂבָכָה
\trl svakah
\ref H01801800800018
\heb שׁוּחָה
\trl shuchah
\ref H02002201400002 H02002302700004 H02401802000016
\heb שַׁחַת
\trl shachath
\ref H01900701600016 H01900901600008 H01903500700010 H02002602700004 H02400502600022 H02601900400012 H02601900800026
\heb שִׁיחָה
\trl shichah
\ref H01905700700020 H01911908500008 H02401802200024
\grk βόθρος
\trl bothros
\ref L07101201600036
\grk βρόχος
\trl brochos
\ref G04600703500022
\grk θήρα
\trl thēra
\ref G04501100900024
\grk σκάνδαλον
\trl skandalon
\ref G04501100900030 L07001401100036 L07700500400028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Included in this entry are a wide variety of devices used to trap and catch animals and birds.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H01801800800018 H01801800900008 H01801801000010\s* uses six different words for various kinds of traps. The present discussion will follow the wording of \a RSV\a*:
\line “Net” (\i resheth\i*; see \l target="REALIA:1.4.2">1.4.2 Net\l*): The net usually ensnared its quarry by entangling the feet, although the one mentioned here seems to be large enough to hold the entire person.
\line “Pitfall” (\i svakah\i*): This word indicates a network of branches and twigs which covers and hides a hole or pit. When the quarry steps on this network, its weight breaks through, and it falls into the pit and is trapped.
\line “Trap” (\i pach\i*): This is a general word for a device used to trap animals or especially birds. Here it is explicitly identified as a trap that catches the bird by its foot (literally “heel”).
\line “Snare” (\i tsamim\i*): This word may refer to some kind of woven material or mesh that entangles the feet.
\line “Rope” (\i chevel\i*): This most likely refers to a hidden noose that is attached at the other end to a bent bough or small tree that springs upright and tightens the noose around the victim when the trap is sprung.
\line “Trap” (\i malkodeth\i*): This is a general word for any kind of trap.
\line Because of the repetition in these three verses, some translations are considerably condensed. \a NCV\a* reduces the six words for traps to only three different words: “8 Their feet will be caught in a net when they walk into its web. 9 A trap will catch them by the heel and hold them tight. 10 A trap for them is hidden on the ground, right in their path.” \a CEV\a* condenses these verses even further: “8 Before they know it, 9 they are trapped in a net, 10 hidden along the path.” See also the lengthy discussion on these verses in \i A Handbook on The Book of Job\i*, pages 339-340.
\line For the Hebrew word \i mazor\i* in \s H03100100700030\s*, see the comments in \i A Handbook on The Books of Obadiah, Jonah, and Micah\i*, page 15.
\line In \s G04501100900024\s* the Greek words \i thēra\i* and \i skandalon\i* are treated as having literal meanings, whereas the passage as a whole is figurative. The three words there for various kinds of traps (including \i pagis\i*; see \l target="REALIA:1.4.2">1.4.2 Net\l*) would all seem to be completely parallel in structure and meaning. As a result, in a number of languages the three terms are reduced often to two, for example, “snare” and “trap.” If there are three different kinds of traps, then, of course, three terms can be used. In some cases, however, it may be preferable to use words to express the acts of catching and trapping as in \a GNT\a*, which has “May they be caught and trapped at their feasts; may they fall, may they be punished!”
\line Hook: See \l target="REALIA:1.3.2">1.3.2 Hook\l*.
\key 1.4.2
\title Net
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֵרֶם
\trl cherem
\ref H02100702600028 H03300700200040
\heb מִכְמָר
\trl mikmar
\ref H02305102000020
\heb מָצוֹד
\trl matsod (see \l target="REALIA:1.3.1.3">1.3.1.3 Net, trammel net\l*)
\ref H02100702600024
\heb מְצוּדָה
\trl mtsudah
\ref H01906601100008 H02601201300018 H02601702000016
\heb רֶשֶׁת
\trl resheth
\ref H01801800800008 H01900901600014 H01901000900036 H01902501500018 H01903100500006 H01903500700012 H01903500800012 H01905700700002 H01914000600016 H02000101700010 H02002900500010 H02500101300020 H02601201300008 H02601702000008 H02601900800022 H02800500100048 H02800701200012
\grk παγίς
\trl pagis
\ref G04202103500004 G04501100900018 G05400300700032 G05400600900018 G05500202600014 L06701401000088 L06701401000108 L07001401100046 L07100900300018 L07100901300060 L07102702000024 L07102702600020 L07102702900002 L07105100200032 L07700103500034 L07700500400024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0339_hunting_net.jpg|col||© Zunkir|Men trapping deer in a net|1.0\fig*The net was a mesh or very loose fabric made of string.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The net was a hunting tool. It was put in places where a bird or animal might fly or run into it and become entangled. Nets could also be used actively in hunting, that is, the hunter stalked the prey, and when he got close enough, he threw the net over his quarry.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Since snares or traps for capturing birds or animals are almost universal, there should be no difficulty involved in obtaining an appropriate term. In many contexts, however, it cannot be certain if the net spoken of is for hunting animals or for hunting birds. In languages where no distinction is required, a generic term for “net” may be used. Where a distinction must be made, the context should be checked carefully. The following breakdown indicates which passages refer to nets for animals (including human beings), which ones refer to nets for birds, and which ones are unclear:
\line Animals: \s H01900901600014\s*; \s H01903500700012 H01903500800012\s*; \s H02002900500010\s*; \s H02305102000020\s*; \s H02500101300020\s*; \s H02601201300018\s*; \s H02601702000016\s*; \s H02601900800022\s*; \s G05400300700032\s*; [\s L07100901300060\s*; \s L07102702000024\s*, \s L07102702600020\s*, \s L07102702900002\s*; \s L07700103500034\s*; \s L07700500400024\s*]
\line Birds: \s H02000101700010\s*; \s H02800701200012\s*
\line Unclear: \s H01801800800008\s*; \s H01901000900036\s*; \s H01902501500018\s*; \s H01903100500006\s*; \s H01905700700002\s*; \s H01914000600016\s*; \s H02100702600028\s*; \s H02800500100048\s*; \s G04202103500004\s*; \s G04501100900018\s*; \s G05400600900018\s*; \s G05500202600014\s*; [\s L06701401000088\s*; \s L07001401100046\s*; \s L07100900300018\s*; \s L07105100200032\s*]
\line In \s G04202103500004\s* it is not so much the physical object that is in focus but rather the unexpected nature of the event; however, the object is usually retained in translation.
\line In cases where the text is speaking figuratively, it may be possible to avoid using the figure of a net, especially where such a reference would be misleading; for example, in \s H03300700200040\s*d \a NCV\a* says “everyone is trying to trap someone else.”
\key 1.4.3
\title Cage
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סוּגַר
\trl sugar
\ref H02601900900010
\grk κάρταλλος
\trl kartallos
\ref L07101103000008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0068_dovesincage.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Birds in a cage|1.0\fig* The cage was a kind of basket, woven loosely of cane or sticks. It had a top or door that could be closed. When a bird or other prey was caught alive, it was confined in the cage. Sometimes the basket itself served as a kind of trap.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i sugar\i* in \s H02601900900010\s* probably refers to a kind of wooden collar put on prisoners (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.1">1.1.1 Yoke\l*). However, perhaps because the prophet pictures Judah’s king as a captured lion here, most translations render it “cage.” A few translations (\a GECL\a*, \a ITCL\a*) have “collar” or “yoke.” \a NJB\a* has “shackled.”
\line Sometimes a captive bird could be used as a lure to capture a larger animal. The bird was tied inside the basket. When the prey entered the basket to take the bait, the basket was closed upon it by some device. It is presumably this interpretation of \s L07101103000080\s* that has caused \a GNT\a* to render the first half of this verse as “A proud person is a decoy to lure you into danger.” Other translations omit the element of the lure; for example, the New American Bible (\a NAB\a*) has “Though he seem like a bird confined in a cage” (similarly \a ITCL\a*).
\key 1.5
\title Artisans
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.1">1.5.1 Potter\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.2">1.5.2 Engraver, woodcarver\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3">1.5.3 Cloth manufacture\l*
\key 1.5.1
\title Potter
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.1.1">1.5.1.1 Potter’s wheel\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.1.2">1.5.1.2 Glue\l*
\key 1.5.1.1
\title Potter’s wheel
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אָבְנַיִם
\trl ’ovnayim
\ref H02401800300032
\grk τροχός
\trl trochos
\ref L07103802900024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0010_wheel_potter.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Potter's wheel (Old Testament times)|1.0\fig* In Old Testament times the potter’s wheel was a flat, horizontal wheel made of stone. On the underside of the stone there was a pointed projection. This projection sat in an indentation on a stationary lower stone and served as an axis around which the upper stone turned. The stone was turned by hand or perhaps by a person other than the potter. In intertestamental and New Testament times the construction was different. An upper wheel, made of wood, was connected by a shaft to a second, larger wheel situated below. The upper wheel was at a height convenient for the potter to work when seated.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Clay was placed in the center of the upper wheel. The wheel was turned by hand or by foot. In the latter period, the spinning of the lower, heavier wheel caused the upper one to spin also. The potter used his fingers to form the spinning clay into the desired shape. See \s L07103802900024\s*: “It is the same with the potter, sitting at his wheel and turning it with his feet . . .” (\a GNT\a*).\fig |WEB-0340_potter_turning_wheel.jpg|col||The Pictorial New Testament, 1881|Potter turning wheel with his foot (New Testament times)|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The context of \s H02401800101000 H02401800201000 H02401800301000 H02401800400100\s* makes it clear that the potter is using the “wheel” to help him make clay pots. However, if it is felt that “wheel” would be misleading, translators may say “work table.”
\key 1.5.1.2
\title Glue
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk συγκολλάω
\trl sugkollaō (verb)
\ref L07102200900002
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Glue is an adhesive substance used to stick one thing to another.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line While nearly all languages have a word for adhesive substances, the Greek text of \s L07102200700000\s* actually uses a verb, and many translations will prefer to describe the action of sticking two things back together; for example, \a GNT\a* has “Trying to teach a fool is like gluing a broken pot back together . . . .” Some languages may distinguish between different kinds of adhesives. The glue chosen here should be appropriate for sticking together pieces of earthenware pottery.
\key 1.5.2
\title Engraver, woodcarver
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.2.1">1.5.2.1 Engraving, carving\l*
\key 1.5.2.1
\title Engraving, carving
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חרשׁ, חָרָשׁ
\trl charash
\ref H00202801100004 H00203503500018 H00203802300018 H02401700100020
\heb חֲרֹשֶׁת
\trl charosheth
\ref H00203100500006 H00203100500018 H00203503300006 H00203503300018
\heb פתח
\trl pathach (verb)
\ref H00202800900016 H00202801100012 H00202803600014 H00203900600020 H01100703600004 H01400200600070 H01400201300098 H01400300700032 H03800300900032
\heb פִּתּוּחַ
\trl pituach
\ref H00202801100008 H00202802100026 H00202803600018 H00203900600022 H00203901400026 H00203903000028 H01400200600072 H01400201300102 H01907400600010 H03800300900034
\heb קלע, מִקְלַעַת
\trl qala‘ (verb), miqla‘ath
\ref H01100601800014 H01100602900016 H01100602900020 H01100603200014 H01100603200018 H01100603500004 H01100703100054
\grk γλύμμα
\trl glumma
\ref L07103802700026 L07104501100006
\grk γλυφή
\trl glufē
\ref L07001802400030
\grk γλύφω
\trl glufō (verb)
\ref L07001301300030 L07103802700024
\grk ἐγγλύφω
\trl egglufō (verb)
\ref L07701302900044
\grk κολάπτω
\trl kolaptō (verb)
\ref L07104501100028 L07900202700032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0341_engraving_ring.jpg|col||The Portable Antiquities Scheme © The Trustees of the British Museum|Engraving on a ring|1.0\fig*An engraving was a picture or words made by scratching lines in a hard surface such as stone, metal, or gems. A carving was a figure usually made out of wood, using a knife or another sharp implement.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages it may be necessary to choose a verb for “engrave” according to the surface that is being used.
\line The Hebrew word \i charosheth\i* is used in \s H00203100500006\s* and \s H00203503300006\s* to describe both engraving and carving.
\line The specific action described in \s L07103802700024\s* is “engrave seals” (\a NJB\a*; compare the even more precise \a RSV\a* rendering “cut the signets of seals”; see also the discussion at \l target="REALIA:10.2">10.2 Seal, signet ring, ring\l*). The point of the passage is the diligence and precision with which the engraver works. Where there is no exact equivalent of signets or seals, it is possible to refer to some other craftsman’s work that requires precision and can be done in great variety.
\key 1.5.3
\title Cloth manufacture
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.2">1.5.3.2 Spindle\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.3">1.5.3.3 Weaver’s beam\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.4">1.5.3.4 Shuttle\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.5">1.5.3.5 Beater, batten, pin\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.6">1.5.3.6 Woven or knitted material\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.8">1.5.3.8 Wool\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.9">1.5.3.9 Silk\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.10">1.5.3.10 Purple cloth\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.11">1.5.3.11 Embroidered cloth, needlework\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.12">1.5.3.12 Patch\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.13">1.5.3.13 Linen cloth, sheet\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.14">1.5.3.14 Dye\l*
\line \fig |WEB-0342_weaving_en.jpg|col||Source unknown|Weaving|1.0\fig*Weaving was the art of making cloth. First the thread was prepared from the unspun fibers. This was done by attaching a piece of the fiber to a short, pointed piece of wood (the \b spindle\b*) and then spinning it while drawing out the fiber into thin, spun thread. The thread thus spun was wound onto the spindle. After the threads were prepared, it was necessary to interlace them at right angles. The \b loom\b* was a device designed to weave cloth in this manner. In the horizontal loom, a series of threads were wound around a thick wooden beam and then tied to another beam. These threads, called the warp, were slightly separated and kept under tension. From the side of the warp another thread (called the woof or weft) was inserted, over the first warp thread, then under the next, and so on until it was passed through the entire warp. To aid this process, the woof thread was attached to a small flat piece of wood or bone, called the \b shuttle\b*. The shuttle, with the woof thread attached, was passed successively back and forth through the warp to form the interwoven cloth. \fig |WEB-0343_loom_en.jpg|col||Source unknown|Loom|1.0\fig*
\key 1.5.3.1
\title Thread, string, yarn
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חוּט
\trl chut
\ref H00101402300006 H00600201800018 H00701601200058 H02100401200024 H02200400300004
\heb פָּתִיל
\trl pathil
\ref H00103801800026 H00103802500054 H00202802800030 H00202803700010 H00203900300018 H00203902100026 H00203903100008 H00401503800046 H00401901500016 H00701600900046 H02604000300026
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0395_piece_string.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|String|1.0\fig* Thread or yarn for weaving was made by twisting fibers on a spindle (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3">1.5.3 Cloth manufacture\l*). A single strand of thread made in this way was not particularly strong, but cloth made by interweaving many of these thin strands together was strong enough for many uses. See also \l target="REALIA:1.14">1.14 Rope, cord\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The essential difference between “thread” or “string” and “cord” or “rope” was less in its thickness than in its composition. A rope or cord was made of two or more single strands twisted or braided together. All the occurrences of the Hebrew word \i pathil\i* are listed here, but in one or two of the passages the translator may consider that a heavier cord is intended.
\line In \s H00203900300018\s* the Hebrew word \i pathil\i* is used to refer to fine “threads” (\a RSV\a*, \a CEV\a*) or “strands” (\a NIV\a*) made of gold. Some languages may have a separate word for such a “filament” made of metal.
\key 1.5.3.2
\title Spindle
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Spindle\b*:
\heb כִּישׁוֹר
\trl kishor
\ref H02003101900010
\heb פֶּלֶךְ
\trl pelek
\ref H01000302900046 H02003101900018
\line \b Whorl\b*:
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0344_spindle_en.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Spindle|1.0\fig*After the fibers had been drawn out, one end of the fibers was attached to the spindle, which was a short, oblong stick with a weight on the top (the whorl). The spindle was suspended in the air and spun, thus spinning the attached fibers into a thread. As the thread grew longer, it was then wrapped around the middle of the spindle until all of the fiber had been drawn out and spun.
\line The action of the spindle resulted in a strong “spun thread.” The Hebrew word for this spun or twisted thread is \i shazar\i* (always appearing in the form \i moshzar\i*) in \s H02003101900010\s*, \s H00202603100024\s*, \s H00202603600032\s*; \s H00202700900032\s*, \s H00202701600034\s*, \s H00202701800036\s*; \s H00202800600028\s*, \s H00202800800038\s*, \s H00202801500040\s*; \s H00203600800032\s*, \s H00203603500028\s*, \s H00203603700032\s*; \s H00203800900028\s*, \s H00203801600014\s*, \s H00203801800032\s*; \s H00203900200030\s*, \s H00203900500038\s*, \s H00203900800040\s*, \s H00203902400028\s*, \s H00203902800036 H00203902900012\s*, and the Greek word is \i klōthō\i* in \s L07104501000028\s*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0345_spindle_en.jpg|col||© Rita Willaert|Woman using a spindle|1.0\fig* \s H02003101900010\s*: The literal \a RSV\a* translation of this verse reads “She puts her hands to the distaff, and her hands hold the spindle,” but this will communicate little to modern readers in most cultures. Common-language translations generally describe the activity of the woman rather than the specific instruments she is using. \a GNT\a* has “She spins her own thread and weaves her own cloth.” \a NCV\a* goes one step further, describing the act of spinning: “She makes thread with her hands and weaves her own cloth.” \a CEV\a* has attempted to simplify this verse even further but has probably gone too far with “She spins her own cloth”; a person does not “spin” cloth, even if the intended audience understands the operation of spinning.
\key 1.5.3.3
\title Weaver’s beam
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מָנוֹר, ארג
\trl mnor ’orgim
\ref H00901700700014 H01002101900054 H01301102300044 H01302000500046
\grk ἱστός
\trl histos
\ref L08501101200058
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0346_loom_en.jpg|col||© CristianChirita|Vertical loom|1.0\fig*The weaver’s beam was a wooden rod approximately 5-6 centimeters (2-2.5 inches) in diameter. The length could vary. Around this beam the warp threads were attached, and the cloth was rolled on it as it grew in length.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line See \l target="REALIA:1.5.3">1.5.3 Cloth manufacture\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In the Old Testament references, it is the exceptional size of each giant’s spear that is in focus. In \s H00901700700014\s* \a CEV\a* has taken into account that weaving on a hand loom is little known today in western English-speaking countries, so it has omitted reference to the weaver’s beam by saying “and his spear was so big . . . .” Where hand weaving is not commonly known, translators may want to follow this pattern. Another possible model is “and the shaft of his spear was twice as thick as an ordinary spear . . . .”
\line The Greek word \i histos\i* in \s L08501101200058\s* may refer to either the beam or the entire loom. It is usually not necessary to render this word literally; compare \a NRSV\a* “a piece she had woven” or \a NJB\a* “a piece of work.”
\key 1.5.3.4
\title Shuttle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֶרֶג
\trl ’ereg
\ref H00701601400044 H01800700600008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The shuttle was the small device used by the weaver to carry the “woof” (or “weft”) thread from one side of the loom to the other. The shuttle darted quickly across the loom, between the “warp” threads, leaving the woof thread stretched behind. The warp threads then closed over and under the woof thread, holding it in place. In this way another line of thread was added to form the cloth. A skilled weaver caused this to happen quite rapidly, with the shuttle moving back and forth constantly, until a whole piece of cloth was formed. See \l target="REALIA:1.5.3">1.5.3 Cloth manufacture\l* and the illustrations there.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line When Samson was startled from sleep in \s H00701601301000 H00701601400044\s*, he tore apart the various elements of the makeshift loom Delilah had prepared for weaving his hair. These included the “pin,” the “shuttle,” and the “fabric,” into which she had woven Samson’s hair. Some translations (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*) inaccurately render the Hebrew word \i ’ereg\i* as “loom” here.
\line In \s H01800700600008\s* one day is compared to one swift movement of the shuttle.
\key 1.5.3.5
\title Beater, batten, pin
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb יָתֵד
\trl yathed
\ref H00701601400010 H00701601400040
\cont \u Description and translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i yathed\i*, which appears twice in \s H00701601400010\s*, has been understood in various ways. It is possible that Delilah tried to anchor Samson’s hair to the ground with a kind of tent peg, which is the normal meaning of the word (see \l target="REALIA:3.2.2">3.2.2 Tent peg, stake\l*). However, it seems more likely that \i yathed\i* here refers to part of the weaving equipment used by Delilah. One possibility is that it was a peg in the wall from which were hung the vertical threads. This possibility is given in the \a CEV\a* rendering, which reads “While Samson was asleep, Delilah wove his braids into the threads on a loom and nailed the loom to a wall. Then she shouted, ‘Samson, the Philistines are attacking!’ Samson woke up and pulled the loom free from its posts in the ground and from the nails in the wall. Then he pulled his hair free from the woven cloth.” It is perhaps most likely that \i yathed\i* here refers to a kind of bar that was used to push the woof threads down tight (along with Samson’s hair). This is reflected in the rendering of \a RSV\a*, which has “So while he slept, Delilah took the seven locks of his head and wove them into the web. And she made them tight with the pin, and said to him, ‘The Philistines are upon you, Samson!’ But he awoke from his sleep, and pulled away the pin, the loom, and the web.”
\key 1.5.3.6
\title Woven or knitted material
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb דַּלָּה
\trl dalah
\ref H02303801200030
\heb עֵרֶב
\trl ‘erev
\ref H00201203800006 H00301304800012 H00301304900044 H00301305100050 H00301305200026 H00301305300044 H00301305600062 H00301305700030 H00301305800018 H00301305900032 H01601300300022 H02402502000010 H02405003700022 H02603000500018
\heb שְׁתִי
\trl shthi
\ref H00301304800006 H00301304900036 H00301305100042 H00301305200018 H00301305300036 H00301305600054 H00301305700022 H00301305800012 H00301305900026 H02101001700038
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0347_weaving.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Woven cloth|1.0\fig* See \l target="REALIA:1.5.3">1.5.3 Cloth manufacture\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The following is adapted from \i A Handbook on Leviticus\i* at \s H00301304800012\s* (page 200): Older translations such as the King James Version (\a KJV\a*) and \a RSV\a* translated the Hebrew words \i shthi\i* and \i ‘erev\i* as “warp” and “woof,” and this is the meaning that the words of the text have taken in modern Hebrew. Such a rendering indicates the threads going in different directions in the cloth. However, it is highly unlikely that this is the meaning of the text. It is difficult to see how the threads going in one direction could be affected by the mildew without affecting those running at right angles to them. The requirement that the affected part be torn out does not make sense either (verse 56), because this would destroy the whole garment. While the interpretation is far from certain, the meaning of these words is probably “woven or knitted material,” as in \a NAB\a*, \a TOB\a* and \a NIV\a* (similarly American Translation [\a AT\a*]). \a GNT\a* has reduced this to “piece [of clothing],” but such a reduction should probably be avoided in the receptor language, if possible.
\line In \s H02303801200030\s* Hezekiah is complaining that his life is to be cut short. He uses a weaving metaphor to say that his life is like cloth cut off from the warp, the vertical threads of the loom.
\key 1.5.3.7
\title Linen
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֵטוּן
\trl ’etun
\ref H02000701600010
\heb בַּד
\trl bad
\ref H00202804200010 H00203902800032 H00300600300012 H00300600300018 H00301600400004 H00301600400014 H00301600400028 H00301600400038 H00301602300024 H00301603200044 H00900201800020 H00902201800082 H01000601400028 H01301502700062 H02600900300050 H02600900300050 H02600901100014 H02601000200016 H02601000600020 H02601000700054 H02701000500024 H02701200600016 H02701200700016
\heb בּוּץ
\trl buts
\ref H01300402100034 H01301502700012 H01400201300084 H01400301400024 H01400501200042 H01700100600016 H01700801500042 H02602701600024
\heb סָדִין
\trl sadin (see \l target="REALIA:6.3">6.3 Shirt, tunic\l*)
\ref H00701401200048 H00701401300026 H02003102400002 H02300302300012
\heb פֵּשֶׁת
\trl pishteh
\ref H00301304700030 H00301304800018 H00301305200040 H00301305900020 H00502201100012 H02401300100020 H02604000300028 H02604401700024 H02604401800004 H02604401800016
\heb שֵׁשׁ
\trl shesh
\ref H00104104200038 H00202500400018 H00202600100016 H00202603100022 H00202603600030 H00202700900030 H00202701600032 H00202701800034 H00202800600026 H00202800800036 H00202801500038 H00202803900010 H00202803900018 H00203500600018 H00203502300028 H00203502500052 H00203503500056 H00203600800030 H00203603500026 H00203603700030 H00203800900026 H00203801600012 H00203801800030 H00203802300058 H00203900300062 H00203900500036 H00203900800038 H00203902700012 H00203902800010 H00203902800022 H00203902800034 H00203902900010 H02003102200008 H02601601000022 H02601601300016 H02602700700002
\grk βύσσινος
\trl bussinos
\ref G06601801200022 G06601801600020 G06601900800012 G06601900800022 G06601901400028 L08100300600034
\grk βύσσος
\trl bussos
\ref G04201601900020
\grk λίνον, λινοῦς
\trl linon, linous
\ref G06601500600030 L06801600800022
\grk ὀθόνιον
\trl othonion
\ref G04202401200026 G04301904000020 G04302000500012 G04302000600032 G04302000700026
\grk σινδών
\trl sindōn
\ref G04002705900020 G04101405100014 G04101405200010 G04101504600006 G04101504600016 G04202305300010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0348_wrapped_linen.jpg|col||© Biblioteca Museu Víctor Balaguer|Strips of linen used to wrap mummified bodies in Egypt|1.0\fig*Linen is a high quality cloth made from the stems of the flax plant. It was known for its strength and coolness.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Most flax in Israel was imported from Egypt and used for a wide range of products. The Bible mentions bed coverings, sails of ships, garments for the priests, furnishings for the tabernacle, burial clothes, and other things. See also \i Plants and Trees in the Bible\i*, \l target="FLORA:5.1.7">5.1.7 Flax (linen)\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages there is no term for “linen,” and though a word for “linen” may be borrowed, what is important in many contexts is primarily the quality of the cloth, not the material from which it was made. Accordingly, many translators have used an expression such as “fine [white] cloth” or “good cloth.” In some cases it will be possible to say “cloth made from the fibers of a plant.” It may be necessary to add an explanatory footnote.
\line In several passages the important characteristic of linen is that it causes less perspiration than other cloths (see \s H00203902701000 H00203902801000 H00203902901000\s*; \s H00300601001000\s*; \s H00301600401000\s*; \s H02604401701000 H02604401801000\s*). Where linen is not known, translators should choose a cloth with a similar characteristic.
\line In \s G04002705900020 G04101504600006\s*; and \s G04202305300010\s*, the Greek word \i sindōn\i* describes the cloth with which Jesus’ body was wrapped for burial. This is also true for the Greek word \i othonion\i* in \s G04202401200026 G04301904000020 G04302000500012 G04302000600032 G04302000700026\s*. Where a language has a special word for such a “burial cloth” or “shroud,” it should be used.
\key 1.5.3.8
\title Wool
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb צֶמֶר
\trl tsemer
\ref H00301304800026 H00301305200032 H00301305900014 H00502201100008 H02305100800020 H02604401700036
\grk ἔριον
\trl erion
\ref G05800901900048
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Wool is the soft wavy hair of sheep and certain other animals. It was used to weave a fabric from which clothing was made.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages translators may have to render “wool” as “cloth made from the hair of a sheep.”
\key 1.5.3.9
\title Silk
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מֶשִׁי
\trl meshi
\ref H02601601000028 H02601601300022
\grk σιρικόν
\trl sirikon
\ref G06601801200030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Silk was a fine, expensive cloth made from the fiber produced by the silkworm in making its cocoon.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Translations and commentaries vary on the translation of the Hebrew word \i meshi\i* in \s H02601601000028 H02601601300022\s*. The traditional translation has been “silk,” which is still followed by many versions (\a KJV\a*, \a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*, \a NCV\a*). Others consider this to be unlikely in the time of Ezekiel, when silk was not yet known in the Middle East. It has been suggested that the word indicates a kind of veil worn by the woman, hiding her face from others but allowing her to see out. Translations that reject “silk” as the proper translation usually find a more general term. Compare \a CEV\a* “most expensive robes,” \a NRSV\a* “rich fabric,” \a GECL\a* “a beautiful, woven robe,” \a TOB\a* “expensive cloth,” and \a REB\a* “fine linen.”
\line In the first-century A.D. setting of \s G06601801200030\s*, it is quite possible to speak of proper silk. However, it cannot be determined from the context of this verse whether the Greek word \i sirikos\i* refers simply to cloth or to garments made of silk.
\key 1.5.3.10
\title Purple cloth
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַרְגְּוָן
\trl ’argewan
\ref H01400200600054 A02700500700060 A02700501600054 A02700502900018
\heb אַרְגָּמָן
\trl ’argaman
\ref H00202500400008 H00202600100026 H00202603100012 H00202603600020 H00202701600022 H00202800600018 H00202800800026 H00202801500028 H00202803300016 H00203500600008 H00203502300018 H00203502500036 H00203503500040 H00203600800040 H00203603500016 H00203603700020 H00203801800020 H00203802300040 H00203900300040 H00203900800028 H00203902400020 H00203902900020 H00400401300020 H00700802600050 H01400201300070 H01400301400016 H01700100600020 H01700801500046 H02003102200012 H02200301000014 H02200700600022 H02401000900034 H02602700700030 H02602701600016
\heb חָמוּץ
\trl chamuts
\ref H02306300100012
\heb כַּרְמִיל
\trl karmil
\ref H01400200600058 H01400201300070 H01400301400020
\heb שָׁנִי
\trl shani
\ref H00103802800032 H00103803000018 H00600201800022 H00600202100032 H01000102400016 H02003102100022 H02200400300008 H02300101800024 H02400403000020
\heb תלע
\trl tala‘
\ref H03400200400012
\heb תּוֹלָע
\trl tola‘
\ref H02300101800042 H02500400500024
\heb תּוֹלַעַת, שָׁנִי
\trl tola‘ath shani, shni tola‘ath
\ref H00202500400012 H00202600100030 H00202603100016 H00202603600024 H00202701600026 H00202800600020 H00202800600022 H00202800800030 H00202801500032 H00202803300020 H00203500600012 H00203502300022 H00203502500040 H00203503500044 H00203600800044 H00203603500020 H00203603700024 H00203801800024 H00203802300046 H00203900300048 H00203900300052 H00203900500030 H00203900800032 H00203902400024 H00203902900024 H00301400400036 H00301400600030 H00301404900028 H00301405100026 H00301405200066 H00400400800010 H00401900600020
\heb תְּכֵלֶת
\trl tekeleth
\ref H00202500400004 H00202600100022 H00202600400008 H00202603100008 H00202603600016 H00202701600018 H00202800600014 H00202800800022 H00202801500024 H00202802800032 H00202803100016 H00202803300012 H00202803700012 H00203801800016 H00203802300032 H00203900300030 H00203900500022 H00203900800024 H00203902200020 H00203902400016 H00203902900016 H00203903100010 H00400400700016 H00400400900008 H00400401100016 H00400401200036 H00401503800048 H01400200600062 H01400201300076 H01400301400012 H01700100600008 H01700801500024 H02401000900030 H02602300600004 H02602700700026 H02602702400014
\grk κόκκινος
\trl kokkinos
\ref G04002702800010 G05800901900050 G06601700400016 G06601801200034 G06601801600028
\grk κόκκος
\trl kokkos
\ref L07104501000030
\grk πορφύρα
\trl porfura
\ref G04101501700008 G04101502000016 G04201601900016 G06601801200026 L06801002100030 L07104501000014 L07300107100008 L07700402300036 L07700801400026 L07701002000036 L07701006200028 L07701006400030 L07701105800034 L07701404300056 L07701404400058 L07800403800018 L08100300600004
\grk πορφυροῦς
\trl porfurous
\ref G04301900200028 G04301900500024 G06601700400012 G06601801600024 L07300101100008
\grk πορφυρόπωλις
\trl porfuropōlis
\ref G04401601400012
\grk ὑακίνθινος
\trl huakinthinos
\ref L07100603000024 L07104000400006
\grk ὑάκινθος
\trl huakinthos
\ref L07104501000010 L07700402300032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Purple cloth was a reddish-purple cloth dyed with substances obtained from several natural sources. The primary source was the murex shellfish. Another source (referred to in the Hebrew words with the root \i tla‘\i*) was a small worm. The dying process could yield a variety of colors, ranging from a dark red through purple to blue. (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.14">1.5.3.14 Dye\l*.)
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The relatively limited source for the purple color and the complicated process for its production made purple cloth extremely expensive and thus available only to kings and the richest families. In time the color came to be associated with royalty, although only several centuries after biblical times did legislation actually forbid its use by people outside the royal family.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages there is no special color term for reddish-purple, since the color in question is sometimes classified as a kind of blue and in other instances it is related to black. Sometimes it may be described as “dark red” or even “bluish red.” However, in all languages it is possible to be somewhat more precise about color terms by likening the color to that of a local flower, bird, or something else.
\line In many verses in Exodus (for example, \s H00202500400008\s*), three colors in this range are mentioned together. Many translations have “blue,” “purple,” and “scarlet/red.” Where possible the translator should find three colors within this range. \i A Handbook on Exodus\i* (page 582) has the following helpful comments on \s H00202500401000\s*: “It may be difficult to distinguish between the three colors, or they are all various shades of a mixture of red and blue. The difference between the words for \b blue\b* and \b purple\b* seems to be that the first has more blue and the second has more red. But both colors were purple. \a NJB\a* translates these tow terms as ‘violet-purple’ and ‘red-purple.’ ” For guidelines on translating the color purple, see \i A Handbook on The Gospel of Mark\i*, page 482.
\line In many of the references to purple cloth, the important element is not the color but the high rank implied by cloth of that color. Translators may prefer to make this information explicit. For example, at \s L07701006400030\s* for the literal clause “saw him clothed in purple” (\a RSV\a*), \a GNT\a* has “saw him clothed in royal robes.”
\line If it is necessary to designate what kind of cloth was dyed purple, translators should, where possible, choose a cloth that indicates high rank or dignity.
\key 1.5.3.11
\title Embroidered cloth, needlework
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַעֲשֶׂה, רקם
\trl ma‘aseh roqem
\ref H00202603600034 H00202701600036 H00202803900026 H00203603700034 H00203801800012 H00203902900028
\heb רִקְמָה
\trl riqmah
\ref H00700503000034 H00700503000038 H01904501500004 H02601601000006 H02601601300026 H02601601800010 H02602601600034 H02602700700006 H02602701600020 H02602702400018
\grk ποικιλτής
\trl poikiltēs
\ref L07104501000018
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0349_embroidered_cloth.jpg|col||© EgyAr|Embroidered cloth|1.0\fig* Embroidered cloth was cloth into which decorative patterns or figures were sewn by hand. Because of the extra work that went into it, embroidered cloth was expensive.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where there is no word for “embroidery,” it is possible to use a descriptive expression; for example, in \s H00202603600034\s* \a NCV\a* has “Someone who can sew well is to sew designs on it,” and in \s H02602700700006\s* it says “linen with designs sewed on it.” Where even this is difficult to express in the receptor language, translators may say simply “fancy linen” or “decorated cloth.”
\key 1.5.3.12
\title Patch
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb טלא
\trl tala’ (verb)
\ref H00600900500010
\grk ἐπίβλημα
\trl epiblēma
\ref G04000901600008 G04100202100004 G04200503600018 G04200503600064
\grk πλήρωμα
\trl plērōma
\ref G04000901600026 G04100202100028
\grk ῥάκος
\trl rhakos
\ref G04000901600010 G04100202100006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0350_patch.jpg|col||Gary Todd|Patches sewn on an old waterskin|1.0\fig*The patch was a piece of cloth or leather sewed on clothing or shoes to repair a hole or tear.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00600900500010\s*: The shoes of the Gibeonite messengers had been “patched” many times, that is, repaired with pieces of leather.
\line \s G04000901600008\s* and \s G04100202100004\s*: The statement that “No one patches up an old coat with a piece of new cloth” (\a GNT\a*) seems almost preposterous or incredible in some societies, since people habitually repair old clothing by putting on patches of new cloth, sometimes to the point where it is difficult to determine what was the original fabric. However, the Greek phrase \i rhakous agnafou\i*, often translated “new cloth,” is literally “unshrunken cloth,” that is, cloth that has not been washed several times to shrink it (\a DUCL\a* “patch that has never been shrunken”; similarly \a RSV\a*, \a REB\a*, \a NJB\a*).
\key 1.5.3.13
\title Linen cloth, sheet
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ὀθόνη
\trl othonē
\ref G04401001100022 G04401100500032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The sheet was a large piece of cloth, usually of linen (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Greek word \i othonē\i* is a general term for a piece of linen cloth that was used for a variety of objects, including a cloth that a person could wrap around himself as clothing or a sail for a boat. In its context in Acts, it has four corners and is large enough to hold a large number of animals. In translation it will not normally be necessary to indicate that the “cloth” or “sheet” was made of linen.
\key 1.5.3.14
\title Dye
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אדם
\trl m’adam
\ref H00202500500008 H00202601400018 H00203500700008 H00203502300040 H00203601900018 H00203903400016
\heb צֶבַע
\trl tseva‘
\ref H00700503000024 H00700503000032 H00700503000036
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Dye was a substance used to color materials, especially textiles. Dyes came from minerals, plants, insects (for example, all those based on the Hebrew root \i tla‘\i* were from a small worm), and sea animals (in particular, certain mollusks).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Translators and commentators differ concerning the exact meaning of the Hebrew word \i m’adam\i*. Most understand it to mean that the rams’ skins or sheep­skins (which it always modifies) have been “dyed red” (\a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a NJB\a*) or “colored red” (\a FRCL\a*, \a PV\a*). However, \a RSV\a*, \a CEV\a*, and \a REB\a* say “tanned” (see \l target="REALIA:1.13">1.13 Leather\l*).
\key 1.6
\title Commerce
\index \l target="REALIA:1.6.1">1.6.1 Balance scales\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.6.2">1.6.2 Stone weights\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.6.3">1.6.3 Money, coins\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.6.4">1.6.4 Bank, table\l*
\key 1.6.1
\title Balance scales
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מֹאזְנַיִם
\trl m’oznayim
\ref H00301903600002 H01800600200020 H01803100600006 H01906201000018 H02001100100002 H02001601100006 H02002002300014 H02304001200058 H02304001500020 H02403201000032 H02600500100048 H02604501000002 H02801200800008 H03000800500052 H03300601100008
\arm מֹאזְנֵא
\trl mo’zne’
\ref A02700502700008
\heb פֶּלֶס
\trl peles
\ref H02001601100002 H02304001200048
\heb קָנֶה
\trl qaneh
\ref H02304600600020
\grk ζυγός
\trl zugos
\ref G06600600500052 L07102102500020 L07102802500012 L07104200400006
\grk πλάστιγξ
\trl plastigx
\ref L07001102200010 L07800900800032
\grk ῥοπή
\trl rhopē
\ref L07100102200016
\grk σταθμός
\trl stathmion, stathmos
\ref L07100601500018 L07102601500018 L07102802500016
\lat statera
\ref V08200303400010 V08200403600034
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0351_balance_scales.jpg|col||Gary Todd|Balance scales|1.0\fig*The balance scales were an instrument for weighing objects. Ancient balance scales often consisted of a rod held by a cord or a chain in the middle and with pans attached to both ends.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Weights were placed in one pan, while the items to be weighed were placed in the other. When the rod was parallel to the ground, then the items in the two pans were of equal weight.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Balance scales” may be rendered in some languages as “tool for weighing” or “instrument for knowing how much something weighs.” The translator should avoid using an anachronistic word for modern types of scales, such as a spring scale or a hydraulic scale.
\line \fig |KNW-0396_balance_scales.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man using balance scales|1.0\fig*Weights (and also measures of volume) from different time periods have been uncovered in various archaeological sites. The weights generally were made of stone, were spherical in shape, and were identified by having their names engraved on them. Because of their rustic manufacture, they were not “accurate” or “just” in a precise modern sense. However, they served as normative standards in a given period and region, although they differed according to time and place. For this reason the equivalents in terms of modern weights are only approximate.
\line Because the ancient scale compared the relative weights of two objects, in the intertestamental period it became a symbol for considering the relative value or right and wrong of two activities or choices. Compare the English idiom “weigh his actions.” This figurative usage appears in \s L07100102200024 L07102102500020 L07102802500012\s*; and to a slightly lesser extent in \s A02700502700008\s*. Translators will often prefer to abandon the physical object and translate according to the meaning; compare \a GNT\a* at \s L07102102500020\s*, which reads “the wise will consider the consequences of what they say.” Similarly, at \s L07100102200024\s*, instead of the literal text “a man’s anger tips the scale to his ruin” (\a RSV\a*), \a GNT\a* has “it [anger] can bring about your downfall.”
\key 1.6.2
\title Stone weights
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֶבֶן
\trl ’even
\ref H00301903600006 H00502501300012 H00502501300016 H00502501500002 H01001402600058 H02001100100012 H02001601100018 H02002001000002 H02002001000006 H02002002300006 H02002002300010 H03300601100018
\grk σταθμίον
\trl stathmion
\ref L07104200400010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0352_weights.jpg|col||© Chamberi|Stone weights|1.0\fig* Stones of various sizes and weights were used on balance scales to determine the price of produce being sold (see \l target="REALIA:1.6.1">1.6.1 Balance scales\l*). The stones were usually marked with their weights.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In most of the references above, the weights are a means of determining the amount to be paid for something; that is, they are a tool for conducting business dealings. So in some of the passages the reference to weights may be left implied; for example, in \s H02001601100018\s* \a CEV\a* has “The LORD doesn’t like it when we cheat in business.”
\line While the Hebrew word \i ’even\i* literally means “stone,” in the references listed above, where the translator decides to indicate the physical object, it will normally be best to translate \i ’even\i* as “weight.”
\key 1.6.3
\title Money, coins
