\key 1.7.1
\title Scroll, book
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מְגִלָּה
\trl mgilah
\ref A01500600200022 H02403600600016 H02403601400038 H02403601400078 H02403602100022 H02403602300056 H02403602500034 H02403602900028 H02403603200008 H02600300100026 H02600300200018 H02600300300026 H03800500100020 H03800500200022
\heb מְגִלָּה, סֵפֶר
\trl mgilath sefer
\ref H01904000800012 H02403600200006 H02403600400044 H02600200900022
\heb סֵפֶר
\trl sefer
\ref H00100500100004 H00201701400022 H00202400700006 H00203203200024 H00203203300024 H00400502300024 H00402101400010 H00501701800036 H00502400100046 H00502400300020 H00502805800034 H00502806100022 H00502901900056 H00502902000036 H00502902600042 H00503001000030 H00503102400030 H00503102600006 H00600100800006 H00600803100028 H00600803400040 H00601001300034 H00601800900038 H00602300600028 H00602402600020 H00901002500030 H01000101800022 H01001101400018 H01001101500010 H01101104100032 H01101401900026 H01101402900028 H01101500700028 H01101502300046 H01101503100028 H01101600500030 H01101601400028 H01101602000028 H01101602700032 H01102100800006 H01102100800026 H01102100800028 H01102100900010 H01102101100050 H01102203900052 H01102204600034 H01200101800024 H01200500500018 H01200500600008 H01200500600030 H01200500700018 H01200802300028 H01201000100022 H01201000200012 H01201000600008 H01201000700012 H01201003400034 H01201202000028 H01201300800032 H01201301200044 H01201400600024 H01201401500042 H01201401800020 H01201402800060 H01201500600028 H01201501100016 H01201501500024 H01201502100028 H01201502600024 H01201503100024 H01201503600024 H01201601900024 H01201901400012 H01202001200024 H01202002000060 H01202101700036 H01202102500024 H01202200800022 H01202200800024 H01202201000022 H01202201100018 H01202201300034 H01202201300076 H01202201600038 H01202300200078 H01202300300098 H01202302100040 H01202302400086 H01202302800028 H01202400500028 H01300900100018 H01401601100026 H01401700900014 H01402003400040 H01402402700034 H01402500400028 H01402502600030 H01402700700026 H01402802600030 H01403201700004 H01403203200034 H01403401400032 H01403401500018 H01403401500020 H01403401600012 H01403401800022 H01403402100036 H01403402100088 H01403402400046 H01403403000072 H01403403100090 H01403501200048 H01403502700022 H01403600800032 H01600700500046 H01600800100054 H01600800300072 H01600800500010 H01600800800010 H01600801800008 H01600900300016 H01601202300016 H01601300100016 H01700102200006 H01700202300030 H01700301300006 H01700600100030 H01700800500064 H01700801000032 H01700902000022 H01700902500022 H01700903000006 H01700903200028 H01701000200040 H01801902300022 H01803103500022 H01906902900006 H01913901600012 H02101201200016 H02302901100020 H02302901100038 H02302901100036 H02302901200008 H02302901200018 H02302901200038 H02302901800022 H02303000800018 H02303400400022 H02303401600008 H02303701400012 H02303900100024 H02305000100012 H02400300800030 H02402501300044 H02402900100010 H02402902500030 H02402902900016 H02403000200036 H02403201000010 H02403201100008 H02403201200010 H02403201200052 H02403201400020 H02403201400028 H02403201400050 H02403201600016 H02403204400008 H02403600800034 H02403601000012 H02403601100030 H02403601300032 H02403601800040 H02403603200026 H02404500100040 H02405106000026 H02405106300018 H02700100400070 H02700101700032 H02700900200022 H02701200100094 H02701200400020 H03400100100006 H03900301600030
\grk βιβλαρίδιον
\trl biblaridion
\ref G06601000200014 G06601000900022 G06601001000008
\grk βιβλίον
\trl biblion
\ref G04001900700016 G04101000400012 G04200401700008 G04200401700022 G04200402000008 G04302003000040 G04302102500046 G04800301000046 G05500401300026 G05800901900062 G05801000700014 G06600101100012 G06600500100022 G06600500200026 G06600500300034 G06600500400020 G06600500500048 G06600500800010 G06600500900020 G06600601400012 G06601000800036 G06601300800036 G06601700800066 G06602001200030 G06602001200038 G06602001200068 G06602102700042 G06602200700026 G06602200900042 G06602201000022 G06602201800022 G06602201800058 G06602201900018 G06602201900068 L06700701400018 L06701202000036 L06900902000016 L06901000200034 L07100100100010 L07100100100010 L07100100100062 L07105002700016 L07200100100012 L07200100300014 L07200101400008 L07700104400010 L07700105600006 L07700105700012 L07700304800008 L07701200900018 L07701402300044 L07701602400010 L07800201300052 L07800202300016 L08100101200034 L08100103100090 L08100201600062 L08100904500010
\grk βίβλος
\trl biblos
\ref G04000100100002 G04101202600022 G04200300400008 G04202004200012 G04400102000008 G04400704200032 G04401901900018 G05000400300054 G06600300500034 G06602001500016 L06700100100002 L07100100100028 L07102402300006 L07200100300052 L07200400100006 L07800601200014 L07800802300016 L08100103100012 L08100104000030 L08100504800020 L08100700600052 L08100700900042
\grk κεφαλίς
\trl kefalis
\ref G05801000700012
\grk τόμος
\trl tomos
\ref L08100602200050
\lat liber
\ref V08200100100002 V08200602000022 V08201203700012 V08201404400014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0397_scrolls.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Scrolls|1.0\fig* The scroll was a long strip of writing material made by sewing together sheets of papyrus or parchment. This strip was then rolled up from one end or from both ends to form one or two cylinders. Usually the ends of the scroll were attached to sticks, around which the scroll was rolled. An unrolled scroll was often about 10 meters (33 feet) in length. It stood approximately 23-25 centimeters (9-10 inches) high. See also the illustration at \l target="REALIA:1.7.2">1.7.2 Ink\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line A scroll was a convenient means to store a large amount of written text in a relatively small space. The text was written in parallel columns, usually on one side of the scroll.\fig |KNW-0398_reading_scroll.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man reading a scroll|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In the case of practically all terms for documents (for example, “letter,” “book,” “scroll”), the meaning involves not only the object on which the writing is done, but also the contents of the writing. In some languages a distinction must be made between these two aspects of such objects, and translators must make certain that the particular expression used in a receptor language will at least include the contents and not refer merely to the materials on which the words were written.
\line Scrolls varied in length but otherwise there was little difference between the physical construction of a short document and a long one. Thus, for example, the Hebrew word \i sefer\i* may indicate a longer document (“book”), or it can also designate something shorter, which may best be translated “letter,” “writing,” or even “document”; for example, \a GNT\a* renders it “papers” in \s H00502400100046\s* and “letter” in \s H01200500600008\s*.
\line Exceptionally long books might be written on more than one scroll. The Greek word \i kefalis\i* in \s G05801000700014\s* refers to one such section or scroll of a book.
\line The codex, or bound book with individual pages, only came into use in the first century B.C. and in common use only a century or two later. Thus, all references to books in the Old Testament, in the Deuterocanon, and probably in the New Testament are to scrolls. Nevertheless, the closest equivalent in most languages for “scroll” is the term used today for “book,” and this will normally be the proper translation.
\line In \s H02302901101000 H02302901201000\s* the Hebrew verb \i yada’\i* (“know”) occurs with the word \i sefer\i* to indicate the ability to read and should be translated “knows how to read” ( \a GNT\a*) or “can read” (\a RSV\a*). In \s H02700100400070\s* the word \i sefer\i* may indicate either “literature/writings” (\a NRSV\a*, \a SPCL\a*, \a REB\a*) or the ability “to read and write” (\a GNT\a*). In some languages the idea of literature may be unfamiliar, but there will probably be some way of talking about “written things,” and this may be the nearest equivalent available.
\line \s L06700701400018\s*: On the scroll in this passage were written the terms of agreement between a man and a woman entering into marriage. Almost all cultures know some means by which two parties agree to a marriage. If this is a written document, then the name for that document may be used.
\key 1.7.2
\title Ink
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb דְּיוֹ
\trl dyow
\ref H02403601800046
\grk μέλας
\trl melas
\ref G04700300300022 G06300101200020 G06400101300018
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0051_scribe_at_work.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz|Writing on a scroll with a reed pen|1.0\fig* Ink was a dark liquid used in writing or marking. Because it was difficult to store liquids for any length of time in the dry conditions of the Middle East, ink was sometimes made from black charcoal carbon. This was mixed with gum or oil and then dried. When the scribe was ready to write, he dipped his pen tip in water and then rubbed it on the ink block. The water dissolved a small amount of the carbon, forming the ink.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The use of ink is so universal at the present time that some term or expression for it is almost inevitable in all languages. In some cases the equivalent is a descriptive phrase, for example, “black stain” or “writing mark.”
\key 1.7.3
\title Pen
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb עֵט, סֹפֵר
\trl ‘et sofer
\ref H01904500200022 H02400800800030
\grk κάλαμος
\trl kalamos
\ref G06400101300022 L07900402000022
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The pen was a reed especially cut for making marks with ink on writing material. It was about 20 centimeters (8 inches) long and was sharpened on one end and split to form a nib. Sometimes it could be made of a rush cut at an angle and then frayed to form a fine brush.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line See \l target="REALIA:1.7.2">1.7.2 Ink\l*.
\key 1.7.4
\title Writing case
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קֶסֶת, סֹפֵר
\trl qeseth sofer
\ref H02600900200056 H02600900300054 H02600901100022
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0354_pen.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Pens in a case|1.0\fig*The writing case was a small box, usually made of wood, for carrying several pens (1.7.2) and sometimes a cake of dried ink (1.7.4). Inside the case, in addition to several reed pens, there were receptacles where the ink was mixed at the time of writing. A person generally carried this case by hanging it from his belt. Sometimes the object for mixing the ink had the shape of a palette, with two circular hollows for two colors of ink, and was carried by hanging it from a cord.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The closest equivalent in many languages for “writing case” would be “pencil case,” but this could sound anachronistic. It is also possible to render it with a descriptive phrase, such as “a small box in which he carried pens” or “. . . in which he carried writing instruments.”\fig |KNW-0399_writing_case_pen_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Writing case and pen|1.0\fig*
\key 1.7.5
\title Stylus
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶרֶט
\trl cheret
\ref H02300800100026
\heb עֵט, בַּרְזֶל
\trl ‘et barzel
\ref H01801902400004 H02401700100010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0013_tablet_stylus.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Tablet and stylus|1.0\fig* The stylus was a short, sharp piece of iron.
\line It was held in the hand and the point was used to engrave marks, usually writing or drawing, on stone or metal.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It is not clear if \s H01801902400004\s* speaks of an engraving tool made of iron or of an iron surface on which the engraving took place. For the first half of this verse, \a HOTTP\a* suggests “on tablets of iron and lead” or “with a stylus and lead [meaning melted lead placed into the spaces of the inscription].”
\line The Hebrew phrase \i cheret ’enosh\i* in \s H02300800100026\s* has been the subject of much debate. Some translations choose to preserve the implement used (\a KJV\a* “man’s pen”; \a NIV\a* “ordinary pen”; \a NJB\a* “ordinary stylus”), while others prefer a rendering that focuses on the words being written (\a RSV\a* “common characters”; \a CEV\a* “big clear letters”; \a NLT\a* “clearly write”).
\key 1.7.6
\title Writing tablet, tablet of brass/bronze
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גִּלָּיוֹן
\trl gilayon
\ref H02300800100014
\heb לוּחַ
\trl luach
\ref H00202401200034 H00203101800028 H00203101800034 H00203201500022 H00203201500032 H00203201600006 H00203201600032 H00203201900056 H00203400100018 H00203400100036 H00203400100052 H00203400400008 H00203400400060 H00203402800044 H00203402900022 H00500401300036 H00500502200064 H00500900900014 H00500900900020 H00500901000014 H00500901100030 H00500901100036 H00500901500034 H00500901700012 H00501000100024 H00501000200010 H00501000200026 H00501000300018 H00501000300042 H00501000400010 H00501000500024 H01100800900014 H01400501000016 H02000300300022 H02000700300012 H02303000800010 H02401700100024 H03500200200024
\grk δέλτος
\trl deltos
\ref L07700802200020 L07701401800008 L07701402600056 L07701404800016
\grk πινακίδιον
\trl pinakidion
\ref G04200106300006
\lat buxus
\ref V08201402400010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0355_tablet.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Wax writing tablet|1.0\fig*The writing tablet was a small, flat board, normally made of wood. It was coated on one side with a thin layer of wax. A pointed stick or stylus was used to make marks and letters in the wax layer for short messages. After use, the wax could be smoothed out and used again. Several tablets could be connected along one edge by cord in order to make a kind of book. See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:1.7.5">1.7.5 Stylus\l*. It is possible that the Old Testament references are to tablets made of clay, metal or stone, on which words were scratched directly with a hard, pointed object.
\line The tablets mentioned in 1 Maccabees were flat pieces of polished brass or bronze on which words were inscribed. The sizes of these tablets are unknown, but they would probably not have been very large.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Translators should avoid a word that indicates a modern “tablet” of writing paper.
\line \s H02000300300022 H02000700300012 H02401700100024\s*: The Hebrew word \i luach\i* has a figurative meaning in these passages and may be rendered without reference to an actual writing tablet; for example, \a GNT\a* renders \s H02000700300012\s*b as “write it on your heart,” and \a ITCL\a* has “guard them in your heart like a treasure.”
\line Although one or two of the references with the Greek word \i deltos\i* speak of the tablets as containing “letters” (that is, correspondence), such tablets were not the normal medium for letters. According to \s L07700802200020\s*, they were special memorial documents, intended “as a memorial of peace and alliance” (\a RSV\a*). Some cultures may have special documents that are exchanged between people groups when they make treaties or alliances.
\key 1.7.7
\title Paper
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk χαρτηρία
\trl chartēria
\ref L07900402000012
\grk χάρτης
\trl chartēs
\ref G06300101200016
\lat carta
\ref V08201500200008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Paper was a material for writing on, made from the papyrus plant.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The name of any material commonly used in the receptor culture for writing letters on may serve as a rendering for the word “paper” in \s G06300101200016\s*.
\line In \s V08201500200008\s* the focus is not on the material on which the writing is done but on the writing itself. So for the literal text “cause them to be written on paper” (\a RSV\a*), \a GNT\a* has “have them written down.”
\key 1.7.8
\title Parchment
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk μεμβράνα
\trl membrana
\ref G05500401300032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Parchment was a sheet of specially prepared animal skin on which someone could write with pen and ink. The skins of sheep and goats were prepared by removing the hair, and then they were smoothed with lime.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Parchment was frequently the medium used in making scrolls (see \l target="REALIA:1.7.1">1.7.1 Scroll, book\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s G05500401300032\s* the reference may be to documents written on parchment or to blank sheets of parchment. It is probably best to understand Paul’s request at the end of this verse to be “bring the rolled-up books [scrolls], and especially the ones made from animal skins [leather].”
\key 1.8
\title Builders
\index \l target="REALIA:1.8.1">1.8.1 Brick mold, brickkiln\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.8.2">1.8.2 Brick\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.8.3">1.8.3 Plaster, stucco, whitewash\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.8.4">1.8.4 Squared stones for building\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.8.4.1">1.8.4.1 Stone plane, saw\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.8.5">1.8.5 Plumb line\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.8.6">1.8.6 Measuring rod, measuring line\l*
\key 1.8.1
\title Brick mold, brickkiln
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַלְבֵּן
\trl malben
\ref H01001203100058 H03400301400034
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0356_brick_mold.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Brick mold|1.0\fig*
\line \b Brick mold\b*: This was a small, rectangular wooden container (about 20-25 by 10 centimeters [8-10 by 4 inches]) used to form each brick into the same shape and size as the other bricks (see \l target="REALIA:1.8.2">1.8.2 Brick\l*).
\line \b Brickkiln\b*: This was a large outdoor oven for baking bricks to harden them (see the illustration at \l target="REALIA:1.11.1">1.11.1 Smelting furnace, kiln\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The mold was packed full with clay or other material from which bricks were made. Once the material was shaped, the brick was removed from the mold and left in the sun to dry. In some places the hardening process was facilitated by baking the bricks in a kiln or oven.\fig |WEB-0357_brick.jpg|col||© Ian Scott|Mud bricks|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H01001203100058\s*: The Hebrew word \i malben\i* is only a proposed \i qere\i* reading; it is unattested in any ancient manuscript or version. However, the text as it stands is unintelligible. \a HOTTP\a* suggests “brickkiln,” which is more or less what is found in most translations. \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a* have “making bricks,” \a NCV\a* uses “build with bricks,” and \a NRSV\a* has “brickworks.”
\line \s H03400301400034\s*: The following is adapted from \i A Handbook on The Books of Nahum, Habakkuk, and Zephaniah\i* (pages 55-56): The last half of this verse speaks about various parts of the process of making bricks. The first two parts are “go into the clay, tread the mortar” (\a RSV\a*). They refer to the trampling of the clay underfoot to make it soft enough to be shaped. \a GNT\a* drops the repetition and expresses this aspect of the brick making in a single clause: “Trample the clay to make bricks.” When the clay was soft enough, it was put into a brick mold. The bricks were then removed from the mold to dry in the sun. Nahum tells the people of Nineveh to “take hold of the brick mold” (\a RSV\a*), or as \a GNT\a* puts it more clearly, “get the brick molds ready.” The last half of this verse can also be rendered “Trample the clay that you use to make bricks, and prepare the brick molds” or “Use your feet to soften the clay that will be used to make bricks . . . .”
\line See also the discussion at \l target="REALIA:3.20.1">3.20.1 Pavement, The Pavement\l*.
\key 1.8.2
\title Brick
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לְבֵנָה
\trl lvenah
\ref H00101100300016 H00101100300034 H00200101400024 H00200500800010 H00200501600014 H00200501800024 H00200501900028 H02300900900002 H02306500300034 H02600400100014
\grk πλίνθος
\trl plinthos
\ref L06800501100026
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The brick was a building block made of clay in a mold and either dried in the sun or hardened in an oven.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Bricks were used as a building material, especially in places where stone or wood was scarce.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line For \s H02306500300034\s* see \l target="REALIA:4.2.4">4.2.4 Incense altar\l*.
\key 1.8.3
\title Plaster, stucco, whitewash
\cont \u References:\u*
\arm גִּיר
\trl gir
\ref A02700500500050
\heb טפל
\trl tafal (verb)
\ref H01801300400008 H01801401700012 H01911906900002
\heb שִׂיד, שׂיד
\trl sid
\ref H00502700200050 H00502700200058 H00502700400048 H00502700400056
\heb טוח, טִיחַ
\trl tuach (verb), tiach
\ref H00301404200032 H00301404300048 H00301404800038 H01302900400030 H02601301000040 H02601301100006 H02601301200024 H02601301200028 H02601301400014 H02601301500022 H02601301500046 H02602202800006
\heb תָּפֵל
\trl tafel
\ref H02601301000044 H02601301100008 H02601301400016 H02601301500026 H02602202800010
\grk κονιάω
\trl koniaō (verb)
\ref G04002302700020 G04402300300026
\grk ψαμμωτός
\trl psammōtos
\ref L07102201700016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0052_plaster_covering.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz|Plaster over stones|1.0\fig* Plaster was a wet, pasty material used to cover a wall. It filled in holes and cracks, and when it dried, it left the wall smooth. Different materials were used, among them mud or a composition of lime, water, and sand. The plaster served to fill and seal spaces between the building stones and thus protect the surface from water seepage. Because it made a smooth surface, the plaster also served as a base for decorating walls with paint.
\line Whitewash was lime mixed with water. It was painted on walls to make them white and cover ugly rough surfaces. Whitewash did not strengthen a structure but only beautified it. Even where decorations were not added, it was common to cover the plaster layer with whitewash.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0358_painted_plaster.jpg|col||British Museum|Painted plaster|1.0\fig*“Plaster” may be translated “dry earth” or “dried mud.” This would be an accurate description of a material widely used at that time and a quite natural translation in many languages of the world (\s H00301404101000 H00301404200032 H00301404500028 H00301404800038\s* uses the Hebrew word \i ‘afar\i*, which was just soil mixed with water to make mud). Where a distinction is made between kinds of plaster or sealant, it should be noted that some of the above references are to plaster made with lime (\s H00502700200050 H00502700400048 A02700500500030\s*). In some languages it may be necessary to resort to a general term meaning “covering” or “stucco.”
\line The Hebrew word \i tafal\i* (\s H01801300400008 H01801401700012 H01911906900002\s*) is always used in a figurative sense, and normally it will not be necessary to find a literal translation; for example, in \s H01801300400008\s* the literal text “you plaster with lies” may be rendered “You hide the truth with your lies” (\a SPCL\a*) or “You cover up your ignorance with lies” (\a GNT\a*).
\line \fig |PTZ-0053_whitewashed_buildings.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz|Whitewashed buildings|1.0\fig*The purpose of plastering a wall was to make it more attractive than just rough stones. This underlying purpose is reflected in \a GNT\a*’s rendering for the last half of \s L07102201700016\s*: “a firm wall, finely decorated.”
\line The references to whitewash in Ezekiel and the New Testament are symbolic. This should be kept in mind when trying to render the meaning; for example, in \s H02602202800006\s* the literal text “And her prophets have spread whitewash for them” is expanded by \a GNT\a* to “The prophets have hidden these sins like workers covering a wall with white­wash.” Where whitewash or some equivalent paint is unknown, translators may follow \a NCV\a*, which has “And the prophets try to cover this up.”
\line In some of the references above it is not clear whether plaster or whitewash is intended. Some languages will require the translator to make a choice between the two. In most cases the context will help with the choice of terms. These following texts probably refer to plaster: \s H00301404300048 H00301404300048 H00301404800038 H00502700200050 H00502700400048 H01911906900002 A02700500500030 L07102201700016\s*. The remaining references are probably to whitewash.
\line \s G04002302700020\s*: For many languages the closest equivalent of the phrase “whitewashed tombs” is simply “tombs that have been painted white.”
\line \s G04402300300026\s*: A literal translation of the phrase “whitewashed wall” is rarely meaningful. Sometimes you can use a descriptive phrase, such as “dirty wall that is made to look white” or “. . . to look clean.” In other instances you may wish to focus upon the function suggested by the idiom “whitewashed wall” and use a phrase such as “one who has been made to look good but really isn’t.”
\key 1.8.4
\title Squared stones for building
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֶבֶן, גָּזִית
\trl gazith, ’even gazith
\ref H00202002500008 H01100503100014 H01100603600020 H01100700900006 H01100701100010 H01100701200016 H01302200200036 H02300900900008 H02500300900008 H02604004200014 H03000501100024
\grk λίθος, λαξεύω
\trl lithos lelaxeumenos
\ref L06800100200016
\grk λίθος, ξυστός
\trl lithos xustos
\ref L08100600800086 L08100602400022
\grk λίθος, τετράποδος
\trl lithos tetrapodos
\ref L07701001100034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0359_squared_stone.jpg|col||© Gilabrand|Squared stone|1.0\fig*Squared stones were stones (often quarried from the bedrock) that were cut square so that they could be laid one on another to form a wall or building.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The size of building stones varied considerably, from stones that could be lifted by a man to some which were several meters long and weighed many tons. Translators should avoid a word that means simply bricks or small stones. We may say “very large stones that have been cut into square blocks.”
\line \fig |PTZ-0054_ceiling_wall_en.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz|Tefachoth|1.0\fig*\s H01100700900006\s*: This verse describes building stones that were smoothed on both back and front. They were used for each wall, from bottom to top. For the top of the wall, the Hebrew text uses the word \i tfachoth\i*, which is usually rendered as “eaves” (\a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*) or “coping” (\a RSV\a*, \a REB\a*). In many languages such a technical term will be lacking or not widely understood (like “eaves” and “coping” in common English). It has recently been suggested, however, that the \i tfachoth\i* were actually a decorative feature at the top of the wall, resembling two or three inverted steps between the ceiling and the wall.
\line Normally it is not necessary to translate such an unsure term with great architectural precision, and for the whole verse it will be preferable to follow a version like \a CEV\a*, which says “From the foundation all the way to the top, these buildings and the courtyard were made out of the best stones carefully cut to size, then smoothed on every side with saws,” or \a NCV\a*, which has “All these buildings were made with blocks of fine stone. First they were carefully cut. Then they were trimmed with a saw in the front and back. These fine stones went from the foundations of the buildings to the top of the walls. Even the courtyard was made with blocks of stone.”
\line \fig |KNW-0400_building_stone.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Men moving a building stone|1.0\fig*The stones in \s H02604004200014\s* are said to form a “table” (\i shulchan\i* in Hebrew). See the discussion at \l target="REALIA:4.3.6">4.3.6 Tables for preparing sacrificial victims\l*.
\key 1.8.4.1
\title Stone plane, saw
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מְגֵרָה
\trl mgerah
\ref H01001203100026 H01100700900022 H01302000300024 H01302000300042
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The stone plane/saw was an instrument used in the preparation of building stones.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H01001203100026\s*: There is disagreement among scholars concerning the precise action that is being described here, and this is reflected in the different translations. It is possible to understand that David tortured or killed the inhabitants of Rabbah with various implements, including saws (\a KJV\a*, \a NASB\a*). Most modern translations, however, understand the text to mean that David put the people to work with those implements (for example, \a NCV\a* “He also brought out the people of the city and forced them to work with saws, iron picks, and axes . . .”). This is the preferred interpretation. While the argument is more complicated for the parallel text at \s H01302000300024\s* (which is not identical), most translations give the same rendering there.
\line It now seems probable that translations have been inaccurate in rendering the Hebrew word \i mgerah\i* as “saw[s].” Archaeology knows of no use of saws either to quarry or to shape stones in the time period described. Many building stones have been found which were finely smoothed, but these stones show none of the marks that would have been left by a saw. It has been proposed that the \i mgerah\i* was a heavy metal instrument with a wide rough surface, like that of a file. This instrument was pushed and pulled across the surface of the stone until it was quite smooth. This would have been heavy and exhausting work, appropriate for captives or slaves (see Barkay, pages 32-37).
\key 1.8.5
\title Plumb line
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֲנָךְ
\trl ’anak
\ref H03000700700018 H03000700700026 H03000700800022 H03000700800034
\heb אֶבֶן בְּדִ֛יל
\trl ’even bedil
\ref H03800401000030
\heb מִשְׁקֶלֶת, מִשְׁקֹלֶת
\trl mishqeleth, mishqoleth
\ref H01202101300020 H02302801700018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0126_plump_line.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Plumb line in use|1.0\fig* The plumb line was a weight suspended on the end of a string, used by builders to determine, for example, if all the stones in a wall were vertically straight.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In many cultures the only tool similar to the plumb line is the water-level, and the Pidgin English word “wataplan” has often become part of the vocabulary. This measures the horizontal plane rather than the vertical one, but might serve the purpose. Where there is no word for plumb line or where an existing word would not be understood by most readers, it may be necessary to use a descriptive phrase, as does \a CEV\a* at \s H03000700700018\s* by saying “a weight tied to the end of it. The string and weight had been used to measure the straightness of the wall.” In addition, some kind of illustration to show the shape and use of the tool might be helpful. In \s H03000700800022\s* \a CEV\a* translates “plumb line” as “measuring line.” “Measuring line” is also used by \a CEV\a* at \s H02302801700018\s* (see \l target="REALIA:1.8.6">1.8.6 Measuring rod, measuring line\l*).\fig |KNW-0125_plump_line.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Builder with a plumb line|1.0\fig*
\line In \s H01202101300020\s* the Hebrew text is literally “And I will stretch out over Jerusalem the measuring line of Samaria and the plumb line of the house of Ahab.” Here both “the measuring line” and “the plumb line” are used symbolically, so translators may convey the meaning without actually referring to them. \a GNT\a* may serve as a model: “I will punish Jerusalem as I did Samaria, as I did King Ahab of Israel and his descendants.” Compare \a CEV\a*: “Jerusalem is as sinful as Ahab and the people of Samaria were.”
\line \s H03000700700018\s*: The LORD is seen as standing on or by a wall, which in Hebrew is called “a wall of a plumb line.” The translation “plumb line” is not fully certain but no other suggestion is as good. \a GNT\a* tries to make sense out of the phrase “a wall of a plumb line” by saying “a wall that had been built with the use of a plumb line” (similarly \a RSV\a*, \i The Translator’s Old Testament\i* [\a TOT\a*]). On the other hand, it may be better to follow most modern English translations (\a AT\a*, \a Mft\a*, \a NAB\a*, \a NEB\a*) as well as many commentators who have something like “standing by a wall with a plumb line in his hand” for the last half of this verse. They consider “of a plumb line” to be the result of a copying mistake. A possible model for the whole verse is “The LORD caused me to see again in a vision. I saw him on the top of a wall stretching out a cord to see whether the wall was straight.”
\key 1.8.6
\title Measuring rod, measuring line
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Rod\b*:
\heb קָנֶה
\trl qaneh
\ref H02604000300036 H02604000500032 H02604000500064 H02604000500072 H02604000600044 H02604000600058 H02604000700008 H02604000700016 H02604000700058 H02604000800020 H02604100800030 H02604201600012 H02604201600024 H02604201600028 H02604201700014 H02604201700018 H02604201800016 H02604201800020 H02604201900018 H02604201900022
\grk κάλαμος
\trl kalamos
\ref G06601100100008 G06602101500016 G06602101600038
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Line\b*:
\heb חֶבֶל, מִדָּה
\trl chevel, chevel midah
\ref H01000800200018 H01000800200032 H01000800200044 H01907805500018 H03000701700044 H03300200500012 H03800200500024
\heb חוּט
\trl chut
\ref H01100701500034 H02405202100028
\heb פָּתִיל
\trl pathil
\ref H02604000300026
\heb קַו, קָוֶה, מִדָּה
\trl qaw, qaw midah, qaweh
\ref H01100702300048 H01100702300052 H01202101300012 H01400400200048 H01803800500020 H02302801700010 H02303401100030 H02303401700024 H02304401300008 H02403103900008 H02403103900010 H02500200800018 H02604700300014 H03800101600038
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0360_measuring_line.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Measuring property with a line|1.0\fig*The measuring rod/line was an instrument used for measuring length. It could be a reed, stick, or rope.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The equivalent for “measuring rod” may be simply “measuring stick” or “stick with which to count the distance.”
\line \s H01202101300012\s*: The declaration of judgment in this verse was given before the capture and exile of Judah but after the defeat of the northern kingdom with its capital in Samaria. The “measuring line” is used as a device to indicate that the sins of the southern kingdom with its capital in Jerusalem are just as bad as those of the northern kingdom with its capital Samaria. Some common-language translations choose to drop the image of the “measuring line” in favor of a direct statement of the essence of the judgment; for example, the first half of this verse in \a CEV\a* reads “Jerusalem is as sinful as Ahab and the people of Samaria were” (see \l target="REALIA:1.8.5">1.8.5 Plumb line\l*).
\line \s H03300200500012\s*: The Hebrew word \i chevel\i* in this verse refers to a line used to measure out property for ownership. The prophet is saying that when the exiles of Judah return, the families of the rich people will have no share or plot of land. The Hebrew refers specifically to the process by which the family shares were chosen. The “lot” (\a RSV\a*) was probably a set of stones with special markings on them (see \l target="REALIA:4.9">4.9 Lots\l*). The stone chosen would show what God’s will was in that particular case. The “line” is the measuring line used to mark out the family plots. The lots may have been used to show where the measuring line should be placed. Most translators prefer to express the general procedure of parceling out the land and its significance rather than trying to render the specific instruments involved in the procedure; for example, \a CEV\a* has “And so you will never again own property among the LORD’s people,” and \a GNT\a* says “So then, when the time comes for the land to be given back to the LORD’s people, there will be no share for any of you.”
\line \s G06601100100008\s*: \a RSV\a* renders the Greek phrase of three words near the beginning of this verse as “a measuring rod like a staff.” However, the meaning of the Greek is better expressed by \a NJB\a* “a long cane like a measuring rod”; compare \a GNT\a* “a stick that looked like a measuring-rod,” \a REB\a* “a long cane to use as a measuring rod,” \a NIV\a* “a reed like a measuring rod,” and the Chewa common language translation, which has “a reed for measuring with that looked like a walking stick.” The first Greek word in this phrase is \i kalamos\i*. It designates a reed or a cane (see its use in \s G06602101500016 G06602101600038\s*, where \a GNT\a* has “measuring stick”). The third Greek word, \i rhabdos\i*, refers to a staff or a rod here. Elsewhere in Revelation it refers to the “iron rod” (or, “scepter”) used by Jesus Christ (\s G06601200500024\s*; \s G06601901500040\s*) and his followers (\s G06600202700010\s*). It is better to follow \a GNT\a* or \a NJB\a* in translating the passage here. See also the remarks at \l target="REALIA:1.2.4">1.2.4 Rod, club, shepherd’s staff\l*.
\key 1.9
\title Barber
\index \l target="REALIA:1.9.1">1.9.1 Razor\l*
\key 1.9.1
\title Razor
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מוֹרָה
\trl morah
\ref H00701300500016 H00701601700020 H00900101100070
\heb תַּעַר
\trl ta‘ar
\ref H00400600500010 H00400800700026 H01905200400010 H02300702000018 H02403602300024 H02600500100018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0361_razor.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Razor|1.0\fig*The razor was a very sharp knife used to shave hair from the skin.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The literal clause “no razor shall come on his head” in \s H00400600500010\s* (compare \s H00701300500016\s*; \s H00701601700020\s*; \s H00900101100070\s*) may be rendered “he must not cut his hair” or “you must not cut your hair or shave” (\a GNT\a*).
\line The implement mentioned in \s H02403602300024\s* was a small knife or razor used by a scribe to sharpen his pens (see \l target="REALIA:1.7.3">1.7.3 Pen\l*). The English word “penknife” (\a RSV\a*) comes from just such an implement, although today it may convey to the hearer a folding pocketknife.
\line Like many physical objects, the razor is sometimes used figuratively in the Bible. In \s H01905200400010\s* the tongue is compared to a sharpened razor. All the translations consulted retain the metaphor. Similarly, in \s H02300702000018\s* the razor symbolizes an attack by the king of Assyria. Almost all translations manage to retain the image of the razor in this passage. \a GNT\a* does so only indirectly with “When that time comes, the Lord will hire a barber from across the Euphrates—the emperor of Assyria!—and he will shave off your beards and the hair on your heads and your bodies.”
\key 1.10
\title Royalty
\index \l target="REALIA:1.10.1">1.10.1 Throne\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.10.2">1.10.2 Crown\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.10.3">1.10.3 Scepter\l*
