\key 1.10.1
\title Throne
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כִּסֵּא
\trl kise’, kiseh
\ref H00104104000026 H00201100500028 H00201202900042 H00501701800012 H00700302000056 H00900200800028 H01000301000024 H01000701300018 H01000701600020 H01001400900048 H01100101300062 H01100101700042 H01100102000032 H01100102400032 H01100102700042 H01100103000042 H01100103500018 H01100103700034 H01100103700038 H01100104600012 H01100104700054 H01100104700058 H01100104800034 H01100200400074 H01100201200010 H01100201900050 H01100201900056 H01100202400024 H01100203300048 H01100204500014 H01100300600086 H01100501900050 H01100700700008 H01100802000032 H01100802500052 H01100900500008 H01100900500048 H01101000900022 H01101001800010 H01101001900010 H01101001900022 H01101601100016 H01102201000022 H01102201900024 H01201000300028 H01201003000058 H01201101900082 H01201301300020 H01201501200030 H01202502800016 H01202502800022 H01301701200016 H01301701400024 H01302201000038 H01302800500038 H01302902300010 H01400601000032 H01400601600052 H01400701800008 H01400900800022 H01400901700010 H01400901800012 H01400901800028 H01401800900022 H01401801800024 H01402302000096 H01700100200024 H01700500100060 H01802600900006 H01803600700022 H01900900500016 H01900900800020 H01901100400018 H01904500700002 H01904700900016 H01908900500022 H01908901500010 H01908903000014 H01908903700012 H01908904500010 H01909300200004 H01909402000006 H01909700200018 H01910301900012 H01912200500008 H01912200500014 H01913201100028 H02001601200018 H02002000800008 H02002002800022 H02002500500022 H02002901400012 H02300600100026 H02300900600026 H02301400900034 H02301401300030 H02301600500012 H02302202300020 H02304700100028 H02306600100012 H02400101500032 H02400301700018 H02401301300050 H02401402100014 H02401701200002 H02401702500028 H02402200200022 H02402200400046 H02402203000048 H02402901600022 H02403301700024 H02403302100026 H02403603000028 H02404301000042 H02404903800006 H02405203200016 H02405203200024 H02500501900012 H02600102600030 H02600102600040 H02601000100038 H02602601600010 H02604300700016 H03200300600022 H03700202200006 H03800601300032 H03800601300042
\arm כָּרְסֵא
\trl korse’
\ref A02700502000026 A02700700900010 A02700700900042
\grk δίφρος
\trl difros
\ref L06801101900032
\grk θρόνος
\trl thronos
\ref G04000503400130 G04001902800240 G04001902800320 G04002302200100 G04002503100210 G04200103200150 G04200105200040 G04202203000160 G04400203000200 G04400704900040 G05100101600200 G05800100800060 G05800401600060 G05800800100140 G05801200200240 G06600100400300 G06600201300060 G06600302100100 G06600302100230 G06600400200070 G06600400200150 G06600400300140 G06600400400040 G06600400400050 G06600400400110 G06600400500040 G06600400500180 G06600400600040 G06600400600140 G06600400600180 G06600400900150 G06600401000110 G06600401000280 G06600500100100 G06600500600060 G06600500700120 G06600501100100 G06600501300310 G06600601600200 G06600700900250 G06600701000150 G06600701100080 G06600701100200 G06600701500060 G06600701500240 G06600701700080 G06600800300330 G06601101600130 G06601200500250 G06601300200320 G06601400300080 G06601601000100 G06601601700200 G06601900400200 G06601900500050 G06602000400030 G06602001100030 G06602001200130 G06602100300070 G06602100500070 G06602200100130 G06602200300090 L06800101200028 L06800900300056 L06900500100030 L06900500100032 L06900801200044 L07000502300040 L07000602100010 L07000700800010 L07000900400012 L07000901000016 L07000901200032 L07001801500016 L07100100800018 L07101001400002 L07102400400014 L07104000300008 L07104701100038 L07200500600040 L07700205700014 L07700700400020 L07701005200020 L07701005300036 L07701005500038 L07701105200014 L08001701800016 L08500300800034 L08600201900024 L08601700600020
\lat thronus
\ref V08200802100006
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0362_darius.jpg|col||© درفش کاویانی|King sitting on his throne|1.0\fig*The throne was a relatively large and elaborate seat upon which a ruler sat. It could be made of stone or wood or even other substances such as precious metals and ivory. It usually had a back and often armrests on the sides. The throne of Solomon is described in \s H01101001901000 H01101002001000\s* and \s H01400901801000 H01400901901000\s* as being elevated and approached by stairs. See \l target="REALIA:3.1.7">3.1.7 Stairs, steps\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line On official occasions the ruler sat on the throne. This could be for the reception of foreign dignitaries, the passing of judgment, or the making and declaration of major decisions regarding the nation.\fig |WEB-0363_crown.jpg|col||© Einsamer Schütze|Egyptian crown|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Throne” may be rendered “great chair,” “important seat,” or “king’s chair.” On the other hand, a description of the “throne” as a place of judging or of decision making may be the rendering, for example, “chair from which the ruler gives orders,” “seat of decision making for a ruler,” or “seat of judging.”
\line The Greek word \i thronos\i* refers only to a throne, but the Hebrew words \i kise’\i* and \i kiseh\i* are the normal words for a seat (see \l target="REALIA:5.9">5.9 Chair, seat\l*). When the seat of a king is in view, then the proper translation of these Hebrew words is “throne.”
\key 1.10.2
\title Crown
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כֶּתֶר
\trl kether
\ref H01700101100024 H01700201700048 H01700600800038
\heb נֵזֶר
\trl nezer
\ref H01000101000032 H01201101200024 H01402301100024 H01908904000016 H01913201800014 H02002702400016 H03800901600030
\heb עטר
\trl ‘atar (verb)
\ref H01900800600020 H02200301100028
\heb עֲטָרָה
\trl ‘atarah
\ref H01001203000008 H01302000200010 H01700801500032 H01902100400016 H02200301100024 H02401301800028 H02601601200022 H02602103100022 H03800601100016 H03800601400006
\grk διάδημα
\trl diadēma
\ref G06601200300250 G06601300100200 G06601901200130 L06900101100024 L06900201700034 L06900801500028 L07000501600020 L07001802400040 L07101100500020 L07104700600032 L07700100900008 L07700601500010 L07700801400020 L07701101300018 L07701101300030 L07701105400032 L07701203900020 L07701303200016 L08100403000008
\grk στέφανος, στεφανόω
\trl stefanos, stefanoō (verb)
\ref G04002702900006 G04101501700020 G04301900200010 G04301900500018 G05800200700020 G05800200900036 G06600400400050 G06600401000048 G06600600200034 G06600900700034 G06601200100048 G06601401400040 L07104000400010 L07104501200002 L07701002000040 L07701002900042 L07701103500054 L07701303700004 L07701303900026 L07801400400030
\cont \u Description and usage: \u*
\line \fig |KNW-0159_crown_king.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Crown|1.0\fig* The crown was a type of headgear worn by a king or queen as a sign of the royal office
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The “crown” may be described as “symbol of his/her power, worn on his/her head.”
\line In some passages the crown serves only as a symbol of the office of king or queen. In those cultures where royalty (or the office of the supreme leader) is indicated by another symbol, this may be substituted for “crown.” Thus, for example, \s H01700201700048\s* might read “he gave her the royal seal and made her queen in place of Vashti.” Similarly, \s H01902100400016\s* might read “you seat him on the chief’s stool” or “you make him chief.”\fig |KNW-0321_crown_thorns.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Crown of thorns|1.0\fig*
\line In some passages (\s H01801900900014 H01803103600014 H02001200400006 H02001603100002 H02001700600002 H02500501600004\s*) it is unclear from the context if the Hebrew word \i ‘atarah\i* refers to a crown or a wreath (see \l target="REALIA:6.8">6.8 Wreath, crown\l*).
\line \a RSV\a* renders \s L07701101300030\s* as “Then Ptolemy entered Antioch and put on the crown of Asia. Thus he put two crowns upon his head, the crown of Egypt and that of Asia.” This literal rendering can create a rather silly picture in the mind of the reader. The crowns, of course, simply represent the authority held by Ptolemy in the two regions mentioned here. \a CEV\a* has avoided the image of a king trying to balance two crowns on his head by saying “Ptolemy went to the city of Antioch, where he crowned himself king—both of Syria and of Egypt.” \a CEV\a*’s rendering, however, gives the mis­impression that he became king of Syria and Egypt simultaneously. A better model is “Ptolemy went to the city of Antioch, where he crowned himself king. This meant that he now ruled over both Egypt and Syria.”
\line It should be noted that the “crown of thorns” placed on Jesus was a wreath made of thorny branches (\s G04002702900006 G04101501700020 G04301900200010 G04301900500018\s*). The action may be described as “put a circle of thorns on his head” or “wove thorn branches together into a wreath [or, circle] and put them on his head.”
\line For \i stefanos\i* as a wreath, see \l target="REALIA:6.8">6.8 Wreath, crown\l*.
\key 1.10.3
\title Scepter
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חקק
\trl mchoqeq
\ref H00104901000014 H00402101800018 H01906000900022 H01910800900020
\heb מַטֶּה
\trl mateh
\ref H01911000200002 H02404801700024
\heb מַקֵּל
\trl maqel
\ref H02404801700028
\heb שֵׁבֶט
\trl shevet
\ref H00104901000006 H00402401700030 H00700501400038 H01904500700012 H01904500700016 H01912500300008 H02301400500010 H02601901100014 H02601901400030 H03000100500024 H03000100800016 H03801001100046
\heb שַׁרְבִיט
\trl sharvit
\ref H01700401100084 H01700500200052 H01700500200080 H01700800400016
\grk ῥάβδος
\trl rhabdos
\ref G05800100800034 G05800100800034 L06900500200010
\grk σκῆπτρον
\trl skēptron
\ref L06900401700010 L07000602100014 L07000700800006 L07001001400028 L07103502100012 L07300101200004
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0364_scepter.jpg|col||Gary Todd|Head of a scepter|1.0\fig*The scepter was a decorated rod, often made at least partially of a precious metal, symbolizing the authority of the ruler. The ruler held the scepter when he was engaged in certain aspects of his office. See also \l target="REALIA:1.2.4">1.2.4 Rod, club, shepherd’s staff\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In languages where a chief’s authority is symbolized by an object associated with him (such as a cane, stool, or scepter), such symbols of authority can often be used in translation; for example, \s H01904500700016\s* may be rendered “Your ceremonial staff shows that you rule your people fairly.”
\line The Hebrew words \i mateh\i* and \i maqel\i* are parallel to each other in \s H02404801700024\s*. It is not always necessary to reproduce the parallelism with two similar words; for example, for the last half of this verse \a RSV\a* has “How the mighty scepter is broken, the glorious staff,” but \a GNT\a* says “Its powerful rule has been broken; its glory and might are no more.” This passage is metaphorical, so the focus here is not on the scepter as a physical object but on authority.
\key 1.10.4
\title Anointing horn, anointing flask
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שֶׁמֶן
\trl pak shemen
\ref H00901000100014 H01200900100042 H01200900300010
\heb קֶרֶן
\trl qeren
\ref H00901600100040 H00901601300010 H01100103900014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0365_horn_ram.jpg|col||© Olve Utne|Ram's horn|1.0\fig* The anointing horn/flask was a small container for holding olive oil. It was made of an animal horn or other material. The horn usually had to be hollowed out.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The ceremony for installing a person in the office of king or priest included pouring olive oil over his head (see \l target="REALIA:1.10.5">1.10.5 Anointing oil\l*). The oil was kept in and poured from the anointing horn/flask, used only for this special ceremony.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i qeren\i* refers to an animal horn, while the word \i pak\i* simply alludes to a container, such as a vial or flask or a jar with a narrow neck. \a NCV\a* renders \i qeren\i* in \s H00901600100040\s* as “container.” A word should be chosen which indicates a container with a small volume, one from which a liquid may be poured, and with the possibility of being closed.
\key 1.10.5
\title Anointing oil
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יִצְהָר
\trl yitshar
\ref H03800401400014
\heb שֶׁמֶן, מִשְׁחָה
\trl shemen mishchah
\ref H00202500600002 H00202900700008 H00202902100024 H00203002500008 H00203002500010 H00203003100016 H00203101100006 H00203500800004 H00203501500022 H00203502800016 H00203702900008 H00203903800016 H00204000900008 H00300800200028 H00300801000010 H00300801200008 H00300803000010 H00301000700022 H00302101000024 H00302101200030 H00400401600016
\grk ἔλαιον
\trl elaion
\ref G04200704600002 G05800100900030 L07104501500018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Plain olive oil was used to anoint kings and sometimes prophets to dedicate them for their tasks.
\line The preparation of a special perfumed oil is commanded in \s H00203002301000 H00203002401000 H00203002501000 H00203002601000 H00203002701000 H00203002801000 H00203002901000 H00203003001000 H00203003101000 H00203003201000 H00203003301000\s*. It was for anointing the priests as well as the Tabernacle and furniture in the Tabernacle. It set them aside as “holy.” It had an olive oil base mixed with a variety of aromatic spices.
\line See also \l target="REALIA:1.15.1">1.15.1 Oil, ointment\l* and \l target="REALIA:9.3">9.3 Olive oil\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The anointing of a king was primarily a religious act, not a political one.
\key 1.11
\title Blacksmith
\index \l target="REALIA:1.11.1">1.11.1 Smelting furnace, kiln\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.11.2">1.11.2 Anvil\l*
\key 1.11.1
\title Smelting furnace, kiln
\index \l target="REALIA:1.11.1.1">1.11.1.1 Bellows\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\arm אַתּוּן
\trl ’atun
\ref A02700300600060 A02700301100050 A02700301500280 A02700301700080 A02700301900150 A02700302000110 A02700302100110 A02700302200070 A02700302300080 A02700302600050
\heb כִּבְשָׁן
\trl kivshan
\ref H00101902800052 H00200900800028 H00200901000012 H00201901800042
\heb כּוּר
\trl kur
\ref H00500402000018 H01100805100024 H02001700300012 H02002702100012 H02304801000018 H02401100400026 H02602201800042 H02602202000026 H02602202200012
\heb מַצְרֵף
\trl matsref
\ref H02001700300002 H02002702100002
\heb עֲלִיל
\trl ‘alil
\ref H01901200700016
\grk κάμινος
\trl kaminos
\ref G04001304200060 G04001305000060 G06600101500090 G06600900200150 L07100200500040 L07102202400016 L07102700500016 L07103102600004 L07103802800072 L07103803000088 L07104300400004 L07900600600084 L08001300900072 L08001600300056 L08001602100060 L11200300600052 L11200301100048 L11200301500086 L11200301700048 L11200301900084 L11200302000060 L11200302100088 L11200302200036 L11200302300052 L11200304600048 L11200304700028 L11200304800036 L11200304900052 L11200304900088 L11200305000024 L11200305100068 L11200308800060 L11200309300032
\grk χωνευτήριον
\trl chōneutērion
\ref L07000300600016
\lat fornax
\ref V08200404800014
\lat clibanus
\ref V08200703600016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0367_kiln.jpg|col||Encyclopaedia Biblica, 1903|Ram's horn|1.0\fig* The kiln was a furnace used for the smelting of ore or the firing of ceramic ware. Such furnaces were made of hardened clay or of brick. They could vary considerably in size and shape. See also \l target="REALIA:5.11">5.11 Oven\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Almost all metals exist in nature in combination with other minerals. To remove the other minerals requires chemical treatment combined with heating the ore to very high temperatures in kilns. Such heating chambers served also for firing bricks or pottery and for other purposes.\fig |WEB-0366_kiln.jpg|col||© Heritage Conservation Outside the City, Pikiwiki Israel|Kiln|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line When translating the word “furnace,” the emphasis should be upon the extreme heat, rather than upon the particular type of construction. However, if a particular word for “furnace” is chosen, it should be remembered that this furnace or oven was not made of metal but of brick or hardened clay.
\line The Hebrew word \i kur\i* is always used in metaphorical or symbolic language describing human sufferings. It will often be possible to portray the meaning of the metaphor without reference to the physical object; for example, \a CEV\a* renders \s H00500402000018\s* as “But you are the LORD’s people, because he led you through fiery trials and rescued you from Egypt.”
\line \s H01901200700016\s*: The Hebrew word \i ‘alil\i* occurs only here in the Old Testament, and its meaning is uncertain. It seems best to translate the obscure clause at the end of this verse in a general sense; for example, \a GNT\a* has “they are as genuine as silver refined seven times in the furnace,” and \a NIV\a* says “like silver refined in a furnace of clay, purified seven times.” “Seven times” means “many times,” that is, as many times as needed to get rid of all the impurities.
\line \s H02001700300012 H02002702100012\s*: Two instruments for heating and refining metals are mentioned in these verses: the \i matsref\i* and the \i kur\i*. If separate words exist in a language for these two instruments (for example, “crucible” and “furnace”), these may be used. Many translations combine the two words; for example, in \s H02001700301000\s*a \a GNT\a* says “Gold and silver are tested by fire,” and \a NCV\a* has “A hot furnace tests silver and gold.”
\line \s A02700300000000\s*: The furnace described here probably had an opening at the top and another at ground level. It was clearly large enough for men to stand and even walk around in. The word for “furnace” here should also be used in \s L11200302300000-L11200302800000\s*and \s L11200306600000\s*.
\line In \s G04001304200060 G04001305000060\s* the Greek word \i kaminos\i* is used figuratively of hell. Alternative renderings for the literal phrase “the furnace of fire” are “the fires of hell” and “hell, which is like a great fire.” Another possibility is simply “the great fire.” Similarly, the Latin word \i clibanus\i* is used metaphorically in \s V08200703600016\s* for the heat of hell.
\line The difference between this entry and \l target="REALIA:5.11">5.11 Oven\l* is primarily one of size rather than of basic design. Ovens, of course, could be put to many uses. Where a language does not have a variety of words, such as “oven,” “furnace” and “kiln” in English, a single word will normally suffice. In that case, it will sometimes be necessary to indicate the relative size of the oven according to the context. An oven in which bread was baked may be rendered “small oven,” while the one into which several people were thrown will be a “very large oven.”
\line The fuel burned in ancient ovens was wood, the leftover flesh of pressed olives, or dried animal dung. Translators should avoid a word for “oven” that indicates a device that runs on electricity or uses a refined fuel like oil or kerosene.
\key 1.11.1.1
\title Bellows
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַפּוּחַ
\trl mapuach
\ref H02400602900004
\grk ζώπυρον, πῦρ
\trl zōpuron tou puros
\ref L08000801300052
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0368_bellows.jpg|col||© Le plombier du désert|Bellows operated by slaves|1.0\fig*Where extremely high temperatures were needed, such as when smelting ore, it was common to blow air into the bottom of the fire with a bellows. One type of bellows consisted of two vertical cylinders covered with thick leather. The operator stood on these, pulling the leather up with an attached strap and then pressing it down with his foot to create the rush of air, which was channeled into the furnace.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Not all present-day English speakers are familiar with the structure or operation of a bellows, so several common-language English translations have avoided using the word in \s H02400602900004\s* by rendering the first line of this verse as “The fire is fanned to make it hotter” (\a NCV\a*), “The furnace burns fiercely” (\a GNT\a*), or “in a fiery furnace” (\a CEV\a*).
\key 1.11.2
\title Anvil
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb פַּעַם
\trl pa‘am
\ref H02304100700020
\grk ἄκμων
\trl akmōn
\ref L07103802800010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0369_anvil.jpg|col||© MikiNikoloski|Modern anvil|1.0\fig*The anvil was a heavy piece of metal that served as a base for hammering and shaping other pieces of metal.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The meaning of the Hebrew phrase \i holem pa‘am\i* in \s H02304100700020\s* is uncertain, so translations vary. The basic meaning seems to be connected to striking blows with a hammer. This has given rise to several interpretations: \a GNT\a* “the one who nails it together,” \a NCV\a* “the one who shapes the metal,” and \a NRSV\a* “the one who strikes the anvil” (similarly \a NIV\a*). \a CEV\a* has “other workers” and adds a footnote explaining that the text is difficult.
\line Where there is no equivalent for “anvil,” in \s L07103802800100\s* translators may say “It is the same with the iron worker at his work.”
\line Tongs: See \l target="REALIA:4.4.3">4.4.3 Tongs\l*.
\key 1.12
\title Carpenter
\index \l target="REALIA:1.12.1">1.12.1 Hammer\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.12.2">1.12.2 Nail, spike\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.12.3">1.12.3 Chisel, plane\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.12.4">1.12.4 Awl\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.12.5">1.12.5 Saw\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.12.6">1.12.6 Stylus, marker\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.12.7">1.12.7 Compass, circle instrument\l*
\cont Axe: See \l target="REALIA:1.1.9.2">1.1.9.2 Fork\l*.
\key 1.12.1
\title Hammer
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb הַלְמוּת
\trl halmuth
\ref H00700502600018
\heb מַקֶּבֶת
\trl maqavah, maqeveth
\ref H00700402100028 H01100600700022 H02304401200024 H02401000400022
\heb מִקְשָׁה
\trl miqshah
\ref H00202501800012 H00202503100012 H00202503600014 H00203700700012 H00203701700016 H00203702200014 H00400800400012 H00400800400024 H00401000200012
\heb פַּטִּישׁ
\trl patish
\ref H02304100700014 H02402302900024 H02405002300010
\heb רִקֻּעַ
\trl riqua‘
\ref H00401700300024
\grk ἐλατός
\trl elatos
\ref L07105001600016
\grk ὁλοσφύρητος
\trl olosfurētos
\ref L07105000900020
\grk σφῦρα
\trl sfura
\ref L07103802800042
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0370_hammer.jpg|col||© Giovanni Dall'Orto|Wooden hammer|1.0\fig* The hammer was an instrument about 30 centimeters (1 foot) long. It had a handle, usually made of wood, to which was attached a stone, wooden, or (less frequently) metal head. The handle was fitted into a hole in the hammer’s head.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The hammer served many purposes, including the breaking or dressing of building stones, pounding nails or pegs into wood, or pounding pegs into the ground. It also was used by blacksmiths to shape hot metal.\fig |KNW-0401_worker_hammer_en.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Worker with a hammer|1.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The meaning of the Hebrew word \i miqshah\i* is uncertain. It seems to refer to the result of the work of an artisan on metal objects, that is, “hammered work” or “beaten work.”
\key 1.12.2
\title Nail, spike
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַסְמֵר
\trl masmer
\ref H01302200300014 H01400300900008 H02304100700040 H02401000400016
\heb מַשְׂמֵרָה
\trl masmerah
\ref H02101201100016
\grk ἧλος
\trl hēlos
\ref G04302002500048 G04302002500068
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0371_spike.jpg|col||Gary Todd|Spike in an anklebone|1.0\fig*The nail was a thin piece of metal (usually iron) sharpened on one end. It served much the same purpose as a modern nail, attaching pieces of wood to each other or to the floor.
\line The spike for crucifixion was a fairly thick, pointed piece of iron. It was roughly 20 centimeters (8 inches) long and about the thickness of a man’s finger. Archaeological excavations in 1968 uncovered the remains of a crucified man. A metal spike was still lodged in an anklebone, passing through it from the side.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages a distinction is made between relatively small nails and larger spikes. The latter would be appropriate when speaking of crucifixion and probably for the spikes used in gate construction in \s H01302200300014\s*. The word chosen should indicate a spike strong enough that two or three of them would have held the weight of a man.
\line \fig |WEB-0372_nails.jpg|col||© Takkk|Iron nails|1.0\fig*The nails mentioned in \s H01400300900008\s* were made of gold and varied widely in size.
\key 1.12.3
\title Chisel, plane
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb מַקְצוּעָה
\trl maqtsu‘a
\ref H02304401300024
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0402_woodcrafting_chisel_en.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Chisel|1.0\fig* The chisel or plane was a metal tool with a sharp edge used to shape wood.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H02304401300024\s*: This verse mentions three tools used by a carpenter in making an idol from a piece of wood. All three tools are mentioned only here in the Bible, and their meanings are derived primarily from the context and from their etymologies. Two of the tools, the \i sered\i* (see \l target="REALIA:1.12.6">1.12.6 Stylus, marker\l*) and the \i mchugah\i* (see \l target="REALIA:1.12.7">1.12.7 Compass, circle instrument\l*), have to do with marking the wood before carving it, while the \i maqtsu‘a\i* was used to cut and shape the wood into the desired form.
\line \a GNT\a* combines \i maqtsu‘a\i* and \i mchugah\i* in the generic rendering “tools.” This may serve for cultures where the chisel or plane is not known. It is also possible to render \i maqtsu‘a\i* as “knife.”
\key 1.12.4
\title Awl
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַרְצֵעַ
\trl martsea‘
\ref H00202100600046 H00501501700010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0373_awl.jpg|col||© Rama|Awl|1.0\fig*The awl was a hand tool with a narrow point used for boring holes in wood, leather, or other substances. The point could be made of metal, bone, or stone. The awl sometimes had a handle made of wood or bone.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In the only references to this implement in Scripture, it is used to pierce the ear of a slave to symbolize that he has chosen to remain with his master for life. It is possible that, in the hole made by the piercing, the master placed a ring or band indicating ownership. The exact instrument is not as important as its form. Where there is no word for “awl,” translators may use a word for some similar pointed implement, such as “nail” or “knife.”
\key 1.12.5
\title Saw
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk πρίζω
\trl prizō (verb)
\ref G05801103700004
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0374_saw.jpg|col||Eloquence|Saw|1.0\fig*The saw was a flat tool with a serrated edge, used for cutting objects in two. It could be made of hard stone such as flint or of metal and was sometimes fitted with a handle.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s G05801103700004\s*: It may not be necessary to be so precise about the instrument here. \a NCV\a* “cut in half” adequately conveys the idea.
\key 1.12.6
\title Stylus, marker
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb שֶׂרֶד
\trl sered
\ref H02304401300016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0375_stylus_en.jpg|col||Source unknown|Stylus|1.0\fig*The stylus was a tool used to make marks on wood to help the carpenter plan out the shape he would make.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H02304401300016\s*: Two different implements are possible for the Hebrew word \i sered\i*, although both would have the same function. One possibility is a pointed tool used to scratch marks in the wood (\a NRSV\a* “stylus”); the other possibility is a soft red stone, similar to chalk, with which the carpenter could make marks on the wood (\a GNT\a* “chalk”; \a NASB\a* “red chalk”; \a NIV\a* “marker”). A good model that expresses the meaning of the second clause in this verse without explicitly mentioning this tool is \a CEV\a* “then draws an outline.” See also the comments at \l target="REALIA:1.12.3">1.12.3 Chisel, plane\l*.
\key 1.12.7
\title Compass, circle instrument
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb מְחוּגָה
\trl mchugah
\ref H02304401300032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0376_compass.jpg|col||© Bullenwächter / Andreas Franzkowiak, Halstenbek|Compass|1.0\fig* The compass was a tool for drawing or marking circles. It is also possible that the instrument was used for making measurements.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line See the comments at \l target="REALIA:1.12.3">1.12.3 Chisel, plane\l*
\key 1.13
\title Leather
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb עוֹר
\trl ‘or
\ref H00100302100022 H00102701600006 H00202202600020 H00202500500004 H00202500500012 H00202601400014 H00202601400024 H00202901400016 H00203402900056 H00203403000026 H00203403500020 H00203500700004 H00203500700012 H00203502300036 H00203502300044 H00203601900014 H00203601900024 H00203903400008 H00203903400024 H00300401100006 H00300700800018 H00300801700014 H00300901100016 H00301103200034 H00301300200010 H00301300200030 H00301300300018 H00301300300050 H00301300400014 H00301300400030 H00301300500046 H00301300600048 H00301300700018 H00301300800024 H00301301000022 H00301301100010 H00301301200018 H00301301200032 H00301301800014 H00301302000022 H00301302100034 H00301302200014 H00301302400012 H00301302500038 H00301302600038 H00301302700030 H00301302800022 H00301303000028 H00301303100034 H00301303200066 H00301303400042 H00301303400056 H00301303500018 H00301303600024 H00301303800016 H00301303900016 H00301303900036 H00301304300042 H00301304800032 H00301304800042 H00301304900028 H00301304900054 H00301305100058 H00301305100070 H00301305200052 H00301305300054 H00301305600046 H00301305700040 H00301305800028 H00301305900040 H00301501700012 H00301602700066 H00400400600010 H00400400800024 H00400401000020 H00400401100028 H00400401200048 H00400401400066 H00401900500018 H00403102000014 H01200100800018 H01800200400018 H01800200400022 H01800700500018 H01801001100002 H01801801300006 H01801902000004 H01801902000022 H01801902600006 H01803003000002 H01804003100010 H02401302300008 H02500300400008 H02500400800022 H02500501000002 H02603700600024 H02603700800026 H03300300200016 H03300300300014
\heb תַּחַשׁ
\trl tachash
\ref H02601601000012
\grk βυρσεύς
\trl burseus
\ref G04400904300022 G04401000600012 G04401003200032
\grk δερμάτινος
\trl dermatinos
\ref G04000300400028 G04100100600020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0377_tanner_with_leather.jpg|col||Deutsche Fotothek|Tanning leather|1.0\fig*Leather was the skin or hide of an animal prepared by special processes to remove the hair and to keep it from decaying or becoming brittle. The person who prepares leather is called a leather worker or tanner.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Leather had many uses, which included making clothing parts, such as belts and sandals. It was also used to make containers for liquids, such as water and wine. Sometimes it was used for making straps for harnessing animals and other binding activities.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Some languages will have a special word for “leather,” but many will use the same word as for the “skin” of an animal.
\line The Hebrew word \i tachash\i* refers to an aquatic animal, the dugong (see \i All Creatures Great and Small\i*, pages 42-43). It is only mentioned in Scripture with reference to its skin, so it is usually accompanied by the Hebrew word \i ‘or\i*. In \s H02601601000012\s* the word \i ‘or\i* is omitted, but \i tachash\i* there means the fine tanned leather made from the skin of that animal.
\key 1.14
\title Rope, cord
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַגְמוֹן
\trl ’agmon
\ref H01804002600006
\heb חֶבֶל
\trl chevel
\ref H00600201500010 H01000800200018 H01000800200032 H01000800200044 H01001701300030 H01002200600002 H01102003100044 H01102003200014 H01700100600014 H01803600800018 H01804002500014 H01901800500004 H01901800600002 H01911600300004 H01911906100002 H02000502200016 H02101200600012 H02300501800012 H02303302000040 H02303302300004 H02403800600050 H02403801100072 H02403801200044 H02403801300012 H02602702400030 H02801100400004
\heb מֵיתָר
\trl meythar
\ref H00203501800024 H00203904000038 H00400302600044 H00400303700022 H00400402600048 H00400403200022 H02305400200022 H02401002000010
\heb מֹשְׁכוֹת
\trl moshkoth
\ref H01803803100012
\heb נִקְפָּה
\trl niqfah
\ref H02300302400020
\heb עֲבֹת
\trl ‘avoth
\ref H00202801400020 H00202801400032 H00202802200018 H00202802400010 H00202802500014 H00203901500018 H00203901700010 H00203901800014 H00701501300044 H00701501400036 H00701601100016 H00701601200008 H01803901000012 H01900200300014 H01911802700018 H01912900400008 H02300501800022 H02600302500016 H02600400800010 H02801100400012
\grk ζευκτηρία
\trl zeuktēria
\ref G04402704000024
\grk κλῶσμα
\trl klōsma
\ref L07100603000022
\grk νευρά
\trl neura
\ref L07800700100044
\grk σχοινίον
\trl schoinion
\ref G04300201500010 G04402703200012 L07300104300044
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0378_rope.jpg|col||Rogers Fund, 1912, Metropolitan Museum of Art|Rope|1.0\fig* Rope was a fairly thick cord formed by twisting or braiding several strands together. It could be made of a variety of materials, including palm fibers, linen, or reeds.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Rope had multiple uses. It could be used to bind things together, to connect draft animals to the implements they pulled, to tie people up, and even to measure the length of things.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In Exodus the Hebrew word \i ‘avoth\i* refers to short, cordlike connectors between the ephod and the shoulder straps. The text says they were made of pure gold. They have been understood as chains with links or as strips of gold braided into a kind of cord. Translations have rendered it various ways, but none of these renderings leave a really clear picture (and in that sense they reflect the Hebrew text); for example, in \s H00202801400020\s* \a CEV\a* and \a NIV\a* have “braided chains of pure gold,” \a GNT\a* says “chains of pure gold twisted like cords,” \a REB\a* uses “chains of pure gold worked into the form of cords,” and \a NJPSV\a* translates “chains of pure gold; braid these like corded work.” An alternative translation model offered by \i A Handbook on Exodus\i* is “gold cords that they have braided [or, twisted] like rope” (page 656).
\line In \s H01803600800018\s* the phrase “cords of affliction” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*; compare similar expressions in \s H01002200600002 H01901800500004 H01901800500004 H01911600300004 H01911906100002 H01912900400008 H02801100400004\s*) will sound as strange in many languages as it does in English. The translator should look for a rendering that is functionally equivalent; for example, \a GNT\a* renders \s H01803600800018\s*b as “suffering for what they have done.” \a NCV\a* maintains the metaphor of ropes while still using idiomatic English: “or if trouble, like ropes, ties them up.”
\line The Hebrew text of \s H01911802700018\s* is uncertain. Most translations (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a CEV\a*), as well as \i A Handbook on Psalms\i*, understand the word \i ‘avoth\i* to refer to leafy branches, perhaps in reference to a custom at the Feast of Tabernacles. Some translations (\a REB\a*, \a NJPSV\a*, \a NASB\a*, New King James Version [\a NKJV\a*]) and rabbinic commentators understand the word to refer to thick ropes used to tie the sacrificial victim to the altar.
\line The ropes mentioned in \s G04402703200012\s* would obviously have been rather thick, while in \s G04300201500010\s* the whip that Jesus made in driving the animals and merchants out of the Temple would probably have consisted of strong cords.
\line In \s G04402704000024\s* the Greek word \i zeuktēria\i* refers to ropes used to link two rudders of a boat (see the illustration at \l target="REALIA:8.1.8">8.1.8 Steering oar, rudder\l*). In most languages translators would simply use a term for “rope.”
\key 1.15
\title Doctors and medicine
\index \l target="REALIA:1.15.1">1.15.1 Oil, ointment\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.15.2">1.15.2 Poultice, fig cake\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.15.3">1.15.3 Eye salve\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.15.4">1.15.4 Bandage\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:1.15.5">1.15.5 Drugged wine, myrrhed wine\l*
\key 1.15.1
\title Oil, ointment
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שֶׁמֶן
\trl shemen
\ref H02300100600052
\grk ἔλαιον
\trl elaion
\ref G04100601300014 G04201003400016 G05900501400032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Ointment was oil extracted from the fruit of olive trees.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The oil itself served to soothe and to soften wounds. It could also serve as a base to which other medicinal plant extracts were added. See also \l target="REALIA:1.10.5">1.10.5 Anointing oil\l* and \l target="REALIA:9.3">9.3 Olive oil\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s G04201003400016\s* it is important to recognize the medicinal value of oil and wine. In some instances translators have indicated the purpose of such an activity by translating “He went over to him. To cleanse and heal his wounds, he poured wine and oil on them and bandaged them ....” It may also be helpful to add a marginal note to explain the antiseptic quality of wine and the value of oil in the healing process.
\line Some have questioned whether the anointing with oil in \s G05900501400032\s* is primarily a medicinal act or a spiritual one. \i A Handbook on The Letter from James\i* says the following concerning this: “As to the function of \b anointing\b*, it is well known that olive oil was often used in the ancient world for medical purposes; for example, in cleansing, soothing, and healing wounds (\s H01202000700010\s*; \s H02300100600052\s*; \s G04100601300014\s*; \s G04201003400016\s*). While not ruling out the possibility that the anointing here is for medical purposes, there are certainly other factors involved. Most probably it also has religious and symbolic purposes, reminding the sick person of God’s concern for his faithful people in time of distress, and stimulating as well as awakening faith. This is confirmed by the fact that the anointing is performed \b in the name of the Lord\b*. In any case these interpretations will not in any way affect the outcome of translation” (page 190).
\key 1.15.2
\title Poultice, fig cake
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb דְּבֵלָה, תְּאֵנָה
\trl dveleth t’enim
\ref H01202000700010 H02303802100010
\grk μάλαγμα
\trl malagma
\ref L07001601200012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The poultice was a lump or pressed block of dried figs.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Such a block of dried figs could be used simply as food (see \l target="REALIA:9.5">9.5 Blocks of pressed dried fruit\l*). The dried fruit would keep for a long time. On occasion it could be applied to a boil or eruption on the skin as a means of softening the skin for healing.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In the story of the healing of Hezekiah (\s H01202000700010 H02303802100010\s*), the exact nature of the fig application is uncertain. Several models for translating the Hebrew phrase \i dveleth t’enim\i* are “mashed figs” (\a CEV\a*), “paste of crushed figs” (\a FRCL\a*), “fig-plaster” (\a REB\a*), and “paste made of figs” (\a GNT\a*). Where figs are unknown, translators may say “fruit named fig” or find some local fruit that could serve both as food and medicine.
\line The Greek word \i malagma\i* in \s L07001601200012\s* refers to a kind of compress that was intended to soften a wound or sore on the skin. The word “ointment” in \a GNT\a* and \a TOB\a* is somewhat imprecise, while the word “poultice” (\a RSV\a*) is obscure in English. \a NAB\a* says “application,” which is a useful model. \a ITCL\a* has “bandage.”
\key 1.15.3
\title Eye salve
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk κολλούριον
\trl kollourion
\ref G06600301800052
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Eye salve was an ointment. It is possible that it was also in the form of a powder.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The salve was applied to the eyes as a medicine.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where the equivalent for a specific “eye salve/ointment/ paste” is not available, the Greek word \i kollourion\i* may be rendered simply as “medicine for the eyes.”
\key 1.15.4
\title Bandage
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֲפֵר
\trl ’afer
\ref H01102003800034 H01102004100014
\heb חִתּוּל
\trl chitul
\ref H02603002100036
\grk καταδέω
\trl katadeō (verb)
\ref L07102702100008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The bandage was a strip of cloth used to wind around a broken arm or leg while it healed.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Most languages will have a word for a bandage or binding for a broken limb. The modern word for a hard plaster cast would be an anachronism and should be avoided. In \s H02603002100036\s* the Hebrew word \i chitul\i* means strictly something that is wound around the broken arm and not a sling in which the arm rests. However, the poetic language of the verse repeats the description and thus makes it possible to expand the translation; for example, the last half of this verse in \a GNT\a* reads “No one bandaged it or put it in a sling so that it could heal and be strong enough to hold a sword again” (similarly \a CEV\a*).
\key 1.15.5
\title Drugged wine, myrrhed wine
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk σμυρνίζω, οἶνος
\trl esmurnismenos oinos
\ref G04101502300008
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Drugged wine was wine mixed with myrrh. It was used as a potion to reduce pain.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In general the Greek phrase \i esmurnismenos oinos\i* must be rendered by means of a phrase or clause, for example, “wine that has been mixed with a drug called myrrh” or “wine mixed with a drug to reduce pain.” It is also possible to use an abbreviated phrase such as “myrrhed wine” and then to place the explanation of its function in a footnote.
\key 1.16
\title Fuller, laundryman
\index \l target="REALIA:1.16.1">1.16.1 Soap, lye\l*
\key 1.16.1
\title Soap, lye
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בֹּרִית
\trl borith
\ref H02400202200020 H03900300200040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Soap or lye was a cleansing agent made by boiling together ashes and animal fat.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In both passages the use of the Hebrew word \i borith\i* is metaphorical, speaking of the judgment or removal (or attempted removal) of sin. Almost all cultures know some sort of cleansing agent for removing dirt.
\line \s H02400202200020\s*: Two cleansing agents are mentioned here; the first one is a mineral (soda or natrium), and the second one is soap or lye. While the use of fat-based soap for washing is not thought to have started as early as the time of Jeremiah, the meaning here seems clear. Translations vary on the rendering of the two cleansing agents (\a NCV\a* “cleanser” and “soap”; \a CEV\a* “soap” and “bleach”; \a RSV\a* “lye” and “soap”). \a GNT\a* combines the two by rendering the first two lines of the verse as “Even if you washed with the strongest soap.” It is also possible to render the meaning without reference to specific cleaning agents; for example, “No matter how hard you try to clean yourself,” “No matter how hard you scrub,” or “No matter how much you wash yourself.”
\line \s H03900300200040\s*: While the \i borith\i* in \s H02400202200020\s* was not able to remove stains, in this verse it symbolizes a strong agent that will purify all stains. The Hebrew phrase \i borith mkabsim\i* in this verse is literally “soap of launderers.” Two models are \a GNT\a* “strong soap” and \a GECL\a* “lye in the washing place.” The strength of the cleansing agent is in focus, so \a ITCL\a* “soap that washes clothes” may be too weak.
\c 2
\key 2
\title Warfare
