\grk συγκεντέω
\trl sugkenteō (verb)
\ref L07801202300016
\grk συνεκκεντέω
\trl sunekkenteō (verb)
\ref L07800502600016
\lat gladius
\ref V08201202700010 V08201202800006 V08201500500006 V08201501500020 V08201501900026 V08201503500036 V08201504900018 V08201505700038 V08201600300006 V08201602200040 V08201602300014
\lat romphea
\ref V08201501500030 V08201502200018 V08201504100010 V08201505700016 V08201603200028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0381_straight_sword.jpg|col||© Rama|Straight swords|2.0\fig* The length and shape of swords varied widely in different periods and different nations. The basic concept, however, remained the same: the sword was a long, heavy knife made of metal, at first of bronze, and later of harder metals like iron. In earlier biblical times the blade tended to be more for cutting; it was curved similar to a sickle (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.6">1.1.6 Sickle\l*), but it was sharpened only on the outside of the curve, unlike the sickle, which was sharpened on the inside of the curve. With this type of sword for cutting, no emphasis was placed on a point for piercing. In the later Old Testament period, swords were made more for piercing. These swords, which were as short as 30-40 centimeters (12-16 inches) at first, had relatively broad, pointed blades that were sharpened on both sides. By the time of the Israelite kings, the blades had become longer and relatively narrower.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages the term for “sword” is simply “large knife,” but in some regions it may be called “machete for killing” or “war knife.” \fig |WEB-0382_curved_sword.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Curved sword|2.0\fig*
\line The Hebrew word \i cherev\i* is a general term and does not specify whether the sword is long or short. Where a language makes a distinction, it will generally be best to translate it “short sword.” In the New Testament the Greek word \i machaira\i* refers to a short sword and \i rhomfaia\i* is a long sword. The phrase “with/by the edge of the sword” (occurring over 30 times with over half of them in Joshua and Judges) usually has in view the older, curved sword, which had only one edge. Normally it will not be necessary to render this expression literally, but it will be sufficient to say something like “with/by the sword.”
\line In many passages we find the phrase “die by the sword” or “slain by the sword” (for example, \s H01803601201000\s*; \s H02400501200028\s*; \s H02402100901000\s*; \s H02603101701000\s*; \s G04002605201000\s*). This is an idiomatic expression meaning to die a violent death. It normally (but not always; compare \s H00900203301000\s*) means to die in war, and translators may often use an expression such as “killed in war” (\a GNT\a* in \s H02401600401000\s*) or “die in battle.” In such cases it usually indicates a non-heroic death; where a language has a special word or phrase for “die the death of a warrior,” the translator should not use that expression unless such a death is what is intended by the biblical text. In cases where death in warfare is not the meaning, one may say “die a violent death” or “killed by people.” One should not substitute a modern weapon for “sword”; for example, it would be anachronistic to say “shot to death.”
\line In some passages the word “sword” simply stands for warfare, for example, \s H02400501201000 G04500803500042 G06600600800066\s*. \s H00602401200038\s* says literally “Then I sent the hornet before you and it drove out the two kings of the Amorites from before you, [but] not by your sword or your bow” (\a NASB\a*). It may be preferable in some languages to translate the last part of this verse without naming the specific weapons: “Your weapons and strength had nothing to do with it.” It is also possible to translate this with both a positive and negative statement: “I defeated them for you. It was not your own strength and weapons that did it.”
\line The phrase “men who drew the sword” occurs in a number of passages (\s H00700801000064 H00700802000028\s* [6 times]; \s H01002400900042 H01302100500044\s*). This is simply an idiomatic expression for “soldiers,” which is the \a GNT\a* rendering in \s H00700801000064\s*.
\line The phrase “lift up the sword” occurs in \s H02300200400026\s* and \s H03300400300030\s* with the meaning “go into battle” or “go to war.” \a GNT\a* gives the correct English equivalent by rendering the second to last line in each of these verses as “Nations will never again go to war.” In some languages a literal rendering of the idiom “to lift up the sword” will have quite a different meaning, such as “to surrender” or “to be victorious.” This is not the meaning of the text and should be avoided.
\line The Hebrew phrase \i cherev pifiyoth\i* (\s H01914900600012\s*) or \i cherev piyoth\i* (\s H02000500400018\s*) refers to a sword sharpened on both edges of the blade, that is, a “two-edged sword” (\a RSV\a*; compare \s G05800401200026 G06600101600030 G06600201200028 L07102100300004\s*). This is the straight sword of later Old Testament times and onward.
\line In \s H00104900500014\s* the meaning of the Hebrew word \i mkerah\i* is doubtful. Most translators connect Jacob’s words to the events described in \s H00103402501000 H00103402601000\s* and understand \i mkerah\i* to be a kind of weapon, probably parallel to the “sword” (\i cherev\i* in Hebrew) in those verses.
\line In \s H01905502200026\s* the Hebrew word \i pthichoth\i* refers to swords that are “drawn” (literally “open”), that is, ready for use. Thus, for the last line of this verse \a CEV\a* has “and he was ready to attack with a sword.” Others prefer to use a simile; for example, \a GNT\a* has “but they [his words] cut like sharp swords” and \a NCV\a* says “. . . cut like knives.”
\line In \s G04200203500016\s* the word “sword” is used figuratively for pain or anguish. Often translators can use a rather literal rendering. Sometimes it is preferable to shift to a simile; for example, the first half of this verse may be rendered “As for your soul, it will be as if a sword pierced it.” In some cases the equivalent expression does not need a term for “sword,” for example, “and you too shall be pierced to the heart” (\a NEB\a*). It is also pos­sible to use a nonfigurative expression, for example, “you will experience anguish.” There is no implication here of a military death, and the translator should avoid the use of a term that might carry that implication.
\key 2.3.1
\title Sheath, scabbard
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb נָדָן
\trl nadan
\ref H01302102700022
\heb תַּעַר
\trl ta‘ar
\ref H00901705100032 H01002000800060 H02404700600022 H02602100800030 H02602100900024 H02602101000022 H02602103500006
\grk θήκη
\trl thēkē
\ref G04301801100024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0403_bodyarmor_weapons_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Armed soldier|2.0\fig* The sheath was a case or bag about the size and shape of a sword, used to cover and to carry the sword. It could be made of a variety of materials, usually leather, but also cloth, metal, or even wood. It was normally attached to a circular strap or belt that could be hung over the shoulder or tied around the waist. In later Old Testament times, when iron swords were too heavy for a belt alone, the sheath was attached to a combination of a belt and a shoulder strap.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The sheath covered the blade of a sword in order to protect the blade and to protect the person carrying the sword and those around him from being cut accidentally.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages “sheath” may be rendered “leather bag for a sword,” “covering for a sword,” or “something in which a sword is carried.”
\key 2.4
\title Dagger
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk ἐγχειρίδιον
\trl egcheiridion
\ref L07300101300006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0202_sword.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Dagger|2.0\fig* The dagger was a short stabbing weapon with a pointed blade. It was held easily in one hand and could be concealed without difficulty.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The dagger was smaller than the short sword and in most cultures will be comparable to a pointed knife.
\key 2.5
\title Spear, lance
\index \l target="REALIA:2.5.1">2.5.1 Spearhead\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֲנִית
\trl chanith
\ref H00901301900038 H00901302200022 H00901700700010 H00901700700022 H00901704500028 H00901704700028 H00901801000058 H00901801100012 H00901900900028 H00901901000016 H00901901000048 H00902003300012 H00902100900024 H00902200600048 H00902600800040 H00902601200012 H00902601600054 H00902602200014 H00902602200016 H01000100600038 H01000202300022 H01000202300036 H01002101900050 H01002300700018 H01002301800034 H01002302100030 H01002302100052 H01002302100068 H01201101000026 H01301101100040 H01301102000028 H01301102300040 H01301102300068 H01301102300084 H01301203500022 H01302000500042 H01402300900024 H01803902300010 H01804101800010 H01903500300006 H01904601000022 H01905700500020 H02300200400034 H03300400300038 H03400300300016 H03500301100024
\heb רֹמַח
\trl romach
\ref H00402500700036 H00700500800022 H01101802800032 H01301200900046 H01301202500012 H01401101200018 H01401400700018 H01402500500086 H01402601400022 H01600400700056 H01600401000038 H01600401500024 H02404600400028 H02603900900054 H02900401000016
\heb שֵׁבֶט
\trl shevet
\ref H01001801400024
\grk γαῖσος
\trl gaisos
\ref L06800900700044
\grk δεξιολάβος
\trl dexiolabos
\ref G04402302300038
\grk δορά, δόρυ
\trl dora, doru
\ref L06800701000024 L06801100200036 L06900801200026 L07102901300012 L07900301500008 L07900504300018 L07900600500020
\grk κάμαξ
\trl kamax
\ref L07800500300030
\grk κέντρον
\trl kentron
\ref L08001401900034
\grk λόγχη
\trl logchē
\ref G04301903400010 L07800500200042 L07801501100018
\grk σιβύνη
\trl sibunē (zibunē)
\ref L06800101500028
\lat framea
\ref V08201300900026 V08201302800010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The spear was a long, straight rod with a sharp end used for piercing by thrusting. Its circumference was less than the grip of a man’s hand, and its length varied from the height of a man to much longer. It was normally made of wood with a metal head or point (see \l target="REALIA:2.5.1">2.5.1 Spearhead\l*). The butt of the spear was also covered with a pointed piece of metal (see \s H01000202300022\s*) and was used to stick the spear in the ground or to drive oxen or horses as a goad.
\line See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:2.3.1">2.3.1 Sheath, scabbard\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line In battle the spear was held in the middle and thrust at the enemy. Only rarely was it intended for throwing (see \l target="REALIA:2.6">2.6 Javelin\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where possible, translators should choose a word or phrase that indicates that this weapon was held and thrust (much like a knife on the end of a stick) rather than thrown.
\line The phrase “lifted up his spear” occurs in \s H01002301800034\s* and \s H01301101100040\s*. \a GNT\a* gives the correct meaning with “fought with his spear.”
\line The meaning of the Greek word \i dexiolabos\i* in \s G04402302300038\s* is uncertain. Most translations have “spearmen” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*), “foot soldiers with spears” (\a CEV\a*), “men with spears” (\a NCV\a*), or “light-armed troops” (\a REB\a*).
\key 2.5.1
\title Spearhead
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לֶהָבָה
\trl lehavah
\ref H00901700700020
\heb קַיִן
\trl qayin
\ref H01002101600028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0383_spearhead.jpg|col||Los Angeles County Museum of Art|Spearhead|2.0\fig* The spearhead was a piece of metal, usually iron or bronze, attached to the end of the spear (see \l target="REALIA:2.5">2.5 Spear, lance\l*). It was either placed over the end of the spear shaft like a sleeve or wedged into a split at the end of the spear shaft and secured by tying it with a cord. The spearhead was sharpened to a point.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In both of the references the spearhead is mentioned because of its exceptional size (about 7 kilograms, 15-16 pounds). The spearhead of an average soldier weighed much less. It is possible, but less likely, that the Hebrew word \i qayin\i* in \s H01002101600028\s* refers to the entire spear, including its iron head.
\key 2.6
\title Javelin
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כִּידוֹן
\trl kidon
\ref H00600801800018 H00600801800050 H00600802600020 H00901700600014 H00901704500034 H01803902300014 H01804102100018 H02400602300006 H02405004200006
\heb שִׁרְיָה
\trl shiryah
\ref H01804101800016
\grk ὕσσος
\trl hussos
\ref G04301902900020
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0200_javelin.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Javelin|2.0\fig* The javelin was a type of short spear or large arrow (see \l target="REALIA:2.14.2">2.14.2 Arrow\l*). It was lighter than the spear and, unlike the spear, was suited for throwing at the enemy from a standing position or while riding on a horse or in a chariot. Javelins were made of wood or reed. Like the spear, the javelin had a metal head or point fixed in the same way as a spearhead (see \l target="REALIA:2.5.1">2.5.1 Spearhead\l*). It often had a cord wrapped around its middle and looped over the finger of the thrower. As the javelin was released, the cord unwound, spinning the javelin and giving it greater stability, accuracy, and distance.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Javelin” may be rendered “throwing spear” or “light spear.”
\line Roland de Vaux suggests that the Hebrew word \i kidon\i* refers to a long sword or type of scimitar. This interpretation has been followed by \a GECL\a*, \a CEV\a* and \a NJB\a* in some of the passages listed above. \a REB\a* has “sabre” at \s H01804102100018\s*, but it shortens the weapon considerably at \s H00600802600020\s* with “dagger.” Most translations, however, prefer “javelin,” “spear,” or “lance.”
\line The Hebrew word \i shiryah\i* in \s H01804101800016\s* refers to a weapon, but it has not been definitely identified. Many translations have “javelin” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*), \a GNT\a* says “lance,” and \a NLT\a* uses “pointed shaft.”
\line In \s G04301902900020\s* the Greek word \i hussos\i* is a variant reading that is accepted by some scholars (but rejected by most) instead of the better-attested \i hussōpos\i* (“hyssop”).
\key 2.7
\title Club, war club, mace, shattering weapon
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כְּלִי, מַפָּץ
\trl kli mapats
\ref H02600900200032
\heb מַפֵּץ
\trl mapets
\ref H02405102000002
\heb מַקֵּל, יָד
\trl maqel yad
\ref H02603900900046
\heb תּוֹתָח
\trl tothach
\ref H01804102100008
\grk ξύλον
\trl xulos
\ref G04002604700038 G04002605500034 G04101404300036 G04101404800028 G04202205200046
\grk ράβδος
\trl rhabdos
\ref L07600102500054
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0384_mace.jpg|col||© Einsamer Schütze|Mace head|2.0\fig* The war club was a short wooden rod used for striking the enemy in hand-to-hand combat. It could be held with one hand and was used to strike the enemy on all parts of his body, particularly where he was unprotected by armor. The mace was normally fitted with a heavy head made of stone or metal. This head was wedged over the end of the stick and secured by tying or by the tapered shape of the stick. The handle too could be tapered wider in order to give a better grip. The handle was some­times curved.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i tothach\i* appears only in \s H01804102100008\s*. Most scholars agree that it means “club,” although it has also been suggested that it refers to the shafts of arrows. However, no translation consulted reflects this latter possibility.
\line Since the main point in \s H02600900200032\s* is the fearfulness of the weapon, some translations focus on this element rather than attempt to find an exact implement in the receptor language. So \a CEV\a* has “deadly weapon,” \a NCV\a* “powerful weapon,” and \a FRCL\a* “destructive weapon.”
\line \s H02603900900046\s*: While many translations have “clubs” (\a GNT\a*) or “war clubs” (\a NCV\a*) here for the Hebrew phrase \i maqel yad\i* (literally “hand staff” or “handstick”), there are other possibilities. Some have “spears” (\a GECL\a*) or “javelins” (\a SPCL\a*). G. Baez-Camargo suggests that it was a kind of boomerang (compare \a REB\a* “throwing-sticks,” which could have several meanings). Since the point of the passage is that abandoned wooden weapons will be in abundance and will be burned instead of firewood, it may be possible to combine several of the weapons listed in this verse under a more general heading; for example, \a ITCL\a* has combined \i maqel yad\i* and “spears” under “lances,” and \a CEV\a* combines the two types of shields under the collective “shields.”
\line The Greek word \i xulos\i* in \s G04002604700038 G04002605500034 G04101404300036 G04101404800028\s*; and \s G04202205200046\s* is literally “wood,” which could be understood simply as “sticks” in this context of a lynch mob. However, all translations consulted have “clubs” or an equivalent word.
\key 2.8
\title Battle-axe
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb סגר
\trl sgor
\ref H01903500300010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0385_battle_axe.jpg|col||Jebulon|Battle-axe|2.0\fig* The battle-axe had a handle about half the length of a man’s body on which was mounted a metal blade sharpened on opposing sides. A soldier could use it in close combat and swing it in two directions without changing his grip on it. The illustration shows one possible shape of the blade.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i sgor\i* looks like the imperative form of the verb meaning “close, shut off,” so the Septuagint understood it to mean “capture, make a prisoner.” Many translations take it to be a second weapon with the sword mentioned just before it, and most have rendered it “javelin” (\a RSV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*). However, \i A Handbook on Psalms\i* (page 329) points out that there is evidence from Qumran that the \i sgor\i* was a kind of axe used in war. Several translations (\a GNT\a*, \a NASB\a*, \a ITCL\a*) have accepted this meaning. \a NJB\a*, citing the Qumran information, has “pike,” which was a long thrusting spear. This Handbook recommends “battle-axe.”
\key 2.9
\title Helmet
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כּוֹבַע
\trl kova‘
\ref H00901700500004 H01402601400026 H02305901700016 H02404600400022 H02602701000026 H02603800500018
\heb מָעוֹז, רֹאשׁ
\trl ma‘oz ro’sh
\ref H01906000900016 H01910800900014
\heb קוֹבַע
\trl qova‘
\ref H00901703800018 H02602302400032
\grk περικεφαλαία
\trl perikefalaia
\ref G04900601700006 G05200500800024 L07700603500036
\grk κόρυς
\trl korus
\ref L07000501800012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0404_helmet.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Helmet|2.0\fig* The helmet was protective armor covering the head. In some helmet designs there were flaps extending down over the ears or even to the neck. Among the Israelites and their immediate neighbors, helmets were usually made of leather. Helmets made of metal were rare and were generally imported from countries to the east and north. See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:2.3.1">2.3.1 Sheath, scabbard\l*.
\line ——— \fig |KNW-0405_helmet.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Helmet|2.0\fig*
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line For languages having no term for “helmet,” translators may use a descriptive equivalent, such as “protection for the head” or “covering for the head in fighting.” The figurative expression “helmet of salvation” in \s H02305901700016\s* and \s G04900601701000\s* may be rendered “salvation, which is like a protection for the head.” \fig |KNW-0406_helmet.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Helmet|2.0\fig*
\key 2.10
\title Shields
\index \l target="REALIA:2.10.1">2.10.1 Large shield\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.10.2">2.10.2 Small shield, buckler\l*
\cont A shield has been defined as “a device to serve as a barrier between the body of a soldier and the weapon of his enemy.”
\key 2.10.1
\title Large shield
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb צִנָּה
\trl tsinah
\ref H00901700700038 H00901704100030 H01101001600014 H01101001600032 H01301200900042 H01301202500008 H01301203500018 H01400901500014 H01400901500034 H01401101200014 H01401400700014 H01402500500090 H01900501300016 H01903500200008 H01909100400018 H02404600300008 H02602302400024 H02602600800040 H02603800400046 H02603900900030
\grk ἀσπιδίσκη
\trl aspidiskē
\ref L07700405700022
\grk ἀσπίς
\trl aspis
\ref L06800900700038 L07000501900004 L07102901300004 L07103700500018 L07700603900022 L07701402400020 L07701501800006 L07701502000012 L07800500300024 L07801501100014
\grk κάλυμμα
\trl kalumma
\ref L07700400600026 L07700600200022
\grk θυρεός
\trl thureos
\ref G04900601600010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0386_large_shield.jpg|col||© Johnbod|Large shields|2.0\fig* The large shield was a long, oblong shield. It was about the height of a man since it was intended to protect the entire body. It could be made of wood, metal, leather stretched over wood, or even plaited strips of wood or reeds.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line This shield was held with one hand by means of straps attached to its back. A warrior who held his sword in his right hand would hold his shield with his left hand, and vice versa. The shield was held between the warrior and his opponent and was used to ward off blows from swords, spears or clubs, as well as to stop any missiles such as arrows, stones, or javelins. In the story of David fighting the giant Goliath (\s H00901700000000\s*), a servant stood in front of Goliath holding the giant’s shield.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages “shield” is rendered “protection a person carries when he fights” or “protection carried to prevent blows from the enemy.” In passages where “shield” is used figuratively, it is possible to preserve the element of protection while avoiding translating the actual piece of armor; for example, “his faithfulness is a shield and buckler” (\s H01909100400018\s* in \a RSV\a*) may be rendered “God keeps his promises and will protect and defend you.”
\line The Hebrew word \i tsinah\i* is sometimes used metaphorically of God as protector (see \s H01900501300016\s* and \s H01909100400018\s* and the discussion at \l target="REALIA:2.10.2">2.10.2 Small shield, buckler\l*).
\line In \s H02602600800040\s* the Hebrew word \i tsinah\i* indicates a special large shield, known technically as a mantelet (see \l target="REALIA:2.19.8">2.19.8 Mantelet\l*), which was held above or in front of soldiers engaged in siege activities. While the Hebrew word is singular, such cover was normally made of many such shields. So for the last part of this verse, \a GNT\a* has “make a solid wall of shields against you” and \a CEV\a* says “set up rows of shields around you.”
\line In the Septuagint the Greek word \i kalumma\i* refers to the veil or a cloth covering furniture in the Tabernacle. In \s L07700400600026\s* almost all translations render it as some piece of protective “armor” (\a RSV\a*, \a CEV\a*). In \s L07700600200022\s* some render it “shields” (\a RSV\a*, \a CEV\a*), while \a NAB\a* and Goldstein prefer “helmets.”
\key 2.10.2
\title Small shield, buckler
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מָגֵן
\trl magen
\ref H00101500100040 H00503302900018 H00700500800014 H01000102100034 H01000102100038 H01002200300010 H01002203100016 H01002203600008 H01101001700008 H01101001700026 H01101402600044 H01101402700014 H01201903200046 H01300501800028 H01400901600008 H01400901600026 H01401200900054 H01401201000014 H01401400700038 H01401701700024 H01402300900032 H01402601400018 H01403200500072 H01403202700056 H01600401000042 H01801502600016 H01804100700006 H01900300400008 H01900701100002 H01901800300022 H01901803100016 H01901803600008 H01902800700008 H01903302000014 H01903500200004 H01904701000020 H01905901200022 H01907600400010 H01908401000002 H01908401200008 H01908901900008 H01911500900014 H01911501000016 H01911501100016 H01911911400006 H01914400200016 H02000200700014 H02000601100020 H02002403400018 H02003000500010 H02200400400020 H02302100500026 H02302200600024 H02303703300046 H02404600300004 H02404600900032 H02602302400028 H02602701000022 H02603800400050 H02603800500014 H02603900900026 H03400200400002
\heb עֲגָלָה
\trl ‘agalah
\ref H01904601000024
\heb שֶׁלֶט
\trl shelet
\ref H01000800700010 H01201101000034 H01301800700010 H01402300900040 H02200400400028 H02405101100012 H02602701100026
\heb שֶׁמֶשׁ
\trl shemesh
\ref H01908401200004 H02305401200008
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0387_round_shield.jpg|col||Gary Todd|Soldiers with round shields|2.0\fig* Like the larger shield, this shield could be made of wood (sometimes covered with leather) or metal. It varied in shape but was usually round. Wooden shields were often reinforced by metal spikes or by being covered with metal plates.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line See \l target="REALIA:2.10.1">2.10.1 Large shield\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line See \l target="REALIA:2.10.1">2.10.1 Large shield\l*. \s H01000102100034\s* and \s H02302100500026\s* speak of oiling the shield. Shields that were covered with leather were oiled periodically to keep the leather from cracking. Oiling also preserved metal shields by keeping them from rusting. Where the idea of oiling a shield may be obscure to the readers, translators may wish to follow the example of \a GNT\a* for the last part of \s H02302100501000\s*, where it has “Prepare your shields!” (similarly \a NCV\a*). Another possible model is \a CEV\a* “Grab your shields” or even \a GECL\a* “to arms!”
\line In many passages, particularly in the Psalms, God is figuratively likened to a shield. Where such a comparison might be misunderstood, it may be replaced with a description of God as protector or defender; for example, in \s H00101500100040\s* \a NCV\a* renders the literal clause “I am your shield” as “I will defend you.” It is also possible to expand the translation in such cases; for example, in \s H01002200300010\s* the Hebrew word rendered “my shield” by \a RSV\a* becomes “He protects me like a shield” in \a GNT\a*. Such figurative references are found in \s H00101500100040 H00503302900018 H01002200300010 H01002203100016 H01002203600008 H01900300400008 H01900701100002 H01901800300022 H01901803100016 H01901803600008 H01902800700008 H01903302000014 H01905901200022 H01908401000002 H01908401200008 H01908901900008 H01911500900014 H01911501000016 H01911501100016 H01911911400006 H01914400200016 H02000200700014 H02003000500010\s*.
\line \s H01904601000024\s*: Some translations render the Hebrew word \i ‘agaloth\i* as “chariots,” but most scholars agree that “chariots” cannot be meant and that “shields” is more likely. The word \i ‘agaloth\i* is related to the Hebrew word for “round,” and this makes it likely that the smaller, round shield is intended. Ancient shields were most commonly made of wood and leather, and frequently rubbed with olive oil. As a result they would burn easily. Where shields are known only to be made of metal, it may be helpful to include a note explaining how shields can be set on fire.
\line The Hebrew word \i shemesh\i*, which normally means “sun,” also carries the meaning of a round shield that formed part of the protection at the top of a city wall (see the illustration at \l target="REALIA:2.19.3">2.19.3 Firing platform, siege tower\l*). Thus, the phrase “sun and shield” (\a RSV\a*) in \s H01908401000002\s* speaks of two types of shield. Most modern translations wrongly retain “sun,” but compare \a NJB\a*, which has “rampart and shield.” \a NJPSV\a* gives “bulwark” in the margin. “Protector and glorious king” in \a GNT\a* keeps the idea of “sun” in “glorious king,” but it reverses the order as it is found in the Hebrew.
\key 2.11
\title Leg armor, leg protectors
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb מִצְחָה
\trl mitschah
\ref H00901700600004
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0388_leg_protectors_roman.jpg|col||© MatthiasKabel|Leg armor, leg protectors|2.0\fig* Leg armor was protective armor for the lower leg. It was made of leather or metal, covered the front half of the leg, and was tied at the back with leather thongs. The leg armor worn by Goliath was made of bronze.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The only protection for the lower leg known in many societies today is related to sports such as football. Translators will have to be careful that use of such a word does not sound amusing to the reader (as is possibly the case with the \a NASB\a* marginal reading “shin guards” in \s H00901700600004\s*). To avoid this, and because the old English word “greaves” is now obscure, modern translations choose descriptive phrases; for example, \a GNT\a* begins \s H00901700600004\s* with “His legs were also protected by bronze armor” (similarly \a CEV\a*).
\key 2.12
\title Breastplate, chest protector
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שִׁרְיוֹן
\trl shiryan
\ref H01102203400040 H01401803300040 H02305901700012
\grk θώραξ
\trl thorax
\ref G04900601400024 G05200500800014 G06600900900006 G06600900900006 G06600901700030 L07000501800008 L07104302000068 L07700300300036 L07700600200056 L07700604300040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0407_chest_protector_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Chest protector|2.0\fig* The breastplate was a piece of armor covering the chest (and sometimes the back) to protect it against blows and arrows. It was normally made of metal or thick leather reinforced with metal. It covered the chest from the neck to the waist and was held on by straps around the back.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The use of the word “breastplate” in \s G04900601400024\s* and \s G05200500800014\s* is figurative to indicate the protective values of certain Christian virtues (compare \s L07000501800008\s*). So it is possible to translate the figurative meaning as follows: “We must protect ourselves, like with armor, with faith and love” (\s G05200500800014\s*b in \a SPCL\a*) and “the protection of right living on your chest” (\s G04900601400024\s*c in \a NCV\a*).
\line In \s G06600900900006\s* the breastplates are worn by the horses. Warhorses sometimes wore breast shields to protect them from the enemy’s spears and swords. For the first half of this verse, \a RSV\a* has “they had scales like iron breastplates.” \a NJB\a* is better with “They had body-armour like iron breastplates.” \a SPCL\a* translates “Their bodies were covered with a kind of iron armor.” Another possible rendering is “Their bodies were covered with what looked like pieces of metal used to protect the chests of people.”
\key 2.13
\title Scale armor, coat of mail
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שִׁרְיוֹן, קַשְׂקֶשֶׂת
\trl shiryon, shiryon qasqasim
\ref H00901700500014 H00901700500016 H00901703800032 H01402601400030 H01600401000054
\grk ἁλυσιδωτός
\trl halusidōtos
\ref L07700603500032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0389_scale_armor_detail.jpg|col||© MatthiasKabel|Scale armor|2.0\fig* Scale armor was a kind of vest or shirt covering the upper part of the body. It was made of several hundred small bronze scales or platelets overlapping each other and sewn on a cloth or leather base. The scales were thin and about 11 by 6 centimeters (4.5 by 2.5 inches). Such armor was lighter than a solid metal breastplate (see \l target="REALIA:2.12">2.12 Breastplate, chest protector\l*) and was also more flexible, giving greater maneuverability. It was used especially by a soldier who could not carry a shield but still needed protection in battle (for example, a chariot driver).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Many languages will not have a specific term for such armor. In \s H00901700500014\s* both \a RSV\a* and \a NRSV\a* have the somewhat archaic term “coat of mail.” \a NIV\a* has “scale armor,” and \a NCV\a* says “coat of . . . armor.” Where body armor is unknown, translators may say “shirt covered with thin metal plates to protect the chest.”
\line King Ahab was killed when a stray arrow penetrated some weak spot in his armor (\s H01102203401000\s*; \s H01401803301000\s*). The Hebrew word used to refer to this weak spot in the armor is \i deveq\i*. \a RSV\a* renders it “scale armor,” but it seems more likely that the word refers to a joint between two parts of the armor. \a GNT\a* has “between the joints of his armor,” and \a CEV\a* says “where two pieces of his armor joined.”
\key 2.14
\title Archery
\index \l target="REALIA:2.14.1">2.14.1 Bow\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.14.2">2.14.2 Arrow\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.14.3">2.14.3 Quiver\l*
\key 2.14.1
\title Bow
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קֶשֶׁת, קַשָּׁת
\trl qesheth, qashath
\ref H00100901300004 H00100901400024 H00100901600008 H00102101600022 H00102102000034 H00102700300016 H00104802200038 H00104902400010 H00602401200046 H00900200400002 H00901800400040 H00903100300028 H01000101800014 H01000102200014 H01002203500016 H01102203400012 H01200602200024 H01200902400014 H01201301500012 H01201301500024 H01201301600020 H01300501800038 H01300804000018 H01301000300026 H01301200200004 H01301200200030 H01401400700044 H01401701700020 H01401803300012 H01402601400034 H01600400700060 H01600401000048 H01802002400012 H01802902000010 H01804102000008 H01900701300012 H01901100200012 H01901803500016 H01903701400012 H01903701500012 H01904400700008 H01904601000014 H01907600400008 H01907800900010 H01907805700018 H02300502800012 H02300702400014 H02301301800004 H02302101500026 H02302101700008 H02302200300012 H02304100200048 H02306601900034 H02400402900012 H02400602300002 H02400900200010 H02404600900042 H02404903500016 H02405001400014 H02405002900014 H02405004200002 H02405100300012 H02405105600022 H02500200400004 H02500301200004 H02600102800008 H02603900300006 H02603900900034 H02800100500022 H02800100700030 H02800202000048 H02800701600012 H03000201500008 H03500300900006 H03800901000024 H03800901300010 H03801000400012
\grk τόξον
\trl toxon
\ref G06600600200026 L06800900700048 L07000502100018
\lat arcus
\ref V08201601300012
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Bowstring\b*:
\heb יֶתֶר
\trl yether
\ref H00701600700018 H00701600800014 H00701600900038 H01803001100004 H01901100200020
\heb מֵיתָר
\trl meythar
\ref H01902101300010
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Archer\b*:
\heb ירה
\trl yarah (verb)
\ref H00903100300020 H01001102400004 H01001102400008 H01301000300020 H01403502300004
\heb רַב
\trl rav
\ref H01801601300006 H02002601000002 H02405002900008
\grk τοξότης
\trl toxotēs
\ref L06800201500038 L07700901100050
\lat sagittarius
\ref V08201600700014 V08201601600014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0408_warrior_shooting_arrow.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Shooting an arrow from a bow|2.0\fig* The bow was an arch made of wood or other flexible material and bent by a string attached to its two ends. Ancient bows were of two types. The simpler and less effective was triangular in shape, with the wooden body of the bow formed from two straight pieces. Much stronger and more effective was the composite bow, which was constructed of alternating layers of material, mostly wood and animal horn glued together. Ancient bows varied in length between about 80 centimeters (30 inches) to over a meter (40 inches). The bowstring was normally made of spun linen or hemp.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The archer gripped the center of the wooden part of the bow in one hand and placed the notch that was cut into the back end of an arrow on the string. With the fingers of his other hand he gripped the string and the arrow and pulled back the arrow. When he released the arrow, it flew forward toward the target. In battle the object was to wound the enemy with the sharp point of the arrow. This weapon allowed the soldier to attack the enemy without coming into physical contact with him. \fig |UBS-0014_bow.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Bending bows for stringing|2.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where bows and arrows are unknown, it may be necessary to say “weapon” or “weapon that shoots darts [or, missiles],” without specifying what kind of weapon it is, while carefully avoiding the implication that it is a gun that uses gunpowder and shoots bullets. The weapon should be recognized as useful in battle and operated by one person.
\line The phrase “bend the bow,” which occurs frequently (\s H01002203500016 H01900701300000 H01901100200012 H01901803501000 H01903701400012 H02300502800012 H02302101500026 H02400900201000 H02404600900042 H02405001400014 H02405002900014 H02405100300012 H02500200400004 H02500301200004 H03800901300010\s*), often does not refer to the drawing of the bowstring in order to shoot but rather to the method of bending the unstrung bow enough to slip the bowstring in place on the end of the bow. Composite bows in particular were very stiff and difficult to string. The underlying idea is preparing the bow for combat. Possible renderings for “bend the bow” are “string the bow” and “prepare the bow for use.” In \s H02405100301000\s*a \a NCV\a* has “Don’t let the Babylonian soldiers prepare their bows to shoot.”
\line In some passages the word “bow” symbolizes warfare. See the discussion on \s H00602401200046\s* at \l target="REALIA:2.3">2.3 Sword\l*.
\line \s H01002203500016 H01802002400012 H01901803501000\s*: In \s H01802002400012\s*a \a RSV\a* says “a bronze arrow will strike him through.” “Bronze arrow” is literally “bow of bronze” in Hebrew. However, bows were not made of bronze, and a bronze bow would not shoot an arrow. The poet attributes to the bow the effect that is produced by the arrow. \a RSV\a* has shifted to “bronze arrow,” but \a GNT\a* has kept “bronze bow.” \a FRCL\a* translates “bronze point,” that is, “bronze arrowhead.” This line may need to be adjusted to say “an arrow with a bronze point will hit him” or “an enemy will shoot an arrow with a bronze point into him.” If “bronze” is unknown, the translator may say “iron” or “metal.” De Vaux suggests that “bronze bow” indicates a kind of metal covering, which was used to strengthen some wooden bows. So “bronze bow” may be rendered “strongest bow” (\a GNT\a* in \s H01002203500016\s* and \s H01901803501000\s*).
\line \s H02400900201000\s*: \a RSV\a* renders the first line of this verse as “They bend their tongue like a bow,” which will be obscure in many languages. \a CEV\a* understands the bent bow to be the actual shooting of the arrows, so it restructures the first half of this verse, saying “Lies come from the mouths of my people, like arrows from a bow.” \a GNT\a* understands the bent bow to indicate readiness for use but avoids the simile with “They are always ready to tell lies.”
\key 2.14.2
\title Arrow
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בֵּן, אַשְׁפָּה
\trl ben ’ashpah
\ref H02500301300008
\heb בֵּן, קֶשֶׁת
\trl ben qesheth
\ref H01804102000006
\heb חֵץ, חֵץִי
\trl chets, chetsi
\ref H00104902300016 H00402400800032 H00503202300008 H00503204200004 H00901700700004 H00902002000010 H00902002100022 H00902002100040 H00902002200020 H00902003600020 H00902003600042 H00902003700016 H00902003700046 H00902003800034 H01002201500006 H01200902400034 H01201301500016 H01201301500028 H01201301700034 H01201301700044 H01201301800010 H01201903200038 H01301200200024 H01402601500042 H01800600400004 H01803400600010 H01900701400012 H01901100200016 H01901801500006 H01903800300004 H01904500600002 H01905700500024 H01905800800014 H01905800800016 H01906400400016 H01906400800008 H01907701800016 H01909100500014 H01912000400002 H01912700400004 H01914400600012 H02000702300006 H02002501800010 H02002601800012 H02300502800004 H02300702400006 H02303703300038 H02304900200028 H02400900700002 H02405000900042 H02405001400026 H02405101100006 H02500301200020 H02600501600008 H02602102600040 H02603900300016 H02603900900040 H03500301100014 H03800901400020
\heb מַטֶּה
\trl mateh
\ref H03500300900010 H03500301400006
\heb רֶשֶׁף
\trl reshef
\ref H01907600400006
\grk βέλος
\trl belos
\ref G04900601600026 L07000501200012 L07101901200004 L07102601200080 L07700605100092 L07800500300072 L07801202700068 L08500202300028 L08500204200012
\grk σχίζα
\trl schiza
\ref L07701008000068
\grk τόξευμα
\trl toxeuma
\ref L07801003000072
\lat sagitta
\ref V08201600700008 V08201601300012 V08201601600008
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0015_arrow.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Arrow|2.0\fig* The arrow was a thin, straight rod made of reed or wood, about 50-70 centimeters (20-28 inches) in length. To one end of the arrow was attached a sharpened point, either of stone or metal. In the other end a notch was carved to fit on the string of the bow. The notched end was sometimes fitted with two or more feathers that helped stabilize the arrow in flight.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line See \l target="REALIA:2.14.1">2.14.1 Bow\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i reshef\i* normally refers to something fiery (for example, spark or lightning bolt; see \s H01800500700016\s*; \s H01907804800022\s*; \s H02200800600046\s*). In \s H01907600400006\s* it is parallel with the word for “bow” and probably indicates some kind of burning arrow.
\line \s H02500301300008\s*: See the comments at \l target="REALIA:2.14.3">2.14.3 Quiver\l*.
\line The Hebrew word \i mateh\i* usually refers to a rod, club, or shepherd’s staff (see \l target="REALIA:1.2.4">1.2.4 Rod, club, shepherd’s staff\l*), but in \s H03500300900010\s* many translations render it “arrows” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*; supported by \a HOTTP\a* and \i A Handbook on The Books of Nahum, Habakkuk, and Zephaniah\i*). This verse is very unclear in Hebrew.
\key 2.14.3
\title Quiver
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַשְׁפָּה
\trl ’ashpah
\ref H01803902300006 H01912700500014 H02302200600008 H02304900200034 H02400501600002 H02500301300010
\heb תְּלִי
\trl tli
\ref H00102700300012
\grk φαρέτρα
\trl faretra
\ref L07102601200044
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0409_bow_quiver_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Quiver with bow and arrows|2.0\fig* The quiver was a cylindrical leather container, closed on one end, for holding arrows. It was slightly shorter than the arrows it held. It was strapped to the back of the archer so that both hands were free to use the bow. It was large enough to hold 20-30 arrows.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Quiver” may be rendered “container holding the arrows” or “arrow box.”
\line The following is adapted from \i A Handbook on Lamentations\i* (page 81) on \s H02500301300010\s*: The Hebrew phrase \i bene ’ashpah\i* (literally “sons of the quiver”) refers to arrows. The quiver as the container for the arrows is not central to the description of God’s attack here, and translators handle this expression in various ways; for example, \a GNT\a* omits the word “quiver” as unnecessary when speaking of the action of “his arrows” (similarly \a FRCL\a* “all his arrows” and \a GECL\a* “Arrow after arrow”). However, translators who are translating into poetry may need to retain the word “quiver” by rendering the whole verse as follows: “His quiver gave [or, produced] arrows that he shot into my heart.”
\line In \s L07102601200044\s* “quiver” is used in a euphemism for the female genitalia. The last half of this verse is literally “she will sit in front of every tent peg and open her quiver to the arrow” (\a NRSV\a*). \a GNT\a* says “She’ll spread her legs anywhere for any man who wants her.” Some translators may consider \a GNT\a*’s English euphemism to be too explicit. If possible, translators should look for an expression that indicates that the woman in the verse is promiscuous without being more explicit than the intended audience can tolerate. One possibility is “she is ready to have sex with anyone who comes along.” Where a suitable euphemism cannot be found, it may be necessary to keep a literal rendering and explain in a footnote that the imagery of the quiver and arrow is intended to portray sexual promiscuity.
\key 2.15
\title Chariot
\index \l target="REALIA:2.15.1">2.15.1 Scythe (chariot weapon)\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מֶרְכָּב, מֶרְכָּבָה
\trl merkav, merkavah
\ref H00104104300010 H00104602900008 H00201402500010 H00201500400002 H00601100600060 H00601100900030 H00700401500056 H00700502800040 H00900801100036 H00900801100052 H01001500100020 H01100500600020 H01100703300018 H01101002900010 H01101201800058 H01102003300054 H01102203500034 H01200502100032 H01200502600026 H01200902700042 H01201001500090 H01202301100056 H01302801800030 H01400101700014 H01400902500020 H01401001800058 H01401400800024 H01401803400034 H01403502400012 H02200601200010 H02300200700040 H02302201800030 H02306601500024 H02400401300018 H02900200500006 H03300101300006 H03300500900034 H03400300200022 H03500300800040 H03700202200026 H03800600100022 H03800600200006 H03800600200022 H03800600300008 H03800600300024
\heb רַכָּב, רכב
\trl rakav (verb or noun)
\ref H01102203400048 H01401803300050 H02405102100012 H02405102100012
\heb רֶכֶב
\trl rekev
\ref H00105000900010 H00201400600008 H00201400700010 H00201400700018 H00201400900028 H00201401700040 H00201401800024 H00201402300020 H00201402600038 H00201402800018 H00201501900012 H00501100400022 H00502000100024 H00502400600010 H00601100400046 H00601701600022 H00601701800040 H00602400600034 H00700101900040 H00700400300020 H00700400700028 H00700401300012 H00700401300018 H00700401500020 H00700401600012 H00700502800028 H00700905300012 H00900801200050 H00901300500020 H01000100600046 H01000800400042 H01000800400052 H01001001800028 H01001102100026 H01100100500026 H01100901900030 H01100902200044 H01101002600008 H01101002600028 H01101002600050 H01101600900018 H01102000100036 H01102002100026 H01102002500038 H01102002500044 H01102203100016 H01102203200014 H01102203300014 H01102203500066 H01102203800010 H01200201100020 H01200201200018 H01200500900020 H01200601400012 H01200601500042 H01200601700058 H01200700600016 H01200701400008 H01200802100016 H01200802100052 H01200902100014 H01200902100038 H01200902400046 H01201000200034 H01201001600030 H01201300700026 H01201301400046 H01201802400036 H01201902300018 H01201902300024 H01301800400012 H01301800400044 H01301800400054 H01301900600058 H01301900700016 H01301901800030 H01400101400008 H01400101400028 H01400101400050 H01400800600038 H01400800900044 H01400902500042 H01401200300010 H01401600800028 H01401803000016 H01401803100014 H01401803200014 H01402100900018 H01402100900052 H01403502400020 H01902000800008 H01906801800002 H01907600700014 H02200100900008 H02302100700006 H02302100700012 H02302100700016 H02302100900010 H02302200600012 H02302200700012 H02303100100026 H02303600900036 H02303702400020 H02304301700006 H02306602000038 H02401702500038 H02402200400054 H02404600900014 H02404700300018 H02405003700012 H02405102100020 H02602302400010 H02602600700042 H02602601000024 H02603902000014 H02701104000034 H03400200400022 H03400200500012 H03400201400022 H03800901000006
\heb רְכוּב
\trl rkuv
\ref H01910400300020
\grk ἅρμα
\trl harma
\ref G04400802900022 G04400802900022 G04400803800010 G06600900900030 L06800101300070 L06800201900050 L06800202200028 L06800702000022 L07104800900014 L07104900800020 L07700101700018 L07700800600042 L07800900700064 L07801300200052 L07900200700010 L07900600400008 L08100102600016 L08100102900010 L08100300600026 L08500100400002 L08500101900012 L11201104000038
\grk ἁρματηλάτης
\trl harmatēlatēs
\ref L07800900400038
\lat currus
\ref V08201502900014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0390_chariot.jpg|col||William C. Morey (Outlines of Greek History, pg. 40)|War chariot|2.0\fig* The chariot was an open vehicle with two or four wheels, used in war or for traveling. War chariots were at first heavy, made of wood, with solid wooden wheels. In later biblical times, they were constructed with a light wooden frame with a standing platform and two wheels set toward the back of the frame. The wheels were a rim with four or six spokes and were set wide apart (about twice the width of the chariot frame) to give extra mobility. The wooden frame was sometimes covered with leather. A pole extended from the center of the front of the frame, and to its end were yoked animals to pull it. It was about 2.5 meters (8 feet) long.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The chariot was harnessed to and drawn by two or four horses. It was manned by a driver and usually another soldier. From its platform the soldier could shoot arrows, throw projectiles, or engage in sword combat. It provided speed of movement on the battlefield but was limited to relatively flat and unobstructed terrain. In combat highest priority was given to mobility and speed of movement, so chariots were made of the lightest materials possible, although several references speak of iron chariots. Note that all these references are to early times (\s H00601701600022\s*, \s H00601701800040\s*; \s H00700101900040\s*; \s H00700400300020\s*, \s H00700401300018\s*). While most translations have simply “iron chariots,” it is possible that these were wooden chariots overlaid with iron (\a REB\a* “iron-clad chariots”). However, it is more likely that the wood was reinforced at certain places with iron and that the wheels had iron rims, making them much less liable to break on rough ground. \fig |WEB-0391_chariot.jpg|col||David Castor (dcastor)|Traveling chariot|2.0\fig*
\line Chariots were also used as a form of transportation, primarily by wealthier people.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In languages that have no technical term for “chariot,” it is possible to speak of a war chariot as “war carriage,” “horse-drawn war cart,” “war cart pulled by horses,” or “horse-drawn cart for fighting.” A traveling chariot, such as the one mentioned in \s G04400802900022\s*, may be rendered “traveling carriage” or “horse-drawn vehicle.”
\line In \s H02200301000012\s* the Hebrew word \i merkav\i* indicates the fancy “bench” or “seat” on which the honored chariot rider sat. For the same word at \s H00301500900008\s*, see \l target="REALIA:8.4">8.4 Saddle, saddle cloth\l*.
\key 2.15.1
\title Scythe (chariot weapon)
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk δρεπανηφόρος
\trl drepanēforos
\ref L07801300200056
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0392_chariot.jpg|col||André Castaigne|Scythe chariots|2.0\fig* The scythe was a sharp, curved blade that was attached to either side of a war chariot. It prevented enemy soldiers from running alongside the chariot to attack. It also could act as an offensive weapon; as the chariot drove swiftly through the enemy, the blade would cut at their legs.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In very few languages will the idea of a weapon attached to a chariot wheel be clear. So a literal translation such as “chariots armed with scythes” (\a NRSV\a*) at the end of \s L07801300200056\s* will probably not communicate sufficient information to the reader. \a GNT\a* expands this to “chariots with sharp blades attached to their wheels.”
\key 2.16
\title Wooden tower on elephant
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk πύργος, ξύλινος
\trl purgos xulinos
\ref L07700603700004
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0393_war_elephants.jpg|col||Bernard Picart|War elephants|2.0\fig* In ancient warfare, elephants were sometimes used almost like a tank in modern warfare. The animal was so large that it frightened opposing soldiers and could hardly be withstood by an individual soldier. Sometimes a kind of wooden tower or box was placed on the back of the elephant as an elevated firing platform for soldiers. The whole heavy apparatus was strapped on the elephant with straps (called \i mēchanē\i* in this verse) that went under the animal’s belly and perhaps around its neck and even under its tail. \a NJB\a* renders these straps as “girths.”
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s L07700603700040\s* the actual number of soldiers on each platform is in doubt. The Greek text has “thirty” or “thirty-two,” which would be too many even for a large elephant. Rahlfs emends the text to read “four” (followed by \a RSV\a*), while \a GNT\a*, \a NJB\a*, and \a TOB\a* have “three.” The Norwegian Bible (\a NOB\a*) has “two.” The normal number of soldiers on an elephant, according to Charles, was three or four, and translators will normally have one of these numbers and perhaps include a footnote.
\key 2.17
\title Standard, ensign, banner
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אוֹת
\trl ’oth
\ref H00400200200010 H01907400400014 H01907400400016
\heb דגל
\trl dagal (verb)
\ref H01902000600016 H02200600400024 H02200601000036
\heb דֶּגֶל
\trl degel
\ref H00400105200022 H00400200200006 H00400200300012 H00400201000002 H00400201700042 H00400201800002 H00400202500002 H00400203100044 H00400203400030 H00401001400006 H00401001800006 H00401002200006 H00401002500006 H02200200400014
\heb נֵס
\trl nes
\ref H00201701500018 H00402100800026 H00402100900020 H01906000600008 H02300502600006 H02301101000026 H02301101200006 H02301300200010 H02301800300018 H02303001700050 H02303100900018 H02304902200028 H02306201000036 H02400400600004 H02400402100008 H02405000200018 H02405101200010 H02405102700004 H02602700700024
\heb נסס
\trl nasas (verb)
\ref H03800901600032
\heb תֹּרֶן
\trl toren
\ref H02303001700034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0394_standards.jpg|col||Cyclopedia of Biblical, Theological and Ecclesiastical Literature, 1888|Standards|2.0\fig* The standard was a distinctive device used to identify a particular group. It could be a flag or a board attached to a stick. In many cases it was a metal device or image (such as an eagle or the head of a lion) that was fitted over the end of a pole in much the same way that a spearhead was attached to a spear.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew words listed above occur in both military and religious contexts. In a time of war the standard was carried with the army into combat and served as a rallying point for the soldiers. If a victory was won or a strategic position was captured, the standard might be set up in that place as a sign of victory. So in a language where flags or military standards are unfamiliar, it is possible to say the following in \s H01907400400014\s*: “they have placed their signs of victory here” or “they have put up the signs that show they have defeated us.” \fig |WEB-0395_standards_en.jpg|col||Original file: © Steerpike (File:Arch of Titus Menorah.png)|Standards|2.0\fig*
\line There is a textual problem in \s H00201701600012\s*. While the Hebrew text reads \i kes\i*, meaning “seat” or “throne,” some translations accept an emended text that reads \i nes\i*, which appears also in the previous verse; for example, for the first half of this verse \a GNT\a* has “He said, ‘Hold high the banner of the LORD!’ ” Other translations prefer to translate the word \i kes\i* without emendation; for example, \a NIV\a* has “He said, ‘For hands were lifted up to the throne of the LORD.’ ”
\line \s H03800901600032\s*: The precise meaning of the Hebrew verb form \i mithnossoth\i* is doubtful. If it is related to the word \i nes\i*, then the literal meaning is “lifted up as an ensign.” However, very few translations (\a KJV\a*, \a NAB\a*, Vulgate) express this meaning. Most translators and commentators take the word to be related to a different Hebrew root meaning “to shine” or “to sparkle.”
\key 2.18
\title Barrier, barricade, roadblock
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk σκάνδαλον
\trl skandalon
\ref L06800500100062
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The barrier was any structure erected to prevent passage.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s L06800500100062\s*: The Greek word \i skandalon\i* refers literally to the trigger peg in an animal trap. It is used frequently in the New Testament with the meaning “something that causes a person to stumble.” It can also refer to an object that hinders someone’s progress. So \a NJB\a* renders it “obstructions” in \s L06800500100062\s*, and \a ITCL\a* uses the verb phrase “blocked the road.” \a GNT\a* says “roadblocks.”
\key 2.19
\title Siege instruments
\index \l target="REALIA:2.19.1">2.19.1 Siege wall\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.19.2">2.19.2 Siege ramp, siege mound\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.19.3">2.19.3 Firing platform, siege tower\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.19.4">2.19.4 Ladder\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.19.5">2.19.5 Fire thrower\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.19.6">2.19.6 Catapult, ballista\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.19.7">2.19.7 Battering ram\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:2.19.8">2.19.8 Mantelet\l*
\line \fig |WEB-0396_siegeworks_en.jpg|col||ChrisO|Attack on a fortified city|2.0\fig* Many ancient cities were surrounded by a high wall for protection. In wartime an attacking army had to find a way to get past the wall and into the city. Five methods were available to the attacker to conquer a fortified city, all of which are reflected in the Bible: 1) penetration over the top of the fortifications; 2) penetration through the fortifications; 3) penetration below the fortifications; 4) penetration by ruse or trickery (\s H00600800000000\s*); and 5) siege. Penetration from above was usually done by scaling the walls using ladders (\s H02900200701000 H02900200801000 H02900200901000\s*). Going through the wall could be done by chopping it with hammers, axes, and other tools, by breaking it down using a catapult, or by breaking or burning the gates (\s H02405105801000\s*). Frequently, however, this was accomplished with a battering ram (\s H02602102201000\s*). The attack on the wall was often aided by the building of a siege tower, which put the attackers on a level with the defenders on the wall, making it easier to attack them with arrows and javelins. Penetration from below usually meant the long process of digging a tunnel under the wall. Sometimes, however, it was possible to use an existing tunnel, such as a shaft connecting the city to its water supply (\s H01000500801000\s*).
\line Defenders of a city were equally ingenious in finding methods to neutralize the efforts of the attacking army. Ladders were pushed over, second walls were built behind the first wall that was about to fall, and large stones or even burning objects could be thrown down on attackers who got close to the wall. In order to protect soldiers working or attacking near the wall, the attacking army would build a large kind of shield that covered the soldiers from above. This device is mentioned by the prophet Nahum: “The attackers rush to the wall and set up the shield for the battering ram” (\a GNT\a*; \s H03400200601000\s*b).
\line When an army did not have the equipment to use one of these methods, or when the terrain was too difficult for an attack, the attacking army could just close off all exits from the city and sit tight. This was called a siege. Its objective was to wait until the people inside the city ran out of food or water and were then ready to surrender (\s H01202500000000\s*).
\key 2.19.1
\title Siege wall
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb דָּיֵק
\trl dayeq
\ref H01202500100072 H02405200400074 H02600400200016 H02601701700044 H02602102700060 H02602600800024
\heb מָצוֹד
\trl matsod
\ref H02100901400036
\heb מָצוֹר
\trl matsor
\ref H00502002000032 H02600400200008 H03300401400010
\heb סלל
\trl salal (verb)
\ref H01801901200010
\grk χάραξ
\trl charax
\ref G04201904300022 L08000301200058
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The siege wall was a fence of poles or stakes used to fortify entrenchments. Sometimes such a wall was reinforced with, or even made of, earth and stones.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line When an army was trying to capture a walled and fortified city, it surrounded the city with an extra wall, which would prevent any of the inhabitants of the city from escaping or launching an attack against the besiegers. Such a wall would also prevent the people in the city from sending for help or from bringing in food and water. After some time the city would be forced to surrender (see \s H00502002000032\s*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew words in some of the passages listed above may be rendered “thick walls” or “strong fences.”
\key 2.19.2
\title Siege ramp, siege mound
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סֹלְלָה
\trl sollah
\ref H01002001500026 H01201903200056 H02303703300056 H02400600600024 H02403202400006 H02403300400044 H02600400200024 H02601701700036 H02602102700054 H02602600800032 H02701101500016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0397_siege_ramp_en.jpg|col||© Andrew Shiva|Siege ramp at Massada|2.0\fig* The siege ramp was a road leading up to the walls of a city that was under attack. Fortified cities were often built on high ground and were difficult to approach. Battering rams (see \l target="REALIA:2.19.7">2.19.7 Battering ram\l*) were very heavy and hard to move. The attackers would build a ramp or road over which they could bring their battering ram and other siege instruments.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It is not always clear from the context if the Hebrew word \i sollah\i* refers to a siege wall or to a ramp for an assault. Most translations choose something like “siege mound,” which will not be understood by most readers. In \s H02600400200024\s* \a GNT\a* has “earthworks,” which is more modern English but does not indicate the function of the structure. \a NIV\a* comes closer with “a ramp up to it.”
\key 2.19.3
\title Firing platform, siege tower
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בַּחוּן
\trl bachun
\ref H02302301300030
\heb מֻצָּב
\trl mutsav
\ref H02302900300020
\heb מְצוּרָה
\trl mtsurah
\ref H02302900300028
\grk βελόστασις
\trl belostasis
\ref L07700602000028 L07700605100022
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0398_battering_ram.jpg|col||Capillon, British Museum|Attacking city walls from a siege tower|2.0\fig* The siege tower was a high, wooden structure that enabled a besieging army to fire arrows, stones and other missiles into the besieged city. It was sometimes constructed with wheels so that it could be pushed closer to the walls. Near its top was a platform on which the attacking soldiers could fire their missiles at the defenders on the walls as a cover for their own troops while they undermined the wall or attacked it with a battering ram.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i matsor\i* and its derivative \i mtsurah\i* refer to both the act of besieging a city and the implements that were built for the siege (see \l target="REALIA:2.19.1">2.19.1 Siege wall\l*). Elsewhere the word can indicate a kind of tower (see \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.3">3.13.3.3 Watchtower, tower\l*). \s H02302900300020\s* says literally “I will raise towers against you.” The “towers” in this context are siege towers. This line may be rendered “I will build battle towers from which to attack you.” Some translators may prefer a more general rendering, such as “I will . . . attack from all sides” (\a CEV\a*) or “I will surround you . . . with devices to attack you” (\a NCV\a*).
\line The Hebrew word \i bachun\i* in \s H02302301300030\s* is an emendation for \i bchin\i*. Almost all translations take it to be some kind of tower. Most have “siege towers” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*, \a GECL\a*). \a NJPSV\a* says “watchtowers,” while others do not make a choice and just have “towers” (\a NAB\a*, \a ITCL\a*, Vulgate).
\line In \s L07700602000028\s* the Greek word \i belostasis\i* has been rendered “siege towers” (\a RSV\a*, \a NRSV\a*), “siege platforms” (\a GNT\a*), “embankments” (\a ITCL\a*), “batteries” (\a NJB\a*), “ballista” (\a TOB\a*), and “catapults” (\a NAB\a*). Liddell and Scott define the word \i belostasis\i* as “battery of warlike engines,” since it is a rather generic term. Translators may want to reflect this by saying “devices to aid in bombarding the city.”
\key 2.19.4
\title Ladder
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk κλῖμαξ
\trl klimax
\ref L07700503000034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0055_wooden_ladder.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz|Ladder|2.0\fig* The ladder was a device by which an attacking army could scale the walls or defenses of a city. It was constructed of wood and consisted of two long poles laid parallel and then joined together by a series of crosspieces that were tied to the poles with ropes. It was carried by the soldiers (or by prisoners captured from the enemy) and placed against the wall of the city so that they could climb it and gain entrance to the city.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It may be necessary to say in translation that the “ladders” in \s L07700503000034\s* were relatively “long” or “high.” While the text itself gives an indication of the purpose of the ladders (\a RSV\a* “. . . carrying ladders and engines of war to capture the stronghold, and attacking the Jews within”), some translators may feel the need to expand it a bit more regarding the use of the ladders: “ladders to climb the walls.” See also the discussion at \l target="REALIA:3.13.3">3.13.3 City fortifications\l*.
\key 2.19.5
\title Fire thrower
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk πυροβόλον
\trl purobolon
\ref L07700605100030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The fire thrower was a kind of catapult device for propelling burning objects (perhaps burning arrows) at a besieged city. It may have been simply an adapted catapult (see \l target="REALIA:2.19.6">2.19.6 Catapult, ballista\l*) or perhaps a kind of large crossbow.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s L07700605100100\s* \a GNT\a* expands the literal expression “fire throwers” to “catapults for throwing fire.”
\key 2.19.6
\title Catapult, ballista
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חִשָּׁבוֹן
\trl chishvon
\ref H01402601500010
\grk λιθοβόλον
\trl lithobolon
\ref L07700605100034
\grk πετροβόλος
\trl petrobolos
\ref L07000502200006
\grk σκορπίδιον
\trl skorpidion
\ref L07700605100038
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0399_catapult_ball.jpg|col||© Moshe Milner, Israel Government Press Office|Ballista stones|2.0\fig* The catapult was a device constructed of wood and ropes or leather cords and used in the siege of a city. It consisted of a base to which was attached a long wooden arm. At one end of the arm was an open bowl-like container that held the object to be projected, usually a heavy stone. The arm was forced down by mechanical means, bending the wood into a tense bow. When released, the arm snapped back into place, hurling the stone in the direction of the besieged city. The size of the stones varied widely according to the size of the catapult.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H01402601500010\s* seems to describe a kind of catapult “to shoot arrows and hurl large stones” (\a NIV\a*), and most translations follow this pattern. However, this seems to be an anachronism. De Vaux and Yadin suggest that the Hebrew word \i chishvon\i* in this context refers to projections or frames (which were possibly made of stone, but were more likely wooden frames covered with shields that were erected when attack was imminent) that protected the defenders on the walls of the city as they shot arrows or slung rocks at the attackers below. This is reflected in \a NJB\a*’s rendering of \s H01402601500010\s*a, which reads “He also erected expertly contrived devices for the towers and angles of Jerusalem from which to shoot arrows and drop large stones.” \a NJB\a* also adds the following footnote: “Defensive screens projecting from the stonework, not platforms for catapults which were still unknown at that epoch.” \fig |WEB-0400_catapult_ball.jpg|col||© ChrisO|Catapult|2.0\fig*
\line While the Greek text of \s L07700605100038\s* uses three words for instruments to propel objects (see \l target="REALIA:2.19.5">2.19.5 Fire thrower\l*), some translators may want to combine the three words in a more general phrase, for example, “weapons [or, machines] that threw fire and spears and rocks.” \a GNT\a* provides a good model: “catapults for throwing fire and stones, and other weapons to throw spears and rocks.”
\key 2.19.7
\title Battering ram
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶרֶב
\trl cherev
\ref H02602600900022
\heb כַּר
\trl kar
\ref H02600400200040 H02602102700018 H02602102700044
\heb קְבֹל
\trl qvol
\ref H02602600900006
\grk ἑλεόπολις
\trl heleopolis
\ref L07701304300028 L07701304400012
\grk κριός
\trl krios
\ref L07801201500028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0401_battering_ram.jpg|col||ChrisO, British Museum|Battering ram|2.0\fig* The battering ram was a log or other long, heavy piece of wood covered on one end with metal. It was rammed by soldiers against the wall or gate of a city under siege. It sometimes had a point since the purpose of the ramming was to wedge a hole in the wall. Others were blunt on the end. Repeated banging on the wall weakened it and caused it to fall or opened a hole in it. After the ram had penetrated the wall, it would be levered back and forth until that section of the wall fell. It could be held and swung by soldiers, or sometimes it was suspended by ropes from a moveable wooden tower.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where there is no word for “battering ram,” translators may use a descriptive phrase. In \s H02602600900022\s* \a NCV\a* has “He will bring logs to pound through your city walls,” and \a CEV\a* says “He will command some of his troops to use large wooden poles to beat down your walls.” However, \a ITCL\a* “They will pound your walls with their heavy weapons” may be misleading to the modern reader.
\line \s H02602600900022\s* has the Hebrew word \i cherev\i*. While this word normally means “sword,” the context here makes this interpretation unlikely. In \s H00202002500024\s* the same word means something like “chisel” (\a GNT\a*). Here in \s H02602600900022\s* it seems to refer to a heavy iron tool that could be used to break apart a stone wall. De Vaux suggests a kind of battering ram with a pointed head or a sapper’s pick. Translations have various renderings, such as “axes” (\a RSV\a*, \a REB\a*), “iron rods” (\a CEV\a*), “iron bars” (\a GNT\a*, \a NCV\a*), and simply “weapons” (\a NIV\a*).
\key 2.19.8
\title Mantelet
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb סֹכֵךְ
\trl sokek
\ref H03400200600026
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0402_mantelet.jpg|col||© Ziko|Mantelet|2.0\fig* The soldiers who operated a battering ram were exposed to attack from above by the defenders of the city. In order to protect them, there was a large protective shield (called a mantelet) over their heads. Sometimes the mantelet was part of the mechanism that carried the battering ram; sometimes it was formed by other soldiers who overlapped individual shields (see \l target="REALIA:2.10.1">2.10.1 Large shield\l*) above their heads.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Many languages will have no word for this ancient warfare technique. In languages that do have a word, like English, it may be so obscure that the average reader will not be familiar with it. It will usually be best to use a descriptive phrase; for example, in \s H03400200600026\s*b) \a CEV\a* has “they hasten to build a shelter to protect themselves against rocks thrown down from the city wall” (\a CEV\a*), and \a ITCL\a* says “the enemies have launched an attack on the wall, all of them huddled tightly under their shields.” \a GECL\a* “the enemy has already erected the protective shelters for his storm troops” could leave the impression that the “protective shelters” are a kind of barracks or secure camp. Where possible, it is advisable to add an explanatory footnote.
\c 3
\key 3
\title Buildings and Structures
\index \l target="REALIA:3.1">3.1 House, permanent dwelling\l*
