\ref H00100400700024 H00100601600028 H00101800100022 H00101800200038 H00101801000038 H00101900600012 H00101901100012 H00101901100046 H00104301900026 H00201202200074 H00201202300052 H00202603600010 H00202900400018 H00202901100018 H00202903200036 H00202904200010 H00203300800032 H00203300900028 H00203301000022 H00203301000044 H00203501500046 H00203501500050 H00203603700010 H00203800800034 H00203803000012 H00203903800038 H00204000500038 H00204000600018 H00204001200018 H00204002800012 H00204002900014 H00300100300022 H00300100500058 H00300300200018 H00300400400014 H00300400700068 H00300401800060 H00300800300016 H00300800400028 H00300803100026 H00300803300006 H00300803500004 H00301000700006 H00301200600050 H00301401100034 H00301402300030 H00301403800018 H00301501400042 H00301502900044 H00301600700026 H00301700400006 H00301700500040 H00301700600022 H00301700900006 H00301902100016 H00400302500032 H00400302600016 H00400402500048 H00400601000036 H00400601300028 H00400601800010 H00401000300022 H00401101000024 H00401200500018 H00401601800030 H00401601900020 H00401602700036 H00401701500014 H00402000600022 H00402500600056 H00402700200042 H00502202100018 H00503101500032 H00601905100056 H00700402000010 H00700905200026 H00701902600022 H00701902700048 H00900202200048 H01001100900008 H01100600800002 H01100603100006 H01100603300010 H01100700500008 H01101400600024 H01101402700036 H01101901300030 H01200401500024 H01200500900026 H01300902100010 H01400402200032 H01401201000036 H01600302000028 H01600302100024 H01700500100074 H01803100900016 H01803103400026 H01902400700012 H01902400900012 H02000500800018 H02000800300016 H02000803400028 H02000901400008 H02001701900012 H02200701400014 H02404300900032 H02600800700010 H02600800800036 H02600801600024 H02603303000030 H02604003800008 H02604100200008 H02604100200020 H02604100300018 H02604100300028 H02604100300040 H02604101100004 H02604101100016 H02604101100028 H02604101700010 H02604102000016 H02604200200014 H02604200400034 H02604201100050 H02604201200006 H02604201200020 H02604700100008 H02800201700026
\arm תְּרַע
\trl tra‘
\ref A02700302600012
\grk θύρα
\trl thura
\ref G04000600600026 G04002403300026 G04002501000040 G04100103300018 G04100200200022 G04101100400016 G04101302900026 G04201100700022 G04201302400012 G04201302500020 G04201302500036 G04301000100020 G04301000200012 G04301000700028 G04301000900008 G04301801600014 G04302001900024 G04302002600038 G04400500900048 G04400501900016 G04400502300032 G04401200600050 G04401201300010 G04401402700038 G04401602600032 G04401602700020 G04402103000048 G04601600900002 G04700201200024 G05100400300022 G05900500900028 G06600300800018 G06600302000010 G06600302000034 G06600400100012
\grk θύρωμα
\trl thurōma
\ref L07101402300020 L07300101700040 L07801404300032
\grk θυρωρός
\trl thurōros
\ref G04101303400042 G04301801600044 G04301801700016
\grk θυρόω
\trl thuroō (verb)
\ref L07700405700040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0058_wooden_outside_door.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz|Door|3.0\fig* The door was the entranceway into a building or structure or the panel that covered that entranceway. Doors were normally made of wood. To one edge along the length of the door was attached a wooden pole which extended slightly past the top and bottom edge of the door. The protruding ends of this pole were sharpened or rounded and set into sockets or holes cut into the stone lintel and threshold, thus allowing the door to swing open and shut. Sometimes the door panel was hung on hinges made usually of leather, sometimes of metal.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some passages “door” means simply “opening” or “doorway” without reference to the physical object (see \s H01800301000008 H01804100600002 H01907802300014\s*). This is especially true of the Hebrew word \i pethach\i*.
\line Occasionally “door” is used as a figure for shutting out; for example, \a CEV\a* says “boundaries” in \s H01803800800008\s*, where God speaks of limiting the extent of the sea. Similarly, in \s H01914100300016\s* the psalmist literally asks the LORD to “keep watch over the door of my lips” (\a RSV\a*). In some languages it may be better to render this line without the image, for example, \a NCV\a* says “help me be careful about what I say.” \a CEV\a* provides a helpful model for the whole verse, saying “Help me to guard my words whenever I say something.”
\line \fig |KNW-0412_door_storeroom_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Door|3.0\fig* There seems to be a textual problem in \s H01100603400006\s*, where the Hebrew text speaks of the two doors to the sanctuary being made of two “curtains.” A minor emendation changes “curtains” to “sections,” which is the reading preferred by most translations. However, the meaning of the text still remains unclear even after the emendation. The rendering of \a GNT\a* shows the way a number of translations solve the difficulty: “There were two folding doors made of pine.” Somewhat more literal is \a NIV\a*, which says “He also made two pine doors, each having two leaves that turned in sockets.”
\line The Aramaic word \i tra‘\i* in \s A02700302600012\s* means “gate” or “door.” Some translations have “door” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*, \a NASB\a*), while others have “opening” (\a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*). The opening may have been in the top of the furnace, but it was more likely in the side as a kind of “doorway.”
\line In \s G04301000700028 G04301000900008\s* the Greek word \i thura\i* is used figuratively to refer to Jesus as the means of access to salvation. The emphasis in these verses is on the “door” as a passageway and not as an object closing off an entrance. The literal translation “I am the door of the sheep” (\a RSV\a*) may often lead to misinterpretation, since the term used for “door” is likely to refer to the door panel rather than to the doorway or entranceway, thus suggesting that Jesus Christ functions primarily to prevent passage rather than to make entrance possible. The translator should use an expression such as “I am the gateway/doorway/entranceway where the sheep enter.”
\key 3.1.2.1
\title Lock
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כַּף, מַנְעוּל
\trl kaf man‘ul
\ref H02200500500032
\heb נעל
\trl na‘al
\ref H00700302300026 H00700302400028 H01001301700034 H01001301800042
\heb סגר
\trl sagar
\ref H00700905100048
\grk κλεῖθρον
\trl kleithron
\ref L07300101700046
\grk κλείω
\trl kleiō
\ref G04002501000036 G04201100700024 G04302001900026 G04302002600040 G04400502300012 G04402103000044 L07104200600020 L07600101400042
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0403_lock_en.jpg|col||© Willh26 (Wikimedia Commons)|Lock and key|3.0\fig* The lock was a device that fastened a door in such a way that it could only be opened by a special key (see \l target="REALIA:3.1.2.2">3.1.2.2 Key\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew expression \i kaf man‘ul\i* in \s H02200500500032\s* probably refers to a wooden protrusion or a cord used to pull back the door bar to allow the door to open. \a GNT\a* has “handle of the door,” while others say “handles of the bolt” (\a RSV\a*, \a NASB\a*) or “handles of the lock” (\a KJV\a*). \a CEV\a* has simply “door.”
\line \fig |ABS-0002_door_with_bar_en.png|col||The Bible for Today's Family, © American Bible Society|Door with bar|3.0\fig* The unusual Greek word used in \s L07300101800000\s* can mean either a lock (so \a RSV\a*) or a bar drawn across a door to secure it (so \a GNT\a*).
\key 3.1.2.2
\title Key
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַפְתֵּחַ
\trl mafteach
\ref H00700302500032 H01300902700028 H02302202200006
\grk κλείς
\trl kleis
\ref G04001601900008 G04201105200016 G06600101800038 G06600300700036 G06600900100040 G06602000100020
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0404_key.jpg|col||© Hermann Junghans (Wikimedia Commons)|Key|3.0\fig* The key was an instrument used for locking and unlocking doors and gates. Ancient keys were generally much larger than anything commonly known today.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Keys are not always well known, so some translators may have to use a descriptive phrase, such as “object that controls whether a door can be opened.” Sometimes it is possible to render “key” by describing its function, for example, “unlocker” or “means to open.” \fig |WEB-0405_keys.jpg|col||© Wolfgang Sauber (Wikimedia Commons)|Keys|3.0\fig*
\line Except for \s H00700302500032\s*, all the references to “key” listed above are symbolic. Nevertheless, all translations consulted use the word “key” even in the symbolic contexts. Note the expansion of \a ITCL\a* at \s H02302202200006\s*: where the text says literally “I will place on his shoulder the key of the house of David (\a RSV\a*), \a ITCL\a* has “To him will be given full authority over the palace of David. The keys will be entrusted to him.” Similarly, \a NLT\a* says “I will give him the key to the house of David—the highest position in the royal court.”
\line It may not be possible to speak of the key to a place, such as “the abyss” (\a GNT\a*) in \s G06600900100040\s* or “the kingdom of heaven” (\a RSV\a*) in \s G04001601900008\s*. In such cases translators may have to say “the key to the entrance to . . .” or “the key used in opening or closing the gate to . . . .”
\key 3.1.2.3
\title Hinge
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גָּלִיל
\trl galil
\ref H01100603400024 H01100603400024
\heb פֹּת
\trl poth
\ref H01100705000040
\heb צִיר
\trl tsir
\ref H02002601400010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0060_hinge.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Metal hinge|3.0\fig* The hinge was a device for attaching two things in a way that they were free to swing relative to each other. On a door the hinge was the point at which the door was attached at the top (the lintel) and at the base (the threshold) or to the doorpost (if there was one), allowing the door to swing open or closed. Hinges for doors of simple dwellings were often just extensions of the wooden door that stood in indentations or sockets in the stone lintel and threshold of the doorway. Hinges for larger doors were made of metal. A metal hinge consisted of three parts: two leaves, one attached to the door and one to the wall or doorpost, and a metal pin that held them together.
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0061_hinge_en.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Wooden hinge|3.0\fig* The exact meaning of the Hebrew word \i galil\i* in \s H01100603400024\s* is uncertain. \a REB\a* takes the word (which is related to a Hebrew verb meaning “to rotate”) to be a “swivel-pin,” that is, a kind of “hinge.” Many translations render this difficult verse in a way that makes it unnecessary to identify the specific object intended by \i galil\i*; for example, \a GNT\a* renders the whole verse as “There were two folding doors made of pine.”
\key 3.1.2.4
\title Doorpost
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַמָּה
\trl ’amah
\ref H02300600400006
\heb אֹמְנָה
\trl ’omnah
\ref H01201801600030
\heb מְזוּזָה
\trl mzuzah
\ref H00201200700022 H00201202200046 H00201202300040 H00202100600030 H00500600900008 H00501102000008 H00701600300050 H00900100900040 H01100603100024 H01100603300016 H01100700500014 H02000803400026 H02305700800014 H02604102100006 H02604300800014 H02604300800018 H02604501900024 H02604501900052 H02604600200028
\heb סַף
\trl saf
\ref H01400300700018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0413_doorpost_lintel_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Doorpost and lintel|3.0\fig* Entrances such as doorways and gateways were rectangular. The two sides of the doorway were sometimes lined with wood, to which the hinges of the door could be attached. The doorposts were these side poles of the doorway. They also served to support the structure above the doorway.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where technical terms for the doorframe parts do not exist, a descriptive phrase may be used; for example, in \s H00201202200046\s*, where \a RSV\a* refers to “the lintel and the two doorposts,” \a NCV\a* has “the sides and tops of the doorframes.”
\line \s H01201801600030\s*: The Hebrew word \i ’omnah\i* only occurs here in Scripture, and its meaning is uncertain. The meaning of the verb root from which it is derived is “to carry, support,” and it could refer either to supporting columns for a large room or to posts that support a door opening. Most translations understand it in this second way and say “doorposts.”
\key 3.1.2.5
\title Lintel
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַשְׁקוֹף
\trl mashqof
\ref H00201200700030 H00201202200036 H00201202300030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The lintel was the top beam of the doorframe (see \l target="REALIA:3.1.2">3.1.2 Door, doorway\l*). See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:3.1.2.4">3.1.2.4 Doorpost\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line See the discussion under \l target="REALIA:3.1.2.4">3.1.2.4 Doorpost\l*.
\key 3.1.2.6
\title Threshold, doorsill
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סַף
\trl saf
\ref H00701902700062 H01101401700026 H02604000600038 H02604000600054 H02604000700036 H02604101600004 H02604101600032 H02604300800006 H02604300800010 H03600201400048
\heb מִפְתָּן
\trl miftan
\ref H00900500400058 H00900500500028 H02600900300028 H02601000400020 H02601001800014 H02604600200058 H02604700100026 H03600100900018
\grk χελωνίς
\trl chelōnis
\ref L06801401500060
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0406_threshold_en.jpg|col||© Dietmar Rabich|Threshold|3.0\fig* The threshold was the bottom part of a doorframe (see \l target="REALIA:3.1.2">3.1.2 Door, doorway\l*); it was the piece that sat horizontally on the ground. It was usually made of stone.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where a technical term for “threshold” does not exist or would not be generally understood, it may be necessary to use a descriptive phrase; for example, in \s H02600900300028\s* \a NCV\a* has “place . . . where the door opened.”
\line \s H03600100900018\s*: The literal phrase “all who jump over [or, on] the threshold” in this verse is obscure and has been rendered in various ways. It may refer to a Philistine religious practice, the origins of which are described in \s H00900500401000 H00900500501000\s*. \a CEV\a* reflects this by saying “worshipers of pagan gods” and adding a footnote. \a NCV\a* is more specific with “those who worship Dagon” but does not add a footnote. Also possible is the expanded translation in \a FRCL\a*, which reads “all those who, like the pagans, jump over the doorsill of the temple.” \a FRCL\a* also includes a footnote with the following alternate rendering: “all those who go up on the [sacred] platform.” See also the discussion in \i A Handbook on The Books of Nahum, Habakkuk, and Zephaniah\i*, pages 152-153.
\line \fig |KNW-0414_threshold_en.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Threshold|3.0\fig* The Greek word \i chelōnis\i* in \s L06801401500060\s* is somewhat obscure. \a NJB\a* has “threshold,” which is also the definition given by Liddell-Scott. In \s L06801300900000\s* we learn that Judith rolled Holofernes’ body off the bed, which means it lay on the floor. So in 14.15 many translations render \i chelōnis\i* as “floor” (\a ITCL\a*, \a NAB\a*), and this seems preferable.
\key 3.1.3
\title Gate or gateway to house or building complex
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַיִל
\trl ’ayil
\ref H01100603100022 H02604000900020 H02604000900024 H02604001000048 H02604001400008 H02604001400018 H02604001600018 H02604001600060 H02604002100026 H02604002100030 H02604002400028 H02604002400030 H02604002600046 H02604002600048 H02604002900012 H02604002900016 H02604003100024 H02604003100026 H02604003300012 H02604003400026 H02604003400028 H02604003600006 H02604003600008 H02604003700004 H02604003700008 H02604003700026 H02604003700028 H02604003800012 H02604004800018 H02604004900044 H02604100100020 H02604100300014
\heb פֶּתַח
\trl pethach
\ref H01001100900008 H01101402700036 H01401201000036 H02404300900032 H02600800700010
\heb פֶּתֶח, שַׁעַר
\trl pethach sha‘ar
\ref H00701801600022 H00701801700074 H02403601000050 H02600800300060 H02600801400012 H02601001900048 H02601100100018 H02604001100014 H02604004000026 H02604600300016
\heb שַׁעַר
\trl sha‘ar
\ref H01700201900020 H01700202100020 H01700300200016 H01700300300016 H01700400200012 H01700400200028 H01700400600026 H01700500900040 H01700501300038 H01700601000058 H01700601200010 H02604000300052 H02604000600008 H02604000600042 H02604000800012 H02604001100014 H02604001100024 H02604001400026
\heb שַׁעַר, אִיתוֹן
\trl sha‘ar ’iton
\ref H02604001500010
\grk προαύλιον
\trl proaulion
\ref G04101406800034
\grk πυλών
\trl pulōn
\ref G04002607100010 G04201602000018 G04401001700062 G04401201300014 G04401201400026 G04401201400044
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The gateway was the area associated with the entrance into the courtyard of a house or other building.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H02604000000000\s*–\s H02604100000000\s*: These chapters contain a detailed and complicated description of a large entrance complex leading into the Temple of Ezekiel’s vision. This complex was made up of nine or ten different rooms or areas, some of them described with more than one term. The narrative description of the entrance complex and of the entire Temple is very difficult to understand without reference to diagrams of some sort. Translators should consider using diagrams of Ezekiel’s Temple similar to those provided in this Handbook (see \l target="REALIA:3.14.1">3.14.1 Jewish Temple\l*).
\line The meaning of the Hebrew word \i ’ayil\i* in \s H02604000000000\s*–\s H02604100000000\s* is disputed. Some translations understand it to be a pillar that stands flush with the wall or with the sides of an entranceway; for example, \a RSV\a* renders it “jambs” (see \l target="REALIA:3.1.2.4">3.1.2.4 Doorpost\l*). In this case it would form only part of the entrance but could be understood to stand for the whole entrance.
\line \a RSV\a* has rendered the Greek word \i pulōn\i* as “porch” in \s G04002607100010\s*. For speakers of American English, this is misleading. \a GNT\a* “entrance of the courtyard” is better. Other possibilities are “entryway” and “passageway.”
\line \s G04401201300014\s*: Here Peter knocks on “the door of the \i pulōn\i*” and waits outside until it is opened. This was either the door leading from the street into the inner court or else a smaller door built into the main door of the gate, which could be used for entrance without opening the larger main one. \a NASB\a* “the door of the gate” is accurate but less than clear. Most translations render it “the outer door” or “the outside door.” Some languages may have a single word for this special door; for example, \a GECL\a* uses a single German word meaning “courtyard-gate”). \a SPCL\a* “street entrance” may also serve as a model.
\key 3.1.4
\title Window
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֲרֻבָּה
\trl ’arubah
\ref H00100701100064 H00100800200012 H01200700200042 H01200701900030 H02101200300052 H02302401800050 H02306000800024 H02801300300042 H03900301000056
\heb חַלּוֹן
\trl chalon
\ref H00100800600022 H00102600800032 H00600201500016 H00600201800034 H00600202100038
\arm כַּוָּה
\trl kawah
\ref A02700601100026
\heb צֹהַר
\trl tsohar
\ref H00100601600002
\heb שֶׁקֶף, שְׁקֻפִים
\trl sheqef, shqufim
\ref H01100600400014 H01100700400004 H01100700500018
\grk θυρίς
\trl thuris
\ref G04402000900018 G04701103300006 L06700301100020 L07101402300010 L07800301900066 L11200601100032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0415_windows_en.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Windows|3.0\fig* The window was an opening in a wall for the entrance of light and air and for the purpose of seeing in or out.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages a distinction is made between windows that may be closed with glass or shutters and those that are simply openings. It is probably the latter type that is involved in \s H02801300300042 G04402000900018\s*; and \s G04701103300006\s*, while it is clear that \s H00100601600002 H00100800600022\s*; and \s A02700601001000\s* speak of the former type. Generally, translators should avoid a word for “window” which indicates something made of glass, which was not used in windows in the ancient world.
\line The Hebrew word \i ’arubah\i* occurs in the phrases “windows of heaven” (\s H00100701100064 H00100800200012 H02302401800050 H03900301000056\s*) and “windows in heaven” (\s H01200700200042 H01200701900030\s*). It is not necessary to translate these phrases literally, as seen in \a GNT\a*, which renders the first phrase as “floodgates of the sky” in \s H00100701100064\s* and \s H00100800200012\s* and “Torrents of rain . . . from the sky” in \s H02302401800050\s*. For the literal expression “if the LORD himself should make windows in heaven” in \s H01200700200042\s*, \a GNT\a* has “even if the LORD himself were to send grain” (\s H01200700201000\s*).
\line Opinions differ concerning the meaning of \i ’arubah\i* in \s H02101200301000\s*. Some versions (for example, \a SPCL\a*, \a TOB\a*, \a NIV\a*) translate literally “those [women] who look through windows,” while others take it to be a reference to the eyes (\a CEV\a* “your eyesight”; \a GNT\a*, \a NCV\a*, \a GECL\a* “your eyes”).
\line The Hebrew phrase \i chalone shqufim ’atumim\i* in \s H01100600400014\s* is understood in various ways. Some translations find technical words for a particular architectural feature; for example, for the whole verse \a REB\a* has “and he fitted the house with embrasures,” and \a NIV\a* says “He made narrow clerestory windows in the temple.” Both of these examples demonstrate what should not be done in a common-language translation, using words that may be technically correct but are obscure to the reader. They would have achieved approximately the same effect by transliterating the Hebrew. Some understand these windows to be covered with a kind of “lattice,” “grill,” or “grate” (compare \a SPCL\a*). Others interpret the phrase as describing the structure of the window in the wall; for example, \a GNT\a* says “The walls of the Temple had openings in them, narrower on the outside than on the inside,” and \a CEV\a* has “The windows were narrow on the outside but wide on the inside.” Some think that a kind of “frame” for the window is being described: “And he made for the house windows with recessed frames” (\a RSV\a*). \a NJB\a* combines two of these elements into “He made windows for the Temple with frames and latticework.” When choosing a translation here, it should be kept in mind that the probable purpose of these openings was to allow light into an otherwise rather dim Temple interior. Many translations add a footnote saying that the Hebrew is unclear.
\key 3.1.5
\title Roof, housetop
\index \l target="REALIA:3.1.5.1">3.1.5.1 Parapet, retaining wall\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.1.5.2">3.1.5.2 Roof tile\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.1.5.3">3.1.5.3 Crossbeam, rafter\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גָּג
\trl gag
\ref H00502200800018 H00600200600010 H00600200600034 H00600200800022 H00700905100058 H00701602700036 H00900902500028 H00900902600030 H01001100200032 H01001100200054 H01001602200018 H01001802400026 H01201902600030 H01202301200016 H01600801600026 H01910200800016 H01912900600008 H02002100900012 H02002502400010 H02301500300012 H02302200100024 H02303702700030 H02401901300044 H02403202900062 H02404803800006 H02604001300014 H02604001300022 H03600100500014
\heb מְקָרֶה
\trl mqareh
\ref H02101001800010
\heb קוֹרָה
\trl qorah
\ref H00101900800074
\grk δῶμα
\trl dōma
\ref G04001002700040 G04002401700008 G04101301500010 G04200501900026 G04201200300048 G04201703100018 G04401000900028 L06800800500014
\grk ὄροφος
\trl orofos
\ref L07001700200028
\grk στέγη
\trl stegē
\ref G04000800800028 G04100200400022 G04200700600064 L08001700300008 L08100600400020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Houses in biblical times had flat roofs. These were often surrounded by a low wall or parapet (see \l target="REALIA:3.1.5.1">3.1.5.1 Parapet, retaining wall\l*) that prevented people or objects from falling off. They were made of a base of heavy wooden beams. These were overlaid with branches or grass, which was then covered with dirt, sometimes mixed with lime or stone. The dirt was pounded flat or rolled down with a heavy stone roller. The roof was normally reached by outside stairs along a wall of the house. See the illustrations at \l target="REALIA:3.1">3.1 House, permanent dwelling\l* and \l target="REALIA:3.1.5.3">3.1.5.3 Crossbeam, rafter\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The roof of the house served several purposes. Certain produce was dried there in the sun. In the evening people sometimes sat on the roof in order to enjoy the cool breeze at the end of a hot day. The roof could also serve as a storage area. It was much more commonly the focus of activity than is true in many cultures today.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In view of the various types of activities described as taking place on the housetop, it may be important in some languages to indicate, either in the text or in a marginal note, the fact that such housetops were flat and that there was usually easy access to the roof. This will be especially true for \s H00600200600010 H00600200800022 H00701602700036 H01001100200032 H01001602200018 H02401901300044 H02403202900062 G04002401700008 G04101301500010 G04201703100018 G04401000900028\s*.
\line Where the normal term for “roof” suggests a pitched roof, the expression will have to be adjusted with a descriptive phrase, such as “top of the house” or “flat house top.”
\line \s H00101900800074\s*: At the end of this verse the literal expression “they have come under the shadow of my roof beam” will probably not be understood. As Lot’s guests, the men are under his protection. Even the rendering “they have come under the shelter [or, protection] of my roof” (so \a RSV\a*) may not be clear or convey the full significance in some languages. The short Hebrew phrase here is expanded by \a GNT\a* to “they are guests in my house, and I must protect them.”
\line Several Old Testament verses speak of grass growing on the housetop. To make this understandable, it may be necessary to explain in a footnote how roofs were constructed. Three Old Testament passages compare human beings to “grass on the housetops” (\s H01201902600030 H01912900600008 H02303702700030\s*). The basis of comparison is the fleeting, transitory character of the life of the people involved. In many cultures, however, grass is used as a roofing material, and it is precisely the grass that has lived long and grown strong that is selected for such thatch. In those languages where a literal rendering would present difficulties to certain readers, the translator should try to find a more natural figure of speech without the word “housetop” in it; for example, “grass in the gutters” or “grass growing in the walls.”
\line \s G04001002700040 G04201200300048\s*: The phrase “proclaim from the housetops” (\a NJB\a* in \s G04001002700040\s*) is an idiom meaning “proclaim publicly.” Compare the following model in \i A Handbook on The Gospel of Matthew\i*: “you must announce to all the world” (page 306).
\line For more discussion on how to translate the words “roof” and “housetop,” see John Ellington’s article “Up on the Housetop.”
\key 3.1.5.1
\title Parapet, retaining wall
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb מַעֲקֶה
\trl ma‘aqeh
\ref H00502200800014
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The parapet was a low stone wall built around the flat roof of a house to prevent people or things from falling off. See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:3.1">3.1 House, permanent dwelling\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Most translations use a single word to render the Hebrew word \i ma‘aqeh\i*, for example, “parapet” (\a RSV\a*) and “railing” (\a GNT\a*). \a NCV\a* and \a CEV\a* have “low wall,” while \a SPCL\a* “protective wall” is also good. The context of \s H00502200800014\s* makes the purpose of the parapet clear as seen in the \a GNT\a* rendering of this verse: “When you build a new house, be sure to put a railing around the edge of the roof. Then you will not be responsible if someone falls off and is killed.” Where possible and necessary, it is advisable to add a note explaining the nature and uses of the roof of an Israelite house (see \l target="REALIA:3.1.5">3.1.5 Roof, housetop\l*).
\key 3.1.5.2
\title Roof tile
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk κέραμος
\trl keramos
\ref G04200501900032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0407_roof.jpg|col||© Arivumathi (Wikimedia Commons)|Clay roof tiles|3.0\fig* The roof tile was a thin slab or bent piece of baked clay used to cover a pitched roof. It is also possible that \s G04200501900032\s* is speaking of thin, flat stones.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line While the normal Israelite house did not have roof tiles, \s G04200501900032\s* mentions them specifically. Roof tiles were part of Greek roof construction, although by the time of the New Testament they were also known in the land of Israel. Many suggestions have been made to understand this seeming anomaly, but the translator should translate the text as it is. \fig |PTZ-0062_clay_tiles_on_roof.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Clay tiles on roof|3.0\fig*
\line “Roof tiles” has been rendered “flat stones” or, more generically, “covering” or “roofing.” Where a roofing material other than tiles is known, it may be necessary to adjust the literal clause “through the tiles they let him down on his bed,” for example, “they parted the roof [of split bamboo] and lowered him on his bed” or, without reference to the material, “where the housetop was opened by them, they lowered him on his bed.” \a NCV\a* eliminates any mention of making a hole: “they . . . lowered the man on his mat through the ceiling.”
\key 3.1.5.3
\title Crossbeam, rafter
\cont \u References:\u*
\arm אָע
\trl ’a‘
\ref A01500601100110
\heb גֵּב
\trl gev
\ref H01100600900026
\heb כָּפִיס
\trl kafis
\ref H03500201100014
\heb קרה, קוֹרָה
\trl qarah (verb), qorah
\ref H01400300700014 H02200101700002 H01403401100042
\heb רָהִיט
\trl rachit
\ref H02200101700008
\heb שְׂדֵרָה
\trl sderah
\ref H01100600900030
\grk δοκός
\trl dokos
\ref L07102902200012 L07300101900008 L07300105400048
\grk ἱμάντωσις
\trl himantōsis
\ref L07102201600002
\grk ξύλον
\trl xulon
\ref L08100603100034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0408_roof_beam_en.jpg|col||© Hagit Baldar (Wikimedia Commons)|Roof beams|3.0\fig* The roof of an Israelite house was made of three or even four layers. First thick wooden poles were laid between two walls at the top and along the length of the house. These were inserted in the top of the wall and were part of the wall structure. If they were removed, the wall would be heavily damaged. These “crossbeams” or “rafters” were separated from each other at a distance about the length of a man’s forearm. On top of these crossbeams and perpendicular to them was laid a layer of smaller poles, roughly 3-4 centimeters (1-2 inches) in diameter. These poles were laid side by side to create a platform. They are probably mentioned in \s H01100600900026\s* as \i sderoth\i* (plural of \i sderah\i*). On top of the smaller poles there was a layer of dirt and sometimes on top of the dirt a layer of tiles.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line While the meaning of the Hebrew word \i gev\i* is uncertain in \s H01100600900026\s*, all the translations consulted render it “beams.” See also the discussion on this word at \l target="REALIA:3.1.6">3.1.6 Room\l*.
\line In \s H02200101700002\s* the Hebrew word \i rachit\i* is used figuratively, and there is also a textual problem. See the discussion of this verse in \i A Handbook on Song of Songs\i*, page 49.
\line \s H03500201100014\s*: The Hebrew word \i kafis\i* appears only here in Scripture, but most translations agree that it refers to a rafter or crossbeam in a house. \a NRSV\a* differs by rendering the last line of this verse as “and the plaster will respond from the woodwork.” Babylonian houses were usually built with brick rather than stone, and the prophet is describing Babylonian homes in terms of the building materials he was familiar with in the land of Israel. In a similar way some translators may have to speak of building materials in common use in their own areas (such as clay and wood, or wood and thatch), rather than try to describe “crossbeams” or “rafters”; for example, they may say “and the wood [or, thatch/clay] in the roof cries back [or, echoes the cry].” In some languages it may not be possible to speak of building materials crying out like people. In such cases it may be possible to use a simile and render the whole verse as “It will be as if even the stones and woodwork of your houses bore witness against your evil deeds.”
\line The crossbeam provided essential support for the building. In \s A01500601100110\s* and \s L08100603100034\s* the act of removing a beam from a person’s house will certainly cause it to fall. So an alternative rendering for the middle of these verses is “his house will be destroyed, and one of its wooden beams will be driven through his body.”
\key 3.1.6
\title Room
