\heb גַּב
\trl gev
\ref H02601602400008 H02601603100006 H02601603900016
\heb חֶדֶר
\trl cheder
\ref H00104303000032 H00503202500014 H00701500100046 H00701600900016 H00701601200042 H01001301000020 H01001301000058 H01100101500016 H01910503000010 H02000702700012 H02002400400008 H02200100400014 H02200300400050 H02302602000010 H02600801200036 H02900201600030
\heb יָצוּעַ, יָצִיעַ
\trl yatsu‘a, yatsi‘a
\ref H01100600600004 H01100600600006 H01100601000010 H01100601000014
\heb לִשְׁכָּה
\trl lishkah
\ref H00900902200022 H01202301100036 H01300902600032 H01300903300024 H01302302800034 H01302801200036 H01403101100012 H01500802900046 H01501000600026 H01601003800038 H01601003900054 H01601004000008 H01601300400022 H01601300500008 H01601300800032 H01601300900012 H02403500200032 H02403500400014 H02403500400034 H02403500400048 H02403601000026 H02403601200014 H02403602000026 H02403602100030 H02604001700020 H02604001700040 H02604003800004 H02604004400018 H02604004500012 H02604004600006 H02604101000008 H02604200100034 H02604200400010 H02604200500006 H02604200700020 H02604200700038 H02604200800008 H02604200900016 H02604200900020 H02604201000036 H02604201100016 H02604201200010 H02604201300008 H02604201300014 H02604201300032 H02604401900056 H02604500500050 H02604601900028
\heb נִשְׁכָּה
\trl nishkah
\ref H01600303000042 H01601204400022 H01601300700036
\heb צֵלָע
\trl tsela‘
\ref H01100600500048 H01100600800006 H01100700300020 H02604100900014 H02604100900034 H02604101100008 H02604102600032
\grk θάλαμος
\trl thalamos
\ref L07900101800012
\grk παστοφόριον
\trl pastoforion
\ref L07700403800062 L07700405700036 L08100805800054 L08100900100024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The room was a subdivision in a house or other structure.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The meaning of the Hebrew word \i gev\i* in \s H02601602400008\s* is uncertain. While \a RSV\a* renders it “vaulted chamber,” most translations prefer a word or phrase that indicates a place of forbidden worship, for example, “shrine[s]” (\a NKJV\a*, \a REB\a*, \a NASB\a*), “place to worship gods” (\a NCV\a*), or “mound” (\a NIV\a*).
\line The Hebrew word \i tsela‘\i* appears first in \s H00100202200014\s* as a rib of Adam. Certain rooms in Solomon’s Temple and in the ideal Temple described by Ezekiel ran along the sides of the Temple, and perhaps from some resemblance to the human rib cage they are also designated as \i tsela‘\i*. See the discussion of \s H01100600500048\s* in \i A Handbook on 1-2 Kings\i*.
\key 3.1.6.1
\title Ceiling
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סִפֻּן
\trl sipun
\ref H01100601500038
\grk φάτνωμα
\trl fatnōma
\ref L07800101600008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The ceiling was the upper surface of a room on the inside, separating the room from a room above or from the outside, in which case the ceiling is the inner surface of the roof. See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:3.1.5.3">3.1.5.3 Crossbeam, rafter\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s L07800101600080\s* some translators may find it strange to speak of a hidden door in a ceiling, so it may be necessary to expand the translation or even add a footnote explaining that the priests were, in fact, in a space above the ceiling. They gained access to it through the hidden door.
\key 3.1.6.2
\title Floor
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קַרְקַע
\trl qarqa‘
\ref H00400501700034 H01100601600034 H01100603000006 H01100700700038 H01100700700044
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i qarqa‘\i* in \s H00400501700034\s* describes the unpaved dirt floor of the Tabernacle. We are not told if Solomon’s Temple had paved floors, but since \s H01100603000006\s* says that he overlaid them with gold, we may assume that they had some kind of paving, either wood or stone.
\key 3.1.6.3
\title Wall
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כֹּתֶל
\trl kothel
\ref H02200200900028
\arm כְּתַל
\trl kethal
\ref A01500500800046 A02700500500034
\heb קִיר
\trl qir
\ref H00301403700022 H00301403700046 H00301403900036 H00901801100030 H00901901000028 H00901901000054 H00902002500028 H00902502200042 H00902503400064 H01000501100036 H01100501300042 H01100600600080 H01100601500008 H01100601500034 H01100602700050 H01100602700070 H01100602900008 H01101401000028 H01101601100038 H01102102100030 H01200401000008 H01200900800024 H01200903300026 H01202000200014 H01301400100030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0409_wall.jpg|col||MM (Wikimedia Commons)|Fitted stones in wall|3.0\fig* A wall is the verticle surface that forms one side of a building or room. It supports the ceiling of a room or the roof of a building. We distinguish here between this kind of wall in a building and a city wall (see \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.1">3.13.3.1 City wall, rampart, battlement\l*) or a boundary wall (see \l target="REALIA:3.6">3.6 Boundary wall, fence\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i qir\i* can refer to both the outer wall and the inner wall of a structure. Where a language has distinct words for these different walls, the translator will need to pay close attention to the context. For example, \s H01100501300042\s* mentions “the hyssop that grows out of the wall” (\a RSV\a*). This “wall” is more likely an external wall rather than one inside a house.
\line In \s H00902502200042 H00902503400064 H01101401000028 H01101601100038 H01102102100030\s*; and\s H01200900800024\s* there is a Hebrew phrase that is literally “one who urinates against a wall.” This phrase refers to men, so most translations say “man/men” or “male[s].”
\line In \s H01000501100036\s* and \s H01301400100030\s* \a RSV\a* says that King Hiram of Tyre sent Solomon “masons,” which is literally “wall-stone workers/cutters” in Hebrew. These were men who shaped stones so they fit together neatly in a wall. \a GNT\a* says “stone masons,” and \a CEV\a* has “stone workers.”
\key 3.1.6.4
\title Upper room, roof chamber
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb עֲלִיָּה
\trl ‘aliyah
\ref H00700302000018 H00700302300020 H00700302400026 H00700302500022 H01001900100016 H01101701900032 H01101702300022 H01200100200016 H01200401000006 H01200401100024 H01202301200018 H01302801100034 H01400300900022 H01600303100042 H01600303200006 H01910400300012 H01910401300008 H02402201300016 H02402201400016
\arm עִלִּי
\trl ‘ili
\ref A02700601100034
\heb מַעֲלָה
\trl ma‘alah
\ref H03000900600012
\grk ἀνάγαιον
\trl anagaion
\ref G04101401500010 G04202201200008
\grk ὑπερῷον
\trl huperōion
\ref G04400101300012 G04400903700030 G04400903900022 G04402000800014 L06700301000030 L06700301700154
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0416_house_upperroom.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|House with an upper room|3.0\fig* The upper room was a room on the level above the ground floor (second story in American usage and first story in most other languages). This room generally would not cover an entire story but only part of the roof.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew phrase \i ‘aliyath mqerah\i* in \s H00700302000018\s* (also called \i cheder mqerah\i* in \s H00700302400050\s*) refers to a special upper room built for coolness. Its higher level exposed it to the breeze, and it was probably built facing north, where it would be less exposed to the sun.
\line \s H01100600601000 H01100600801000\s* mentions second and third stories (American usage) built around the outside of the Temple. \s H01100600801000\s* refers to the “entrance for the middle story” (\a NRSV\a*). \a HOTTP\a* makes the following comment on this: “These stories seem to have been \u open\u* arcades or galleries. Therefore it was necessary to speak, not about the entrance of the open ground-floor, but about the entrances of the first (or middle) and of the second (or highest) floor.” This comment is based on the reading of the Hebrew text, which states clearly that the entrance was to the middle story and that steps led to the middle story and from the middle story to the upper story. However, the Septuagint as well as an ancient Jewish Aramaic translation (Targum) understood the two appearances of the Hebrew adjective \i tikonah\i* (“middle”) at the end of verse 8 to refer to the middle floor, while the first appearance refers in fact to the lowest floor. Thus, for example, \a NJB\a* has “The entrance to the lowest storey was at the right-hand corner of the Temple; access to the middle storey was by a spiral staircase, and so from the middle storey to the third.”
\line \s H01910400300012 H01910401300008\s*: The Hebrew word \i ‘aliyoth\i* in these verses refers to God’s dwelling place. Many translations avoid a literal rendering. \a CEV\a* has “home” in both verses, while \a GNT\a* says “home” in verse 3 and “the sky” in verse 13. \a NJB\a* has “palace” and “halls” respectively.
\key 3.1.6.5
\title Third floor
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk τρίστεγον
\trl tristegon
\ref G04402000900050
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The third floor was the third story of a building, that is, the second floor above ground level, which is “second story” in British usage and “third story” in American usage.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Translators should be careful when expressing what happened to Eutychus in \s G04402000900050\s*. While some languages will designate the room from which he fell as the “second floor,” they may have to say that he fell “three floors.” When designating the location of the floor, it would be called the second, but the distance he fell includes also the ground floor, so he fell three floors.
\key 3.1.6.6
\title Inner room
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶדֶר
\trl cheder bcheder
\ref H01102003000058 H01102202500026 H01200900200044 H01401802400026
\heb חֶדֶר, פְּנִימִי
\trl cheder pnimi
\ref H01302801100038
\grk μυχός
\trl muchos
\ref L07001700400012
\grk ταμεῖον
\trl tameion
\ref G04000600600016 G04002402600030 G04201200300040
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The inner room was a room in the interior of a house, normally without windows opening to the outside.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s G04201200300040\s* the emphasis is upon the strictly private location of the inner room. In such a context translators may say “a strictly private room” or “a small room in the center of the house.”
\key 3.1.6.7
\title Bedroom
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶדֶר, מִטָּה
\trl cheder mitah
\ref H01201100200062 H01402201100056
\heb חֶדֶר, מִשְׁכָּב
\trl cheder mishkav
\ref H00200702800028 H01000400700022 H01200601200054 H02101002000018
\grk κοιτών
\trl koitōn
\ref G04401202000036 L06801300300020 L06801300400022 L06801401500018 L06801601900042 L08100300300032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The bedroom was a room in a dwelling used primarily for sleeping.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s G04401202000036\s*: In this verse Blastus is referred to literally as “the one over the bedroom of the king.” The emphasis here is not on the use of a bedroom but on the position of Blastus, who was a highly respected person with considerable responsibility for the king’s living quarters and personal affairs. So Blastus may be spoken of as “a high official of the king.”
\line Every occurrence of the Greek word \i koitōn\i* in Judith refers to a bedroom in a tent, not in a permanent building. Where a language has a specific word for such a compartment in a tent, this word should be used here.
\key 3.1.6.8
\title Bridal chamber (marriage bed)
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶדֶר
\trl cheder
\ref H00701500100046 H02900201600030
\heb חֻפָּה
\trl chupah
\ref H01901900600014 H02900201600038
\grk νυμφών
\trl numfōn
\ref L06700601400038 L06700601700012
\grk παστός
\trl pastos
\ref L07700102700016 L07900101900020 L07900400600018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The bridal chamber was the room to which a newly married couple retired together immediately after the wedding.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s L07700102700016\s* the Greek word \i pastos\i* has more than one possible meaning. In addition to the definition given above, it can also indicate the bed on which the marriage is physically consummated. So \a NJB\a* says “marriage-bed.”
\key 3.1.6.9
\title Guest room
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk κατάλυμα
\trl kataluma
\ref G04101401400030 G04202201100028
\grk ξενία
\trl xenia
\ref G04402802300020 G05700102200012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The guest room was a place of temporary lodging for a person away from home, usually in the home of another.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s G04101401400030\s* and \s G04202201100028\s* the Greek word \i kataluma\i* refers to a large room that could serve as a dining room. Many translations have “guest room” (\a RSV\a*, \a NCV\a*). Others have simply “room” (\a GNT\a*) or “place.” It is also possible simply to place Jesus’ question at the end of these verses by saying “Where is it that I am to eat the Passover meal with my disciples?” or “Where am I to eat . . . ?” The next verse after each of these verses provides a description of the room.
\line It is also possible that the Greek word \i xenia\i* in both New Testament passages is an abstract noun that refers to hospitality or the activity involved in receiving a guest. This is the more common meaning of \i xenia\i*, but it fits less well in the two contexts in which it occurs.
\key 3.1.7
\title Stairs, steps
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לוּל
\trl lul
\ref H01100600800028
\heb מַעֲלָה, מַעֲלֶה
\trl ma‘alah, ma‘aleh
\ref H00202002600010 H01101001900004 H01101002000020 H01200901300026 H01202000900046 H01202000900054 H01202001000022 H01202001000038 H01202001100030 H01202001100038 H01202001100046 H01400901800006 H01400901900020 H01600301500078 H01600900400008 H01601203700020 H01601203700030 H01912000100006 H01912100100008 H01912200100006 H01912300100006 H01912400100006 H01912500100006 H01912600100006 H01912700100006 H01912800100006 H01912900100006 H01913000100006 H01913100100006 H01913200100006 H01913300100006 H01913400100006 H02303800800012 H02303800800020 H02303800800034 H02303800800046 H02303800800052 H02604000600026 H02604002200048 H02604002600004 H02604003100030 H02604003100034 H02604003400044 H02604003400046 H02604003700044 H02604003700046 H02604004900028 H02604301700058
\heb סֻלָּם
\trl sulam
\ref H00102801200010
\grk ἀναβαθμός
\trl anabathmos
\ref G04402103500012 G04402104000018
\grk κρηπίς
\trl krēpis
\ref L07801002600012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0063_steps.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Steps|3.0\fig* Steps were a series of levels by which a person could ascend or descend by foot. They connected one story of a building to another or one level of ground to another. They could be laid down as blocks of stone or cut into the earth or bedrock.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00102801200010\s*: The Hebrew word \i sulam\i* occurs only here in the Bible. It indicates a kind of stairway or ramp made of stones piled up. In older translations it was mistakenly rendered “ladder” (so \a RSV\a*). Some scholars see here a reference to a kind of ziggurat (see \l target="REALIA:3.14.3">3.14.3 Tower, ziggurat\l*). In a footnote \a TOB\a* gives “ramp, slope” as a possible alternative and suggests that the object intended is similar to the steps ascending a ziggurat. Translators should employ a word for an object on which many people can ascend and descend together at the same time.
\line \s H01100600800028\s*: The Hebrew word \i lulim\i* refers to stairs that go up in a spiral. Some languages will make a distinction between a straight stairway and a spiral staircase; for example, \a REB\a* has “spiral stairway,” and \a NRSV\a* has changed \a RSV\a* “stairs” to “winding stairs.” Most translations consulted, however, do not indicate the spiral form of the steps.
\line The Hebrew word \i ma‘alah\i* is used in \s H01101001900004 H01101002000020\s* and \s H01400901800006 H01400901900020\s* for the steps leading up to Solomon’s elevated throne (see also \l target="REALIA:1.10.1">1.10.1 Throne\l*).
\line \s H01600900400008\s*: Some translations believe the Hebrew word \i ma‘aleh\i* in this context refers to the “wooden platform” in \s H01600800400014\s*, which had been built specially for addressing the people (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a NASB\a*). Others (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*) render it “stairs,” possibly understanding it as a flight of steps leading from one courtyard of the Temple to another. In the rebuilt Temple of Herod, it is known that there was such a flight of steps on which the Levites stood and sang. The important point is that they were standing in an elevated position where they could be seen and heard by the people. \i A Handbook on Psalms\i* (page 1047) says the following about the titles of \s H01912000100002\s* - \s H01913400100002\s*: “Psalms 120–134 all have a title in the Hebrew text which is translated by \a RSV\a* as \b A Song of Ascents\b* (\a TEV\a* [that is, \a GNT\a*] does not include this title). The collection is also called ‘The Book of Pilgrim Songs.’ The Hebrew word translated \b Ascents\b* comes from the verb ‘to go up,’ but other than this there is no agreement as to what the phrase means. Some take it to indicate the return of the Hebrew exiles from Babylonia; others take it to refer to a stylistic feature found in some of the psalms, in which the order of the statement progresses in a step-like fashion from one verse to the other; others take it to refer to the steps in the Temple precincts which led from one court to the other; the majority take it to refer to the ascent up the mountain on which the Temple was built (Mount Moriah, known as Mount Zion). Thus understood, these psalms are songs which the pilgrims sang as they came to Jerusalem for one of the three major annual festivals (see \a GECL\a*).”
\line The Greek word \i krēpis\i*, which appears in \s L07801002600012\s*, is literally the “foundation,” “base,” or even “foot” or “edge” of a structure. It is used to refer to the bank of a river as well as the tiers of seats in an amphitheater. Perhaps for this reason, \a RSV\a* and \a GNT\a* render it “steps” in this verse, saying “the steps of/before the altar.” Similarly, \a NJB\a* has “the terrace before the altar.” \a NAB\a* has a good idiom, “the foot of the altar,” which may work also in other languages. It is also possible to translate more generally “in front of the altar.”
\key 3.2
\title Tent
\index \l target="REALIA:3.2.1">3.2.1 Door of tent, dividing curtain\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.2.2">3.2.2 Tent peg, stake\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אהל
\trl ’ahal (verb)
\ref H00101301200028 H00101301800004 H02301302000028
\heb אֹהֶל
\trl ’ohel
\ref H00100402000020 H00100902100024 H00100902700016 H00101200800026 H00101300300032 H00101300500028 H00101800100026 H00101800200042 H00101800600010 H00101800900024 H00101801000042 H00102406700010 H00102502700036 H00102602500026 H00103102500020 H00103103300010 H00103103300018 H00103103300026 H00103103300046 H00103103300056 H00103103400044 H00103301900020 H00103502100012 H00201800700044 H00301400800060 H00401101000026 H00401602600024 H00401602700038 H00401901400016 H00401901400028 H00401901400040 H00401901800030 H00402400500006 H00500102700008 H00500503000014 H00501100600052 H00501600700042 H00600301400016 H00600702100072 H00600702200016 H00600702200026 H00600702300012 H00600702400076 H00700401100030 H00700401700014 H00700401800040 H00700402000014 H00700402100018 H00700502400026 H00700600500014 H00700701300060 H00700701300084 H00700801100018 H00901705400032 H01000601700028 H01000700600050 H01001602200012 H01100103900024 H01200700700022 H01200700800028 H01200700800076 H01200701000072 H01300404100032 H01300501000034 H01301500100036 H01301600100026 H01301700500042 H01301700500046 H01400100400034 H01401401400006 H01906902600010 H01910602500008 H01911801500012 H02200100500016 H02303801200014 H02304002200042 H02305400200006 H02400600300016 H02401002000002 H02401002000028 H02403500700038 H02403501000010 H02403701000034 H02404902900002 H02500200400030 H02701104500006 H02801201000022 H03500300700008
\heb מִשְׁכָּן
\trl mishkan
\ref H00402400500010 H01907802800016 H02200100800042 H02305400200012 H02403001800020 H02602500400032
\heb סֻכָּה
\trl sukah
\ref H01001101100030 H01102001200038 H01102001600024
\heb קֻבָּה
\trl qubah
\ref H00402500800016
\grk αὐλή
\trl aulē
\ref L07801301500036
\grk προσκήνιον
\trl proskēnion
\ref L06801002200020
\grk σκηνή
\trl skēnē
\ref G05801100900020 L06800300300048 L06800502200036 L06800601000024
\grk σκῆνος
\trl skēnos
\ref G04700500100020 G04700500400014 L07000901500020
\grk σκήνωμα
\trl skēnōma
\ref G06100101300020 G06100101400016 L06800202600020 L06800900800058 L06801001800024 L06801400700040 L06801500100014 L07700906600028 L07801000600014 L08100104800038 L08500400700014
\grk σκηνοποιός
\trl skēnopoios (“tentmaker”)
\ref G04401800300026
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0410_tent.jpg|col||© yeowatzup (Wikimedia Commons)|Tent|3.0\fig* The tent was a portable dwelling of cloth and/or skins, held up by poles and secured to the ground by cords tied to stakes. Tents were normally made of cloth woven from the hair of goats.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Tents served as the regular dwelling of nomadic peoples. They could also be used as temporary shelter by soldiers in the field or perhaps by people moving from one permanent house to another.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages “tent” is rendered “house made of cloth.” Translators should avoid terms that would imply a temporary shelter used only on vacations or holidays. In Old Testament times such tents were permanent dwellings of nomadic groups and were moved from place to place as livestock were transferred from one pasture area to another. \fig |UBS-0017_tent_nomad.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Nomad's tent|3.0\fig*
\line The Hebrew verb \i ’ahal\i* means “to pitch a tent” (\a NIV\a*), “to move a tent” (\a RSV\a*, \a NASB\a*), “to encamp, camp, set up camp” (\a GNT\a*, \a TOB\a*).
\line The word \i ’ohel\i* serves in Hebrew to describe both dwellings used by nomads and tents used by soldiers on military campaigns (see also \l target="REALIA:3.15">3.15 Tent of Meeting and Tabernacle\l*). Where a language distinguishes between the two, the context should be checked carefully. The following passages seem to refer to military tents: \s H00700701300060 H00901705400032 H01200700700022 H01200700800028 H01200700901000 H01200701001000\s*. It has also been suggested that, in \s G04401800300026\s* Paul, Aquila and Priscilla made tents for military use, although the Greek word traditionally translated “tentmaker” more properly means “leather worker.”
\line It should be kept in mind that in Israel’s earlier history, many people lived in tents. The phrase “went to his tent” or “fled to their tents” often means simply “went home”; for example, \s H01201401201000\s* is literally “every man fled to his tent,” but, because the context tells us that they lived in houses, \a RSV\a* says “every man fled to his home.”
\line The Hebrew word \i mishkan\i* means “dwelling place” and is used most often for the Tabernacle in the wilderness (see \l target="REALIA:3.15.2">3.15.2 Tabernacle\l*). In the passages listed above it refers specifically to a tent for people to live in (either as nomads or as soldiers). In \s H00402400500010 H02305400200012\s*; and \s H02403001800020\s* \i mishkan\i* appears in poetic parallelism with a word for “tent.” In these places it will be best to use a general word meaning “dwelling place,” “residence.”
\line The meaning of the Hebrew word \i qubah\i* in \s H00402500800016\s* is uncertain. Many translations understand it to be a tent, perhaps with a high dome (\a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a KJV\a*, \a NASB\a*), while others take it to be a partition or room in a tent (\a RSV\a*, \a NEB\a*). Some translations (\a TOB\a*, \a SPCL\a*) believe it is a bedroom, but they give a footnote describing it to be a special tent dedicated to pagan religious rites, such as prostitution or divination. There seems no way to be certain which understanding is correct, so the translator will just need to choose one of them.
\line \s L07801301500036\s*: Originally the Greek word \i aulē\i* referred to a courtyard and later to the court of a king. The context of this verse speaks of the part of the encampment where the king was located, so \a GNT\a* says “the area near the king’s tent.” Most others have “the king’s pavilion” (\a RSV\a*). At best the word “pavilion” will be obscure; at worst (in British English, for example) it could be misunderstood. Translators should follow \a GNT\a* or say something like “the camp where Antiochus’ headquarters were located” (\a ITCL\a*).
\line The Greek word \i proskēnion\i* in \s L06801002200020\s* refers to an area just inside the entrance to a tent. \a GNT\a* renders it “outer part of the tent,” \a NJB\a* has “entrance to the tent,” and \a NAB\a* says “antechamber.”
\key 3.2.1
\title Door of tent, dividing curtain
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb דֹּק
\trl doq
\ref H02304002200030
\heb יְרִיעָה
\trl yri‘ah
\ref H01910400200020 H02200100500022 H02305400200010 H02400402000028 H02401002000034 H02404902900010 H03500300700014
\grk αὐλαία
\trl aulaia
\ref L06801401400014
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Curtains divided different parts of a large tent.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i yri‘ah\i* is first used for the cloth strips that covered the Tabernacle (see \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6.1">3.15.2.3.6.1 Linen cloth strips\l*). In most of the passages listed above this word appears in parallelism with a word meaning “tent,” and for that reason it sometimes seems to be a metonym for tent (compare “the ark of God dwells in the \i yri‘ah\i*” in \s H01000700200048\s* with “the ark of the covenant of the LORD is under a \i yri‘ah\i*” in \s H01301700100056\s*). In \s H01910400200020\s* the visual imagery “stretched out the heavens like a \i yri‘ah\i*” comes from the curtains in the Tabernacle stretched out above the ark.
\line \s L06801401400014\s* says “Bagoas went in and knocked at the door of the tent” (\a RSV\a*). This will sound as strange in some languages as it does in English. \a NAB\a* and \a NRSV\a* try to solve the problem by changing “door” (\i aulaia\i* in Greek) to “entry.” \a GNT\a* goes even farther by rendering “Bagoas went in and clapped his hands in front of the sleeping quarters of the tent.” \a NJB\a* is closer to the literal meaning of \i aulaia\i*, saying “Bagoas went inside and struck the curtain dividing the tent.” The point of the story is that Bagoas thought Holofernes was in bed with Judith and made noise so as not to surprise them in an indecent position.
\key 3.2.2
\title Tent peg, stake
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יָתֵד
\trl yathed
\ref H00202701900022 H00202701900028 H00203501800004 H00203501800014 H00203802000008 H00203803100032 H00203803100044 H00203904000042 H00400303700018 H00400403200018 H00700402100014 H00700402100054 H00700402200068 H00700502600008 H01500900800040 H02303302000030 H02305400200026 H03801000400008
\grk πάσσαλος
\trl passalos
\ref L07101402400018 L07102601200032 L07102700200012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0411_loop_in_rope_en.jpg|col||Source unknown|Peg and rope|3.0\fig* The tent peg was a shortened stick, pointed on one end. It was driven into the ground, and tent ropes were tied to it to anchor the tent in place. See the illustrations at \l target="REALIA:3.2">3.2 Tent\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The stakes of the Tabernacle, mentioned in Exodus and Numbers, were made of bronze. They were used to anchor the various coverings of the Tabernacle (see \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6">3.15.2.3.6 Coverings\l*) and also some of the standing posts (see \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.3">3.15.2.3.3 Upright beam, tenon, crosspiece, rung\l*).
\line The tent stake provided security. It guaranteed that the tent would not fall nor be blown out of its place by winds. Thus it is sometimes a symbol of stability and security. This element of security may be reflected in translation in \s H01500900800040\s* and \s H02303302000030\s*; for example, in \s H01500900800040\s* the literal clause “to give us a tent peg within the place of his holiness” is rendered by \a RSV\a* as “to give us a secure hold within his holy place,” and \a GNT\a* has “live in safety in this holy place.”
\line \fig |WEB-0412_tent_pegs_en.jpg|col||Don Ellens, The Tabernacle of Israel, 1888|Tent pegs|3.0\fig* or another sense of the Hebrew word \i yathed\i* in \s H00701601400010\s*, see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.5">1.5.3.5 Beater, batten, pin\l*.
\line \s L07101402400018\s*: The Greek word \i passalos\i* refers to a tent peg. The Hebrew version of Sirach has a word that, with a very slight emendation of part of one letter, could mean “tent cords” or “tent pegs.” With either reading, the basic meaning remains the same and is expressed well by \a GNT\a*: “Camp as close to her house as you can get.” If translators wish to maintain the image of the tent and the house, they may say “he attaches his tent to the wall of her house.”
\key 3.3
\title Inn
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מָלוֹן, ארח
\trl malon ’orchim
\ref H02400900100012
\grk κατάλυμα
\trl kataluma
\ref G04200200700046 L07101402500022 L07700304500054 L08500101300032
\grk πανδοχεῖον
\trl pandocheion
\ref G04201003400042
\grk πανδοχεύς
\trl pandocheus (“innkeeper”)
\ref G04201003500020
\grk ταβέρνη
\trl tabernē
\ref G04402801500034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The inn was a place for the lodging of travelers. Meals were also served. Unlike some modern bars and hotels, it did not have particular associations with alcohol or prostitution.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages it may be necessary to describe the role of an inn as “a place where people could stay overnight and get something to eat” or even “a place where people could pay in order to stay overnight and get something to eat.” Compare \a NCV\a*’s rendering of inn in \s H02400900100012\s*, where it has “a house where travelers spend the night.” It is highly likely this is the only place in the Old Testament where the Hebrew word \i malon\i* refers to an actual inn or permanent structure for the lodging of travelers.
\key 3.4
\title Palace
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַרְמוֹן
\trl ’armon
\ref H01101601800026 H01201502500026 H01403601900028
\heb בִּירָה
\trl birah
\ref H01302900100056 H01302901900046
\heb בַּיִת
\trl bayith
\ref H00101201500030 H00101201700020 H00104104000008 H00104500200024 H00104500800044 H00104501600010 H00104701400058 H00105000400018
\heb בַּיִת מֶלֶךְ
\trl beyth (ha)melek
\ref H01001100200034 H01001100800032 H01001100900010 H01001503500038 H01100900100026 H01100901000038 H01101001200030 H01101402600020 H01101402700038 H01101501800040 H01101601800028 H01101601800042 H01201100500038 H01201101600022 H01201101900070 H01201102000036 H01201201900070 H01201401400044 H01201502500028 H01201600800036 H01201801500030 H01202401300024 H01202500900016 H01400701100018 H01400801100046 H01400901100030 H01401201000038 H01401600200024 H01402101700032 H01402300500010 H01402301500024 H01402302000078 H01402502400048 H01402802100018 H01600302500028 H01700200800052 H01700200900066 H01700201300048 H01700401300028 H01700500100032 H01700500100044 H01700600400028 H01700900400010 H02401901300012 H02402101100006 H02402200100010 H02402601000026 H02402701800054 H02402702100032 H02403200200040 H02403300400030 H02403601200006 H02403800700022 H02403800800010 H02403801100022 H02403802200018 H02403900800006 H02405201300016
\heb בִּיתָן
\trl bithan
\ref H01700100500066 H01700700700028 H01700700800016
\heb הֵיכָל
\trl heykal
\ref H01102100100036 H01202001800030 H01403600700026 H01904500900016 H01904501600016 H01914401200026 H02003002800016 H02301302200018 H02303900700028 H02700100400058 A02700400100020 A02700402600014 H02900400500024
\arm הֵיכַל
\trl heykal
\ref A01500401400014 A02700400100020 A02700402600014 A02700500500036 A02700601900010
\grk αὐλή
\trl aulē
\ref L07701104600014
\grk βασιλεία, βασίλειον, βασίλειος
\trl basileia, basileion, basileios
\ref G04200702500040 L07300105800082 L07700201000010
\grk οἶκος, βασιλεία, βασιλεύς
\trl oiko (basileias), oikos (basileōs)
\ref G04001100800032 L06800200100032 L06800201800024 L06801102300062 L06801201300104 L06801401800024 L07700700200012
\grk πραιτώριον
\trl praitōrion
\ref G04002702700022 G04101501600022 G04301802800020 G04301802800040 G04301803300012 G04301900900010 G04402303500026 G05000101300024
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0064_palace_model_nt.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Model of a palace in New Testament times|3.0\fig* The palace was the dwelling of a king or ruler. Such a dwelling was usually larger and more elaborate than the dwelling of an average person. Its structure and building materials varied widely.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Palace” may be rendered “home of a king” or “home of a ruler.”
\line The Hebrew word \i ’armon\i* sometimes indicates the fortified part of a king’s residence or other fortified dwellings; see \s H01101601800026\s*. In such cases it will be better to render it as “citadel” or “stronghold.” See also \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.2">3.13.3.2 Fortress, stronghold, castle, citadel, fort\l*.
\line \s H01904500900016\s*: “Ivory palaces” (\a RSV\a*; see also \s H01102203900020\s*) are not palaces built completely of ivory, but palaces decorated with ivory, either on the building itself or on its furniture (see \s H01101001800010\s*; \s H03000301500028\s*; \s H03000600400010\s*).
\line \s H01914401200026\s*: The Hebrew word \i heykal\i* can also mean “temple.” It is almost always clear which meaning is intended, either from the context or from some modifier such as “of the LORD” or “of the king.” However, the meaning in this verse is in doubt; some translations have “palace” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*) while others have “temple” (\a NAB\a*, \a NCV\a*).
\line There are differences of opinion concerning what building in Jerusalem is indicated by the Greek word \i praitōrion\i* in the Gospels. It may have been either the palace of Herod in the western part of the city or the fortress Antonia northwest of the Temple area. The \i praitōrion\i* in Caesarea (\s G04402303500026\s*) was the palace built by Herod the Great. In the Gospels it is satisfactory to translate \i praitōrion\i* as “palace where the governor lived” or “large dwelling where the ruler lived.” In some languages the term for “palace” may suggest a military fortification, and this would be quite appropriate for these New Testament passages.
\key 3.5
\title Column, pillar, capital
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Column\b*:
\heb דְּבִיר
\trl dvir
\ref H01400301600012
\heb זָוִית
\trl zawith
\ref H01914401200020
\heb מִסְעָד
\trl mis‘ad
\ref H01101001200018
\heb מָצוּק
\trl matsuq
\ref H00900200800040
\heb עַמּוּד
\trl ‘amud
