\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0413_column.jpg|col||© Sailko (Wikimedia Commons)|Columns with capitals supporting roof|3.0\fig* The column was an upright shaft or structure used as a building support. It was usually made of stone, sometimes of wood. It was sometimes made of three parts. The central body of the column (often cylindrical and, for large columns, itself made of several pieces) stood on a base that was somewhat broader than the width of the column. On top of the column was sometimes placed a wider top, the capital. The size of the column and its parts varied widely according to the dimensions of the building or room in which they were found. See also \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.2">3.14.1.2 Colonnade, porch, covered walkway, stoa, portico\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The column served to support the weight of a roof and anything built on the roof. The capital expanded the support area on the top of the column and also added an element of decoration. \fig |WEB-0414_columns.jpg|col||© James Gordon from Los Angeles, California, USA (Wikimedia Commons)|Columns|3.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages “pillars” may be rendered “poles that support the house” or “standing logs that hold up the roof.” Usually, however, there are rather specific terms to designate these important parts in the construction of houses or halls. \a GNT\a* avoids the technical term “capitals” and has “tops of the . . . columns” (\s H03000900100024\s*).
\line The Hebrew word \i matsuq\i*, by its etymology, refers to a pillar that has been formed by pouring molten metal. There will normally be no need to express this in translation. This word is used as a metaphor in \s H00900200800040\s* for God establishing the earth. Several translations choose to replace the “column” or “pillar” metaphor with “foundations” (for example, \a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a REB\a*, \a NCV\a*).
\line \s H00701602900012\s*: It is most likely that the columns which Samson pushed were made of wood, essentially large logs.
\line \s H01100701500012 H01100701600020 H01100701700028 H01100701800010 H01100701900014 H01100702000012 H01100702100010 H01100702200010\s*: Particular difficulties are presented by the description of the two special bronze columns placed by Solomon on either side of the entrance to the Temple. These columns were even given names.
\line While \s H01100701500012\s* describes the two columns, the Hebrew text makes use of a typical figure of speech, ellipsis: when speaking of the \i first\i* column and its \i height\i*, it is understood that the same applies to the \i second\i* column too; when speaking, then, of the \i second\i* column and its \i circumference\i*, it is understood again that the same applies to the \i first\i* column also. A translation should not try to retain this rather confusing device. While it is possible to describe the dimensions of one of the columns and then add that the second column was the same (so \a RSV\a*, \a REB\a*), it is better to give a combined description of the two. \a NCV\a* has “He made two bronze pillars, each one twenty-seven feet tall and eighteen feet around.” \a CEV\a* tries to make the picture even clearer by changing the circumference to an easier-to-visualize diameter: “Hiram made two bronze columns twenty-seven feet tall and about six feet across.” \a NIV\a*’s footnote gives the metric equivalents of the height and circumference: about 8.1 meters high and about 5.4 meters around.
\line There is an unclear text at \s H01100701700028\s*, which describes the design of the capitals on these columns, and \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a* both indicate the difficulty in a footnote. Nevertheless, the translator must supply a rendering that makes sense. Thus it is inadequate to provide a literal but unintelligible translation like that of \a NASB\a*: “There were nets of network and twisted threads of chainwork for the capitals which were on top of the pillars; seven for the one capital and seven for the other capital.” It should be kept in mind that this is a description of a decorative design that somehow incorporated a network (or “mesh/lattice-work”) in which chains could be found. This should be conveyed to the reader in a description that is as simple as possible. Good examples are \a GNT\a* “The top of each column was decorated with a design of interwoven chains,” and \a CEV\a* “The caps [capitals] were decorated with seven rows of designs that looked like chains.” The same idea is probably reflected in the parallel text at \s H01400301600012\s*, where the Hebrew word \i dvir\i* (normally referring to the Holy of Holies) is thought to be a transposition of the Hebrew letters from the word \i ravid\i*, which means a kind of chain or necklace. For the first half of this verse \a RSV\a* has “He made chains like a necklace and put them on the tops of the pillars.”
\line \s H01100701900014\s* speaks of capitals in the shape of “lilies” (\i shushan\i* in Hebrew). It is impossible to know what their exact shape was. While the word \i shushan\i* is usually translated “lily,” it probably served to designate several kinds of flower. So the Jerusalem Bible (\a JB\a*) renders it “flower-shaped,” which, however, could be misleading in some contexts. Where lilies are not known, translators should choose a local flower with a head shaped like a cup.
\line As part of the description of the two bronze columns, \s H01100702000012\s* uses the Hebrew word \i beten\i*, which literally means “belly.” This is understood by most translations to be a kind of projection protruding all around the top of each column. \a REB\a* uses the technical architectural term “cushion,” which will be inappropriate for a common-language translation. Other renderings are “bowl-shaped part/section” (\a NIV\a*/\a NCV\a*) and “rounded section/tops” (\a GNT\a*/\a CEV\a*).
\line \s H01803800600006\s*: The Hebrew word \i ’adanim\i* is used here in a manner similar to the use of \i matsuq\i* in \s H00900200800040\s*, discussed above. The writer of Job thought of the earth as a building set on pillars. These pillars in turn rested on bases. The reference is to the “bases” (\a RSV\a*) or “footings” on which the pillars rest. \a NEB\a* translates the first line of this verse clearly, saying “On what do its supporting pillars rest?” This line may require more information to make it clear, for example, “On what do the bases rest that hold up the pillars of the earth?” or “What is beneath the footings that support the pillars holding up the earth?”
\line All the New Testament references to “pillar” are figurative. Some translations prefer to express the meaning rather than retain the pillar figure; for example, in \s G04800200900030\s*, where “pillars” refers to the leaders in the church, \a CEV\a* has “the backbone of the church,” while \a NCV\a* says “the leaders.”
\key 3.6
\title Boundary wall, fence
