\grk φραγμός
\trl fragmos
\ref G04002103300022 G04101200100024 G04201402300026 G04900201400032 L07103602500008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0415_fence.jpg|col||© بدارين (Wikimedia Commons)|Stone fences|3.0\fig* The fence was a structure for enclosing an area. Fences in the land of Israel were most often made of stone, less often (and only as a temporary structure) of sticks and brush.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In many societies there is some type of fence, wall, or barrier employed to surround fields. In some instances the fence may consist of piled up logs or sticks; in other instances it may be made of packed dirt or of laid-up stone. What is important, however, is not the form of the “fence,” but its function, and therefore translators may often use a descriptive expression, for example, “barrier to surround a field” or “barrier to keep animals out of the field.” Because stone was such a common material in the land of Israel, fences were usually made of loose stones. In many cultures such stone structures are called “walls,” not “fences.”
\line The Hebrew word \i gvul\i*, which normally means “boundary” (see \l target="REALIA:3.7">3.7 Boundary marker\l*), is used in several places in Ezekiel with a somewhat different meaning. In \s H02604001200004\s* it seems to refer to a “low wall” (\a GNT\a*), “railing” (\a CEV\a*), or simply “barrier[s]” (\a RSV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*). In \s H02604301300042 H02604301700032 H02604302000038\s* the word describes a kind of “rim” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*) around the base and different levels of the altar.
\line Some languages distinguish between the outer wall of a building and the inner walls that separate rooms. The Hebrew word \i chomah\i* normally indicates an outer wall, specifically of a city (see \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.1">3.13.3.1 City wall, rampart, battlement\l*). The references listed above are exceptional. The other Hebrew words can be used for both inner and outer walls, and the translator must decide the correct meaning from the context. The Greek word \i toichos\i* refers to an inner wall. In translation the outer wall of a house may be called “side of a house,” and an inner wall may be referred to as “partition in a house.”
\line \s H02601301000034\s*: In this verse the Hebrew word \i chayits\i* indicates a “divider,” a wall that is temporary and not very substantial. Translations attempt to indicate this by the addition of a modifier, such as “shaky” (\a CEV\a*), “flimsy” (\a NIV\a*, Living Bible [\a LB\a*]), “weak” (\a NCV\a*), “unstable” (\a SPCL\a*), or “of loose stones” (\a GNT\a*, \a GECL\a*).
\line The Hebrew words \i shur\i* and \i shurah\i* have been understood in various ways. They literally mean “row.” This could mean a row of stones, so a wall or a fence. In \s H00104902200022\s* most translations have “wall” (\a RSV\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a FRCL\a*). However, in \s H01802401100004\s* \a RSV\a* renders \i shurah\i* as “olive rows.” As pointed out by \i A Handbook on The Book of Job\i*, this not likely to be the meaning of the text. Olive trees in the Middle East are very often grown on specially prepared terraces. The terraces themselves are supported by retaining walls, which could be the meaning of \i shurah\i* here. \a NRSV\a* has abandoned the \a RSV\a* rendering with “terraces” (also \a NIV\a*). \a GECL\a* says “garden,” and \a NASB\a* has “walls.” \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a* choose not to translate the word.
\line In \s G04900201400028\s* the Greek words \i mesotoichon\i* and \i fragmos\i* are used figuratively of the Law, which constituted a barrier between Jews and Gentiles, “the wall of separation” (\a RSV\a*). Here these words may be rendered “the wall to keep apart” or “the wall to divide.”
\key 3.7
\title Boundary marker
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גְּבוּל, גְּבוּלָה
\trl gvul, gvulah
\ref H00501901400006 H00502701700006 H01802400200002 H02002202800006 H02002301000006 H02800501000012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0416_boundary_marker.jpg|col||© Oren Rozen (Wikimedia Commons)|Stone boundary marker|3.0\fig* Boundary markers were stones placed at the edges of property to show where one man’s field ended and another man’s field began. They could take several forms. One form was a single large stone inscribed with some appropriate formula; another form was simply a pile of flat stones.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew phrase \i hisig gvul\i*/\i gvulah\i* occurs in all the references listed above. It means literally “push back the border.” By moving the landmark, a person could increase his holdings at the expense of his neighbor. In \s H01802400200002\s* \a GNT\a* makes the purpose of moving the landmarks clear: “to get more land.” Where such landmarks used to signify land ownership are unknown, the first line of this verse will require some adjustments, for example, “Men take land that is not theirs,” “People farm without permission on other people’s land,” “People farm other people’s land and the owners don’t know it,” “People grow their crops on other people’s land,” or “People steal their neighbors’ farm lands.” These models may be useful in translating the other references too.
\key 3.8
\title Well
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בְּאֵר
\trl b’er
\ref H00101401000010 H00101401000012 H00101601400012 H00102101900016 H00102102500016 H00102103000040 H00102401100022 H00102402000028 H00102601500008 H00102601800014 H00102601900022 H00102602000034 H00102602100006 H00102602200014 H00102602500038 H00102603200036 H00102900200010 H00102900200040 H00102900200066 H00102900300032 H00102900300060 H00102900800040 H00102901000062 H00200201500060 H00402001700032 H00402101600008 H00402101600014 H00402101700020 H00402101800002 H00402102200028 H00700902100016 H01001701800044 H01001701900026 H01001702100018 H01905502400012 H01906901600026 H02000501500018 H02002302700012 H02200401500006
\heb בֹּאר
\trl bo’r
\ref H01002301500020
\heb בּוֹר
\trl bor
\ref H00500601100020 H00901902200020 H01000302600032 H01301101700024 H01301101800024
\heb בַּיִר
\trl bayir
\ref H02400600700006
\grk πηγή
\trl pēgē
\ref G04300400600008 G04300400600036 G04300401400054
\grk φρέαρ
\trl frear
\ref G04201400500022 G04300401100022 G04300401200026
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0134_water_drawing.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Women drawing water from a well|3.0\fig* The well was a deep construction, often walled with stone, at the bottom of which was a pool of water. Wells were dug as deep as was necessary to reach usable water, sometimes more than 50 meters (165 feet) deep. For the difference between a well and a cistern, see \l target="REALIA:3.9">3.9 Cistern\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Wells varied widely in construction, depending on the topography. In some cases a “well” was little more than a walled-in spring, and in fact the Greek word \i pēgē\i* may indicate either a well or a spring, although most often it indicates a natural water source rather than a man-made one. In \s G04300400000000\s* \i pēgē\i* is used interchangeably with \i frear\i*, a word that refers to something dug or carved from rock. At \s G04300401400054\s* most translations render \i pēgē\i* as “spring,” although \a KJV\a* and \a NASB\a* have “well.” Most translations render \i pēgē\i* as “well” in verse 6 and as “spring” in verse 14. \i A Handbook on The Gospel of John\i* (page 111) offers a suggestion of how both are possible in a single context.
\line The Hebrew words given above all indicate holes that have been dug. Hebrew uses separate words for natural springs, which, of course, were not made by people. Because the Greek word \i frear\i* indicates a hole that has been dug or carved out, it is not always possible to tell whether it indicates a cistern or a well.
\line \s H02000501500018\s*: The context of this verse indicates that the words “well” and “cistern” are used figuratively of a man’s wife. So \a GNT\a* translates “Be faithful to your own wife and give your love to her alone.” \a CEV\a* preserves the imagery by saying “You should be faithful to your wife, just as you take water from your own well” (similarly \a NCV\a*). Compare also \a FRCL\a*: “Your wife is like a spring of pure water. Drink from that source!” (similarly \a ITCL\a*).
\line \s G04201400500022\s*: Any common term for “well,” “pond,” “fountain,” or “cistern” is acceptable here, provided that falling into it implies the danger of drowning.
\key 3.9
\title Cistern
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בֹּאר
\trl bo’r
\ref H01002302000064 H02400201300028 H02400201300030
\heb בּוֹר
\trl bor
\ref H00103702000022 H00103702200024 H00103702400014 H00103702400020 H00103702800028 H00103702900012 H00103702900026 H00104001500038 H00104101400024 H00201202900060 H00202103300010 H00202103300020 H00202103400006 H00301103600008 H00500601100020 H00901300600068 H00901902200020 H01002301500020 H01002301600026 H01002302000064 H01201001400022 H01201803100054 H01301101700024 H01301101800024 H01301102200056 H01402601000018 H01600902500028 H01900701600002 H01902800100034 H01903000400022 H01904000300008 H01908800500008 H01908800700006 H01914300700028 H02000101200018 H02000501500008 H02002801700014 H02101200600052 H02301401500014 H02301401900032 H02302402200012 H02303601600056 H02303801800020 H02305100100028 H02400201300028 H02400201300030 H02400600700006 H02403701600014 H02403800600020 H02403800600058 H02403800700040 H02403800900044 H02403801000052 H02403801100068 H02403801300024 H02404100700034 H02404100900006 H02500305300008 H02500305500010 H02602602000010 H02602602000040 H02603101400084 H02603101600024 H02603201800038 H02603202300012 H02603202400064 H02603202500054 H02603202900042 H02603203000056 H03800901100018
\heb גֵּב
\trl gev
\ref H02401400300022
\grk ἀποδοχεῖον
\trl apodocheion
\ref L07105000300010
\grk λάκκος
\trl lakkos
\ref L06800702100006 L06800803100036 L07105000300014 L07801003700014
\grk φρέαρ
\trl frear
\ref L07700701900060 L07800101900050
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0417_cistern.jpg|col||© ד''ר אבישי טייכר|Inside a cistern|3.0\fig*The cistern was a pit hollowed out of solid rock for the purpose of storing water. Cisterns could be 6 meters (20 feet) across and 6 meters (20 feet) deep or even larger. In earliest times they were hewn out of rock that did not allow water to seep through it. With the discovery how to make plaster, cisterns could be dug in many kinds of rock and then lined with plaster, which sealed any holes or cracks.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line In the land of Israel, almost all of the annual rain falls between the months of November and March. Cisterns served to store excess rainwater or water from springs that dried up in the summer. The stored water could be used during the dry months of the year.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line A cistern differed from a well in that a cistern received water that flowed to it from a source removed from it at some distance, while the water in a well accumulated from its immediate vicinity. It is not always clear from the context whether a well or a cistern is intended in the passages listed above; for example, in \s H01600902500028\s* \a NIV\a*, \a TOB\a* and \a NCV\a* have “wells,” while \a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a* have “cisterns.” Similar uncertainty exists for most of the above references to the Hebrew word \i bor\i*. In some cases \i bor\i* can refer to a “pit” that occurs naturally. This may be true of the \i bor\i* into which Joseph was thrown by his brothers in \s H00103700000000\s*. Some translations have “cistern” (\a NIV\a*, \a FRCL\a*, \a GECL\a*), some say “well” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*), while others are noncommittal with “pit” (\a RSV\a*, \a NASB\a*).
\line It is possible to render “cistern” with a descriptive phrase such as “hollowed place in a rock for storing water.” In \s H01402601000018\s* \a CEV\a* provides a helpful model for the clause “he dug cisterns” by expanding it as follows: “he had cisterns dug there to catch the rainwater.” In \s H02400201300028\s* \a CEV\a* says “you’ve tried to collect water in cracked and leaking pits dug in the ground.”
\line \s H02000501500008\s*: See the comments on this verse at \l target="REALIA:3.8">3.8 Well\l*.
\line \s H02101200600052\s*: For the last clause in this verse, \a RSV\a* has “the wheel broken at the cistern.” This rendering is uncertain and translations differ. At the end of this verse the Hebrew text has two parallel clauses, which are literally “the jar will be shattered at the spring, and the wheel will be broken at the cistern.” Most translators and commentators understand the Hebrew word \i galgal\i* (“wheel”) to refer to a kind of pulley that aided in lifting the water container at a well; for example, for the last clause \a CEV\a* has “the pulley at the well is shattered” (similarly \a NJB\a*, \a NAB\a*, \a ITCL\a*). Scott points out that the parallelism demands that \i galgal\i* correspond to \i kad\i*, which is a clay pitcher or jar. However, in his own translation he has “the water wheel broken at the cistern” (page 254). \a GNT\a* seems to reverse the last two clauses in order to follow the order of events: “the rope at the well will break, and the water jar will be shattered.” It is probably best to treat the “wheel” as a pulley. Where a pulley wheel is unknown, translators may follow the \a GNT\a* model. However, even if you follow \a GNT\a*, a note may be necessary to explain that the rope was used to pull up a water container attached to it.
\key 3.10
\title Pool
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בְּרֵכָה
\trl brekah
\ref H01000201300024 H01000201300040 H01000201300054 H01000401200040 H01102203800014 H01201801700076 H01202002000026 H01600201400018 H01600301500056 H01600301600034 H02100200600006 H02200700500014 H02300700300038 H02302200900028 H02302201100020 H02303600200044 H03400200900008
\heb מִקְוֶה, מִקְוָה
\trl miqveh, miqvah
\ref H00200701900054 H02302201100004
\grk κολυμβήθρα
\trl kolumbēthra
\ref G04300500200018 [G04300500400018] G04300500700036 G04300900700016
\grk κρήνη
\trl krēnē
\ref L07104801700034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0418_pool.jpg|col||© Liadmalone (Wikimedia Commons)|Lower Solomon's Pool|3.0\fig* The pool was a relatively large, open construction for holding water.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00200701900054\s*: The Hebrew word \i miqveh\i* in this verse may mean a specific kind of reservoir, or, more likely, it is a general word that repeats the earlier phrase “the water of Egypt.”
\line \s H02302201100020\s*: The pool created between the city walls of Jerusalem may have served a dual purpose: storage of water during the siege, and a kind of moat or water-filled ditch to deter an attacker. Most translations render the Hebrew word \i miqvah\i* here as “reservoir” (\a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*).
\line \s H03400200900008\s*: There is a textual problem in the Hebrew of this verse, and many translations work from an emended text. Water escaping from a reservoir is a simile for the people of Nineveh fleeing from the city. For the first half of this verse \a NIV\a* has “Nineveh is like a pool, and its water is draining away.” \a GNT\a* also provides a useful model: “Like water from a broken dam the people rush from Nineveh.”
\line In \s G04300500200018\s* the Greek term \i kolumbēthra\i* refers to a pool having five porches, one on each of four sides and another porch that went across the middle of the pool. Even though the same Greek word is used, the pool mentioned in \s G04300900700016\s* was considerably smaller and less elaborate. This pool has been excavated in Jerusalem.
\key 3.11
\title Water shaft, water tunnel, water channel, water supply
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb צִנּוֹר
\trl tsinor
\ref H01000500800032
\heb תְּעָלָה
\trl t‘alah
\ref H01201801700072 H01202002000034 H02300700300034 H02303600200040
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The water shaft was an underground channel dug to convey water from a spring into a city.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Jerusalem was walled to protect it from enemies, but there were few natural water sources within the city itself. Not far outside the wall, and below the level of the city, was a natural spring, called Gihon. If the city came under siege, the outside spring would be inaccessible to those inside the city. To overcome this problem, a tunnel was cut out of the rock connecting the lower spring to a point inside the city and on a slope that allowed water to flow into the area within the city walls. At the same time, access to the spring at its source was blocked so that an enemy could not get at it. The place where the water reached the city was considerably below ground level, and a vertical shaft, rather like a well, was cut out so that water could be drawn up with buckets. Thus there were two cut shafts, a near-horizontal one leading under the city from the spring, and a vertical one down to the horizontal one and through which water was drawn up.
\line The exact meaning of the Hebrew word \i tsinor\i* in \s H01000500800032\s* is uncertain and debated. Modern translations generally have “water shaft,” “water tunnel,” or something similar. Translators may use a descriptive phrase such as “tunnel cut in the rock to bring water into the city.”
\key 3.12
\title Storehouse
\index \l target="REALIA:3.12.1">3.12.1 Grain-store, silo\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בַּיִת, אָסֹף
\trl (beyth) ’asupim
\ref H01601202500024
\heb אוֹצָר
\trl ’otsar
\ref H01302702700030 H01302702800034 H01401101100022 H01601204400028 H01601301200032 H01601301300008 H01803802200008 H01803802200014 H01903300700020 H01913500700030 H02303900200078 H02303900400046 H02401001300054 H02403801100034 H02405101600048
\grk ἀποδοχεῖον
\trl apodocheion
\ref L07100101700018
\grk θησαυρός
\trl thēsauros
\ref L07104101200022 L07104301400008
\grk ταμεῖον
\trl tameion
\ref G04201202400024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The places listed above were for general storage. Their shape and structure are undefined. See also \l target="REALIA:3.13.4">3.13.4 Armory, arsenal\l* and \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.4">3.14.1.4 Treasury, strongroom\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In most of the references listed above it is stated what was being stored. Where the commodity being stored is named, languages may have a special word for the particular place where such a commodity is stored; for example, in \s H01302702700030\s* \a GNT\a* has “Wine cellars” for the Hebrew word \i ’otsar\i*. However, in the following verse, where the same word is used together with “oil,” \a GNT\a* has “Olive oil storage,” because English has no special word for a place to store olive oil.
\key 3.12.1
\title Grain-store, silo
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אָסָם
\trl ’asam
\ref H00502800800016 H02000301000006
\heb אוֹצָר
\trl ’otsar
\ref H02900101700012
\heb מַאֲבוּס
\trl ma’avus
\ref H02405002600012
\heb מְגוּרָה
\trl mgurah
\ref H03700201900014
\heb מַמְּגוּרָה
\trl mamgurah
\ref H02900101700016
\heb מִסְכְּנוֹת
\trl misknoth
\ref H00200101100026 H01100901900012 H01400800400026 H01400800600018 H01401600400064 H01401701200034 H01403202800004
\grk ἀποθήκη
\trl apothēkē
\ref G04000301200040 G04000602600030 G04001303000068 G04200301700036 G04201201800016 G04201202400028
\lat promptuarium
\ref V08200500900042
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0419_grain_store.jpg|col||© Ian Scott (Wikimedia Commons)|Grain-store at Megiddo|3.0\fig* The grain-store or silo was a small structure for storing agricultural produce. It normally was made of stone.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages an important distinction is made between buildings used to store farm produce and those that are warehouses for other types of material. This structure was actually not a “building” in the sense that it was constructed like a house. The English word “barn” conveys the idea of a large, multi-purpose structure. Something like “grain-store,” “granary,” or “grain bin” will be preferable.
\line Most of the references to the Hebrew word \i misknoth\i* (except \s H01403202800004\s*) appear with the word for “city.” The following advice comes from of \i A Handbook on Exodus\i* (page 22) at \s H00200101100026\s*: “The \b store-cities\b* were special centers built as warehouses for storing grain and other supplies for the government. If such centers are unknown in the receptor culture, it is possible to translate this word as ‘cities in which to store supplies,’ or ‘cities . . . to serve as supply centers,’ as in \a TEV\a* [that is, \a GNT\a*]. In cultures where the only large human settlements are villages surrounded by fences, translators will need other more descriptive ways to translate \b store-cities\b*; for example, ‘large villages with high walls [or, fences] around them, where supplies are stored’ or ‘large places with high fences around them, where they store grain and other things.’ ”
