\ref L08100504600038 L08100900600016 L08100903800018 L08100904100018
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0240_marketplace.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Marketplace inside a city (Roman period)|3.0\fig* The square was an open place in a town or city, often formed by the intersection of two or more streets (see \l target="REALIA:3.13.1">3.13.1 Street, road, path, way, track\l*). Like the streets, the square was usually unpaved, only sometimes paved with stones. The square was open to the sky and often served as a gathering place for the inhabitants of the city. One of the squares of a town usually served as a marketplace, a central location for bartering, buying, and selling.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Many cultures, where people live in permanent settlements, will know an open place in the middle of a settlement used for public gatherings.
\line In biblical times one such open area, which was often the most important one in the city, stood inside the city wall, near the gates. In this place, town administration meetings (\s H00502101900030\s*), legal transactions (\s H00800400100010\s*, \s H00800401100018\s*), and markets (\s H01200700100048\s*, \s H01200701800028\s*) were held (see \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.5">3.13.3.5 City gate\l*). It will sometimes be possible in translation to indicate the place by the activity that is taking place there rather than by a word that corresponds to “square.” A good example of this is the way \a GNT\a* renders \s H01802900700016\s*. The Hebrew reads literally “When I went out to the gate of the city, when I prepared my seat in the square” (\a RSV\a*); \a GNT\a* says “Whenever the city elders met and I took my place among them.” Compare also \a GNT\a* at \s H02000701200016\s*: “or stood waiting at a corner, sometimes in the streets, sometimes in the marketplace.”
\line While most translations and commentaries understand the Hebrew word \i rchov\i* to mean “city square,” some understand it in the more general sense of “street” in some passages (and this indeed has become its only meaning in modern Hebrew); for example, \a KJV\a* renders it “street[s]” in all but three instances, and \a NIV\a*, while usually rendering \i rchov\i* as “square[s],” has “streets” in about one-third of its appearances. By way of example, most translations render \i rchovoth\i* in \s H02700902500054\s* as “streets”; some common-language translations (\a GECL\a*, \a FRCL\a*, \a ITCL\a*) avoid a direct translation of \i rchovoth\i* by speaking of “Jerusalem” being reconstructed.
\key 3.13.3
\title City fortifications
\index \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.1">3.13.3.1 City wall, rampart, battlement\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.2">3.13.3.2 Fortress, stronghold, castle, citadel, fort\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.3">3.13.3.3 Watchtower, tower\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.4">3.13.3.4 Moat\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.5">3.13.3.5 City gate\l*
\cont Ancient cities were often built with special fortifications to protect the inhabitants from attacks from the outside. Sometimes the fortifications were natural, for example, on the top of a steep hill or next to a river. Man-made fortifications included at least a high, thick wall, usually made of bricks or stones. A city wall had one or more entrances, which were closed with gates. The gates were usually made of wood. The entranceway itself was often quite complex, involving one or more turns and several guardrooms. The gate, as well as the rest of the wall, could be supplemented with towers that stood up higher than the wall. These towers served both as vantage points from which to see someone approaching from a distance and also as high points from which missiles could be dropped or thrown on an attacking enemy.
\key 3.13.3.1
\title City wall, rampart, battlement
