\ref G04701000400030 L07700100200014 L07700406100034 L07700500900052 L07700501100014 L07700502700032 L07700502900020 L07700503000044 L07700506500060 L07700606100028 L07700606200022 L07700801000082 L07700905000026 L07701001200018 L07701003700014 L07701101800032 L07701101800046 L07701104100040 L07701203300022 L07701203400012 L07701203500032 L07701204500062 L07701303300010 L07701303300048 L07701303800018 L07701404200064 L07701500700032 L07701600800048 L07701601500018 L07800803000028 L07801001500018 L07801001600038 L07801002300028 L07801003200018 L07801100600022 L07801201900036 L07900602500020
\grk φρούριον
\trl frourion
\ref L07801003200024 L07801003300018 L07801301900008
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0066_antonia_fortress_model.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Model of the Antonia fortress in Jerusalem|3.0\fig* The fortress was a large fortification, often part of the defense of a town. In the Middle East such fortifications were built of stone. A fortress could consist of one extra strong building or of a complex of buildings surrounded by its own strong wall.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages the word “fortress” may be rendered in terms of its function, for example, “place for protection” or “place to defend oneself.” Often, however, a fortress is described in terms of its construction, for example, “strong-walled place.”
\line The Hebrew word \i birah\i* in \s H01600200800042 H01600700200022\s* refers to a fortified enclosure that stood on the northwest corner of the Temple complex in Jerusalem to guard the Temple on the northern side, from which attacks were most likely to come. It was later expanded and strengthened by Herod the Great and named the Antonia (see \l target="REALIA:3.20.1">3.20.1 Pavement, The Pavement\l*). In \s H01600200800042\s* \a CEV\a* renders the literal phrase “the fortress of the Temple” as “the fortress near the temple”; \a GNT\a* has “the fort that guards the Temple”; \a REB\a* says “the citadel, which adjoins the temple.”
\line The Hebrew phrase \i migdal shkem\i* in \s H00700904600010 H00700904700018 H00700904900064\s* is understood in various ways. Most English translations consulted have “tower of Shechem” or “fortress of Shechem”; some capitalize “Tower” (\a RSV\a*), suggesting that it could be a place name. Many non-English translations (for example, \a SPCL\a*, \a FRCL\a*, \a DUCL\a*, \a TOB\a*) take it to be a place name and simply transliterate it (\a DUCL\a* “Migdal-Sichem”).
\line In the New Testament the Greek term \i ochurōma\i* occurs only in \s G04701000400030\s*, where it is used figuratively of the strength of false arguments. In a number of languages it may be more satisfactory to render the word in a simile in order to mark this figurative usage; for example, the verse may be rendered “The weapons we use in our fight are not the world’s weapons but God’s powerful weapons with which to destroy false arguments in the same way that people would destroy fortresses.”
\key 3.13.3.3
\title Watchtower, tower
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַלְמָן
\trl ’alman
\ref H02301302200010
\heb בַּחַן
\trl bachan
\ref H02303201400018
\heb מִגְדָּל, מִגְדֹּל
\trl migdal, migdol
\ref H00700800900032 H00700801700006 H00700905100004 H00700905100062 H00700905200012 H00700905200030 H01200901700014 H01201700900040 H01201800800022 H01302702500052 H01401400600030 H01402600900008 H01402601500024 H01402700400028 H01403200500030 H01600300100050 H01600300100060 H01600301100026 H01600302500020 H01600302600038 H01600302700020 H01601203800050 H01601203900036 H01601203900042 H01904801300012 H01906100400010 H02001801000002 H02200400400004 H02200501300012 H02200700500006 H02200700500030 H02200801000014 H02300201500008 H02303002500042 H02303301800024 H02403103800028 H02602600400014 H02602600900016 H02602701100022 H03801401000066
\heb מָצוֹר
\trl matsor
\ref H03500200100014
\heb מִצְפֶּה
\trl mitspeh
\ref H02302100800010 H01402002400012
\heb פִּנָּה
\trl pinah
\ref H01402601500032 H03600101600026 H03600300600008
\heb שֶׁמֶשׁ
\trl shemesh
\ref H02305401200008
\grk πύργος
\trl purgos
\ref G04002103300042 G04101200100036 G04201300400018 G04201402800012 L06701301400046 L06701301700094 L06800100300006 L06800101400026 L06800700500028 L06800703200030 L07700103300020 L07700406000028 L07700500500014 L07700500500036 L07700506500068 L07701303300020 L07701304300042 L07701601000010 L07801001800018 L07801002000024 L07801002200022 L07801003600026 L07801300500012 L07801404100012 L07900202700026 L08001300600010 L08100105200028 L08100400400056
\grk σκοπή
\trl skopē
\ref L07103701400028
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0069_watchtower_model.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Model of a watchtower|3.0\fig* The watchtower was a tall structure with a lookout at the top.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Watchtowers were placed at intervals along city walls to watch for an approaching enemy. They also allowed the defenders of the city to shoot at an attacker from his flank. Sometimes towers were built on private property to protect it. See also \l target="REALIA:2.19.3">2.19.3 Firing platform, siege tower\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages the expression for “tower” is simply “high building” (though of course not a skyscraper). In other instances it may be more appropriately rendered “high platform” or “high lookout place.”
\line The Hebrew word \i ’alman\i* in \s H02301302200010\s* means literally “his widows.” It is very similar to a word meaning “palace” (see \i ’armon\i* under \l target="REALIA:3.4">3.4 Palace\l*). It is not clear if there is a textual corruption here or if the author has deliberately interchanged the letters in order to suggest “desolation” (see de Waard, \i A Handbook on Isaiah\i*, page 61).
\line \s H01402002400012\s*: While some translations (for example, \a NRSV\a*, \a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*) translate the Hebrew word \i mitspeh\i* as “tower” or “watchtower,” it is just as likely that the \i mitspeh\i* was simply a high natural point from which a person had a good view. So where \a RSV\a* has “the watchtower of the wilderness,” \a NIV\a* says “the place that overlooks the desert,” \a NCV\a* renders “a place where they could see the desert,” and \a ITCL\a* has “a hill from which it was possible to see the desert.”
\line The Hebrew word \i pinah\i* is literally “corner.” In the references given the word may not necessarily mean a distinct structure but rather just a corner of the city wall. In \s H03600101600026\s* some translations have “corner towers” (\a NIV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*), while others are more general with “lofty battlements” (\a RSV\a*; similarly \a NLT\a*).
\line Some older translations (for example, \a KJV\a*) rendered the Hebrew word \i tsafith\i* as “watchtower” in \s H02302100500012\s*. It is now commonly accepted that it means “carpet” (see \l target="REALIA:5.17">5.17 Carpet, rug\l*).
\line In the New Testament the Greek word \i purgos\i* may designate any type of tower, whether employed for military purposes or used by watchmen protecting a harvest (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.11">1.1.11 Watchtower\l*). In \s G04201300400018\s* the tower was probably part of the ancient walls of Jerusalem.
\key 3.13.3.4
\title Moat
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb חָרוּץ
\trl charuts
\ref H02700902500058
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0421_moat_en.jpg|col||© Ya'acov Sa'ar, Israel Government Press Office|Ruins of a fortress surrounded by a moat|3.0\fig* The moat was a wide ditch or trench dug outside the walls of a city in order to make the wall a more difficult obstacle for those who would attempt to attack from the outside. A moat could be dry or filled with water, but in the conditions of the land of Israel a dry moat was more likely.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i charuts\i* with the meaning of part of a city’s defenses occurs only in \s H02700902500058\s*. Interpretations have varied widely, but it is most likely that it refers to a moat as defined above. \a RSV\a* and \a NASB\a* have “moat”; \a NIV\a* says “trench”; \a CEV\a* expands to “a trench will be dug around the city for protection.” \a GNT\a* “strong defenses” may also serve as a model.
\line See also the note on \s H02302201101000\s* at \l target="REALIA:3.10">3.10 Pool\l*.
\key 3.13.3.5
\title City gate
\index \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.5.1">3.13.3.5.1 Gate bar, bolt\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.5.2">3.13.3.5.2 Guardroom\l*
