\ref L07102802500032 L07104901300032 L07300101700050 L07700905000078 L07701203800032 L07701303300036
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0018_gate_locked_ bar_en.png|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|City gate with a bar|3.0\fig* The bars of gates were usually made of wood (see the description of the gate at \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.5">3.13.3.5 City gate\l*). However, there are several specific references to bars made of metal (\s H01100401300054\s*; \s H01910701600012\s*; \s H02304500200026\s*), but even these bars may have been made of wood that was reinforced with metal.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages it may be necessary to use a descriptive phrase for “bar,” such as “big stick that held the doors closed.” Another model is “bar that bolts the doors of the mouth/opening/entrance in the walls/fences around the city.” Since the bar functioned to secure the gate in much the same way a modern lock would, translators may wish to speak of a “lock” rather than a bar; for example, in \s H02404903100030\s* \a GNT\a* refers to “locks.” In \s H00500300500018\s* \a GNT\a* presents another model: “bars to lock the gates.”
\line \s H01803801000014\s*: See the discussion under \l target="REALIA:3.1.3">3.1.3 Gate or gateway to house or building complex\l*.
\line In \s H03000100500006\s* \a RSV\a* renders the Hebrew word \i briach\i* literally in the first line, saying “I will break the bar of Damascus.” Like \a RSV\a*, most translations treat the first line as a literal threat to destroy the city of Damascus. \a NIV\a* has “I will break down the gate of Damascus,” \a CEV\a* says “I will break through the gates of Damascus,” and \a GNT\a* translates “I will smash the city gates of Damascus.” This is also the only option presented by \i A Handbook on The Book of Amos\i*. It is possible, however, to see a parallelism between the first two lines of the verse and the last two lines, where “gate bar” in the first line is parallel to “scepter” (\i shevet\i* in Hebrew) in the third line. This would mean that the gate bar is a metaphor for the ruler. Of the translations consulted, only \a REB\a* comes close to this approach with “I shall crush the nobles of Damascus . . . and the sceptred ruler of Beth-eden.”
\line \s H03400301300028\s*: It is not clear whether the bars and gates mentioned here are to be taken literally or figuratively. If they are understood figuratively, then the “bars” probably stand for the fortresses that guarded the mountain passes, which are called “gates” earlier in the verse. If they are understood literally, then the “bars” would be the wooden beams that prevented the gates of Nineveh from being opened. \a GNT\a* follows this interpretation and renders the last half of this verse as “Fire will destroy the bars across your gates.” Probably it is better either to take both the gates and bars as figurative, or both as literal. If translators take both the gates and bars as figurative, a possible translation model is “The borders of your land are wide open to your enemies, and fire will destroy your fortresses.”
\line \s H01600300300034 H01600300600044 H01600301300034 H01600301400040 H01600301500048\s* lists both \i briach\i* and \i man‘ul\i* as part of the gate. They were in fact parts of the system for securing the gate from the inside so that it could not be opened. The Hebrew word \i briach\i* refers to a pole or bar, while the word \i man‘ul\i* comes from a root meaning “to close.” Most translations render the two objects as “bolts and bars.” \a CEV\a* “metal bolts and wooden beams as locks” suggests the materials from which these objects were made and the function they served. The exact structure and function of the \i man‘ul\i* is not clear. The rendering of \a GECL\a* (expanded a bit) may come close: “the bars and the mechanisms that secured them in place.”
\key 3.13.3.5.2
\title Guardroom
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb תָּא
\trl t’a
\ref H01101402800032 H01401201100036 H02604000700006 H02604000700028 H02604001000004 H02604001200012 H02604001200034 H02604001300018 H02604001600012 H02604002100004 H02604002100008 H02604002900004 H02604002900008 H02604003300004 H02604003300008 H02604003600002 H02604003600004
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Ancient city gates were sometimes constructed with guardrooms on either side of the entrance. These usually came in sets of two, four, or six rooms (see \l target="REALIA:3.13.3.5">3.13.3.5 City gate\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i t’a\i* means simply “chamber,” “room,” “cell,” or “compartment.” The purpose of the room in \s H01101402800032\s* and \s H01401201100036\s* is different from that in \s H02604000001000\s*. Many languages will need to use two different words or expressions.
\line \s H01101402800032 H01401201100036\s*: In these verses \i t’a\i* refers to a room where valuable objects were kept under guard, although it is possible that the room in question was not actually designed as a treasury. In this context most translations render it “guardroom” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*). \a NJPSV\a* has “armory of the guards.” \a GECL\a* avoids a technical term and has “their [bronze shields] place.” This might be expanded to “the place where they were kept” or “the place where they were guarded.”
\line \s H02604000001000\s*: In this chapter the prophet Ezekiel describes the gates of an ideal Temple he saw in a vision. Each gate was constructed as a kind of corridor or covered passageway. On each side of this corridor were three small three-sided rooms (\i t’a\i* in Hebrew) facing each other. In these rooms sat soldiers who guarded the access to the outer and inner courts of the Temple. Here again, most translations have “guardrooms” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*). Luther (followed by \a GECL\a*) provides an alternative, translating \i t’a\i* as “niche.” This may actually be more accurate than “room,” since the area had walls on three sides with the side facing the passageway remaining open, making it more of a “recess” or “alcove.”
\key 3.13.4
\title Armory, arsenal
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אוֹצָר
\trl ’otsar
\ref H02405002500008
\heb בַּיִת, כְּלִי
\trl beyth kli
\ref H01202001300018 H02303900200016
\heb נֶשֶׁק
\trl nesheq
\ref H01600301900034
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0423_theatre.jpg|col||© Doron Horovitz, Israel Government Press Office|Reconstructed theater at Caesarea|3.0\fig* No specific description can be given for the armory. It is to be assumed that it was possible to close the place so that there was limited access.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Many languages may lack a specific word for a room or a building where many weapons are stored. It should normally be possible to use an expanded phrase, for example, “where he kept his weapons,” (\a CEV\a*; \s H01202001300018\s*) or “the place where my weapons are stored” (\a GNT\a*; \s H02405002500008\s*). The \a NCV\a* rendering of \s H02405002500008\s* shows that a general word for a storage place will work well: “The LORD has opened up his storeroom and brought out the weapons . . . .”
\key 3.13.5
\title Theater
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk θέατρον
\trl theatron
\ref G04401902900024 G04401903100036
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The theater was normally a semicircular open structure capable of seating several thousand people and used for public assemblies.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages the most appropriate equivalent for “theater” is actually “meeting place.” In other languages translators may use a term that designates an “enclosure.” Translators should avoid a word that has the narrow meaning of “cinema.” The ancient theater was used for a variety of public events, including drama presentations. Perhaps for this reason, \a CEV\a* has rendered the Greek word \i theatron\i* in \s G04401902900024\s* as “place where the town meetings were held” and has left the word untranslated in \s G04401903100036\s*.
\key 3.13.6
\title Stadium
\index \l target="REALIA:3.13.6.1">3.13.6.1 Discus\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ἱππόδρομος
\trl hippodromos
\ref L07900401100048 L07900504600022 L07900601600042
\grk παλαίστρα
\trl palaistra
\ref L07800401400050
\grk στάδιον
\trl stadion
\ref G04600902400012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0071_roman_stadium_model.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Stadium|3.0\fig* The stadium was an open, oval area (frequently including a racetrack) around which was built an enclosed series of tiers of seats for those who came to watch the spectacles.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s G04600902400012\s* the important feature is not the stadium as a construction, but as a place where races were conducted. Accordingly, the literal phrase “all the runners in the stadium” may very well be rendered as “all the runners who are racing.” The focus here is upon the competition rather than upon the type of place in which the competition took place.
\key 3.13.6.1
\title Discus
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk δίσκος
\trl diskos
\ref L07800401400062
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The discus was a round, flat disk about the size of a small dinner plate. Throwing such a disk to the greatest possible distance was part of the athletic contests of the ancient Greeks.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Athletic contests in ancient Greece were inseparably connected with the religious cult. This is an important aspect of the discus throwing in \s L07800401400062\s*, and this aspect should be preserved in translation, even if it means not mentioning the specific sport of throwing the discus; for example, \a GNT\a* renders the last part of this verse as “they would rush off to take part in the games that were forbidden by our Law.”
\key 3.13.7
\title Gymnasium, school
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk γυμνασία, γυμνάσιον
\trl gumnasia, gumnasion
\ref L07700101400006 L07800400900036 L07800401200014 L08001102000028
\grk σχολή
\trl scholē
\ref G04401900900048
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The gymnasium was an open area where Greek men did both physical and intellectual training together.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Transliterating the Greek word \i gumnasion\i* as “gymnasium” is misleading in English and may be also in other languages. In several modern European languages the word for “gymnasium” means “school,” which reflects the aspect of intellectual training but misses the physical training that also took place there.
\line \s L07800400900036\s* mentions two institutions together, which are called \i gumnasion\i* and \i efebeion\i* in Greek. The second word indicates a special place for youth gatherings. \a RSV\a* somewhat misses the point by saying “a gymnasium and a body of youth for it.” \a GNT\a* combines the two words with “a stadium where young men could train.” Other possible models are “a gymnasium and youth centre” (\a NJB\a*) and “a gymnasium and a youth club for it” (\a NAB\a*). \a NAB\a* adds this note: “\i Youth club\i*: an educational institution in which young men were trained both in Greek intellectual culture and in physical fitness.”
\key 3.13.8
\title Archives, library
\cont \u References:\u*
\arm בֵ֨ית גְּנַז
\trl beyth gnaz
\ref A01500501700020 A01500600100020
\grk βιβλιοθήκη
\trl bibliothēkē
\ref L07800201300040
\grk βιβλιοφυλάκιον
\trl bibliofulakion
\ref L08100602000020 L08100602200020
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0282_scroll.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Man reading a scroll in a library|3.0\fig* The library was a place for the storage of official or public documents. There was no distinctive structure for such a building.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s L07800400900000\s* several translations render the Greek word \i biblion\i* as “archives” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*). However, here this word refers more to “books” or “records” rather than to the place were those records were kept.
\key 3.13.9
\title Tell, mound
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גַּל, נצה
\trl gal (nitsim)
\ref H01201902500042 H01801502800024 H02302500200014 H02303702600040 H02400901000012 H02405103700010
\heb מְעִי, מַפָּלָה
\trl m‘i mapalah
\ref H02301700100020
\heb עִי
\trl ‘i
\ref H01907900100034 H02402601800058 H03300100600010 H03300301200018
\heb תֵּל
\trl tel
\ref H00501301700054 H00600802800018 H00601101300016 H02403001800032 H02404900200036
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0424_tell.jpg|col||© Grauesel (Wikimedia Commons)|Tell (Bet She'an)|3.0\fig* The tell was a hill formed by the accumulation of ruins of a succession of ancient towns. There are numerous tells in the Bible lands, and many have been excavated and identified as ancient biblical cities.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Ancient cities and towns were often destroyed in war or abandoned after plague or famine, and the buildings collapsed over time. Frequently new cities were built on the ruins of the old cities without clearing away all of the foundations and buildup of the former cities. This process of building on top of the old gradually created an artificial hill or mound. In biblical descriptions these mounds represent destruction and decay. However, cities built on top of these mounds had a higher elevation and were thus easier to fortify and defend.
\line With \s H00601101300016\s* and \s H02403001800032\s* as possible exceptions, the words listed above all connote something negative, not just a mound on which a city sits but a pile of ruins resulting from destructive activity.
\line \s H02404900200036\s*: The literal clause “it will become a desolate tell” is rendered by \a NCV\a* as “It will become a hill covered with ruins.” Some versions do not try to preserve the element of elevation; for example, \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a* have “it will be left in ruins.” \a GECL\a* provides a useful model with “Rabbah will become a heap of rubble.”
\key 3.13.10
\title Platform
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כִּיּוֹר
\trl kiyor
\ref H01400601300008
\heb מִגְדָּל
\trl migdal
\ref H01600800400014
\grk βῆμα
\trl bēma
\ref L07801302600008 L08100904200026
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0072_platform_ruins.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Ruins of a platform|3.0\fig* The platform was a large raised surface on which someone stood to address a crowd of people. The one described in \s H01400601300008\s* was made of bronze, and was 2.5 meters (8 feet) square and 1.5 meters (5 feet) high. These dimensions may serve as an approximate model for all of the references above, although the others may have been made of stone (as in the illustration) or wood.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Many cultures are familiar with a special place or structure from which a person addresses an assembled crowd.
\line The Hebrew word \i migdal\i* in \s H01600800400014\s* literally means “tower.” \a RSV\a* “pulpit” sounds anachronistic, even though the structure upon which Ezra stood fulfilled a purpose similar to that of a modern pulpit in some Christian traditions. \a NJB\a* “dais” is accurate but obscure for most English speakers. “Platform” (\a GNT\a*) or “high platform” (\a CEV\a*, \a NCV\a*) is good. The same rendering should be used at \s L08100904200026\s*.
\key 3.14
\title Temples
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.1">3.14.1 Jewish Temple\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.2">3.14.2 Pagan temple, idol’s temple\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.3">3.14.3 Tower, ziggurat\l*
\key 3.14.1
\title Jewish Temple
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.1">3.14.1.1 Entrance room, entrance hall\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.2">3.14.1.2 Colonnade, porch, covered walkway, stoa, portico\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.3">3.14.1.3 Rooms for boiling meat from sacrifices, kitchens\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.4">3.14.1.4 Treasury, strongroom\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.5">3.14.1.5 Pinnacle\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.6">3.14.1.6 Curtain, veil, drape\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.7">3.14.1.7 Additional Temple features\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.8">3.14.1.8 Other features of the Temple treated elsewhere in this chapter\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בַּיִת
\trl bayith
