\arm הֵיכַל
\trl heykal
\ref A01500501400030 A01500501400046 A01500501400062 A01500501500024 A01500600500028 A01500600500052 A02700500200036 A02700500300018
\heb מוֹעֵד
\trl mo‘ed
\ref H01907400400010 H02500200600016
\heb מִקְדָּשׁ
\trl miqdash
\ref H01302201900032 H01302801000024 H01402000800016 H01402601800060 H01402902100046 H01403000800028 H01403601700032 H01601004000050 H01906803600008 H01907301700008 H01907400700010 H01907806900010 H01909600600020 H02306001300028 H02306301800018 H02401701200014 H02405105100024 H02500101000022 H02500200700010 H02500202000036 H02600501100022 H02600800600050 H02600900600048 H02602303800014 H02602303900022 H02602402100024 H02602500300036 H02603702600036 H02603702800026 H02604302100036 H02604400100014 H02604400500088 H02604400700026 H02604400800024 H02604400900032 H02604401100008 H02604401500024 H02604401600008 H02604500400022 H02604500400052 H02604501800044 H02604701200060 H02604800800072 H02604801000070 H02604802100108 H02700801100032 H02700901700030 H02701103100016
\heb קָדוֹשׁ
\trl qadosh
\ref H02100801000024
\heb קֹדֶשׁ
\trl qodesh
\ref H01302303200022 H01302400500022 H01402900500046 H01402900700042 H01403001900032 H01902000300008 H01902400300022 H01906300300008 H01906801800022 H01906802500018 H01907400300022 H01913400200006 H01915000100012 H02304302800008 H02604402700014 H02604402700034 H02604500300046 H02604500300048 H02604500300048 H02700801300054 H02700801400026 H02700902400018 H02700902600036
\heb שֹׂךְ
\trl sok
\ref H02500200600012
\grk ἅγιος
\trl hagios
\ref L06800401200074 L06800401300056 L06800802100030 L06800802400034 L06800900800050 L06801602000022 L07700201200008 L07700304300044 L07700305100006 L07700305800058 L07700305900036 L07700403600032 L07700404100026 L07700404300008 L07700404800008 L07700601800024 L07700605400010 L07700703300036 L07700704200036 L07700905400042 L07701004200026 L07701003900018 L07701003900036 L07701004400018 L07701300300054 L07701300600020 L07701401500004 L07701401500018 L07701402900068 L07701403100032 L07701403600078 L07701404200026 L07701404800032 L07701500700010 L07801501700076
\grk ἁγίασμα
\trl hagiasma
\ref L06800501900042 L07104701000046 L07104701300038 L07105001100036 L07700102100010 L07700103600012 L07700103700014 L07700103700022 L07700103900004 L07700104500020 L07700104600006 L07700200700062 L07700304500038 L07700403800008 L07700500100030 L07700600700030 L07700602600030 L07700605100010
\grk ἁγιασμός
\trl hagiasmos
\ref L07900201800012
\grk ἱερός
\trl hieros
\ref G04000400500034 G04001200500028 G04001200600012 G04002101200012 G04002101200032 G04002101400018 G04002101500038 G04002102300012 G04002400100014 G04002400100038 G04002605500048 G04101101100014 G04101101500018 G04101101500038 G04101101600020 G04101102700018 G04101203500018 G04101300100012 G04101300300022 G04101404900016 G04200202700016 G04200203700024 G04200204600020 G04200400900024 G04201801000012 G04201904500010 G04201904700018 G04202000100026 G04202100500012 G04202103700014 G04202103800020 G04202205200026 G04202205300018 G04202405300014 G04300201400010 G04300201500020 G04300501400018 G04300701400020 G04300702800010 G04300800200014 G04300802000022 G04300805900030 G04301002300014 G04301105600022 G04301802000034 G04400204600016 G04400300100016 G04400300200038 G04400300200062 G04400300300020 G04400300800024 G04400301000034 G04400400100030 G04400502000014 G04400502100018 G04400502400022 G04400502500036 G04400504200012 G04401902700038 G04402102600032 G04402102700034 G04402102800060 G04402102900034 G04402103000038 G04402201700024 G04402400600008 G04402401200010 G04402401800016 G04402500800028 G04402602100018 G04600901300012 G04600901300012
\grk ναός
\trl naos
\ref G04002301600024 G04002301600046 G04002301700024 G04002302100012 G04002303500056 G04002606100014 G04002700500014 G04002704000012 G04002705100012 G04101405800020 G04101502900032 G04101503800010 G04200100900024 G04200102100030 G04200102200028 G04202304500018 G04300201900016 G04300202000022 G04600301700008 G04600301700028 G04700601600008 G04900202100016 G05300200400030 G06600301200016 G06600701500034 G06601100100024 G06601100200014 G06601101900008 G06601101900040 G06601401500014 G06601401700014 G06601500500016 G06601500600026 G06601500800008 G06601500800044 G06601600100014 G06601601700034
\grk νεώς
\trl neōs
\ref L07800401400030 L07800600200014 L07800901600012 L07801000300006 L07801000500012 L07801302300058 L07801403300012
\grk οἰκία, οἶκος
\trl oikia, oikos
\ref G04001200400010 G04002101300012 G04002101300012 G04100202600010 G04101101700020 G04101101700020 G04200600400010 G04201105100028 G04201904600014 G04201904600014 G04300201600026 G04300201700022 G04301400200006 G04400704700010 G04400704900026 G05800300200024 G05800300500016 G05801002100012
\grk σκήνωμα
\trl skēnōma
\ref L06800900800058
\grk τόπος, ἅγιος, ἁγίασμα
\trl topos, hagios topos, topos hagios, topos tou hagiasmatos
\ref G04002401500032 G04301104800036 G04400601300030 G04402102800036 L07800201800068 L07800301800036 L07800501700050 L07800501900010 L07800501900026 L07800801700018 L07801000700036 L07801302300064 L07900100900036 L07900100900050 L07900102300040 L07900201400048 L08000400900036 L08000401200034 L08100807500038
\lat sanctificatio
\ref V08200710800024 V08201002100008 V08201204800052 V08201502500018
\lat templum
\ref V08201002100030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0250_temple_herods_en.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Drawing of Herod's temple|3.0\fig* The Temple was the building in Jerusalem in which God was regarded as dwelling and where he was worshiped. From the time it was first built by Solomon, it was the center of worship for the Jewish people. In Jewish history three temples were constructed, all of them quite different from the others. The first Temple, built by Solomon, was destroyed in 587/586 B.C. A new, more modest Temple was built about seventy years later by Zerubbabel and lasted until almost the time of the New Testament, when it was rebuilt by Herod the Great. This third structure was only completed about 63 A.D. and was destroyed by the Roman army seven years later.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line There are, in fact, four different Jewish temples in the Bible: those built by Solomon, Zerubbabel, and Herod the Great, and the vision of an ideal Temple in the last chapters of Ezekiel. While the same word should be used for all of them, it will be helpful for the reader to have a note or glossary entry explaining the differences between them. It will not normally be necessary—or even advisable—to reflect those differences in translation. \fig |PTZ-0073_temple_herod.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Model of Herod's temple|3.0\fig*
\line “Temple” may be rendered “house of God,” “place where God dwells,” or “God’s building.” Some languages often say “holy house” or “holy place.” Other renderings are “God’s great singing house” and “God’s big prayer house.”
\line The Hebrew word \i mo‘ed\i* means literally an appointed time or place of meeting. In the references given above it refers to the Temple as the place where people came for the sacred festivals. \fig |UBS-0019_temple_ezekiel.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Artist's conception of the temple envisioned by Ezekiel|3.0\fig*
\line In some languages there is a technical term for “temple,” and this is often carefully distinguished from an expression designating a central sanctuary in which the deity is thought to dwell. In the New Testament the Greek word \i naos\i* refers to a single building, while the word \i hieron\i* points to the entire Temple precinct with its buildings, courts, and storerooms. Even though in a number of contexts it is not necessary to distinguish between \i hieron\i* and \i naos\i*, in \s G04002101200012\s* (and the parallel passages \s G04101101500018 G04201904500010 G04300201400010\s*), it is important to indicate this distinction in order not to leave the impression that sacrificial animals were actually being sold inside the central sanctuary. When translating “temple,” translators should avoid using the same term used to translate “synagogue” in the New Testament. \fig |UBS-0020_temple_ezekiel.jpg|col||Good News Study Bible, © United Bible Societies|Diagrams of Ezekiel's temple|3.0\fig*
\key 3.14.1.1
\title Entrance room, entrance hall
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֵילָם, אוּלָם
\trl ’eylam, ’elam, ’ulam
\ref H01100600300006 H01100700600006 H01100700600030 H01100700700004 H01100700700016 H01100700800026 H01100700800062 H01100701200044 H01100701900024 H01100702100014 H01302801100020 H01400300400006 H01400801200030 H01401500800086 H01402900700010 H01402901700042 H02600801600034 H02604000700046 H02604000800008 H02604000900008 H02604000900032 H02604001500026 H02604001600042 H02604002100034 H02604002100038 H02604002200012 H02604002200016 H02604002200058 H02604002200062 H02604002400034 H02604002400038 H02604002500012 H02604002500018 H02604002600014 H02604002600018 H02604002900020 H02604002900024 H02604002900046 H02604002900052 H02604003000004 H02604003100004 H02604003300020 H02604003300024 H02604003300046 H02604003300052 H02604003400004 H02604003400008 H02604003600012 H02604003600016 H02604003900006 H02604004000052 H02604004800008 H02604004800020 H02604004900006 H02604101500060 H02604102500046 H02604102600028 H02604400300036 H02604600200012 H02604600800014 H02900201700006
\heb מִסְדְּרוֹן
\trl misdron
\ref H00700302300010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The entrance hall was a kind of foyer or anteroom that extended across the entrance of a large building. The entrance hall of the Temple stood higher than the rest of the Temple, and it may not have had a roof. While the biblical text considers it part of the internal space of the sanctuary, it may have served as a kind of forecourt, a transition from the outside courtyard to the inside of the building. Several of the passages above do not refer to the entrance hall of the Temple. \s H00700302300010\s* and \s H01100700601000 H01100700701000 H01100700801000\s* refer to the entrance halls of palaces, while some of the passages in Ezekiel (\s H02604000701000 H02604000801000 H02604000901000\s*, \s H02604001501000 H02604001601000 H02604001701000 H02604001801000 H02604001901000 H02604002001000 H02604002101000 H02604002201000 H02604002301000 H02604002401000 H02604002501000 H02604002601000 H02604002701000 H02604002801000 H02604002901000 H02604003001000 H02604003101000 H02604003201000 H02604003301000 H02604003401000 H02604003501000 H02604003601000\s*, \s H02604003901000 H02604004010000\s*; \s H02604600201000\s*, \s H02604600801000\s*) refer to the entrance halls of the Temple gates.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In many languages the only approximate equivalent for the Hebrew word \i ’ulam\i* may be a small hall inside the entrance to a house. This could be misleading since this word refers to a very large hall, which was even wider than the main building. It may be necessary to add a modifier of size, saying “large entry hall.”
\key 3.14.1.2
\title Colonnade, porch, covered walkway, stoa, portico
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk στοά
\trl stoa
\ref G04300500200030 G04301002300020 G04400301100034 G04400501200042
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0074_temple_herod_covered_walkway.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Model of covered walkway in Herod's temple|3.0\fig* The porch was a covered colonnade, open normally on one side, where people could stand, sit, or walk, protected from the weather and the heat of the sun. It consisted of two parallel rows of columns that supported a roof.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In many parts of the world the closest equivalent for the Greek word \i stoa\i* would be a verandah, an extensive type of porch. Such a porch may be rendered “long outside room” or “room made with pillars and open.” All of the above references except \s G04300500200030\s* are to “Solomon’s Porch,” which was probably located along the eastern edge of the Court of the Gentiles in the Temple complex.
\key 3.14.1.3
\title Rooms for boiling meat from sacrifices, kitchens
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb בַּיִת, בשׁל
\trl beyth mvashlim
\ref H02604602400010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line In Ezekiel’s description of the Temple, special rooms were designated at the four corners of the outer court for boiling the meat from the sacrifices. The people who brought certain sacrifices were to eat a sacred meal, which was prepared in these rooms by servants (perhaps Levites) designated for the task.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Most translations render \i beyth mvashlim\i* in \s H02604602400010\s* as “kitchen” (\a RSV\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a NIV\a*). \a NASB\a* has “boiling places.” \a GECL\a* avoids translating the name of the rooms by saying “Here the Temple servants will cook the meat for the sacred meal of the people.”
\key 3.14.1.4
\title Treasury, strongroom
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֲרוֹן
\trl ’aron
\ref H01201201000012 H01201201100022 H01402400800014 H01402401000032 H01402401100016 H01402401100076
\heb בַּיִת, אָסֹף
\trl (beyth) ’asupim
\ref H01302601500014 H01302601700048
\heb בַּיִת, אוֹצָר
\trl (beyth) ’otsar
\ref H00502801200010 H00503203400016 H00600601900030 H00600602400052 H01100705100022 H01101501800028 H01101501800030 H01201201900062 H01201401400034 H01201600800026 H01201801500020 H01202001300018 H01202001500012 H01202401300014 H01202401300016 H01300902600040 H01302602000012 H01302602000014 H01302602200016 H01302602400020 H01302602600014 H01302702500006 H01302702500024 H01302801200024 H01302801200042 H01302900800016 H01400500100020 H01400801500038 H01401200900022 H01401200900024 H01401600200016 H01402502400032 H01403202700022 H01500206900010 H01600706900032 H01600707000016 H01601003900046 H02000802100012 H02602800400030 H02700100200028 H02801301500042 H03900301000014
\heb בַּיִת, נְכֹאת
\trl beth nkoth
\ref H01202001300018 H02303900200016
\arm גְּנַז
\trl gnaz
\ref A01500702000008
\heb גֶּנֶז
\trl genez
\ref H01700300900046 H01700400700040
\heb גַּנְזַךְ
\trl ganzak
\ref H01302801100030
\grk γαζοφυλάκιον
\trl gazofulakion
\ref G04101204100010 G04101204100028 G04101204300048 G04202100100016 G04300802000014 L07700302800008 L07701404900016 L07800300600022 L07800302400018 L07800302800026 L07800304000018 L07800404200048 L07800501800044 L08000400300032 L08000400600024 L08100504400012 L08100801800040 L08100804400028
\grk θησαυρός
\trl thēsauros
\ref L07100102500004 L07700302900018
\grk κορβανᾶς
\trl korbanas
\ref G04002700600028
\grk ταμιεῖον
\trl tamieion
\ref L07102901200010
\grk θησαυρός
\trl thesaurus
\ref L08000400700040
\lat thesaurus
\ref V08200604000008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0075_pinnacle_en.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Southwest corner of the Temple Mount|3.0\fig* The treasury was a place for storing valuables belonging to a king or other national authorities. The Temple in Jerusalem had its own treasury. There was no standard size or structure of a treasury.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i ’aron\i* in \s H01201200901000 H01201201000012\s* and \s H01402400800014 H01402401000032 H01402401100016\s* refers to a large collection box. According to \s H01201200901000\s*, a hole was cut in its “door.” This would refer to one surface of the box, presumably its top. People could bring their donations (not coins, which were not yet invented) and insert them into the box through the hole. The donations could then be removed by opening or removing the top.
\line In some passages the Hebrew word \i ’otsar\i* refers to treasure (for example, \s H01202401300014 H01401200900022\s*), while in other places it indicates the place where treasure was stored, that is, a treasury (for example, \s H01202001300018 H01403202700022\s*). The first half of \s H01101501800028\s* says literally “And Asa took all the remaining silver and gold in the \u treasuries\u* of the house of the LORD and [he took] the \u treasures\u* of the king’s house.” No translation consulted makes the distinction, although some render both words “treasures” (\a RSV\a*), while others render both words “treasuries” (\a NJPSV\a*). In fact, in many of the references under \i ’otsar\i* it is not easy to determine if the meaning is “treasure” or “treasure storehouse.” In only three places is there specific reference in Hebrew to a “treasure house” (\s H01601003900062 H02700100200028 H03900301000014\s*).
\line Where a word for “treasury” is not available, it may be rendered with a descriptive phrase, such as “safe place where the king’s [or, Temple’s] valuables were kept/were guarded.” An alternative model for the last half of \s G04002700600028\s* is “It is against our Law to put it with the money that belongs to the Temple since it is blood money.”
\line In the New Testament the Greek word \i gazofulakion\i* also refers to a box in which donations were collected. According to Jewish tradition, there were thirteen such offering boxes in the Temple, and the receptacles that channeled the money down to the boxes were in the form of trumpets or rams’ horns. As a result, the sound of coins falling into the boxes was rather conspicuous. In some cultures such a collection box may be unknown, or at best people know the container that is passed around to collect money in church. If possible, the translation should indicate that the offering box was in a fixed place and not something passed around. In \s G04202100100016\s* \a NCV\a* has “Temple money box” and adds this note: “A special box in the Jewish place of worship where people put their gifts to God.” \a PV\a* uses a longer expression, saying “place reserved for them [gifts].”
\key 3.14.1.5
\title Pinnacle
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk πτερύγιον
\trl pterugion
\ref G04000400500030 G04200400900020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The pinnacle was the tip or high point of a structure. The passages listed above refer to the pinnacle of the Temple.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The precise meaning of the Greek word \i pterugion\i* is uncertain. Some scholars have proposed “lintel” or “superstructure of the gate [of the Temple].” The Greek word translated “temple” (\i hieron\i*) in \s G04000400500034\s* and \s G04200400900020\s* refers to the whole area occupied by the sanctuary (see \l target="REALIA:3.14.1">3.14.1 Jewish Temple\l*), and the pinnacle (literally “small wing”) could designate a corner or extreme point. So some scholars have suggested that it refers to the southwest corner of the Herodian wall surrounding the Temple complex. It is less likely that the word refers to some top corner of the Temple building itself. Common-language translations often render it “very high point” or “highest part.”
\key 3.14.1.6
\title Curtain, veil, drape
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb פָּרֹכֶת
\trl paroketh
\ref H00202603100006 H00202603300010 H00202603300032 H00202603300048 H00202603500020 H00202702100016 H00203000600014 H00203501200024 H00203603500010 H00203802700034 H00203903400034 H00204000300030 H00204002200036 H00204002200036 H00204002600026 H00300400600044 H00300401700038 H00301600200046 H00301601200056 H00301601500040 H00302102300008 H00302400300008 H00400400500026 H00401800700040 H01400301400010
\grk καταπέτασμα
\trl katapetasma
\ref G04002705100008 G04101503800006 G04202304500014 G05800601900034 G05800900300010 G05801002000020 L07105000500018 L07700102200038 L07700405100020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0417_tabernacle_veil_en.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Veil|3.0\fig* The veil was a hanging cloth that covered the entrance to a room or served as a divider between two parts of a room. In the Tabernacle and in the Temple, it hung in front of the Most Holy Place and divided the Most Holy Place from the Holy Place, standing directly in front of the Covenant Box. Some scholars say the veil did not hang but was draped over the top of the enclosure in which the Covenant Box stood, forming a kind of pavilion. The veil was woven of three colors of wool and one of linen and was decorated with figures of winged creatures. It was a heavy cloth (post-biblical Jewish tradition saying it was as thick as the width of a man’s hand).
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line In addition to shielding the Most Holy Place from view, the veil served the same purpose for the Covenant Box when it was being moved. When the Tabernacle was dismantled, the veil was lowered from the front (or above) directly onto the Box, thus preventing anyone from seeing the Box even during the transitions.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i paroketh\i* literally means “partition.” In Jewish tradition it was identified with a special partition that separated a king from the people. Some languages may have a special word for such a partition.
\line The Hebrew word \i paroketh\i* and the Greek word \i katapetasma\i* in connection with the Temple have been traditionally rendered “veil” in English, but a literal corresponding word for “veil” in another language could be misleading since it might suggest something that merely covers the face. Even a corresponding word for “curtain” could be misleading since it might suggest something that covers a window. Frequently it is necessary to use some kind of descriptive equivalent, for example, “large piece of cloth hanging down from the ceiling” or “large piece of cloth covering the entrance.”
\line \s H00202603100006\s* provides a description of this object. The “veil” (\a RSV\a*; Hebrew \i paroketh\i*) was a “curtain” (\a GNT\a*), of course, but it is good to distinguish this from the “screen” (\a RSV\a*; Hebrew \i masak\i*) at the entrance to the Tabernacle, which was also a curtain (see \s H00202603600006\s* and \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.8">3.15.2.3.8 Screen, entrance curtain\l*). The word \i masak\i* has the primary meaning of covering something, or even hiding something, while \i paroketh\i* primarily means making a division and setting something apart. Some translations make no distinction between the two words (\a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*), but others have “curtain/screen” (\a NRSV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*, \a NJB\a*, \a REB\a*), “veil/curtain” (\a NAB\a*), “Veil/Screen” (Durham), “screen/covering” (\a TOT\a*), and even “curtain/veil” (\a Mft\a*). The \i paroketh\i*, however, was there to separate the Holy Place from the Most Holy Place (see \s H00202603300010\s*). So this information may be brought forward to this verse. This will indicate that it was a “screen” or “veil” to hide the contents of the Most Holy Place. In cultures where a “curtain” such as this is unknown, translators may say “holy [or, taboo] cloth.”
\line \s H00202603300010\s*: “And you shall hang the veil from the clasps” (\a RSV\a*) is literally “And you [singular] shall place the veil under the clasps.” “The clasps” refers to the gold clasps mentioned in 26.6, which held together the two large pieces of the inner linen layer of the Tabernacle. When this layer was placed over the framework according to the instructions, the row of clasps would be exactly ten cubits (4.5 meters, or 15 feet) from the west end. \a NAB\a* and \a NIV\a* suggest with \a RSV\a* that the veil was suspended from these clasps, but \a NRSV\a* has corrected this to “under the clasps.” This means “under the row of hooks in the roof of the Tent” (\a GNT\a*).
\key 3.14.1.7
\title Additional Temple features
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַתּוּק, אַתִּיק
\trl ’atuq, ’atiq
\ref H02604101500028 H02604101500028 H02604101600020 H02604200300038 H02604200300038 H02604200500018
\heb עָב
\trl ‘av
\ref H02604102500036 H02604102600042
\heb שְׂחִיף, עֵץ
\trl schif ‘ets
\ref H02604101600036
\heb מִגְרַעַת
\trl migra‘ah
\ref H01100600600058
\cont \u Description and translation:\u*
\line The meaning of the Hebrew word \i ’atuq\i*/\i ’atiq\i* in \s H02604101500028 H02604101600020 H02604200300038 H02604200500018\s* is unknown. Translations of this term vary widely as follows: “walls” (\a RSV\a*), “side rooms” (\a CEV\a*), “galleries” (\a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*), “ledges” (\a NJPSV\a*), and “corridors” (\a REB\a*).
\line The meaning of the Hebrew word \i ‘av\i* in \s H02604102500036 H02604102600042\s* is also unknown. The same word appears as some sort of architectural feature in \s H01100700601000\s*, where its meaning is equally obscure. Among a variety of renderings we find “covering” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*), “canopy” (\a RSV\a*), “overhang” (\a NIV\a*), and “lattice” (\a NJPSV\a*).
\line The Hebrew adjective \i schif\i* appears only in \s H02604101600020\s* and its meaning is unknown. From the description of Solomon’s Temple in \s H01100600600058\s* we learn that many things were made of wood and then overlaid with gold. Since it was difficult to overlay stone with gold, it was sometimes the practice to cover the stone first with a thin layer of wood paneling or veneer and then overlay the wood with gold. Even though there is no mention of gold overlay in Ezekiel’s description of the future Temple, it has been suggested that such a wood veneer covered the inner stone walls and was itself overlaid with gold. A translator should not, of course, introduce gold where none is mentioned. The phrase \i schif\i* \i ‘ets\i* has been rendered “paneled with wood” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*), “trimmed in wood” (\a CEV\a*), “covered with wood” (\a NIV\a*), “framed with wood” (\a REB\a*), and “overlaid with wood” (\a NJPSV\a*).
\line The Hebrew word \i migra‘ah\i* in \s H01100600600058\s* describes a structural device in Solomon’s Temple. Against the outer wall of the Temple building were built smaller rooms (see \i tsela‘\i* under \l target="REALIA:3.1.6">3.1.6 Room\l*). This meant that the outer wall of the Temple building formed one wall of these smaller rooms. One end of the crossbeams (mentioned in the Aramaic Targum but not in the text of 1 Kings; see \l target="REALIA:3.1.5.3">3.1.5.3 Crossbeam, rafter\l*) was set into the outer wall of the small room, while the other end had to take its support from the outer wall of the Temple. Rather than make a hole right through the Temple wall, they made a recess or niche (or narrow ledge) in which the end of the beam sat. This supporting feature is called a \i migra‘ah\i*. It has been rendered “offsets” (\a RSV\a*), “recesses” (\a NJPSV\a*), “ledges” (\a CEV\a*), or “offset ledges” (\a NIV\a*).
\key 3.14.1.8
\title Other features of the Temple treated elsewhere in this chapter
\cont Beams - \l target="REALIA:3.1.5.3">3.1.5.3 Crossbeam, rafter\l*
