0042 H00400404700046 H00400601000038 H00400601300030 H00400601800012 H00400700500020 H00400708900012 H00400800900016 H00400801500020 H00400801900046 H00400802200024 H00400802400040 H00400802600012 H00400901500030 H00400901700020 H00401000300024 H00401101600052 H00401102400050 H00401102600062 H00401200400032 H00401200500022 H00401201000016 H00401401000034 H00401601800032 H00401601900022 H00401700700030 H00401700800016 H00401701500016 H00401701900008 H00401702200022 H00401702300018 H00401800200046 H00401800300016 H00401800400016 H00401800400028 H00401800600044 H00401802100040 H00401802200016 H00401802300016 H00401803100034 H00401900400030 H00402000600024 H00402500600058 H00402700200044 H00403105400046 H00503101400034 H00503101400058 H00503101500012 H00503101500036 H00601800100024 H00601905100058 H00900202200050 H01000601700028 H01000700600050 H01100103900024 H01100202800042 H01100202900022 H01100203000010 H01100800400016 H01100800400038 H01300601700014 H01300901900050 H01300902100014 H01300902300028 H01301700500042 H01301700500046 H01302303200010 H01400100300036 H01400100600028 H01400101300028 H01400500500016 H01400500500038 H01402400600072 H01902700600022 H01907806000010
\heb הֵיכָל
\trl heykal
\ref H00900100900042 H00900300300020
\heb מִשְׁכָּן
\trl mishkan
\ref H00202500900020 H00202600100008 H00202600600040 H00202600700018 H00202601200036 H00202601300048 H00202601500016 H00202601700036 H00202601800016 H00202602000010 H00202602200010 H00202602300016 H00202602600022 H00202602700016 H00202602700036 H00202603000010 H00202603500042 H00202700900012 H00202701900010 H00203501100006 H00203501500054 H00203501800008 H00203600800024 H00203601300040 H00203601400018 H00203602000016 H00203602200036 H00203602300016 H00203602500010 H00203602700010 H00203602800016 H00203603100022 H00203603200016 H00203603200034 H00203802000014 H00203802100008 H00203802100010 H00203803100036 H00203903200010 H00203903300010 H00203904000056 H00204000200028 H00204000500044 H00204000600020 H00204000900022 H00204001700040 H00204001800012 H00204001900016 H00204002100016 H00204002200024 H00204002400030 H00204002800018 H00204002900016 H00204003300018 H00204003400028 H00204003500042 H00204003600018 H00204003800012 H00300801000024 H00301503100032 H00301700400030 H00400105000016 H00400105000048 H00400105000072 H00400105100010 H00400105100028 H00400105300014 H00400105300048 H00400300700040 H00400300800036 H00400302300012 H00400302500018 H00400302600028 H00400302900016 H00400303500028 H00400303600016 H00400303800014 H00400401600052 H00400402500012 H00400402600032 H00400403100026 H00400501700038 H00400700100022 H00400700300060 H00400901500014 H00400901500026 H00400901500050 H00400901800040 H00400901900016 H00400902000022 H00400902200026 H00401001100046 H00401001700008 H00401001700028 H00401002100024 H00401600900040 H00401702800014 H00401901300032 H00403103000074 H00403104700060 H00602201900032 H00602202900070 H01300601700012 H01300603300018 H01301603900024 H01302102900004 H01302302600022 H01400100500030 H01902600800014 H01907400700020 H01907806000006 H02603702700006
\heb מִקְדָּשׁ
\trl miqdash
\ref H00201501700024 H00202500800008 H00301200400038 H00301903000010 H00302000300054 H00302600200010 H00302101200008 H00302101200022 H00302102300040 H00400303800044 H00401002100014 H00401800100034 H00401902000040 H00602402600050
\heb קֹדֶשׁ
\trl qodesh
\ref H00203600100056 H00203600400024 H00203600600044 H00203802400026 H00203802400064 H00203802700024 H00301000400048 H00400302800036 H00400303100034 H00400303200030 H00400401200026 H00400401500020 H00400401500032 H00400401600064 H00400801900088 H00401800300026 H00401800500012
\grk ἅγιος
\trl hagia, hagion
\ref G05800800200004 G05800900100022 G05800900800012
\grk σκηνή
\trl skēnē
\ref G04400704400004 G05800800200012 G05800800500028 G05800900800032 G05800901100026 G05800902100006 G05801301000022 G06601500500020 L07000900800030 L07102401000004 L07102401500050 L07800200400016 L07800200500020
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0427_tabernacle.jpg|col||© Ruk7 (Wikimedia Commons)|Tabernacle with outer court|3.0\fig* The Tabernacle was a relatively large tent with a surrounding enclosed courtyard, used as a central place of worship by the Israelites prior to the building of the Temple.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew and Greek terms listed above can change in meaning depending on the context. The translator should pay careful attention to the context, which will generally indicate what meaning is in view. For example, the Hebrew word \i mishkan\i* may be used to indicate the entire Tabernacle complex (\s H00202500800008\s*) or the Tabernacle proper, that is, the tent in the courtyard which contained the Holy Place and the Most Holy Place (\s H00202600100008\s*). Similarly, the Hebrew word \i miqdash\i* sometimes means the Holy Place (\s H00302000300054\s*), sometimes the Most Holy Place (\s H00301603300008\s*), and sometimes the whole Tabernacle complex (\s H00202500800008\s*). \fig |WEB-0428_tabernacle_entrance.jpg|col||© Mboesch (Wikimedia Commons)|Reconstruction of tabernacle|3.0\fig*
\line The Hebrew word \i ’ohel\i*, which means “tent” (see \l target="REALIA:3.2">3.2 Tent\l*), can indicate the Tabernacle proper (\s H00202603600014\s*) or, as explained above (see \l target="REALIA:3.15">3.15 Tent of Meeting and Tabernacle\l*), the Tent of Meeting.
\line In some languages “Tabernacle” may be rendered “largest tent in which God lived,” “large tent for worshiping God,” or “holy tent.” In selecting a proper designation, it is important to indicate that the function of the Tabernacle was essentially the same as that of the Temple; there was only a difference of construction and not a difference of use or of religious relevance. Refer to the discussion at 3.14.1 “Jewish Temple.”
\line Osborn makes the following comments concerning the translation of “Tabernacle”: “A few recent translations have broken from the traditional rendering of ‘tabernacle’ and simply translate it as ‘Dwelling.’ \i The Translator’s Old Testament\i* (\a TOT\a*) uses the word ‘Shrine,’ which is perhaps a bit more appropriate for what was to become the wilderness dwelling of Yahweh. Either term, of course, could still refer to the tent within the enclosure or to the entire structure including the tent. Both terms suggest, however, something different from the more permanent Temple of Solomon, which seems to have influenced the priestly description of the tabernacle.”
\line \s H00203903200012 H00204000200030 H00204000600022 H00204002900018 H01300601700012\s*: The Hebrew in these verses combines the terms \i mishkan\i* and \i ’ohel mo‘ed\i*, which \a RSV\a* renders “the tabernacle of the tent of meeting.” In the three references in \s H00204000001000\s*, it is probable that \i mishkan\i* refers to the inner tent, made of the frames and four coverings, while \i ’ohel mo‘ed\i* refers to the entire Tabernacle complex. In \s H00203903200012\s* the two terms are used for the same thing, the second term explaining the first one. \a GNT\a* uses only one expression for both terms in this verse: “the Tent of the LORD’s presence.” \a NIV\a* is better with “the tabernacle, the Tent of Meeting.” Another way to express this is “the sacred tent, where the people met with the LORD.”
\line \s G05800800200004 G05800901100026 G06601500500020\s*: These verses speak about a sacred tent, using the same Greek word \i skēnē\i* that refers to the tent in the wilderness (for example, \s G05800800500028\s*). However, in these passages the text is speaking of a heavenly or spiritual counterpart (actually, original) of the physical tent. Where possible, the translation should keep the same word to render \i skēnē\i*, whether it refers to the physical tent or its heavenly counterpart.
\line The following is adapted from the comments in \i A Handbook on The Revelation to John\i* (pages 226-227) at \s G06601500500020\s*: There is some uncertainty concerning what is meant by the compound genitive “the temple of the tent of witness” (\a RSV\a*/\a NRSV\a*). This literal rendering is quite ambiguous, but the average reader probably understands it to mean that in the tent of witness there is a temple. There are three possible meanings for this expression: (1) “the tent of witness” and “the temple” refer to the same thing, so it may be rendered “the temple, that is, the Witness Tent” (so \a AT\a*, \a NJB\a*, \a SPCL\a*, \a NIV\a*); (2) “the Witness Tent in the Temple” (so \a GNT\a*, \a FRCL\a*, Brazilian common language version); (3) “the sanctuary in the Witness Tent” (so \i The Translator’s New Testament\i* [\a TNT\a*], \a REB\a*, Brc, Phillips [\a Phps\a*]). In favor of the last interpretation—which is the one that is recommended—is the fact that the word translated “temple” (\i naos\i* in Greek) is the special term for the inner sanctuary of the Temple, as contrasted with the Temple’s large worship area (\i hieron\i* in Greek). The inner sanctuary (in which the Covenant Box was kept) was separated by a heavy curtain from the worship area, in which were located the altar of incense and the table on which were placed daily the loaves of bread offered to God. This was also the design of the Tabernacle (see \s H00204000101000-H00204003301000\s*). It seems best, then, to translate here “the sanctuary [or, most holy place] that was in the Witness Tent” or “. . . that was in the Tabernacle.” A translation should use here and in \s G04400704400004\s* the name for Tabernacle most often used in the Old Testament.
\key 3.15.2.1
\title Holy Place
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb הֵיכָל
\trl heykal
\ref H01100601700022 H01100603300014 H01100705000074 H01400402200064 H01402901600040 H01600601000046 H01600601000056 H01600601100028 H01900500800020 H01901100400006 H01901800700026 H01913800200006 H02300600100044 H02600801600026 H02600801600058 H02604100100010 H02604100400028 H02604101500052 H02604102000036 H02604102100004 H02604102300012 H02604102500014 H02604200800036 H03200200500026 H03200200800026 H03300100200034 H03500202000008 H03900300100026
\heb קֹדֶשׁ
\trl qodesh
\ref H00202903000036 H00203001300030 H00203002400016 H00203101100026 H00203501900018 H00203600300038 H00203600400024 H00203600600044 H00203802400026 H00203802400064 H00203802500042 H00203802600022 H00203802700024 H00203900100038 H00203904100018 H00300400600048 H00300501500020 H00300602300030 H00301000400048 H00301001700020 H00301001800016 H00301001800030 H00301200400026 H00301401300040 H00301600200036 H00301600300014 H00301601600010 H00301601700030 H00301602000014 H00301602300038 H00301602700038 H00301603300012 H00302700300048 H00302702500016 H00400302800036 H00400303100034 H00400303200030 H00400304700024 H00400305000042 H00400401200026 H00400401500020 H00400401500032 H00400401600064 H00400701300036 H00400701900038 H00400702500034 H00400703100034 H00400703700034 H00400704300034 H00400704900034 H00400705500034 H00400706100034 H00400706700034 H00400707300034 H00400707900034 H00400708500052 H00400708600028 H00400801900088 H00401800500012 H00401801600030 H00402800700026 H01100800800024 H01100801000018 H01302303200022 H01302400500022 H01400501100018 H01402900500046 H01402900700042 H01403001900032 H01403500500010 H01500900800046 H01906000800008 H01906300300008 H01906801800022 H01906802500018 H01907400300022 H01910800800008 H01913400200006 H01915000100012 H02304302800008 H02306200900026 H02604102100016 H02604102300020 H02604201400020 H02604402700014 H02604402700034 H02604500200012 H02700801300054 H02700801400026 H02700902600036 H03900201100028
\grk ἅγιος
\trl hagia
\ref G05800900200042 G05800902400012 L07104502400016
\grk σκηνή
\trl skēnē
\ref G05800900200002 G05800900600018
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The Holy Place was the interior of the Jerusalem Temple or of the earlier Tabernacle. This interior contained two rooms, an outer one and an inner one. “Holy Place” may refer to either one of these rooms. Most often “Holy Place” refers to the larger room outside the veil, while the smaller room on its west end is called the “Most Holy Place” or “Holy of Holies” (see \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.2">3.15.2.2 Holy of Holies, Most Holy Place\l*). In the Tabernacle the Holy Place measured 10 by 20 cubits (5 by 10 meters; 16.5 by 33 feet), while in the Temple it was 20 cubits by 40 cubits (10 by 20 meters; 33 by 66 feet).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages the outer room of the sanctuary may be referred to simply as “the first room of the Tabernacle/Temple” or “the first holy room of the Tabernacle/Temple.” “Holy Place” may also be rendered “taboo place [or, room]” or possibly “restricted place,” meaning that only the priests could enter it.
\line There may be complications in speaking of the first part of the sanctuary as being the Holy Place, since in some languages the word “place” only indicates a location and not an enclosure. Therefore “the Holy Place” must be rendered in these languages as “the Holy Room.” Other possible renderings are “the Place/Room where God is [present]” and “the Place/Room of God.” In \s H00302000301000\s* \a CEV\a* has “the place where I [the LORD] am worshiped.”
\line \s H00302102301000\s*: The use of the plural “my sanctuaries” (\a RSV\a*) here is surprising and troubling to scholars. Some have suggested that it is evidence of a time when there were several shrines where the Israelites worshiped, but others see it as a reference to “my sanctuary and all its contents” (so \a TOB\a*). This interpretation is essentially the one followed by \a NJB\a* and \a NAB\a* as well as \a GNT\a*, and should be adopted in the receptor language. A literal rendering of “my sanctuaries” would be misleading, and the singular “my sanctuary” (\a NIV\a*, \a LB\a*) does not accurately reflect the text.
\line \s G05800900101000-G05800900201000\s*: “Sanctuary” (\a RSV\a*) in verse 1 is literally “holy place” (\i hagion\i* in Greek). Here it refers to the entire place of worship. It is also called a “tent” (\a RSV\a*; \i skēnē\i* in Greek) in \s G05800800201000\s*. A different Greek word (\i hagia\i*) is used for the Holy Place in 9.2 (literally “holy places”), which is the outer part of the sanctuary. The text is, however, complicated by the fact that the same Greek word for “tent” is used to describe the whole building (8.2), the Holy Place (9.2), and the Most Holy Place (9.3). \a GECL\a* solves the problem by beginning 9.2 with “There was a tent set up with two rooms.” \a NJB\a* is similar: “There was a tent which comprised two compartments.” The writer was not interested in the details of any particular sanctuary, but the details that he does give are consistent with a general picture of a large room divided into two parts by a curtain.
\key 3.15.2.2
\title Holy of Holies, Most Holy Place
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בַּיִת, כַּפֹּרֶת
\trl beyth hakaporeth
\ref H01302801100026
\heb דְּבִיר
\trl dvir
\ref H00601000300044 H00601003800016 H00601003900066 H00601102100040 H00601201300004 H00601500700010 H00601501500014 H00601501500020 H00601504900012 H00602101500018 H00700101100014 H00700101100020 H01100600500042 H01100601600052 H01100601900004 H01100602000010 H01100602100040 H01100602200040 H01100602300010 H01100603100010 H01100704900030 H01100800600024 H01100800800032 H01300604300016 H01400301600012 H01400402000030 H01400500700024 H01400500900032 H01902800200022
\heb מִקְדָּשׁ
\trl miqdash
\ref H00301603300008 H02604500300044
\heb פְּנִימָה, פְּנִימִי
\trl pnimah, pnimi
\ref H02604100300008 H02604101700022 H02604101700050
\heb קֹדֶשׁ
\trl qodesh
\ref H00301600300014 H00301601700030 H00301602000014 H00301602300038 H00301602700038 H00301603300012 H02604102100016 H02604102300020
\heb קֹדֶשׁ
\trl qodesh haqodashim
\ref H00202603300056 H00202603400022 H01100601600058 H01100705000056 H01100800600032 H01300603400036 H01400300800010 H01400301000010 H01400402200046 H01400500700032 H02604100400038
\grk ἅγιος
\trl hagia
\ref G05800900800012 G05800901200032 G05800902500024 G05801001900018 G05801301100022
\grk ἅγιος
\trl hagia hagiōn
\ref G05800900300018
\grk ναός
\trl naos
\ref G06601500500016 L07900101000024
\grk οἶκος, καταπέτασμα
\trl oikos katapetasmatos
\ref L07105000500016
\grk σκηνή
\trl skēnē
\ref G05800900300012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The Holy of Holies was a cubical room at the west end of the Tabernacle proper and the Temple. In the Tabernacle it measured 10 cubits (5 meters; 16.5 feet) in each direction; in the Temple the dimensions were doubled.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Holy of Holies” is a literal translation of the Hebrew expression meaning “most holy of all holy things.” The literal phrase will not be meaningful to most readers. It may be rendered “Most Holy Place” (\a GNT\a*), “second holy room of the Tabernacle/Temple,” or “interior holy room of the Tabernacle/Temple.” What is important here is the degree of holiness, not so much the actual location within the Tabernacle/Temple. It is for this reason that many translators say “most sacred place,” “very, very sacred room,” or “Place/Room that is surpassingly sacred.” In this type of context the term “sacred” may be rendered “dedicated especially to God” or “consecrated to God,” so other possible models for “Holy of Holies” are “room that belongs to God more than any other place” or “room that has been dedicated to God more than any other room.” Another possibility is “Place/Room inside/within the Place where God is.” See also the comments at \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.1">3.15.2.1 Holy Place\l*.
\line The inner room of the sanctuary could also be referred to as “within (or, behind) the curtain” (\s H00301600200046 H00301601200056 H00301601500040 H00401800700040 G05800601900034\s*; see \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.6">3.14.1.6 Curtain, veil, drape\l*).
\key 3.15.2.3
\title Tabernacle construction
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.1">3.15.2.3.1 Frames, boards\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.2">3.15.2.3.2 Base, stand, socket, mortise\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.3">3.15.2.3.3 Upright beam, tenon, crosspiece, rung\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.4">3.15.2.3.4 Ring\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.5">3.15.2.3.5 Bar, pole\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6">3.15.2.3.6 Coverings\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.7">3.15.2.3.7 Posts from which curtains were hung in and around the Tabernacle\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.8">3.15.2.3.8 Screen, entrance curtain\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.9">3.15.2.3.9 Hangings, perimeter curtain\l*
\cont Attempted depictions of the structure of the Tabernacle vary rather widely. Like the dwellings of desert nomads, it was a temporary structure, easy to assemble and disassemble, easy to transport. There is a lot of difficulty in determining the precise meaning of much of the terminology used to describe the construction. The general description that follows reflects the opinion of most scholars, and it should be sufficient to assist the translator in his task. The individual parts will be described separately.
\line The Tabernacle complex consisted of two main structures. There was an outer wall made of poles and curtains. This defined the borders of the courtyard. Entry into the courtyard was through an opening in the eastern side of the outer wall. The Hebrew word \i mishkan\i* is sometimes used to indicate the entire complex. More often, however, it means the second structure, the large tent that stood inside the enclosed complex. It is for this latter structure that we use the word Tabernacle here.
\line The Tabernacle was basically a tent spread over a framework. The framework was made of a series of individual frames that were joined together. A frame was made of five pieces of acacia wood. Two long uprights were joined at the top, the middle, and near the bottom by crosspieces or rungs. The ends of the uprights extended below the bottom rung. These two extensions, technically called tenons, fit into corresponding holes in a heavy silver base, which was the same width as the frame. The frames on their bases were set side-by-side, forming a wall. This frame wall was then made stable by inserting bars through three lines of rings that were attached to the frames. There were three such frame walls; the east side had no wall but only an entrance of curtains hung from poles.
\line The top and sides of the Tabernacle were covered by four layers of different materials. The inner layer, which would have been visible on the inside above and through the openings in the frames, was made of embroidered linen (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen\l* and \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.11">1.5.3.11 Embroidered cloth, needlework\l*). This layer stretched out over the top of the frame from one side to the other. In this way it formed the ceiling and hung down on both sides to within about 50 centimeters (20 inches) of the ground. Over top of the entire structure were spread three layers intended to protect the frames, the linen curtains, and the implements inside the Tabernacle. While the outer layers were not decorated (except that one was dyed red) and would not have been particularly attractive, they were chosen for their ability to protect against rain, even the relatively small amounts that fall in the Sinai region. Spreading the four layers over the top had the effect of giving the Tabernacle a flat roof, not sloped, and thus it would have resembled a box. The outer layers were longer than the linen layer and hung down to the ground. One end was left open as an entrance.
\line A number of the objects for the Tabernacle were constructed according to the same basic pattern. For example, the top coverings of the sanctuary were made of two pieces and joined together with a system of hooks and rings. Similarly, the curtain in front of the Most Holy Place was hung on hooks by means of rings sewn into the fabric, and the same method was used to hang the curtains that formed the outer boundary of the courtyard as well as the curtain that closed the entrance to the Holy Place. All of these curtains were held up in the same basic way, by wooden posts that stood in heavy metal bases. Once a translator has determined the proper words to use for ring, hook, post, base, and curtain, the same words should be employed throughout.
\line Several of the items in the Tabernacle were made of acacia wood (\i shitah\i* in Hebrew).
\line Even in languages where there is no particular difficulty in translating the individual parts of the Tabernacle, it will be good to include some kind of illustration or diagram.
\key 3.15.2.3.1
\title Frames, boards
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קֶרֶשׁ
\trl qeresh
\ref H00202601500010 H00202601600010 H00202601600028 H00202601700010 H00202601700032 H00202601800010 H00202601800020 H00202601900018 H00202601900028 H00202601900050 H00202602000024 H00202602100018 H00202602100034 H00202602200018 H00202602300006 H00202602500008 H00202602500030 H00202602500046 H00202602600016 H00202602700010 H00202602700030 H00202602800018 H00202602900008 H00203501100026 H00203602000010 H00203602100010 H00203602100028 H00203602200010 H00203602200032 H00203602300010 H00203602300020 H00203602400018 H00203602400028 H00203602400050 H00203602500026 H00203602600018 H00203602600034 H00203602700018 H00203602800006 H00203603000008 H00203603000034 H00203603100016 H00203603200010 H00203603200030 H00203603300026 H00203603400008 H00203903300032 H00204001800028 H00400303600012 H00400403100022 H02602700600012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0021_tabernacle_frame_and_base_en.png|col||Howard Hatton © United Bible Societies|Tabernacle frame and base|3.0\fig* These parts of the Tabernacle have traditionally been understood as solid pieces of wood. It is more likely—and commonly accepted now—that they were wooden frames as described above. Each frame was 5 meters (16.5 feet) high and 75 centimeters (30 inches) wide. There were twenty such frames along the north and south sides of the Tabernacle and six along the back (west) side plus two corner frames, bringing the total on the back to eight (\s H00202602501000\s*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Most reconstructions of the Tabernacle show walls made of solid pieces of wood. Some scholars have even thought these walls were as much as 50 centimeters (20 inches) thick. This seems unlikely, however, in light of the difficulties of (1) finding such large pieces of wood and (2) transporting their weight. A suggestion that is now generally accepted is that the Hebrew word \i qeresh\i* indicates a kind of “frame” made of wood. The outer dimensions would be the same, but such frames would be lighter, they would make the structure cooler, and they would allow the embroidered inner curtain to be seen on the inside. This suggestion is now included in most modern translations and is recommended here. See Hatton’s article, entitled “The Projections on the Frames of the Tabernacle.” Hatton (page 209) translates \s H00202601601000 H00202601701000 H00202601801000 H00202601901000\s* as follows: “\t 16\t* Each frame is to be 15 feet high and 27 inches wide, \t 17\t* with two matching arms that are joined together by rungs. All the frames have these arms. \t 18\t* Make 20 frames for the south side, \t 19\t* and 40 silver bases to go under them, two bases under each frame to hold its two arms.” \fig |UBS-0022_tabernacle_frame.png|col||Howard Hatton © United Bible Societies|Tabernacle frame|3.0\fig*
\key 3.15.2.3.2
\title Base, stand, socket, mortise
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֶדֶן
\trl ’eden
\ref H00202601900006 H00202601900022 H00202601900044 H00202602100006 H00202602100012 H00202602100028 H00202602500012 H00202602500020 H00202602500024 H00202602500040 H00202603200028 H00202603700038 H00202701000010 H00202701100036 H00202701200028 H00202701400024 H00202701500026 H00202701600046 H00202701700022 H00202701800040 H00203501100042 H00203501700018 H00203602400006 H00203602400022 H00203602400044 H00203602600006 H00203602600012 H00203602600028 H00203603000012 H00203603000020 H00203603000024 H00203603000028 H00203603600032 H00203603800030 H00203801000008 H00203801100024 H00203801200026 H00203801400022 H00203801500046 H00203801700006 H00203801900010 H00203802700020 H00203802700030 H00203802700038 H00203802700054 H00203803000010 H00203803100006 H00203803100018 H00203903300044 H00203904000018 H00204001800020 H00400303600028 H00400303700014 H00400403100038 H00400403200014 H01803800600006 H02200501500012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The frames that made up the wall of the Tabernacle, as well as the posts that surrounded its court, stood in recessed metal bases, or mortises, which provided them with stability. The bases for the Tabernacle frames were made of silver, while those for the outer court were made of bronze.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The fact that there were forty bases for each side wall of the Tabernacle (\s H00202601901000 H00202602001000 H00202602101000\s*) means that there was one base for each tenon, or “two bases under one frame for its two tenons” (\a RSV\a*). The repeated phrase, “two bases under another frame for its two tenons” (\a RSV\a*), simply means that there were to be “two bases under each frame to hold its two projections” (\a GNT\a*).
\key 3.15.2.3.3
\title Upright beam, tenon, crosspiece, rung
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Upright beam/arm\b*:
\heb יָד
\trl yadoth
\ref H00202601700004 H00202601900038 H00202601900060 H00203602200004 H00203602400038 H00203602400060
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Crosspiece/rung\b*:
\heb שׁלב
\trl mshulavoth
\ref H00202601700016 H00203602200016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The individual frames were set into heavy metal bases (see \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.2">3.15.2.3.2 Base, stand, socket, mortise\l*). Each frame was made of two wooden uprights that were each 5 meters (16.5 feet) long. These uprights were joined at the top, middle, and near the bottom by wooden rungs. Part of each upright extended below the last rung, forming a kind of leg. The two legs (technically known as tenons) were placed into corresponding holes in the metal bases.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Traditionally the Hebrew word \i yadoth\i*, which is literally “hands,” has been understood in the passages listed above to refer to small projections on the side of the frame that fit into holes in the neighboring frame to hold the wall together and stabilize it. However, there are a number of difficulties with this interpretation. It is more consistent to see the \i yadoth\i* as referring to the long, vertical side boards from which the frame was constructed. These were connected by crosspieces, or “rungs,” as described above. These crosspieces are referred to by the Hebrew word \i mshulavoth\i*. \i A Handbook on Exodus\i* suggests the following rendering for \s H00202601501000 H00202601601000 H00202601701000\s*: “15 Build upright frames for the sacred tent out of acacia wood. 16 Each frame is to be fifteen feet high and twenty-seven inches wide, 17 with two matching arms that are joined together by cross-pieces. All the frames have these cross-pieces” (page 620).
\key 3.15.2.3.4
\title Ring
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb טַבַּעַת
\trl taba‘ath
\ref H00202602400030 H00202602900018 H00203602900030 H00203603400018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0429_tabernacle_ring.jpg|col||© Mboesch (Wikimedia Commons)|Poles in rings|3.0\fig* The frame walls of the Tabernacle were held together by a system of horizontal poles that were placed through rings attached to the individual frames. These rings were made of gold.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00202602400030\s*: “At the first ring” (\a RSV\a*) is literally “unto the one [or, first] ring.” It may also be rendered “into a single ring” (\a NIV\a*, \a REB\a*; similarly Durham). \a NJPSV\a* has “inside one ring.” Nothing has been mentioned earlier in the text about rings for the framework, but \s H00202602900018\s* mentions gold rings that are evidently to be placed along the individual frames for holding the crossbars. “The first ring” may therefore be the one at “the top.” In verse 24 \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a*, for some reason, omit any reference to the “ring.” This may be because referring to the ring here doesn’t appear to make sense. However, if this is a ring for a crossbar (see verse 29), we may translate 26.24b as “and [or, but] joined at the top near the first gold ring for holding a crossbar.”
\key 3.15.2.3.5
\title Bar, pole
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בְּרִיחַ
\trl briach
\ref H00202602600006 H00202602700006 H00202602700026 H00202602800006 H00202602900030 H00202602900040 H00203501100032 H00203603100006 H00203603200006 H00203603200026 H00203603300010 H00203603400030 H00203603400040 H00203903300034 H00203903300036 H00204001800036 H00400303600020 H00400403100030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Bars or poles made of acacia wood were passed through rings attached to the frames. The dimensions of these poles are not given, although \s H00202602800006\s* says that the center pole ran the entire length of the Tabernacle wall, that is, 30 cubits (15 meters; 50 feet) for the side walls and 10 cubits (5 meters; 16.5 feet) for the back wall. There were five such crossbars along each of the three walls (see the discussion below), and they were overlaid with gold. See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.4">3.15.2.3.4 Ring\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00202602800006\s* states that the middle or “center crossbar” (\a CEV\a*) passed through the rings “from end to end” (\a RSV\a*). As noted above, this means that it extended the length of the wall. The length of the other four crossbars is not stated. It is commonly thought that there were only three lines of rings. If this were so, it would mean that the other four crossbars were each half the length of the middle crossbar and ran half the length of the wall. This information will probably not be reflected in translation, but it may be useful to include it in a footnote or illustration.
\key 3.15.2.3.6
\title Coverings
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6.1">3.15.2.3.6.1 Linen cloth strips\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6.2">3.15.2.3.6.2 Loops and hooks\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6.3">3.15.2.3.6.3 Goat hair cloth strips\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6.4">3.15.2.3.6.4 Outer coverings for the Tabernacle\l*
\line \fig |UBS-0023_tabernacle_covering.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Layers of coverings on the Tabernacle|3.0\fig*
\key 3.15.2.3.6.1
\title Linen cloth strips
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יְרִיעָה, שֵׁשׁ, שׁזר
\trl yri‘ah (shesh mashzar)
\ref H00202600100014 H00202600200006 H00202600200038 H00202600200054 H00202600300006 H00202600300022 H00202600400016 H00202600400044 H00202600500012 H00202600500032 H00202600600020 H00203600800028 H00203600900006 H00203600900038 H00203600900054 H00203601000012 H00203601000024 H00203601100016 H00203601100042 H00203601200012 H00203601200032 H00203601300020 H00400402500008 H01000700200048 H01301700100056
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0430_tabernacle_covering.jpg|col||© Ori229 (Wikimedia Commons)|The tabernacle's inside covering of linen strips|3.0\fig* Ten broad cloth strips were joined together to form a large kind of tent-cloth or tarp that was draped over the top, sides, and back of the Tabernacle. The size of the individual cloth strips is given in the Exodus references above. They were made of linen (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen>\l*) and were decorated with figures of cherubim (see \l target="REALIA:4.1.2">4.1.2 Winged creatures, cherubim\l*). Five such pieces were sewn together, forming one large cloth. The two cloths formed in this way were then joined to each other in the middle by a system of hooks and eyes (or, clasps and loops), making the whole into one large cloth.
\line The reason for dividing the total cloth into two parts was probably to make it easier to transport.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i yri‘ah\i* always refers to tent fabric or material used in making tents. Tents were usually made from goats’ hair (see \l target="REALIA:3.2">3.2 Tent\l*), but according to \s H00202600100014\s*, this first layer of the Tabernacle was made of “fine twined linen” (\a RSV\a*). \a NRSV\a* has “fine twisted linen,” since the Hebrew word for “twined” refers to twisting the thread in spinning.
\line The description of how the strips of cloth were decorated in \s H00202600100014\s* leaves open the question of whether the figures of cherubim were woven into the cloth or embroidered on it. The older Jewish commentators understood the figures to have been an integral part of the weaving of the strips (compare \a NJPSV\a* “with a design of cherubim worked into them” and \i God’s Word\i* [\a GW\a*] “and creatively work an angel design into the fabric”). Most translations, however, prefer using the word “embroider” here (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a GECL\a*; see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.11">1.5.3.11 Embroidered cloth, needlework\l*). Some translations find ways to describe the decoration without determining the method by which it was put on the cloth; for example, \a ITCL\a* has “you will decorate them with figures of cherubim.”
\key 3.15.2.3.6.2
\title Loops and hooks
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Loops\b*:
\heb לוּלָאָה
\trl lula’ot
\ref H00202600400006 H00202600500004 H00202600500022 H00202600500050 H00202601000008 H00202601000036 H00202601100026 H00203601100006 H00203601200004 H00203601200022 H00203601200050 H00203601700006 H00203601700032
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Hooks\b*:
\heb קֶרֶס
\trl qrasim
\ref H00202600600008 H00202600600032 H00202601100006 H00202601100020 H00202603300016 H00203501100020 H00203601300008 H00203601300032 H00203601800006 H00203903300030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0431_hook_loops_en.jpg|col||Source unknown|Hooks and loops|3.0\fig* The two larger pieces of cloth (see \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6.1">3.15.2.3.6.1 Linen cloth strips\l* and \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6.3">3.15.2.3.6.3 Goat hair cloth strips\l*) were joined in the middle with a system of loops and hooks. Loops made of cord were sewn at intervals along one edge of one of the large pieces of cloth. Along the edge of the second large piece of cloth, metal hooks were attached so that they were exactly opposite the loops on the first piece of cloth. When the hooks were inserted into the loops, the two pieces became one large cloth. This system was used for both the linen curtain and the goat hair curtain.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word for “loops” suggests a “U-shaped” doubling of the blue yarn with both ends of the “U” sewn to the edge of the linen strip, leaving an opening just large enough for a gold clasp to pass through it. In some languages it will be necessary to make the action of “sewing” explicit in \s H00202600400006\s* by saying “Make loops out of blue cloth and sew them to the outside piece in each set” or “Use blue cloth and make loops . . . .” In some languages “loops” will be rendered “ears” or some similar object.
\line The Hebrew word for “hooks” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*) can also mean “clasps” (\a RSV\a*) or “fasteners” (\a REB\a*). It is derived from the verb meaning “to bend over.” They were possibly S-shaped.
\key 3.15.2.3.6.3
\title Goat hair cloth strips
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יְרִיעָה, עֵז
\trl yri‘ah (‘ez)
\ref H00202600700006 H00202600700008 H00202600800006 H00202600800034 H00202600800050 H00202600900012 H00202600900026 H00202600900040 H00202601000016 H00202601000044 H00202601200012 H00202601200022 H00202601300032 H00203601400006 H00203601400008 H00203601500006 H00203601500030 H00203601500046 H00203601600012 H00203601600026 H00203601700016 H00203601700042
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line See the description of the linen cloth strips in \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6.1">3.15.2.3.6.1 Linen cloth strips\l*. On top of the linen cover was laid another cover, constructed in the same manner, made of goat hair. Like the linen cloth, the goat hair cloth was also made of individual strips sewn together. It was formed of a total of eleven such strips, as compared to the ten in the linen cloth.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00202600700006\s* calls the whole second layer a “tent.” Some translations have the literal phrase “tent over the tabernacle” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a REB\a*). This might give the impression that there was a tent standing on the roof of the Tabernacle. It is better to follow \a GNT\a* for the whole verse: “Make a cover for the Tent out of eleven pieces of cloth made of goats’ hair.” Also good is \a NCV\a* “Then make another tent that will cover the Holy Tent, using eleven curtains made from goat hair.”
\line Cloth made of goat hair is commonly used by nomadic groups in the Middle East for making tents (see \l target="REALIA:3.2">3.2 Tent\l*). As soon as it gets wet, the hairs swell and seal the cloth tight so that no water drips through. Where goats are unknown, it may be necessary to say “cloth made of hair from an animal called goat” or “cloth made from domestic animal hair.”
\line The word “curtain,” which appears in many translations in the passages listed above, is somewhat misleading, since these goat hair cloth strips covered both the top and the sides of the Tabernacle.
\key 3.15.2.3.6.4
\title Outer coverings for the Tabernacle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִכְסֶה
\trl mikseh
\ref H00202601400006 H00202601400022 H00203501100016 H00203601900006 H00203601900022 H00203903400006 H00203903400022 H00204001900024 H00400302500026 H00400402500022 H00400402500026
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0418_tabernacle_outertent_en.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Outer cover and ropes of the tabernacle|3.0\fig* Above the two inner layers that covered the Tabernacle there were two more layers. They are mentioned only briefly and not really described. We are not sure if they only covered the top of the Tabernacle or hung down to the ground on the sides like the goat hair cloth. These two covers were made of two different animal skins. The first layer was made of rams’ skins dyed red (or, tanned rams’ skins; see \l target="REALIA:1.13">1.13 Leather\l*). The second layer was made of the skin of a sea mammal.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0432_dugong.jpg|col||© Julien Willem (Wikimedia Commons)|Sea cow/dugong|3.0\fig* \s H00202601400006\s*: The name of the mammal from which the outermost cover was made presents a difficulty for the translator. Translations include the skins of the “badger” (\a KJV\a*), “seal,” and “dugong” (\a REB\a*), or the somewhat more inclusive “sea cow” (\a NIV\a*), “dolphin” (\a NJPSV\a*), “porpoise” (\a NEB\a*), and “goat” (\a RSV\a*). Most of these possibilities indicate a skin that was rare and thus very special. Perhaps for this reason, the trend among more recent common-language translations is to render the Hebrew word \i tachash\i* as “fine leather” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a NCV\a*, \a NJB\a*) without specifying which animal it came from. If a language must specify what animal the skin came from, then “sea cow” or “porpoise” would be best.
\key 3.15.2.3.7
\title Posts from which curtains were hung in and around the Tabernacle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb עַמּוּד
\trl ‘amud
\ref H00201302100016 H00201302100034 H00201302200006 H00201302200016 H00201401900036 H00201402400028 H00202603200012 H00202603700014 H00202701000004 H00202701000020 H00202701100026 H00202701100030 H00202701100046 H00202701200022 H00202701400018 H00202701500020 H00202701600040 H00202701700004 H00203300900018 H00203301000014 H00203501100034 H00203501700012 H00203603600010 H00203603800006 H00203801000002 H00203801000018 H00203801100018 H00203801100034 H00203801200020 H00203801200034 H00203801400016 H00203801500040 H00203801700012 H00203801700020 H00203801700046 H00203801900004 H00203802800034 H00203903300040 H00203904000012 H00204001800044 H00400303600024 H00400303700004 H00400403100034 H00400403200004 H00401200500010 H00401401400064 H00401401400082 H00503101500016 H00503101500024 H00701602500070 H00701602600038 H00701602900012 H00702004000020 H01100700200044 H01100700200058 H01100700300028 H01100700600010 H01100700200058 H01100701500012 H01100701500026 H01100701500048 H01100701600020 H01100701700028 H01100701800010 H01100701900014 H01100702000012 H01100702100010 H01100702100028 H01100702100052 H01100702200010 H01100702200024 H01100704100002 H01100704100022 H01100704100056 H01100704200060 H01201101400020 H01202300300014 H01202501300006 H01202501600004 H01202501700012 H01202501700038 H01301800800048 H01400301500014 H01400301600024 H01400301700010 H01400401200002 H01400401200024 H01400401200058 H01400401300060 H01402301300018 H01600901200006 H01600901200018 H01600901900026 H01600901900058 H01700100600030 H01800900600014 H01802601100002 H01907500400016 H01909900700004 H02000900100010 H02200301000002 H02200501500004 H02400101800024 H02402701900016 H02405201700006 H02405202000004 H02405202100006 H02405202100020 H02405202200058 H02604004900038 H02604200600014 H02604200600018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0433_tabernacle_entrance.jpg|col||© Mboesch (Wikimedia Commons)|Posts at the tabernacle entrance|3.0\fig* The Holy Place was divided from the Most Holy Place by means of a hanging curtain (see \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.6">3.14.1.6 Curtain, veil, drape\l*). The curtain was hung from four vertical posts or poles that stood in silver stands. At the top of the curtain there were four rings or clasps. Each of these rings was fitted over a hook at the top of each of the poles in order to hang the curtain. The poles were overlaid with gold, and the hooks were made of gold.
\line The same construction was used for the hanging of the curtain that covered the entrance of the Tabernacle and for the curtains that made the outer wall of the courtyard.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The posts from which the veil and the entrance curtain were hung were made of acacia wood (\s H00202603200012 H00202603700014\s*). The text does not state the material from which the posts of the courtyard perimeter were made, but they were presumably also of wood. Where a language requires that the material be named, this information may be added.
\line \a CEV\a*’s restructuring of \s H00202603201000 H00202603301000\s*a gives a clear picture: “Cover four acacia wood posts with gold and set them each on a silver stand. Then fasten gold hooks to the posts and hang the curtain there.”
\line The words that are used to translate the different objects in \s H00202603201000\s* should be used also for the same objects in \s H00202603701000\s*.
\key 3.15.2.3.8
\title Screen, entrance curtain
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מָסָךְ
\trl masak
\ref H00202603600006 H00202603700010 H00202701600012 H00203501500042 H00203501700024 H00203603700006 H00203801800004 H00203903800036 H00203904000026 H00204000500034 H00204000800020 H00204002800008 H00204003300034 H00400302500030 H00400302600014 H00400402500046 H00400402600016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0419_posts_entrycurtain_en.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Posts and entry curtain|3.0\fig* The screen was a large hanging curtain that was suspended from five posts. It served as a kind of door to the Tabernacle, almost like a tent flap. Its purpose was to block from public view the activities that went on inside the Tabernacle. See the description at \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.7">3.15.2.3.7 Posts from which curtains were hung in and around the Tabernacle\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i masak\i* is used for the hanging at the entrance to the Holy Place and also for the curtain that hung at the entrance to the outer courtyard of the Tabernacle complex.
\key 3.15.2.3.9
\title Hangings, perimeter curtain
\index \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.9.1">3.15.2.3.9.1 Band, ring, rod\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קֶלַע
\trl qela‘
\ref H00202700900022 H00202701100018 H00202701200016 H00202701400010 H00202701500018 H00203501700004 H00203800900020 H00203801200010 H00203801400002 H00203801500032 H00203801600004 H00203801800058 H00203904000004 H00400302600004 H00400402600006 H00901704000058 H00901705000018 H00902502900064 H01100603400030 H01402601400042 H01804102000020 H03800901500020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0420_tabernacle_perimeter_en.png|col||Louise Bass, © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Perimeter curtain|3.0\fig* The system of posts with rings at the top (as described in 3.15.2.3.7 above) was also used to suspend curtains or hangings that formed the perimeter of the Tabernacle courtyard. The hangings were made of linen (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen\l*). Their dimensions are given in \s H00202700901000-H00202701901000\s* and \s H00203800901000-H00203802001000\s*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word for “hangings” in \s H00202700900022\s* is different from the word for “curtains” in \s H00202600100014\s* (see \l target="REALIA:3.15.2.3.6.1">3.15.2.3.6.1 Linen cloth strips\l*) and may suggest a different kind of weaving. Many English translations have “hangings” (\a RSV\a*, \a REB\a*), one has “draperies,” and both \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a* say “curtains.” In many languages this will be rendered “large pieces of [linen] cloth.”
\key 3.15.2.3.9.1
\title Band, ring, rod
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חשׁק, חָשׁוּק
\trl chashaq (verb), chashuq
\ref H00103400800018 H00202701000024 H00202701100050 H00202701700012 H00203603800024 H00203801000022 H00203801100038 H00203801200038 H00203801700040 H00203801700040 H00203801900028 H00203802800044 H00500700700016 H00501001500008 H00502101100020 H01100901900052 H01400800600062 H01909101400006 H02303801700018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The exact function of these bands overlaid with silver is not clear. In fact, the text does not even state how many there were on each perimeter post nor where exactly they were placed. They may have been simply decorative, or they may also have served to strengthen the wooden posts and keep them from splitting. It has also been suggested that the cloth covers could be attached to them so that they would not billow out in the wind. One commentator suggests that the Hebrew word \i chashuq\i* refers to a kind of cable wound around a post from top to bottom.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where possible, it is advisable to select a general word for “band.”
\line \s H00202701700012\s*: Here the text uses the verb form of the Hebrew noun \i chashuq\i* in verse 10, and it can mean either “banded” (\a NRSV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*) or “connected” (\a GNT\a*, \a NJB\a*). The idea of “banded” suggests that each of the posts had its own band that encircled the top of the post. The idea of “connected” suggests that the posts were joined to one another “with silver rods” (\a GNT\a*). Another way to express this in the first part of this verse is “They are to connect all the posts around the courtyard with silver rods” or “They must use silver rods to connect all the posts around the courtyard.”
\line If the interpretation of \a GNT\a* and \a NJB\a* is followed, this means there were connecting “rods” that gave support to the posts, and the curtains could have been hung from these rods. The veil and the screen of the Tabernacle, however, were evidently hung from the posts, which had their own hooks (see \s H00202603200020\s*, \s H00202603700026\s*). Most translations therefore follow the other interpretation and consider these to be “bands” (\a NIV\a*, \a TOT\a*) at the top of each of the posts.
\line Tent peg, stake: See \l target="REALIA:3.2.2">3.2.2 Tent peg, stake\l*.
\key 3.16
\title Booth, tabernacle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סֹךְ, סֻכָּה
\trl sok, sukah
\ref H00103301700026 H00302303400040 H00302304200006 H00302304200030 H00302304300014 H00501601300006 H00501601600062 H00503101000038 H01001101100030 H01002201200010 H01102001200038 H01102001600024 H01400801300082 H01500300400012 H01600801400038 H01600801500076 H01600801600020 H01600801700022 H01600801700032 H01802701800016 H01803602900014 H01803804000018 H01901000900016 H01901801200010 H01902700500008 H01903102100020 H01907600300010 H02300100800012 H02300400600004 H02402503800010 H03000901100016 H03200400500036 H03801401600066 H03801401800060 H03801401900036
\grk σκηνή
\trl skēnē
\ref G04001700400038 G04100900500034 G04200903300046 G04401501600014 L07801000600032
\grk σκήνωμα
\trl skēnōma
\ref L07801000600014
\grk σκηνοπηγία
\trl skēnopēgia
\ref G04300700200018 L07701002100032 L07800100900016 L07800101800042 L08100505000010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0434_shelter.jpg|col||© Ori229 (Wikimedia Commons)|Temporary dwelling (sukkah)|3.0\fig* The booth was a small, temporary dwelling usually made of natural materials such as leafy branches, reeds, or grass. While it had no fixed size or shape, it was probably only large enough for a family to sleep in.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Many languages will have no common word for such a temporary dwelling. In English the words “tabernacle” and “booth,” used by older translations, are likely to be misunderstood today. Common-language translations have “shelter,” which adequately preserves the sense of the word.
\line \fig |UBS-0024_shelter.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Watchman's shelter|3.0\fig* On the other hand, many languages will have a word for a structure that is almost identical to the structure referred to by the Hebrew word \i sukah\i*, even though such a structure is the normal dwelling and not considered temporary or portable. Translators should seek for a word that indicates a temporary and portable dwelling. If at all possible, however, a word meaning “tent” should be avoided, since the tent, while portable, was the permanent dwelling of many Bible characters (see \l target="REALIA:3.2">3.2 Tent\l*). Often such temporary dwellings may be used by farmers during the day for shade, or even overnight if they have to stay in the fields to protect their crop from monkeys and other pests. Or they may be used by herders when traveling with their cattle.
\line Where no single appropriate word exists, it is possible to use a descriptive expression, such as “temporary hut” or “temporary dwelling.”
\line In \s H01002201200010 H01803602900014 H01901801200010 H01902700500008\s*; and \s H01903102100020\s* the Hebrew word \i sukah\i* symbolizes the dwelling place of God.
\line \s H03000901100016\s*: The Hebrew word \i sukah\i* is used here as a picture to which the kingdom of David is probably being compared. The point of similarity is almost certainly to be found in the word “fallen” (\a RSV\a*). David’s kingdom is now destroyed, broken down, like an old broken down building. “The kingdom of David” (\a GNT\a*) refers to the people of Israel at the highest point of their political and military power. In English it is more natural to translate \i sukah\i* here as “house”; for example, \a NEB\a* says “On that day I will restore David’s fallen house . . . .” \a GNT\a* has made the comparison clear in every way, which is what most translations need to do: “The LORD says, ‘A day is coming when I will restore the kingdom of David, which is like a house fallen into ruins. I will repair its walls and restore it. I will rebuild it and make it as it was long ago.’ ”
\line The Greek word \i skēnopēgia\i*, which appears in \s G04300700200018\s*, is the name of the festival, often known as the “Feast of Tabernacles” (\a NIV\a*) or the “Festival of Booths.” During this festival the people of Israel were commanded to live in huts. The name of this festival should be rendered the same as in \s H00302303400040\s*.
\key 3.17
\title Synagogue
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ἀποσυνάγωγος
\trl aposunagōgos
\ref G04300902200042 G04301204200038 G04301600200002
\grk ἀρχισυνάγωγος
\trl archisunagōgos
\ref G04100502200010 G04100503600020 G04100503800014 G04200804900016 G04201301400008 G04401301500024 G04401800800008 G04401801700012
\grk συναγωγή
\trl sunagōgē
\ref G04000402300020 G04000600200030 G04000600500026 G04000903500028 G04001001700028 G04001200900014 G04001305400022 G04002300600026 G04002303400048 G04100102100024 G04100102300012 G04100102900010 G04100103900012 G04100300100012 G04100600200016 G04101203900010 G04101300900022 G04200401500012 G04200401600042 G04200402000030 G04200402800014 G04200403300008 G04200403800010 G04200404400012 G04200600600020 G04200700500016 G04200804100024 G04201104300022 G04201201100014 G04201301000014 G04202004600040 G04202101200032 G04300605900008 G04301802000026 G04400600900014 G04400900200018 G04400902000010 G04401300500024 G04401301400032 G04401304300008 G04401400100024 G04401502100028 G04401700100026 G04401701000040 G04401701700012 G04401800400010 G04401800700040 G04401801900026 G04401802600014 G04401900800010 G04402201900028 G04402401200036 G04402601100010 G05900200200010 G06600200900048 G06600300900010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0077_synagogue_nazareth_outside.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Synagogue outside|3.0\fig* The synagogue was a building for assemblies, associated with religious activity (normally a building in which Jewish worship took place and in which the Law was taught). Synagogues were not normally large structures in New Testament times, and often they were not much larger than a home. \fig |PTZ-0076_synagogue_nazareth_inside.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Synagogue inside|3.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Synagogues are mentioned frequently in the New Testament, but surprisingly little is known about their physical structure at that time, since almost none have been excavated which can be dated definitely to the time of Jesus. While they probably had a literal “orientation” (that is, facing east), they had little of a distinctive architecture until after the period of the New Testament. Fortunately, it is not essential for the task of the translator to know details of the structure of the synagogue.
\line It is important to distinguish clearly between “synagogue” and “temple,” and it is not enough to speak of synagogues merely as “small temples.” There were many synagogues, but only one Temple in Jerusalem, the only place for Jewish sacrifices. It is better either to borrow a term for synagogue or to employ a descriptive equivalent such as “place where Jewish people worshiped God” or “building for worshiping God.”
\line It is also important to distinguish in translation between “synagogue” and “church,” whether these terms refer to the congregation or to the building.
\line The Greek word \i sunagōgē\i* appears about a dozen times in the Deuterocanon, always with the meaning of a congregation or assembly of people. It should never be rendered in these books as some kind of building.
\key 3.18
\title Hall, auditorium
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk ἀκροατήριον
\trl akroatērion
\ref G04402502300034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The auditorium was a relatively large building normally used for legal hearings, though possibly also employed for more general purposes.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages “auditorium” may be rendered “large hall,” “place where many people could gather together,” or “building where many people could sit to listen.”
\key 3.19
\title Judgment seat, tribunal
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk βῆμα
\trl bēma
\ref G04002701900012 G04301901300030 G04401202100026 G04401801200036 G04401801600012 G04401801700020 G04402500600038 G04402501000014 G04402501700026 G04501401000040 G04700501000018
\grk δίφρος
\trl difros
\ref L07103803300026
\lat sedes iudicii
\ref V08200703300010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The tribunal was a raised platform mounted by steps and usually furnished with a seat. It was used by officials in addressing an assembly, often on judicial matters. One tribunal excavated in Corinth (and possibly the same one mentioned in \s G04401801200036\s*) was a small platform supported by stone blocks and with a narrow railing around the top.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The association of the Greek word \i bēma\i* with judicial procedures means that there is almost always an important component of judicial function associated with this term. The focus upon judgment is particularly important in those passages that refer to the judgment seat of God (\s G04501401000040\s*) and of Christ (\s G04700501000018\s*). However, in those passages where a historical judicial event is in focus (all of the references in the Gospels and Acts), it will not usually be necessary to specify the place of judgment in translation. The following models illustrate this: “While Pilate was judging the case” (\s G04002701900012\s* in \a CEV\a*), “took him into court” (\s G04401801200036\s* in \a GNT\a*), and “he opened the legal proceedings” (\s G04402500600038\s* in \a GECL\a*).
\line If translators wish to preserve the idea of a specific place of judgment, it is possible to use a phrase such as “place where a judge decides,” “place where decisions are made,” or “judge’s seat.”
\key 3.20
\title Courtyard, court
\index \l target="REALIA:3.20.1">3.20.1 Pavement, The Pavement\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חָצֵר
\trl chatser
\ref H00200800900032 H00202700900008 H00202700900028 H00202701200008 H00202701300008 H00202701600010 H00202701700008 H00202701800006 H00202701900032 H00203501700008 H00203501700030 H00203501800018 H00203800900010 H00203800900024 H00203801500030 H00203801600008 H00203801700050 H00203801800010 H00203801800062 H00203802000022 H00203803100010 H00203803100024 H00203803100048 H00203904000008 H00203904000034 H00204000800010 H00204000800026 H00204003300010 H00204003300040 H00300600900030 H00300601900024 H00400302600008 H00400302600020 H00400303700008 H00400402600010 H00400402600024 H00400403200008 H01001701800048 H01100603600010 H01100700800012 H01100700900056 H01100701200004 H01100701200030 H01100806400024 H01202000400012 H01202100500022 H01202301200048 H01302302800026 H01302800600020 H01302801200022 H01400400900006 H01400700700014 H01402000500030 H01402300500040 H01402402100024 H01402901600046 H01403300500022 H01600302500042 H01600801600032 H01600801600038 H01601300700040 H01700100500062 H01700201100022 H01700401100046 H01700500100030 H01700500200028 H01700600400016 H01700600400026 H01700600500024 H01906500500012 H01908400300014 H01908401100010 H01909201400012 H01909600800022 H01910000400010 H01911601900004 H01913500200014 H02300101200024 H02306200900024 H02401901400032 H02402600200012 H02403200200032 H02403200800022 H02403201200074 H02403300100026 H02403601000042 H02403602000012 H02403702100022 H02403702100076 H02403800600034 H02403801300034 H02403802800010 H02403901400016 H02403901500022 H02600800700014 H02600801600010 H02600900700024 H02601000300040 H02601000400044 H02601000500018 H02604001400022 H02604001700010 H02604001700032 H02604001900028 H02604002000022 H02604002300010 H02604002700010 H02604002800008 H02604003100012 H02604003200010 H02604003400014 H02604003700014 H02604004400026 H02604004700010 H02604101500064 H02604200100010 H02604200300014 H02604200300032 H02604200600022 H02604200700026 H02604200800016 H02604200900052 H02604201000010 H02604201400026 H02604300500016 H02604401700016 H02604401700048 H02604401900012 H02604401900022 H02604402100022 H02604402700020 H02604501900058 H02604600100014 H02604602000058 H02604602100010 H02604602100028 H02604602100034 H02604602100042 H02604602100044 H02604602100052 H02604602200010 H02604602200012 H03800300700048
\heb עֲזָרָה
\trl ‘azarah
\ref H01400400900016 H01400400900030 H01400601300022
\grk αὐλαῖος
\trl aulaios
\ref L07801404100020
\grk αὐλή
\trl aulē
\ref G04002600300024 G04002605800020 G04002606900016 G04101405400024 G04101406600016 G04101501600016 G04201102100016 G04202205500014 G04301801500048 G06601100200006 L06700200900030 L06700200900030 L06900100100038 L06900201100020 L06900400200036 L07300101700018 L07700403800034 L07700404800024 L07700905400038 L07701104600014 L07900202700024 L07900501000042 L07900504600032 L08100900100012
\grk περιβολή
\trl peribolē
\ref L07105001100034
\arm תְּרַע
\trl tera‘
\ref A02700204900140
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0435_courtyard_en.jpg|col||Daderot (Wikimedia Commons)|Courtyard of a house|3.0\fig* The courtyard was an open area enclosed by structures within a building complex, such as the Temple, a palace, or even a house.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line As in English, so also in the biblical languages the words for “court” indicate both the physical courtyard and also the place of residence or activity of a king.
\line A number of times in the Old Testament, particularly in the Psalms, we encounter a phrase like “the courts of the LORD,” “your courts,” or “my courts.” In these places the word “courts” is a metonym for the Tabernacle or the Temple, and where necessary it may be translated as such. For example, in \s H01906500500012\s* \a GNT\a* has “your sanctuary” and \a CEV\a* says “your temple.” The translator should avoid using a word that indicates a court of law. \fig |WEB-0436_courtyard_en.jpg|col||© Ariely (Wikimedia Commons)|Temple courtyard|3.0\fig*
\line In some places the Greek word \i aulē\i* refers to the courtyard of a private house. It has this meaning in \s G04002600300024\s* and \s G04201102100016\s*, so \a CEV\a* renders it “home” in these passages.
\line \s G06601100200006\s*: “The court outside the temple” (\a RSV\a*) was known as the Court of the Gentiles, for that is where they could assemble. They could not get closer to the inner sanctuary, however. In this passage this court and its people stand for the unbelievers, who will not be spared the disasters to come. Another way of expressing the initial clause in this verse is “But do not measure the open spaces with walls around them outside the Temple.”
\key 3.20.1
\title Pavement, The Pavement
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לְבֵנָה
\trl lvenah
\ref H00202401000022
\heb מַלְבֵּן
\trl malben
\ref H02404300900026
\heb רִצְפָה
\trl ritsfah
\ref H01400700300044 H01700100600044 H02604001700024 H02604001700046 H02604001800006 H02604001800028 H02604200300024
\grk λιθόστρωτον
\trl lithostrōton
\ref G04301901300038
\grk ἔδαφος
\trl edafos
\ref L07101100500010 L07102001800006 L07600101900036 L07900202200024 L08000600700010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0437_pavement_roman_petra.jpg|col||© High Contrast (Wikimedia Commons)|Roman pavement|3.0\fig* Pavement was an area paved with flat blocks of stone to form a courtyard (not a road). “The Pavement” was the name given to the inner courtyard of the Roman fortress of Antonia, which bordered the northwest corner of the Temple complex in Jerusalem.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H02404300900026\s*: The Hebrew word \i malben\i* occurs elsewhere with the meaning of “brick mold” or “brickkiln” (see the discussion and references at \l target="REALIA:1.8.1">1.8.1 Brick mold, brickkiln\l*). Here it seems to indicate the material from which the pavement is made; \a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*, and \a CEV\a* all render it “brick pavement.” Jeremiah is told to hide the stones “in the \i melet\i* of the \i malben\i*.” The Hebrew word \i melet\i* occurs only here, and its meaning is uncertain. Translations usually render it as some material in which the bricks would be set, for example, “clay” (\a NRSV\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*), “mortar” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*), or “cement” (\a REB\a*). \a CEV\a* avoids finding a specific material and focuses instead on the location, saying “underneath the brick pavement.”
\line \s G04301901300038\s*: In some languages translators may render “The Pavement” as “the court covered with large blocks of flat stone” or “the stone-paved courtyard.”
\line The Greek word \i edafos\i* does not refer to a specific place or even to a particular kind of construction. Thus it may be translated with a generic term such as “floor” or even “ground.”
\key 3.21
\title Prison and penal activity
\index \l target="REALIA:3.21.1">3.21.1 Prison, dungeon\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.21.2">3.21.2 Stocks\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.21.3">3.21.3 Cross\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.21.4">3.21.4 Chain\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.21.5">3.21.5 Shackle, fetter, manacle\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:3.21.6">3.21.6 Rack and other instruments of torture\l*
\key 3.21.1
\title Prison, dungeon
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בַּיִת, אסר, אָסִיר, אֵסוּר
\trl beyth ’esur, beyth ’asurim, beyth hasurim
\ref H00701602100026 H00701602100042 H00701602100046 H00701602500042 H00701602500046 H02100401400006 H02403701500026
\heb בַּיִת, בּוֹר
\trl (beyth) bor
\ref H00104001500038 H00104101400024 H00201202900056 H02302402200012 H02403701600010 H02403800600020 H02403800700022 H02403800900044 H02403801000052 H02403801100022 H02403801300024
\heb בַּיִת, כֶּלֶא, כְּלִיא
\trl (beyth) kele’, beyth kelu’
\ref H01102202700020 H01201700400064 H01202502700074 H01202502900010 H01401802600018 H02304200700022 H02304202200028 H02403700400028 H02403701500026 H02403701800048 H02405203100080 H02405203300010
\heb בַּיִת, מִשְׁמָר
\trl beyth mishmar
\ref H00104201900016
\heb בַּיִת, פְּקֻדָּה
\trl beyth pqudoth
\ref H02405201100036
\heb בַּיִת, סֹהַר
\trl beyth sohar
\ref H00103902000018 H00103902000022 H00103902100032 H00103902200008 H00103902200012 H00103902300006 H00104000300012 H00104000300022
\arm גֹּב
\trl gov
\ref A02700600800074 A02700601300066 A02700601700024 A02700601800018 A02700602000026 A02700602100010 A02700602400028 A02700602400038 A02700602500030 A02700602500054
\heb מַטָּרָה
\trl matarah
\ref H01600302500046 H01601203900068 H02403200200036 H02403200800026 H02403201200078 H02403300100030 H02403702100026 H02403702100080 H02403800600038 H02403801300038 H02403802800014 H02403901400020 H02403901500026
\heb מַסְגֵּר
\trl masger
\ref H01914200800006 H02302402200020 H02304200700016
\heb עֹצֶר
\trl ‘otser
\ref H02305300800004
\grk δεσμωτήριον
\trl desmōtērion
\ref G04001100200014 G04400502100068 G04400502300008 G04401602600022
\grk εἱρκτή
\trl heirktē
\ref L07001701500028
\grk λάκκος
\trl lakkos
\ref L07001001400008 L07600103100028 L07600103200020 L07600103400072 L07600103500040 L07600103600088 L07600104000064 L07600104200052 L08001801300012
\grk τήρησις
\trl tērēsis
\ref G04400400300018 G04400501800024
\grk φυλακή
\trl fulakē
\ref G04000502500058 G04001400300022 G04001401000016 G04001803000020 G04002503600020 G04002503900016 G04002504300030 G04002504400042 G04100601700026 G04100602700036 G04200302000022 G04201205800074 G04202101200036 G04202203300024 G04202301900030 G04202302500020 G04300302400014 G04400501900020 G04400502200020 G04400502500028 G04400800300034 G04401200400012 G04401200500016 G04401200600056 G04401201700032 G04401602300016 G04401602400020 G04401602700024 G04401603700032 G04401604000010 G04402200400024 G04402601000026 G04700600500008 G04701102300024 G05801103600024 G06000301900012 G06600201000028 G06602000700024 L08001801100032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |ABS-0003_man_praying_in_prison.jpg|col||Bible for Today's Family © American Bible Society|Man in prison|3.0\fig* The prison was a place where criminals or other prisoners were confined. There was no standard size or construction for a prison or jail.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Practically all languages have terms for a jail or a prison, though in some instances a descriptive phrase is employed, for example, “place where people are tied up” or “place to be chained.” In some languages highly idiomatic expressions are used, such as “place for eating iron” or “room with rats.” The translation should convey the idea that it is a place where a person is restrained against his will.
\line The Hebrew word \i bor\i*, the Aramaic word \i gov\i*, and the Greek word \i lakkos\i* refer to a hole or depression in the ground. The \i bor\i* into which Jeremiah was lowered in \s H02403800000000\s* was probably a cistern (see \l target="REALIA:3.9">3.9 Cistern\l*). In the rest of the texts listed for these three words, it is not clear if the hole or pit was natural or man-made.
\key 3.21.2
\title Stocks
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַהְפֶּכֶת
\trl mahpeketh
\ref H01401601000022 H02402000200026 H02402000300024 H02402902600048
\heb סַד
\trl sad
\ref H01801302700010 H01803301100008
\grk ξύλον
\trl xulon
\ref G04401602400036
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0334_wooden_stocks.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Wooden stocks for feet|3.0\fig* Stocks were a device consisting of blocks of wood through which the legs, arms, and/or head of a prisoner were placed and then securely fastened. Two pieces of wood each had half-circle holes cut in them. When placed together, they formed circular holes that held the limbs or head of the prisoner. The two pieces were then locked together so that the prisoner could not move. Stocks were employed both as an instrument for imprisoning and also as a means of punishment.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Many translations will need to use a descriptive phrase for “stocks” to give the sense. Compare \a NCV\a* at \s H02402000200026\s*: “And he locked Jeremiah’s hands and feet between large blocks of wood.” \fig |KNW-0337_paul_silas.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Men in stocks|3.0\fig*
\line \s H01801302700010\s*: Here Job pictures himself as God’s prisoner, with his movements severely restricted. In the first line of this verse “stocks” refers to a wooden block in which a prisoner’s feet were locked, but according to the second line, there may have been some possibility of movement. \a GNT\a* translates the first line as “You bind chains on my feet.” This line may also be rendered “You tie my feet together” or “You tie my feet so I cannot walk.”
\line \s G04401602400036\s*: For the phrase “in the stocks” (\a RSV\a*), \a GNT\a* has “between heavy blocks of wood.” The term “stocks” was avoided by \a GNT\a* for two reasons: (1) it was felt that its meaning would not be readily understood by the readers for whom the \a GNT\a* was designed, and (2) the stocks used by the Romans were of a different type from those otherwise known. The Romans used stocks as an instrument of torture. It had more than one pair of holes for the legs, so that a prisoner’s legs could be spread wide apart, causing him great pain.
\key 3.21.3
\title Cross
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ἀνασταυρόω
\trl anastauroō (verb)
\ref G05800600600014
\grk ξύλον
\trl xulon
\ref G04400503000026 G04401003900042 G04401302900024 G06000202400026
\grk σταυρός, σταυρόω
\trl stauros, stauroō (verb)
\ref G04001003800012 G04001602400038 G04002001900024 G04002303400034 G04002600200034 G04002702200028 G04002702300026 G04002702600024 G04002703100040 G04002703200026 G04002703500002 G04002703800004 G04002704000046 G04002704200028 G04002800500032 G04100803400044 G04101501300010 G04101501400028 G04101501500040 G04101502000038 G04101502100036 G04101502400004 G04101502500012 G04101502700008 G04101503000012 G04101503200020 G04101600600024 G04200902300032 G04201402700010 G04202302100010 G04202302100012 G04202302300016 G04202302600030 G04202303300022 G04202400700028 G04202402000030 G04301900600024 G04301900600026 G04301900600044 G04301901000038 G04301901500012 G04301901500030 G04301901600014 G04301901700010 G04301901800006 G04301901900022 G04301902000034 G04301902300010 G04301902500010 G04301903100024 G04301904100014 G04400203600042 G04400401000040 G04600101300012 G04600101700034 G04600101800012 G04600102300010 G04600200200028 G04600200800036 G04701300400006 G04800300100026 G04800501100032 G04800502400016 G04800601200026 G04800601400020 G04800601400040 G04900201600024 G05000200800018 G05000301800032 G05100102000028 G05100201400042 G05801200200034 G06601100800046
\grk συσταυρόω
\trl sustauroō (verb)
\ref G04002704400016 G04101503200034 G04301903200032 G04500600600016 G04800201900022
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0438_cross.jpg|col||Aaron Burden aaronburden (Wikimedia Commons)|Cross|3.0\fig* The cross was a pole stuck into the ground in an upright position with a crosspiece attached to its upper part so that it was shaped like a \b T\b* or like a \b †\b*. Also found, although possibly less common, was a cross in the shape of an \b X\b* made from two sticks. The fact that Jesus had a writing attached above his head indicates that his cross probably had the \b †\b* shape.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The condemned man often carried the horizontal part of the cross to the place of execution, where the vertical pole (or even the trimmed trunk of a tree) was already standing. His hands were nailed (through the wrist just below the palm) to the horizontal bar and then the man and the bar were raised up to the vertical pole and the bar was tied to it. Sometimes the man sat on a small projection from the vertical pole. The feet were then nailed to the pole, one nail (or spike) holding both feet through the ankles, which were turned sideways. Death was usually slow, frequently taking several days.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Because of the symbolism associated with the cross, translations of the New Testament in all languages preserve some expression that will identify the cross, not only as a means of capital punishment, but also as having a particular form, namely, an upright pole with a crossbeam. In some receptor languages the term for a cross means simply “crossbeam.” In other languages it is expressed by a phrase meaning “crossed poles.”
\line \fig |KNW-0327_cross_inscription.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Cross inscription|3.0\fig* If at all possible, translators should employ a term or phrase that may be used in an extended sense, since in so many contexts the term “cross” refers not only to the instrument of Christ’s death, but also to the event of his execution. It also becomes a symbol of the message of forgiveness and reconciliation. Because of these extended meanings, it is important to choose an expression that can, if at all possible, support these additional meanings.
\line The Greek word \i xulon\i* is literally “wood.” Outside the New Testament \i xulon\i* often refers to a gallows; in the New Testament contexts that speak of capital punishment, the reference is to the cross on which Jesus was crucified. In \s G04800301300040\s* it is not necessary to render \i xulon\i* by a term that means a live tree. The Greek term here may refer simply to a “post,” and it may be more appropriate to employ a term that would also be applicable to a cross. To use an expression that must refer to a live tree would introduce an unnecessary inconsistency. While the phrase in this verse is in part a quotation from \s H00502102301000\s*, the translator should not try to harmonize the two texts. The commandment in Deuteronomy is to put a sinner to death and then hang the dead body on a tree. Unlike crucifixion, this hanging was not a means of execution but probably some kind of public warning.
\key 3.21.4
\title Chain
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֲזִקִּים
\trl ’aziqim (plural of ’azeq)
\ref H02404000100054 H02404000400018
\heb זֵק
\trl ziqim (plural of zeq)
\ref H01803600800012 H01914900800010 H02304501400044 H03400301000056
\heb מַעֲדַנּוֹת
\trl ma‘adanoth
\ref H01803803100006
\heb מֹשְׁכוֹת
\trl moshkoth
\ref H01803803100012
\heb רַתּוּקָה
\trl ratuqah
\ref H01100602100028
\grk ἅλυσις
\trl halusis
\ref G04100500300020 G04100500400014 G04100500400028 G04200802900036 G04401200600038 G04401200700056 G04402103300020 G04402802000036 G04900602000010 G05500101600028 G06602000100028 L07001701600044
\grk δέσμιος, δεσμός
\trl desmios, desmos
\ref G04200802900050 G04201301600040 G04401602600042 G04402002300026 G04402302900028 G04402602900064 G04402603100022 G05000100700042 G05000101400020 G05000101700028 G05100401800020 G05500200900010 G05700101000022 G05700101300028 G05801103600020 G06500100600036 L07001001400014 L07100602500024 L07100603000018 L07101301200026 L07102802000018 L07102802000022 L07102802000018 L07900302500046 L07900400700002 L07900500600034 L07900602700008 L08001200200030 L08100103800026
\grk σειρά
\trl seira
\ref G06100200400020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0421_fetters_chains_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Chain and fetter|3.0\fig* The chain was a series of links, usually made of metal.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line A chain was normally used for restraining or for holding objects together. It is especially associated with the restriction of the movement of prisoners. See also \l target="REALIA:10.5.4">10.5.4 Necklace, chain, cord\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages the expression for “chain” is simply “metal rope.” In other languages it may be rendered “linked rope” in contrast with “twisted rope,” that is, a rope made out of some kind of fiber. In some languages a distinction is made between terms for a chain used in tying up a person and one employed in agricultural or industrial work.
\line In some of the passages listed above “chains” is symbolic language for imprisonment. Many translations will want to follow the model of \a GNT\a* in a passage like \s G05000100700042\s*. In the middle of this verse the Greek text says literally “in that I am chained,” but \a GNT\a* has “now that I am in prison.”
\line The chains placed by Solomon in front of the Holy of Holies (\s H01100602100028\s*) were made of gold and served primarily as decoration, although they would also have reminded those serving in the sanctuary not to come any closer to the Holy of Holies.
\line In \s H01803803100006\s* two Hebrew words demand special attention. The word \i ma‘adanoth\i* (which appears also in \s H00901503200028\s* with an unrelated meaning) comes together with a verb meaning “to tie, bind.” The word \i ma‘adanoth\i* is of uncertain meaning, but it seems likely that there has occurred a reversal of two Hebrew letters from a word meaning “ring,” so that \i ma‘adanoth\i* means a series of connected rings, that is, a “chain” (\a RSV\a*). Some translations prefer to combine the verb with the noun and render them simply “tie together” (so \a GNT\a*, \a GECL\a*) with no reference to the object used to bind. The second Hebrew word, \i moshkoth\i*, appears only here in Scripture. It comes from a verb meaning “to pull, draw.” In modern Hebrew \i moshkoth\i* means “reins” (leather straps for controlling a horse), and this is reflected in \a NJPSV\a*, which renders the second line of this verse as “Or undo the reins of Orion.” Other translations (\a NEB\a*, \a REB\a*, \a GECL\a*) understand \i moshkoth\i* to refer to the three aligned stars that make up the “belt” of the Orion constellation.
\line \s H01914900800010\s*: For this verse \a RSV\a* has “to bind their kings with chains and their nobles with fetters of iron.” “Their nobles” is parallel to “their kings” and indicates the military leaders. In some languages the use of “chains” and “fetters of iron” will tend to give the impression that the kings were bound with chains that were not made of iron. The poetic parallel, however, indicates that they are equivalent. In some languages this verse may be rendered “to capture their kings and leaders and tie them up.”
\line \s G06602000100028\s*: “A great chain” (\a RSV\a*) may be rendered “a heavy chain” (\a GNT\a*) or “a thick chain.” We assume the chain was made of metal. The expressed purpose of this chain is to restrain Satan. In cultures where metal chains are unknown, translators may say “a big [or, thick] rope,” or they may employ some other material that is used for tying up people.
\key 3.21.5
\title Shackle, fetter, manacle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כֶּבֶל
\trl kevel
\ref H01910501800008 H01914900800018
\heb נְחֹשֶׁת
\trl nchosheth
\ref H00701602100032 H01000303400016 H01202500700034 H01403301100048 H01403600600020 H02403900700020 H02405201100020 H02500300700014
\grk πέδη
\trl pedē
\ref G04100500400010 G04100500400034 G04200802900040 L07100602900010 L07102101900002 L07900400900046 L07900601900030 L07100602400016 L07103302900024 L07700304100036
\grk χειροπέδη
\trl cheiropedē
\ref L07102101900016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0439_shackle.jpg|col||Daderot (Wikimedia Commons)|Ankle manacle|3.0\fig* Fetters were metal chains with special links prepared to go around the ankles. They served to restrict the movement of someone considered dangerous or being imprisoned. There is considerable overlap between this entry and the preceding one on “chain.” See also the illustration there.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The equivalent in some languages for “fetters” is simply “chains on the feet.” \s G04100500400010\s* and \s G04200802900040\s* refer to both chains and fetters. Fetters were used to bind the legs and feet and chains were used to bind the hands and arms. Where a specific word for “fetters” is not known, it is possible to render the literal phrase “bound with fetters and chains” as “put chains on his hands and feet.”
\line The Old Testament text usually specifies the material of which the fetters or chains were made. The Hebrew word \i nchosheth\i* refers to brass or bronze, while the two references to \i kevel\i* in the Psalms are to instruments of iron.
\key 3.21.6
\title Rack and other instruments of torture
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ἄξων
\trl axōn
\ref L08000902000040
\grk καταπέλτης
\trl katapeltēs
\ref L08001102600018 L08000801300024 L08000902600050 L08001100900022 L08001802000050
\grk στρέβλη
\trl streblē
\ref L07103302700018 L08000700400042 L08000701400024 L08000801100022 L08000802400020 L08000902200022 L08001401200028 L08001502400018 L08001502500036
\grk στρεβλωτήριον
\trl streblōtērion
\ref L08000801300014
\grk τροχός
\trl trochos
\ref L08000503200006 L08000801300006 L08000901200026 L08000901700020 L08000901900018 L08000902000012 L08001000800012 L08001101000050 L08001101700014 L08001502200020
\grk τύμπανον
\trl tumpanon
\ref L07800601900034 L07800602800048
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The rack was an instrument of torture. The victim was stretched out on a kind of table with his hands above his head. On either end of the table the hands and feet were tied to a wheel or other device that could pull the limbs more and more causing great pain. While the victim was stretched out like this, he could be whipped or otherwise physically abused.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Most cultures will not know this exact instrument of torture. It is best to follow \a GNT\a* and not attempt to describe the rack exactly; for example, in \s L07800601900034\s* \a GNT\a* renders it “place of torture.”
\line The Greek word \i trochos\i* means literally “wheel.” In \s L08000503200060\s* \a RSV\a* renders it “torture wheels.” In most of the contexts in 4MA it is clear that, similar to the rack, the “wheel” was used to stretch the victim. In those same references it seems to have been used in conjunction with a fire that burned the victim while he was being stretched.
\line Similarly, the Greek word \i katapeltēs\i* in \s L08000801300024\s* seems to refer to an instrument for stretching the limbs and dislocating the joints. \a RSV\a* renders this word as “catapults,” but \a CEV\a* has “pounding machines” (although this does not seem to fit the torture described in \s L08001100900020 L08001101000036\s*, where \a CEV\a* has “place where he would be tortured”).
\line Some of the instruments of torture listed in 4 Maccabees may have been components of larger instruments; for example, in \s L08001101000036\s* the “wedge” (\a RSV\a*’s rendering of the Greek word \i sfēn\i*), the “iron clamps” (\i podagra sidērous\i*), and the “wheel” (\i trochiaios\i*) are all employed in the torture with the \i katapeltēs\i*.
\line The Greek word \i axōn\i* normally refers to the axle of a wheel (see \l target="REALIA:8.3">8.3 Wheel\l*). However, in \s L08000902000040\s* it does not refer to part of a vehicle wheel but rather to part of a stationary torture machine. Wheels made up part of its operating mechanism, and these wheels, like wheels on a cart, turned around a central axle.
\line A number of other torture implements are mentioned in 4 Maccabees. They are listed here with suggested translations. For the most part the stucture of the devices is unknown. They are as follows:
\line \i arthrembolon\i* \s L08000801300040\s* “joint-dislocator” (\a RSV\a*), “stretching frame” (\a CEV\a*)
\line \i trochantēr\i* \s L08000801300040\s* “bone-crusher” (possibly related to the wheel)
\line \i daktulēthra\i* \s L08000801300040\s* “thumbscrew” (\a RSV\a*), “iron clamps” (\a CEV\a*)
\line \s L08000801300040 L08000902600038\s* “iron gauntlets having sharp hooks” (\a RSV\a*), “heavy iron club with sharp hooks on its end” (\a CEV\a*)
