\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Rim, molding\b*:
\heb זֵר
\trl zer
\ref H00202501100030 H00203700200026
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0283_ark.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Priests carrying the covered Covenant Box|4.0\fig* The instructions for making the Covenant Box are found in \s H00202501100030\s*, and its construction is described in \s H00203700000000\s*. It was a rectangular box, about 125 centimeters (49 inches) long, 75 centimeters (30 inches) wide, and 75 centimeters (30 inches) high. It was made of acacia wood and was overlaid with gold. It had a raised gold rim or molding around it for decoration. Evidently it stood on four legs on its corners. A gold ring was attached to each of the four feet. Through these rings were inserted two poles for carrying the Box. (In the illustration below, the rings and poles should be at the bottom, nearer to the foot of the Box; see the illustration above.) The poles were also of acacia wood overlaid with gold. Their length or circumference is not given. Inserting the poles through the rings made it possible to lift and move the Box without actually touching it. The Box had a special lid or cover (see \l target="REALIA:4.1.1">4.1.1 Mercy seat, atonement cover, atonement lid\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0440_convenant_box.jpg|col||© Fernando Shoiti Schatzmann from Suzano, Brasil (Wikimedia Commons)|Covenant Box|4.0\fig* In English some people object to speaking of the so-called “Ark of the Covenant” as “the Covenant Box,” since they assume that the English word “ark” has some special meaning equivalent to the corresponding Hebrew or Greek terms. However, the term “ark” in Old English and Middle English is simply a transliteration of the Latin word \i arca\i*, which means “box, chest, coffer.” Indeed, the Hebrew word for “ark” (\i ’aron\i*) is used also to refer to other types of boxes (\s H00105002600032\s*; \s H01201201000012 H01201201100022\s*; \s H01402400800014 H01402400900000 H01402401000032 H01402401100016\s*; see, for example, \l target="REALIA:4.8.4">4.8.4 Bier, coffin\l*).
\line In present-day English the term “ark” is known primarily from the context of “Noah’s ark.” Translators should be aware that it is only by historical accident that the same word was used in older translations in English, French, and some other European languages both for Noah’s ship (see \l target="REALIA:8.1.3">8.1.3 Ark, ship\l*) and for the Covenant Box. Hebrew uses a different word for Noah’s vessel. No attempt should be made to render them identically in the receptor language.
\cont \b Molding\b*: The gold “border” or “band” around the Covenant Box seems to have been for decoration. In H00202501100030 the Hebrew word rendered “round about” by \a RSV\a* means “all around it,” as \a GNT\a* renders it, since the word has the basic meaning of encircling. \a NAB\a* has “around the top of it,” but the molding may have been placed somewhat lower than at the top edge of the Box. For the last half of this verse \a CEV\a* has “put a gold edging around the lid”, but this seems to miss the point since the edging was around the Box itself.
\cont \b Poles and rings\b*: Several pieces of the Tabernacle furniture were carried by means of long poles inserted into rings attached to the objects. The translator should employ the same terminology uniformly for these poles and rings. It is explicitly stated in \s H00202501500008\s* that the poles of the Box were not to be removed. In \s H00400401000032 H00400401200060\s* the Hebrew word \i mot\i* is rendered “carrying frame” by \a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*, and \a NIV\a*. \a REB\a* understands it to be a “pole” from which a bundle was hung.
\key 4.1.1
\title Mercy seat, atonement cover, atonement lid
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כַּפֹּרֶת
\trl kaporeth
\ref H00202501700006 H00202501800026 H00202501900036 H00202502000028 H00202502000044 H00202502100010 H00202502200022 H00202603400010 H00203000600032 H00203100700028 H00203501200018 H00203700600006 H00203700700026 H00203700800032 H00203700900028 H00203700900044 H00203903500022 H00204002000046 H00301600200054 H00301600200084 H00301601300038 H00301601400028 H00301601400040 H00301601500074 H00301601500084 H00400708900042 H01302801100050
\grk ἱλαστήριον
\trl hilastērion
\ref G05800900500016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The “mercy seat” was a lid that covered the Covenant Box (see \l target="REALIA:4.1">4.1 Covenant Box, Ark of the Covenant\l*). It was rectangular with the same dimensions as the top of the Covenant Box. It was made of beaten gold. Standing on its top were two golden figures with wings, called literally “cherubim” (see \l target="REALIA:4.1.2">4.1.2 Winged creatures, cherubim\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Besides serving as a top for the Covenant Box, the atonement lid (or, cover) was the focal point for an annual act of atonement by the High Priest of the Jewish people. Once a year, on the Day of Atonement (see \s H00301601401000 H00301601501000\s*), the priest sprinkled blood from sacrificial animals on and in front of the atonement lid.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i kaporeth\i* comes from a root meaning “to cover,” but this may be understood in two different ways in the context of the Covenant Box. It may refer to the “covering” or forgiving of sin (that is, “atonement”), or it may simply mean a “covering” or lid on top of the Covenant Box. Possibly the Hebrew word contained both of these elements of meaning in this context. \a JB\a* renders it “throne of mercy” (although \a NJB\a* reverts to “mercy-seat”). \a NIV\a* has “atonement cover.” Many other versions have simply “cover” (\a NJPSV\a*, \a FRCL\a*, \a Mft\a*, \a NEB\a*). Most French versions have \i propitiatoire\i* (\a TOB\a*; compare \a AT\a* “propitiatory”), which places the emphasis on the “atonement” or “forgiveness” domain of meaning in the word \i kaporeth\i*. All things considered, it is probably better to translate “lid” or “cover.”
\key 4.1.2
\title Winged creatures, cherubim
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כְּרוּב
\trl kruv
\ref H00100302400030 H00202501800008 H00202501900006 H00202501900020 H00202501900044 H00202502000008 H00202502000052 H00202502200032 H00202600100034 H00202603100034 H00203600800048 H00203603500038 H00203700700008 H00203700800002 H00203700800016 H00203700800040 H00203700900008 H00203700900052 H00400708900062 H00900400400034 H01000600200060 H01002201100008 H01100602300014 H01100602400012 H01100602400028 H01100602500014 H01100602500036 H01100602600006 H01100602600026 H01100602700010 H01100602700034 H01100602700058 H01100602800010 H01100602900022 H01100603200020 H01100603200046 H01100603500006 H01100702900024 H01100703600022 H01100800600046 H01100800700006 H01100800700026 H01201901500028 H01301300600048 H01302801800034 H01400300700034 H01400301000016 H01400301100008 H01400301100060 H01400301200008 H01400301200050 H01400301300006 H01400301400032 H01400500700046 H01400500800008 H01400500800028 H01901801100008 H01908000200022 H01909900100012 H02303701600014 H02600900300018 H02601000100024 H02601000200042 H02601000200062 H02601000300006 H02601000400016 H02601000500010 H02601000600048 H02601000700008 H02601000700022 H02601000700036 H02601000800010 H02601000900018 H02601000900028 H02601000900042 H02601001400022 H02601001500008 H02601001600010 H02601001600028 H02601001800028 H02601001900008 H02601002000030 H02601102200008 H02602801400004 H02602801600032 H02604101800006 H02604101800018 H02604101800022 H02604101800034 H02604102000020 H02604102500016
\grk Χερούβ
\trl cheroub
\ref G05800900500008 L07104900800044 L08500805400016 L11200305500032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0442_cherub.jpg|col||© I, Sailko (Wikimedia Commons)|Winged creature|4.0\fig* The cherub is mentioned over ninety times in Scripture and seems to be a composite being. (Some of the references are to the creatures themselves, but the places listed above refer to physical representations of those creatures.) The only consistent information given to describe cherubim (the Hebrew plural of \i kruv\i*) is that they had wings. In some places they have one face, in others four faces. Sometimes they are said to have two legs, at other times four legs. Three-dimensional statues of them were part of the atonement lid that covered the Covenant Box (see \l target="REALIA:4.1.1">4.1.1 Mercy seat, atonement cover, atonement lid\l* and the illustration at \l target="REALIA:4.1">4.1 Covenant Box, Ark of the Covenant\l*). These figures faced each other from either end of the lid, and their wings arched up to meet over the middle of the lid, providing a kind of protecting cover over the Box.
\line Much larger three-dimensional cherubim were placed by Solomon in the Most Holy Place of the Temple. These were carved of olivewood and were overlaid with gold. Unlike the cherubim on the atonement lid, these stood side by side facing the same direction. Their wings were extended, with one wing of each meeting a wing of the other in the center of the room.
\line Representations of cherubim were also embroidered on different cloth items in the Tabernacle. In the Temple, where walls replaced the curtains, similar figures were carved in relief on the walls.
\line The cherubim serve in Scripture as symbols of God’s majesty and presence. They have also been understood as guardians of the approach to the presence of God (compare \s H00100302401000\s*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Since the term “cherub” is largely unknown or misunderstood, translators should normally avoid transliterating this word unless it is accompanied by a descriptive phrase, and even then the transliterated form may not be helpful. In most translations a descriptive note will be helpful. Some attempts at rendering this word by means of a descriptive phrase may result in confusing the reader, due to the very large number of winged creatures he already knows. If the descriptive phrase is confusing for the reader, it may be better to borrow the term from a major language in the area. Translators must not give the impression that the cherub is a variant of some locally known large bird. Even though the cherub’s distinguishing characteristic was the fact of having wings, “winged animal” does not do justice to the composite nature of this ancient symbol. A phrase like “flying being” may be meaningless, and “flying thing” may be equated with anything from an insect to an airplane. It may be appropriate to say “winged image” or “winged figure.” In general, it may be best to employ a phrase such as “image of a winged heavenly creature” or “statue of a winged heavenly animal.”
\key 4.2
\title Altars
\index \l target="REALIA:4.2.1">4.2.1 Stone altar\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.2.2">4.2.2 Tabernacle altar\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.2.2.1">4.2.2.1 Grating, mesh\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.2.3">4.2.3 Temple altar\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.2.4">4.2.4 Incense altar\l*
\line \fig |KNW-0255_sheep_offered.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Sheep on an Israelite stone altar|4.0\fig* An altar was a kind of table or platform where sacrifices of animals or other offerings were made to God. Several different kinds of altars are mentioned in the Bible:
\line 1. Israelite altars that were used for making sacrifices
\line (a) Stone altars built in the open air, such as those mentioned in Genesis and elsewhere in the Old Testament
\line (b) The altars for making sacrifices in the Tabernacle and in the Jerusalem Temple
\line 2. Israelite altars that were used for purposes other than making sacrifices
\line (a) The altar for burning incense in the Tabernacle/Temple, including the altar mentioned in Revelation, where prayers were offered and incense was burnt
\line 3. Pagan altars
\line In the entries that follow, different altars are described. However, in many verses it is uncertain exactly which altar is intended. This is especially true of events in the Tabernacle complex or the Temple, where either the altar for sacrifices or the incense altar may be intended. Many languages have a generic term for an altar or a ceremonial platform that can serve many purposes. Where there is no term for a place of sacrificial offerings, translators may need to use a descriptive phrase or borrow a term. See \l target="REALIA:4.2.1">4.2.1 Stone altar\l* for further discussion.
\key 4.2.1
\title Stone altar
\index \l target="REALIA:4.2.1.1">4.2.1.1 Horns of the altar\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִזְבֵּחַ
\trl mizbeach
\ref H00100802000008 H00100802000054 H00101200700038 H00101200800052 H00101300400008 H00101301800034 H00102200900034 H00102200900066 H00102602500008 H00103302000008 H00103500100030 H00103500300018 H00103500700008 H00201701500008 H00202002400002 H00202002500006 H00202002600014 H00202101400026 H00202400400030 H00202400600038 H00203200500012 H00203401300006 H00402300100022 H00402300200036 H00402300400024 H00402300400042 H00402301400024 H00402301400040 H00402302900022 H00402303000030 H00500700500012 H00501200300008 H00502700500008 H00502700500016 H00502700600010 H00503301000032 H00600803000008 H00600803100034 H00600902700038 H00602201000048 H00602201000056 H00602201100042 H00602201600052 H00602201900068 H00602201900074 H00602202300008 H00602202600020 H00602202800034 H00602202900036 H00602203400020 H00700200200024 H00700602400010 H00700602500058 H00700602600006 H00700602800024 H00700602800060 H00700603000032 H00700603100068 H00700603200038 H00701302000020 H00701302000040 H00702100400024 H00900701700032 H00901403500008 H00901403500022 H01002401800036 H01002402100046 H01002402500010 H01100300400042 H01101203200054 H01101203300010 H01101203300076 H01101300100036 H01101300200010 H01101300200022 H01101300200024 H01101300300038 H01101300400032 H01101300400054 H01101300500006 H01101300500022 H01101303200026 H01101603200006 H01101802600078 H01101803000038 H01101803200012 H01101803200040 H01101803500016 H01101901000030 H01101901400030 H01201101800026 H01201101800028 H01201101800060 H01201601000032 H01201601000064 H01201802200038 H01202100300028 H01202301200008 H01202301200036 H01202301500010 H01202301500046 H01202301600056 H01202301700074 H01202302000024 H01302101800032 H01302102200028 H01302102600010 H01302102600052 H01401400200008 H01402301700026 H01402301700056 H01402802400050 H01403001400014 H01403100100060 H01403201200020 H01403300300028 H01403301500034 H01403400400012 H01403400500012 H01403400500014 H01403400700010 H02301700800012 H02301901900014 H02302700900034 H02303600700038 H02401101300024 H02401101300032 H02401700100034 H02401700200008 H02600600400006 H02600600500030 H02600600600030 H02600601300026 H02800801100008 H02800801100018 H02801000100028 H02801000200014 H02801000800024 H02801201200026 H03000200800016 H03000301400022 H03000301400034
\grk βωμός
\trl bomōs
\ref G04401702300020 L07700104700008 L07700105400100 L07700202300068 L07700202400092 L07700202500064 L07700204500044 L07700506800044 L07801000200024
\grk θυσιαστήριον
\trl thusiastērion
\ref G04501100300014 G05900202100032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0078_altar_flat_uncut_stones.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Altar of uncut stones|4.0\fig* In Old Testament times, especially before the Tabernacle or the Temple was made, stone altars were built in the open air for the purpose of making sacrifices. The altars were made from large stones, piled together to form a platform. The sacrifices were of sheep or goats, or of offerings of grain. The stones used to make Israelite altars were not to be cut or shaped with iron tools (\s H00202002501000\s*; \s H00502700501000\s*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Some languages may distinguish between natural stone and blocks that are the result of cutting and shaping. Where the stones of the altar are mentioned, translators should choose a word for natural stones. \fig |PTZ-0079_altar_circular_canaanite.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Canaanite altar|4.0\fig*
\line If sacrificing animals is something that is done in the receptor-language culture, then consider whether there is some cultural equivalent for an altar. A number of modern cultures have elevated structures for sacrificing animals or for offering gifts to a deity. Sometimes this will be a stone or wood platform or table. Be sure that the translation makes it clear that the sacrifice is being offered to God.
\line A descriptive equivalent of “altar” occurs in some languages as “place where gifts are given to God.” Several other models are “place/plat­form/hearth where people offer sacrifices,” “bed/platform for [killing and] offering sacrifices,” and “[hearth] stones for/of sacrificing things.” In some contexts it may be necessary to add a phrase such as “where sacrifices are burned to God” or “where incense is burned to honor God.” Other possible translations include “thing on which [sacred] offerings are placed” and “place of sacrifice.” In most passages the actual form of the altar is not in focus; the important fact is that it was a place where sacrifices were made.
\line Warning: In some South American languages a transliterated form of “altar” (or its Spanish or Portuguese equivalent) may occur. This word is often “borrowed” with a restricted meaning, sometimes referring to the shrine of a particular saint, or to the front section of a church, or to a patriotic shrine. When a borrowed word of this kind occurs, always check carefully what meaning it has for speakers of the receptor language in order to know whether or not it is suitable.
\line Similarly, translators may be tempted to use a transliteration of the word “altar” because that is what is used locally in the Roman Catholic, Anglican, or other church. As in the case of the term “priest,” it is recommended that this Christian term not be used as the basis for Old Testament translation, because it has a very different theological significance. See also \l target="REALIA:4.7">4.7 Cult place, high place\l*.
\key 4.2.1.1
\title Horns of the altar
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קֶרֶן
\trl qarnoth (plural form of qeren)
\ref H00202700200006 H00202700200018 H00202901200020 H00203000200024 H00203000300028 H00203001000010 H00203702500040 H00203702600028 H00203800200006 H00203800200018 H00300400700018 H00300401800014 H00300402500028 H00300403000024 H00300403400028 H00300801500024 H00300900900036 H00301601800054 H01100105000028 H01100105100036 H01100202800052 H01911802700022 H02401700100032 H02604301500036 H02604302000018 H03000301400030
\grk κέρας
\trl keras
\ref L06800900800078
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0254_sacrificial_sheep_en.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Horned stone altar|4.0\fig* Altar horns were projections from the four upper corners of an altar, shaped like the horn of a sacrificial animal. Some scholars maintain that the horns were intended to represent the animals sacrificed, but others feel that they originally functioned as points on which cooking utensils rested. In Israelite law the horns of the altar were also a place of refuge where a person who had accidentally killed someone could be safe from an avenging relative of the one who had been killed.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Even though the Hebrew word \i qeren\i* and the Greek word \i keras\i* are the same terms used to refer to the horns of animals (cattle or oxen, for example), it is not necessary to retain this image in translation. In some languages this may be the natural thing to do, but in others it will probably be better to use a word like “projections” (\a GNT\a*), “knobs” (\a Mft\a*), or “protruding corners.” Some may find it useful to expand the rendering for “horns”; for example, in \s H00202700200006\s* \a CEV\a* says “and make each of the four top corners stick up like the horn of a bull.” \fig |WEB-0443_incense_altar.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Horned incense altar|4.0\fig*
\line It would be possible to translate the literal phrase “the horns of the altar” as “the projections in the form of horns on the corners of the place of sacrifice [or, of the thing on which offerings are placed],” but there is no need for something so long and involved; the emphasis is not usually on the shape. For this reason in \s H03000301400030\s* \a GNT\a* has “The corners of every altar,” which makes clear the location instead of the shape. This will be a good solution in many languages.
\line \s H01911802700022\s*: The last two lines of this verse contain directions about the festival procession in the Temple, but there is some uncertainty concerning the exact meaning of the Hebrew, which seems to say “Bind up the festival with branches to [or, as far as] the horns of the altar.” \a HOTTP\a* says the Hebrew text can be taken in two different ways: “bind the feast victim(s) with ropes as far as the horns of the altar” or “line up the feast [pilgrims] with ropes at the horns of the altar,” meaning that the worshipers were enclosed within ropes to set them off as a holy people. \a HOTTP\a* follows \a NJPSV\a* in translating “ropes” instead of “branches” [or, boughs].” \a NJPSV\a* translates “bind the festal offering to the horns of the altar with cords.” \a NJB\a* has “Link your processions, branches in hand, up to the horns of the altar,” and explains the following in a footnote: “Ritual of the \i lulab\i*, branch of myrtle or palm, waved as the procession circled the altar.” These interpretations, however, seem rather doubtful, and the \a GNT\a* translation is recommended as a reasonable representation of the meaning of the text: “With branches in your hands, start the festival and march around the altar.” \a SPCL\a* has “Begin the festival, and take boughs up to the horns of the altar.” \a AT\a* says “Arrange the festal dance with branches, up to the horns of the altar.”
\key 4.2.2
\title Tabernacle altar
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִזְבֵּחַ
\trl mizbeach
\ref H00202700100010 H00202700100036 H00202700500014 H00202700500036 H00202700600012 H00202700700032 H00202804300036 H00202901200024 H00202901200048 H00202901300066 H00202901600028 H00202901800016 H00202902000084 H00202902100018 H00202902500018 H00202903600030 H00202903700012 H00202903700026 H00202903700042 H00202903800014 H00202904400018 H00203001800038 H00203002000032 H00203002800006 H00203100900006 H00203501600004 H00203800100008 H00203800300014 H00203800400010 H00203800700024 H00203803000022 H00203803000052 H00203903900004 H00204000600008 H00204000700024 H00204001000008 H00204001000030 H00204001000038 H00204002900006 H00204003000024 H00204003200022 H00204003300026 H00300100500052 H00300100700020 H00300100800054 H00300100900034 H00300101100014 H00300101100044 H00300101200054 H00300101300042 H00300101500014 H00300101500030 H00300101500044 H00300101600024 H00300101700028 H00300200200058 H00300200800042 H00300200900026 H00300201200020 H00300300200046 H00300300500014 H00300300800046 H00300301100012 H00300301300044 H00300301600012 H00300400700020 H00300401000028 H00300401800018 H00300401800052 H00300401900020 H00300402500030 H00300402500048 H00300402600014 H00300403000026 H00300403000048 H00300403100040 H00300403400030 H00300403400052 H00300403500044 H00300500900020 H00300500900042 H00300501200036 H00300600200040 H00300600200060 H00300600300054 H00300600300064 H00300600500012 H00300600600012 H00300600700032 H00300600800050 H00300700200036 H00300700500014 H00300703100018 H00300801100012 H00300801100026 H00300801500028 H00300801500044 H00300801500062 H00300801600056 H00300801900022 H00300802100042 H00300802400074 H00300802800022 H00300803000030 H00300900700018 H00300900800012 H00300900900040 H00300900900058 H00300901000042 H00300901200036 H00300901300034 H00300901400032 H00300901700028 H00300901800058 H00300902000028 H00300902400024 H00301001200058 H00301402000026 H00301601200022 H00301601800010 H00301601800058 H00301602000030 H00301602500016 H00301603300028 H00301700600018 H00301701100030 H00302102300020 H00302202200048 H00400302600036 H00400303100026 H00400401300010 H00400401400056 H00400402600040 H00400502500052 H00400502600026 H00400700100050 H00400701000016 H00400701000044 H00400701100044 H00400708400008 H00400708800044 H00401700300034 H00401700400038 H00401701100034 H00401800300034 H00401800500022 H00401800700026 H00401801700038 H00501202700020 H00501202700036 H00501602100016 H00502600400026 H00602202900036 H00900202800028 H00900203300016 H01100105000032 H01100105100040 H01100105300022 H01100202800056 H01100202900034 H01302102900022 H01400100500004 H01400100600012
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Rim, ledge\b*:
\heb כַּרְכֹּב
\trl karkov
\ref H00202700500010 H00203800400022
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0444_tabernacle_altar.jpg|col||© Ori229 (Wikimedia Commons)|Tabernacle altar|4.0\fig* The Tabernacle altar was made of acacia wood overlaid, perhaps inside and out, with bronze. It measured five cubits (2.5 meters; 8.3 feet) on a side and stood three cubits (1.5 meters; 5 feet) high. Around its top was a kind of ledge or rim (\i karkov\i* in Hebrew), the purpose of which is not given. The altar was hollow.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line See \l target="REALIA:4.2">4.2 Altars\l* and \l target="REALIA:4.2.1">4.2.1 Stone altar\l* above.
\line \b Rim, ledge\b*: The Hebrew word \i karkov\i* is found only in \s H00202700500014\s* and \s H00203800400010\s*, and its meaning is unclear. Some scholars think of it as a decorative “rim” (\a GNT\a*) around the altar that could also support the weight of the altar when lifted by the rings on the grating (\s H00202700400028\s*; see \l target="REALIA:4.2.3">4.2.3 Temple altar\l* for an illustration of a rim). Others imagine that it may have been a “ledge” (\a RSV\a*) wide enough for the officiating priests to stand on, but this is unlikely since the altar itself was only about 1.5 meters (5 feet) high.
\line It is not clear whether this rim was at the top, the middle, or the bottom of the altar. Neither is it clear whether it was on the inside or the outside of the altar. \a NAB\a* translates \i karkov\i* simply as “around,” since its root meaning may have been to surround or encircle. \s H00202700500014\s*a in \a NAB\a* reads “Put it [the grating] down around the altar, on the ground.”
\line Note that the Hebrew clause in \s H00202700501000\s* uses both the words “under” and “below,” possibly for emphasis or clarity. \a NJPSV\a* has “Set the mesh below, under the ledge of the altar,” and \a NJB\a* says “You will put it below the ledge of the altar, underneath.” Since there is so much uncertainty about the meaning of these terms, translators must choose either the idea of a “ledge” or a “rim.” We may assume that it was a structural rim located probably around the top of the altar.
\key 4.2.2.1
\title Grating, mesh
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִכְבָּר
\trl mikbar
\ref H00202700400008 H00203501600014 H00203800500020 H00203800500020 H00203803000032 H00203903900014
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Ring\b*:
\heb טַבַּעַת
\trl taba‘ath
\ref H00202700400028 H00202700700014 H00203800500008 H00203800700016
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Pole\b*:
\heb בַּד
\trl bad
\ref H00202700600006 H00202700600014 H00202700700008 H00202700700022 H00203800500032 H00203800600010 H00203800700010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0445_grating_en.jpg|col||Don Ellens, The Tabernacle of Israel, 1888|Grating|4.0\fig* The grating of the Tabernacle altar was similar to a spider’s web with a fine meshwork, except that it was made of bronze. Its purpose is not explained, but it was probably intended to hold the burning coals and allow the ashes and grease to fall through to the ground, as well as to allow for a draft of air to pass through from underneath. Both were necessary for a hot fire. On the four upper corners of the grating were attached bronze rings. Poles were inserted through these rings for transporting the altar.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word for grating (\i mikbar\i*) is related to the word for “sieve” in \s H03000900900038\s*. The Hebrew phrase that describes it in \s H00202700400008\s* is \i ma‘aseh resheth\i*, which is literally “net-work.” The exact position and function of this mesh are disputed. Some scholars have suggested that it was simply wrapped around the bottom half of the altar as a decoration, perhaps also serving to strengthen the wooden frame of the altar; for example, \a CEV\a* renders \s H00202700400008\s*a as “cover the bottom half of the altar with a decorative bronze grating.” Most, however, understand it as it is described above. Its placement on or in the altar was related in some way to the rim or ledge, which went around the top of the altar (see \l target="REALIA:4.2.2">4.2.2 Tabernacle altar\l*). \fig |WEB-0446_grating.jpg|col||© Ben P L (Wikimedia Commons)|Grating inside the altar|4.0\fig*
\line “So that the net shall extend halfway down the altar” (\s H00202700501000\s*b in \a RSV\a*) is literally “and the net will be until half of the altar.” This does not indicate whether it means halfway down or “halfway up the altar” (\a GNT\a*). Most translations have “halfway up,” suggesting that the grating was placed in some way at the lower half of the altar. But \a RSV\a* and \a NRSV\a* suggest that this grating was near the top. It is probably better for translators to follow this interpretation.
\line As can be seen from an overview of various translations, it is possible to translate \s H00203800401000 H00203800501000\s* and the parallel passage in \s H00202700401000 H00202700701000\s* without actually leaving the reader with a clear picture of how the grating, rim, and altar were related. While it is true that the functions of the rim and the grating are disputed, a clear description of one feasible option is to be preferred to a rendering that is meaningless to the reader. The following model is given in \i A Handbook on Exodus\i* (page 635):
\line 4 Make a bronze grating, like a strainer, and attach a bronze ring at each of its four corners. 5 Then place the grating under the rim that goes around the altar, so that it extends halfway down inside the altar.
\line Another possible model is:
\line 5 Build a rim around the altar near the top, and hang a bronze grating from it extending halfway down inside the altar. At each of the four corners of the grating attach a bronze ring.
\line \b Rings and poles\b*: \s H00202700401000\s* says that bronze rings were to be put on the “ends” or “edges” of the grating. Verse 7 describes the placing of the poles into “the rings, so that the poles shall be upon the two sides of the altar” (\a RSV\a*). The Hebrew seems to indicate that there is only one set of rings, those attached to the grating, and that they were used to carry the entire altar. The placement of the rings will depend on the translator’s understanding of the grating as discussed above. If the “grating” is understood as a mesh going around the outside of the altar, then the rings are simply attached to the mesh. If, on the other hand, the “grating” is understood to be horizontal and sitting inside the altar, the rings projected through the corners of the altar so that the poles could be put through them.
\line The poles were placed into the rings for carrying the altar, and they were probably removed after it had been set into place. Where a language distinguishes between installing an object permanently or temporarily, the latter option is the correct one here. This may mean using a different verb in \s H00202700701000\s* from the one used in \s H00202501401000\s* (see the discussion under \l target="REALIA:4.1">4.1 Covenant Box, Ark of the Covenant\l*).
\key 4.2.3
\title Temple altar
\cont \u References:\u*
\arm מַדְבַּח
\trl madbach
\ref A01500701700042
\heb מִזְבֵּחַ
\trl mizbeach
\ref H01100802200012 H01100803100036 H01100805400046 H01100806400068 H01100902500028 H01201101100048 H01201201000036 H01201601100016 H01201601200026 H01201601200040 H01201601300044 H01201601400008 H01201601400042 H01201601400066 H01201601500032 H01201601500118 H01201802200038 H01202100400006 H01202100500006 H01202300900016 H01300603400014 H01301604000014 H01302200100024 H01400400100006 H01400501200066 H01400601200010 H01400602200034 H01400700700048 H01400700900024 H01400801200016 H01401500800076 H01402301000052 H01402901800032 H01402901900044 H01402902100074 H01402902200030 H01402902200050 H01402902200070 H01402902400020 H01402902700020 H01403201200020 H01403300400006 H01403300500006 H01403301600012 H01403501600038 H01500300200038 H01500300300008 H01601003500066 H01902600600016 H01904300400008 H01905102100022 H01908400400026 H01911802700026 H02300600600036 H02303600700038 H02305600700034 H02306000700024 H02500200700006 H02600800500046 H02600801600042 H02600900200076 H02604004600030 H02604004700032 H02604301300010 H02604301300064 H02604301800026 H02604302200034 H02604302600012 H02604302700040 H02604501900046 H02604700100076 H02900101300016 H02900201700014 H03000900100014 H03800901500046 H03801402000054 H03900100700006 H03900101000020 H03900201300016
\heb שֻׁלְחָן
\trl shulchan
\ref H03900100700026 H03900101200014
\grk βωμός
\trl bōmos
\ref L07105001200028 L07105001400010 L07700105900022 L07800201900044 L07801300800018
\grk θυσιαστήριον
\trl thusiastērion
\ref G04000502300018 G04000502400016 G04002302000012 G04002303500062 G04201105100022 G04600901300030 G04600901300036 G04601001800026 G05800701300028 G05801301000004 G06601100100034
\lat altare
\ref V08201002100020
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0422_altar_temple_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Temple altar|4.0\fig* Inside the Temple courtyard in Jerusalem there was a large, boxlike structure, made of bronze, which had a grate or grid in it. It stood outside the Holy Place. The priests kept a fire there all the time, for burning the animals that people brought to sacrifice to God. According to \s H01400400101000\s*, this altar was made by Solomon and was 10 meters (33 feet) square and 5 meters (16.5 feet) high. The priests actually stood on top of this large altar, working at one of several fires maintained there. Access to the altar was by a large ramp (larger than the one in the illustration below).
\line This altar may have been constructed in steps or platforms or terraces. Such an altar, with three levels, is mentioned and described in \s H02604301301000-H02604301701000\s*. The base would have had the dimensions given above, while the total height was 5 meters. The height of each level is not known.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line See the discussion at \l target="REALIA:4.2">4.2 Altars\l* and \l target="REALIA:4.2.1">4.2.1 Stone altar\l* above.
\key 4.2.4
\title Incense altar
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִזְבֵּחַ, מִקְטָר, קְטֹרֶת
\trl mizbeach (miqtar qetoreth)
\ref H00203000100006 H00203002700036 H00203100800040 H00203501500006 H00203702500008 H00203903800006 H00204000500008 H00204002600008 H00300400700020 H00400401100006 H01100602000046 H01100602200032 H01100704800024 H01300603400014 H01302801800006 H01400401900028 H01402601600044 H01402601900064 H02604102200004
\heb מְקַטֶּרֶת
\trl meqatereth
\ref H01403001400030
\heb לְבֵנָה
\trl lvenah
\ref H02306500300034
\heb שֻׁלְחָן
\trl shulchan
\ref H02604102200048 H02604401600018
\grk θυμιατήριον
\trl thumiatērion
\ref G05800900400006
\grk θυσιαστήριον, θυμίαμα
\trl thusiastērion (tou thumiamatos), thumiama
\ref G04200101100020 G06600600900020 G06600800300018 G06600800300032 G06600800300054 G06600800500028 G06600901300030 G06601401800014 G06601600700008 L07700102100022 L07700404900024 L07700405000010 L07800200500032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0447_incense_altar.jpg|col||© Ori229 (Wikimedia Commons)|Incense altar|4.0\fig* The incense altar was a boxlike table, made of wood. It was completely covered over with beaten gold. This was a relatively small altar, about one meter (40 inches) high and 50 centimeters (20 inches) square. According to \s H00203001001000\s*, this altar also had “horns” (see \l target="REALIA:4.2.1.1">4.2.1.1 Horns of the altar\l*). It stood inside the Holy Place in the Tabernacle and in the Temple in Jerusalem, and a priest burned incense (see \l target="REALIA:4.4.7.1">4.4.7.1 Incense, frankincense\l*) on it daily and prayed.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Incense altar” may be rendered in some languages as “place where incense is burned in worship of God.” Translators must avoid a rendering that would imply that the altar was made of incense. Alternative models are “table/place/brazier/hearth where people burned incense to God” or “. . . where people burned oil that smelled sweet to God.” \fig |PTZ-0080_high_priest_incense_altar.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|High Priest at the incense altar|4.0\fig*
\line If there is any comparable kind of table or charcoal stove used for ceremonial purposes in the receptor-language culture, this may be an appropriate word to use.
\line The relationship between the incense altar and the censers of the priests (see \l target="REALIA:4.4.7">4.4.7 Censer\l*) may seem confusing. The comments of Noordtzij (page 144) may be helpful: “The use of censers for the burning of incense here [\s H00401600601000\s*, \s H00401601701000\s*] has led some to conclude that this author did not know of the golden altar of incense of \s H00203000101000-H00203001001000\s*; \s H00203702501000-H00203702901000\s*, but this is based on a misunderstanding. The altar was used for the daily burning of incense in order to close off, as it were, the most holy place from the Holy Place by means of a cloud of incense, so that the proximity of the Lord who dwelled above the ark would not be dangerous to the priests. But the censer was used when the priest (in Israel this was only the high priest!) approached the ark itself (\s H00301601201000 H00301601301000\s*).” However, see also the comments below at \l target="REALIA:4.4.5">4.4.5 Small shovel, firepan\l*.
\line The incense altar of the Tabernacle was carried by poles inserted through rings attached to its sides (\s H00203000401000 H00203000501000\s*; \s H00203702701000 H00203702801000\s*). See the discussion at \l target="REALIA:4.1">4.1 Covenant Box, Ark of the Covenant\l* above. Unlike the poles used to carry the Covenant Box, the poles for other objects, such as the incense altar, were removed after the piece of furniture was set in its appointed place.
\line \s H02306500300034\s*: The exact meaning of the literal clause “they burn incense on bricks” is not clear. What is clear is that the prophet is speaking against some pagan practice adopted by the people of Israel. Translators may wish to follow \a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*, and \a SPCL\a* by rendering “bricks” as “altars of brick” (similarly \a REB\a*). \a GNT\a* is even more explicit with “pagan altars.” The main point of the prophecy is that the incense was being burned in a forbidden way, in a location other than the incense altar in the Temple.
\line \s G06600600900020 G06600800300018 G06600800500028 G06600901300030 G06601100101000 G06601401800014 G06601600700008\s*: There are eight references to an altar in Revelation, but commentators are divided as to whether John is speaking of the same altar each time and which altar he intends in any given verse. A comment by Mounce (page 157) on \s G06600600900020\s* is attractive: “It is probably unimportant to conjecture whether the altar is the altar of burnt offering or the altar of incense. The theme of sacrifice would suggest the former, and the prayers which rise (vs. 10) seem to indicate the latter. There is no reason why in John’s vision the two should not blend together as one.” The distinction will be important, however, if a translator has no general word for altar that can retain the ambiguity of Revelation and include both types of altar. Where a translator must choose between a word meaning “altar for burning animal sacrifices” and a word meaning “incense altar,” there are two basic options: 1) choose one of the two words and use it consistently throughout the book, or 2) choose the word according to the context.
\line In the book of Revelation an altar is first mentioned at \s G06600600901000\s*; however, it is referred to as if both it and its location are already well known, or the author assumes that the readers are aware that they are in a Temple-like setting. This kind of reference should be retained, even though readers of the translation may not yet be acquainted with it. The word chosen should make it clear that this altar is dedicated to God.
\key 4.3
\title Furniture of the Tabernacle and Temple
\index \l target="REALIA:4.3.1">4.3.1 Tabernacle: Washstand, basin, bowl\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.3.2">4.3.2 Temple: Sea, tank\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.3.3">4.3.3 Temple: Movable stand, cart, stand, base\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.3.4">4.3.4 Lampstand, menorah\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.3.5">4.3.5 Table for consecrated bread\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.3.6">4.3.6 Tables for preparing sacrificial victims\l*
\cont Some of the Tabernacle furniture was preserved or duplicated in the Temple built by Solomon. Items like the Ark of the Covenant and the lampstand were preserved, so they remained unchanged from the temporary sanctuary to the permanent one. However, one object in particular underwent a significant change, one that can be rather confusing to the reader and the translator. A large washbasin stood between the sacrificial altar and the Holy Place in the Tabernacle. It served the dual purpose of (1) washing the hands and feet of those about to offer sacrifices or to enter the Holy Place and (2) washing the bodies of animals about to be sacrificed.
\line The single standing washbasin of the Tabernacle is not found in the description of Solomon’s Temple, which contained two different objects for the two kinds of washing. They are described in \s H01400400601000\s*: “He also made ten lavers in which to wash, and set five on the south side, and five on the north side. In these they were to rinse off what was used for the burnt offering, and the sea was for the priests to wash in” (\a RSV\a*). The water with which the priests washed was contained in a large tank called a “sea.” The water for washing the many sacrifices was held in ten tubs set in movable stands.
\key 4.3.1
\title Tabernacle: Washstand, basin, bowl
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כִּיּוֹר
\trl kiyor
\ref H00203001800006 H00203002800026 H00203100900026 H00203501600040 H00203800800010 H00203903900040 H00204000700010 H00204001100010 H00204003000010 H00300801100042
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The basin was a large copper pot that stood on a copper base. It was used by the priests to wash their hands and feet. It was probably open at the top for filling with water and may have had spouts near the bottom to allow the water to run out. According to \s H00203001801000\s*, it stood “between the tent of meeting and the altar” (\a RSV\a*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The priests were commanded to wash their hands and feet before beginning their daily work. This was a ceremonial act of purification for which the basin held the water.
\line The word “laver,” used by some English translations (for example, \a RSV\a* and \a NJPSV\a*), is obscure and communicates little to the average reader. \a NCV\a* “bowl” is likely to be perceived as something much smaller than its actual size. It is better to say “large bowl” (so \a CEV\a*) or “large basin.”
\key 4.3.2
\title Temple: Sea, tank
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יָם
\trl yam
\ref H01100702300010 H01100702400034 H01100702500024 H01100702500046 H01100703900048 H01100704400008 H01100704400030 H01201601700044 H01202501300030 H01202501600010 H01301800800036 H01400400200010 H01400400300034 H01400400400024 H01400400400046 H01400400600050 H01400401000008 H01400401500006 H02405201700032 H02405202000010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0026_bronze_sea.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Artist's drawing of the bronze Sea|4.0\fig* The Sea was a very large tank or pool for holding water. It was made of bronze and was 2.5 meters (8 feet) deep, 5 meters (16.5 feet) in diameter, and about 15 meters (49 feet) in circumference at its rim. Its sides were almost 8 centimeters (about 3 inches) thick. When empty, it would have weighed 25-30 tons or more. The two places where it is described differ on the amount of water it could hold; \s H01100702601000\s* indicates 38,000 liters (10,000 gallons), while \s H01400400501000\s* has 57,000 liters (15,000 gallons). It is not clear from the texts whether the Sea was shaped like a bowl (hemisphere) or a cylinder standing on end. According to \s H01100702401000\s* and \s H01400400301000\s*, around its outer edge were two rows of bronze gourds (\a NRSV\a* “panels”; \a NCV\a* “plants”) as decoration. The “legs” of the Sea were 12 oxen, also made of bronze, in four sets of three each. They faced outward, and the Sea rested on their backs. \s H01400400601000\s* states that the water was used by the priests for washing, but details are lacking.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages it will be best to use a descriptive phrase for “Sea”; compare \a NCV\a*, which renders it “large round bowl, which was called the Sea” in \s H01100702301000\s*. While this basin is called \i yam\i* (“Sea”) in Hebrew, there is no reason why a translation needs to retain this metaphorical name.
\key 4.3.3
\title Temple: Movable stand, cart, stand, base
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Box on wheels\b*:
\heb מְכוֹנָה
\trl mkonah
\ref H01100702700010 H01100702700028 H01100702800010 H01100703000014 H01100703200034 H01100703400016 H01100703400026 H01100703500010 H01100703500032 H01100703700014 H01100703800050 H01100703800062 H01100703900010 H01100704300008 H01100704300026 H01201601700020 H01202501300024 H01202501600020 H01400401400008 H01400401400026 H02402701900032 H02405201700026 H02405202000032
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Water container\b*:
\heb כִּיּוֹר
\trl kiyor
\ref H00203001800006 H00203002800026 H00203100900026 H00203501600040 H00203800800010 H00203903900040 H00204000700010 H00204001100010 H00204003000010 H00300801100042 H01100703000044 H01100703800008 H01100703800020 H01100703800036 H01100703800042 H01100704000012 H01100704300018 H01201601700036 H01400400600006 H01400401400018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0027_laver_stand.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Movable stand|4.0\fig* A detailed description of the movable stand is given in \s H01100702701000-H01100703901000\s*. It was a box about 2 meters (6.5 feet) long, 2 meters (6.5 feet) wide, and 1.5 meters (5 feet) deep. The sides were bronze panels decorated with figures of various animals. The box stood on four wheels connected to axles on its four corners. The wheels were about 65 centimeters (25 inches) in diameter. On the upper corners of the box were four handles. Thus it was a kind of large decorated pushcart.
\line The top of the box was left open, and lining the top part of its inside was a round strip or sleeve in which sat a round container, also made of bronze. This container may have been shaped like a bowl or basin, or it may have been more like a cone, tapering down almost to a point. According to \s H01400400601000\s*, the container held water for washing the parts of the animals that were to be burned as sacrifices (see \s H00300100901000\s*, \s H00300101301000\s*). Given the size of the cart, the fact that it was made of bronze, and the weight of the large volume of water in it (about 800 liters [200 gallons]), it would have been very difficult to move, even though it had wheels. It has been estimated that each stand, when filled with water, could have weighed between two and three tons.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \b Box on wheels\b*: For the Hebrew word \i mkonah\i*, some translations choose a word that indicates a more or less stationary object (\a KJV\a* and \a SPCL\a* “base”; \a RSV\a* “stand”), while others have a word which indicates that movement was normal (\a GNT\a* and \a FRCL\a* “cart”; \a REB\a* “trolley”). Perhaps better than any of these words is “movable stand” in \a NIV\a* and \a CEV\a*. This expression indicates that the object normally stood in one place but was designed to be moved if necessary. \s H01100703900010\s* may indicate that the ten stands/carts had fixed positions.
\line \b Water container\b*: Most translations consulted render the Hebrew word \i kiyor\i* in the passages listed above as “basin” (for example, \a GNT\a* and \a NIV\a*). Perhaps it is better to say “tub” or “vat” (\a TOB\a*). While the word \i kiyor\i* is the same one used for the washstand in the Tabernacle, its construction was quite different in the Temple.
\line As noted above, \s H01100702701000-H01100703901000\s* describes in detail the structure of the movable stand. Several other elements are named there. These include the rectangular or square panels (\i misgaroth\i* in Hebrew) that formed the walls of the box, the frames (\i shlabim\i*) into which the panels were set, the spoked wheels (\i ’ofanim\i*; see \l target="REALIA:8.3">8.3 Wheel\l*) and the axles (\i sarnim\i* or \i yadoth\i*) on which they turned, and four corner supports (\i yadoth\i* or \i kthefoth\i*) for the water. The round opening (\i ‘agol\i*) at the top of the stand was decorated with “carvings” (\a GNT\a*; \a NASB\a* “engravings”; \i miqla‘oth\i*), and the base was decorated or carved with something that may have resembled “wreaths” (\i loyoth\i*; \a GNT\a* “spiral figures”). The water container was set in a circular collar (\i kothereth\i*, literally “crown”). See the discussion on these verses in \i A Handbook on 1-2 Kings\i*.
\key 4.3.4
\title Lampstand, menorah
\index \l target="REALIA:4.3.4.1">4.3.4.1 Snuffer, wick trimmer\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מְנוֹרָה
\trl mnorah
\ref H00202503100006 H00202503100018 H00202503200018 H00202503200034 H00202503300066 H00202503400008 H00202503500060 H00202603500028 H00203002700024 H00203100800022 H00203501400006 H00203701700010 H00203701700024 H00203701800018 H00203701800034 H00203701900062 H00203702000008 H00203903700006 H00204000400028 H00204002400010 H00302400400006 H00400303100020 H00400400900016 H00400800200032 H00400800300018 H00400800400010 H00400800400052 H01100704900008 H01200401000032 H01302801500008 H01302801500024 H01302801500028 H01302801500038 H01302801500050 H01302801500060 H01302801500064 H01400400700008 H01400402000008 H01401301100062 H02405201900040 H03800400200028 H03800401100030
\grk λυχνία
\trl luchnia
\ref G05800900200020 L07102601700008 L07700102100032 L07700404900018 L07700405000026
\lat candelabrum
\ref V08201002200034
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0423_lampstand_parts_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Lampstand|4.0\fig* The construction of the lampstand in the Tabernacle is discussed in \s H00202503101000-H00202504001000\s*; \s H00203701701000-H00203702401000\s*; \s H00302400101000-H00302400401000\s*. It was shaped from a single block of gold and consisted of five distinct parts. These parts were the base, the shafts (or stems), and the flowerlike cups with buds and petals. The lampstand had a central shaft, which stood on a base and out of which projected six arms, making a total of seven branches. A lamp that burned oil stood on the top of each of these branches.
\line Only one lampstand was prescribed for the Tabernacle. However, when Solomon built and furnished the Temple, he is said (\s H01100704901000\s*; \s H01400400701000\s*) to have included ten lampstands. No explanation is given in the text for the increase to ten. Solomon also furnished the Temple with ten tables and ten washbasins, where only one of each was called for in the Tabernacle. One Jewish tradition says that the ten lampstands were in addition to the single prescribed lampstand and that their location “to the right” and “to the left” meant to the right and left of the single holy lampstand. We have no indication that the structure of the lampstand changed in Solomon’s time, and the ten lampstands which he made probably looked like the one described for the Tabernacle.
\line \fig |KNW-0424_lampstand_branch_parts_en.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Branch of lampstand|4.0\fig* For the basic functioning of oil lamps, see \l target="REALIA:5.1">5.1 Oil lamp and wick\l* and \l target="REALIA:5.2">5.2 Lampstand\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Since there is no special word for “lampstand” in many cultures, it may have to be translated “lamp holder” or “thing on which lamps are placed.” It should be emphasized that this object did not hold candles but oil lamps (see \l target="REALIA:5.1">5.1 Oil lamp and wick\l*).
\line The lampstand (\i mnorah\i* in Hebrew) is mostly described in terms of flower parts. Knowing this may be helpful when seeking for appropriate terms to translate the individual parts of the lampstand. The flowerlike parts included “stems,” “buds” or “calyxes,” and “cups,” which were like the heads of open flowers. \a ITCL\a* includes the following useful footnote: “The terms used in the Hebrew text are difficult to interpret. It has been suggested that the decorations of the lampstand were taken from the world of plants and flowers.”
\line \fig |KNW-0277_levite_lampstand.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Lighting the menorah|4.0\fig* In \s H00202503100006\s*, where the parts of the lampstand are listed, \a CEV\a* has simply “The whole lampstand, including its decorative flowers, must be made of a single piece of hammered gold.” \a GECL\a* is even more condensed with “It must be made with all of its parts from one piece [of gold].” This solution may be adopted by some translations for this verse, although it will still be necessary to translate individual parts of the lampstand in the verses that follow.
\line \s H00302400400006\s*: In this verse the Hebrew text literally speaks of “the pure lampstand” (so \a NJB\a*, \a NJPSV\a*), which possibly refers to the sacred character or ritual cleanness of the lampstand without reference to the gold of which it was made. \a NEB\a*, for example, has “the lamp-stand, ritually clean.” But the majority of versions (for example, \a NIV\a*) take it to mean “the pure gold lampstand.” If the “pure gold” interpretation is followed, the idea of “purity” in this case may have to be expressed as “containing no other things” or “made of nothing but [gold].” The word for “gold” may have to be borrowed in some languages (in which case, it should be explained in the glossary).
\line The parts of the lampstand, from bottom to top, were:
\line \i Yarek\i* (\s H00202503100020\s*; \s H00203701700026\s*; \s H00400800400018\s*): This Hebrew word refers to the “base” or “foot” on which the entire lampstand stood. In \s H00400800401000\s* the literal phrase “from its base to it’s flowers” (\a RSV\a*) may be rendered “from top to bottom” (so \a GNT\a*).
\line \i Qaneh\i* (\s H00202500010000\s* [12 times]; \s H00203700010000\s* [12 times]): This Hebrew word literally means “reed.” In \s H00202500000000\s* and \s H00203700000000\s* it indicates a long, straight stem of a flower. There were six of these stems on the lampstand, three on each side symmetrically, coming out of a central one, making a total of seven. \a GECL\a* drops the flower image and calls them “arms.” This will be natural where a multi-branched candlestick is known, but it may sound strange where such an item is unknown.
\line \i Gavi‘a\i* (\s H00202503101000\s*, \s H00202503301000 H00202503401000\s*; \s H00203701701000\s*, \s H00203701901000 H00203702001000\s*): This Hebrew word refers to a kind of cup at the top of each of the seven stems of the lampstand. Olive oil and wicks that burned, giving off light, were placed into the seven cups. The cups were evidently shaped like the head of a flower when it is open. \a NCV\a* has “flower-like cups” (similarly \a NIV\a*). \a REB\a* has simply “cups,” while \a GNT\a* says “decorative flowers.”
\line \i Kaftor\i* (\s H00202500000000\s* [8 times]; \s H00203700000000\s* [8 times]): This Hebrew word is also used to designate the “capital” (so \a RSV\a* in \s H03000900101000\s*) of a column (see \l target="REALIA:3.5">3.5 Column, pillar, capital\l*). Here it seems to indicate a kind of knob or bulb, a swelling like a ball or an egg at the joints between the branches and where the head of the flower joined the stem. Most translations maintain the flower image by rendering this word “buds” (\a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*) or “calyxes” (\a NRSV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*).
\line \i Perach\i* (\s H00202500001000\s* [4 times]; \s H00203700001000\s* [4 times]; \s H00400800401000\s*; \s H01100704901000\s*; \s H01400402101000\s*): This Hebrew word means “flower,” or more specifically “bloom,” which is the head of a flower made by the open petals. The flowers of the lampstand formed the cups. While most translations keep the flower image for this word, they vary in how they express it. Some have “petals” (\a GNT\a*, \a NJPSV\a*), while others say “flowers” (\a RSV\a*).
\key 4.3.4.1
\title Snuffer, wick trimmer
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מְזַמֶּרֶת
\trl mzamereth
\ref H01100705000012 H01201201400016 H01202501400024 H01400402200006 H02405201800024
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line A snuffer is a kind of cap placed over the burning wick of a lamp to extinguish it by cutting off the air supply. The specific ones mentioned for the Temple service would have been made of gold.
\line A wick trimmer is a kind of scissors for cutting off the burnt part of the wick so that it makes less smoke when it burns.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Translations are divided concerning the proper identification of the Hebrew word \i mzamereth\i*. The word could indicate some kind of musical instrument, although no translation consulted reflects this meaning. The same Hebrew root can also mean “to cut, to trim” (see \s H00302500401000\s*), and it is on this basis that some versions (for example, \a NIV\a* and \a NCV\a*) interpret it to mean a kind of scissors for trimming a burnt wick. Others (for example, \a RSV\a* and \a CEV\a*) take it to be a kind of cap placed over the burning wick to put it out. Another interpretation is that it was a small plate set under a lamp to catch the ashes of the wick as it burned down.
\line In any society where oil lamps or at least extensive candle lighting is unfamiliar, it will be difficult to find a suitable term for this Hebrew word. Even something like “wick trimmers” (\a NCV\a*) or “lamp snuffers” (\a CEV\a*) is not readily understood by modern English readers. Translators are advised to select a term that will be understood by most people and, where possible, to include a note or glossary entry describing the operation of an oil lamp (see \l target="REALIA:5.1">5.1 Oil lamp and wick\l*).
\line Curtain, veil, drape: See \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.6">3.14.1.6 Curtain, veil, drape\l*.
\key 4.3.5
\title Table for consecrated bread
\index \l target="REALIA:4.3.5.1">4.3.5.1 Consecrated bread, bread of the presence, showbread\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שֻׁלְחָן
\trl shulchan (lechem hapanim, hama‘areketh)
\ref H00202502300006 H00202502800034 H00202503000010 H00202603500010 H00202603500034 H00202603500050 H00203002700008 H00203100800008 H00203501300006 H00203701000010 H00203701400032 H00203701500032 H00203701600018 H00203903600006 H00204000400010 H00204002200010 H00204002400022 H00302400600022 H00400303100014 H00400400700006 H01100704800036 H01302801600014 H01302801600022 H01302801600026 H01302801600034 H01400401900040 H01401301100054 H01402901800050
\grk τράπεζα, πρόθεσις
\trl trapeza (tēs protheseōs)
\ref G05800900200026 L07700102200006 L07700404900034 L07700405100010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0448_showbread.jpg|col||© Mboesch (Wikimedia Commons)|Table with loaves of bread|4.0\fig* The construction of this table is described in \s H00202502301000-H00202502801000\s*. The table was made of acacia wood and overlaid with gold. It was about one meter (40 inches) long, 50 centimeters (20 inches) wide, and 75 centimeters (30 inches) high. The instructions for Tabernacle furniture specify only one table for the showbread. When Solomon built the Temple, he increased the number of tables to ten, like he did with the lampstands and the washbasins. Since the instructions given to Moses on Mount Sinai were for one of each of these items, it is possible that there was only one official table with the others as a kind of decoration. In any case, the word \i shulchan\i* is used for all of them, and the same word that was used in \s H00202500000000\s* should be used to translate both the singular and the plural occurrences of the word in \s H01400400000000\s*. In \s H01302801600014\s* there is reference to “silver tables.” These are mentioned nowhere else in the Bible, and their purpose is not given. A good rendering for these tables is “tables covered with silver.”
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00302400600022\s*: This verse has the literal phrase “the pure table” (so \a NJB\a*, \a NJPSV\a*). The problem here is identical with “the pure lampstand” in verse 4. “Pure” may refer to the gold, or it may speak of ritual purity. \a NEB\a* translates “the table, ritually clean.” The two problems should be solved in the same manner. If the “pure gold” solution is followed, it will be better to say “the table covered with pure gold” (\a GNT\a*) rather than “the table made of pure gold” (see \s H00202502401000\s* and \s H00203701101000\s*).
\line The showbread table was carried by poles inserted through rings attached to its sides. Unlike the poles used to carry the Covenant Box, the poles for other objects, such as this table, were removed after the piece of furniture was set in its appointed place. See the discussion at \l target="REALIA:4.1">4.1 Covenant Box, Ark of the Covenant\l*.
\line See the discussion also at \l target="REALIA:5.7">5.7 Table for eating\l*.
\key 4.3.5.1
\title Consecrated bread, bread of the presence, showbread
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לֶחֶם
\trl lechem
\ref H00204002300010 H00902100700022
\heb לֶחֶם, פָּנֶה
\trl lechem hapanim
\ref H00202503000012 H00203501300026 H00203903600018 H00902100700022 H01100704800042 H01400401900046
\heb לֶחֶם, מַעֲרֶכֶת
\trl lechem hama‘areketh
\ref H01300903200018 H01302302900006 H01601003400004
\heb לֶחֶם, קֹדֶשׁ
\trl lechem qodesh
\ref H00902100500020 H00902100500034
\heb מַעֲרֶכֶת
\trl ma‘areketh
\ref H01302801600018 H01400200300038 H01402901800054
\heb מַעֲרֶכֶת, לֶחֶם
\trl ma‘areketh lechem
\ref H01401301100046
\heb פָּנֶה
\trl panim
\ref H00400400700010
\heb קֹדֶשׁ
\trl qodesh
\ref H00902100700012
\grk ἄρτος
\trl artos
\ref L07700405100012
\grk ἄρτος, πρόθεσις
\trl artoi tēs protheseōs
\ref G04001200400020 G04100202600026 G04200600400020 L07801000300054
\grk πρόθεσις
\trl prothesis
\ref L07700102200010
\grk πρόθεσις, ἄρτος
\trl prothesis tōn artōn
\ref G05800900200032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The showbread was set out as an offering in the presence of God in the Tabernacle and later in the Temple. The size and shape of the bread is not given in Scripture, although there is a detailed description of it in Jewish literature from the time of the New Testament.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The term “showbread” is an English attempt at translating what in Hebrew is literally “bread of the face/presence” or “bread laid out.” The translator should not try to reproduce the English term. In some languages “showbread” is rendered “bread placed before God” or “bread placed in the presence of God.” Others have “sacred bread” (\a GNT\a*), “sacred loaves of bread” (\a CEV\a*), or even “special bread” (\a NCV\a* in \s H01300903201000\s*).
\key 4.3.6
\title Tables for preparing sacrificial victims
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שֻׁלְחָן
\trl shulchan
\ref H00202502300006 H00202502700032 H00202502800034 H00202503000010 H00202603500010 H00202603500034 H00202603500050 H00203002700008 H00203100800008 H00203501300006 H00203701000010 H00203701400032 H00203701500032 H00203701600018 H00203903600006 H00204000400010 H00204002200010 H00204002400022 H00302400600022 H00400303100014 H00400400700006 H01100704800036 H01302801600014 H01302801600022 H01302801600026 H01302801600034 H01400400800006 H01400401900040 H01401301100054 H01402901800050 H02602304100014 H02604003900014 H02604003900024 H02604004000034 H02604004000060 H02604004100004 H02604004100014 H02604004100030 H02604004200006 H02604004300030 H02604102200048 H02604401600018 H03900100700026 H03900101200014
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Hooks\b*:
\heb שְׁפַתַּיִם
\trl shfatayim
\ref H02604004300006
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0449_sacrifice_table.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Sacrifice table|4.0\fig* Inside and outside the vestibule of the north gate of Ezekiel’s Temple, there were a number of tables made of hewn stone. They served several purposes in the slaughter and preparation of the sacrificial victims. They were to stand at a height of 50 centimeters (20 inches), and their tops were square, 75 by 75 centimeters (30 by 30 inches). We are not told if they had legs or stood on a single pedestal. On some of the tables were kept the implements used in the slaughter, skinning, and gutting of the victims.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Unlike furniture that was prescribed for the Tabernacle, these tables do not seem to be mobile. One problem in understanding \s H02604003900014 H02604004000034 H02604004100004 H02604004200006 H02604004300030\s* has to do with the number of tables. Most translations understand that there were eight tables altogether, four inside the vestibule and four outside (\a GNT\a* “\t 41\t* Altogether there were eight tables on which the animals to be sacrificed were killed: four inside the room and four out in the courtyard. \t 42\t* The four tables in the annex, used to prepare the offerings to be burned whole, were of cut stone . . .”). However, some understand that there were twelve tables altogether (\a NIV\a* “\t 41\t* So there were four tables on one side of the gateway and four on the other—eight tables in all—on which the sacrifices were slaughtered. \t 42\t* There were also four tables of dressed stone for the burnt offerings . . .”).
\line Verse 43 presents the translator with a couple of interrelated problems. The meaning of the Hebrew word \i shfatayim\i* is not certain. With a small change of its first letter, some versions take it to mean a “ledges/shelves” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a REB\a*, \a NJPSV\a*). Others understand it to mean “hooks” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a GECL\a*). In addition to its meaning, its location is also problematic. The Hebrew text (in the middle of describing the tables) says it was “inside all around.” If this means all around the tables, it makes little sense (\a NJPSV\a* “Shelves . . . were attached all around the inside”). How can we visualize shelves around the inside of the table? \a GNT\a* simply ignores the word for “inside” and says “Ledges 3 inches wide ran around the edge of the tables.” Some have avoided the problem by assuming that “all around” refers to the walls of the vestibule rather than the tables (\a CEV\a* “All around the walls of this room was a three inch shelf”). It is difficult to see the purpose of such a narrow shelf, if indeed it served any purpose at all. Rendering \i shfatayim\i* as “hooks” solves only part of the problems. The length of 75 millimeters (3 inches) would be reasonable for a hook. The problem of “all around inside” the tables is the same for hooks as it is for shelves. However, if “Hooks were anchored in the wall all around” (\a GECL\a*), then we can imagine several possible purposes for such hooks. They could have been used for hanging the work implements, or (as suggested by Jewish tradition) they could have been for hanging the freshly-slaughtered victim while its skin was removed (something that is difficult to do while it lies on a table). The form of the word \i shfatayim\i* suggests something doubled, so \a NIV\a* has “double-pronged hooks.”
\key 4.4
\title Tabernacle and Temple implements
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.1">4.4.1 Pan, pot, pail\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.2">4.4.2 Fork\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.3">4.4.3 Tongs\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.4">4.4.4 Basin, bowl\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.5">4.4.5 Small shovel, firepan\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.6">4.4.6 Large shovel, scraper\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.7">4.4.7 Censer\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.8">4.4.8 Plate\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.9">4.4.9 Incense dish\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.10">4.4.10 Jar for the wine offering, libation vessel\l*
\cont The sacrificial cult was a fairly messy business, and the work at the altar required a number of special implements to make things move more efficiently. The victims were killed by cutting the throat, which normally caused a large flow of blood. The blood was caught in a special container. Some of the blood was then sprinkled ceremonially on the altar, and the rest was poured out at the base of the altar. The sacrificial victim was laid on wood on the altar and burned. In order to speed up the process, the victim was occasionally turned. Because it was lying on a large fire, this turning required a long-handled instrument that could hold the meat and move it around; this instrument was a kind of long, heavy fork. Once the burning was completed, the remains of the meat and bones and greasy ashes had to be removed from the altar, so that it could be prepared for the next sacrifice. This operation was done with the same fork and with a long-handled instrument resembling a shovel (or perhaps a kind of rake or hoe), with which the ashes could be lifted or raked off the altar. These waste products were placed into a large bronze pot and were carried away from the altar and disposed of in a specially designated place outside. One final altar implement was a smaller type of shovel. Hot coals were removed from the altar with this shovel and carried to the smaller incense altar.
\line These five items are listed in \s H00202700301000\s* (referred to as “bowls,” “hooks,” “shovels,” “pans”, and “fire pans” in \a GNT\a*). They were all to be made of bronze. The exact description cannot be determined for all of them. On the other hand, some of them were more or less common items that were used also at home. Unless special words exist in the receptor language for a particular implement, translators may use the same word for both the secular and the religious item. It should be kept in mind that all of these items were made of heavy metal. The instruments themselves, then, would not have been so large as to make them difficult to lift.
\key 4.4.1
\title Pan, pot, pail
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סִיר
\trl sir
\ref H00202700300006 H00203800300020 H01100704500008 H01202501400008 H01400401100012 H01400401600008 H02405201800008 H02405201900032 H03801402000034 H03801402100008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0450_pot.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Pot|4.0\fig* The pot was a bronze container used to collect the ashes and animal remains that were on the altar after the sacrificial victim had been burned. The same implement could serve, in another context, as a simple, fairly large cooking pot (see \l target="REALIA:5.12">5.12 Cooking pot, kettle\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line See the comments at \l target="REALIA:4.4">4.4 Tabernacle and Temple implements\l* above.
\line \s H02405201800008 H02405201900032\s* mentions \i sir\i* two times as an object carried off to Babylon. It is not clear if two different items are referred to by the same name or if one item has been listed twice. Almost all translations consulted include the same word twice. \s H03801402000034 H03801402100008\s* speaks of a time when even common things will be put to holy use. The \i sir\i* in verse 20 is the Temple implement described here, while the \i sir\i* in verse 21 is the everyday pot in every home in Judah, which will one day be put into service like a Temple implement.
\key 4.4.2
\title Fork
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַזְלֵג
\trl mazleg
\ref H00900201300046 H00900201400044
\heb מַזְלֵג
\trl mizlgoth
\ref H00202700300022 H00203800300042 H00400401400032 H01302801700006 H01400401600024
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0451_fork.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Fork|4.0\fig* The fork was used in the Tabernacle and Temple to turn sacrificial victims on the altar or to remove them. Its exact form is unknown, but it may have resembled a hook or a kind of two-pronged fork.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line For the Hebrew word \i mizlgoth\i*, some translations (\a RSV\a*, \a REB\a*) have “forks,” while \a GNT\a* says “hooks.” However, a more descriptive expression is recommended, such as “meat forks” (\a NIV\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a FRCL\a*).
\line The Hebrew word \i mazleg\i* for fork used to describe the actions of the sons of Eli in \s H00900201300046 H00900201400044\s* differs slightly from the word \i mizlgoth\i*. It is reasonable to assume that they used something ready at hand, probably the same fork used at the altar. Translators are advised to use the same word. In many languages the word used for both of these will be the same as the word for a common fork, used as an item of table cutlery.
\key 4.4.3
\title Tongs
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מֶלְקָחַיִם
\trl melqachayim
\ref H00202503800004 H00203702300014 H00400400900032 H01100704900052 H01400402100018 H02300600600026
\heb מַעֲצָד
\trl ma‘atsad
\ref H02304401200006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0452_tongs.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Tongs|4.0\fig* A pair of tongs was a metal tool that was U-shaped. The user held the tool near its closed end; by squeezing its two arms together, it was possible to pick up hot coals or other objects. Tongs may be thought of as a large version of the tweezers often used today for plucking hairs or removing thorns or splinters.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i melqachayim\i* always refers to an implement used by the priests. Except for \s H02300600600026\s*, where no material is specified, they were all made of gold, and they were used in connection with the lamps of the Tabernacle and Temple. Some commentators understand the word \i melqachayim\i* in these passages to refer to a smaller set of tongs used to adjust or remove the wicks in the lamps (see \l target="REALIA:4.3.4.1">4.3.4.1 Snuffer, wick trimmer\l* and \l target="REALIA:5.1">5.1 Oil lamp and wick\l*). So in this context it would be a kind of “pincers” or large tweezers.
\line The Hebrew word \i ma’atsad\i* in \s H02304401200006\s* refers to tongs similar in construction to those used in the Tabernacle and Temple. The pair of tongs in this verse, however, was used by a blacksmith to hold hot metal while he worked on it.
\key 4.4.4
\title Basin, bowl
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַגָּן
\trl ’agan
\ref H00202400600022
\heb אֲגַרְטָל
\trl ’agartal
\ref H01500100900008 H01500100900014
\heb כְּפוֹר
\trl kfor
\ref H01302801700028 H01302801700040 H01302801700044 H01302801700050 H01302801700062 H01302801700066 H01500101000002 H01500101000008 H01500802700004
\heb מִזְרָק
\trl mizraq
\ref H00202700300018 H00203800300036 H00400401400048 H00400701300020 H00400701900022 H00400702500018 H00400703100018 H00400703700018 H00400704300018 H00400704900018 H00400705500018 H00400706100018 H00400706700018 H00400707300018 H00400707900018 H00400708400034 H00400708500024 H01100704000028 H01100704500024 H01100705000018 H01201201400018 H01202501500016 H01302801700012 H01400400800038 H01400401100028 H01400402200012 H01600706900040 H02405201800032 H02405201900024 H03000600600008 H03800901500040 H03801402000046
\heb מַחֲלָף
\trl machalaf
\ref H01500100900020
\heb סַף
\trl saf
\ref H01100705000006 H01201201400012 H02405201900008
\grk φιάλη
\trl fialē
\ref L07700102200022 L08100201000002
\grk χρύσωμα
\trl chrusōma
\ref L07800403200016 L07800403900054 L08100805600038
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0453_basin.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Bronze basin|4.0\fig* The basin was a concave dish used in Israelite worship for a variety of purposes, such as holding blood to be sprinkled or holding parts of sacrificial animals. It was probably shaped like a large bowl or perhaps like a pan or pitcher with a handle. For the most part, the basins mentioned in the Bible were made of gold or silver, although some in daily use were made of bronze (see \s H00202700301000\s* and \s H00203800301000\s*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The function of this basin was to hold liquids. It could be used to catch the blood of sacrificial victims but also to hold water for washing off the blood on the altar. Implements into which liquids can be poured are universally known. The size of the container chosen should not be too large or too small. \fig |KNW-0273_offering.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|High priest holding a basin|4.0\fig*
\line The Hebrew word \i ’agartal\i* appears only in \s H01500100900008\s*. The exact shape of the dishes referred to by this word is not in focus but rather that they were large and valuable. \a CEV\a* has “large … dishes”; others have “basins” (\a RSV\a*) or simply “bowls” (\a GNT\a*). The Hebrew word \i machalaf\i* in the same verse appears only here in Scripture, and its meaning is uncertain. Translations have suggested a variety of implements, including “knives” (\a NRSV\a*), “bowls” (\a GNT\a*), and “pans” (\a NIV\a*). The Hebrew word has the root meaning “change,” and it is possible that \i machalaf\i* (perhaps with different vowels) means simply “other vessels.” Something like \a REB\a* “vessels of various kinds” is recommended.
\line The Hebrew words \i saf\i* and \i mizraq\i* are listed together in \s H01100705000018\s*, and it is not clear how they differ from each other. A sampling of translations will illustrate the uncertainty: “cups … basins” (\a RSV\a*), “basins … sprinkling bowls” (\a NJPSV\a*, \a NIV\a*), “cups . . . small sprinkling bowls (\a CEV\a*). \a A Handbook on 1-2 Kings\a* suggests that the \i saf\i* was shallower than the \i mizraq\i*. On the other hand, Keil (page 115) says the \i saf\i* was a deep bowl, while the \i mizraq\i* was a bowl or can with a spout. The translator should choose two words for shallower and deeper dishes.
\key 4.4.5
\title Small shovel, firepan
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַחְתָּה
\trl machtah
\ref H00202503800008 H00202700300026 H00203702300018 H00203800300050 H00301000100018 H00301601200010 H00400400900038 H00400401400026 H00401600600010 H00401601700008 H00401601700030 H00401601700038 H00401601700050 H00401601800008 H00401700400014 H00401701100018 H01100705000030 H01202501500008 H01400402200024 H02405201900016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0263_firepan_en.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Firepan in use|4.0\fig* The firepan was used to move or turn coals on the altar and to carry them to the altar of incense for other purposes (see \l target="REALIA:4.2.4">4.2.4 Incense altar\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It has been suggested that the Hebrew word \i machtah\i* also designated a special container for holding the holy fire while the altar was being cleaned or when the Tabernacle was being moved. This would make it a kind of “fire receptacle.” Translators may also express this as “container for carrying away the hot ashes.”
\line In some of the references listed above, the word \i machtah\i* is associated with the burning of incense (\s H00301000100018 H00401600600010 H00401601700008 H00401601800008\s*). Where a specific word for “censer” exists, it may be used in these passages, although care should be taken that the word does not suggest a modern censer. A more general word for “firepan” is also acceptable, since it seems that in most of the references listed above the word \i machtah\i* refers to an implement that was used for carrying coals onto which incense was placed sometimes see also \l target="REALIA:4.2.4">4.2.4 Incense altar\l* and \l target="REALIA:4.4.7">4.4.7 Censer\l*.
\line \fig |WEB-0454_firepan.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Firepan|4.0\fig* In \s H00202503800008 H00203702300018\s* and \s H00400400900038\s* the \i machtah\i* is associated with the lampstand (see \l target="REALIA:4.3.4">4.3.4 Lampstand, menorah\l*). Some versions still translate it “firepans” in those places (\a REB\a*, \a NJPSV\a*), while others say “trays” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*). In either case, it is not clear what purpose the \i mach­tah\i* served in connection with the lampstand. The object described and illustrated here could have served multiple purposes.
\key 4.4.6
\title Large shovel, scraper
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יָע
\trl ya‘
\ref H00202700300014 H00203800300028 H00400401400040 H01100704000020 H01100704500016 H01202501400016 H01400401100020 H01400401600016 H02405201800016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0455_shovel.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Large shovels|4.0\fig* The scraper was used to remove the refuse from the altar after a victim had been burned. It may have resembled a kind of shovel, with which the ashes could be lifted, or a kind of rake or hoe, with which they could be scraped into the bronze pot (see \l target="REALIA:4.4.1">4.4.1 Pan, pot, pail\l*).
\key 4.4.7
\title Censer
\index \l target="REALIA:4.4.7.1">4.4.7.1 Incense, frankincense\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִקְטֶרֶת
\trl miqtereth
\ref H01402601900014 H02600801100040
\grk θυΐσκη
\trl thuiskē
\ref L07700102200028 L08100200900024
\grk θυμιατήριον
\trl thumiatērion
\ref L08000701100014
\grk λιβανωτός
\trl libanōtos
\ref G06600800300022 G06600800500012
\grk πυρεῖον
\trl pureion
\ref L07105000900012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0081_censer_firepan.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Censer and incense shovel|4.0\fig* The censer was a small bowl or pan in which incense was burned. It was usually made of metal. It had a handle so that the priest could hold it and carry it to the altar.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Coals, usually from the altar, were placed into the bowl or flat pan. On top of these coals was sprinkled a small amount of incense, which gave off a pleasant smell when it was burned by the coals.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Some cultures will be familiar with burning incense in religious ceremonies, and there may be a special word for the instrument in which this is done. However, translators should be careful not to choose a word that is associated only with the rites of cultic or non-Christian worship. It may be necessary to expand the expression by saying “small pan for burning sweet-smelling perfume.” See also \l target="REALIA:4.2.4">4.2.4 Incense altar\l* and \l target="REALIA:4.4.5">4.4.5 Small shovel, firepan\l*.
\key 4.4.7.1
\title Incense, frankincense
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לְבוֹנָה
\trl lvonah
\ref H00203003400032 H00300200100038 H00300200200042 H00300201500016 H00300201600028 H00300501100068 H00300600800034 H00302400700012 H00400501500056 H01300902900050 H01601300500032 H01601300900038 H02200300600026 H02200400600040 H02200401400020 H02304302300036 H02306000600028 H02306600300032 H02400602000008 H02401702600066 H02404100500046
\arm נִיחוֹחַ
\trl nichoach
\ref A01500601000008 A02700204600030
\heb קטר, קִטֵּר, קְטוֹרָה, קְטֹרֶת
\trl qatar (verb), qiter, qtorah, qtoreth
\ref H00202500600024 H00203000100008 H00203000700004 H00203000700010 H00203000700036 H00203000800022 H00203000800024 H00203000900008 H00203002700040 H00203003500008 H00203003700006 H00203100800044 H00203101100016 H00203500800028 H00203501500010 H00203501500032 H00203502800036 H00203702500012 H00203702900020 H00203903800026 H00204000500016 H00204002700004 H00204002700008 H00300200200046 H00300201600004 H00300400700022 H00300600800046 H00301000100034 H00301601200038 H00301601300010 H00301601300032 H00400401600024 H00400701400012 H00400702000012 H00400702600012 H00400703200012 H00400703800012 H00400704400012 H00400705000012 H00400705600012 H00400706200012 H00400706800012 H00400707400012 H00400708000012 H00400708600012 H00401600700016 H00401601700016 H00401601800024 H00401603500034 H00401700500036 H00401700500038 H00401701100040 H00401701200052 H00503301000020 H00900202800032 H00900202800034 H01100300300038 H01100902500040 H01101100800018 H01101203300080 H01101300100040 H01101300200064 H01102204400022 H01201200400022 H01201400400022 H01201500400022 H01201503500022 H01201600400008 H01201701100004 H01201800400066 H01202201700010 H01202300500022 H01202300500048 H01202300800032 H01300603400010 H01300603400028 H01302301300038 H01302801800010 H01400200300026 H01400200300032 H01400200500056 H01401301100004 H01401301100040 H01402501400054 H01402601600040 H01402601600048 H01402601800028 H01402601800052 H01402601900018 H01402601900068 H01402800300006 H01402800400008 H01402802500024 H01402900700024 H01402900700028 H01402901100042 H01403201200054 H01403402500010 H01403402500014 H01914100200006 H02002700900006 H02200300600020 H02300101300012 H02306500300028 H02306500700018 H02400101600022 H02400700900024 H02401101200030 H02401101300036 H02401101700048 H02401801500014 H02401900400024 H02401901300040 H02403202900058 H02404400300022 H02404400500030 H02404400800014 H02404401500022 H02404401700026 H02404401800012 H02404401900008 H02404402100010 H02404402300008 H02404402500058 H02404803500020 H02600801100054 H02601601800022 H02602304100024 H02800201500018 H02800401300020 H02801100200030 H03500101600014
\grk λίβανος
\trl libanos
\ref G04000201100056 G06601801300020 L07102401300012 L07102401500044 L07103901400006 L07105000800028 L07105000900008 L07105001200048 L07200101000034 L07900501000032
\grk θυμίαμα, θυμιάω
\trl thumiama, thumiaō (verb)
\ref G04200101000026 G04200101100024 G06600500800050 G06600800300032 G06600800400012 G06601801300012 L06700601700018 L06700800200026 L06800900100060 L07001802100026 L07104501600018 L07104900100010 L07300104200020 L07700105500022 L07700404900028 L07700405000004 L07800200500036 L07801000300044 L08500703800040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0456_incense_altar.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Incense on stands|4.0\fig* Incense was any aromatic substance (usually a resin) burned for its pleasing aroma.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Since some form of incense is very widely known, there is normally no difficulty involved in finding some term to designate “incense.” However, it is always possible to employ a descriptive phrase, for example, “a substance which gives off a sweet-smelling smoke” or “. . . a good smelling smoke.”
\line In the Bible the burning of incense occurs only in the context of religious worship, including both Israelite worship and pagan worship.
\line The Hebrew word \i lvonah\i* refers to “frankincense”; the Greek word \i libanos\i* is derived from \i lvonah\i*. “Frankincense” would always be a correct translation for these two words. Where no specific word for frankincense exists, a general word for “incense” will usually be acceptable. One exception is \s H00203003400032\s*, where frankincense is just one of several ingredients of the “incense” to be used in the Tabernacle. \i A Handbook on Exodus\i* (pages 734-735) suggests listing the ingredients by their names and then describing them in a glossary.
\line In \s A02700204600030\s* the Aramaic word \i nichoach\i* means “pleasing smell” and could refer to animal sacrifices or to incense or even to a combination of the two. If it is understood to refer to incense (so \a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*), it will be best to use a general word for incense. Other translations prefer “offerings” (\a GNT\a*), “soothing offerings” (\a REB\a*), or “pleasing offerings” (\a NJPSV\a*). The same word is used in \s A01500601000008\s*, where \a RSV\a* renders it “pleasing sacrifices” (similarly \a NIV\a*).
\line In \s H02002700900006\s* the Hebrew word \i qtoreth\i*, which appears together with (and follows) the word for “oil,” is understood by some versions to mean “perfume” in this context (so \a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*), but others render it “incense” (\a NIV\a*, \a REB\a*, \a NJPSV\a*).
\key 4.4.8
\title Plate
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קְעָרָה
\trl q‘arah
\ref H00202502900006 H00203701600022 H00400400700028 H00400701300006 H00400701900008 H00400702500004 H00400703100004 H00400703700004 H00400704300004 H00400704900004 H00400705500004 H00400706100004 H00400706700004 H00400707300004 H00400707900004 H00400708400026 H00400708500010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line For a description of an equivalent implement used in the home, see \l target="REALIA:5.20.2">5.20.2 Plate, platter\l*. All of the references listed above are to gold or silver plates in the Tabernacle.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i q‘arah\i* always appears together with \i kaf\i* (see \l target="REALIA:4.4.9">4.4.9 Incense dish\l*) in lists of Tabernacle implements. While the \i q‘arah\i* was probably somewhat less flat than today’s familiar dinner plate, it was not as deep as the \i kaf\i*, which was more like a bowl.
\key 4.4.9
\title Incense dish
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כַּף
\trl kaf
\ref H00202502900010 H00203701600028 H00400400700036 H00400701400002 H00400702000002 H00400702600002 H00400703200002 H00400703800002 H00400704400002 H00400705000002 H00400705600002 H00400706200002 H00400706800002 H00400707400002 H00400708000002 H00400708400042 H00400708600002 H00400708600020 H00400708600036 H01100705000024 H01202501400032 H01400402200018 H01402401400052 H02405201800040 H02405201900048
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The incense dish was an implement used to hold incense in the Tabernacle and Temple. It was probably used only to hold incense, not burn it, so it should not be confused with the censer.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i kaf\i* literally means “hand,” specifically the palm of the hand (or sometimes the sole of the foot). Most translations and commentators agree that it is used in the passages listed above to refer to the incense dish. The references in \s H00400700000000\s* specifically connect the \i kaf\i* to incense. Some translations choose to modify the rendering for \i kaf\i* with their word “incense”; for example, in \s H00400400700036\s* \a RSV\a* has “dishes for incense” and \a GNT\a* says “incense bowls.”
\line Cooking pot, kettle: see \l target="REALIA:5.12">5.12 Cooking pot, kettle\l*.
\key 4.4.10
\title Jar for the wine offering, libation vessel
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מְנַקִּית
\trl mnaqith
\ref H00202502900018 H00203701600034 H00400400700044 H02405201900056
\heb קַשְׂוָה
\trl qaswah
\ref H00202502900014 H00203701600042 H00400400700050 H01302801700018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0457_libation.jpg|col||© Mary Harrsch from Springfield, Oregon, USA|Figure with libation jar|4.0\fig* The libation in the Tabernacle and Temple was the pouring out of wine as an offering to God. Two vessels were involved in this operation. From the first vessel the wine was poured into the second one. Both vessels were placed on the table for consecrated bread (see \l target="REALIA:4.3.5">4.3.5 Table for consecrated bread\l*) and are only mentioned in connection with that table. The first container was a kind of jar or pitcher (\i qaswah\i* in Hebrew), and the second one was a small bowl (\i mnaqith\i* in Hebrew). Both objects were made of gold.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00202502900018 H00203701600034 H00400400700044\s*: In these passages the Hebrew words \i mnaqith\i* and \i qaswah\i* occur together with a verb that normally carries the meaning of “pouring out as a drink offering.” According to Jewish tradition, an alternate rendering of this word would define the two objects as part of a frame for covering and protecting the bread of God’s presence. In \s H00202502900018\s*b such a rendering would be something like “the rods and the side frames with which to cover them,” where \a RSV\a* has “its flagons and bowls with which to pour libations.” However, no translation consulted (not even \a NJPSV\a*) reflects this.
\key 4.5
\title High Priest’s clothing
\index \l target="REALIA:4.5.1">4.5.1 Undergarment, breeches, shorts\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.5.2">4.5.2 Tunic, shirt\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.5.3">4.5.3 Robe\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.5.4">4.5.4 Ephod\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.5.5">4.5.5 Sacred pocket, breastpiece\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.5.6">4.5.6 Sash, cloth belt\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.5.7">4.5.7 Forehead plate, forehead ornament\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.5.8">4.5.8 Turban, headdress\l*
\line \fig |PTZ-0082_garments_high_priest.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|High Priest's clothes|4.0\fig* The High Priest’s clothing consisted of eight items. First he put on, as an undergarment, a pair of linen shorts. Over these he wore the tunic, a kind of long shirt, and then he wrapped a sash around his waist. Over all of this, he put on a long blue robe. Next came the ephod, which was a kind of apron with its own belt and shoulder straps. Between the straps and the belt of the ephod was a jeweled breastpiece. The biblical description does not make it clear if the shoulder straps of the ephod reached all the way to the waist in the front (as shown in the illustration at the right), or if the breastpiece with its cords formed the bridge between the shoulder straps and the top of the ephod at the waist. Tied around his forehead was a gold plate, and on top of his head he wore a sort of turban.
\line The precise identification of the various articles of clothing is very difficult. In some cases the exact meaning is unknown. The translator should try to visualize the whole outfit and then formulate it in a way that is meaningful to the readers. Footnotes may be necessary in order to emphasize the fact that the full set of clothing mentioned here was special and reserved for the High Priest. Some of this clothing was also worn by the other priests. The practice of transliterating the Hebrew terminology should be avoided if at all possible, but if no other solution can be found, a footnote or glossary explanation will definitely be required.
\key 4.5.1
\title Undergarment, breeches, shorts
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִכְנָסַיִם
\trl miknasayim
\ref H00202804200008 H00203902800028 H00300600300016 H00301600400012 H02604401800014
\grk περισκελής
\trl periskelēs
\ref L07104500800020
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0458_shorts.jpg|col||© Ben P L (Wikimedia Commons)|Shorts|4.0\fig* The shorts were an undergarment for the lower body. The references above indicate that it was made of linen (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen\l*). While this garment was in common use, it is mentioned only in reference to the High Priest and his fellow priests. It was to be worn next to their skin, under their priestly garments.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The closest natural equivalent for “shorts” in the receptor language should be used. Some languages differentiate between undergarments worn by men and those worn by women. In all of the references listed above, a word for men’s undergarments should be chosen.
\key 4.5.2
\title Tunic, shirt
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כֻּתֹּנֶת
\trl kutoneth
\ref H00202800400026 H00202803900008 H00202804000012 H00202900500024 H00202900800014 H00203902700010 H00204001400016 H00300800700012 H00300801300018 H00301000500012 H00301600400002 H01500206900040 H01600706900044 H01600707100032
\grk χιτών
\trl chitōn
\ref G04101406300012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0425_priest_tunic.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Priest wearing a tunic|4.0\fig* The tunic was another undergarment worn by the High Priest and his fellow priests. It went over the shorts, but from the waist up it was next to the skin, and over top of it went the robe. It was a kind of shirt and probably had long sleeves and reached nearly to the ankles. It was woven of linen. It was probably pulled over the head and was held in place by a sash wound around the waist. See also \l target="REALIA:6.3">6.3 Shirt, tunic\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In ordinary usage the Hebrew word \i kutoneth\i* refers to an everyday article of clothing worn by men and women alike and was probably a sort of “shirt.” The \a RSV\a* rendering “coat” (\s H00202800400026\s*) is misleading since this piece of clothing was not an outer garment but one worn underneath other clothing and next to the body. \i Kutoneth\i* has often been translated “tunic” (\a NIV\a*, \a NEB\a*, \a NAB\a*, \a NJB\a*). “Shirt” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*) will be the closest equivalent in many languages. According to \s H00202800400026\s*, the tunic was “embroidered” (\a GNT\a*). For translating the word “embroidered,” see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.11">1.5.3.11 Embroidered cloth, needlework\l*.
\key 4.5.3
\title Robe
\index \l target="REALIA:4.5.3.1">4.5.3.1 Jinglet, bell\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִדָּה
\trl midah
\ref H01913300200038
\heb מְעִיל
\trl m‘il
\ref H00202800400022 H00202803100008 H00202803400024 H00202900500030 H00203902200008 H00203902300008 H00203902400012 H00203902500036 H00203902600020 H00300800700036 H00900201900004 H00901502700020 H00901800400012 H00902400500074 H00902401200016 H00902401200032 H00902801400028 H01001301800026 H01301502700010 H01500900300026 H01500900500028 H01800102000014 H01800201200036 H01802901400012 H01910902900016 H02305901700042 H02306101000026 H02602601600026
\grk ἔνδυμα
\trl enduma
\ref L07001802400008
\grk ἱμάτιον
\trl himation
\ref G04002606500012
\grk περιστολή
\trl peristolē
\ref L07104500700034
\grk ποδήρης
\trl podērēs
\ref L07001802400006 L07104500800024
\grk στολή
\trl stolē
\ref L07104501000002 L07105001100010 L07701002100012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The robe of the High Priest was worn on top of the tunic and thus was a kind of jacket or overshirt. It was woven of light blue wool thread. It was a long garment, hanging down to the ankles. It is not clear whether it had sleeves or not, nor whether it was open or closed in the front. Somewhat like a Latin American poncho, it may even have been a rectangular piece of cloth with a hole in the middle for the head. Around the hem of the robe were sewn alternating golden bells (see \l target="REALIA:4.5.3.1">4.5.3.1 Jinglet, bell\l*) and pomegranates made of woven threads. The robe was held in place by the ephod, which was worn over it. See the illustrations at \l target="REALIA:4.5">4.5 High Priest’s clothing\l* and \l target="REALIA:4.5.4">4.5.4 Ephod\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line This garment is sometimes called “the robe of the ephod” (so \a RSV\a* in \s H00202803100008 H00202900500030 H00203902200008\s*). This means simply that the ephod was worn over it.
\key 4.5.3.1
\title Jinglet, bell
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb פַּעֲמֹן
\trl pa‘amon
\ref H00202803300032 H00202803400002 H00202803400010 H00203902500006 H00203902500020 H00203902600002 H00203902600008
\grk κώδων
\trl kōdōn
\ref L07104500900012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0460_bell.jpg|col||© Ben P L (Wikimedia Commons)|Bells and jinglets|4.0\fig* Jinglets were small platelets of metal. Their exact size and shape are not known. They were sewn to the hem of the High Priest’s robe (see \l target="REALIA:4.5.3">4.5.3 Robe\l*). As he walked or moved, they knocked together making a jingling or tinkling sound.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Bells as we know them today, with a bell shape containing a ringing clapper, were not known at the time of Exodus and are probably not intended. Nevertheless, almost all the modern translations consulted render the Hebrew word \i pa‘amon\i* as “bells” (for example, \a RSV\a* and \a NIV\a*). Where a word for jingling platelets exists and is commonly understood, it should be used. Otherwise translators may use “bells,” since they have the same function and are not very different in form. Where “bells” are not known, it will be necessary to find some sort of ornamentation, made of pieces of metal (perhaps coins) or even shells, which makes a sound when the clothing is moved.
\key 4.5.4
\title Ephod
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֵפֹד, אֲפֻדָּה
\trl ’efod, ’afudah
\ref H00202500700016 H00202800400018 H00202800600010 H00202800800006 H00202801200020 H00202801500018 H00202802500036 H00202802600040 H00202802700026 H00202802700056 H00202802800026 H00202802800044 H00202802800062 H00202803100012 H00202900500034 H00202900500042 H00202900500064 H00203500900018 H00203502700032 H00203900200010 H00203900500006 H00203900700014 H00203900800020 H00203901800036 H00203901900038 H00203902000024 H00203902000054 H00203902100022 H00203902100040 H00203902100058 H00203902200012 H00300800700048 H00300800700062 H00403402300022 H00700802700012 H00701700500020 H00701801400054 H00701801700044 H00701801800022 H00701802000020 H00900201800018 H00900202800040 H00901400300032 H00902101000046 H00902201800080 H00902300600022 H00902300900036 H00903000700028 H00903000700040 H01000601400026 H01301502700060 H02303002200018 H02800300400040
\grk ἐπωμίς
\trl epōmis
\ref L07104500800028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0426_highpriest_clothing_en.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|High Priest's clothing|4.0\fig* The ephod of the High Priest was a kind of apron or vest with shoulder straps and a belt. The belt was an integral part of the ephod; it was wrapped around the waist and tied either in the front or the back (see also the discussion below). The top of the ephod was at about the bottom of the ribcage. According to a tradition preserved by Josephus (\i Antiquities\i* III 7, 5), the ephod had a length of one cubit (about 50 centimeters or 20 inches). This would mean that it extended approximately to the middle of the upper leg. The dimensions of the ephod are not given in Scripture.
\line In order to gain a better picture of the structure of this ephod, it is helpful to consider it together with the breastpiece (see \l target="REALIA:4.5.5">4.5.5 Sacred pocket, breastpiece\l*). According to one interpretation, the shoulder straps of the ephod were attached in the back and in the front of the ephod, and the breastpiece was attached to these straps in the front by gold rings. This is demonstrated in the illustration at \l target="REALIA:4.5">4.5 High Priest’s clothing\l*. According to another interpretation, the shoulder straps of the ephod did not reach the belt at the top of the ephod. The space between the end of the straps and the belt (about 25 centimeters or 10 inches) was taken up by the breastpiece. On the four corners of the breastpiece were sewn gold rings. The lower two rings were tied with a blue thread to corresponding rings in the belt of the ephod. The upper rings of the breastpiece were connected to the ends of the shoulder straps by means of small gold chains. On the end of each shoulder strap was a kind of clasp consisting of a precious stone in a gold setting. Engraved on these stones were the names of the twelve tribes of Israel. It was to these devices that the other ends of the gold chains were attached. See the illustrations here and \l target="REALIA:4.5.5">4.5.5 Sacred pocket, breastpiece\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Ephod” is a transliteration of the Hebrew word \i ’efod\i* and is perhaps the most difficult piece of the priestly clothing to translate. In some languages there will be a word for an item of clothing corresponding in design (if not in purpose) to the ephod. However, in some cases the word may not be usable because it designates something used only by women. In other cases a word for a workman’s apron may be inappropriate because its primary purpose is to protect the clothing. This was not the purpose of the ephod, which was the most elaborate and expensive item in the High Priest’s wardrobe. Almost all English versions transliterate \i ’efod\i*, but \a Mft\a* has simply “apron” and \a AT\a* translates “[sacred] apron.” In other languages it may be possible to say “priestly apron.”
\line In \s H00202800800006\s* and \s H00203900500006\s* \a RSV\a* has the phrase “the skilfully woven band.” This band or belt seems to have been made with the same material as the ephod and attached to its corners so that it could be tied. The use of the singular does not necessarily mean that there was only one belt. The term may have been used in a collective sense. The Hebrew word here simply means “girdle,” “waistband,” or “belt.” The idea of “skilfully woven” is therefore omitted in \a NJB\a* and \a NEB\a* as well as in many non-English versions, and may also be left out of the receptor-language rendering. \a NJB\a* has “The waistband on the \i ephod\i*.”
\line \i Other meanings of ’efod\i*: In a number of the passages listed above, the word \i ’efod\i* describes something other than an item of the High Priest’s clothing. In most (some would say all) cases it still indicates an item of clothing, probably a kind of vest or apron tied around the upper abdomen. See \s H00900201800018 H00902201800080 H01000601400026\s*; and \s H01301502700060\s*, where the Hebrew phrase \i ’efod bad\i* is used; this phrase is literally “linen ephod” or “cloth ephod.” The renderings of \a GNT\a* at \s H00900201801000\s* (“sacred linen apron”) and \s H01000601401000\s* (“linen cloth around his waist”) may serve as models.
\line \s H00700802700012\s*: The exact nature of the “ephod” made by Gideon remains uncertain. Because he collected a large quantity of gold before he made it, many have thought it to be a kind of “idol” (\a GNT\a*, International Children’s Bible, \a Mft\a*). However, even here it is possible that a copy of the priestly apron is intended; gold was a major component of the priestly garment, and some of Gideon’s gold could have been used to pay the skilled workers to make the ephod. \a NCV\a* says “holy vest,” but most versions simply have the transliteration “ephod” (for example, \a RSV\a* and \a NIV\a*). If no explanation is given, however, the average reader will probably associate it with the object of the same name first mentioned in Exodus. It seems best, then, to decide between “idol/image/statue” and “priestly apron”; or, if “ephod” is kept, to include a footnote indicating the possible meanings. The \a TOB\a* note on this verse is a good model: “The \i ephod\i* may designate here either a receptacle for the sacred lots, used for divination, or the statue of a god.”
\line In \s H00701700500020 H00701801400054 H00701801800022 H00701801800022 H00701802000020\s*; and \s H02800300400040\s*, the ephods mentioned may well have been sacred clothing similar in purpose and perhaps in form to the ephod of the High Priest. However, both Micah’s ephod in Judges and the one mentioned in \s H02800300400040\s* were not the High Priest’ ephod. These ephods are associated in their contexts with illicit worship.
\key 4.5.5
\title Sacred pocket, breastpiece
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֹשֶׁן
\trl choshen
\ref H00202500700024 H00202800400014 H00202801500006 H00202802200010 H00202802300010 H00202802300038 H00202802400030 H00202802600026 H00202802800010 H00202802800054 H00202802900018 H00202803000008 H00202900500050 H00203500900026 H00203502700040 H00203900800010 H00203900900014 H00203901500010 H00203901600040 H00203901700030 H00203901900024 H00203902100010 H00203902100050 H00300800800012 H00300800800022
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0427_highpriest_breastpiece_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Breastpiece|4.0\fig* The breastpiece was a piece of embroidered cloth worn by the High Priest over the center of his chest. It formed a bridge between the shoulder straps of the ephod and its belt (see the description of its attachment to the ephod at \l target="REALIA:4.5.4">4.5.4 Ephod\l*).
\line The breastpiece was rectangular, twice as long as it was wide, but it was doubled so that it was square. Its dimensions are given as two spans by one span. When it was folded it was a square, one span on each side. (The span is usually considered to have been about half a cubit [compare \s H02604301301000\s*, \s H02604301701000\s*], which equals about 25 centimeters [10 inches].) The fold was at the bottom, and this formed a kind of pocket. In this pocket were kept the Urim and Thummim (see \l target="REALIA:4.9.1">4.9.1 Urim and Thummim\l*).
\line Mounted on the breastpiece in gold settings were four rows of three (or three rows of four) precious stones each. On each of the twelve different stones was engraved a name of one of the tribes of Israel.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It may not be easy to find a single term appropriate to translate the Hebrew word \i choshen\i*. The English word “breastplate” gives the mistaken impression that it was made of metal or other hard substance. \i Die Bibel: Einheitsübersetzung\i* (\a BE\a*) has “lot pouch,” which focuses on the function of the breastpiece in holding the Urim and Thummim. It may also be translated “sacred pouch” (\a Mft\a*), “chest covering” ( \a NCV\a*), or “pocket over the heart.” The Hebrew phrase \i choshen mishpat\i* (“breastpiece of judgment” in \a RSV\a*) in \s H00202801500006\s* is rendered “pouch of judgment” (\a TOT\a*), “judicial pouch” (\a Mft\a*), “breastpiece of decision” (\a NJPSV\a*, \a NAB\a*), and “breastpiece for making decisions” (\a NIV\a*). \a CEV\a* has “breastpiece for the high priest to use in learning what I want my people to do.”
\key 4.5.6
\title Sash, cloth belt
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַבְנֵט
\trl ’avnet
\ref H00202800400034 H00202803900022 H00202804000020 H00202900900008 H00203902900008 H00300800700024 H00300801300026 H00301600400026
\heb חגר
\trl chagar
\ref H00202900900004 H00300800700016 H00300800700052 H00300801300022 H00301600400030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The sash was a long cloth belt that was wrapped several times around the waist of the High Priest over the tunic (see \l target="REALIA:4.5.2">4.5.2 Tunic, shirt\l*). His fellow priests also wore sashes. According to \s H00203902900008\s*, the High Priest’s sash was embroidered of four kinds of thread. According to post-biblical Jewish tradition, it was 32 cubits (about 16 meters or 53 feet) long. Even if the tradition exaggerates the length, it was probably long enough to be wound around the waist several times before being tied. See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:4.5.4">4.5.4 Ephod\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In modern English the word “girdle” (\a RSV\a*) for this belt is misleading. In addition to its purely functional use as a long embroidered sash that was wrapped around the midsection, it also seems to have had a symbolic meaning as a sign of the priesthood. Many English versions use the word “sash,” but in some languages it may be necessary to say “broad band.” In \s H00300800700024\s* it should be carefully distinguished from “the skilfully woven band of the ephod” (\a RSV\a*; \a GNT\a* “its finely woven belt”), mentioned later in this verse (see \l target="REALIA:4.5.4">4.5.4 Ephod\l*).
\line See also the discussion at \l target="REALIA:6.6">6.6 Waistband, sash, belt\l*.
\key 4.5.7
\title Forehead plate, forehead ornament
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb צִיץ
\trl tsits
\ref H00202803600006 H00203903000008 H00300800900034
\grk στέφανος
\trl stefanos
\ref L07104501200002
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0428_highpriest_foreheadplate_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Forehead plate|4.0\fig* The High Priest was commanded to wear a kind of headband on his forehead just below the level of his turban. It was made of two materials. In the front was a thin piece of gold beaten into the form of a narrow band. On this plate were inscribed the words “Consecrated [or, Dedicated/Holy] to the LORD).” Through the ends of this band were threaded blue ribbons or threads. These were tied at the back of the head holding the band against the forehead.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Ten English translations of \s H00202803600006\s* that were consulted had eight different renderings of the Hebrew word \i tsits\i*. Something like \a CEV\a* “narrow strip” or \a GECL\a* “small plate” will probably be best. Another possibility is “gold headband.”
\line \s H00300800900034\s* has the literal expression “the golden flower, the holy crown.” In the first phrase “flower” renders the Hebrew word \i tsits\i*. This word may mean “blossom” or “flower,” as in \s H00401702300050\s* (verse 23 in Hebrew), or “shining thing.” When it is used with the qualifying word “golden,” many English versions understand it in the sense of “plate” (for example, \a RSV\a* and \a NIV\a*). \a FRCL\a*, however, translates “the golden jewel in the form of a flower.” \a NJB\a* has simply “the golden flower.” However, these words in Hebrew are in apposition with the phrase “the holy crown” and are explained by it. “The holy crown” was clearly not a crown in the sense of a sign of royalty. The Hebrew word translated “crown” may also mean “consecration,” and the whole expression probably indicates that the golden plate was a symbol of the High Priest’s dedication to God. It has been suggested that the meaning of the second phrase may be rendered by an expression such as “the sign showing that Aaron was given over to [or, consecrated to] God.” A possible model for translating the whole expression is “the golden object showing that he was dedicated to God.”
\key 4.5.8
\title Turban, headdress
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מִגְבָּעָה
\trl migba‘ah
\ref H00202804000024 H00202900900022 H00203902800020 H00300801300034
\heb מִצְנֶפֶת
\trl mitsnefeth
\ref H00202800400030 H00202803700022 H00202803700032 H00202803900016 H00202900600008 H00202900600030 H00203902800008 H00203903100020 H00300800900010 H00300800900024 H00301600400036
\heb פְּאֵר
\trl p’er
\ref H00203902800016 H02604401800002
\heb צָנִיף
\trl tsanif
\ref H03800300500008 H03800300500022
\grk κίδαρις
\trl kidaris
\ref L06800401500012 L07104501200008
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The turban was a headpiece formed by winding a long piece of cloth many times around the top of the head. It may have been wound permanently and put on and taken off like a hat. See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:6.7">6.7 Headdress, turban, hat\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages there may be a very general word for anything worn on the head. If such a term must be used to describe the High Priest’s headdress, it may be necessary to include a footnote explaining that such a headpiece symbolized the authority of the High Priest.
\line The Hebrew words \i migba‘ah\i* and \i p’er\i* (literally “beauty” or “decoration”) refer to the headgear of the normal priests. In form their headgear was like the headdress worn by the High Priest, although slightly less elaborate. It will usually be possible to use the same word for both.
\line In \s H00203902800020\s* the words \i migba‘ah\i* and \i p’er\i* are combined to describe the caps of the ordinary priests. Since both words are used elsewhere to describe a single piece of headwear, different approaches have been tried here in translation. Most translations have a single word, such as “caps” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*) or “headbands” (\a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*). Others take the word \i p’er\i* to be a modifier of \i migba‘ah\i*, saying “decorated turbans” (\a NJPSV\a*), “decorated caps” (\a NASB\a*), “beautiful turbans” (\a GW\a*), or “fancy caps” (\a CEV\a*). \a REB\a* treats the two words (in reverse order) as two different items, saying “the tall headdresses and their bands.”
\key 4.6
