\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Statue, image\b*:
\arm צְלֵם
\trl tselem
\ref A02700203100000 A02700203100001 A02700203200000 A02700203400001 A02700203500002 A02700300100040 A02700300200170 A02700300300140 A02700300300220 A02700300500160 A02700300700220 A02700301000230 A02700301200230 A02700301400130 A02700301500210 A02700301800010 A02700301900050
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0461_clay_goddess_idols.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Idols|4.0\fig* The idol was an artifact that was made to represent a god as an object of worship. Idols took many forms and were made in many sizes, from smaller than a finger to several meters high. They most frequently were shaped like a human figure, but they often took the form of some animal or bird or even a combination of human and animal.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Though the existence of idols and corresponding terms for them are widespread, idols are by no means universal. Therefore it may be necessary in some languages to employ some type of descriptive equivalent for “idols,” for example, “objects that are made to look like gods” or “carved statues that represent gods.” \fig |UBS-0028_idols.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Men carrying idols|4.0\fig*
\line In some languages it may be necessary to specify the material from which an idol is made. The idols mentioned in the Bible were made from a variety of materials, including stone, clay, metal, and wood.
\line In the Old Testament, idols are often not named as such but rather are called by a wide variety of pejorative terms indicating such things as “iniquity,” “terror,” “grief,” and “horror.” Most translations will render these words as “idol,” even though the word idol is only implied. For example, \s H02405003800006\s* uses the Hebrew word \i ’eymim\i*, which means “terrors,” so the last half of this verse is literally “For it is a land of idols, and they go crazy with the terrors.” Here \a NRSV\a* has “For it is a land of images, and they go mad over idols.” \a GNT\a* says “Babylonia is a land of terrifying idols that have made fools of the people.” Other Hebrew words used to refer to idols in a negative way are the following:
\heb אָוֶן
\trl ’awen (meaning “trouble, wickedness”)
\ref H02306600300036
\heb גִּלּוּל
\trl gilul (“lifeless [rolling] thing, dung”)
\ref H00302603000030 H00502901600014 H01101501200026 H01102102600016 H01201701200008 H01202101100054 H01202102100028 H01202302400034 H02405000200046 H02600600400024 H02600600500018 H02600600600040 H02600600900054 H02600601300022 H02600601300082 H02600801000030 H02601400300016 H02601400400038 H02601400400082 H02601400500026 H02601400600030 H02601400700042 H02601603600036 H02601800600022 H02601801200026 H02601801500022 H02602000700020 H02602000800036 H02602001600034 H02602001800040 H02602002400028 H02602003100030 H02602003900020 H02602003900060 H02602200300034 H02602200400016 H02602300700032 H02602303000024 H02602303700018 H02602303900014 H02602304900014 H02603001300014 H02603302500032 H02603601800030 H02603602500028 H02603702300012 H02604401000034 H02604401200014
\heb הֶבֶל
\trl hevel (“vain thing”)
\ref H00503202100016 H01101601300046 H01101602600048 H01201701500044 H01903100700008 H02400801900046 H02401000800016 H03200200900004
\heb מִפְלֶצֶת
\trl mifletseth (“horrible thing”)
\ref H01101501300024 H01101501300040 H01401501600030 H01401501600040
\heb עָצָב, עצב
\trl ‘atsav (“grief, pain”; noun or verb)
\ref H00903100900036 H01000502100010 H01301000900038 H01402401800032 H01910603600008 H01910603800024 H01911500400002 H01913501500002 H02301001100034 H02304600100012 H02404401900044 H02405000200042 H02800401700004 H02800800400030 H02801300200028 H02801400900014 H03300100700028 H03801300200030
\heb עֹצֶב
\trl ‘otsev (“grief, pain”)
\ref H02304800500024
\heb עֵצָה
\trl ‘etsah (“disobedience, rebellion”)
\ref H02801000600034
\heb שִׁקּוּץ
\trl shiquts (“detested thing”)
\ref H00502901600008 H01101100500022 H01101100700014 H01101100700038 H01202301300046 H01202301300056 H01401500800038 H02400400100022 H02400703000024 H02401302700024 H02401601800028 H02403203400006 H02600501100030 H02600702000020 H02601101800016 H02601102100008 H02602000800024 H02602003000036
\line While it is possible to translate most of these terms simply as “idol,” the negative sense of the Hebrew will be better rendered by adding an appropriate modifier such as “disgusting,” “detestable,” or “filthy.”
\line The exact meaning of the Hebrew word \i chaman\i* (which always appears in the plural, \i chamanim\i*) is uncertain. The form of the word is similar to a Hebrew word for the sun, and so some have understood it to be an idol or sacred pillar to the sun god (\a Mft\a* “sun-pillars”; see \l target="REALIA:4.6.6">4.6.6 Sacred pillar, sacred stone, memorial stone\l*). Most translations prefer “incense altars” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*) or “incense stands” (\a NJPSV\a*).
\line The Greek words \i eikōn\i*, \i tupos\i*, and \i charagma\i* primarily refer to a likeness or a resemblance, so in \s G04002202000000\s* \a CEV\a* renders \i eikōn\i* simply as “picture.” When these words refer to the likeness of a god (for example, in \s G04400704300030\s* and \s G04500102300020\s*), they may be rendered in the same way as the Greek word \i eidōlon\i*, which means “idol.”
\line The technical distinction between a statue or an image and an idol is that a statue may merely represent a supernatural being, while an idol not only represents such a being but is also believed to possess certain inherent supernatural powers. Statues often become idols when they are assumed to possess such powers in and of themselves rather than being mere representations of some supernatural entity. If, for example, various images of a particular supernatural being are believed to have different healing powers, then what began merely as images or representations of a supernatural power have become idols since the different images themselves have acquired special power. In other words, an “image” becomes an “idol” when people relate to it as a god.
\line The following discussion on \s H00302600100008\s* from \i A Handbook on Leviticus\i* (pages 401-402) may prove helpful in distinguishing between different kinds of idols:
\line This verse contains four different words or expressions referring to false gods (or attempts to represent the deity in physical form) that are forbidden to the people of Israel. In some languages it may be difficult to find four different synonymous terms, but an effort should be made to do so if possible:
\line (1) \b Idols\b*: the root of the word thus translated [\i ’elil\i* in Hebrew] really means “worthless; insufficient; inadequate.” \a NAB\a* translates it “false gods,” while \a Mft\a* has “unreal gods.” In some languages it may be best translated “worthless (or, useless) things [used for worship].”
\line (2) \b Graven image\b*: this [\i pesel\i* in Hebrew; see \l target="REALIA:4.6.2">4.6.2 Graven (stone) image\l*] refers to something fashioned into the shape of an object, animal, or a person. It may be made of stone, clay, wood, or metal. According to the context here, the purpose of making such a likeness was to provide an object that could be worshiped. It may be rendered “carved out to look like something,” or “made to resemble something living,” or something similar.
\line (3) \b Pillar\b*: this [\i matsevah\i* in Hebrew; see \l target="REALIA:4.6.6">4.6.6 Sacred pillar, sacred stone, memorial stone\l*] probably refers to a long stone that was made to stand up by itself and served as an object of worship. It is the same term used in \s H00102801800036\s* and \s H00202400400044\s*, when such objects were apparently acceptable in Hebrew worship. \a NEB\a* has “sacred pillars,” and \a JB\a* translates “standing-stone,” but \a NJB\a* changes this to “cultic stones.”
\line (4) \b Figured stone\b*: compare \s H00403305200028\s*. It is uncertain exactly what this [\i ’even maskith\i* in Hebrew] refers to. The root meaning of the word has to do with the verb “to look.” Some commentators therefore take it to refer to some sort of remarkable stone or mosaic at which people look with adoration. However, most English versions take it to refer to a stone that has been carved or shaped by human efforts to look like an object of worship.
\line \s A02700300100000-A02700301801000\s*: According to some commentators, the proportions of the “image” or “statue” mentioned in this passage suggest that it was probably a sort of symbolic column rather than an exact representation of a human or divine figure, and that perhaps some carving on the column pictured the features of a person, whether human or divine. But others feel that it must have had the shape of human features. The church fathers thought it may have been an image of a king who was considered a god, and several modern commentators think it may have been a representation of a Babylonian god; but the information given in verses 12, 14 and 18 does not really make it possible to decide one way or another. If a language has a word for symbolic representation rather than exact likeness, then this word should probably be used in translation here rather than the other one.
\line \s L07800200200052\s*: The Greek word \i agalma\i* literally means “image” or “statue,” which is the rendering in some translations (\a NRSV\a*, \a NJB\a*). Others (\a GNT\a*, \a NAB\a*, \a ITCL\a*) prefer “idol,” which seems to be indicated by the context.
\key 4.6.1
\title Teraphim, household idol
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb תְּרָפִים
\trl trafim
\ref H00103101900026 H00103103400012 H00103103500056 H00701700500024 H00701801400058 H00701801800030 H00701802000028 H00901502300016 H00901901300012 H00901901600016 H01202302400026 H02602102600048 H02800300400044 H03801000200006
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0462_teraphim_with_mold.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|A teraphim with its mold|4.0\fig* A teraphim was a sculpted or molten figure representing a god. Its size could vary considerably, from quite small to almost the size of a man.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Teraphim played a role in acts of divination. The one who possessed them was usually recognized as the head of the household, with all of the rights that went with that position. By showing proper reverence to the household idols, the family expected to be rewarded with prosperity, health, plenty of food, and other necessities of home life.
\line Some cultures will know a similar kind of idol or representation of a local god, and the word for such an idol or representation may be used.
\line The Hebrew word \i trafim\i* is evidently a kind of royal plural, used to speak of multiple idols but also of a single idol.
\line \s H00103101900026\s*: Translations use a variety of terms for the word \i trafim\i* in this verse; for example, “household gods” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*), “family idols” (\a SPCL\a*), and “small idols” (first edition of \a GECL\a*). Some translations choose to use simply the generic term “idols” (\a NCV\a*, \a ITCL\a*, Septuagint), and this is the practice of many translations in most of the references listed above. \a CEV\a* adds the following footnote: “\i household idols\i*: These were thought to protect the household from danger. It is also possible that the person who had them would inherit the family property.”
\line \s H00901502300016\s*: A few translations simply transliterate the word \i trafim\i* here; for example, for the second line of this verse \a NJPSV\a* has “Defiance, like the iniquity of teraphim.” However, most translations understand \i trafim\i* to refer to idol worship in general. \a NIV\a* has “and arrogance like the evil of idolatry,” and \a NCV\a* says “Pride is as bad as the sin of worshiping idols.”
\line \s H00901901300012\s*: Even though there seems to be only one idol involved in the story here, the Hebrew word \i trafim\i* in this verse is still in the plural, as it always is in the Bible. The idol in this instance was big enough that Michal thought it would fool Saul’s men into thinking that it was a grown man. For this reason \a CEV\a* says “statue,” although most translations consulted prefer a word that indicates that it was an object involved in pagan worship. \a ITCL\a* includes both elements with “statue of an idol,” while \a GECL\a* has “carved figure of the household god.”
\key 4.6.2
\title Graven (stone) image
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֶבֶן, מַשְׂכִּית
\trl ’even maskith
\ref H00302600100026 H00403305200028
\heb פָּסִיל
\trl pasil
\ref H00500700500030 H00500702500002 H00501200300032 H00700301900012 H00700302600022 H01201704100024 H01403301900048 H01403302200034 H01403400400046 H01403400700024 H01907805800014 H02301001000020 H02302100900036 H02303002200010 H02304200800030 H02400801900042 H02405003800016 H02405104700016 H02405105200020 H02801100200028 H03300100700006 H03300501200006
\heb פֶּסֶל
\trl pesel
\ref H00202000400008 H00302600100012 H00500401600012 H00500402300030 H00500402500032 H00500500800008 H00502701500012 H00701700300054 H00701700400040 H00701801400062 H00701801700036 H00701801800018 H00701802000036 H00701803000016 H00701803100010 H01202100700008 H01403300700008 H01909700700008 H02304001900004 H02304002000028 H02304201700018 H02304400900004 H02304401000010 H02304401500046 H02304401700014 H02304502000030 H02304800500030 H02401001400020 H02405101700020 H03400101400028 H03500201800006
\grk γλυπτός
\trl gluptos
\ref L07001401700012 L07001501300026 L07700506800030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0463_stone_image.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Stone image|4.0\fig* The graven image was an idol carved out of wood or, sometimes, stone. The sizes and shapes of these images could vary greatly.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line These images were formed by carving or sculpting. For other translation considerations, see \l target="REALIA:4.6.3">4.6.3 Molten image\l*.
\key 4.6.3
\title Molten image
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַסֵּכָה
\trl masekah
\ref H00203200400028 H00203200800022 H00203401700004 H00301900400016 H00403305200038 H00500901200052 H00500901600024 H00502701500016 H00701700300058 H00701700400044 H00701801400066 H00701801700060 H00701801800038 H01101400900038 H01201701600022 H01402800200018 H01403400300082 H01403400400052 H01600901800012 H01910601900016 H02303002200020 H02304201700026 H02801300200018 H03400101400032 H03500201800014
\heb נָסִיךְ
\trl nasik
\ref H02701100800010
\heb נֶסֶךְ
\trl nesek
\ref H02304102900018 H02304800500034 H02401001400026 H02405101700026
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The molten image was an idol made by pouring molten metal into a mold. The sizes and shapes of these images could vary widely. See the illustration at \l target="REALIA:4.6.1">4.6.1 Teraphim, household idol\l* above, where an image is shown with its mold.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew words listed above indicate the act of pouring, and in fact the word \i nesek\i* refers far more often to a drink offering or libation that is poured out (see \l target="REALIA:9.1">9.1 Wine\l*). Some translations try to reflect this with a qualifier such as “molten” or “cast.” In most passages it will be sufficient to use a general term for “idol.”
\line \s H03400101400032\s*: This verse and others refer to two kinds of images. \u Graven images\u* were carved from stone or, more commonly, from wood. \u Molten images\u* were made by melting metal and pouring it into a mold. Few languages today have separate words for these two different kinds of image. \a REB\a* uses two words in English, “image and idol,” but there is no particular need to do this. The use of the two words together in Hebrew is a way of referring to all kinds of images (compare \s H00502701501000\s*; \s H02304800501000\s*; \s H02401001401000\s*; \s H03500201801000\s*), and a general expression for these images is quite adequate (the way they were made had no spiritual significance). \a GNT\a* uses just one English word, saying “idols.” Some translations succeed in expressing the two separate objects in simple language; for example, \a NIV\a* has “carved images and cast idols,” and \a ITCL\a* says “idols [made] of wood and metal.”
\key 4.6.4
\title Asherah
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֲשֵׁרָה
\trl ’asherah
\ref H00203401300022 H00500700500024 H00501200300020 H00501602100008 H00700602500076 H00700602600058 H00700602800034 H00700603000046 H01101401500082 H01101402300020 H01101603300012 H01201300600036 H01201701000012 H01201701600034 H01201800400030 H01202100300040 H01202300600010 H01202301400020 H01202301500082 H01401400200038 H01401700600032 H01401900300018 H01402401800024 H01403100100042 H01403300300040 H01403301900042 H01403400400040 H01403400700018 H02301700800034 H02302700900048 H02401700200012 H03300501300006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0464_asherah_en.jpg|col||© Louvre Museum (Wikimedia Commons)|Bronze model with Asherah pole, from Elam|4.0\fig* The Asherah was a wooden pole used to worship the goddess Asherah.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Asherah was worshiped as the consort (wife) of the head of the gods. She was considered the mother of the gods, a symbol of fertility.
\line In the Old Testament the Hebrew word \i ’asherah\i* sometimes refers to the goddess Asherah and sometimes to the wooden cult-object that was her symbol. In the former category are \s H00700300700048 H01101501300030 H01101801900050 H01202100700012 H01202300400076 H01202300700038 H01401501600024\s*. In \s H01101501300030\s* \a GNT\a* expands “Asherah” to “the fertility goddess Asherah.” When the word \i ’asherah\i* refers to the wooden pole used for worshiping Asherah, it may be expanded to “image/idol of the goddess Asherah.” Another good model of expansion is \a CEV\a* “sacred poles for worshiping the goddess Asherah” in \s H01101401500082\s*. \a CEV\a* also adds the following note: “\i sacred poles\i*: Or “trees,” used as symbols of Asherah, the goddess of fertility.” Scholars now believe that the Asherah was not exactly an image or statue of the goddess but rather a special wooden pole that symbolized her. For this reason \a GNT\a* often says “symbol[s] of the goddess Asherah” (see \s H00203401300022 H00501602100008\s*).
\key 4.6.5
\title Sacred cakes
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כַּוָּן
\trl kawan
\ref H02400701800038 H02404401900040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Sacred cakes were special baked items made of bread dough and offered as part of pagan worship to an idol representing a god or goddess.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The “queen of heaven” for whom the sacred cakes are baked in \s H02400701800038\s* and \s H02404401900040\s* was identified with the planet Venus, and her symbol was an eight-pointed star. Cakes made for her were probably in the shape of her image or of a star. In \s H02404401900040\s* \a CEV\a* uses a good descriptive phrase for “sacred cakes” which can serve as a model: “special loaves of bread shaped like her [the Queen of Heaven].”
\key 4.6.6
\title Sacred pillar, sacred stone, memorial stone
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַצֵּבָה, מַצֶּבֶת
\trl matsevah, matseveth
\ref H00102801800036 H00102802200016 H00103101300016 H00103104500014 H00103105100028 H00103105200018 H00103105200068 H00103501400008 H00103501400022 H00103502000008 H00103502000016 H00202302400038 H00202400400044 H00203401300014 H00302600100016 H00500700500018 H00501200300016 H00501602200010 H01001801800024 H01001801800024 H01101402300016 H01200300200036 H01201002600008 H01201002700008 H01201701000008 H01201800400020 H01202301400010 H01401400200028 H01403100100034 H02301901900030 H02404301300008 H02602601100028 H02800300400034 H02801000100040 H02801000200018 H03300501200010
\grk στήλη
\trl stēlē
\ref L07701402600066 L07900202700028 L07900702000010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0465_pillar_memorial_stone.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Sacred pillars|4.0\fig* The sacred pillar was a column that was usually made of a single stone. It could sometimes be inscribed with some memorial of an event that had happened at the place where the stone stood. Such monuments could be made of a single stone or a pile of stones.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The erection of pillars for special sacred purposes was a common practice in biblical culture. They were set up to commemorate important events, such as a divine manifestation or a military victory, as well as to solemnize a vow or an agreement, or to keep alive the memory of some ancestor or other notable person.
\line The Hebrew words \i matsevah\i* and \i matseveth\i* are used for two distinct things. On the one hand, they can describe legitimate memorial stones set up, as in the case of \s H02301901900030\s*, even to the LORD himself. On the other hand, the same kind of memorial stone could be set up by idol worshipers to honor their gods. In the latter case, they are strongly condemned by the Scriptures, and the Israelites were even told to destroy them (for example, \s H00202302400038 H00500700500018\s*). Some languages will make a distinction between the two, either with different words or with qualifiers. For example, \a GNT\a* translates the Hebrew word \i matsevah\i* in \s H00103501400008\s* as “memorial stone,” while in \s H00202302400038\s* the same word is rendered “sacred stone pillars.” Some translators will want to expand the translation of “memorial stone” with a descriptive phrase, such as “large rock, so that he would remember what had happened there” (\a CEV\a*).
\line Memorial stones (often referred to as witnesses) are found in \s H00102801800036\s*, \s H00102802200016\s*; \s H00103101300016\s*, \s H00103104500014\s*, \s H00103105100028 H00103105200018\s*; \s H00103501400008\s*, \s H00103502000016\s*; \s H00202400400044\s*; \s H01001801800024\s*; \s H02301901900030\s*.
\line Sacred stones are found in \s H00202302400038\s*; \s H00203401300014\s*; \s H00302600100016\s*; \s H00500700500018\s*; \s H00501200300016\s*; \s H00501602200010\s*; \s H01101402300016\s*; \s H01200300200036\s*; \s H01201002600008 H01201002700008\s*; \s H01201701000008\s*; \s H01201800400020\s*; \s H01202301400010\s*; \s H01401400300036\s*; \s H01403100100034\s*; \s H02404301300008\s*; \s H02602601100028\s*; \s H02800300400034\s*; \s H02801000100040 H02801000200018\s*; \s H03300501300010\s*.
\key 4.6.7
\title Shrine model
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk ναός
\trl naos
\ref G04401902400014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0466_shrine.jpg|col||© Oren Rozen (Wikimedia Commons)|Clay shrine model|4.0\fig* The shrine model was a small replica or model of a temple or shrine. It is likely that some people treated them with special veneration, but the models mentioned in Acts were primarily souvenirs.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s G04401902400014\s* the Greek term \i naos\i* is rendered in some languages as “tiny temples” or “souvenir temples.” This will often be a good place to use a descriptive phrase. For the literal phrase “silver temples of Artemis,” \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a* have “silver models of the temple of the goddess Artemis,” \a NCV\a* has “little silver models that looked like the temple of the goddess Artemis,” and \a SPCL\a* says “small silver figures which represented the temple . . . .”
\key 4.7
\title Cult place, high place
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בָּמָה
\trl bamah
\ref H00302603000008 H00403305200048 H00900901200056 H00900901300024 H00900901400040 H00900901900030 H00900902500010 H00901000500050 H00901001300016 H01100300200014 H01100300300030 H01100300400024 H01101100700008 H01101203100010 H01101203200092 H01101300200060 H01101303200044 H01101303300044 H01101303300062 H01101402300012 H01101501400006 H01102204400006 H01102204400028 H01201200400006 H01201200400028 H01201400400006 H01201400400028 H01201500400006 H01201500400028 H01201503500006 H01201503500028 H01201600400014 H01201700900030 H01201701100012 H01201702900024 H01201703200024 H01201703200040 H01201800400010 H01201802200032 H01202100300014 H01202300500028 H01202300800028 H01202300800056 H01202300900012 H01202301300008 H01202301500020 H01202301500058 H01202301500070 H01202301900014 H01202302000014 H01301603900032 H01302102900042 H01400100300022 H01400101300012 H01401101500014 H01401400200018 H01401400400018 H01401501700006 H01401700600024 H01402003300006 H01402101100008 H01402800400014 H01402802500020 H01403100100052 H01403201200014 H01403300300014 H01403301700016 H01403301900034 H01403400300064 H01907805800008 H02301601200020 H02303600700032 H02400703100006 H02401900500008 H02403203500008 H02404803500016 H02600600300076 H02600600600018 H02601601600016 H02602002900012 H02801000800006 H03000700900006
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i bamah\i* has been defined as “a raised elevation, platform, or mound often alongside or near a sanctuary and set up primarily for the purpose of sacrifices.” One of the forms that it could have was a round platform varying in height and diameter. Some were provided with steps at the side so that the worshiper or priest could go up onto the platform. Each high place had at least one altar, which was situated either on the platform or beside it. Both the platforms and altars were made of stone.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The name “high place” is a somewhat misleading translation of \i bamah\i*. While the Hebrew word can include the element of elevation, this is not its primary focus. More important is that it was a site where religious rites and sacrifices—primarily pagan—took place. In most passages where this word occurs, it is best to make explicit that these sites were “places of worship” (so \a GNT\a*) and that they were generally associated with pagan cults. Some translations have rendered \i bamah\i* as “sanctuary” (\a SPCL\a* in \s H01101100700008\s*) or “place of sacrifice” (\a GECL\a* in \s H01101100700008\s*). If the context does not make it clear that the text is speaking of pagan sacrifice, then it will be necessary to expand the translation to clarify this. Thus \a SPCL\a* usually adds the word “pagan” or even expands to “high places of pagan cultic worship” (\s H01100300200014\s*). Something like this is recommended.
\line If there is a word in the receptor language for a “shrine” or a place where offerings are placed for fetishes, this may be appropriate. Where such a word is lacking, translators can always say “places where various gods are worshiped.”
\line In a few passages the word \i bamah\i* indicates an Israelite place of worship. See, for example, \s H00900901200056 H00900901300024 H00900901400040 H00900901900030 H00900902500010 H00901000500050 H00901001300016 H01100300200014 H01100300300030 H01100300400024\s*. It is significant that these examples come before the dedication of the Temple by Solomon. The later writings of the Old Testament condemn not only pagan worship at the “high places,” but also Israelite worship at any place except the Temple at Jerusalem. In these later books, in fact, “high place” seems to indicate any sanctuary not recognized by the official authorities. Because of this tendency, it is not recommended that one standard translation, such as “pagan places of worship,” be adopted except where the context clearly indicates that this is the case. A translation such as “country temple” for an unauthorized worship place should be avoided, lest readers think that there were temples in the rural areas similar to the Temple in Jerusalem. “Country shrine” may be a good neutral expression, but perhaps the best translation, at least in those passages where unauthorized worship is condemned, is “illegitimate places of worship” or “places where people were not supposed to offer sacrifices.” Translators will normally be able to employ the same word or phrase whether the text is speaking of Israelite or pagan worship.
\key 4.8
\title Burial and mourning
\index \l target="REALIA:4.8.1">4.8.1 Tomb, grave\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.8.2">4.8.2 Burial mound\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.8.3">4.8.3 Body preparation\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.8.4">4.8.4 Bier, coffin\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:4.8.5">4.8.5 Sackcloth, mourning clothes\l*
\key 4.8.1
\title Tomb, grave
\index \l target="REALIA:4.8.1.1">4.8.1.1 Stone for closing a tomb\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בַּיִת
\trl bayith
\ref H02301401800020
\heb גָּדִישׁ
\trl gadish
\ref H01802103200016
\heb צְרִיחַ
\trl tsriach
\ref H00901300600060
\heb קְבוּרָה
\trl qvurah
\ref H00103502000012 H00103502000018 H00104703000024 H00503400600034 H00901000200024 H01200902800020 H01202102600010 H01202303000026 H01402602300028 H02100600300048 H02301402000010 H02402201900002 H02603202300022 H02603202400014
\heb קֶבֶר
\trl qever
\ref H00102300400018 H00102300600020 H00102300600034 H00102300900046 H00102302000028 H00104903000058 H00105000500018 H00105001300046 H00201401100018 H00401901600042 H00401901800092 H00700803200024 H00701603100044 H01000203200016 H01000303200032 H01000401200062 H01001702300064 H01001903800018 H01002101400030 H01101302200052 H01101303000012 H01101303100038 H01101401300034 H01201302100036 H01202202000018 H01202300600062 H01202301600016 H01202301600046 H01202301700036 H01401601400008 H01402102000054 H01402402500074 H01402802700034 H01403203300020 H01403400400070 H01403402800016 H01403502400046 H01600200300038 H01600200500046 H01600301600024 H01800302200016 H01800502600010 H01801001900020 H01801700100010 H01802103200008 H01900501000016 H01908800600016 H01908801200010 H02301401900010 H02302201600024 H02302201600030 H02305300900010 H02306500400010 H02400501600006 H02400800100068 H02402001700020 H02402602300046 H02603202200014 H02603202300006 H02603202500022 H02603202600016 H02603701200028 H02603701200038 H02603701300018 H02603701300030 H02603901100026 H03400101400036
\grk μνῆμα
\trl mnēma
\ref G04100500500018 G04200802700058 G04202305300020 G04202400100020 G04400202900040 G04400701600018 G06601100900054
\grk μνημεῖον
\trl mnēmeion
\ref H00102300601160 H00102300601260 H00102300901280 H00103502001070 H00103502001120 H00104903001240 H00105000501090 H00105001301250 H02302201601130 H02302201601190 H02302601901090 H02603901101120 G04000802800180 G04002302900160 G04002705200030 G04002705300050 G04002706000080 G04002706000210 G04002800800060 G04100500200120 G04100602900160 G04101504600130 G04101504600260 G04101600200110 G04101600300140 G04101600500050 G04101600800060 G04201104400070 G04201104700060 G04202305500140 G04202400200080 G04202400900050 G04202401200080 G04202402200130 G04202402400090 G04300502800130 G04301101700130 G04301103100290 G04301103800100 G04301201700150 G04301904100130 G04301904200120 G04302000100160 G04302000100240 G04302000200250 G04302000300130 G04302000400190 G04302000600120 G04302000800130 G04302001100060 G04302001100150 G04401302900150 L07001000700032
\grk τάφος
\trl tafos
\ref G04002302700018 G04002302900020 G04002706100028 G04002706400010 G04002706600012 G04002800100038 G04500301300002 L06700400400040 L06700401700014 L06700601500104 L06700801000014 L06700801800014 L07001900300020 L07103001800020 L07700207000028 L07700901900030 L07701302700012 L07701303000006 L07800501000028 L07801203900058 L07900603100056 L08100102900044
\lat monumentum
\ref V08200201600018
\lat sepulchrum
\ref V08200202300012 V08200503500044
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0467_burial.jpg|col||© Carole Raddato from FRANKFURT, Germany|Burial niches inside a tomb|4.0\fig* The tomb was a construction for the burial of the dead. Since much of the land of Israel, especially in the hilly regions, has little topsoil, tombs were often hewn out of bedrock. In some cases natural caves were used for burial. The entrance to a tomb was closed with a stone (see \l target="REALIA:4.8.1.1">4.8.1.1 Stone for closing a tomb\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Death is a universal experience, and all languages and cultures have words to express the disposal of a dead body. In a number of languages it is important to distinguish clearly between a grave (a hole in the ground in which a corpse is placed) and a tomb (a construction built above the surface of the ground for housing one or more corpses). In some contexts, however, it may be better to use a more generic expression, for example, “places where people are buried” or “places where corpses are placed.”
\line In some passages the word “grave” is used as a symbol for death. Translators should consider whether the physical burial place is in focus or rather the fact that a person has died. In the latter case, it may be better to use a term indicating “death.” This will be true especially in poetic passages. For example, \s H01800302200016\s* is literally “who rejoicing unto joy are glad when they find a grave,” but \a GNT\a* has “They are not happy till they are dead and buried.” \s H01800502600010\s* is literally “You will come to the grave at an old age,” but \a GNT\a* says “you will live to a ripe old age.”
\line Certain verses speak of “graves” in the plural. Here it will often be appropriate to use a word like “graveyard” (\a GNT\a* in \s H01802103200016\s*) or “cemetery.”
\line In the upper levels of Israelite society burial was often done in two stages. In the first stage the body was either laid on a kind of shelf inside a burial chamber or it was placed in a large box called a sarcophagus (“flesh eater”) in English. After about a year, when the flesh had rotted, the bones were moved to a designated place in the chamber. By New Testament times the bones were being placed into an ossuary (“bone box”). These practices gave rise to two expressions in the Hebrew language: “he lay down with his fathers” and “he was gathered to his fathers.” In \s H01401601400008\s*, the place where the body was laid out (\i mishkav\i* in Hebrew) is referred to in the burial of King Asa of Judah. Some translations render the word as “bier” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*; see \l target="REALIA:4.8.4">4.8.4 Bier, coffin\l*), but the structure of the verse indicates that Asa’s body was taken into the tomb and laid in its permanent place, that is, on a shelf in the tomb. The rendering of \a NJPSV\a* gives the sense better with “resting-place.”
\line \s H00901300600060\s*: The meaning of the Hebrew word \i tsrichim\i* in this verse is uncertain. Some versions understand it to mean “tombs” (\a RSV\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a GECL\a*, \a ITCL\a*). These would be cave-like structures hewn out of the rock. Others use a more generic term, such as “pits” (\a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*) or “vaults” (\a NJB\a*). Some have thought this word is related to a Hebrew word meaning “stronghold” or “tower” in \s H00700904600020\s*, \s H00700904900034\s*, but this meaning does not seem to fit the context here.
\line In \s G04002302900160\s* the Greek word \i mnēmeion\i* may also be understood as referring to monuments built as memorials to people who have died. Here it may be translated “monuments to the dead.” This is also its meaning in \s G04201104700060\s*. The Latin word \i monumentum\i* in \s V08200201600018\s* may be understood in the same way.
\line In \s G04100500200120\s* it is important to avoid a term that would designate merely graves, for the demoniac who met Jesus was not living down in graves in the ground, but had found some habitation either in burial caves or in tombs constructed above ground.
\key 4.8.1.1
\title Stone for closing a tomb
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk λίθος
\trl lithos
\ref G04002706000032 G04002706600018 G04002800200032 G04101504600042 G04101600300018 G04101600400014 G04202400200008 G04301103900012 G04301104100008 G04302000100040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0468_stone_closure.jpg|col||© Ian Scott (Wikimedia Commons)|Round stone by a tomb entrance|4.0\fig* A large, heavy stone was used to close the entrance to a cave or tomb cut out of the rock.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Two different methods were used to close tombs with stones, and it is unclear from the Gospels which method is described in the accounts of Jesus’ burial. In one method the stone was cylindrical. It sat on its side in a channel the same width as the stone, and it was pushed sideways until it covered the mouth of the tomb. By the second method the entrance to the tomb was reached by going down a short incline. The stone was spherical and was rolled down the incline until it plugged the tomb entrance.
\line \s G04301103900012 G04301103900012 G04301104100008\s*: The place where Lazarus was buried is described as a cave with a stone placed at the entrance. In \s G04301103800030\s* the Greek phrase that \a GNT\a* renders “at the entrance” is ambiguous. It may mean “on it,” in which case the shaft of the burial tomb was vertical. Or it may mean “against it,” in which case the shaft was horizontal. Commentators are divided in their opinions, but the weight of evidence seems to favor a horizontal cave. In either case, the purpose of the stone was primarily to keep animals from entering the tomb and devouring the body. “A stone placed at the entrance” (\a GNT\a*) may often be best translated “a stone covering the opening to the cave” or “a large stone covering the hole of the cave.” Note that the text does not state here, as in the case of Jesus’ burial, that the stone was “rolled” in front of the entrance.
\key 4.8.2
\title Burial mound
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk χειμών
\trl cheimōn
\ref L07102100800030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0469_burial_mound.jpg|col||© ניסים טבקה Pikiwiki Israel (Wikimedia Commons)|Marker stones|4.0\fig* The burial mound was a pile of stones placed over the place of burial. Its purpose was to mark the burial site and to prevent animals from digging up the body.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Since the “burial mound” was just another kind of tomb, \a GNT\a* has simply “tomb” in \s L07102100800030\s*. There is a textual variation in this verse. Some manuscripts have “for the winter” instead of “for his burial mound” (\a RSV\a*). Most translations use a word for “tomb” and add a footnote giving the alternate reading (so \a GNT\a*).
\key 4.8.3
\title Body preparation
\index \l target="REALIA:4.8.3.1">4.8.3.1 Embalming oils\l*
\cont Burial cloth, shroud, grave clothes: See \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen\l*.
\key 4.8.3.1
\title Embalming oils
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ἀλόη
\trl aloē
\ref G04301903900032
\grk ἄρωμα
\trl arōma
\ref G04101600100032 G04202305600008 G04202400100030 G04301904000026
\grk μύρον
\trl muron
\ref G04202305600012
\grk σμύρνα
\trl smurna
\ref G04301903900028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Embalming oils were aromatic oils or salves used especially in preparing a dead body for burial in a way that it would be preserved. See also \l target="REALIA:10.6.1.1">10.6.1.1 Myrrh\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s H01401601401000\s* we find the Hebrew expression \i bsamim uznim mruqachim\i* in the context of the burial of King Asa of Judah. The text says that spices and aromatic oils were placed in the tomb (\a CEV\a* “the tomb was filled with spices and sweet-smelling oils”). There is no reason to assume that Asa’s body was embalmed (like Jacob’s body in \s H00105000201000 H00105000301000\s*), although \a GNT\a* comes close with “They used spices and perfumed oils to prepare his body for burial.”
\line In \s G04202305600008\s* translators may use a descriptive phrase to render the Greek word \i muron\i*, for example, “perfumed oil for preserving the body” or “. . . to keep the body from rotting.”
\line Ingredients mentioned in the New Testament for embalming oils are “myrrh” (\i smurna\i* in Greek) and “aloes” (\i aloē\i* in Greek). Most translators borrow terms for these ingredients and then use some kind of marginal note to explain the nature of their substance.
\key 4.8.4
\title Bier, coffin
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֲרוֹן
\trl ’aron
\ref H00105002600032
\heb מִטָּה
\trl mitah
\ref H01000303100060
\grk σορός
\trl soros
\ref G04200701400010
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0470_coffin.jpg|col||© Deror Avi (Wikimedia Commons)|Stone coffins|4.0\fig* The bier was a board on which a body was carried to its place of burial, and the coffin was a box in which a body was placed for burial.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s H00105002600032\s* the Hebrew word \i ’aron\i* is literally “box,” but it means “coffin” in this context.
\line In \s H01000303100060\s* the Hebrew word \i mitah\i* is literally “bed.” The context, however, makes it clear that the object is serving as a bier or, less likely, a coffin.
\line \s G04200701400010\s*: In this verse some translations render the Greek word \i soros\i* as “coffin” (\a GNT\a*, \a NCV\a*). This word can also refer to a “bier,” and that is its more probable meaning here. In some languages it may be necessary to use a descriptive expression, for example, “board on which the body was being carried” or “box in which the body lay.”
\key 4.8.5
\title Sackcloth, mourning clothes
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בֶּגֶד, אֵבֶל
\trl bigdey ’evel
\ref H01001400200038
\heb שַׂק
\trl saq
\ref H00103703400014 H01000303100034 H01002101000016 H01102003100036 H01102003200006 H01102102700032 H01102102700050 H01200603000056 H01201900100032 H01201900200042 H01302101600072 H01600900100038 H01700400100030 H01700400200038 H01700400300052 H01700400400054 H01801601500002 H01903001200014 H01903501300012 H01906901200008 H02300302400040 H02301500300008 H02302000200038 H02302201200044 H02303700100032 H02303700200044 H02305000300010 H02305800500036 H02400400800008 H02400602600008 H02404803700032 H02404900300020 H02500201000028 H02600701800006 H02602703100014 H02700900300034 H02900100800010 H02900101300026 H03000801000032 H03200300500024 H03200300600038 H03200300800006
\grk σάκκος
\trl sakkos
\ref G04001102100046 G04201001300046 G06600601200038 G06601100300028 L06800401000046 L06800401100054 L06800401200008 L06800401400036 L06800800500034 L06800900100034 L06801000300008 L06900400100026 L06900400200038 L06900400300034 L06900400400054 L07200402000016 L07700201400026 L07700304700016 L07800301900016 L07801002500038
\lat saccus
\ref V08201600200006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Sackcloth was a coarse dark material made of goat or camel hair. It was worn next to the skin as a sign of mourning or repentance (\s H01200603000056\s*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Customs associated with mourning vary greatly in different cultures, and in some the clothing or lack of clothing is not relevant. In most languages “sackcloth” is described as “coarse cloth” and sometimes as “heavy cloth.” It will often be best to clarify the relation between these clothes and mourning; for example, “clothes that show someone is mourning for the dead.”
\line In some languages there may exist an equivalent symbol of mourning, such as body painting, smearing ashes over the face or chest, carrying objects such as bags symbolizing a needy widow’s mourning, or wearing a cord of mourning around the neck. There are dangers as well as advantages in such a cultural translation. Particular aspects of the Israelite culture are lost, and there may be undesirable meanings associated with the local practice. Whenever this is done, all of its ramifications should be checked carefully. Generally it will be preferable to use the Israelite custom, with a footnote explaining its meaning or providing the equivalent custom. A footnote might read “Mourning clothes were coarse pieces of cloth sewed together from woven goat or camel hair.”
\line \s H01001400200038\s* does not specifically mention sackcloth but speaks of “mourning clothes.” It was the Jewish custom to tear the outer garment as a sign of despair or sadness. However, this verse indicates something more than just tearing the clothing. For the literal clause “put on mourning clothes,” \a CEV\a* and \a NCV\a* have “Put on funeral clothes.” Where no special custom is known, or where a known one would be inappropriate for the context of this story, it may be possible to expand this clause to “Go and put on special clothes that will make David think you are sad because someone has died.”
\line \s H01801601500002\s*: The first half of this verse is literally “I have sewed sackcloth upon my skin” (so \a RSV\a*). This may suggest that Job will wear the sackcloth permanently, or that he wears it next to his skin. \a GNT\a* “I mourn and wear clothes made of sackcloth” avoids expressing either suggestion. \a GECL\a*, however, translates “The mourning clothes are my second skin,” which implies that Job will wear them all the time. This line may be rendered “I have put mourning clothes on my body,” “I have dressed myself in the clothes of those who mourn for the dead,” or “I wear the rough cloth of those who are in mourning.”
\line In some passages the wearing of sackcloth is not an act of mourning because of death but rather an expression of sorrow and penitence. See, for example, \s H02305800500036 H02700900300034 H03200300600038\s*.
\line \s G04001102100046\s*: The last part of this verse is literally “they would have repented long ago in sackcloth and ashes” (so \a RSV\a*; see also \s G04201001300046\s*). Instead of retaining the reference to putting on “sackcloth and ashes,” some translations have said simply “long ago they would have shown to everyone that they were turning from their sins.” However, translators should try to retain these cultural actions in the text, since they were a common aspect of biblical culture.
\key 4.9
\title Lots
\index \l target="REALIA:4.9.1">4.9.1 Urim and Thummim\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גּוֹרָל
\trl goral
\ref H00301600800016 H00301600800018 H00301600800028 H00301600900022 H00301601000016 H00402605500006 H00402605600008 H00403305400014 H00403305400058 H00403401300032 H00403600200030 H00403600300058 H00601400200004 H00601500100008 H00601600100008 H00601700100008 H00601701400026 H00601701700048 H00601800600032 H00601800800072 H00601801000010 H00601801100006 H00601801100024 H00601900100008 H00601901000008 H00601901700010 H00601902400008 H00601903200012 H00601904000018 H00601905100044 H00602100400008 H00602100400066 H00602100500044 H00602100600054 H00602100800050 H00602101000034 H00602102000032 H00602104000034 H00700100300020 H00700100300044 H00702000900026 H01300603900038 H01300604600036 H01300604800038 H01300605000010 H01302400500008 H01302400700008 H01302403100010 H01302500800006 H01302500900008 H01302601300006 H01302601400008 H01302601400030 H01302601400036 H01601003500006 H01601100100026 H01700300700042 H01700902400044 H01901600500016 H01902201900016 H01912500300016 H02000101400002 H02001603300014 H02001801800008 H02301701400030 H02303401700010 H02305700600014 H02401302500004 H02602400600054 H02701201300024 H02900400300010 H03100101100040 H03200100700018 H03200100700046 H03200100700054 H03300200500016 H03400301000042
\grk κλῆρος
\trl klēros
\ref G04002703500018 G04101502400020 G04202303400038 G04301902400062 G04400102600006 G04400102600016 G04400802100012 L06900300700024 L06900300700062 L07101401500026 L07102501900014 L07103700800044
\grk λαγχάνω
\trl lagchanō (verb)
\ref G04200100900012 G04301902400018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0471_pottery_shard_lots.jpg|col||© Eliot from The Negev (Wikimedia Commons)|Pottery shard lots|4.0\fig* Lots were specially marked pebbles, pieces of pottery or sticks used in making decisions. It is not possible to know the particular method used in “choosing by lot,” for evidently various devices were used. See also \l target="REALIA:4.9.1">4.9.1 Urim and Thummim\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Drawing lots (literally “throwing lots” in Hebrew) was viewed by the people of Israel as a way of discerning God’s will, since it was believed that God directed the outcome (see \s H02001603300014\s*). In some cultures the closest natural equivalents of deciding by lot are procedures involving “drawing straws,” “throwing down sticks,” and “dropping pebbles.”
\line \s G04301902400062\s*: “Throw dice” (\a GNT\a*, \a JB\a*, \a NAB\a*) translates the Greek verb \i lagchanō\i*, which means to get something either by casting or drawing lots (so \a RSV\a*, \a Mft\a*, \a AT\a*, \a Phps\a*). However, for contemporary readers the idea of throwing dice or tossing a coin may be the nearest cultural equivalent; for example, for the third clause in this verse \a NEB\a* has “let us toss for it.” In some languages a generic expression may be employed, for example, “let us gamble for it.” However, in some parts of the world where there is no cultural equivalent of gambling, a parallel type of behavior can be described, for example, “let us play a game to see who wins and therefore gets the robe.”
\line In \s G04400102600006\s* \a RSV\a* “they cast lots for them” is literally “they gave them lots” in Greek. In this context it is probable that small sticks were handed out.
\key 4.9.1
\title Urim and Thummim
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Urim\b*:
\heb אוּרִים
\trl ’urim
\ref H00202803000018 H00300800800028 H00402702100028 H00503300800014 H00902800600034 H01500206300034 H01600706500036
\grk δῆλος, δήλωσις
\trl dēlos, dēlōsis
\ref L07103300300024 L07104501000024 L08000200700034 L08100504000034
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Thummim\b*:
\heb תָּמִים
\trl tamim
\ref H00901404100018
\heb תֻּמִּים
\trl tumim
\ref H00202803000018 H00300800800028 H00503300800014 H01500206300034 H01600706500036
\grk ἀλήθεια
\trl alētheia
\ref L07104501000026 L08100504000040
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The actual appearance of the Urim and Thummim is not known. Many suggestions have been made, including small black and white stones, or lots in some other form.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line These two objects were somehow used by the High Priest to find out the will of God (see, for example, \s H00402702100028\s*; \s H00901404100018\s*; \s H00902800600034\s*). One suggestion is that the breastpiece (see \l target="REALIA:4.5.5">4.5.5 Sacred pocket, breastpiece\l*) served as a kind of pocket into which the Urim and Thummim were placed. Questions were asked of God requiring a yes or no answer, and whichever of the objects was drawn from the pouch indicated the answer.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Ancient translations (like the Septuagint) tended to translate the Hebrew words \i ’urim\i* and \i tumim \i*according to their literal meaning, saying “lights and perfections,” or they rendered them nonfiguratively, saying “perfect revelation” or “complete illumination.” In most modern versions the two words are simply transliterated, but some (\a Mft\a*, \a GECL\a*) render the meaning quite adequately with “the sacred lots.” Other languages may have to say “the lots of God.” However these terms are rendered, it is advisable to include a footnote explaining their meaning in greater detail. \a GNT\a* has the following footnote at \s H00202803001000\s*: “urim and thummim: \i Two objects used by the priest to determine God’s will; it is not known precisely how they were used.\i*” The \a CEV\a* footnote on this verse reads “\i two small objects\i*: The Hebrew text has ‘urim and thummim,’ which may have been made of wood, stone, or metal, and were used in some way to receive answers from God.”
\line In \s H00901404100018\s* the Hebrew text uses the word \i tamim\i*, which has the same letters as \i tumim\i* but with different vowels. It does not have the word \i ’urim\i*. The Septuagint has a longer text here, including words corresponding to both \i ’urim\i* and \i tumim\i*. For a discussion of the textual problem here and different translation solutions, see \i A Handbook on The First and Second Books of Samuel\i*, pages 300-301. on of the textual problem here and different translation solutions, see \i A Handbook on The First and Second Books of Samuel\i*, pages 300-301.
\c 5
