\key 5.1
\title Oil lamp and wick
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מָאוֹר
\trl ma’or
\ref H00202500600008 H00202702000032 H00203500800010 H00203501400010 H00203501400032 H00203502800020 H00203903700038 H00302400200028 H00400400900020 H00400401600020
\heb נִיר
\trl nir
\ref H01101103600018 H01101500400016 H01200801900038 H01402100700048 H02002100400012
\heb נֵר
\trl ner
\ref H00202503700008 H00202503700018 H00202702000038 H00203000700034 H00203000800014 H00203501400022 H00203702300008 H00203903700014 H00203903700016 H00204000400036 H00204002500008 H00302400200034 H00302400400018 H00400400900026 H00400800200022 H00400800200040 H00400800300022 H00900300300004 H01002101700064 H01002202900006 H01100704900046 H01302801500016 H01302801500032 H01302801500054 H01400402000012 H01400402100012 H01401301100070 H01402900700020 H01801800600012 H01802101700006 H01802900300006 H01901802900008 H01911910500002 H01913201700014 H02000602300004 H02001300900010 H02002002000012 H02002002700002 H02002402000016 H02003101800026 H02402501000036 H03600101200026 H03800400200046 H03800400200062
\grk λύχνος
\trl luchnos
\ref G04000501500006 G04000602200004 G04100402100014 G04200801600006 G04201103400004 G04201103600038 G04201203500016 G04201500800026 G04300503500008 G06100101900024 G06601802300006 G06602102300048 G06602200500022 L07102601700002 L07300101800002 L07700405000018 L07800100800046 L07801000300048
\lat lucerna
\ref V08201204200028 V08201402500020
\lat lumen
\ref V08201000200008
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Wick\b*:
\heb פִּשְׁתָּה
\trl pishtah
\ref H02304200300012 H02304301700032
\grk λίνον
\trl linon
\ref G04001202000012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0149_oil_lamps.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Oil lamps|5.0\fig* The oil lamp produced light by burning a wick saturated with oil contained in a relatively small vessel. The vessel was oblong, usually made of clay. While lamps could vary in size, an average home oil lamp measured about 13 by 8 by 4 centimeters (5 by 3 by 1.5 inches). It could take several forms. One form was simply a shallow dish filled with oil with a wick floating in it. Another kind of lamp was about the same size but closed, making it easier to carry without spilling the oil. In its top were two holes, a smaller one into which the wick was inserted, and a larger one for refilling the oil. The wick was usually made of linen.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0472_lamp.jpg|col||© Davidbena (Wikimedia Commons)|Oil lamp|5.0\fig* The body of the lamp was filled with oil, into which the wick was placed. The wick was lit and periodically had to be trimmed as it burned down. The lamp lit a small area. It gave off more or less light and smoke, depending on the quality of the oil used and the condition of the wick. Olive oil was the most common fuel, although in the very earliest times fish oil was also used. (see also \l target="REALIA:1.10.5">1.10.5 Anointing oil\l*, \l target="REALIA:1.15.1">1.15.1 Oil, ointment\l*, and \l target="REALIA:9.3">9.3 Olive oil\l* for further uses of olive oil.)
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages the closest equivalent for “oil lamp” is “kerosene lamp.” Translators should avoid an expression that suggests a flashlight or any sort of electric light, which would be highly anachronistic. It is possible to say “lantern” or “light.” Another good cultural equivalent could be the candle, which works on the same principle as the oil lamp, only with solid fuel rather than oil. Candles were known in the ancient world, although they are not mentioned in the Bible.
\line As an object whose purpose is to give light, the lamp is sometimes used figuratively in Scripture. All the occurrences of the Hebrew word \i nir\i* and the Greek word \i lucerna\i* are figurative. The Hebrew word \i ner\i* is used figuratively of Israel’s king (\s H01002101700064\s*), God or some something about him, such as his protection, guidance, blessing or word (\s H01002202900006\s*; \s H01802101700006\s*; \s H01901802900008\s*; \s H01911910500002\s*; \s H02000602300004\s*), life or death as the extinguishing of life (\s H01801800600012\s*; \s H01802101700006\s*; \s H01913201700014\s*; \s H02001300900010\s*; \s H02002002000012\s*; \s H02002402000016\s*), the spirit of man (\s H02002002700002\s*), peace or normalcy (\s H02402501000036\s*), and thoroughness (\s H03600101200026\s*). The Greek word \i luchnos\i* is figurative of a person’s enlightenment (\s G04000602200004\s*; \s G04201103400004\s*, \s G04201103600038\s*), preparedness (\s G04201203500016\s*), prophetic voice (\s G04300503500008\s*), and a person’s face (\s L07102601700002\s*).
\line “Lamp” is often used metaphorically for a person’s life; for example, at \s H01802101700006\s* (\a RSV\a* “How often is it that the lamp of the wicked is put out?”) \i A Handbook on The Book of Job\i* (page 398) points out that this line speaks of premature or unexpected death.
\line In several places the light-giving element of the lamp becomes a metaphor for God’s direction, usually supplied by his word, as a person walks through life. An example is \s H01911910500000\s*, which \a NIV\a* renders “Your word is a lamp to my feet and a light for my path.”
\line While translators will usually agree that a particular passage is figurative, they may not always agree concerning the exact nature of the figure; for example, \a GNT\a* and \a GECL\a* do not agree about the meaning of the lamp imagery in \s H01802900300006\s*. This line is literally “when his lamp shone upon my head” (\a RSV\a*). \a GNT\a* says “God was always with me then,” while \a GECL\a* has “He gave me success every day.”
\line For \s H02402501000036\s* see the comments at \l target="REALIA:5.10">5.10 Millstones, mill\l*.
\line When translating the Hebrew word \i pishtah\i* in \s H02304200300012\s*, more formal translations use the literal rendering “wick”; for example, for the whole line \a RSV\a* has “and a dimly burning wick he will not quench.” Common-language translations usually avoid such a word-for-word rendering that will not be commonly understood. Several good examples are \a GNT\a* “He will not . . . put out a flickering lamp,” \a CEV\a* “He won’t . . . put out a dying flame,” and \a NCV\a* “He will not . . . put out even a weak flame.” Where a translator prefers to retain the image of the wick, it may be rendered “small strip of cloth.”
\key 5.2
\title Lampstand
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מְנוֹרָה
\trl mnorah
\ref H01200401000032 H03800400200028 H03800401100030
\arm נֶבְרְשָׁה
\trl nevrshah
\ref A02700500500026
\grk λυχνία
\trl luchnia
\ref G04000501500026 G04100402100042 G04200801600028 G04201103300028 G06600101300010 G06600102000030 G06600102000056 G06600200100050 G06600200500040 G06601100400018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0029_lampstand.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Lampstands|5.0\fig* The lampstand was a stand designed to hold a single lamp or a series of lamps. It could be made of a variety of materials and took various shapes and sizes. Its purpose was to raise the light higher than the level of the floor or table and so light a larger area. For the lampstand in the Tabernacle, see \l target="REALIA:4.3.4">4.3.4 Lampstand, menorah\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0150_oil_lamps.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Lamps on lampstands|5.0\fig* Since there is no special word for “lampstand” in many cultures, this may have to be translated “lamp holder,” “thing on which lamps are placed,” or “place for putting lamps.” Where the translator has chosen to render the oil lamp as “candle,” the appropriate word for a candleholder could be used.
\line \s A02700500501000\s*: The writing on the wall is said to have been “opposite the lampstand” (\a RSV\a*). This would be in the most clearly illuminated part of the banquet hall. This should probably be stated clearly in most languages. \a GNT\a* has “where the light from the lamps was shining most brightly.” Also possible is “where the light was strongest” or “where people could see very clearly.”
\key 5.3
\title Lantern
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk φανός
\trl fanos
\ref G04301800300038
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0473_lantern.jpg|col||© Jiří Sedláček (Wikimedia Commons)|Lantern|5.0\fig* The lantern was a small fire that was carried around for the sake of its light and that had some type of protection from the wind and weather. The lantern itself was cylindrical in shape with an opening in one side into which a normal oil lamp could be placed. It could be made of terra cotta, but the Romans are also known to have had lanterns made of metal with translucent sides made of animal horn. The lantern was carried by means of a ring (or cloth or leather strap) attached to the top.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In earlier Greek the word \i fanos\i* meant a torch, but by New Testament times it appears to have been used primarily to refer to a type of lamp used outdoors. \s G04301800300038\s* mentions two instruments for giving light. It is obvious that these two kinds of light are close in meaning since translations are evenly divided in translating “torches and lanterns” (so \a CEV\a*, \a NIV\a*) or “lanterns and torches” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*), even though the Greek text has only one reading.
\line Where it is difficult to find words for two distinct objects that give light by a burning fire, it may be necessary to use one word for the two things. Translators should avoid a word for an object that gives light through the use of electricity or batteries.
\line See also the discussion in the following entry.
\key 5.4
\title Torch
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לַפִּיד
\trl lapid
\ref H00101501700028 H00700701600040 H00700702000040 H00701500400022 H00701500400038 H00701500500012 H01804101100006 H02306200100038 H02600101300026 H02701000600026 H03400200500028 H03801200600034
\grk δᾳδουχία
\trl dadouchia
\ref L07800402200022
\grk λαμπάς
\trl lampas
\ref G04002500100024 G04002500400022 G04002500700020 G04002500800030 G04301800300042 G04402000800006 G06600400500026 G06600801000030 L06801002200024 L07104800100024 L07700603900040
\grk φῶς
\trl fōs
\ref G04401602900006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0475_torch.jpg|col||© Andrew Dunn (Wikimedia Commons)|Torches|5.0\fig* The torch was a burning stick or bundle of sticks carried about as a light. In order to lengthen the time of burning, one end of the stick could be wrapped with cloth, which was soaked in a flammable substance such as pitch.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In modern British English, a “torch” is a handheld electric light powered by batteries, that is, a “flashlight” in American English. Such a word would be entirely out of place in the translation of the Bible.
\line \s H01804101300010\s*: Here the focus is on the flame, not on the torch that contains the flame, so for the first line of this verse \a GNT\a* has “Flames blaze from his mouth.”
\line While the Greek word \i lampas\i* most properly refers to a “torch,” in some places (for example, \s G04402000800006 G06600400500026\s*) some translations prefer the English derived term “lamp.”
\line Some languages may find it difficult to distinguish between “torches” and “lanterns” in \s G04301800300042\s*. It is possible to say “burning sticks and containers with small fires for light.” See also the discussion \l target="REALIA:5.3">5.3 Lantern\l*.
\line \s G04401602900006\s*: The jailer demanded that “lights” be brought, but the text does not indicate the specific instruments. Many languages will be able to follow the pattern of \a GNT\a* and \a GECL\a* by beginning this verse with “The jailer called for a light.” It is likely that torches from the entrance to the jail would have been most readily available. However, the intention of the jailer will be adequately expressed also with “The jailer called for someone to bring a lamp.”
\key 5.5
\title Bed, sleeping mat
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יָצוּעַ
\trl yatsu‘a
\ref H00104900400026 H01300500100026 H01801701300018 H01906300700008 H01913200300020
\heb מִטָּה
\trl mitah
\ref H00104703100028 H00104800200038 H00104903300026 H00200702800036 H00901901300022 H00901901500034 H00901901600022 H00902802300056 H01000400700018 H01101701900048 H01102100400058 H01200100400014 H01200100600086 H01200101600062 H01200401000020 H01200402100012 H01200403200026 H01201100200066 H01402201100060 H01402402500050 H01700100600034 H01700700800038 H01900600700016 H02002601400018 H02200300700004 H02602304100008 H03000301200056 H03000600400008
\heb מֵסַב
\trl mesav
\ref H02200101200012
\heb מַצָּע
\trl matsa‘
\ref H02302802000008
\heb מִשְׁכָּב
\trl mishkav
\ref H00104900400018 H00200702800030 H00202101800042 H00301500400006 H00301500500012 H00301502100012 H00301502300010 H00301502400036 H00301502600006 H00301502600022 H00301802200012 H00302001300014 H00403101700030 H00403101800022 H00403103500020 H00702101100026 H00702101200032 H01000400500046 H01000400700024 H01000401100024 H01001100200024 H01001101300042 H01001300500014 H01001702800002 H01100104700072 H01200601200056 H01401601400030 H01800701300016 H01803301500026 H01803301900012 H01900400500018 H01903600500008 H01904100400014 H01914900500014 H02000701700004 H02002202700016 H02101002000020 H02200300100004 H02305700200010 H02305700700014 H02305700800034 H02305700800046 H02602301700014 H02603202500010 H02800701400020 H03300200100016
\heb עֶרֶשׂ
\trl ‘eres
\ref H00500301100026 H00500301100028 H01800701300008 H01900600700022 H01904100400008 H01913200300018 H02000701600006 H02200101600014 H03000301200064 H03000600400018
\grk κλινάριον
\trl klinarion
\ref G04400501500024
\grk κλίνη
\trl klinē
\ref G04000900200014 G04000900600048 G04100402100032 G04100700400046 G04100703000026 G04200501800012 G04200801600020 G04201703400018 G06600202200010 L06700800400018 L06701401100044 L06800800300046 L06801002100014 L06801300200026 L06801300400042 L06801300600012 L06801300700008 L06801501100048 L06900100600042 L06900700800026 L07102301800010 L07104800600018
\grk κλινίδιον
\trl klinidion
\ref G04200501900042 G04200502400050
\grk κοίτη
\trl koitē
\ref G04201100700042 G04500901000018 G04501301300022 G05801300400016 L06801300100058 L06900401700024 L07000301300018 L07000301600018 L07103101900020 L07104000500012 L07104102400020 L07700100500014 L07700600800036 L08601701600024
\grk κράβαττος
\trl krabattos
\ref G04100200400036 G04100200900034 G04100201100012 G04100201200014 G04100605500020 G04300500800016 G04300500900020 G04300501000030 G04300501100028 G04400501500028 G04400903300026
\grk στρωμνή
\trl strōmnē
\ref L06800900300020 L06801300900016
\grk φορεῖον
\trl foreion
\ref L07800302700028 L07800900800054
\lat cubile
\ref V08200300100034
\lat lectus
\ref V08201202600026
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0429_sleepingmat.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man lying on a sleeping mat|5.0\fig* The bed was an object on which a person slept. In some cases it could be a raised piece of furniture. However, the Semites from Canaan did not usually sleep on raised beds, but rather on skins spread on the floor. When the bed was a piece of raised furniture, it took a form similar to beds used in most cultures today: a low platform standing on four legs, a bit longer than the length of a man, and about 70-80 centimeters (27-31 inches) wide.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0083_wooden_bed.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Copy of an ancient wooden bed|5.0\fig* \s H00104703100028\s*: The beds used from ancient times in Egypt, especially by richer people, were similar to beds known in most cultures today. Specimens of them have been found in a number of Egyptian tombs. Sometimes in place of pillows, the Egyptians made use of headrests. These were made of wood, concave in form, with a base or pedestal 20 centimeters (8 inches) or more in height. It is probable that it was this kind of headrest upon which Jacob bowed himself (compare \a NJB\a* “pillow”). Another possibility may be considered when translating this verse. The Hebrew word \i mitah\i* translated “bed” by \a RSV\a* can also mean “staff,” and this indeed is how it was understood by the Septuagint (followed by \s G05801102101000\s* and \a NIV\a*). However, the great majority of translations say “bed.” Translators should not attempt to harmonize the translations of this verse and \s G05801102101000\s*.
\line \fig |UBS-0030_bed.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Beds|5.0\fig* \s H01900600700022\s*: “My couch” (\a RSV\a*) in the third line of this verse is synonymous with “my bed” in the second line. \a GNT\a* (also \a NJB\a*, \a REB\a*) uses “bed” and “pillow” as more natural contemporary equivalents.
\line \s H02200101200012\s*: The Hebrew word \i mesav\i* referring to a piece of furniture occurs only here. While most modern translations understand it to be a kind of “couch” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*), some understand it to refer to the low “table” (\a KJV\a*, \a NASB\a*, \a SPCL\a*) at which people reclined for meals. Some translations avoid having to make the choice by rendering the first line of this verse as “As long as my king is near me” (\a GECL\a*) or “While my king is at his banquet” (\a FRCL\a*). \a TOB\a* renders \i mesav\i* as “enclosure” and adds a footnote explaining that the word, which may designate the bed that surrounded the dining table or the courtiers surrounding the couple, here speaks of a garden whose perfume attracts the king. \a ITCL\a* has adopted this interpretation by rendering the first line as “Now that my king is here in his garden.”
\line \fig |KNW-0308_rollingup_mat.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Rolling up a sleeping mat|5.0\fig* In a number of New Testament contexts, the Greek terms \i klinarion\i*, \i klinidion\i* and \i krabattos\i* refer to cots or stretchers on which sick or convalescent persons might be resting or on which they could be transported. It could be made of reeds or cloth. It was thin and light and could be rolled or folded and carried easily by one person. There is no New Testament context in which these terms refer to couches on which people reclined while eating.
\line The Greek word \i klinē\i* refers generally to any piece of furniture employed for reclining or lying on. In \s G04000900200014\s* a rendering such as “stretcher” or “cot” (in American English) is certainly more advisable than the traditional rendering “bed” (\a RSV\a*), which might imply a large piece of furniture. In each passage translators must employ a term for \i klinē\i* that is most likely to identify the type of object which fits the context.
\line \s G04201100700042\s*: It is not necessary to understand the statement “my children are with me in bed” (\a RSV\a*) to mean that the children were in the same bed with the man, but it is, of course, possible that the reference here is to a relatively humble house in which all the members of the family would sleep on the floor in the same corner of the room or on a single raised platform. This passage may be rendered simply as “I have gone to bed and so have my children” or “I am already in bed and so are my children.”
\line The bed is sometimes used figuratively. In several places it refers to sexual intercourse (\s G04501301300022 L07000301300018 L07000301600018 L07102301800010\s*), whether in marriage or in an unlawful union. When the Greek word \i koitē\i* is used together with the verb \i echō\i* in \s G04500901000018\s*, it means “to be pregnant.” In \s L07700100500014\s* the text says literally that Alexander “fell into bed,” that is, he got sick or “fell sick” (\a RSV\a*).
\key 5.5.1
\title Bedpost
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk κανών
\trl kanōn
\ref L06801300600008
\grk στῦλος
\trl stulos
\ref L06801300900030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The flat sleeping surface of the raised bed was supported on its four corners by legs or posts. Sometimes these posts extended above the bed about the height of a person standing. A thin cloth could be spread over the top of the posts and hung down to the ground. This enclosed the bed, preventing insects from disturbing the sleeper (see \l target="REALIA:5.5.2">5.5.2 Canopy, mosquito net\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where beds with posts are not known, it is possible to translate the verses listed above without reference to the structure of the bed. So \s L06801300600080\s* may be rendered “She went to the head of the bed and took down Holofernes’ sword from the place where it was hanging.” \s L06801300900030\s*b may be translated “she pulled down the mosquito netting from the bed.”
\key 5.5.2
\title Canopy, mosquito net
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk κωνώπιον
\trl kōnōpion
\ref L06801002100022 L06801300900024 L06801301500044 L06801601900030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The mosquito net was a fine fabric, thin enough to allow air to pass through, but heavy enough to prevent insects from going through its mesh. It was usually suspended from posts that projected above the bed on its four corners (see \l target="REALIA:5.5.1">5.5.1 Bedpost\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line For the Greek word \i kōnōpion\i*, some older English translations have “canopy” (\a RSV\a*, \a KJV\a*). This, however, can be misleading. The purpose of this covering was not decoration but rather to keep the insects, especially the mosquitoes, away. Many languages will have a special word for such a net, perhaps even, like the Greek, one based on the word for “mosquito” (though this is not a necessary part of the meaning).
\key 5.6
\title Cushion, pillow
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk προσκεφάλαιον
\trl proskefalaion
\ref G04100403800018 L08100300800026
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The pillow was an object, usually soft, on which a person would lay his or her head.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It is important to avoid a translation in \s G04100403800018\s* that would suggest that Jesus was so small or curled up as to be able to sleep on a single pillow. \a GECL\a*, for example, has Jesus lying “on a seat-cushion.” It is better to say “with his head on a cushion” (\a NLT\a*) or “with his head on a pillow” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a* ).
\key 5.7
\title Table for eating
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מֵסַב
\trl mesav
\ref H02200101200012
\heb שֻׁלְחָן
\trl shulchan
\ref H00202502300006 H00202502700032 H00202502800034 H00202503000010 H00202603500010 H00202603500034 H00202603500050 H00203002700008 H00203100800008 H00203501300006 H00203701000010 H00203701400032 H00203701500032 H00203701600018 H00203903600006 H00204000400010 H00204002200010 H00204002400022 H00302400600022 H00400303100014 H00400400700006 H00700100700028 H00902002900070 H00902003400014 H01000900700058 H01000901000060 H01000901100046 H01000901300016 H01001902900042 H01100200700026 H01100500700034 H01100704800036 H01101000500006 H01101302000014 H01101801900058 H01200401000024 H01302801600014 H01302801600022 H01302801600026 H01302801600034 H01400400800006 H01400401900040 H01400900400006 H01401301100054 H01402901800050 H01600501700042 H01803601600026 H01902300500008 H01906902300004 H01907801900022 H01912800300028 H02000900200014 H02302100500006 H02302800800006 H02306501100030 H02602304100014 H02603902000008 H02604003900014 H02604003900024 H02604004000034 H02604004000060 H02604004100004 H02604004100014 H02604004100030 H02604004200006 H02604004300030 H02604102200048 H02604401600018 H02701102700020 H03900100700026 H03900101200014
\grk κατακλίνω
\trl kataklinō (verb)
\ref G04200703600036 G04202403000010 L06801201500074
\grk τράπεζα
\trl trapeza
\ref G04001502700036 G04100702800026 G04201602100018 G04202202100024 G04202203000014 G04400600200040 G04401603400016 G04501100900012 G04601002100022 G04601002100022 L06900401700014 L07100601000010 L07101401000020 L07102902600008 L07103101200004 L07104002900008 L07600101800024 L07700102200006 L07700404900034 L07700405100010
\lat mensa
\ref V08200901900028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0476_meal.jpg|col||Matson Collection, Library of Congress|Family eating at a low table|5.0\fig* Meals were eaten from a mat or low table. The mat could be made of straw or an animal skin. The low table stood only about 30 centimeters (12 inches) high.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i shulchan\i* (literally “a thing thrown”) originally referred to a straw mat or animal skin spread on the ground. People sat on the ground or reclined on one side. By New Testament times, people ate while lying on their side next to a low table. Normally a person reclined on the left side, leaning on the left elbow and eating with the right hand. The knees were bent with the feet behind the back. While Jesus was in this position, the woman in \s G04200703600036 G04200703701000 G04200703801000\s* was able to perfume his feet from behind him while he was eating. This would have been an almost impossible action if he had been seated in a chair. In this passage an explanatory note may be appropriate. In most of the other passages listed above, a common word for “table” will be adequate since the exact structure will be unimportant. \fig |KNW-0320_last_supper.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Men reclining at a low table|5.0\fig*
\line A higher table, at which a person could sit in a chair, was also known in ancient times. Such tables often had three legs, two on one side and one opposite, giving the table stability on uneven surfaces. In fact, the Greek word \i trapeza\i* means “three legs.” Such tables, however, were used for purposes other than eating.
\line For the Hebrew word \i shulchan\i* used with the sense of “altar,” see \l target="REALIA:4.2.3">4.2.3 Temple altar\l* and \l target="REALIA:4.2.4">4.2.4 Incense altar\l*.
\line For the Hebrew word \i mesav\i* in \s H02200101200012\s*, see the comments at \l target="REALIA:5.5">5.5 Bed, sleeping mat\l* above.
\line In a number of New Testament passages, the word “table” is used in a phrase in which the focus is on what happens at a table rather than on the table itself. Thus, for example, “eat and drink at my table” (\s G04202203000014\s*; \a RSV\a*) may be rendered “eat and drink with me” (\a CEV\a*); “to serve tables” (\s G04400600200040\s*; \a RSV\a*) may be “to assist in the distribution” (\a REB\a*) or “to handle finances” (\a GNT\a*); and “You cannot partake of the table of the Lord and the table of demons” (\s G04601002100022\s*; \a RSV\a*) may be “You cannot participate at the same time in the Lord’s meal and in the meals of evil spirits” (\a PV\a*).
\line In \s G04200703600036\s* most English translations consulted use the word “table” in some phrase like “sat down at table.” It is possible, however, to avoid introducing the table. \a CEV\a* has “got ready to eat.”
\key 5.8
\title Footstool
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb הֲדֹם, רֶגֶל
\trl hadom regel
\ref H01302800200014 H01909900500014 H01911000100028 H01913200700012 H02306600100020 H02500200100036
\heb כֶּבֶשׁ
\trl kevesh
\ref H01400901800016
\grk ὑποπόδιον
\trl hupopodion
\ref G04000503500012 G04202004300014 G04400203500014 G04400704900016 G05800101300036 G05801001300018 G05900200300054
\lat scabillum
\ref V08200600400028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0477_footstool.jpg|col||© Zunkir (Wikimedia Commons)|Man seated with his feet on a footstool|5.0\fig* The footstool was a piece of furniture on which a person could rest his feet. It took the form of a low stool on which the feet were placed to keep them off the ground. Egyptian footstools, such as the one shown below actually depicted enemies the Egyptian king had defeated.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Since footstools are a common cultural feature in many parts of the world, it is may not be necessary to use a descriptive phrase. Translators can, however, use an expression such as “thing on which to rest one’s feet.” In some languages the functional equivalent of “footstool” is “footstick,” which is a stick on which a person normally places his feet in order to raise them from the relatively damp dirt floor of a typical house or hut. \fig |PTZ-0084_footstool.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Egyptian footstool|5.0\fig*
\line Except for \s G05900200300054\s*, the Greek word \i hupopodion\i* occurs only as a figure in the New Testament. As a figure, it occurs in quotations from or allusions to Old Testament verses. Most translations consulted render it literally; for example, in \s G04202004300014\s* \a GNT\a* has “until I put your enemies as a footstool under your feet.” \a NCV\a* renders it nonfiguratively, saying “until I put your enemies under your control.” Similarly, at \s G04000303501000\s* instead of the literal “or by the earth, for it is his footstool” (\a RSV\a*), \a NCV\a* has “using the name of the earth, because the earth belongs to God.” In \s G05900200300054\s* \i hupopodion\i* refers to an actual footstool, when the host insults the poor man by telling him, “Sit under my footstool.” \a REB\a* retains the reference to the footstool with “sit here on the floor by my footstool.” However, most translations choose to omit the footstool with something similar to \a NIV\a*, which says “Sit on the floor by my feet.”
\key 5.9
\title Chair, seat
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כִסֵּא
\trl kise’
\ref H00700302000056 H00900100900036 H00900200800028 H00900401300018 H00900401800028 H01100201900050 H01100201900056 H01200401000028 H01700300100042 H02000901400014
\heb מוֹשָׁב
\trl moshav
\ref H00902001800022 H00902002500012 H00902002500024 H01802900700020 H01900100100036 H02600800300076 H02602800200036
\heb תְּכוּנָה
\trl tkunah
\ref H01802300300016
\grk καθέδρα
\trl kathedra
\ref G04002101200050 G04002300200010 G04101101500054 L07100700400018 L07101201200046
\grk πρωτοκαθεδρία
\trl prōtokathedria
\ref G04002300600020 G04101203900004 G04201104300016 G04202004600034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0478_chair.jpg|col||© Anthony Huan (Wikimedia Commons)|Chair without a back|5.0\fig* The chair was an object on which a person sat. Chairs differed widely in shape and materials. Most often they were made of a wooden or cane frame with the seat woven of reeds or made of wood. Sometimes the chair had a back, sometimes not. See also \l target="REALIA:1.10.1">1.10.1 Throne\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line All cultures have words for places to sit. In most of the references above, the object on which a person sits is not specifically described, and usually a generic word for “seat” is to be preferred. \fig |WEB-0479_chair.jpg|col||© Rama (Wikimedia Commons)|Chair with a back|5.0\fig*
\line \s H01802300300016\s*: The Hebrew word \i tkunah\i* means literally “prepared place.” Older translations, such as \a RSV\a* and \a KJV\a*, have “seat” (and Luther even has “throne”). Most modern translations prefer something like “where [he] is” (\a GNT\a*) or “dwelling” (\a NIV\a*).
\line In \s G04002300200010\s* the phrase “seat of Moses” carries a double meaning. On the one hand, there was in many synagogues a stylized chair, usually made of stone, which was called by this very name. Examples of this chair have been found by archaeologists. On the other hand, the chair symbolized the authority to make religious rulings. To “sit on the seat of Moses” meant holding a position of authority. It is this latter meaning that is the more important in the words of Jesus. Most English translations prefer a literal rendering of the text, but a dynamic translation is to be preferred. The following renderings are ways in which this has been done:
\line “have inherited the authority of Moses” (Brc);
\line “speak with the authority of Moses” (\a Phps\a*);
\line “teach with Moses’ authority” (\a GW\a*);
\line “are the authorized interpreters of Moses’ Law” (\a GNT\a*);
\line “have the authority to tell you what the law of Moses says” (\a NCV\a*);
\line “are experts in the Law of Moses” (\a CEV\a*).
\line The Greek word \i prōtokathedria\i* refers to a position or place of particular importance, implying special status to the person occupying it. Here the important element is not the structure of the seat but rather the honor which having that seat gives to a person. Many cultures have a special word for such a seat of honor. If such a word does not carry with it pagan overtones, it should be used. English translations find several appropriate renderings: “most important seats” (\a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*), “best seats” (\a RSV\a*), “reserved seats” (\a GNT\a*), and even “front seats” (\a CEV\a*).
\key 5.10
\title Millstones, mill
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb פֶּלַח
\trl pelach
\ref H00700905300010 H01001102100024 H01804101600016
\heb רֵחַיִם
\trl rechayim
\ref H00201100500044 H00401100800020 H00502400600006 H02304700200004 H02402501000030
\heb רֶכֶב
\trl rekev
\ref H00502400600010 H00700905300012 H01001102100026
\grk μυλικός
\trl mulikos
\ref G04201700200010
\grk μύλινος
\trl mulinos
\ref G06601802100016
\grk μύλος
\trl mulos
\ref G04001800600034 G04002404100010 G04100904200038 G06601802200058
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0481_handmill.jpg|col||Matson Collection, Library of Congress|Handmill|5.0\fig* \fig |WEB-0482_handmill.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Handmill|5.0\fig* The mill was two flat stones between which grain was ground into flour by scraping the top stone against the bottom one. In Old Testament times the normal mill was relatively small and operated by hand. The grain was placed on the stationary bottom stone, and the top stone was pressed down on top of the grain and scraped back and forth to grind the grain into flour. The work of grinding was normally done by women in the early hours of the morning before sunrise. It was hard work and took a lot of time. It is estimated that to produce enough flour to make bread for a family of five, a woman would have needed to grind for over three hours each day. The sound of grinding in the early hours by the light of an oil lamp symbolized stability and security. \s H02402501001000\s* describes the tragedy that is to come upon the people of Judah when Jeremiah quotes God as saying “I will remove from them . . . the sound of the millstone and the light of the lamp.”
\line \fig |WEB-0483_handmill.jpg|col||© Marcus Cyron (Wikimedia Commons)|Woman grinding with a handmill|5.0\fig* The same type of mill continued in use in New Testament times, but round millstones also came into use. With this type of mill, the upper stone and the lower stone were essentially the same size, and the upper stone was rotated on the lower stone. Grain was poured into this type of mill through a hole in the center of the upper stone, and the flour gradually emerged from around the edges of the two stones. Some of these mills were relatively small and operated by hand. Others, however, were quite large, and animals were used to rotate the upper stone.
\line In many parts of the world, grain is ground in one way or another. Quite frequently mills are of the same general structure as those used in ancient times, in which two relatively large, flat stones were placed one on top of the other, and the grain was ground between the two stones. In some parts of the world, a mortar and pestle are used for the grinding or pounding of grain.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0484_millstrone.jpg|col||Matson Collection, Library of Congress|Later handmill|5.0\fig* Frequently the word “millstones” may be rendered “stones for grinding grain.” In other instances, even a more generic expression may be used, for example, “large stones.” In most contexts what is important is either the large size of the stones or the function of grinding grain, not necessarily the particular form of the mill. However, in the context that speaks about tying a millstone to a man’s neck and his being thrown into the depths of the sea (\s G04001800600034 G04100904200038 G04201700200010\s*), it is important to refer to relatively large stones that would cause a person to sink immediately. In such a context the use of a term for “mortar,” especially one of wood, would hardly be appropriate since it would normally float.
\line \fig |KNW-0430_handmill_grinding.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Women grinding with a handmill|5.0\fig* The Hebrew word \i pelach\i* refers to one of the two stones of the Old Testament type of hand mill. In \s H00700905300010\s* and \s H01001102100024\s* it is the upper stone (\i pelach rekev\i* in Hebrew), while in \s H01804101600016\s* it is the lower stone (\i pelach tachtith\i*).
\key 5.11
\title Oven
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb תַּנּוּר
\trl tanur
\ref H00101501700022 H00200702800056 H00300200400014 H00300700900016 H00301103500018 H00302602600024 H01600301100030 H01601203800054 H01902101000006 H02303100900038 H02500501000006 H02800700400008 H02800700600010 H02800700700010 H03900301900018
\grk κλίβανος
\trl klibanos
\ref G04000603000024 G04201202800024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0431_bakingoven_tending.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Oven|5.0\fig* The oven was an implement for cooking food. Ovens were made of hardened clay or brick. They could vary in size and shape. An oven in an average home was roughly 50 centimeters (20 inches) in diameter. In the winter the oven could also serve the purpose of heating a small house. See also \l target="REALIA:1.11.1">1.11.1 Smelting furnace, kiln\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line All cultures know of devices for cooking food. The word “oven” may be rendered “place heated for baking bread” or “place for heating food.” It may be useful in some instances to employ a more extensive description in a glossary. However, this is rarely necessary since the function of an oven is far more important than its form. The difference between an oven and a smelting furnace (see \l target="REALIA:1.11.1">1.11.1 Smelting furnace, kiln\l*) is primarily one of size rather than of basic design.
\line The Hebrew word \i tanur\i* in \s H00101501700022\s* seems to refer to a portable stove or fire pot, a kind of round earthenware bowl holding coals.
\line \s G04000603000024 G04201202800024\s*: The point of the illustration in these verses is that God will take care of his people even more than he takes care of something like wild grass, which only serves as fuel for burning. So it is possible to omit mention of the instrument in which the grass is burned; for example, instead of “thrown into the oven” (\a RSV\a*), \a NIV\a* says “thrown into the fire,” and \a GECL\a* has “burned up.” Such a translation will be especially appropriate for cultures where grass is not burned in an oven. The above comments should be considered also when translating \s H03900301900018\s*.
\key 5.12
\title Cooking pot, kettle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb דּוּד
\trl dud
\ref H00900201400018 H01403501300042 H01804101200012
\heb כִּיּוֹר
\trl kiyor
\ref H00900201400010
\heb כְּלִי
\trl kli
\ref H00300602100004
\heb סִיר
\trl sir
\ref H00201600300036 H00202700300006 H00203800300020 H01100704500008 H01200403800050 H01200403900052 H01200404000044 H01200404100020 H01200404100052 H01202501400008 H01400401100012 H01400401600008 H01403501300034 H01804102300008 H01905801000008 H01906001000004 H01910801000004 H02100700600016 H02400101300028 H02405201800008 H02405201900032 H02601100300020 H02601100700034 H02601101100012 H02602400300034 H02602400600020 H03300300300042 H03801402000034 H03801402100008
\heb פָּרוּר
\trl parur
\ref H00401100800040 H00700601900048 H00900201400034
\heb צַלַּחַת
\trl tsalachath
\ref H01403501300050
\heb קַלַּחַת
\trl qalachath
\ref H00900201400026 H03300300300054
\grk λέβης
\trl lebēs
\ref L07101300200034 L08100101300032 L07800700300018 L08000801300028 L08001200100018 L08001802000034
\grk ξέστης
\trl xestēs
\ref G04100700400038
\grk τήγανον
\trl tēganon
\ref L07800700300014 L07800700500042 L08000801300030 L08001201000012 L08001201900016
\grk χαλκεῖον, χαλκίον
\trl chalkeion, chalkion
\ref G04100700400042 L08100101300028
\grk χύτρα
\trl chutra
\ref L07101300200030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0485_pot.jpg|col||© Bukvoed (Wikimedia Commons)|Ceramic pots|5.0\fig* The cooking pot was a deep container made of metal or fired earthenware. It was filled with water and placed over a fire. Food was boiled in the water.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line All cultures know some kind of pot for cooking. A distinction will usually need to be made between a flat cooking pan and one that is deeper and is used to boil liquids. The latter is intended here.
\line In \s H00900201400018\s* and \s H01403501300042\s* several words for cooking vessels are listed in a series. It is possible to use an inclusive term rather than try to find separate words for each one; for example, for the list of four containers in \s H00900201400018\s*, \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a* have simply “cooking pot.”
\line \fig |WEB-0486_pot.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Metal and ceramic cooking pots|5.0\fig* \s H01804102300008\s* (following comments adapted from \i A Handbook on The Book of Job\i*): The second line of this verse is literally “like a blown pot and rushes.” \a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*, and \a GNT\a* all have somewhat different translations, since, as in \s H02400101300028\s*, “a boiling pot” is literally “a blown pot,” suggesting that it means a pot under which the flame is blown so that its contents boil from the increased heat. \a RSV\a* interprets the “rushes” as “burning rushes,” while \a GNT\a* describes the smoke pouring out of Leviathan’s nose as being “like smoke from weeds burning under a pot.” The word “weeds” is a shift to a more general term. The \a GNT\a* rendering is not a very close translation of the Hebrew. \a NIV\a* apparently likens the smoke from Leviathan’s nostrils to the vapor “from a boiling pot over a fire of reeds.” This represents the Hebrew more closely than either \a RSV\a* or \a GNT\a*, but it is doubtful whether the reeds are really part of the picture in the writer’s mind. A more satisfactory translation for the whole verse is “Smoke pours forth from his snout as from a boiling cooking pot.”
\line \s H01905801000008\s*: The Hebrew of this verse is particularly difficult. Refer to \i A Handbook on Psalms\i*, page 519.
\line In \s G04100700400038\s* the vessels in question were kitchen tools, used in preparing or serving food. Most modern translations render the Greek word \i chalkion\i* here as “pots” (\a NCV\a*) or “bowls” (\a CEV\a*). In a number of languages the most natural equivalent for this word is “metal vessel” or “kettle.”
\line In \s L07800700300018\s* the Greek words \i lebēs\i* and \i tēganon\i* occur together. The \i lebēs\i* seems to have involved boiling water, so it may be rendered “caldrons” (\a RSV\a*) or “kettles” (\a GNT\a*). The \i tēganon\i* was for cooking without water, that is, frying. In this context both implements would have been very large, so \a REB\a* renders \i tēganon\i* as “great pans,” and \a GNT\a* has “huge pans.”
\key 5.13
\title Griddle
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַחֲבַת
\trl machvath
\ref H00300200500012 H00300601400004 H00300700900034 H01302302900038 H02600400300010
\heb מַשְׂרֵת
\trl masreth
\ref H01001300900010
\heb מַרְחֶשֶׁת
\trl marchesheth
\ref H00300200700008 H00300700900028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The griddle was a thick plate made of pottery (and later of metal) with small depressions similar to a modern waffle iron. It was placed on three stones between which a fire was built. Bread dough was then put on the surface of the griddle and cooked.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages translators may have to render the Hebrew word \i machvath\i* as “flat cooking pan” or “flat iron for baking.”
\line In \s H02600400300010\s* it is not the function of the griddle that is important but its form. Most translations use a more general term here, such as “iron pan” (\a GNT\a*) or “iron plate” (\a RSV\a*).
\key 5.14
\title Mirror
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַרְאָה
\trl mar’ah
\ref H00203800800024
\heb רְאִי
\trl r’i
\ref H01803701800014
\grk ἔσοπτρον
\trl esoptron
\ref G04601301200010 G05900102300040 L07000702600014 L07101201100040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0487_mirror.jpg|col||© Louvre Museum (Wikimedia Commons)|Hand mirror|5.0\fig* The mirror was a flat piece of highly polished metal used to reflect an image. Mirrors were usually made of copper, bronze, or brass, sometimes of silver.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Even though the ancient world did not have mirrors made of glass, in \s G04601301200010\s* and \s G05900102300040\s* the function of the mirror to give a reflection is more important than the material from which it is made. However, in \s H00203800800024\s* it will be necessary to employ an expression (or a footnote) that shows that the mirrors in question were made of metal.
\line In \s H01803701800014\s* it is the hard and polished appearance of the mirror which is in focus. It is not easy to convey both the hardness and the shininess without considerable expansion, and translations tend to emphasize one aspect or the other; for example, \a ITCL\a* says “As shiny as a mirror,” and \a NIV\a* has “hard as a mirror of cast bronze.” Attempts to combine the two without much expansion may leave the reader with questions; for example, \a GNT\a* has “as hard as polished metal,” but is polished metal harder than metal that is not polished? An expanded translation for the whole verse might be “Can you join God in spreading out the sky so that it looks as hard as a shiny mirror made of cast bronze?”
\key 5.15
\title Wineskin, water bag
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אוֹב
\trl ’ov
\ref H01803201900016
\heb חֵמֶת
\trl chemeth
\ref H00102101500014 H00102101900032 H03500201500010
\heb נֹאד
\trl no’d
\ref H00600900400036 H00600901300006 H00700401900026 H00901602000014 H01905600900014 H01911908300008
\heb נֵבֶל
\trl nevel
\ref H00900102400030 H00901000300070 H00902501800022 H01001600100060 H01803803700014 H02401301200030 H02401301200054 H02404801200034
\grk ἀσκοπυτίνη
\trl askoputinē
\ref L06801000500012
\grk ἀσκός
\trl askos
\ref G04000901700012 G04000901700028 G04000901700042 G04000901700056 G04100202200014 G04100202200032 G04100202200046 G04100202200056 G04200503700014 G04200503700038 G04200503700050 G04200503800010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0145_objects_tools.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Wineskin|5.0\fig* The wineskin or water bag was a bag made of skin or leather. Normally the skin of a goat or a sheep was used, although the skin of an ox or a camel was also possible. The skin was removed from the animal by separating it at the neck and then pulling it back whole over the body, and the skin was tanned and the hair usually removed. The skin was then turned inside out and four of the five openings (neck and four legs) were tied shut.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0488_waterskin.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Waterskin|5.0\fig* The bag was used to contain liquids, primarily wine or water. The skin was only a temporary storage vessel since the leather tended to spoil the taste of the liquid.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i ’ov\i* occurs only in \s H01803201900016\s* with the meaning “wineskin,” which is made clear in the context. See the discussion on this verse in \i A Handbook on The Book of Job\i*, pages 601-602.
\line \s H01905600900014 H03500201500010\s*: Some authorities do not see references to wineskins in these passages. See the discussions on these verses in \i A Handbook on Psalms\i* (pages 505-506) and \i A Handbook on The Books of Nahum, Habakkuk, and Zephaniah\i* (pages 105-106).
\line \s H01911908300008\s*: For the first line of this verse, \a GNT\a* has “I am as useless as a discarded wineskin.” In many languages this rendering will have little or no meaning. Accordingly, the translator has two choices: either to say “I am of no account,” or to use a local object instead of “wineskin,” such as a mildewed bag.
\line \s G04000901700012 G04100202200014 G04200503700014 G04200503800010\s*: These parallel passages in the New Testament refer to “wineskins.” A number of translators have attempted to substitute “bottles” for “wineskins,” but this has not been satisfactory, since fermenting wine does not normally break glass or earthen bottles, while it would break old wineskins. In circumstances in which the use of wineskins is not known, it may be necessary to employ some kind of descriptive phrase (for example, “container made of skin,” “closed bag of skin,” or “goat skin like a bottle”) and a fuller explanation in a footnote.
\key 5.16
\title Basin, washbasin
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סַף
\trl saf
\ref H00201202200026 H00201202200060 H01001702800006
\heb סִיר, רַחַץ
\trl sir rachats
\ref H01906001000004 H01910801000004
\grk νιπτήρ
\trl niptēr
\ref G04301300500012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0432_washing_bassin.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man washing hands in a basin|5.0\fig* The basin was a large bowl, normally made of clay. It had several uses; commonly it held water and was used for washing the hands, face, and feet.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s G04301300500012\s*: The word \i niptēr\i* does not appear elsewhere in Greek literature; its meaning is uncertain, but most translations have “basin,” “washbasin,” or “bowl.” It can be argued that the word means “pitcher” or “jug,” since in the Ancient Near East, people’s feet were not generally washed in a basin of standing water but by pouring water over the feet from a pitcher. With this understanding the picture in \s G04301300500012\s* would be as follows: The disciples were on cushions, reclining on their left sides, and using their right hands to reach into the dishes that were on the table, or tables, placed in front of them. Jesus poured water into “the pitcher” (the Greek text has the definite article “the,” suggesting that it was a particular vessel used specifically for that purpose) and then went around behind the disciples, where their feet were stretched out behind them. There he poured water from the pitcher over their feet and dried them with the towel (see \l target="REALIA:10.4">10.4 Towel\l*) wrapped around his waist.
\key 5.17
\title Carpet, rug
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גֶּנֶז
\trl genez
\ref H02602702400024
\heb מַד
\trl mad
\ref H00700501000012
\heb צָפִית
\trl tsafith
\ref H02302100500012
\heb שְׂמִיכָה
\trl smikah
\ref H00700401800050
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0489_carpet.jpg|col||© Grand Parc - Bordeaux, France (Wikimedia Commons)|Carpets|5.0\fig* The carpet was a covering for the floor of a room. It could be made of skins or cloth, usually woven from the hair of animals.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H02602702400024\s*: Like the other words in this entry, the Hebrew word \i genez\i* may appear only once in the Bible. \a REB\a* understands it to mean “stores” (see \s H01700300900046\s*; \s H01700400700040\s*, and \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.4">3.14.1.4 Treasury, strongroom\l*), and \a GECL\a* has “garments,” but most translations agree that it means “carpets” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*) or “rugs” (\a NIV\a*).
\line \s H00700501000012\s*: The meaning of the Hebrew word \i mad\i* here is uncertain, so translations vary widely. A brief survey shows the following renderings: “rich carpets,” “carpets” (\a RSV\a*, \a NRSV\a*, \a ITCL\a*, \a GECL\a*, \a SPCL\a*, Luther, \a BE\a*); “saddles,” “saddle-cloths,” “saddle blankets” (\a GNT\a*, \a REB\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*); “caparisons” (\a JB\a*); “rich cloths” (the Jewish Publication Society’s \i The Holy Scriptures\i*); “judgment” (Vulgate, \a KJV\a*). In this verse the speakers address a broad range of society, but it is unclear if they divide society into three groups (\a RSV\a* “you who ride on tawny asses, you who sit on rich carpets, and you who walk by the way”) or into two groups (\a CEV\a* “Whether you ride on a donkey with a padded saddle or have to walk”). The decision on how many groups are in view depends on the meaning adopted for the Hebrew word \i mad\i*. Since saddles were frequently made of a piece of cloth that closely resembled a floor rug, those riding on donkeys could be the same as those sitting on (a saddle made of) a carpet.
\line \s H02302100500012\s*: Some older translations (for example, \a KJV\a*) rendered the Hebrew word \i tsafith\i* here as “watchtower.” It is now commonly accepted that it probably means a floor carpet on which people sat while eating.
\line \s H00700401800050\s*: The Hebrew word \i smikah\i* appears only here in Scripture. It designates a thick cloth, perhaps a vertical hanging in a tent or a floor rug that could serve as a cover against the cold. \a GNT\a* follows the first option by rendering the last clause in this verse as “she hid him behind a curtain.” \a RSV\a* selects the second option with “she covered him with a rug.” If the second option is chosen, the translator may want to follow the example of \a CEV\a* by adding some implicit information here: “[Sisera lay down, and] Jael covered him with a blanket.”
\key 5.18
\title Containers, vessels
\index \l target="REALIA:5.18.1">5.18.1 Containers for storage\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.18.2">5.18.2 Basket\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אָסוּךְ
\trl ’asuk
\ref H01200400200056
\heb בַּקְבֻּק
\trl baqbuq
\ref H01101400300020 H02401900100014 H02401901000008
\heb חֶרֶשׂ
\trl cheres
\ref H02002602300010
\heb כְּלִי
\trl kli
\ref H00104202500014 H00104301100034 H00104502000012 H00203701600010 H00300602100004 H00300602100022 H00301103200024 H00301103300006 H00301103400038 H00301400500026 H00301405000018 H00301501200004 H00301501200024 H00400400900046 H00400501700016 H00401901500006 H00401901700034 H00502302500028 H00800200900050 H00900900700040 H01001702800010 H01101002100006 H01101701000062 H01200400300012 H01200400300030 H01200400400032 H01200400600012 H01200400600028 H01200400600040 H01400902000006 H01700100700008 H01700100700014 H01700100700018 H01802801700016 H01900200900012 H02302202400028 H02302202400036 H02302202400048 H02306500400042 H02306602000094 H02401400300032 H02401800400008 H02401800400038 H02401901100050 H02402202800022 H02403201400066 H02404001000056 H02404801100028 H02404801100032 H02404801200028 H02404803800030 H02405103400020 H02600400900040
\heb עֶצֶב
\trl ‘etsev
\ref H02402202800004
\grk ἀγγεῖον
\trl aggeion
\ref G04002500400016 L06800702000054 L06801000500048 L07102101400008 L07700605300014
\grk ἄγγος
\trl aggos
\ref G04001304800028
\grk ἄντλημα
\trl antlēma
\ref G04300401100014
\grk κάλπη
\trl kalpē
\ref L08000301200046
\grk καψάκης
\trl kapsakēs
\ref L06801000500018
\grk σκεῦος
\trl skeuos
\ref G04200801600014 G04301902900002 G04500902100036 G06600202700018 L07300101500006
\lat vas
\ref V08200605600040 V08200903400028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0433_storage_containers.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Storage containers|5.0\fig* The container was a solid object for holding things. Containers were made of earthenware or metal, sometimes of wood. They varied widely in size and shape.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0490_flask.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Flask|5.0\fig* Most languages have a generic term for containers. The Hebrew word \i kli\i* is extremely general, similar in its usage to English words like “implement,” “instrument,” or even “object” or “thing.” Translators should be guided by the context. In \s H00800200900050\s*, for example, it is obvious that the reference is to vessels from which the workers can get a drink of water, and the translator may want to indicate this; for example, \a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a* and \a CEV\a* have “water jars,” and \a NCV\a* says “water jugs.” In most passages a general word will be the right choice. Translators should avoid words that indicate containers made of plastic, rubber, tin, or any other materials that were not known in biblical times.
\line The Hebrew word \i ’asuk\i* in \s H01200400200056\s* refers to some kind of jar or flask, probably made of earthenware. Most translations add the qualifier “small” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*).
\line The Hebrew word \i baqbuq\i* refers to a small flask with a narrow neck. In modern Hebrew it is the word for “bottle.”
\line In \s H02002602300010\s* the Hebrew word \i cheres\i* refers to a vessel that is made from cheap and commonplace material.
\line \s H01802801700016\s*: At the end of this verse the Hebrew is literally “a vessel of fine gold.” While most translations have something like “jewels of fine gold” (\a RSV\a*), \a GNT\a* and others understand “vessel” (\i kli\i* in Hebrew) to refer to a “gold vase,” which is probably more accurate than “jewels.” In some languages “a vessel of fine gold” may be rendered “a pot made of fine gold.” Since the focus is on the high value of wisdom, rather than on a comparison with any particular implement, translators may want to follow \a CEV\a* for the whole verse: “Nothing is its equal—not gold or costly glass.”
\line The vessels referred to in \s G04002500400016\s* would have been relatively small, containing not more than a liter (about a quart).
\line The containers in \s G04001304800028\s* would have been rather large, containing perhaps 15-19 liters (4-5 gallons).
\line \s G04300401100014\s*: The Samaritan woman observes that Jesus has “nothing to pull up water with.” The Greek word \i antlēma\i*\s G04300401100014\s* comes from a verb meaning “to draw water.” It gives no indication of its shape or of the material from which it was made. Many translations say “bucket.” This may imply a container made of metal, plastic or even rubber, which are all inappropriate. Even a bucket made of wood was probably unlikely in New Testament times. It was more likely a container made of leather. In many languages the best solution will be to avoid using a word for a specific object. An acceptable solution would be to begin the woman’s words in this verse with “Sir, the well is deep, but you have nothing to pull up water with.” A similar rendering is employed by \a GW\a*, \a NCV\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a SPCL\a*, \a PV\a*, and others.
\line \s G04301902900002\s*: While \a RSV\a* and \a GNT\a* render the Greek word \i skeuos\i* as “bowl,” others have “jar” (\a CEV\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a NLT\a*, \a REB\a*). Here it is best to use a generic term such as “vessel” or “container” (\a GECL\a*). The word \i skeuos\i* is used often in the New Testament with the broad meaning of “thing, object, stuff” (see \s G04001202900026 G04100302700024 G04101101600014 G04201703100024 G04401001100016 G04401001600020 G04401100500026 G04402701700034 G05500202000016 G05500202100018 G05800902100016 G06601801200048 G06601801200056\s*).
\key 5.18.1
\title Containers for storage
\index \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.1">5.18.1.1 Stone jar\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.2">5.18.1.2 Clay jar\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.3">5.18.1.3 Alabaster jar, alabaster flask\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.4">5.18.1.4 Money box, treasure box\l*
\cont Storage jars were containers of varying size used for holding and storing liquids such as water and oil or dry foods such as grains. These containers were generally carved out of soft stone or were made from clay. They were more or less cylindrical in shape with an opening at the top. The opening could be closed with a lid (see \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.2.1">5.18.1.2.1 Lid, cover\l*).
\key 5.18.1.1
\title Stone jar
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk λίθινος, ὑδρία
\trl (lithinos) hudria
\ref G04300200600008 G04300200600010 G04300200700014
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0491_vessel_stone.jpg|col||© Zde (Wikimedia Commons)|Stone jar|5.0\fig* Stone jars were water containers. In the only place in the Bible where these water containers are mentioned, they are described in unusual detail. Their capacity is given as “between twenty and thirty gallons” (\a GNT\a*; about 80-120 liters), and they are said to be made of stone. Stoneware in Bible times was made from soft stone. It could be carved with a hammer and chisel and made smooth with various tools, or it could be turned on a lathe much like wood was turned by a carpenter.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0135_liquid_jars.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Filling stone jars with water|5.0\fig* For the water containers in \s H00800200900050\s*, see the discussion at \l target="REALIA:5.18">5.18 Containers, vessels\l*.
\line \s G04300200600008\s*: The fact that the jars here are stone, rather than earthenware, is important. According to Jewish law, earthenware jars, if contaminated, had to be broken, but contaminated stone jars could simply be washed. The Greek word \i hudria\i* indicates that the jars were intended for water. The relation between the words in the phrase “six stone water jars” (\a GNT\a*) must be made more explicit in some languages, for example, “six large jars made of stone and used for holding water.”
\key 5.18.1.2
\title Clay jar
\index \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.2.1">5.18.1.2.1 Lid, cover\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.2.2">5.18.1.2.2 Potsherd\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כַּד
\trl kad
\ref H00102401400020 H00102401500046 H00102401600036 H00102401700028 H00102401800018 H00102402000010 H00102404300048 H00102404500026 H00102404600010 H00700701600034 H00700701600048 H00700701900064 H00700702000024 H01101701200034 H01101701400014 H01101701600002 H01101803400010 H02101200600032
\heb נֵבֶל
\trl nevel
\ref H02303001400010 H02500400200026
\heb צַפַּחַת
\trl tsapachath
\ref H00902601200018 H00902601600064 H01101701200046 H01101701400026 H01101701600014 H01101900600018
\grk κεράμιον
\trl keramion
\ref G04101401300036 G04202201000028
\grk ὑδρία
\trl hudria
\ref G04300402800008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0434_well_clayjars.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Women at a well fill clay jars|5.0\fig* The clay jar was an earthenware vessel that was used as a storage container for liquids like wine and olive oil (see also \l target="REALIA:5.18.1">5.18.1 Containers for storage\l*). It could also be used to carry water and other liquids.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Unlike stone water jars (see \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.1">5.18.1.1 Stone jar\l*), which were intended only for the storage of water, clay jars had to be light enough when full to be carried by a woman, who normally did such work in the society of that time. While John uses the same Greek word for “jar” in 2.6 and in 4.28, it is clear from the context that two different kinds of vessels are intended. The woman in \s G04300402800008\s* would not have been carrying a stone jar, which would have been very heavy. Most translations have “water jar” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*). Where a language makes a distinction between a vessel for drawing or carrying water and a vessel for drinking, a word for the former vessel should be used.
\key 5.18.1.2.1
\title Lid, cover
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb צָמִיד
\trl tsamid
\ref H00401901500014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0492_storiage_jar.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Jar with lid|5.0\fig* The lid was a cover made to fit tightly over the opening of a pot or jar. In some cases the lid was secured by tying it to the container.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i tsamid\i* normally means a kind of bracelet worn as jewelry (see \l target="REALIA:10.5.2">10.5.2 Bracelet, armlet, anklet\l*). In \s H00401901500014\s*, however, it indicates the way a jar was covered. The translation of this verse should convey the idea that the vessel is not closed or covered and so foreign objects might fall into it. Possible models are \a GNT\a* “Every jar and pot in the tent that has no lid on it also becomes unclean” and \a NCV\a* “And every open jar or pot without a cover becomes unclean.” In this verse the Hebrew word \i pathil\i*, which describes the situation of the lid relative to the vessel, is expressed by some translations as “tied” (\a NASB\a*, \a REB\a*, Luther, \a ITCL\a*). Others choose a more general term, such as “fastened” (\a RSV\a*, \a NRSV\a*, \a NIV\a*). Another model for the whole verse is “Any jar or pot that is not closed tightly becomes unclean.”
\key 5.18.1.2.2
\title Potsherd
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶרֶשׂ
\trl cheres
\ref H01800200800008 H01804102200006 H01902201600008 H02303001400030 H02602303400016
\grk ὄστρακον
\trl ostrakon
\ref L07102200900004
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0493_broken_pottery.jpg|col||© Davidbena (Wikimedia Commons)|Pieces of broken pottery|5.0\fig* The potsherd was a piece of pottery that had broken. Since it resulted from breaking, it had no regular shape. Potsherds were usually not very large, smaller than the palm of a hand, and they could have sharp edges.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Most household vessels for eating, drinking, cooking, and so on were made of clay, either sun-dried or fired. Such vessels broke easily and were not usually repaired. Pieces of such broken vessels were extremely common. Most translations render “potsherd” as “piece of broken pottery” (\a GNT\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*) or something similar.
\key 5.18.1.3
\title Alabaster jar, alabaster flask
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ἀλάβαστρον, ἀλάβαστρος
\trl alabastron, alabastros
\ref G04002600700010 G04101400300034 G04101400300048 G04200703700040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0494_alabaster_oinment_pot.jpg|col||© Wellcome Images, UK (Wikimedia Commons)|Alabaster jar|5.0\fig* The alabaster jar was a jar made of calcite stone. This jar normally had a rather long neck that had to be broken off for the contents to be used. It served primarily as a container for precious substances such as perfumes. Such jars were usually small.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Archaeological and literary evidence reveals that in the Hellenistic period jars for perfume, originally of alabaster, were replaced by glass jars. But these continued to be called “alabasters.” They were sealed when purchased and were opened by breaking. This is why \s G04101400300034\s* very properly says that the woman broke the jar, a detail not recorded in the Matthew parallel. While glass was not as expensive as alabaster, it too was not commonplace and was a valued commodity.
\line \fig |KNW-0142_alabaster.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Alabaster jars|5.0\fig* When rendering “alabaster jar,” many translators have used a term meaning “jar” or “flask” along with a descriptive qualifier, such as “made of alabaster stone,” “made of valuable stone,” or “made of valuable stone called alabaster.” Since alabaster is not widely known today, some translations omit this information; for example, for the literal phrase “an alabaster flask of ointment of pure nard, very costly” (\a RSV\a*) in \s G04101400300034\s*, \a CEV\a* says “a very expensive bottle of sweet-smelling perfume”; this, however, leaves the reader in doubt as to whether the bottle was expensive or its contents (it was the contents). \a GECL\a* and the Hebrew common language version are better with “a small bottle with pure, expensive nard oil.”
\key 5.18.1.4
\title Money box, treasure box
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk γλωσσόκομον
\trl glōssokomon
\ref G04301200600034 G04301302900012
\grk θησαυρός
\trl thēsauros
\ref G04000201100042 G04001203500014 G04001203500034 G04001305200044 G04200604500014
\grk κιβωτός
\trl kibōtos
\ref L08100105100030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0435_moneybox.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Money box|5.0\fig* The money box was a container, perhaps made of wood, in which money or other small valuable objects were kept. The box would probably have been small enough to be carried easily in one hand or under the arm.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Treasure box” may be rendered “box with valuable objects” or “box with objects costing a great deal of money.”
\line In \s G04301302900012\s* the physical money box is not in focus but rather the function performed by Judas. Therefore, for the literal phrase “Judas had the money box,” it may be useful to say simply “Judas was in charge of the money” (\a CEV\a*) or “Judas was the treasurer for the group.” The Greek expression here may be understood as an idiom.
\line \s G04000201100042\s*: The Greek word \i thēsaurus\i*, translated “treasures” by \a RSV\a* here, may refer either to something valuable that is stored away or to the place or object in which something valuable is stored away. In this verse the translations are divided between the meaning “treasure” and “treasure container”; and even where the second of these interpretations is followed, commentators do not agree concerning the nature of the container. For example, some suggest “treasure box,” while others deny this meaning and argue for “sack.” In light of the many possibilities, none of which is conclusive, the best solution is simply to translate \i thēsaurus\i* in a way that is most natural in the receptor language yet does not contradict the biblical culture. Some examples of things that contradict the biblical culture would be “suitcases,” “trunks,” and “safes.” These words should be avoided. Many translators have used general expressions such as “baggage” and “sacks [or, containers] they carried their valuable things in.”
\key 5.18.2
\title Basket
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֵיפָה
\trl ’eyfah
\ref H00201603600012 H00300501100044 H00300601300032 H00301903600010 H00400501500034 H00402800500008 H00502501400012 H00502501400016 H00502501500014 H00700601900018 H00800201700034 H00900102400022 H00901701700022 H02002001000008 H02002001000012 H02300501000024 H02604501000008 H02604501100004 H02604501100042 H02604501300016 H02604501300032 H02604502400006 H02604502400016 H02604502400036 H02604600500006 H02604600500038 H02604600700004 H02604600700014 H02604600700052 H02604601100024 H02604601100034 H02604601100064 H02604601400026 H03000800500036 H03300601000018 H03800500600018 H03800500700028 H03800500800024 H03800500900054 H03800501000028
\heb דּוּד
\trl dud, dudai
\ref H01201000700048 H01908100700014 H02402400100012 H02402400200004 H02402400200026
\heb טֶנֶא
\trl tene’
\ref H00502600200044 H00502600400012 H00502800500004 H00502801700004
\heb כְּלוּב
\trl kluv
\ref H02400502700004 H03000800100014 H03000800200018
\heb סַל
\trl sal, salsiloth
\ref H00104001600040 H00104001700008 H00104001700040 H00104001800020 H00202900300010 H00202900300024 H00202902300028 H00202903200034 H00300800200058 H00300802600006 H00300803100052 H00400601500004 H00400601700022 H00400601900036 H00700601900034
\heb תֵּבָה
\trl tevah
\ref H00200200300018 H00200200500042
\grk κόφινος
\trl kofinos
\ref G04001402000026 G04001600900024 G04100604300010 G04100801900020 G04200901700024 G04300601300012
\grk σαργάνη
\trl sarganē
\ref G04701103300010
\grk σπυρίς
\trl spuris
\ref G04001503700026 G04001601000018 G04100800800020 G04100802000016 G04400902500028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0495_basket.jpg|col||© Habib M’henni (Wikimedia Commons)|Basket|5.0\fig* The basket was a container made of woven material, usually grass or reeds. Baskets could vary widely in size, depending on their intended use. Baskets were used for carrying a great variety of things, including food and produce and even for moving soil from one place to another.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i ’eyfah\i* sometimes refers to a volume of measure and sometimes to the basket used to hold that measure. The translator will need to pay special attention to the context.
\line In \s H03800500700028\s* there is reference to something that serves as a lid or cover (\i kikar\i* in Hebrew) for a basket. This object is said to be made of lead and does not seem to be a normal feature of a basket. Most translations render it “lid made of lead” (\a GNT\a*) or “lead cover” (\a CEV\a*, \a GW\a*).
\line \fig |ABS-0004_paul_lowered_in_basket.jpg|col||Bible for Today's Family © American Bible Society|Man in a basket|5.0\fig* The Hebrew word \i kluv\i* in \s H02400502700004\s* seems to refer to a very specialized type of basket, in fact, a cage for holding birds. \a RSV\a* begins the verse with “Like a basket full of birds,” implying that the birds must be dead. However, instead of the word “basket,” most other translations prefer the word “cage,” which seems to sustain the imagery of the previous verse better. On the other hand, in \s H03000800100014 H03000800200018\s* \i kluv\i* is no doubt a general term for “receptacle.” The translation should have a general word if possible, one that would be appropriate for showing fruit for sale in the marketplace, carrying it, or storing it. If no kind of basket is suitable, then any container used for such purposes would be acceptable.
\line It is impossible to determine precisely the differences in meaning among the three New Testament terms for baskets listed above. In \s G04701103300010\s*, which is the only place where the Greek word \i sarganē\i* occurs, the basket was evidently rather large, since it was used to let Paul down from an opening in the wall of Damascus. The same basket is referred to in \s G04400902500028\s* with the Greek word \i spuris\i*.
\line Translators often find it difficult to find satisfactory equivalents for the Greek words \i spuris\i* and \i kofinos\i*, since in various receptor languages there are highly specific terms for particular kinds of baskets depending upon the type of construction and size. Unfortunately, there is no way of determining from the Greek text precisely the size or type of baskets involved. The translator should be careful not to use a word that indicates a container made of modern materials such as plastic or rubber.
\key 5.19
\title Closet, cabinet, cupboard
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מֶלְתָּחָה
\trl meltachah
\ref H01201002200014
\grk κυλικεῖον
\trl kulikeion
\ref L07701503200032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The “closet” was actually a niche built into a wall of a house in which objects could be kept.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i meltachah\i* in \s H01201002200014\s* indicates a place for storing clothes, that is, a “clothes closet” or “wardrobe.” It will be confusing in some languages to say that a person is responsible for a closet and getting the clothes from it. It is preferable to follow \a GNT\a* and others and avoid using the name of the object. For the whole verse \a GNT\a* says “Then Jehu ordered the priest in charge of the sacred robes to bring the robes out and give them to the worshipers.”
\line The Greek word \i kulikeion\i* refers to a place or stand for storing drinking vessels, that is, a “cupboard.” In \s L07701503200032\s* the items stored seem to include more than just cups. In English the word “cupboard” has come to indicate a general storage place. Other languages may have a similar generic term or even a specific term for a place for storing eating utensils like cups and plates.
\key 5.20
\title Eating utensils
\index \l target="REALIA:5.20.1">5.20.1 Bowl\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.20.2">5.20.2 Plate, platter\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.20.3">5.20.3 Cup\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.20.4">5.20.4 Knife\l*
\cont People in biblical times ate food from plates and bowls, as is familiar in most cultures today, but it seems that they did not use implements to lift the food from the plate to their mouth. This was done with the right hand.
\key 5.20.1
\title Bowl
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַגָּן
\trl ’agan
\ref H02200700300004 H02302202400040
\heb גֻּלָּה
\trl gulah
\ref H02101200600022 H03800400200036 H03800400300018
\heb מִזְרָק
\trl mizraq
\ref H03000600600008
\heb מִשְׁאֶרֶת
\trl mish’ereth
\ref H00200702800062 H00201203400018 H00502800500008 H00502801700008
\heb צְלֹחִית
\trl tslochith
\ref H01200202000010
\grk ἀργύρωμα
\trl argurōma
\ref L06801200100016 L06801501100042 L07701503200040
\grk ὁλκεῖον
\trl holkeion
\ref L06801501100054
\grk σκάφη
\trl skafē
\ref L07600103300034
\grk τρύβλιον
\trl trublion
\ref G04002602300026 G04101402000028 L07103101400024
\grk φιάλη
\trl fialē
\ref G06600500800044 G06601500700024 G06601600100034 G06601600200016 G06601600300012 G06601600400012 G06601600800012 G06601601000012 G06601601200012 G06601601700012 G06601700100024 G06602100900024 L07700102200022 L08100201000002
\grk χρύσωμα
\trl chrusōma
\ref L07701503200036
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The bowl was a concave dish used for holding or cooking food or liquids. Bowls varied widely in diameter and depth. Such bowls would normally have been made of fired clay, but the reference in \s G06600500800046\s* specifically states that the bowls there were of gold. Because of the variety in size and depth, and because cups frequently had no handles, there was essentially no physical difference between cups and smaller bowls. The first illustration under 5.20.3 “Cup” also pictures bowls.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s H03800400200036\s* the purpose of the bowl (\i gulah\i* in Hebrew) may not be immediately clear to the reader. It is recommended that the translator follow the example of \a GNT\a* by saying “At the top is a bowl for the oil.”
\line The bowls mentioned in \s H03000600600008\s* are specifically said to be for drinking (see \l target="REALIA:5.20.3">5.20.3 Cup\l*). Some kind of cultural adaptation may be necessary. In some cultures, for example, it is possible to use a word for a particular kind of large calabash, or a general word for calabash which is qualified as “big” and “filled.”
\line The Hebrew word \i mish’ereth\i* refers to a large bowl in which bread dough was kneaded and allowed to rise before baking. Most translations have “kneading bowls” (\a RSV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*) or “kneading troughs” (\a NIV\a*, \a REB\a*). “Baking pans” in \a GNT\a* is misleading. Where a special word for such a bowl does not exist or is not well known, translators may follow the example of \a CEV\a* with “bowls of bread dough.”
\line In \s G04002602300026\s* and \s G04101402000028\s* the Greek word \i trublion\i* can be understood as part of an idiom, which is literally “to dip one’s hands into a bowl with someone.” Most translations render the idiom more or less literally, which can give the reader the wrong impression that a person is putting his fingers in the bowl rather than dipping food that he holds in his hand. If the translator chooses to translate the idiom somewhat literally, it is important to render it “to dip food into a bowl together with someone” or “to dip food jointly into a sauce.” It is probably preferable to interpret the idiom as “sharing a meal with someone” or “eating together with someone.” For the last half of \s G04101402000028\s* \a CEV\a* has “one . . . who is eating from this dish with me,” and \a NLT\a* says “one who is eating with me now.”
\line \s L07701503200036\s*: The Greek word \i chrusōma\i* is literally “golden object.” However, here it is used to refer to gold or gold-plated eating utensils. \a GNT\a* and \a NRSV\a* say “gold[en] bowls.”
\key 5.20.2
\title Plate, platter
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb צַלַּחַת
\trl tsalachath
\ref H01202101300044 H02001902400012 H02002601500012
\grk παροψίς
\trl paropsis
\ref G04002302500030
\grk πίναξ
\trl pinax
\ref G04001400800026 G04001401100014 G04100602500034 G04100602800014 G04201103900034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0496_platter.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Platter|5.0\fig* The plate was a flat dish on which food was eaten or served. It was normally made of baked clay, but the dishes of royalty and rich people could be made of precious metals.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H02001902400012 H02002601500012\s*: In these passages the lazy person is described as someone who puts his hand in the dish and will not lift it to his mouth. In many cultures this could be misunderstood to mean that he is too lazy even to pick up a fork but just puts his hand in his food. This, however, is not the point of the proverb. It was normal to eat food with one’s hand. The person is lazy because he will not even lift his hand to his mouth. A translator should try to focus on the real reason for the person’s laziness. Two good models for \s H02001902400012\s* are \a GNT\a* “Some people are too lazy to put food in their own mouths” and \a CEV\a* “Some people are too lazy to lift a hand to feed themselves.”
\line \s G04001400800026\s*: The Greek noun \i pinax\i* may refer to any kind of flat dish; the word originally meant “board” or “plank.” In cultures where plates are not normally used, translators will use “bowl” or whatever is the normal object on which someone would carry food.
\key 5.20.3
\title Cup
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גָּבִיעַ
\trl gavi‘a
\ref H00104400200006 H00104400200008 H00104401200030 H00104401600058 H00104401700026 H00202503100026 H00202503300004 H00202503300028 H00202503400012 H00203701700032 H00203701900004 H00203701900028 H00203702000012 H02403500500018
\heb כּוֹס
\trl kos
\ref H00104001100004 H00104001100030 H00104001100042 H00104001300030 H00104002100024 H01001200300056 H01100702600018 H01400400500018 H01901100600024 H01901600500010 H01902300500024 H01907500900004 H01911601300002 H02002303100020 H02305101700022 H02305101700030 H02305102200028 H02305102200038 H02401600700030 H02402501500020 H02402501700010 H02402502800016 H02403500500026 H02404901200024 H02405100700002 H02500402100028 H02602303100014 H02602303200010 H02602303300010 H02602303300018 H03500201600024
\heb סַף
\trl saf
\ref H03801200200012
\heb סֵפֶל
\trl sefel
\ref H00700502500012 H00700603800042
\grk ποτήριον
\trl potērion
\ref H00104001101030 H00104001101180 H00104001101220 H00104001301200 H00104002101120 H01001200301370 H01100701201080 H01400400501120 H01901000601140 H01901500501090 H01902200501180 H01907400901020 H01911500401010 H02002303101190 H02305101701080 H02305101701150 H02305102201180 H02401600701160 H02402800701010 H02403000601110 H02403201501090 H02403201701040 H02403202801080 H02404200501090 H02500201301210 H02500402101160 H02602303101110 H02602303201050 H02602303301070 H02602303301090 H03500201601150 G04001004200090 G04002002200130 G04002002300050 G04002302500120 G04002302600080 G04002602700030 G04002603900200 G04100700400170 G04100904100060 G04101003800130 G04101003900120 G04101402300030 G04101403600110 G04201103900140 G04202201700030 G04202202000030 G04202202000110 G04202204200080 G04301801100140 G04601001600020 G04601002100030 G04601002100070 G04601102500040 G04601102500110 G04601102600100 G04601102700100 G04601102800140 G06601401000160 G06601601900270 G06601700400180 G06601800600170 L06900100700002 L08600801400022
\grk σπονδεῖον
\trl spondeion
\ref L07105001500006 L07700102200016 L08100200900012 L08100200900018
\grk χρύσωμα
\trl chrusōma
\ref L07701105800008 L07701105800026 L08100300600012
\lat calix
\ref V08201403900014
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0497_drinking_bowl_philistine.jpg|col||Hanay (Wikimedia Commons)|Drinking bowl|5.0\fig* The cup was an implement used for drinking. Common cups were made of earthenware, sometimes fired and glazed. By New Testament times, cups made of glass were common. Richer people often used cups made of bronze, silver, or gold. A cup could be cylindrical, similar to a modern cup, or it could be more the half-globe shape of a bowl. In either of these forms, it might have one or two handles or no handles at all.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0032_vessels_for_drinking.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Cups|5.0\fig* While many objects resembling a modern drinking cup have been found, people in ancient times often drank from something resembling a small bowl. In terms of historical development, the drinking bowl was probably first. The Hebrew word \i sefel\i* refers to an implement that came after the drinking bowl. It had about equal height and diameter and had handles.
\line Several of the words listed above could equally well be translated “cup” or “bowl,” and this is reflected in the translations. Some translations say “drinking bowl.” However, a generic word for “cup” will be a close enough equivalent in most languages.
\line In \s H00104400000000\s* the Hebrew word \i gavi‘a\i* refers to a special cup, one that is explicitly said to be made of silver. In some cultures it will be necessary to choose a word that does not indicate a drinking vessel made of another substance, such as a gourd, or a cup made of wood or clay.
\line \s G04001004200090 G04100904100060\s*: In place of the literal expression “cup of water” in \s G04100904101000\s* (in which “cup” not only identifies the container but also indicates the quantity of water), some languages use the expression “water in a cup.” But it is even more likely that the typical equivalent of “cup of water” would be “drink of water” (\a GNT\a*). In some parts of the world, the expression “cup of water” suggests something rather strange and foreign, so some translators might find that an expression like “gourd of water” would not only be more natural, but would also be the semantic equivalent of “drink of water.”
\line \s L07701105800080\s* and \s L08100300600012\s* say literally “drink from golden.” The meaning is clearly “drink from golden cups” or “. . .golden vessels.”
\key 5.20.4
\title Knife
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶרֶב, צוּר
\trl cherev tsur
\ref H00600500200024 H00600500300010
\heb מַאֲכֶלֶת
\trl ma’akeleth
\ref H00102200600046 H00102201000020 H00701902900018 H02003001400010
\heb שַׂכִּין
\trl sakin
\ref H02002300200006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0498_knife.jpg|col||© Chamberi (Wikimedia Commons)|Knife|5.0\fig* The knife was a small blade with a handle, used for cutting meat and other food.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew words listed above refer to a sharp knife, which probably was also pointed. Translators should avoid a word that is limited to the rather blunt kind of instrument with which things are spread on bread.
\line \s H00600500200024 H00600500300010\s*: The Hebrew word \i cherev\i* normally refers to a sword (see \l target="REALIA:2.3">2.3 Sword\l*). Here it is used in the context of the delicate operation of circumcision, so it is clear that a smaller implement is in view. The Hebrew modifier \i tsur\i* indicates that this knife was made from flint, an extremely hard type of quartz stone. From ancient times tools and weapons were made from flint by chipping or flaking to produce very sharp edges.
\key 5.21
\title Other household items
\index \l target="REALIA:5.21.1">5.21.1 Needle\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.21.2">5.21.2 Broom\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.21.3">5.21.3 Peg (on a wall)\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:5.21.4">5.21.4 Birthstool\l*
\key 5.21.1
\title Needle
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk βελόνη
\trl belonē
\ref G04201802500014
\grk ῥαφίς
\trl rhafis
\ref G04001902400020 G04101002500016
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0499_needles.jpg|col||© Portable Antiquities Scheme (Wikimedia Commons)|Needles|5.0\fig* The needle was a small, slender, and very smooth instrument, pointed on one end and with a hole at the other end. It was used to aid in passing thread through cloth in sewing. It could be made of metal, bone, or even a strong thorn.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line There is no convincing evidence that the literal expression “eye of a needle” in \s G04001902400020 G04101002500016\s* and \s G04201802500014\s* is a figurative name for a narrow gate. The reference to a camel passing through the eye of a needle is an example of rhetorical hyperbole. Here it is a purposeful exaggeration to point out the extreme difficulty of the event to which it is compared. It seems that Jesus chose the largest land animal known in Israel and the smallest man-made opening to express this difficulty. The hole in a needle is referred to differently in various languages, for example, “nostril of a needle,” “ear of a needle,” “mouth of a needle,” and even “anus of a needle.”
\key 5.21.2
\title Broom
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb מַטְאֲטֵא
\trl mat’ate’
\ref H02301402300024
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0500_broom.jpg|col||© Juan R. Lascorz (Wikimedia Commons)|Brooms|5.0\fig*\fig |KNW-0436_broom_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Broom|5.0\fig* The broom was a longer or shorter stick to one end of which was attached some flexible material such as small branches. The broom was used to sweep dirt from the floor.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i mat’ate’\i* appears only in \s H02301402300024\s*, although it is known from extra-biblical literature. In the Isaiah reference it is an instrument of destruction and judgment, and most translations render literally “broom of destruction” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*). Where an equivalent implement is not known, or where a destructive broom might seem too strange, translators may follow \a CEV\a*, which renders the last half of the verse as “The LORD will sweep out the people.”
\key 5.21.3
\title Peg (on a wall)
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יָתֵד
\trl yathed
\ref H02302202300006 H02302202500022 H02601500300024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The peg was a short wooden stick, pointed on one end. It was pounded into a crack between stones that formed the wall of a house. It then served as a place to hang objects.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s H02302202300006 H02302202500022\s* the wall peg is a symbol of stability. See the discussion at \l target="REALIA:3.2.2">3.2.2 Tent peg, stake\l*.
\key 5.21.4
\title Birthstool
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb אָבְנַיִם
\trl ’ovnayim
\ref H00200101600024
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The birthstool was a special seat, perhaps made of two stones side by side with a space between them, on which a woman sat to give birth.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i ’ovnayim\i* literally means “pair of stones” or “double stone.” Lexicographers and commentators differ concerning its meaning in \s H00200101600024\s*. In \s H02401800300032\s* the same word refers to the potter’s wheel (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.1.1">1.5.1.1 Potter’s wheel\l*). The dictionaries offer two probable meanings: (1) it may be a euphemism to refer to the genitals, so the second clause in \s H00200101600024\s* may be rendered “you will look to see if the baby is a boy”); or (2) it may designate a birthstool because of a certain resemblance to the potter’s bench, so the same clause may be rendered “you will watch as they give birth.” The context allows either interpretation.
\line It is not necessary to give a literal translation; for the first half of this verse, compare \a GNT\a* “When you help the Hebrew women give birth.” Where such a stool or chair is known, of course, it may be used here. \a NIV\a* has “When you help the Hebrew women in childbirth and observe them on the delivery stool.” here. \a NIV\a* has “When you help the Hebrew women in childbirth and observe them on the delivery stool.”
