\grk ἐσθής
\trl esthēs
\ref G04202301100028 G04202400400032 G04400101000034 G04401003000054 G04401202100014 G05900200200020 G05900200200036 G05900200300014 L07800803500032
\grk μαλακός
\trl malakos
\ref G04001100800014 G04001100800024 G04200702500014
\lat tunica
\ref V08200203900016 V08200204500018
\lat vestimentum
\ref V08200903800064
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line All the words listed above are general terms for clothing. For a specific discussion on the clothing of the High Priest, see \l target="REALIA:4.5">4.5 High Priest’s clothing\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line At times the context may indicate with some degree of certainty which specific article of clothing is intended. For the most part, however, a generic word for “clothing,” “clothes,” “dress,” or “covering” may be used.
\line Some have seen symbolic significance in the Hebrew word \i ’adereth\i* in \s H01101901900062\s*, when Elijah throws his mantle over Elisha. While this may be confirmed by the events of \s H01200200800010 H01200201300008 H01200201400008\s*, the translator should probably not use a different word than the one used in the other references for \i ’adereth\i*.
\line The Hebrew word \i ksuth\i* means “covering” in the passages listed above.
\line The Hebrew word \i pthigil\i* appears only in \s H02300302400036\s*, and its meaning is uncertain. The context makes it clear that it was some kind of fine garment that was probably wrapped around the wearer.
\line The Hebrew word \i takrik\i* appears only in \s H01700801500020\s*, and its root appears nowhere else in the Hebrew Bible. It was some sort of “mantle” (\a RSV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*), “cape” (\a CEV\a*), or “cloak” (\a GNT\a*) that was wrapped around the outer garment. The one worn by Mordecai was a symbol of royalty like the rest of his clothes.
\line While the Greek word \i esthēs\i* does not indicate a specific piece of clothing, it does refer to the high and impressive quality of the clothing. It is used several times for the clothing of angels. The Greek word \i malakos\i* also refers to clothing of high quality.
