\trl failonēs
\ref G05500401300004
\grk χλαμύς
\trl chlamus
\ref G04002702800008 G04002703100016 L07801203500034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0437_robe_hem_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Robe and hem|6.0\fig* The cloak was a long, flowing outer garment reaching to the feet. It was generally a loose-fitting cloth that was draped around the body and held in place in the middle by a sash wrapped around the waist (see \l target="REALIA:6.6">6.6 Waistband, sash, belt\l*) or some means of fastening such as pins or buttons. The cloak was worn at all levels of society, including also priests and other religious leaders. It served more purposes than just an outer covering. Women sometimes carried bowls or other implements or grain (see \s H00202202601000\s*) in its folds. For poorer people it also served as a covering when sleeping. For this reason Jewish law prohibited taking a person’s robe overnight as a guarantee (\s H00202202601000\s* [25]).
\line For the robe of the High Priest, see \l target="REALIA:4.5.3">4.5.3 Robe\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The outer garment is referred to by a number of Hebrew and Greek terms that are not easily distinguished. The choice of an equivalent for these terms relating to “outer garment” will depend largely upon the specific context and the usage in each receptor language. The most common equivalent is usually a term meaning “coat.” In some passages the long robe is culturally significant as an indication of high social status and dignified occupation or activity.
\line Some Bible passages refer to people tearing their clothes. This was done as an act of grief (see \s H00103703400008 H00600700600008 H01000101100018 H01000303100026 H01001303100012 H01200500700022 H01500900300026 H01500900500028 H01700400100018 H01800102000014 H01800201200036\s*). Translators may expand the expression for tearing clothes; for example, in \s H01800102000010\s*a \a GNT\a* has “Then Job got up and tore his clothes in grief,” where the addition of “in grief” makes clear the purpose of the gesture. It is also possible to translate the meaning of the gesture only; for example, “Job stood up full of grief” or “Job got to his feet, his heart broken.” Where there is a common local custom used to display grief, it may be helpful to keep the biblical custom in the text and to compare it to the local custom in a note; for example, the note may read “This is equivalent to the practice of painting the face to show that the person is in mourning.”
\line \s H00800301500010\s*: The Hebrew word \i mitpachath\i* would normally be expected to mean a kind of “veil” (\a KJV\a*; compare \s H02300302200004\s*). In this context, however, it is clear that a veil of thin material would not have been strong enough to carry the weight of the barley. Older translations understood it to be a kind of “mantle” (\a RSV\a*), while modern translations prefer something like “cloak” (\a GNT\a*, \a REB\a*). Others look for a more modern equivalent, such as “cape” (\a CEV\a*) or “shawl” (\a NJPSV\a*, \a NCV\a*).
\line \s H02300302200004\s*: Sheffer suggests translating the Hebrew word \i machalatsoth\i* (plural of \i machalatsah\i*) in this verse as “loincloths.” It is probably better to say “cloaks” or “shawls.”
\line \s G05400200900042\s*: The Greek word \i himatismos\i* in this verse is the general word for garments of any kind, but since women are being referred to, then the word “dresses” (\a GNT\a*) will fit this context if “dresses” are the natural wear in a translator’s culture. However, in cultures where women wear some other type of clothing, translators should use a more general word, as the Greek does.
\key 6.2.1
\title Hem, corner of a garment
\index \l target="REALIA:6.2.1.1">6.2.1.1 Fringe, tassel\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כָּנָף
\trl kanaf
\ref H00401503800026 H00401503800044 H00502201200012 H00502300100020 H00502702000016 H00800300900024 H00901502700018 H00902400600028 H00902401200014 H00902401200030 H02400203400006 H02600500300024 H02601600800026 H03700201200014 H03700201200024 H03800802300044
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0276_pharisee_en.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Hem of a garment|6.0\fig* The hem was the lower edge of an outer garment (see \l target="REALIA:6.2">6.2 Outer garment, cloak, mantle, robe\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line See \l target="REALIA:6.2.1.1">6.2.1.1 Fringe, tassel\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Most translations render the Hebrew word \i kanaf\i* in \s H00401503800026\s* and \s H00502201200012\s* as “corners” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*). In \s H00401503800026\s* \a CEV\a* says “bottom edge,” which may also serve as a model.
\line \s H03800802300044\s*: While the word \i kanaf\i* indicates the lower edge of a garment, it is sometimes used for the garment itself (compare \s H02400203400006 H02601600800026\s*). In such passages it may be possible to use a word for the outer garment. Two models for the first part of \s H03800802300044\s* are “When this happens, ten people from nations with different languages will grab a Jew by his clothes” (\a CEV\a*) and “At that time, ten men from different countries will come and take hold of a Judean by his coat” (\a NCV\a*). \a GNT\a* “In those days ten foreigners will come to one Jew” is also possible, although it loses the element of urgency conveyed by the act of grabbing hold of the robe.
\key 6.2.1.1
\title Fringe, tassel
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb צִיצִת
\trl tsitsith
\ref H00401503800022 H00401503800040 H00401503900010
\heb גָּדִל
\trl gadil
\ref H00502201200002
\grk κράσπεδον
\trl kraspedon
\ref G04000902000022 G04001403600016 G04002300500040 G04100605600050 G04200804400010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0501_fringe_en.jpg|col||DRosenbach (Wikimedia Commons)|Fringes on a prayer shawl|6.0\fig* The decorative tassel was attached to the bottom edge of a long, outer robe, specifically to one of the robe’s four corners.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line According to \s H00401503701000-H00401504101000\s* and \s H00502201200000\s*, Israelite men were required to wear tassels on the four corners of their outer garments (see \l target="REALIA:6.1">6.1 Clothing (generic)\l*). These tassels reminded them of their obligation to keep the commandments of the Mosaic Law.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s G04002300500040\s* the Greek word \i kraspedon\i* refers to the tassels worn at the four corners of outer garments. It is also possible that in all instances in which \i kraspedon\i* is used in reference to Jesus’ clothing (\s G04000902000022 G04001403600016 G04100605600050 G04200804400010\s*), the reference may be specifically to the tassels and not merely to the edge of his garment. The interpretation of such passages depends upon how Jesus may have understood and followed the Mosaic Law and the manner in which the authors may have understood the meaning of \i kraspedon\i*.
\line In some languages the literal phrase “tassels on the corners” (\a RSV\a*) in \s H00401503800022\s* may be rendered “decorated corners” or “ribbons at the corners.” Where a word for tassel does not exist or would be obscure, translators may use a descriptive phrase; for example, \a NCV\a* renders the second clause of this verse as follows: “Tie several pieces of thread together and attach them to the corners of your clothes.”
\key 6.2.2
\title Train
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שׁוּל
\trl shulayim (plural of shul)
\ref H00202803300008 H00202803300026 H00202803400020 H00203902400008 H00203902500032 H00203902600016 H02300600100036 H02401302200026 H02401302600010 H02500100900006 H03400300500016
\grk ἔνδυσις
\trl endusis
\ref L06900500100056
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The train was a long cloth that extended from the bottom of a robe or dress, dragging behind a person as he or she walked. Sometimes a servant would walk behind holding the train off of the ground, so that it would not become dirty.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H02300600100036\s*: Translations treat the Hebrew word \i shulayim\i* here with varying degrees of precision. Thus \a KJV\a* has “his train,” which is the exact meaning but may not be well understood by the modern reader. \a REB\a* “skirt of his robe” and \a NRSV\a* “hem of his robe” focus on the bottom edge of the long robe (see \l target="REALIA:6.2.1">6.2.1 Hem, corner of a garment\l*). Common-language translations tend to refer to the whole garment by saying “his robe” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*). \a NCV\a* is good with “His long robe.”
\line In \s L06900500100056\s* it will normally be sufficient to say something like “the other holding up a long part of her robe which extended behind her.” Where the idea of a “train” is unknown, it will be important to indicate that the cloth extended well behind Esther and to not give the impression that the servant is lifting up the bottom of her dress.
\key 6.2.3
\title Buckle, brooch, clasp
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חָח
\trl chach
\ref H00203502200024
\grk πόρπη
\trl porpē
\ref L07701008900008 L07701105800040 L07701404400064
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0502_robe_pin.jpg|col||© Marcus Cyron (Wikimedia Commons)|Robe pin|6.0\fig* The buckle was a kind of clasp or pin used to fasten a cape or robe at the shoulder. It served as a symbol of rank, and the wearing of it was granted as a privilege.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Some cultures may have a special symbol worn by certain privileged or honored persons. It may be a piece of jewelry worn on the clothing, a necklace, a special headgear, or something else. It may be possible to use such a word in all three references for the Greek word \i porpē\i*.
\line The Hebrew word \i chach\i* in \s H00203502200024\s* refers to some kind of jewelry, perhaps a brooch or even a kind of ring (see \l target="REALIA:10.5.1">10.5.1 Earring, nose ring\l*). In other contexts it refers to a device placed in the nose of a prisoner by which he was led around against his will (see \l target="REALIA:1.3.3">1.3.3 Fishing spear, harpoon\l*).
\key 6.3
\title Shirt, tunic
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כֻּתֹּנֶת
\trl kutoneth
\ref H00100302100020 H00103700300034 H00103702300028 H00103702300032 H00103703100008 H00103703100028 H00103703200008 H00103703200036 H00103703300010 H00202800400026 H00202803900008 H00202804000012 H00202900500024 H00202900800014 H00203902700010 H00204001400016 H00300800700012 H00300801300018 H00301000500012 H00301600400002 H01001301800006 H01001301900016 H01001503200042 H01500206900040 H01600706900044 H01600707100032 H01803001800016 H02200500300006 H02302202100006
\heb סָדִין
\trl sadin
\ref H00701401200048 H00701401300026 H02003102400002 H02300302300012
\arm פטישׁ
\trl ptash
\ref A02700302100018
\grk χιτών
\trl chitōn
\ref G04000504000016 G04001001000014 G04100600900016 G04200301100016 G04200602900040 G04200900300042 G04301902300042 G04301902300050 G04400903900042 G06500102300038 L06801401900026 L07300103000022 L07800403800026 L07801204000016 L08000901100024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0252_building_an_altar.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Men wearing tunics|6.0\fig* The tunic was a long, close-fitting garment worn next to the skin under the outer cloak or coat. It was usually made of wool but could also be of other materials, such as linen. It often had sleeves. It was a simple garment, made of two equal halves, front and back, sewn together with holes left for the head and arms (see also \l target="REALIA:4.5.2">4.5.2 Tunic, shirt\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The tunic was worn by both sexes. Usually a loincloth (see \l target="REALIA:6.4">6.4 Loincloth\l*) was worn under this garment. The tunic was worn under the robe, but it could also be worn without the robe when a person was engaged in physical activity (similar to the T-shirt in modern Western culture).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line For the Hebrew word \i kutoneth\i* in \s H00100302100020\s*, \i Nouvelle Bible de Jérusalem\i* has “tunics.” However, most translations choose not to be so specific and render this piece of clothing made from animal skins as “garments” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*) or “clothes” (\a GNT\a*, \a CEV\a*, \a FRCL\a*, \a GECL\a*).
\line \s H00103700001000\s* and \s H01001301800006 H01001301900016\s* speak literally of “a long robe with sleeves” (\a RSV\a*). However, the Hebrew for “with sleeves” could be rendered “of many colors.” Translations vary. In \s H00103700300034\s* \a GNT\a* says “a long robe with full sleeves” and adds the following footnote: “\i or\i* decorated robe.” The point of the story is that Jacob favored Joseph above his brothers and so honored him with a special gift. \a CEV\a* has “a fancy coat” and then gives the following two options in a footnote: “Or ‘a coat of many colors’ or ‘a coat with long sleeves.’ ”
\line Some commentators and translations understand the Hebrew word \i sadin\i* to refer to a simple linen sheet; for example, in \s H00701401200048 H00701401300026\s* \a GNT\a* has “a piece of fine linen.” Most, however, understand it as a piece of clothing made of linen (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen\l* and \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.13">1.5.3.13 Linen cloth, sheet\l*). The type of clothing here in the versions varies widely from “linen wraps” (\a NASB\a*) to “linen shirts” (\a NCV\a*). In most cases translators may use a general expression such as “linen clothes” or “linen shirts.”
\line \s A02700302100018\s*: In this verse the writer uses four terms for articles of clothing worn by the three men being thrown into the blazing furnace. The precise meaning of these articles of clothing is uncertain and not very important; the writer uses this list (as he uses other lists elsewhere) for rhetorical effect. What is important is to use words indicating that the men were fully clothed, and that their dress included inner garments, outer garments, and something worn on the head. \a CEV\a*’s rendering of these articles of clothing is helpful: “with all of their clothes still on, including their turbans.”
\line In \s G04000504000016\s* and \s G04200602900040\s* the Greek word \i chitōn\i* refers to an essential garment; therefore translators should avoid the use of a term referring to a garment that is considered a luxury in the receptor culture. In some languages it will be difficult in these verses to distinguish between this garment and the outer garment (see \l target="REALIA:6.2">6.2 Outer garment, cloak, mantle, robe\l*). If there are terms that distinguish between the outer and inner garments, they can usually be used, as \a GNT\a* has used “coat” and “shirt.” Otherwise, translators may use descriptive phrases; for example, the word \i chitōn\i* may be rendered “clothing you wear under your outer wrap [or, near your body]” or “clothing that covers the outer clothing.” However, to help readers realize the difference in value of the two garments, something Jesus’ hearers would have understood immediately, translators may prefer to say “your garment that is of little value” and “your outer garment that is more valuable.”
\line \s G04301902300042\s*: This verse notes that Jesus’ tunic was woven in one piece, without a seam. The technique for making such a garment in the ancient period is uncertain, but this does not mean that the garment was unique or particularly expensive.
\key 6.4
\title Loincloth
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֵזוֹר
\trl ’ezor
\ref H01801201800012
\heb חֲגוֹרָה
\trl chagorah
\ref H00100300700034
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0503_loincloth.jpg|col||Eloquence (Wikimedia Commons)|Workers wearing loincloths|6.0\fig* The loincloth was a piece of cloth wrapped around the waist to cover the private parts. It was commonly worn by slaves.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The second line of \s H01801201800012\s* is literally “and he binds a girdle on their waist.” Some scholars take this to mean that God strengthens kings by placing a girdle or wide band around their middle (see \l target="REALIA:6.6">6.6 Waistband, sash, belt\l*). However, it is more probable that God, having removed their symbol of authority, puts on the kings a loincloth, which is worn for doing hard physical labor, and so depicts them as slaves. \a GNT\a* says “and makes them prisoners.” \a NIV\a* has “and ties a loincloth around their waist,” which is a literal rendering. Such a rendering needs an explanatory note to indicate that God reduces kings to slaves. It is better to give the cultural significance of this line in the text by saying “and makes them slaves” or “and ties a loincloth on them and makes them slaves.” A translation model for the whole verse is “God takes away the authority of kings and makes them like slaves.” If translators want to keep the change of clothes imagery in this verse, a possible model is “God takes away from kings their robes of authority and puts on them the loincloth of a slave.”
\line The following is adapted from the comments of \i A Handbook on Genesis\i* (page 86) on the Hebrew word \i chagorah\i* in \s H00100300700034\s*: This Hebrew word refers to something worn around the waist or hips. \a RSV\a* renders it “aprons” here, but the word “apron” is not really a good translation in English, since an apron is a partial covering that is usually worn for a particular purpose or in particular situations, rather than being a general item of clothing. In some languages it is necessary to say “a man’s loincloth” and “a woman’s loincloth” since the words are different. The exact nature of these loincloths is not known, so it may be best to use a general term like “coverings,” or to render the last half of this verse as “and they put leaves together to cover their private parts.” One translation expresses the whole sentence as “So they-two sewed together fig leaves and put them on like a skirt to hide their bare skin.”
\key 6.5
\title Animal skin
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb עוֹר
\trl ‘or
\ref H00100302100022 H00102701600006 H00202202600020 H00202500500004 H00202500500012 H00202601400014 H00202601400024 H00202901400016 H00203402900056 H00203403000026 H00203403500020 H00203500700004 H00203500700012 H00203502300036 H00203502300044 H00203601900014 H00203601900024 H00203903400008 H00203903400024 H00300401100006 H00300700800018 H00300801700014 H00300901100016 H00301103200034 H00301300200010 H00301300200030 H00301300300018 H00301300300050 H00301300400014 H00301300400030 H00301300500046 H00301300600048 H00301300700018 H00301300800024 H00301301000022 H00301301100010 H00301301200018 H00301301200032 H00301301800014 H00301302000022 H00301302100034 H00301302200014 H00301302400012 H00301302500038 H00301302600038 H00301302700030 H00301302800022 H00301303000028 H00301303100034 H00301303200066 H00301303400042 H00301303400056 H00301303500018 H00301303600024 H00301303800016 H00301303900016 H00301303900036 H00301304300042 H00301304800032 H00301304800042 H00301304900028 H00301304900054 H00301305100058 H00301305100070 H00301305200052 H00301305300054 H00301305600046 H00301305700040 H00301305800028 H00301305900040 H00301501700012 H00301602700066 H00400400600010 H00400400800024 H00400401000020 H00400401100028 H00400401200048 H00400401400066 H00401900500018 H00403102000014 H01200100800018 H01800200400018 H01800200400022 H01800700500018 H01801001100002 H01801801300006 H01801902000004 H01801902000022 H01801902600006 H01803003000002 H01804003100010 H02401302300008 H02500300400008 H02500400800022 H02500501000002 H02603700600024 H02603700800026 H03300300200016 H03300300300014
\grk δέρμα
\trl derma
\ref G05801103700024
\grk μηλωτή
\trl mēlōtē
\ref G05801103700018
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0438_animalskin.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man wearing an animal skin|6.0\fig* The hide or skin of an animal could be tanned or untanned. It could be tanned with the hair or wool left on or after the hair or wool had been removed.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Animal skins served many purposes, including their use as a rough kind of outer clothing.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages it is important to distinguish clearly between tanned and untanned skins or hides. Furthermore, translators must often make a distinction between a skin that still has the hair on it and one that does not. In \s G05801103700024\s* the likelihood is that these skins were tanned and still retained the hair as extra protection. While the Greek here has two words for “skins” (\i derma\i* and \i mēlōtē\i*), most translations use only one word for “skins” and name the two animals from which the skins came by saying “skins of sheep and/or goats” (\a RSV\a*, \a GNT\a*). \a NIV\a* says “sheepskins and goatskins.”
\line The passages listed above with the Hebrew word \i ‘or\i* do not refer specifically to clothing but rather to tanned animal hides for unspecified usage. In these passages most translations use a general word for “leather.” Where such a word is lacking, it may be necessary to use a descriptive phrase, such as “dried animal skin.”
\key 6.6
\title Waistband, sash, belt
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַבְנֵט
\trl ’avnet
\ref H02302202100010
\heb אֵזוֹר
\trl ’ezor
\ref H01200100800016 H01801201800012 H02300502700030 H02301100500008 H02301100500018 H02401300100018 H02401300200010 H02401300400008 H02401300600040 H02401300700020 H02401300700042 H02401301000066 H02401301100012 H02602301500004
\heb חגר, חֲגוֹר, חֲגוֹרָה
\trl chagar (verb), chagor, chagorah
\ref H00201201100012 H00901800400046 H01001801100054 H01002000800034 H01002000800048 H01100200500082 H01200302100032 H01200302100034 H01200402900010 H01200900100030 H01910901900020 H02003102400012 H02300302400018 H02701000500030
\heb מֵזַח
\trl mezach
\ref H01910901900016 H02302301000018
\heb קִשֻּׁרִים
\trl qishurim
\ref H02300302000016 H02400203200012
\grk ζώνη
\trl zōnē
\ref G04000300400026 G04100100600018 G04402101100016 G04402101100060 G06600101300032 G06601500600046
\grk μήτρα
\trl mētra
\ref L06800900200036 L06800900200058
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0439_sash_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Sash|6.0\fig* The waistband held a robe (see \l target="REALIA:6.2">6.2 Outer garment, cloak, mantle, robe\l*) at the waist. It was usually made of linen (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen\l*), but leather ones are also mentioned. The waistband was not exactly a belt, such as worn with modern Western clothing, but it was a wide sash in which money and other things could also be kept (see \l target="REALIA:10.1">10.1 Bag, sack, money bag, purse\l*). It was wound around the waist and tied to hold it in place.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i ’avnet\i* always refers to an item in the clothing of the High Priest (see \l target="REALIA:4.5.6">4.5.6 Sash, cloth belt\l*), except for \s H02302202100010\s*, where it is connected to a high official.
\line Opinions are divided concerning the exact form of the clothing referred to by the Hebrew word \i ’ezor\i*. Some scholars have suggested that it was a kind of short undergarment that was wrapped around the waist (see \l target="REALIA:6.3">6.3 Shirt, tunic\l*, and compare \a GNT\a* and \a CEV\a* at \s H02401300101000-H02401301101000\s*, where they render it “shorts”). Others have seen it as an apron that was tied around the waist over the outer clothing to protect it when working (see \l target="REALIA:6.10">6.10 Apron\l*). Most likely, however, the word \i ’ezor\i* in most passages refers to a wide belt or sash that was tied around the waist to keep the outer garment from flowing loose (“belt” in \a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*, \a NLT\a*; “sash” in \a NKJV\a*). It was sometimes decorated and could indicate the social standing of the person wearing it. The outer garment could be tucked up into it for work or rapid walking. It could also be used as a holder for tools, money, or other small objects.
\line \s H01200302100032\s*: In this verse the literal expression “all those who put on a belt” indicates men of military age. A literal translation will lack meaning. Translators should follow such models as \a GNT\a* “all the men who could bear arms,” \a CEV\a* “all of their fighting men,” \a NCV\a* “everyone old enough to put on armor,” and \a SPCL\a* “all young and old men of military age.”
\line \s H02701000500030\s* refers to “a belt of the finest gold” (\a NIV\a*). This does not mean a solid object made only of gold. It rather refers to a cloth sash but with fine gold threads woven into the fabric, enough gold thread, in fact, to give the entire sash a golden appearance.
\line In \s G04000300400026\s* and \s G04100100600018\s* translators may render the Greek expression \i zōnē dermatinos\i* as “leather belt” (\a GNT\a*). Possible renderings for the literal phrase “leather belt around his waist” are “belt of dried animal skin” and “strip of dried animal skin around his waist to hold his clothing.”
\key 6.7
\title Headdress, turban, hat
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb טְבוּל
\trl tvul
\ref H02602301500010
\arm כַּרְבְּלָה
\trl karbla’
\ref A02700302100022
\heb מִצְנֶפֶת
\trl mitsnefeth
\ref H02602103100014
\heb פְּאֵר
\trl p’er
\ref H02300302000004 H02602401700014 H02602402300004
\heb צָנִיף
\trl tsanif
\ref H01802901400016 H02300302300018 H02306200300018
\grk κίδαρις
\trl kidaris
\ref L08100300600032
\grk πέτασος
\trl petasos
\ref L07800401200032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0440_turbans.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Men wearing turbans|6.0\fig* The turban was a piece of material wrapped around the top of the head.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The cloth of the turban was wound around the upper part of the head several times and the end was tucked in. It may have been wound permanently and put on and taken off like a hat. See also \l target="REALIA:4.5.8">4.5.8 Turban, headdress\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages there may be a very general word covering anything worn on the head. Where no more specific word exists for “turban,” this general word may be used for most of the references listed above. In some languages a descriptive phrase may be used, such as “covering made of cloth and wrapped around the head.”
\line While some translations use words such as “hat” (\s H01802901400016\s* in \a CEV\a*) or “cap” (\s A02700302100022\s* in \a GNT\a*), these words are generally used in English to refer to something more western than Bible characters would have worn. Terms like “turban” or “headdress” are more appropriate since they clearly refer to something less western. But this kind of distinction may be difficult to reflect in some languages that have only one term that refers to anything worn on the head. A possible model for “turban” in such languages is “special head covering.”
\line For the translation of the Aramaic word \i karbla’\i* in \s A02700302100022\s*, see the comments at \l target="REALIA:6.3">6.3 Shirt, tunic\l*.
\line \s L07800401200032\s* says literally “he induced the noblest of the young men to wear the Greek hat” (\a RSV\a*). The hat in question was something worn by Greek athletes to identify with the god Hermes. Since this information is lacking for the modern reader, \a REB\a* has expanded this part of the verse to “he made the most outstanding of the young men adopt the hat worn by Greek athletes.” Some translations prefer to omit the hat and focus on the real issue that Jewish youth were being made to participate in forbidden Greek activities with their pagan associations; for example, \a GNT\a* has “[he] led our finest young men to adopt the Greek custom of participating in athletic events.”
\key 6.8
\title Wreath, crown
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לִוְיָה
\trl liwyah
\ref H02000100900004 H02000400900008
\heb צְפִירָה
\trl tsefirah
\ref H02302800500028
\grk κισσός
\trl kissos
\ref L07800600700042
\grk στεφανηφορέω
\trl stefanēforeō (verb)
\ref L07000400200024
\grk στέφανος, στεφανόω
\trl stefanos, stefanoō (verb)
\ref G04600902500024 G05000400100018 G05200201900016 G05500200500014 G05500400800014 G05900101200022 G06000500400020 G06600201000060 G06600301100020 L06801501300004 L06800300700022 L06801501300056 L06900801500020 L07100101100018 L07100101800002 L07100603100012 L07101500600006 L07102500600002 L07103200200032 L07104501200002 L07105001200034 L07300100800016 L07700102200044 L07700405700016 L07701002000040 L07900302800050 L08001701500014 L08600801700022
\grk στέφος
\trl stefos
\ref L07900400800014
\grk στέφω
\trl stefō (verb)
\ref L07000200800002
\lat corona
\ref V08200204300046 V08200204600022
\lat corono (verb)
\ref V08200204500040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0158_wreath.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man wearing a wreath|6.0\fig* The wreath was a ring consisting either of foliage or of precious metals formed to resemble foliage and worn around the top of the head as a symbol of honor or victory, or as a badge of high office. For the crown of royalty, see \l target="REALIA:1.10.2">1.10.2 Crown\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line It may be important in some contexts to indicate clearly the significance of the wreath worn on the head, for example, “wreath to show victory.” To describe “a wreath” merely as “a circle of leaves” would hardly be sufficient to indicate its cultural significance. In order to do justice to the cultural relevance of such a wreath, it may be important to add some type of marginal note.
\line In some languages the term “crown” suggests only a symbol of ruling rather than a symbol of reward as the result of being victorious. It may therefore be better in some passages to translate “crown” as “prize” or “reward”; for example, for the literal clause “he will receive the crown of life” (\a RSV\a*) in \s G05900101200022\s* (which has no implications of royalty), \a CEV\a* has “He will reward you with a glorious life.”
\line \s G05000400100018\s*: Here Paul refers to the Philippians as “my crown.” In some languages translators may be able to preserve this figurative expression by saying “you are like a crown for my head.” But sometimes this type of rendering has resulted in wrong meanings; for example, it has been understood in the sense of “you are a weight upon my head,” and thus a mental burden. Other possible renderings are “how proud I am of you!” (\a GNT\a*), “I am always glad to tell people about you,” and “I am always boasting about you.” For the literal expression “my joy and crown,” \a CEV\a* has found a closely parallel English idiom with “You are my pride and joy.”
\key 6.9
\title Garland
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk στέμμα
\trl stemma
\ref G04401401300026
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The garland was a wreath of wool to which leaves and flowers might be added and either wound around a staff or woven into a circle to be worn on the head.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line Garlands were an important part of the ritual involved in the worship of pagan gods in the ancient world. As in \s G04401401300026\s*, the flowers were draped around animals to be sacrificed. \fig |WEB-0504_garland.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Garland painted on a wall panel|6.0\fig*
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Garlands” in \s G04401401300026\s* may be rendered “circles of leaves,” “rings of flowers,” or “wreaths of flowers.”
\key 6.10
\title Apron
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk σιμικίνθιον
\trl simikinthion
\ref G04401901200026
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0505_apron_leather.jpg|col||© MikiNikoloski (Wikimedia Commons)|Leather apron|6.0\fig* The apron was a cloth or piece of leather wrapped by a workman around his waist or chest to protect his clothes.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In some languages “apron” may be rendered “workman’s cloth” or “work­man’s cloth to protect clothing.”
\line For the meaning of “ephod” as a kind of work apron, see \l target="REALIA:4.5.4">4.5.4 Ephod\l*.
\key 6.11
\title Phylactery
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk φυλακτήριον
\trl fulaktērion
\ref G04002300500030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0033_phylacteries.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Man with phylacteries on his forehead and arm|6.0\fig* The phylactery was a small leather box containing Old Testament verses.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line When Jewish men prayed, they tied these small containers to the forehead and upper left arm near the heart. They did this in obedience to a literal interpretation of \s H00201300901000\s*; \s H00500600801000\s*; \s H00501101801000\s*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s G04002300500030\s*: In this verse the word “phylacteries” (so \a RSV\a* and most other English translations) is a technical religious term that will not be understood by most readers. \a GNT\a* handles the specialized term with the explanatory phrase “straps with scripture verses on them which they wear on their foreheads and arms.” Several translations retain the traditional rendering and provide a footnote to help the reader. Brc (“prayer-boxes”) and \a GECL\a* (“prayer straps”) attempt dynamic equivalent translations. There is no good reason to retain the word “phylacteries,” and most translators will use an explanatory phrase like that in \a GNT\a*. However, the \a GNT\a* expression is rather long, and some restructuring may be required to combine it well with the verb “make . . . broad” (\a RSV\a*); for example, “the leather boxes with scripture verses in them that these people wear [on their foreheads and arms] are very big,” “they make sure that the boxes with scripture verses that they wear are really big,” and “see how big they make those little boxes with scripture verses in them, the ones they wear on their foreheads and arms.”
\key 6.12
\title Veil
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַסְוֶה
\trl masweh
\ref H00203403300022 H00203403400028 H00203403500036
\heb מִסְפָּחָה
\trl mispachah
\ref H02601301800036 H02601302100008
\heb צַמָּה
\trl tsamah
\ref H02200400100022 H02200400300034 H02200600700018 H02304700200014
\heb צָעִיף
\trl tsa‘if
\ref H00102406500054 H00103801400022 H00103801900014
\heb רְדִיד
\trl rdid
\ref H02200500700026 H02300302300024
\heb רְעָלָה
\trl r‘alah
\ref H02300301900016
\grk κάλυμμα
\trl kalumma
\ref G04700301300012 G04700301400026 G04700301500016 G04700301600018
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0506_veil.jpg|col||© Trjames (Wikimedia Commons)|Bridal dress and veil|6.0\fig* The veil was a thin piece of cloth worn over the face. The material would be sufficiently thin that the wearer would be able to see through it if it covered the eyes (unlike the illustration here), but others would find it difficult to recognize the facial features through the veil.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Where a word is lacking in a language for “veil,” a descriptive phrase may be used, such as “thin cloth to hide the face.” It may be necessary to expand the translation a little to convey the meaning; compare \a NCV\a* at \s H00103801400022\s*, where it renders the second clause as “covered her face with a veil to hide who she was.”
\line Translators should be aware that it is only by historical accident that, in older English translations, the word “veil” was used also for the curtain that divided the Holy Place from the Most Holy Place (see \l target="REALIA:3.14.1.6">3.14.1.6 Curtain, veil, drape\l*). No attempt should be made to render them identically in the receptor language.
\line \s H02601301800036 H02601302100008\s*: The Hebrew word \i mispachah\i* refers to a long veil, almost a sheath, reaching from the head to the feet.
\line The Hebrew word \i rdid\i* in \s H02200500700026\s* and \s H02300302300024\s* probably refers to a long veil, covering more than just the face. Both the \i mispachah\i* and the \i rdid\i* were similar to the \i niqab\i* or \i burqah\i* worn by some Muslim women.
\key 6.13
\title Sandal, shoe
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb נַעַל, נעל
\trl na‘al
\ref H00101402300014 H00200300500014 H00201201100014 H00502500900022 H00502501000018 H00502900400030 H00600501500018 H00600900500004 H00600901300032 H00800400700040 H00800400800022 H01100200500094 H01402801500048 H01906001000014 H01910801000014 H02200700200012 H02300502700042 H02301101500050 H02302000200048 H02601601000010 H02602401700022 H02602402300012 H03000200600046 H03000800600022
\grk σανδάλιον
\trl sandalion
\ref G04100600900006 G04401200800022 L06801000400006 L06801600900004
\grk ὑπόδημα, ὑποδέομαι
\trl hupodēma, hupodeomai (verb)
\ref G04000301100044 G04001001000018 G04100100700038 G04100600900004 G04200301600048 G04201000400014 G04201502200050 G04202203500024 G04300102700032 G04401200800018 G04400703300016 G04401302500050 G04900601500004 L07104601900030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0507_sandals.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Sandals|6.0\fig* The sandal was a type of footwear consisting of a sole made of leather (or possibly wood) tied to the foot by means of leather thongs or straps, and used as a shoe for walking.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Sometimes a term for “sandal” indicates the footwear of particularly poor people or, in some situations, footwear used only for recreation or sport. If this is the case, it will usually be better to use a general designation for footwear which would include sandals.
\line \fig |KNW-0161_sandals.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Sandals on feet|6.0\fig* Sandals were not buckled, as is done with most modern sandals, but rather tied with straps that were wrapped around the ankles. In those passages that speak of putting sandals on or taking them off, translators should choose a word for tying or untying rather than one that indicates the use of a buckle.
\key 6.13.1
\title Straps
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שְׂרוֹךְ
\trl srok
\ref H00101402300012 H02300502700040
\grk ἱμάς
\trl himas
\ref G04100100700034 G04200301600044 G04300102700028 G04402202500012
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Straps were long, thin pieces of leather. They were put to many uses, including tying sandals, binding other things (that is, used like rope; see \l target="REALIA:1.14">1.14 Rope, cord\l*), or wielding as a whip (\l target="REALIA:1.1.3">1.1.3 Whip, scourge\l*). See the illustrations at \l target="REALIA:6.13">6.13 Sandal, shoe\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages the Greek word \i himas\i* may be rendered “leather string” or “strip of leather.” In \s G04300102700028\s* the term may be absorbed within the total expression at the end of the verse, for example, “I am not worthy to untie his sandals” (implying the untying of the straps with which the sandals were bound). This may be done in \s G04100100700034\s* and \s G04200301600044\s* also.
\line In \s G04402202500012\s* two meanings are possible for the Greek word \i himas\i*. Luke may either be telling the reason why Paul was being tied up or the means by which Paul was being tied up. So translators may render the first clause in this verse as “they tied him up with thongs” or “they tied him up for whipping,” in which case \i himas\i* would refer to an event, not to an object.
\key 6.14
\title Wristband, magic charm
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כֶּסֶת
\trl keseth
\ref H02601301800020 H02601302000016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0508_wristband.jpg|col||© Osama Shukir Muhammed Amin FRCP(Glasg) (Wikimedia Commons)|Wristband|6.0\fig* The wristband was a strip of sewn cloth worn on the wrist.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The context of \s H02601301800020 H02601302000016\s* indicates that these bands of cloth were used in magic rituals. An exact equivalent may be available in some languages. Where no equivalent exists, a descriptive phrase may be used. \a GNT\a* calls them “magic wristbands,” while both \a CEV\a* and \a NCV\a* say “magic charms.” According to verse 18, they were sewn on “all the joints of the hands,” which is taken by all translations consulted to mean the wrists and not the elbows, as noted in the Hebrew lexicon by Brown, Driver, and Briggs under the word \i ’atsil\i*.
\key 6.15
\title Widow’s clothing
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בֶּגֶד, אָלְמָנוּת
\trl bigdey ’almanuth
\ref H00103801400006 H00103801900024
\grk ἱμάτιον, χηρεύσις
\trl himatia tēs chēreuseōs
\ref L06800800500046 L06801000300020
\grk στολή, χήρευσις
\trl stolē chēreuseōs
\ref L06801600700006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The widow’s clothing was a robe or dress with a special design or color to indicate that her husband had died. The exact nature of the widow’s clothing of Judith is unknown, although it is possible that at least part of what she wore was made of sackcloth (see \l target="REALIA:4.8.5">4.8.5 Sackcloth, mourning clothes\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In many cultures a widow can be identified by her dress or some other external sign. In some places she will wear black or white for a certain period of time or even for the rest of her life. Where such a custom exists, a translation may use the word for the clothing or other symbol that identifies the widow.
\line \s H00502401701000\s* mentions the “cloak of a widow.” This does not seem to be a garment peculiar to widows only but a normal cloak worn by everyone (see \l target="REALIA:6.2">6.2 Outer garment, cloak, mantle, robe\l*). Because of the protected status of widows in Israelite society, items of clothing were not to be taken from them. Similarly, in \s G04400903901000\s* there is no reason to assume that the clothes made by Dorcas were special “widows’ clothing,” although they were certainly women’s clothes.
\key 6.16
\title Cloth for wrapping a baby
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חתל, חֲתֻלָּה
\trl chathal, chathulah
\ref H01803800900014 H02601600400044 H02601600400048
\grk σπάργανον
\trl sparganon
\ref L07000700400004
\grk σπαργανόω
\trl sparganoō (verb)
\ref G04200200700018 G04200201200016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The cloth for wrapping a baby was a kind of bandage about the width of a hand and several meters (yards) long. This strip of cloth was wrapped around a child from shoulders to feet. This practice, technically known as “swaddling,” was done in the belief that the child’s limbs would grow straight if they were tightly bound to his sides immediately after birth.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Some cultures may have a similar custom of wrapping a newborn infant. Where this is known, translators should use the word for the cloth in which the child is wrapped.
\line In the second line of \s H01803800900014\s* God says he wrapped the newborn sea in darkness like an infant is wrapped in cloth. Some translations try to maintain this metaphor by saying “I made . . . thick darkness its swaddling band” (\a NASB\a*) or “I gave him the dark fog for a diaper” (\a GECL\a*, \a SPCL\a*). \a CEV\a* changes the metaphor by rendering the whole verse as “and wrapped it in blankets of thickest fog.” Others (for example, \a GNT\a* and \a NCV\a*) maintain the act of wrapping without keeping the picture of wrapping a baby. In some languages it will be necessary to avoid the image of “swaddling band” (\a RSV\a*) and render the whole verse as follows: “I am the one who covered the sea with clouds and made it dark.”
\line See also the discussion at \l target="REALIA:1.15.4">1.15.4 Bandage\l*.
\line Patch: See \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.12">1.5.3.12 Patch\l*.
\c 7
\key 7
\title Music
\index \l target="REALIA:7.1">7.1 Musical instruments (generic)\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.2">7.2 Stringed instruments\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.3">7.3 Wind instruments\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.4">7.4 Percussion instruments\l*
\key 7.1
\title Musical instruments (generic)
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כְּלִי
\trl kli
\ref H01301600500046 H01302300500026 H01907102200010
\heb כְּלִי
\trl kle david
\ref H01402902600012 H01402902700052
\heb כְּלִי, עֹז
\trl kle ‘oz
\ref H01403002100062
\heb כְּלִי, שִׁיר
\trl kle shir
\ref H01301501600030 H01301604200024 H01400501300074 H01400700600022 H01402301300072 H01403401200074 H01601203600028 H03000600500022
\heb מֵן
\trl men
\ref H01904500900020 H01915000400016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The terms listed above refer to musical instruments collectively.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew expression \i kle david\i* in \s H01402902600012 H01402902700052\s* associates certain musical instruments with King David. Some translations retain the ambiguity of the Hebrew with “instruments of David” (\a RSV\a*, \a REB\a*, \a NJPSV\a*). \a CEV\a* has “instruments that belonged to David,” while \a GNT\a* “instruments like those that King David had used” does not assume that David’s own instruments were still in working condition after three hundred years.
\line In \s H01403002100062\s* the Hebrew expression \i kle ‘oz\i* has been understood in various ways. Some take it to refer to instruments (\a NJPSV\a* “powerful instruments,” \a CEV\a* “instruments”; compare \a NCV\a* “loud music”). Others take the phrase to describe the atmosphere of praise (\a REB\a* “unrestrained fervour,” \a GNT\a* “all their strength”). This latter interpretation is based on a minor emendation of the text to make it agree with \s H01301300801000\s*, but \a HOTTP\a* does not recommend it.
\line \s H01915000301000 H01915000400016 H01915000501000\s* lists several musical instruments. The trumpets were played by the priests; the Levites played the harps, lyres, and cymbals; and the other instruments (verse 4) were played by lay people. In verse 4 the Hebrew word \i men\i* probably refers to “stringed instruments.” The translation of the Hebrew terms for these musical instruments is usually handled in one of three ways: (a) by using descriptive phrases; (b) by using local instruments; or (c) by using generic terms accompanied by a loan word. An illustration of the first way would be to translate “cymbals” as “flat metal plates that were struck together.” An example of the third way would be to render the same word as “percussion instruments called cymbals.”
\line In \s A02700300501000 A02700300701000 A02700301001000 A02700301501000\s*, the writer gives a list of six different musical instruments. In many languages where such instruments are not well known, this poses serious translation problems. If it proves impossible to have the same number of instruments as in the biblical text, the number may be reduced (in some manuscripts there are only five names here); however, lists are an important characteristic of the book of Daniel, and it is recommended that a list of instruments be maintained here and not replaced by a summary expression, such as “the band” in \a LB\a*.
\key 7.2
\title Stringed instruments
\index \l target="REALIA:7.2.1">7.2.1 Nevel, large lyre, guitar, harp\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.2.2">7.2.2 Kinor, small lyre, lute\l*
\line \fig |KNW-0442_stringed_instruments.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Stringed instruments|7.0\fig* In many musical instruments strings are stretched over a sounding box or connected to the sounding box. Sound is produced by causing the strings to vibrate by plucking them.
\line There is considerable uncertainty about the identification of the various stringed instruments in the Bible. Confusion is increased by the fact that the Hebrew words \i nevel\i* and \i kinor\i* are frequently used interchangeably or in parallel (see, for example, \s H00901000501000 H01000600501000 H01903300201000 H01905700801000 H01907102201000 H01908100201000 H01909200301000 H01910800201000 H01915000301000\s*). Both instruments were likely types of lyre, varying only in size. The \i kinor\i* was the smaller of the two. A clear distinction between the \i nevel\i* and the \i kinor\i* is not easy to make, and the main difference may have been the thickness of the sound box, which was thicker for the \i nevel\i*. For further discussion on these stringed instruments, see Braun, Lawergren (page 55), and O’Connell. \fig |WEB-0509_stringed_instruments.jpg|col||Encyclopaedia Biblica, 1903|Playing stringed instruments|7.0\fig*
\key 7.2.1
\title \i Nevel\i*, large lyre, guitar, harp
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb נֵבֶל
\trl nevel
\ref H00901000500058 H01000600500040 H01101001200042 H01301300800044 H01301501600034 H01301502000036 H01301502800046 H01301600500048 H01302500100048 H01302500600026 H01400501200052 H01400901100042 H01402002800010 H01402902500022 H01601202700058 H01903300200014 H01905700900010 H01907102200012 H01908100300018 H01909200400010 H01910800300006 H01914400900014 H01915000300014 H02300501200010 H02301401100010 H03000502300016 H03000600500012
\arm קַתְרוֹס
\trl qathros
\ref A02700300500016 A02700300500018 A02700300700030 A02700300700032 A02700301000028 A02700301000030 A02700301500026 A02700301500028
\grk κιθάρα
\trl kithara
\ref G04601400700018 G06600500800040 G06601400200052 G06601500200066 L07700405400040
\grk κιθαρίζω
\trl kitharizō
\ref G04601400700044 G06601400200046
\grk κιθαρῳδός
\trl kitharōidos
\ref G06601400200044 G06601802200006
\grk νάβλα
\trl nabla
\ref L07701305100060
\grk ψαλτήριον
\trl psaltērion
\ref L07001901800018 L07104002100006
\arm פְּסַנְתֵּרִין
\trl psanterin
\ref A02700300500090 A02700300700130 A02700301000150 A02700301500140
\lat psalterium
\ref V08201002200004
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0175_harp.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Harp|7.0\fig* The exact identification of the \i nevel\i* is very problematic. Some take it to be a kind of harp. The harp consisted of a neck projecting out of a soundbox. Strings were stretched from the extremity of the neck down its length and into the sound box. The body of the harp was made of wood and its strings of animal intestines (perhaps from sheep). The number of strings varied.
\line Others place the \i nevel\i* in the category of lyres, where the strings are stretched over top of and parallel to the soundbox (see \l target="REALIA:7.2.2">7.2.2 Kinor, small lyre, lute\l*). While this is the interpretation preferred here, we will discuss the harp-type of instrument, since the identification is problematic and many translations have preferred “harp” for \i nevel\i*.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The strings were plucked either with the fingers or with a thin piece of ivory or metal to give a resonating sound, probably in a lower register than that made by the \i kinor\i*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In several Psalms (\s H01903300200014\s*; \s H01909200400010\s*; \s H01914400900014\s*), the \i nevel\i* is linked to the Hebrew word \i ‘asor\i*, which could indicate it was “ten-stringed.”
\line Some degree of cultural adaptation must be made in the translation of these stringed instruments since cultures differ from each other in the shape, the number of strings, and the function of their instruments. Translators will have to select an equivalent instrument in the receptor language. In most passages the most accurate translation for \i nevel\i* will be “guitar” or some equivalent medium-sized stringed instrument on which the strings are stretched over a sound box and are plucked.
\line In those passages where \i nevel\i* and \i kinor\i* appear together it is recommended that the translator use an instrument that can vary in size and then render the two words as “large and small X,” for example, “large and small guitars.” Alternately, it may be possible to select two stringed instruments that are similar in construction but different in size, for example, “guitar and lute.” It is also possible to say “large and small stringed instruments” or to combine the two, saying “stringed instruments.”
\line \s H01903300201000\s*: “Praise the LORD with the lyre” (\a RSV\a*) contains two major translation problems. The first problem is that in many languages, the phrase “with the lyre” must be changed into a verb phrase or clause; for example, the whole line may be rendered “Praise the LORD by playing music on the lyre” or “Make music with the lyre, and praise the LORD.” The second problem, which applies also to the second line of this verse, is the terms to be used for the musical instruments here. In languages in which there are several stringed instruments, translators may use one of the smaller ones for \i kinor\i* (“lyre”) and a larger one for \i nevel\i* (“harp” in \a RSV\a*). In languages where there is little or no choice, they should use the known local stringed instrument for the \i kinor\i*, and a more generic expression for the \i nevel\i*. Where there are no known stringed instruments, it will often be necessary to say “small instruments with strings” for \i kinor\i* and “large instruments with strings” for \i nevel\i*.
\key 7.2.2
\title \i Kinor\i*, small lyre, lute
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כִּנּוֹר
\trl kinor
\ref H00100402100020 H00103102700046 H00901000500070 H00901601600026 H00901602300028 H01000600500034 H01101001200038 H01301300800038 H01301501600038 H01301502100028 H01301502800050 H01301600500054 H01302500100044 H01302500300040 H01302500600030 H01400501200056 H01400901100038 H01402002800016 H01402902500028 H01601202700064 H01802101200010 H01803003100010 H01903300200010 H01904300400026 H01904900500014 H01905700900014 H01907102200024 H01908100300012 H01909200400018 H01909800500010 H01909800500014 H01910800300010 H01913700200012 H01914700700020 H01914900300016 H01915000300018 H02300501200006 H02301601100016 H02302301600004 H02302400800018 H02303003200030 H02602601300014
\arm שַׂבְּכָא
\trl sabka’
\ref A02700300500020 A02700300700034 A02700301000032 A02700301500030
\grk κινύρα
\trl kinura
\ref L07103901500032 L07700304500078 L07700405400044 L07701305100048
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0176_lyre.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Lyre|7.0\fig* The lyre consisted of a sound box out of the ends or sides of which projected two arms. The arms supported a crosspiece. Strings descended from the crosspiece over the sound box. As with the \i nevel\i*, the number of strings could vary. Their varying thickness and tension gave the instrument a range of notes. The lyre was normally made of wood. The strings were made of animal intestines (perhaps from sheep).
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The strings were normally plucked with the fingers. The \i kinor\i* in particular is frequently depicted as an instrument that accompanied singing.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0510_lyre.jpg|col||© Carole Raddato from FRANKFURT, Germany (Wikimedia Commons)|Woman playing a lyre|7.0\fig* See \l target="REALIA:7.2.1">7.2.1 Nevel, large lyre, guitar, harp\l*.
\line \s H01802101200010\s*: For the stringed instrument (\i kinor\i* in Hebrew) accompanying the tambourine, \a FRCL\a* has “guitar” and \i La Bible de Jérusalem\i* has “zither,” which seems to be an instrument used in \s H00901000500070\s*. The first line of this verse may also be rendered “The children sing as people play the tambourine and the lyre.” In some languages these instruments will be a local drum and a stringed instrument; the latter may be a guitar. If no instruments can be found to render any of the instruments in this verse, the translator may have to express the whole verse differently; for example, “The children dance and sing and make joyful sounds/music.”
\line The identity of the instrument called \i sabka’\i* in Aramaic in \s A02700300500020 A02700300700034 A02700301000032 A02700301500030\s* is uncertain. \a RSV\a* renders it “trigon,” which is a small triangular lyre-type instrument with four strings. Probably trigon is technically correct, but it is unknown to the average English reader. \a GNT\a* has attempted to find a better-known equivalent with “zither,” but the zither has far too many strings (over thirty). Some translations use “lyre” for \i sabka’\i* and render the Aramaic word \i qathros\i* before it as “zither” (\a NIV\a*, \a NJPSV\a*, \a NLT\a*). \a REB\a* has “triangle,” but most readers will wrongly identify that as a percussion instrument. \a CEV\a* avoids the problem by rendering only the first three instruments in the list and grouping the last three together, including \i sabka’\i* as follows: “Trumpets, flutes, harps, and all other kinds of musical instruments.”
\key 7.3
\title Wind instruments
\index \l target="REALIA:7.3.1">7.3.1 Horn, ram’s horn\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.3.2">7.3.2 Trumpet, horn\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.3.3">7.3.3 Flute, pipe\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.3.4">7.3.4 Bagpipe (kettledrum, large drum)\l*
\cont Wind instruments are instruments that produce sound through the vibration of air in, through, or around them. This category includes two types of instrument: (1) those where the lips of the player produce the vibration of air in the instrument (\l target="REALIA:7.3.1">7.3.1 Horn, ram’s horn\l* and \l target="REALIA:7.3.2">7.3.2 Trumpet, horn\l*), and (2) those where the point of entry into the instrument produces the vibration of air (\l target="REALIA:7.3.3">7.3.3 Flute, pipe\l* and \l target="REALIA:7.3.4">7.3.4 Bagpipe (kettledrum, large drum)\l*).
\key 7.3.1
\title Horn, ram’s horn
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb יוֹבֵל
\trl yovel
\ref H00201901300040 H00600600400016 H00600600500016 H00600600600046 H00600600800034 H00600601300018
\heb קֶרֶן
\trl qeren
\ref H00600600500012 A02700300500012 A02700300700026 A02700301000024 A02700301500022
\heb שׁוֹפָר
\trl shofar
\ref H00201901600050 H00201901900010 H00202001800034 H00302500900006 H00302500900042 H00600600400012 H00600600400062 H00600600500032 H00600600600044 H00600600800030 H00600600800052 H00600600900024 H00600600900050 H00600601300014 H00600601300040 H00600601300080 H00600601600026 H00600602000018 H00600602000038 H00700302700018 H00700603400022 H00700700800022 H00700701600024 H00700701800010 H00700701800030 H00700701900056 H00700702000016 H00700702000052 H00700702200012 H00901300300036 H01000202800012 H01000601500032 H01001501000032 H01001801600012 H01002000100034 H01002002200052 H01100103400040 H01100103900042 H01100104100042 H01200901300036 H01301502800028 H01401501400032 H01600401200032 H01600401400016 H01803902400024 H01803902500006 H01904700600016 H01908100400010 H01909800600010 H01915000300008 H02301800300030 H02302701300020 H02305800100016 H02400400500024 H02400401900028 H02400402100014 H02400600100022 H02400601700016 H02404201400028 H02405102700014 H02603300300028 H02603300400016 H02603300500008 H02603300600030 H02800500800004 H02800800100006 H02900200100004 H02900201500004 H03000200200040 H03000300600006 H03600101600004 H03800901400032
\heb תָּקוֹעַ
\trl taqo‘a
\ref H02600701400008
\grk σάλπιγξ
\trl salpigx
\ref G04002403100014 G04601400800010 G04601505200018 G05200401600024 G05801201900004 G06600101000030 G06600400100038 G06600800200030 G06600800600018 G06600801300052 G06600901400016
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0443_ramshorn_blowing.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man blowing a ram’s horn|7.0\fig* The horn was a wind instrument made from the horn of an animal, usually a male sheep.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The animal horn was softened so that it could be shaped. The point of the horn was cut off to leave a small opening through which the user blew. The vibration of the lips produced the sound.
\line \fig |KNW-0179_horn.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Rams’ horns|7.0\fig* The ram’s horn served two general purposes:
\line 1. It was blown in certain religious contexts, not as musical accompaniment to worship but as a signal for important events. Some of these events were the giving of the Law on Mount Sinai, the Day of Atonement, the bringing of the Ark of the Covenant into Jerusalem, and the coronation of kings.
\line 2. It also served as a signal or alarm when war was approaching. Such references are particularly common in the prophetic books, when the prophets are calling the people to repent (\s H02800500800004 H02800800100006 H02900200100004 H02900201500004 H03000300600006\s*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0511_horn_ram.jpg|col||© Olve Utne (Wikimedia Commons)|Ram’s horn|7.0\fig* In many passages the purpose of the ram’s horn called \i shofar\i* in Hebrew was to sound an alarm. This will be easy to express in those cultures where the horns of animals are used as musical instruments to give signals to large groups of people. In other cultures it may be possible to find another instrument that is used for an equivalent purpose. In some languages, for example, instruments such as bells or drums are the warnings for war. Some translations have transliterated the word \i shofar\i*. Unless the instrument is well known, such a borrowing should normally be accompanied by a footnote or a glossary entry.
\line The Hebrew words \i yovel\i* and \i qeren\i* (literally “animal horn”) in \s H00201901300040\s* and \s H00600600000000\s* are used as parallel to \i shofar\i* and can be treated as equivalent to \i shofar\i*. Some scholars have suggested that the Hebrew word \i taqo‘a\i* (literally “blowing”) in \s H02600701400008\s* refers not to an instrument but to the town of Tekoa (compare \s H02400600101000\s*). It is more likely, however, that the word refers to the object on which the alarm was blown, that is, the ram’s horn.
\line In some passages it will be necessary to expand the translation in order to indicate that the blowing of the ram’s horn was not just for music; for example, in \s H02600701400008\s* \a CEV\a* has “A signal has been blown on the trumpet,” and \a GECL\a* says “An alarm is sounded.”
\line It may be possible to follow \a NCV\a*’s descriptive phrase for “ram’s horn” in \s H00302500900006\s*, where it has “horn of a male sheep.”
\line In \s H03600101600004\s* \a GNT\a* has “sound of war trumpets,” which emphasizes the function of the ram’s horn, and in the same place \a NCV\a* avoids a translation of the instrument with “alarms.”
\key 7.3.2
\title Trumpet, horn
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חצצר, חֲצֹצְרָה
\trl chatsotsrah, chatsar (verb)
\ref H00401000200008 H00401000800016 H00401000900032 H00401001000030 H00403100600056 H01201101400038 H01201101400064 H01201201400020 H01301300800062 H01301502400034 H01301502800034 H01301600600016 H01301604200012 H01400501200082 H01400501300014 H01400700600070 H01400700600072 H01401301200024 H01401301400038 H01401501400026 H01402002800022 H01402301300036 H01402301300062 H01402902600024 H01402902700044 H01402902800024 H01500301000030 H01601203500014 H01601204100024 H01909800600004 H02800500800012
\heb קֶרֶן
\trl qeren
\ref A02700300500012 A02700300700026 A02700301000024 A02700301500022
\grk σάλπιγξ, σαλπίζω, σαλπιστής
\trl salpigx, salpizō (verb), salpistēs
\ref G04000600200012 G04002403100014 G04601400800010 G04601505200018 G04601505200020 G05200401600024 G05801201900004 G06600101000030 G06600400100038 G06600800200030 G06600800600018 G06600800600026 G06600800700008 G06600800800010 G06600801000010 G06600801200010 G06600801300052 G06600801300064 G06600900100010 G06600901300010 G06600901400016 G06601000700024 G06601101500010 G06601802200018 L07105001600014 L07700305400004 L07700305400008 L07700401300018 L07700404000018 L07700404000022 L07700503100032 L07700503300018 L07700503300022 L07700603300052 L07700603300056 L07700704500030 L07700704500038 L07700901200024 L07700901200028 L07700901200042 L07701600800004 L07701600800008 L07801502500014 L08100505700034 L08100505900010 L08100506100008 L08100506200014 L08100506200036 L08100506300032
\lat tuba
\ref V08200602300004
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0180_trumpet.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Trumpet|7.0\fig* The trumpet was a wind instrument, frequently used in signaling, especially in connection with war. It was made of metal (the trumpets mentioned in \s H00401000000000\s* were made of silver). It was a straight, narrow tube, about 40-45 centimeters (16-18 inches) in length. One end had a mouthpiece, while the other end was widened into a bell shape.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0444_trumpet_blowing.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Man blowing a trumpet|7.0\fig* The sound on the trumpet was made by blowing into the mouthpiece in such a way as to vibrate the lips. The vibrations were magnified as they passed along the widening body of the tube.
\line The purpose of the trumpet in Israel was primarily to signal. \s A02700300500012 A02700300700026 A02700301000024 A02700301500022 G04601505200018 H00901000500066 H01100104000024 H02300501200016 H02303002900034 H02404803600014\s* lists a variety of occasions in which the trumpets were to be used, including signaling the people to break camp, calling all of the people together for a meeting, calling only the leaders together, sounding an alarm at the beginning of a battle, and blowing them for liturgical purposes during certain festivals. It is significant that it was the task of the priests to sound the trumpets.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Generally speaking, translators may distinguish between the Hebrew words \i chatsotsrah\i* and \i shofar\i* (see \l target="REALIA:7.3.1">7.3.1 Horn, ram’s horn\l*) by rendering \i chatsotsrah\i* as “trumpet” or “bugle” and \i shofar\i* with a more generic word for “horn” or with “ram’s horn.” Note the following comment in \i A Handbook on Psalms\i* (page 846) on \s H02404803600030\s*: “In some languages it will not be possible to make a distinction between the two Hebrew terms translated \b trumpets\b* and \b horn\b*. In such cases the local term for a horn will be used. The Greek Old Testament used only one term.”
\line The exact meaning of the Aramaic word \i qeren\i* in \s A02700300500014 A02700300700028 A02700301000026 A02700301500024\s* is debated. It probably refers to a brass wind instrument and is best rendered “horn.”
\line The present-day equivalent for the Greek word \i salpigx\i* is “bugle.” A bugle is generally smaller than a trumpet and is often associated with the sounding of military signals.
\line \s G04601505200020\s*: It may be necessary to introduce an agent in the literal phrase “at the last trumpet” (\a RSV\a*); for example, “when someone blows the trumpet for the last time.” Also possible is “when someone produces a noise on the trumpet for the last time”; however, any term for “noise” should imply a meaningful sound.
\key 7.3.3
\title Flute, pipe
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חָלִיל
\trl chalil
\ref H00901000500066 H01100104000024 H02300501200016 H02303002900034 H02404803600014 H02404803600030
\arm מַשְׁרוֹקִי
\trl mashroqi
\ref A02700300500014 A02700300700028 A02700301000026 A02700301500024
\heb נְחִילוֹת
\trl nchiloth
\ref H01900500100012
\heb עוּגָב
\trl ‘ugav
\ref H00100402100024 H01802101200020 H01803003100014 H01915000400020
\grk αὐλέω, αὐλητής, αὐλός
\trl auleō (verb), aulētēs, aulos
\ref G04000902300026 G04001101700004 G04200703200026 G04601400700014 G04601400700038 G06601802200014 L07104002100002 L07700304500074 L08100500200042
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0512_flute.jpg|col||Vassil (Wikimedia Commons)|Flute|7.0\fig* The flute was a wind instrument consisting of a tube with a series of finger holes used to alter the tone. Some flutes were made of reed and could take several forms: the tube could be a cylinder or it could be more in the shape of a cone. There were instruments made of a single tube, while others had two tubes side by side. Often ancient double flutes or double pipes were arranged in a V-shape, with two separate reeds. One of these pipes had several holes while the other had only one hole and acted as a kind of drone, providing an unchanging tone to accompany the varying tones coming from the first pipe. Some pipes or flutes were made of other materials, such as wood, ivory, bone, or metal.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0178_double_flute.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Double flute|7.0\fig* Sound was produced with the flute by blowing across an opening leading into a hole running inside the length of the instrument; in some cases the opening hole was in the end of the instrument while in others this hole was in the side of the instrument toward one end. With the reed pipe, on the other hand, a column of air was set in motion by blowing over a reed device, causing it to vibrate.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0189_flutes_playing.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Men playing flutes|7.0\fig* If there is no wind instrument available to translate “flute,” a different kind of wind instrument may be used.
\line The Hebrew word \i ‘ugav\i* is usually understood to refer to a wind instrument; for example, in \s H00100402100024\s* \a RSV\a* says “pipe” and \a GNT\a* has “flute.” It is possible, however, that it is a generic term for “instrument” or even refers to a particular stringed instrument. In \s H01802101200020\s* and \s H01803003100014\s* it is identified as an instrument that expressed joy and contentment.
\line \s H01900500100012\s*: The Hebrew word \i nchiloth\i* appears only here in the Old Testament, and its meaning is uncertain. It may mean “wind instruments” in general or “flutes” in particular. Extra-biblical evidence indicates that it may have been an instrument played for funeral laments.
\line \s G04000902300026\s*: Here \a RSV\a* has “flute players” (\a GNT\a* “musicians”): According to Jewish tradition, even the poorest people were expected to have two flute players and a wailing woman for a funeral. In order to clarify the role of the flute players, \a GNT\a* adds “for the funeral.” This information was immediately evident to a Jewish reader who was familiar with the funeral customs, but it will not be clear to other readers. Many cultures are familiar with the flute or other instruments that are played by blowing through a wooden tube. If no such instrument exists, then translators can say “those who played musical instruments for a funeral” or, as in \a GNT\a*, “musicians for the funeral”; \a NCV\a* has “funeral musicians.”
\line For the translation of the Aramaic word \i mashroqi\i*, see the discussion on \s A02700300001000\s* at the beginning of this chapter.
\key 7.3.4
\title Bagpipe (kettledrum, large drum)
\cont \u References:\u*
\arm סוּמְפֹּנְיָה
\trl sumponyah
\ref A02700300501100 A02700301001160 A02700301001170 A02700301501150
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0513_bagpipe_en.jpg|col||Cyclopedia of Biblical, Theological and Ecclesiastical Literature, 1888|Bagpipe|7.0\fig* The bagpipe consisted of two pipes connected to an air bag. The bag was inflated by blowing into a third tube or pipe. The air in the bag escaped through the double pipes. These had finger holes that could be opened or closed producing a range of notes.
\line The kettledrum was a larger drum, in construction similar to the drum discussed under \l target="REALIA:7.4.6">7.4.6 Drum, hand drum, frame drum\l*. However, it was not held but stood on the ground.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Several instruments have been suggested for the Aramaic word \i sumponyah\i* in \s A02700300001000\s*, including a double pipe, a drum, and a bagpipe (depicted in the illustration above). Translations include “pipes” (\a NIV\a*, \a NCV\a*), “bagpipe” (\a RSV\a*, \a NJB\a*), “drum” (\a NRSV\a*), and “dulcimer” (\a KJV\a*, \a REB\a*). The identification of \i sumponyah\i* as a large drum is based on the assumption that this Aramaic word is a transliteration of a dialect form of the Greek word \i tumpanon\i*.
\line Many scholars are convinced that the word \i sumponyah\i* is not actually the name of a particular instrument, but rather that it referred to the playing together of all the individual instruments mentioned before (so \a GNT\a* “and then all the other instruments will join in”). This interpretation is probably derived from a reading of \i sumponyah\i* as meaning “accompanying sound.” \a NEB\a* follows this interpretation, using the general term “music” here.
\key 7.4
\title Percussion instruments
\index \l target="REALIA:7.4.1">7.4.1 Sistrum\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.4.2">7.4.2 Cymbals\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.4.3">7.4.3 Gong\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.4.4">7.4.4 Shaker, rattle\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.4.5">7.4.5 Wooden clappers\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:7.4.6">7.4.6 Drum, hand drum, frame drum\l*
\cont Percussion instruments are made of resonant material and make sounds when they are struck or shaken. This category includes entries \l target="REALIA:7.4.1">7.4.1 Sistrum\l* through \l target="REALIA:7.4.5">7.4.5 Wooden clappers\l*. For convenience, we may also include the drums, entry \l target="REALIA:7.4.6">7.4.6 Drum, hand drum, frame drum\l* (see also \l target="REALIA:7.3.4">7.3.4 Bagpipe (kettledrum, large drum)\l*). In the case of drums, the sound is made by striking a stretched membrane, often of animal skin.
\key 7.4.1
\title Sistrum
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb שָׁלִישׁ
\trl shalish
\ref H00901800600078
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0181_sistrum.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Sistrum|7.0\fig* The sistrum consisted of a frame carrying short wires on which small metal rings were threaded.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The sistrum was shaken, making a rattling or tinkling sound. Its use accompanied singing and dancing.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i shalish\i* meaning “sistrum” appears only in \s H00901800600078\s*. Its exact meaning is uncertain. Other possible meanings are “triangle,” “three-stringed lute,” “triangular harp,” and “triangular hand drum.”
\key 7.4.2
\title Cymbals
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מְצִלְתַּיִם
\trl mtsiltayim
\ref H01301300800056 H01301501600042 H01301501900018 H01301502800040 H01301600500064 H01301604200016 H01302500100054 H01302500600024 H01400501200046 H01400501300068 H01402902500018 H01500301000046 H01601202700056
\heb צֶלְצְלִים
\trl tseltselim
\ref H01000600500058 H01915000500006 H01915000500014
\grk κύμβαλον
\trl kumbalon
\ref G04601300100036 L06801600100028 L07700405400048 L07701305100054 L08100505700050
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0514_cymbals.jpg|col||© Finoskov (Wikimedia Commons)|Cymbals|7.0\fig* Cymbals were a percussion instrument consisting of two metal discs that were struck together in order to make a shrill, clashing sound. There were two types of cymbals: (1) flat metal plates that were struck together, and (2) metal cones, one of which was brought down on top of the other, on the open end.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The equivalent of “cymbal” in many languages is a phrase such as “loud metal.”
\line In \s H01915000500006\s* two kinds of cymbals are mentioned, literally “cymbals of hearing” and “cymbals of shouting.” This may mean “small cymbals . . . large cymbals, or it may be just a poetic variation with the meaning “clanging cymbals . . . clashing cymbals.”
\line In \s G04601300100036\s* \a GNT\a* renders the Greek word \i kumbalon\i* as “bell” instead of “cymbal” since it is more widely understood.
\key 7.4.3
\title Gong
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk χαλκός
\trl chalkos
\ref G04601300100030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The gong was a concave, platelike piece of metal that reverberated loudly when struck.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In a number of languages the equivalent of “gong” is “noisy metal,” “reverberating metal,” or “echoing metal,” but frequently translators have simply used an expression meaning “loud bell.”
\line The Greek word \i chalkos\i* can refer to a metal such as copper or bronze, something made out of metal such as coins (see \l target="REALIA:1.6.3">1.6.3 Money, coins\l*), or armor. The mention of a “cymbal” immediately after this word in \s G04601300100030\s* suggests that a musical instrument such as a gong is intended here. As noted in \l target="REALIA:7.4.2">7.4.2 Cymbals\l*, the cymbal in ancient times was a metal basin used like modern cymbals, in pairs, to produce a musical sound. Other translators will have to decide what musical instruments in their cultures carry the same meaning if there are no gongs or cymbals. Gongs and cymbals were sometimes part of pagan ritual in the time of the New Testament, and it is possible that Paul has this in mind in this verse. Recent scholarship has determined that the Greek phrase \i chalkos ēchōn\i* (literally “booming brass”) in this verse may refer to a practice known from Greek amphitheaters. A type of resonating brass vase was placed at several locations at the back of the amphitheater to amplify the voices of the singers or actors on the stage. It served as a kind of amplification (Braun, page 44).
\key 7.4.4
\title Shaker, rattle
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb מְנַעַנְעִים
\trl mna‘an‘im
\ref H01000600500052
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0515_shaker.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|A shaker (rattle)|7.0\fig* The shakers were small closed pottery containers holding small rattling pellets. When shaken, they provided the rhythm to accompany dancing.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The precise meaning of the Hebrew word \i mna‘an‘im\i* is uncertain, and translations differ, including “castanets” (\a RSV\a*, \a JB\a*, \a REB\a*), “sistrums” (\a NIV\a*, \a TOB\a*), and “rattles” (\a GNT\a*, \a NCV\a*). The translation “castanets” would associate the word with instruments that produced sound by banging together two flat pieces of wood. This would also imply different hand and finger movements from the translation “shakers,” as well as a different sound. The \a GNT\a* translation “rattles” has the danger of being associated with baby toys, as well as the disadvantage that it lacks the association with dance and the assonance of the Hebrew word in its context. It is probably best to translate \i mna‘an‘im\i* with something that indicates a kind of shaker or rattle.
\key 7.4.5
\title Wooden clappers
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\heb עֵץ, בְּרוֹשׁ
\trl ‘atsey broshim
\ref H01000600500026
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Clappers were flat, oblong, rectangular, or curved. They could be made of wood, ivory, or bone. They were tied together at one end, enabling them to be struck together. This produced a kind of slapping sound.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line For “wooden clappers,” many cultures will know comparable percussion instruments, similar in use and appearance to castanets.
\line The Hebrew phrase \i ‘atsey broshim\i* in \s H01000600500026\s* has been given several interpretations. The phrase means literally “cypress trees” or “pieces of cypress wood.” This has led some scholars to suggest that this is not a reference to musical instruments, but that the people were waving cypress branches as a sign of joy. Others interpret this to mean “instruments made of cypress wood” (\a ITCL\a*), indicating a separate entry in the series of instruments named. It is also possible to understand the phrase to indicate the material from which the instruments that follow in the list were made; compare, for example, \a NCV\a*’s rendering of the last half of this verse: “They were playing wooden instruments: lyres, harps, tambourines, rattles, and cymbals.”
\key 7.4.6
\title Drum, hand drum, frame drum
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb תֹּף, תפף
\trl tof, tafaf (verb)
\ref H00103102700040 H00201502000020 H00201502000040 H00701103400030 H00901000500062 H00901800600068 H01000600500046 H01301300800050 H01802101200006 H01906802600016 H01908100300010 H01914900300012 H01915000400006 H02300501200012 H02302400800006 H02303003200024 H02403100400018
\grk τύμπανον
\trl tumpanon
\ref L06800300700030 L06801600100018 L07700903900060 L08100500200038
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0184_tambourine.png|col||Horace Knowles, revised by Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Hand drum|7.0\fig* The drum consisted of a membrane, usually of animal skin, which was stretched over a shallow circular, triangular, or square frame.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line The drum was struck sharply with one or two hands, depending on where it was situated. It could be held in the left hand, under the left arm, or against the chest and struck with the right hand, or it could be held on the knees or the ground and struck with one or two hands. The fingers of the left hand could be used to tighten or loosen the tension on the membrane as it was struck with the palm of the right hand.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0516_drum.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Wikimedia Commons)|Women beating hand drums|7.0\fig* The use of the Hebrew word \i tof\i* is usually associated with singing, processions, and festivals. Archaeological evidence indicates that drums with metal circlets on the frame (“tambourines” or “timbrels”) were not known in biblical times. As a general rule, the best translation for this word will be “hand drum” or simply “drum.” tion for this word will be “hand drum” or simply “drum.”
\c 8
\key 8
\title Transportation
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1">8.1 Boat, ship\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.2">8.2 Cart, wagon\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.3">8.3 Wheel\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.4">8.4 Saddle, saddle cloth\l*
\key 8.1
\title Boat, ship
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.1">8.1.1 Basket, small boat\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.2">8.1.2 Raft, float\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.3">8.1.3 Ark, ship\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.4">8.1.4 Mast\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.5">8.1.5 Sail\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.6">8.1.6 Anchor\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.7">8.1.7 Oar\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.8">8.1.8 Steering oar, rudder\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.9">8.1.9 Keel\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.10">8.1.10 Figurehead\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:8.1.11">8.1.11 Deck\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֳנִי
\trl ’oni
\ref H01100902600004 H01100902700012 H01101001100006 H01101002200004 H01101002200022 H01101002200036 H02303302100030
\heb אֳנִיָּה
\trl ’oniyah
\ref H00104901300020 H00502806800012 H00700501700022 H01100902700020 H01102204900008 H01102204900036 H01102205000026 H01400801800016 H01400801800018 H01400902100004 H01400902100032 H01402003600012 H01402003600024 H01402003700044 H01800902600006 H01904800800010 H01910402600004 H01910702300010 H02003001900024 H02003101400006 H02300201600008 H02302300100008 H02302301400004 H02306000900012 H02602700900020 H02602702500002 H02602702900008 H02701104000046 H03200100300032 H03200100400036 H03200100500036
\heb כְּלִי, גֹּמֶא
\trl kle gome’
\ref H02301800200018
\heb סְפִינָה
\trl sfinah
\ref H03200100500064
\heb צִי
\trl tsi
\ref H00402402400004 H02303302100036 H02603000900026 H02701103000008
\grk ναυαγέω
\trl nauageō (verb)
\ref G04701102500012 G05400101900024
\grk ναύκληρος
\trl nauklēros
\ref G04402701100016
\grk ναῦς
\trl naus
\ref G04402704100016 L07000501000004 L08000700100030
\grk πλοιάριον
\trl ploiarion
\ref G04100300900014 G04300602200024 G04300602300006 G04300602400038 G04302100800012
\grk πλοῖον
\trl ploion
\ref G04000402100038 G04000402200012 G04000802300012 G04000802400022 G04000900100008 G04001300200020 G04001401300016 G04001402200018 G04001402400006 G04001402900018 G04001403200012 G04001403300010 G04001503900016 G04100101900036 G04100102000026 G04100400100034 G04100403600022 G04100403600028 G04100403700024 G04100403700034 G04100500200012 G04100501800012 G04100502100014 G04100603200010 G04100604500020 G04100604700012 G04100605100014 G04100605400012 G04100801000012 G04100801400032 G04200500200008 G04200500300012 G04200500300042 G04200500700016 G04200500700038 G04200501100008 G04200802200022 G04200803700044 G04300601700008 G04300601900038 G04300602100014 G04300602100024 G04300602200062 G04300602300006 G04302100300038 G04302100600022 G04402001300012 G04402003800040 G04402100200006 G04402100300038 G04402100600014 G04402700200006 G04402700600010 G04402701000034 G04402701500008 G04402701700014 G04402701900016 G04402702200032 G04402703000016 G04402703100030 G04402703700016 G04402703800012 G04402703900044 G04402704400030 G04402801100014 G05900300400008 G06600800900036 G06601801900054 L07001400100026 L07103300200028 L07700802600022 L07700802800018 L07701100100034 L07701302900042 L07701500300056 L07701501400014 L07701503700010 L07900400700016 L07900400900026
\grk σκάφη, σκάφος
\trl skafē
\ref G04402701600024 G04402703000024 G04402703200016 L07600103300028 L07801200300038 L07801200600042
\grk στόλος
\trl stolos
\ref L07700101700034 L07801200900022 L07801400100048 L07900701700036
\grk τριήρης
\trl triērēs
\ref L07800402000042
\lat navis
\ref V08200903400022 V08201204200042
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0217_ship_sailing.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Sailing ship|8.0\fig* Boats and ships were vessels used for transport on water. They varied in size from very small boats, large enough for only three or four people, to ocean-going ships capable of transporting many people and large amounts of cargo. Boats and ships were generally made of wood, although in Egypt, reeds were also used to construct at least parts of boats. These vessels were propelled in several ways: sails attached to a mast caught the wind and so moved the vessel; in smaller vessels (but also in some larger ones), oars were used to row; in places where the water was shallow, they could be moved by means of a pole pushing along the bed or bank of a river or stream.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0208_fishermen_boat.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Fishing boat|8.0\fig* It may be very important to distinguish clearly between small fishing boats and larger ships or vessels. In a number of languages the distinction is based on whether or not such vessels have decks (see \l target="REALIA:8.1.11">8.1.11 Deck\l*). For the fishing boats on Lake Galilee there was probably no deck structure, while vessels going for long distances on the Mediterranean Sea would certainly have had decks.
\line Translators must avoid a word for “ship” that indicates modern ocean-going steam-powered ships; all larger vessels mentioned in the Bible (with the exception of the ark, which had no means of propulsion) were powered either by sails or by rowers. In land-bound cultures where only small fishing boats are known, it is important to render “ships” as, for example, “big boats that sail on the ocean” or “big boats with sails to make them move on the ocean.”
\line \s H01800902600006\s*: “Skiffs of reed” (\a RSV\a*) or papyrus were Nile River boats whose sides were made of papyrus reeds and which were known for their swift travel on the river. The first line of this verse may be rendered “My days go quickly like fast sailing boats.” In areas where sailing boats are unknown, the comparison may be shifted to any swift watercraft; for example, “My days flow swiftly like a fast dugout/canoe.” Where boats are completely unknown, it may be necessary to drop the image and say “My life is over very soon” or “The days of my life come quickly to an end.”
\line \fig |WEB-0517_ship.jpg|col||© MatthiasKabel (Wikimedia Commons)|Greek warship with many oars|8.0\fig* \s H02301800200018\s*: Here the unique Hebrew phrase \i kle gome’\i* means “vessels of papyrus” (\a RSV\a*) or “boats made of papyrus reed” and is equivalent to the Hebrew phrase \i ’oniyoth ’eveh\i* in \s H01800902600006\s*. \a CEV\a* provides a footnote, which reads “Ancient Egypt was famous for the papyrus reeds that grew in the Nile Delta,” but its rendering “ships made of reeds” gives the impression of too large a vessel. \a GNT\a* and \a NCV\a* are better with “boats made of reeds”; compare \a NJB\a* “little reed-boats.”
\line In \s H03200100500036\s* the Hebrew word \i sfinah\i* indicates a ship that had a covered deck. It is equivalent to the word \i ’oniyah\i* in this verse. Where did Jonah go to sleep? To speak of the “ship’s hold” (\a GNT\a*) may suggest a more elaborate vessel than this one would be; the Hebrew word here is used for any recess or corner, as in a cave (\s H00902400301000\s*) or a house (\s H03000601001000\s*). Jonah was simply finding the most remote and comfortable place for going quietly to sleep, where he would not be disturbed. \a CEV\a* “down below deck” may serve as a model. Also good is \a FRCL\a* “bottom of the boat.”
\line In the Gospels there is no real difference between the Greek words \i ploion\i* and \i ploiarion\i*, even though the latter word is the Greek diminutive of the former word. Both words refer to a fishing boat measuring about 8.5 meters (28 feet) long and 2.5 meters (8 feet) wide and able to hold 12-15 people. In the book of Acts and \s G05900300400008\s*, the word \i ploion\i* refers to a larger vessel, capable of sailing on the open sea. This is true also in \s G06601801701000 G06601801900054\s*. The reference in \s G06600800900036\s* may be to boats and ships of many sizes.
\line \s G04402701600024 G04402703000016 G04402703200016\s*: In these verses the Greek word \i skafē\i* refers to a small boat that was normally kept aboard a larger ship and used by sailors in placing anchors, repairing the ship, or saving lives in the case of storms. In some languages \i skafē\i* is equivalent to “rowboat” or “lifeboat.”
\line A few of the passages listed above (for example, \s L07800402000042\s*) refer to “warships.” The context will usually make this clear. Where special words exist for ships built for war, they can be used. However, translators should be careful not to introduce anachronistic terms for modern specialized warships such as cruisers, battleships, or aircraft carriers.
\line The Hebrew words \i ’oni\i* and \i tsi\i* and the Greek word \i stolos\i* refer to a large group of ships, that is, a “fleet.”
\key 8.1.1
\title Basket, small boat
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb תֵּבָה
\trl tevah
\ref H00200200300018 H00200200500042
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0518_basket.jpg|col||Don Ellens, The Tabernacle of Israel, 1888|Reed basket|8.0\fig* The basket in \s H00200200300018\s* was a small boat made of papyrus reeds. Its exact size is not given, but it would have been large enough to hold a newborn baby. The basket was made watertight by a coating of tar (bitumen) and pitch, presumably on the outside.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Older English versions translated the Hebrew word \i tevah\i* as “ark” (\a KJV\a*) in \s H00200200300018 H00200200500042\s*. This is confusing. Even though the same Hebrew word (literally “box”) is used for both this small boat and for Noah’s large ship (see \l target="REALIA:8.1.3">8.1.3 Ark, ship\l*), the translator should not try to find a single word for both.
\key 8.1.2
\title Raft, float
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb דֹּבְרוֹת
\trl dovroth
\ref H01100502300020
\grk σχεδία
\trl schedia
\ref L07001400500044 L07001400600024 L08100505300056
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0519_raft.jpg|col||Austen Henry Layard, Nineveh and Babylon: a narrative of a second expedition to Assyria during the years 1849, 1850, & 1851|Raft made of animal skins|8.0\fig* The raft was a floating surface made by binding logs or planks together. A raft could also be made of inflated animal skins, as in the illustration below. It could be used for transporting people or goods.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line While many languages have a special word for logs tied together to make a raft, it is possible to avoid using a precise term. In the middle of \s H01100500901000\s*, \a CEV\a* has “They will tie the logs together and float them along the coast.” Here and in \s L08100505300056\s*, the rafts are not for transport but only a means of moving the logs from one place to another.
\line In \s L07001400500044 L07001400600024\s* there is a double usage of the Greek word \i schedia\i*. Verse 5 speaks of the way people can travel on the big ocean on nothing more than a small amount of floating wood. Verse 6 is a recollection of the ark in which Noah and his family (and through them all of humanity) were saved. \a RSV\a*, \a NAB\a*, and \a NJB\a* use “raft” in both verses, so the reference to the ark is somewhat obscured. \a NJB\a* adds a footnote to verse 6 indicating that the reference is to Noah’s ark. \a GNT\a* is better with the word “boat” in both verses. \a GNT\a*’s section heading for \s L07001400100000-L07001401100000\s* is “Wooden Idols Compared with Noah’s Wooden Boat.” This explains that the whole passage is about Noah’s ark.
\key 8.1.3
\title Ark, ship
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb תֵּבָה
\trl tevah
\ref H00100601400006 H00100601400020 H00100601500022 H00100601600010 H00100601600032 H00100601800020 H00100601900030 H00100700100026 H00100700700028 H00100700900016 H00100701300054 H00100701500014 H00100701700036 H00100701800028 H00100702300074 H00100800100040 H00100800400008 H00100800600026 H00100800900030 H00100800900068 H00100801000030 H00100801300060 H00100801600008 H00100801900042 H00100901000052 H00100901800018
\grk κιβωτός
\trl kibōtos
\ref G04002403800050 G04201702700024 G05801100700020 G06000302000026 L07800200400022 07800200500026 L08001503100010 L08100100300034 L08100105100030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0520_ark_noah.jpg|col||Don Ellens, The Tabernacle of Israel, 1888|Artist's conception of Noah's ark|8.0\fig* The ark was the vessel built by Noah. Its dimensions and materials are described in \s H00100601401000 H00100601501000 H00100601601000\s*, which gives it a length of 135-150 meters (443-492 feet), a width of 22.5-25 meters (74-82 feet), and a height of 13.5-15 meters (44-49 feet). The ark was made of wood and had three decks or levels and a roof. Each deck was divided into rooms or compartments. Except for an entrance door in its side and one window (both of unspecified size), the ark was closed in all around and would have resembled a large wooden box.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The central meaning of both the Hebrew word \i tevah\i* and the Greek word \i kibōtos\i* is “box” or “chest.” These words were apparently applied to Noah’s vessel in view of the type of construction and the fact that it resembled more a barge than a seagoing vessel. However, in view of the size of Noah’s ark, it is probably best in most languages to speak of it as a “ship.”
\line When translating the dimensions of Noah’s ark given in \s H00100601500022 H00100601600010\s*, it is best to use modern units of measurement understood by the reader. Thus the American edition of \a GNT\a* uses feet and inches, while other modern languages give the measurements in metric units (for example, \a SPCL\a* and \a FRCL\a*). While the exact length of the Hebrew unit used in \s H00100600000000\s* is uncertain, it is clear that the dimensions of the ark would have made it the largest ship ever built until the early twentieth century. Where possible, translations should reflect that this was an extremely large vessel. Thus, for example, in English “ship” is preferable to “boat.”
\key 8.1.4
\title Mast
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חִבֵּל
\trl chibel
\ref H02002303400026
\heb תֹּרֶן
\trl toren
\ref H02303302300012 H02602700500030
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0445_ship_mast_en.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Mast|8.0\fig* The mast was a strong wooden pole to which a sail (\l target="REALIA:8.1.5">8.1.5 Sail\l*) was attached. The pole was mounted vertically on the boat or ship and attached to its bottom. Its height and diameter varied with the size of the vessel.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In \s H02002303400026\s* some translations render the Hebrew word \i chibel\i* as “rigging” (\a REB\a*, \a HOTTP\a*). However, languages that cannot express “mast” will probably also have difficulty with “rigging.” Where it is difficult to express the idea of the mast or rigging of a ship, translators may follow \a CEV\a*, which renders the whole verse as “You will feel tossed about like someone trying to sleep on a ship in a storm.”
\key 8.1.5
\title Sail
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb נֵס
\trl nes
\ref H02303302300018
\heb מִפְרָשׂ
\trl mifras
\ref H02602700700014
\grk ἀρτέμων
\trl artemōn
\ref G04402704000036
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0446_ship_sails_en.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Sails|8.0\fig* The sail was a cloth attached above a boat in such a way as to catch the wind and thus propel the boat through the water.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line A sail may be rendered in some languages as “piece of cloth to make the ship move” or “cloth on the ship to catch the wind.” In \s G04402704000036\s* the Greek word \i artemōn\i* may refer to the foresail, that is, a relatively small sail toward the prow or front of the ship.
\key 8.1.6
\title Anchor
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ἄγκυρα
\trl agkura
\ref G04402702900024 G04402703000040 G04402704000006 G05800601900006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0521_anchor.jpg|col||© Bukvoed (Wikimedia Commons)|Iron anchor|8.0\fig* The anchor was a heavy object attached to a boat by a rope or chain and dropped to the bottom of the water in order to prevent or restrict the movement of the boat. Ancient anchors were often made of stone, sometimes of metal.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |PTZ-0085_anchor_stone_en.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Stone anchor (Egyptian drawing)|8.0\fig* For languages spoken by people far removed from a coast, an expression for “anchor” may be extremely difficult to find or even to develop. In some languages “anchor” is rendered as “heavy weights on ropes to keep a boat from moving” or even “heavy object that holds the boat in one place.” However, if the people in question have no experience with anchors, it may be important to have a marginal note to indicate specifically what an anchor is, and then to employ some abbreviated form of that description to render the object in the text.
\line For the metaphorical use of “anchor” in \s G05800601900006\s*, see the extensive comments in \i A Handbook on The Letter to the Hebrews\i* (pages 130-131). \fig |WEB-0522_anchor.jpg|col||© Deror avi (Wikimedia Commons)|Stone anchor|8.0\fig*
\key 8.1.7
\title Oar
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מָשׁוֹט
\trl mashot
\ref H02602700600010 H02602702900014
\heb שַׁיִט
\trl shot
\ref H02303302100032
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0447_ship_steeringoars.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Steering oars at the stern of a ship|8.0\fig* The oar was a means of propelling a boat or ship either when there was not enough wind for sailing or when the vessel had to be maneuvered in a confined space. The oar was a long pole with a broad flat surface attached to one end. Pushing the flat surface through the water created resistance and moved the vessel forward or backward. Oars were usually attached to the boat or ship somewhere near the middle of the pole. This was often done in larger vessels by passing the pole through an opening in the hull of the ship. See the illustrations at \l target="REALIA:8.1.8">8.1.8 Steering oar, rudder\l*.
\key 8.1.8
\title Steering oar, rudder
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk οἴαξ
\trl oiax
\ref L08000700300016
\grk πηδάλιον
\trl pēdalion
\ref G04402704000028 G05900300400030
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0523_boat.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Boat propelled and steered by oars|8.0\fig* The rudder was a large plank at the stern of a ship used to direct its course. This could also take the form of two long oars, one extending from each side either behind the ship or in front of it. By moving the rudder or steering oars from side to side, it was possible to control the direction of the ship.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Ancient ships had “steering oars,” one on each side sticking out toward the back or toward the front. In some languages “steering oars” may be rendered “rudders” or “oars that served like rudders.” In other languages translators must use a descriptive phrase, such as “large oars that the boat used for steering.” For languages in which there is no regular term for “oar” or “rudder,” you may even use an expression such as “large pieces of wood at the back of the boat used to steer it.” Also possible is “instrument for steering the ship” or “instrument for making the ship go the way one wants it to go.”
\line Even though the rudder could be a large wooden plank, it was small in relation to the size of the whole ship. This is the point in \s G05900300400030\s*: a relatively small plank can change the direction of a large ship.
\key 8.1.9
\title Keel
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk τρόπις
\trl tropis
\ref L07000501000028
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0050_keel_en.jpg|col||Bible Lands as Classroom © United Bible Societies|Keel|8.0\fig* The keel was the bottom, center structural part of a boat or ship. It usually extended somewhat below the bottom of the vessel in order to add to its stability.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Even where ships and boats are known, the average reader may not be familiar with specific parts of such a vessel. Therefore it may be best to avoid the technical term in \s L07000501000028\s*. For the more literal “when it has passed no trace can be found, nor track of its keel in the waves” (\a RSV\a*), \a GNT\a* has “when it is gone, it leaves no trace. You cannot tell it was ever there.”
\key 8.1.10
\title Figurehead
\cont \u Reference:\u*
\grk παράσημος
\trl parasēmos
\ref G04402801100026
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0448_ship_figurehead.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Figurehead|8.0\fig* The figurehead was an identifying emblem, often a carved figure, mounted on the prow of a ship. It was made of wood.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line When translating the literal expression “figurehead of the Twin Gods” in \s G04402801100026\s*, it may be possible to use a phrase such as “carving of the heads of the Twin Gods” or “statue of the Twin Gods.”
\key 8.1.11
\title Deck
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb תַּחְתִּי
\trl tachti
\ref H00100601600040
\heb קֶרֶשׁ
\trl qeresh
\ref H02602700600012
\grk σανίδωμα
\trl sanidōma
\ref L07900401000012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0449_ship_deck.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Men standing on a ship's deck|8.0\fig* The deck was a platform extending from one side of a ship to the other side. Larger ships could have more than one deck at different levels. The ark described in \s H00100600000000\s* had three decks.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line A “deck” in a ship is equivalent to a “floor” in a building, and some translations of \s H00100601600040\s* use “stories” (\a CEV\a*). \a GECL\a* expands the last clause of this verse, saying “put in two middle decks, so that it is three floors high.” The three decks of the large ship built by Noah were evidently all inside the ship, because the whole structure was roofed, unlike a normal ancient ship.
\line Chariot: See \l target="REALIA:2.15">2.15 Chariot\l*.
\key 8.2
\title Cart, wagon
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גַּלְגַּל
\trl galgal
\ref H02602302400014 H02602601000020
\heb עֲגָלָה
\trl ‘agalah
\ref H00104501900022 H00104502100020 H00104502700030 H00104600500044 H00400700300018 H00400700300030 H00400700600012 H00400700700008 H00400700800010 H00900600700012 H00900600700050 H00900600800022 H00900601000030 H00900601100016 H00900601400006 H00900601400046 H01000600300016 H01000600300056 H01301300700016 H01301300700040 H01904601000024 H02300501800026 H02302802700020 H02302802800024 H03000201300018
\heb צָב, עֲגָלָה
\trl tsav, ‘egloth tsav
\ref H00400700300018 H00400700300020 H02306602000046
\grk ἅμαξα
\trl hamaxa
\ref L06801501100088 L07103300500004
\grk καρρον
\trl karron
\ref L08100505300026
\grk ῥέδη
\trl rhedē
\ref G06601801300052
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0035_wagon_model.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Wagon model|8.0\fig* The wagon was a two or four-wheeled carriage or cart used for travel or the transport of loads. Such vehicles were usually made of wood. They were pulled by draft animals, usually oxen, donkeys, or horses. These animals were attached to a long pole that was in turn attached to the front of the wagon. The upper section of the wagon was often formed by crossed wooden bars in the shape of a cage.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Wagons and carts in the Bible were always pulled by animals. Translators should avoid any word for “wagon” that indicates a vehicle propelled by an engine.
\line \fig |KNW-0450_cart_yokedoxen.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Oxen pulling a cart|8.0\fig* \s H00400700300018\s*: The meaning of the Hebrew phrase \i ‘egloth tsav\i* here is uncertain. Most translators and commentators say something like “covered wagons” (\a RSV\a*, \a REB\a*). These would be wagons as described above with a cloth covering the items carried in each wagon. Such a wagon might resemble a tortoise or turtle, which is a meaning of the Hebrew word \i tsav\i*.
\line \s H02602302400014 H02602601000020\s*: The Hebrew word \i galgal\i* is literally “wheel.” In the context of these verses, it is clear that this is a metonym for a vehicle with wheels, that is, a cart or wagon.
\line \s L08100505300026\s*: In this verse some Greek manuscripts have the word \i chara\i* (“joy”), which makes no sense in this context. One manuscript has the word \i karron\i*, meaning “wagon” as described above.
\key 8.3
\title Wheel
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אוֹפַן
\trl ’ofan
\ref H00201402500008 H01100703000006 H01100703200008 H01100703200028 H01100703200042 H01100703300008 H01100703300014 H02002002600016 H02302802700018 H02600101500014 H02600101600006 H02600101600044 H02600101600052 H02600101900016 H02600101900042 H02600102000034 H02600102000054 H02600102100034 H02600102100052 H02600301300026 H02601000600062 H02601000900012 H02601000900020 H02601000900034 H02601000900052 H02601001000022 H02601001000030 H02601001200024 H02601001200036 H02601001300006 H02601001600016 H02601001600052 H02601001900036 H02601102200018 H03400300200012
\heb גַּלְגַּל
\trl galgal
\ref H02300502800030 H02404700300022 H02601000200032 H02601000600038 H02601001300014 A02700700900050
\heb גִּלְגָּל
\trl gilgal
\ref H02302802800022
\grk τροχός
\trl trochos
\ref L07103300500002
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Axle\b*:
\heb יָד
\trl yad
\ref H01100703200024 H01100703300020
\heb סֶרֶן
\trl seren
\ref H01100703000022
\grk ἄξων
\trl axōn
\ref L07103300500014
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Wheel hub\b*:
\heb חִשּׁוּר
\trl chishur
\ref H01100703300032
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Wheel spoke\b*:
\heb חִשּׁוּק
\trl chishuq
\ref H01100703300028
\cont \u References:\u*
\scont \b Wheel rim\b*:
\heb גַּב
\trl gav
\ref H01100703300024 H02600101800004 H02600101800020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0524_wheel_en.jpg|col||Gary Todd (Flickr)|Hub, spoke, and rim of a wheel|8.0\fig* The wheel was a ring or round disk with a rod (the axle) running through its center or hub. Wheels were made of wood and sometimes partly of metal. They could be a solid piece of wood (see the illustrations at \l target="REALIA:8.2">8.2 Cart, wagon\l*) or a central hub connected by several spokes to an outer rim. The axle normally extended from one side of the vehicle to the other side, with a wheel attached to each end of the axle.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0525_axle_en.jpg|col||Cyclopedia of Biblical, Theological and Ecclesiastical Literature, 1888|Axle|8.0\fig* The “wheels” mentioned in \s H02600101500014 H02600101600006 H02600101701000 H02600101800004 H02600101900016 H02600102000034 H02600102100034\s* and \s H02601000600062 H02601000701000 H02601000801000 H02601000900012 H02601001000022 H02601001101000 H02601001200024 H02601001300006 H02601001401000 H02601001501000 H02601001600016 H02601001701000 H02601001801000 H02601001900036\s* may not refer to devices on which a vehicle rolls. These “wheels” may be understood as some sort of spinning disks, for which a language may have a separate word. Jewish tradition interprets this image as a vehicle on which the LORD is seated, and these are the wheels of the vehicle.
\line While most languages will have a word for “axle,” \a NAB\a* renders \s L07103300500020\s* accurately without reference to this piece on which the wheel turns: “Like the wheel of a cart is the mind of a fool; his thoughts revolve in circles.”
\key 8.4
\title Saddle, saddle cloth
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בֶּגֶד, חֹפֶשׁ, רִכְבָּה
\trl bigde chofesh lrikbah
\ref H02602702000008
\heb חבשׁ
\trl chavash (verb)
\ref H00102200300016 H00402202100016 H00701901000046 H01001600100036 H01001702300018 H01001902700022 H01100204000010 H01101301300010 H01101301300020 H01101302300020 H01101302700014 H01101302700026 H01200402400004
\heb כַּר
\trl kar
\ref H00103103400020
\heb מַד
\trl mad
\ref H00700501000012
\heb מֶרְכָּב
\trl merkav
\ref H00301500900008
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0451_camel_saddle.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man sitting on a camel saddle|8.0\fig* The saddle was a seat placed on the back of an animal to enable a person to ride. It could also serve as a rack on which baggage was carried. Saddles could take many forms, from specially shaped wood to a simple piece of cloth.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew verb \i chavash\i* always occurs in the context of an animal prepared or being prepared for riding. Where a specific term for “saddle” is lacking, the second clause in \s H00102200300016\s* may be rendered “he prepared his donkey for riding.”
\line \fig |KNW-0452_camel_saddlebags.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Camel with loaded saddle|8.0\fig* \s H00103103400020\s*: The Hebrew word \i kar\i* appears only here, and its exact meaning is uncertain. It is variously rendered “saddle” (\a RSV\a*, \a NIV\a*), “saddlebag” (\a GNT\a*), “the cushion she used as a saddle” (\a CEV\a*), “[camel]bag” (\a REB\a*), “cushion” (\a NJB\a*), and “saddle basket” (\a GECL\a*). From the context it is evident that it was something that Rachel could sit on and that her father would not have thought it strange that she did so. On the other hand, she had hidden some household idols (see \l target="REALIA:4.6.1">4.6.1 Teraphim, household idol\l*) in (or under) this thing, so we may assume that it was more than just a cloth laid over the camel. Camel saddles could be rather elaborate. Sometimes the saddle was an entire large basket or litter in which a person sat. At other times a wooden frame was placed over the camel’s humped back. Over this frame were draped cloths and blankets to cushion the ride and to separate the rider’s legs from the animal’s back. In either of these arrangements, it would not have been difficult for Rachel to find recesses in which to hide a number of small idols. The text does not say that Rachel is sitting on the camel but rather on the camel’s saddle, and it is clear from the context that she is in her tent. When travelers arrived at their camp for the night, it was the custom to remove the saddle and store it in the tent. If it was a wooden frame, then it also served as a place to sit. The wooden frame, shaped to fit over the camel’s back, created a fairly large hollow area as it sat on the floor of the tent. Rachel had evidently hidden the idols under her chair.
\line \fig |WEB-0526_saddle.jpg|col||© Aziz Kingrani (Wikimedia Commons)|Camel saddle|8.0\fig* In \s H00301500900008\s* the Hebrew word \i merkav\i* could refer to a saddle, a cloth, or even the seat of a chariot. In some languages there may be no technical term for “saddle.” In any case, it is better to express the idea generally here, as in \a REB\a*, which renders the whole verse as “Everything on which this person sits when riding will be unclean.”
\line \s H00700501000012\s*: See the discussion on the meaning of the Hebrew word \i mad\i* at \l target="REALIA:5.17">5.17 Carpet, rug\l*.
\line For “saddlebags,” see the comments on the Hebrew word \i mishpthayim\i* at \l target="REALIA:1.2.1">1.2.1 Sheep pen, sheepfold\l*.
