\ref H00103501400032 H00202904000024 H00202904100034 H00203000900022 H00302301300032 H00302301800052 H00302303700038 H00400400700054 H00400601500040 H00400601700044 H00401500500010 H00401500700010 H00401501000012 H00401502400060 H00402800700004 H00402800700030 H00402800800034 H00402800900042 H00402801000020 H00402801400004 H00402801500030 H00402802400042 H00402803100028 H00402900600032 H00402901100036 H00402901600028 H00402901800008 H00402901900030 H00402902100008 H00402902200028 H00402902400006 H00402902500028 H00402902700008 H00402902800028 H00402903000008 H00402903100026 H00402903300008 H00402903400026 H00402903700006 H00402903800028 H00402903900040 H01201601300022 H01201601500094 H01302902100048 H01402903500026 H01901600400014 H02305700600022 H02400701800052 H02401901300060 H02403202900074 H02404401700042 H02404401800028 H02404401900026 H02404401900052 H02404402500076 H02602002800084 H02604501700026 H02900100900008 H02900101300046 H02900201400024
\heb שֶׁמֶר
\trl shemer
\ref H01907500900032 H02302500600034 H02302500600040 H02404801100018 H03600101200044
\grk οἶνος
\trl oinos
\ref G04000901700006 G04000901700034 G04000901700050 G04002703400008 G04100202200008 G04100202200028 G04100202200038 G04100202200050 G04101502300010 G04200101500016 G04200503700008 G04200503700030 G04200503800004 G04200703300022 G04201003400020 G04300200300006 G04300200300022 G04300200900016 G04300201000018 G04300201000040 G04300404600026 G04501402100016 G04900501800008 G05400300800014 G05400502300008 G05600200300018 G06600600600048 G06601400800030 G06601401000012 G06601601900058 G06601700200032 G06601800300008 G06601801300024 G06601901500056 L06700401500012 L06801000500014 L06801101300020 L06801200100040 L06801201300072 L06801202000016 L06801300200040 L06900100700024 L06900401700032 L07000200700002 L07100900900028 L07101900200002 L07103102500004 L07103102500018 L07103102600014 L07103102700006 L07103102700028 L07103102800012 L07103102900006 L07103103100006 L07103200500020 L07103200600020 L07104002000002 L07104900100040 L07600101100024 L07600101500052 L07600102100040 L07600103300038 L07801503900006 L07801503900032 L07900500200020 L07900501000022 L07900504500030 L07900603000028 L08100301000012 L08100301700022 L08100301800010 L08100302300010 L08100302400012 L08100401400024 L08100401600032 L08100403700006 L08100602900016 L08100802000018 L08500201400046 L08500203300008 L08500203800022 L08600801400024
\lat vinum
\ref V08200902400044
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Wine was a fermented drink made from the juice of grapes. The grape harvest season began in the land of Israel around the start of July and went on through the summer. The process of extracting the juice (see \l target="REALIA:1.1.10">1.1.10 Wine press\l*) and fermentation meant that the first wine (the “new wine”) was available in September. Fully fermented wine could be stored for several years, although not as long as is possible today with modern methods of pasteurization and storage. It was common practice to dilute wine with water before drinking it (as much as 50 percent or more). Similarly, wine could also be sweetened with some agent such as honey.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Some people have argued that whenever mention is made of Jesus either making or drinking wine, we must assume that this was only unfermented grape juice. There is no real basis for such a conclusion. Only where “new wine” is mentioned can we assume that this is unfermented grape juice or grape juice in the initial stages of fermentation (see \l target="REALIA:9.1.1">9.1.1 New wine\l*).
\line In a number of languages there is no indigenous term for “wine,” and some expression may simply be borrowed from a dominant language. On the other hand, it is sometimes possible to use a descriptive phrase, for example, “fermented fruit juice.” In some languages the equivalent for “wine” is more specifically “palm wine,” which is a wine made from the sap of certain palm trees. Such a term may also have a more generic meaning and may be applicable to any kind of wine. The term used must be an alcoholic drink (not, for example, simply “grape juice”), otherwise references to its intoxicating power will not make sense.
\line \s H02302700200014\s*: The Hebrew text contains the word \i chemer\i*, meaning “wine.” However, there has probably been a corruption in the final letter of the word, making the proper reading “pleasant” or “delightful.”
\line \s H00100902400010 H00900101400020 H00902503700018\s*: Some translators render the Hebrew word \i yayin\i* in these verses as “drunkenness.”
\line The Hebrew words \i mezeg\i* and \i mesek\i* indicate a mixture and probably refer to wine that was diluted with water. In \s H02200700300016\s* some interpreters and translators understand the meaning to be “spiced wine” (\a GNT\a*, \a GW\a*). Other translations are “mixed wine” (\a NRSV\a*) and “blended wine” (\a NIV\a*).
\line The Hebrew word \i nesek\i* literally indicates a liquid poured out. In practice, it was the pouring out of wine as an offering to God or other gods. It will sometimes be possible to translate it simply “wine.” Usually, however, something like “drink offering” is to be preferred.
\line When juice was pressed from grapes, a certain amount of small solids escaped the filtering process. When the juice stood in containers to ferment into wine, these solids (called in English “dregs” or “lees”) sank to the bottom and even aided in the fermentation process, adding to the quality of the wine. They could be filtered out of the wine before it was served. The Hebrew word for these settled solids is \i shemer\i*. Depending on the context, it can symbolize the quality of the wine (\s H02302500600034\s*), the fact that the wine had not yet been disturbed (\s H02404801100018 H03600101200044\s*), or simply what remains at the very bottom of the container (\s H01907500900020\s*). Common-language translations, especially in those places where winemaking is unfamiliar, avoid a literal rendering of \i shemer\i*. Here are the renderings of \a GNT\a* for the four appearances of \i shemer\i*: “to the last drop” (\s H01907500900020\s*), “the finest wine” (\s H02302500600034\s*), “like wine left to settle undisturbed” (\s H02404801100018\s*), and “who are self-satisfied and confident” (\s H03600101200044\s*).
\line There are a number of passages in the New Testament where translators must be particularly careful in the selection of terms to render “wine”; for example, in \s G04900501800008\s* a literal translation of “do not get drunk with wine” (\a RSV\a*) could be interpreted to mean that it is permissible for people to get drunk on other types of intoxicating drinks. Therefore it may be necessary in some languages to render this clause simply as “do not get drunk.”
\line In \s G04201003400020\s* the second and third clauses are literally “he bandaged his wounds, pouring olive oil and wine over [them].” Here it is important to recognize the medicinal value of oil and wine. In some languages translators have indicated the purpose of such an activity by saying “to cleanse and heal his wounds, he poured wine and oil on them and bandaged them.” It may also be helpful to add a footnote about the antiseptic quality of the wine and the value of the oil in the healing process.
\key 9.1.1
\title New wine
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb עָסִיס
\trl ‘asis
\ref H02200800200026 H02304902600020 H02900100500022 H02900401800022 H03000901300046
\heb תִּירוֹשׁ
\trl tirosh
\ref H00102702800038 H00102703700046 H00401801200014 H00500701300032 H00501101400028 H00501201700020 H00501402300036 H00501800400006 H00502805100030 H00503302800024 H00700901300018 H01201803200026 H01403100500022 H01403202800014 H01600501100040 H01601003800022 H01601004000034 H01601300500050 H01601301200020 H01900400800018 H02000301000012 H02302400700004 H02303601700026 H02306200800044 H02306500800016 H02403101200034 H02800201000026 H02800201100018 H02800202400022 H02800401100010 H02800701400028 H02800900200014 H02900101000018 H02900201900032 H02900202400020 H03300601500028 H03700101100036 H03800901700020
\grk οἶνος, νέος
\trl oinos neos
\ref G04000901700006 G04000901700008 G04100202200008 G04100202200010 G04200503700008 G04200503700010 G04200503800004 L07100901000024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line New wine was newly pressed grape juice, unfermented or in the initial stages of fermentation.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line While the Hebrew words \i ‘asis\i* and \i tirosh\i* may refer to unfermented juice, they sometimes indicate wine in the first stages of fermentation. Some languages, especially in wine-growing areas, have a special word for this drink, which is available for only a short time after the grape harvest. The context may indicate if the beverage intended is fermented or not. Where it is determined that fermented juice is spoken of, translators may simply render \i ‘asis\i* or \i tirosh\i* as “wine,” which \a GNT\a* does in the middle of \s H00700901300018\s*: “I would have to stop producing my wine.”
\key 9.1.2
\title Sweet wine
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַמְתַקִּים
\trl mamthaqim
\ref H01600801000018
\grk γλεῦκος
\trl gleukos
\ref G04400201300012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Sweet wine was wine (see \l target="REALIA:9.1">9.1 Wine\l*) to which a sweetening agent, such as honey, had been added.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H01600801000018\s*: Nehemiah orders the people to “eat choice foods and drink sweet drinks” (\a NJPSV\a*). The “sweet drinks” are understood by the Vulgate to be wine sweetened with honey, which is likely (\a RSV\a* “sweet wine”). Like \a NJPSV\a*, many other translations have simply “sweet drinks” without specifying the type (\a NIV\a*, \a REB\a*).
\line \s G04400201300012\s*: In classical Greek the word \i gleukos\i* could designate new wine, that is, grape juice in the initial stages of fermentation (or even unfermented grape juice). For this reason some translations have rendered it “new wine” (\a RSV\a*). However, the chronology of \s G04400201300012\s* seems to eliminate this possibility. The events described in \s G04400200000000\s* could not have happened later than the middle of the month of June. This is well before grapes are harvested, and therefore there could have been no fermenting juice. It would have to be from wine from a previous harvest. Those who accused the disciples of being drunk would have known this. While there were methods for keeping such wine sweet, it would not have been “new.” Therefore it seems best to translate \i gleukos\i* here as “sweet wine” or even “sweetened wine.” It is possible, and in many languages preferable, to translate the last clause of this verse as “They have been drinking” (\a REB\a*) or “These people are drunk” (\a GNT\a*).
\key 9.1.3
\title Vinegar
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֹמֶץ
\trl chomets
\ref H00400600300012 H00400600300018 H00800201400042 H01906902200020 H02001002600006 H02002502000012
\grk ὄξος
\trl oxos
\ref G04002704800024 G04101503600014 G04202303600016 G04301902900006 G04301902900018 G04301903000010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Vinegar was wine that had fermented to the point of becoming sour. It is supposed that this drink was produced by making the grape juice ferment artificially, for instance, by adding barley or some bacterial agent.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Mixed with water, sour wine or wine vinegar was a popular drink among soldiers and workmen since it was cheaper than wine, and good for quenching thirst. Without water, it would be very strong and intoxicating, and could even cause unconsciousness.
\line “Sour wine” is sometimes rendered “bitter wine,” “sour juice,” or simply “sour drink.”
\key 9.2
\title Strong drink, beer
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סֹבֶא
\trl sove’
\ref H02300102200010 H02800401800004 H03400101000014
\heb שֵׁכָר
\trl shekar
\ref H00301000900006 H00400600300008 H00400600300020 H00402800700032 H00501402600048 H00502900500014 H00701300400020 H00701300700030 H00701301400028 H00900101500030 H01906901300016 H02002000100010 H02003100400034 H02003100600004 H02300501100012 H02300502200022 H02302400900016 H02302800700022 H02302800700038 H02302800700054 H02302900900028 H02305601200012 H03300201100032
\grk σίκερα
\trl sikera
\ref G04200101500020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Beer was an intoxicating fermented drink made from grain. It was usually less strong (that is, had a lower alcholic content) than wine.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Many languages will have a general expression such as “strong drink.” Distilled alcoholic beverages, such as whiskey, gin and vodka, were not known in the ancient world.
\line \s H00301000900006\s*: The Hebrew word translated “wine” by \a RSV\a* indicates a drink made from grapes, and the context makes it clear that fermentation is probably involved. The next Hebrew term, rendered “strong drink” in \a RSV\a*, refers to a fermented drink made from barley. The most common equivalent in many languages is “beer.” But these two terms used together represent any alcoholic beverages, and the prohibition is not limited to two kinds. The translation should make it clear that a general rule is intended. If a language has terms for wine and beer, or for wines of lesser and greater alchoholic content, these may be used here. It is not necessary to have two terms, however, if it is difficult to find two. “All kinds of intoxicating drinks” is another possibility.
\line \s G04200101500020\s*: Even though the Greek word \i sikera\i* may have a generic meaning and thus refer to any type of intoxicating drink, in the New Testament it occurs only here, where it contrasts with wine and refers to intoxicating beverages made from grain. Several translations have “beer” (\a CEV\a*, \a NCV\a*). \a NIV\a* says “other fermented drink,” and \a PV\a* has “any other alcohol.”
\key 9.3
\title Olive oil
