\trl raqiq
\ref H00202900200024 H00202902300022 H00300200400032 H00300701200036 H00300802600040 H00400601500022 H00400601900040 H01302302900026
\heb תֻּפִינִים
\trl tufin
\ref H00300601400018
\grk ἄρτος
\trl artos
\ref G04000400300034 G04000400400016 G04000601100004 G04000700900024 G04001401700022 G04001401900024 G04001401900056 G04001503300020 G04001503400014 G04001503600008 G04001600500018 G04001600700016 G04001600800024 G04001600900014 G04001601000008 G04001601100014 G04001601200022 G04002602600014 G04100603700034 G04100603800012 G04100604100010 G04100604100036 G04100604400012 G04100605200012 G04100800400028 G04100800500012 G04100800600026 G04100801400008 G04100801400018 G04100801600012 G04100801700016 G04100801900008 G04101402200010 G04200400300034 G04200703300016 G04200901300034 G04200901600010 G04201100500044 G04201501700024 G04202201900006 G04202403000022 G04202403500032 G04300600500040 G04300600700014 G04300600900014 G04300601100008 G04300601300022 G04300602300024 G04300602600044 G04302100900028 G04302101300012 G04400204200028 G04400204600026 G04402000700020 G04402001100012 G04402703500012 G04601001600030 G04601001700006 G04601001700030 G04601102300042 G04601102600012 G04601102700012 G04601102800018 G04700901000016 G05300300800006 L06700101700004 L06801000500036 L07001602000022 L07101002700024 L07101200500020 L07101401000010 L07101500300006 L07103302500014 L07600103300030 L08100900200008
\lat panis
\ref V08200101900022 V08200501800010 V08201404300008 V08201501900040 V08201505800034
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Bread was dough made from the flour of various grains, mixed with oil or water, and baked for eating.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Bread,” as the basic, staple food of ancient times, often appears in Scripture with the more general meaning of “food.” So the expression “to eat bread” means “to eat a meal” (see \s H00103702500010 H00104303200058 H00200202000034\s*;). Since the bread was not usually cut with a knife but rather broken or torn with the hands, the expression “to break bread” means “to eat” or “to eat a meal” (see \s H02401600700008 G04400204200028 G04400204600026 G04402000700020\s*).
\line In many passages the word that indicates one unit of bread is simply “bread,” as, for example, in \s G04001401700022\s*, where the disciples say “All we have here are five loaves [literally ‘five breads’]” (\a GNT\a*). In many languages it will be more natural to substitute the word “loaf” for “bread.”
\line The Hebrew word \i chalah\i* refers to bread of higher quality since it was made with more expensive flour, called \i soleth\i* in Hebrew (see \l target="REALIA:9.4.1">9.4.1 Plain flour\l* and \l target="REALIA:9.4.2">9.4.2 Fine flour\l*). In some languages it will be possible to make a distinction between this bread and the bread of lower quality.
\line The Hebrew word \i kawan\i* in \s H02400701800038\s* and \s H02404401900040\s* refers to bread that was intended not as food but as an offering to a pagan goddess. It may have been shaped like the goddess or marked with her image; translations reflect both possibilities. Similarly, in \s H01001300600054 H01001300701000 H01001300800054 H01001300901000 H01001301000040\s* the Hebrew word \i lvivah\i* may indicate a special shape (heart-shaped?). In \s H01001300600054\s* \a CEV\a* renders it “special bread” and adds this footnote: “Or ‘heart-shaped bread’ or ‘dumplings.’ ” Translators are advised to follow this example. The point of the story here is that the “special bread” or “special cake” was something better than average, which could help to revive a sick person or at least cheer him up.
\line The Hebrew word \i raqiq\i* refers to very thin bread, perhaps even crisp. It appears most often connected to the Hebrew word \i matsah\i*, which means “unleavened bread” (see \l target="REALIA:9.4.4">9.4.4 Unleavened bread\l*). In these passages (\s H00202900200010 H00300200400018 H00300701200022 H00400601500010 H00400601900026 H01302302900006\s*), it will be best to translate it as a unit together with the word for “unleavened bread” (see the suggestions at <l target="REALIA:9.4.4">9.4.4 Unleavened bread\l*). In \s H00201603100034\s* the Hebrew word \i tsapichith\i* probably has about the same meaning.
\line \s H00202900200010 H00300701200022 H00300802600022\s* (following comments adapted from \i A Handbook on Leviticus \i*at \s H00300701200022\s*, page 95): These verses mention three types of unleavened bread (\a RSV\a* “unleavened cakes mixed with oil, unleavened wafers spread with oil, and cakes of fine flour well mixed with oil” in \s H00300701200022\s*) to accompany animal sacrifices: (1) The first type was a perforated loaf made with flour mixed with oil but without yeast. (2) The second type was a kind of thin, round bread also made without yeast, but on which olive oil was spread. It was similar to biscuits or possibly pancakes. It is mistakenly called “wafers” in \a RSV\a* and \a KJV\a*. Neither should it be translated “cakes,” which will be misleading in most languages. General terms should be used for these first two types of bread, as long as both terms indicate that they are made without yeast. (3) There is some question about exactly what is meant by the third kind of bread. It was apparently to be similar to the first type, perhaps pierced or perforated, but there is no mention of its being made without yeast and no indication that it was actually baked. This has led some commentators to assume that it was merely a kind of dough made of choice flour and oil. However, \a GNT\a* seems to understand the text to imply both that it was unleavened and that it was baked. Since David shared such loaves with people (\s H01000601900038\s*), it seems best to assume they were baked. And although “unleavened” is not explicitly mentioned for the third type, the contrast with \s H00300701301000\s* probably indicates that they were made without yeast. Translators will need to find three different words or descriptive phrases for these three types of unleavened bread.
\line \s H00300601400016\s*: The Hebrew word \i tufin\i*, which is translated “baked” in \a RSV\a* and some other English versions, is difficult and uncertain. A number of other translations and commentaries have understood the word to mean “broken” (\a NIV\a*, \a NAB\a*) or “crumbled” (\a GNT\a*, \a REB\a*). Still others, following the Septuagint, see it as referring to a kind of pastry (\a NJB\a*, \a TOB\a*). Translators should probably look for an equivalent to the idea of breaking or crumbling into small pieces. But it may be advisable to add a footnote explaining the uncertainty concerning this term and the different possible translations of it.
\line The Greek word \i artos\i* refers to a relatively small and generally round loaf of bread. It was considerably smaller than typical present-day loaves of bread and thus more like “rolls” or “buns.”
\key 9.4.1
\title Plain flour
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קֶמַח
\trl qemach
\ref H00400501500036 H00700601900020 H00900102400026 H00902802400032 H01001702800024 H01100500200028 H01101701200028 H01101701400018 H01101701600006 H01200404100010 H01301204100060 H02304700200010 H02800800700026
\grk ἄλευρον
\trl aleuron
\ref G04001303300034 G04201302100018
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Flour was the product of grinding kernels of grain. The grains most commonly used were wheat or barley. Flour was the main ingredient of bread, which was the staple food in ancient times (see \l target="REALIA:9.4">9.4 Bread\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line In Hebrew there are two words that refer to ground grain. The first word \i soleth\i* refers to a kind of semolina or coarser wheat flour. It is a product that is less finely ground than the flour referred to by the second word \i qemach\i*. However, the first type was considered a more sumptuous kind of flour, used primarily in ritual offerings. The second type, on the other hand, was just ordinary flour (made from barley or wheat) and was rarely used in offerings to God. In translation the primary focus should not be on the fineness of the grinding, but on the high quality of the one type of flour as opposed to the commonness of the other type. If the translator has trouble finding corresponding terminology, it is possible to use an ordinary word for the common flour or meal and the same word qualified by “best” or “finest” for the more luxurious product (compare \a NJPSV\a* “choice flour”). In some languages “wheat flour” is rendered “ground wheat” or “powdered wheat.”
\key 9.4.2
\title Fine flour
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סֹלֶת, קֶמַח
\trl soleth, qemach soleth
\ref H00101800600026 H00101800600028 H00202900200036 H00202904000006 H00300200100018 H00300200200030 H00300200400016 H00300200500016 H00300200700012 H00300501100046 H00300600800014 H00300601300034 H00300701200050 H00301401000040 H00301402100042 H00302301300010 H00302301700018 H00302400500006 H00400501500036 H00400601500008 H00400701300042 H00400701900044 H00400702500040 H00400703100040 H00400703700040 H00400704300040 H00400704900040 H00400705500040 H00400706100040 H00400706700040 H00400707300040 H00400707900040 H00400800800016 H00401500400018 H00401500600014 H00401500900016 H00402800500010 H00402800900028 H00402801200008 H00402801200036 H00402801300008 H00402802000006 H00402802800006 H00402900300006 H00402900900006 H00402901400006 H00700601900020 H00900102400026 H00902802400032 H01001702800024 H01100500200020 H01100500200028 H01101701200028 H01101701400018 H01101701600006 H01200404100010 H01200700100030 H01200701600026 H01200701800038 H01300902900032 H01301204100060 H01302302900016 H02304700200010 H02601601300028 H02601601900012 H02604601400046 H02800800700026
\grk σεμίδαλις
\trl semidalis
\ref G06601801300032 L07103500200008 L07103801100010 L07103902600030 L07600100300030 L07800100800038
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Fine flour was a fine grade of wheat flour.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line See \l target="REALIA:9.4.1">9.4.1 Plain flour\l*. In some languages “fine flour” is best rendered “expensive flour.”
\key 9.4.3
\title Loaf
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כִּכָּר
\trl kikar
\ref H00202902300004 H00700800500016 H00900203600032 H00901000300060 H01301600300028 H02000602600012 H02403702100034
\heb צְלִיל
\trl tslil
\ref H00700701300036
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0453_bread_flat.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Loaves of flat bread|9.0\fig* The loaf was a unit of bread. The normal loaf was round and flat, about the size of a man’s hand with fingers spread. However, sizes and shapes could vary widely. It has been suggested that there were three kinds of loaves: a small loaf like a modern roll or biscuit; a big, round loaf; and a flat, thin bread that was used to scoop up food. Generally, bread made of wheat was eaten by richer people, while bread made of barley was the food of the poor (\s H00700701300036\s*; \s G04300600700014\s*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0527_bread_tandir.jpg|col||© jeffreyw (Wikimedia Commons)|Loaves of flat bread|9.0\fig* Most languages that have a word for bread will also have a word for “loaf,” that is, an individual unit of bread. In many places in Scripture, the word that indicates one unit of bread is simply “bread,” so it may be rendered “loaf” in these places (see the discussion under \l target="REALIA:9.4">9.4 Bread\l*).
\line \s H00700701300036\s*: The important characteristic of the barley loaf in this verse is that it rolls down the hill. Where a language distinguishes between types of loaves according to shape, a word for a round loaf would be appropriate here.
\line Consecrated bread, bread of the presence, showbread: See \l target="REALIA:4.3.5.1">4.3.5.1 Consecrated bread, bread of the presence, showbread\l*.
\key 9.4.4
\title Unleavened bread
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מַצָּה
\trl matsah
\ref H00101900300034 H00201200800028 H00201201500006 H00201201700010 H00201201800030 H00201202000018 H00201203900022 H00201300600008 H00201300700002 H00202301500008 H00202301500018 H00202900200006 H00202900200012 H00202900200026 H00202902300032 H00203401800008 H00203401800018 H00300200400020 H00300200400034 H00300200500026 H00300600900018 H00300701200024 H00300701200038 H00300800200062 H00300802600010 H00300802600024 H00301001200052 H00302300600026 H00302300600036 H00400601500006 H00400601500024 H00400601700026 H00400601900028 H00400601900042 H00400901100032 H00402801700028 H00501600300018 H00501600800008 H00501601600042 H00600501100022 H00700601900022 H00700602000028 H00700602100040 H00700602100072 H00902802400042 H01202300900030 H01302302900030 H01400801300062 H01403001300022 H01403002100024 H01403501700038 H01500602200008 H02001301000010 H02001701900008 H02305800400010 H02604502100036
\grk ἄζυμος
\trl azumos
\ref G04002601700010 G04101400100014 G04101401200012 G04202200100012 G04202200700012 G04401200300034 G04402000600016 G04600500700022 G04600500800030 L08100101100006 L08100101700036 L08100701400012
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0528_bread_unleavened.jpg|col||© Edsel Little (Wikimedia Commons)|Unleavened bread|9.0\fig* Unleavened bread was a thin cracker-like bread resulting from baking the dough quickly before fermentation could cause it to rise.
\line ———
\cont \u Usage:\u*
\line When the people of Israel left Egypt in a hurry, they baked their bread quickly before it had time to rise. Such bread became a symbol of their redemption from Egypt and was included as a special feature of the Feast of Passover, which celebrated that redemption. It was also included in some of the sacrificial offerings.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The phrase “unleavened bread” may be rendered “bread made without yeast” or “bread that does not rise.” Some languages will have to say “bread lacking that which causes it to rise.”
\line Except for \s G04600500700022 G04600500800030\s*, in which the Greek word \i azumos\i* occurs in a highly figurative passage referring to pure and true life, this term is used exclusively in the New Testament in reference to the Feast of Unleavened Bread.
\key 9.5
\title Blocks of pressed dried fruit
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אָשִׁישׁ, אֲשִׁישָׁה
\trl ’ashish, ’ashishah
\ref H01000601900052 H01301600300038 H02200200500008 H02301600700018 H02800300100054
\heb דְּבֵלָה
\trl dvelah
\ref H00902501800054 H00903001200010 H01202000700010 H01301204100062 H02303802100010
\grk παλάθη
\trl palathē
\ref L06801000500032
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The fruit of the fig tree was dried in the sun and then pressed together in blocks for storage and for transporting. The same was done with raisins, that is, dried grapes. For blocks of dried fruit used medicinally, see \l target="REALIA:1.15.2">1.15.2 Poultice, fig cake\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line For the fig tree and grapevine, see \l target="FLORA:2.6">Fig\l* and \l target="FLORA:2.12">Vine\l* respectively. In \s H00902501800054\s* \a GW\a* has “fig cakes,” but this rendering is likely to give the misimpression that these were baked cakes with figs in them. Most translations consulted also use the word “cakes” but in a phrase like “cakes of pressed figs” (\a NIV\a*), which is slightly better. However, even here the modern reader is most likely to understand “cake” as a baked food. \a GECL\a* avoids this problem with “portions of dried figs,” while \a CEV\a* has “handfuls of dried figs.” It will often be possible (and preferable) to say “lumps of pressed figs” or “blocks of dried figs.” Some languages will have a specific word for such blocks of pressed dried fruit.
\line In \s H00903001200010\s* \a RSV\a* has “a piece of a cake of figs,” but \a GNT\a* is better with “some dried figs.”
\key 9.6
\title Soup, stew
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מָרַק
\trl maraq
\ref H00700601900040 H00700602000050 H02306500400036
\heb מֶרְקָחָה
\trl merqachah
\ref H02602401000026
\heb נָזִיד
\trl nazid
\ref H00102502900008 H00102503400016 H01200403800060 H01200403900056 H01200404000026 H03700201200038
\grk ἕψεμα
\trl hepsēma
\ref L07600103300024
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Soup was a meal made by boiling vegetables and/or meat in water.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i maraq\i* refers to a stew made with meat, while the word \i nazid\i* indicates a stew made with vegetables or legumes. Some languages will have a distinct word for each one.
\key 9.7
\title Yogurt, curds
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֶמְאָה
\trl chem’ah
\ref H00101800800006 H00503201400002 H00700502500018 H01001702900008 H01802001700018 H01905502200004 H02003003300010 H02300701500002 H02300702200016 H02300702200020
\heb חֵמָה
\trl chemah
\ref H01802900600010
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Yogurt is a semisolid food created when milk has been curdled by bacteria.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Translations of the Hebrew word \i chem’ah\i* differ considerably. \a GNT\a* ignores the souring process and translates it as “milk” in \s H02300701500002\s*, while \a NCV\a* has “milk curds,” which is probably not well understood by its target audience. \a CEV\a* “yogurt” is better.
\c 10
\key 10
\title Personal
\index \l target="REALIA:10.1">10.1 Bag, sack, money bag, purse\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:10.2">10.2 Seal, signet ring, ring\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:10.3">10.3 Handkerchief, cloth\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:10.4">10.4 Towel\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:10.5">10.5 Jewelry, ornaments\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:10.6">10.6 Cosmetics\l*
\key 10.1
\title Bag, sack, money bag, purse
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַמְתַּחַת
\trl ’amtachath
\ref H00104202700048 H00104202800022 H00104301200030 H00104301800036 H00104302100022 H00104302100036 H00104302200032 H00104302300030 H00104400100022 H00104400100050 H00104400200020 H00104400800014 H00104401100014 H00104401100024 H00104401200034
\heb חָרִיט
\trl charit
\ref H01200502300032 H02300302200022
\heb כִּיס
\trl kis
\ref H00502501300010 H02000101400010 H02001601100020 H02304600600010 H03300601100016
\heb כְּלִי
\trl kli
\ref H00104202500014 H00900900700040
\heb צִקְלוֹן
\trl tsiqalon
\ref H01200404200040
\heb צְרוֹר
\trl tsror
\ref H00104203500018 H00104203500032 H00902502900034 H01801401700006 H02000702000002 H02200101300002 H03700100600054
\heb שַׂק
\trl saq
\ref H00104202500030 H00104202700012 H00104203500010 H00104203500024 H00301103200038 H00600900400026
\grk βαλλάντιον
\trl ballantion
\ref G04201000400006 G04201203300020 G04202203500016 G04202203600016 L06700101400030 L06700800200036
\grk ζώνη
\trl zōnē
\ref G04001000900020 G04100600800040
\grk θυλάκιον
\trl thulakion
\ref L06700900500034
\grk μαρσίππιον
\trl marsippion
\ref L07101803300024
\grk πήρα
\trl pēra
\ref G04001001000004 G04100600800032 G04200900300026 G04201000400010 G04202203500020 G04202203600024 L06801000500024 L06801301000012 L06801301500014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0454_carrying_bag.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Man carrying a bag|10.0\fig* The bag was a receptacle, made of leather or cloth, used to carry possessions, including money. See also \l target="REALIA:1.2.5">1.2.5 Shepherd’s bag/pouch\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Generally, the words listed above carry a range of usages similar to that of the English word “bag.” These words refer to bags that can vary in size, in material, and in quality. Thus they indicate sacks for carrying grain but also handbags carried by women. Often a generic word for a bag made of pliable material such as cloth or leather will suffice. Translators should, of course, avoid a word that specifically indicates a bag made of plastic or other modern synthetic material. The context will usually help the translator choose between specialized terms, where such exist; for example, the Hebrew word \i charitim\i* in \s H01200502300032\s* may be rendered “bags” or even “sacks,” while the same word in \s H02300302200022\s* is better translated “purses” or “handbags.”
\line In \s H00104200000000\s* – \s H00104400000000\s* the Hebrew word \i ’amtachath\i* indicates a large bag for carrying grain.
\line \s H00502501300010 H02001601100020 H03300601100016\s*: In these verses the Hebrew word \i kis\i* refers to a bag in which a merchant carried weights. The point of these verses is that business dealings must always be honest, and the fact that the weights were kept in a bag is insignificant. For this reason \a GNT\a* renders \s H00502501300010\s* (literally “You shall not have in your bag a stone and a stone, large and small”) as “Do not cheat when you use weights [and measures].” The same approach is taken for the other two references. It is a good model.
\line In some passages it will be possible to replace the word “purse” with its contents, “money.” The second line of \s H02000101400010\s* is rendered by \a GECL\a* in a similar way, where it has “We will share the booty.” \a GNT\a* says “we’ll all share what we steal.”
\line The Hebrew word \i tsror\i* may usually be understood as “bundle,” that is, a wrapping prepared for the occasion and not so much a ready container or bag.
\line The Greek word \i zōnē\i* in \s G04001000900020\s* and \s G04100600800040\s* (\a RSV\a* “belts”) refers to the place where a man usually carried his money. \a GNT\a* “pockets” provides a cultural equivalent, and so does \a NJB\a* with “purses.” \a NAB\a* retains “belts,” while Brc says “money-belts.” Some translators will use a general expression, such as “money carriers” or “things where you carry your money.” However, more often this object is dropped altogether; for example, the last clause of \s G04001000901000\s* may be rendered “carry no money with you.”
\line \s G04001001000004 G04100600800040 G04200900300026\s*: In these verses the Greek word \i pēra\i* is translated many different ways: “beggar’s bag (\a GNT\a*), “beggar’s knapsack” (Brc), “haversack” (\a NJB\a*), “pack” (\a REB\a*), “traveling bag” (\a NAB\a*), “knapsack” (\a Phps\a*), “bag” (\a RSV\a*, \a AT\a*), and “wallet” (\a Mft\a*). The problem is that this word in the New Testament may refer in general to any sort of bag that a traveler may put his things in or it may have the specialized sense of a bag carried by a beggar. As the survey of translations suggests, there is no agreement among scholars. Therefore translators can say either “bag for travelers” or “bag carried by beggars.” Obviously the apostles were to carry nothing with them when they went out.
\key 10.2
\title Seal, signet ring, ring
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חתם, חוֹתָם, חוֹתֶמֶת
\trl chatham, chotham, chothemeth
\ref H00103801800022 H00103802500048 H00202801100010 H00202802100028 H00202803600020 H00203900600024 H00203901400028 H00203903000030 H00503203400012 H01102100800016 H01102100800020 H01601000100026 H01601000200008 H01700301200120 H01700800800034 H01700800800062 H01700801000018 H01803801400008 H01804100700010 H02200800600008 H02200800600018 H02300801600006 H02302901100024 H02302901100060 H02402202400026 H02403201000014 H02403201100018 H02403201400044 H02403204400024 H02602801200032 H02701200400016 H02701200900016 H03700202300040
\arm עִזְקָה
\trl ‘izqah
\ref A02700601800022
\heb טַבַּעַת
\trl taba‘ath
\ref H00104104200010 H00203502200032 H00403105000028 H01700301000012 H01700301200124 H01700800200012 H01700800800038 H01700800800066 H01700801000022 H02300302100004
\grk δακτύλιος
\trl daktulios
\ref G04201502200038 L06700102200036 L06801000400034 L07600101400064 L07600101400070 L07700601500024
\grk σφραγίς, σφραγίζω, κατασφραγίζω
\trl sfragis, sfragizō (verb), katasfragizō (verb)
\ref G04002706600014 G04300303300012 G04300602700052 G04500401100010 G04600900200024 G04700102200006 G04900101300038 G04900403000024 G05500201900020 G06600500100032 G06600500100034 G06600500200034 G06600500500056 G06600500900028 G06600600100022 G06600600300010 G06600600500010 G06600600700010 G06600600900012 G06600601200012 G06600700200020 G06600700300026 G06600700400012 G06600700400022 G06600700500012 G06600700800032 G06600800100010 G06600900400050 G06601000400032 G06602000300020 G06602201000010
\grk χρυσοδακτύλιος
\trl chrusodaktulios
\ref G05900200200016
\lat consigno (verb)
\ref V08200600500030
\lat signaculum
\ref V08200710400046 V08201002300010
\lat signo (verb)
\ref V08200203800014 V08200805300004
\lat supersignabitur
\ref V08200602000006
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |KNW-0160_signet_ring.png|col||Horace Knowles © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1954, 1967, 1972|Signet ring on finger|10.0\fig* The seal, or signet, was an engraved object used to make a mark denoting ownership, approval, or closure of something. It was an important object in common use among persons of rank. It was a symbol of ownership and was used to seal contracts and other secret or confidential documents, and even as a mark of personal identification (see \s H00103801801000\s*). It was either round or (more frequently) oval and was pressed onto fresh clay before it was fired, or onto hot wax, which was left to cool showing its imprint. It could be applied to a document or letter or the object to be closed. The seal itself was engraved with a reverse image, so that the impression would come out correctly. It sometimes carried some figure or symbol, in addition to the owner’s occupation, office, or status. The seal was made from some precious stone and was normally inseparable from its owner, who wore it either mounted in a ring or attached to a cord around the neck.
\line \fig |WEB-0529_signet_ring.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Signet ring|10.0\fig* Important or confidential letters or legal documents that had to be kept private were sealed. Those written on papyrus (and later on vellum and parchment) were rolled and tied, and a seal was affixed to the knot. The seal had to be broken before the scroll could be unrolled. When the writing was on a clay tablet or potsherd, it was encased in a sort of clay envelope. If the writing was a contract or other legal document, a summary of its contents was sometimes inscribed on the envelope. A separate copy of a document might be kept in another place (see \s H02403201401000\s*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \fig |UBS-0036_seal_cord.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Seal on a cord|10.0\fig* In some languages the closest equivalent to “seal” or “signet” is the mark made by the seal, for example, “symbol of his name” or “mark of his ownership,” or a translator may use a term for “rubber stamp,” as long as it does not explicitly refer to rubber or to ink. In some passages translators may employ a phrase such as “instrument by which a mark is made.”
\line The Hebrew word \i taba‘ath\i* comes from a root meaning “to stamp an impression.” This indicates that its original purpose was to serve as a signet as described above. However, rings were also worn as decorative jewelry, and such rings are probably referred to in \s H00203502200032\s* and \s H00403105000028\s*. While finger rings are widely known, signet rings are less well known. Thus, it may be necessary to expand the expression for it; for example, \a NCV\a* expands the literal phrase “his ring” in \s H00104104200010\s* to “his ring with the royal seal on it.” \a GNT\a* says “the ring engraved with the royal seal,” and \a SPCL\a* has “the ring which held his official seal.” In \s H01700301000012\s* \a GNT\a* is even more expansive with “his ring, which was used to stamp proclamations and make them official.” However, some translators may prefer to place such a long explanation in a footnote.
\line \s G04002706600014\s*: No one is quite certain what is meant by the act of “sealing the tomb” in this verse. One scholar has suggested that a rope was drawn over the stone and then a seal attached to it. Others believe that the sealing was done by means of filling the space between the face of the rock and the stone used for a door with soft clay, and then stamping on the seal of the Jewish authorities. Since sealing is not known in all societies, a possible translation for the end of this verse is “they put a mark on the stone to know if it was moved” or “they put their mark on the stone so no one would move it.”
\key 10.3
\title Handkerchief, cloth
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk σουδάριον
\trl soudarion
\ref G04201902000030 G04301104400030 G04302000700006 G04401901200022
\grk κειρία
\trl keiria
\ref G04301104400020
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line The handkerchief was a small, rectangular piece of cloth used for wiping perspiration from the face. It was also sometimes tied around the forehead by workmen to keep the sweat from running into the eyes and face.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line For all of the above references, translators may use a generic word or phrase, such as “piece of cloth.” Some languages will have a special word for a cloth for wiping the face. This may be used in \s G04201902000030\s* and \s G04401901200022\s*.
\line \s G04301104400030 G04302000700006\s*: The Greek word \i soudarion\i* in these verses refers to cloths used to cover or wrap the face of a person who was being buried. This may have been done especially in the case of poor people. Some societies may have a special word for such a piece of cloth or other material. \s G04301104400030\s* says Lazarus had his hands and feet bound with “strips of linen cloth” (\i keiria\i* in Greek). The length and width of these cloth strips is not known. \a NIV\a* provides a good model for translation with “strips of linen.”
\line See also the discussion on the Hebrew word \i sdinim\i* in \s H02300302300012\s* under \l target="REALIA:10.5">10.5 Jewelry, ornaments\l*.
\key 10.4
\title Towel
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk λέντιον
\trl lention
\ref G04301300400022 G04301300500034
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The towel was a piece of cloth used primarily for drying. It would most likely have been made of cotton or linen (see \l target="REALIA:1.5.3.7">1.5.3.7 Linen\l*).
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The particular piece of cloth in \s G04301300400022 G04301300500034\s* was large enough for Jesus to wrap around himself. The act of washing feet was normally performed by a servant or a slave. Such servants often performed their services dressed only in a loincloth (see \l target="REALIA:6.4">6.4 Loincloth\l*). While it may be good to explain this fact in a footnote, the translation itself will only be able to indicate it if there is a similar piece of clothing used by servants.
\key 10.5
\title Jewelry, ornaments
\index \l target="REALIA:10.5.1">10.5.1 Earring, nose ring\l*
