\ref G06000300300028 L06801000400078 L07100603000002 L07102102100004
\grk χρυσίον
\trl chrusion
\ref G05400200900034 G06000300300020 G06601700400022 G06601801600036 L07300100900024
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0530_assorted_jewelry.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Assorted jewelry|10.0\fig* Jewelry was personal ornamentation worn on various parts of the body, often made with precious metals and gems. Items of jewelry could be worn on various parts of the head and face, around the neck, on all parts of the arms and fingers, and on the ankles. While jewelry was worn mostly by women, there were also certain items that were worn by men.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line “Jewelry” may be rendered “things to make someone look beautiful” or “things with which someone tries to appear attractive.” “Gold jewelry” may be referred to as “pretty things made out of gold.”
\line The Hebrew word \i kli\i* is actually a general term meaning “object” or “thing.” In the references above, a partial list is given of places where \i kli\i* is usually accompanied by a modifier such as “gold” or “ornamental.” These occurrences may be taken as referring to jewelry in a generic sense and translated simply as “jewels” or “valuable objects.”
\line \s G06601700400022 G06601801600036\s*: Instead of saying that the woman was “covered with gold ornaments, precious stones, and pearls” (\s G06601700400022\s* in \a GNT\a*), it may be far more appropriate to say “she wore many gold ornaments, precious stones, and pearls” or “many gold ornaments, precious stones, and pearls were fastened to her clothes.” The Greek text in these two passages has no word for “jewelry” but only mentions the materials from which the jewelry was made. \a CEV\a* may serve as a good model: “she wore jewelry made of gold, precious stones, and pearls.”
\line \s H02300301801000-H02300302301000\s*
\line The list in these verses contains over 20 items, including jewelry and clothing. Many of the items occur only once in Scripture, and their exact meaning is unclear. In these verses some translations do not try to find separate words for each item of jewelry but rather use a general term for jewelry indicating where it is worn; for example, \a CEV\a* has “When that day comes, I will take away from those women all the fine jewelry they wear on their ankles, heads, necks, ears, arms, noses, fingers, and on their clothes. I will remove their veils, their belts, their perfume, their magic charms, their royal robes, and all their fancy dresses, hats, and purses.”
\line There is an obvious connection to foreign cults in the origin of some of the jewelry. The “sun” and “moon” (referred to by the Hebrew words rendered “headbands” and “crescents” by \a RSV\a* in verse 18) were worshiped in Semitic religions, and the “amulets” of verse 20 probably had their origin in a magical or religious function. However, just as this foreign religious connection was not specifically condemned in \s H02300300201000 H02300300301000\s*, so it is not part of the focus here. The focus is on the false sense of power and pride that is going to be inverted because it is based on injustice.
\line The following comment by Watts in his commentary on Isaiah is worth quoting. “It is impossible now to gain a clear picture of the articles named . . . Fashion then as now changes rapidly and tends to name its articles in ways that defy rational definition. . . . Hartmann . . . has shown that \a LXX\a* [the Septuagint] simply made a list of such articles from his own period to serve as a translation which many a translator has done in similar circumstances since then” (page 46).
\line The following discussion goes through the list item by item. Words in brackets are the translation of \a NRSV\a* followed by that of \a GNT\a* for each Hebrew word.
\cont \u Verse 18\u*
\line \i ‘Akasim\i* (“anklets,” “ornaments they wear on their ankles”): The “anklets” can refer to little chains or ornaments attached to shoes, legs, or ankles. A related Hebrew verb (translated “tinkling”) was used in \s H02300301600048\s*. See \l target="REALIA:10.5.2">10.5.2 Bracelet, armlet, anklet\l* below.
\line \i Shvisim\i* (“headbands,” “[ornaments] on their heads”) and \i saharonim\i* (“crescents,” “[ornaments] on their necks”): The “headbands,” as the word is used in later Hebrew, were made of gold or wool thread and hung from a headpiece worn on top of the head. However, many scholars think that the word applies to sun-shaped, disk ornaments (that is, “little suns, sunettes”) and is intended as a pair with the moon-shaped ornaments, the “crescents.” This later interpretation is preferable. \a FRCL\a* has “headbands” for the first word, but with a footnote saying “Or \i jewels in the shape of the sun\i*.” For “crescents,” \a NCV\a* has “necklaces shaped like the moon.” \a GECL\a* has “suns and half-moons, which they wear on the neck.” Another possible rendering is “little pendants/jewels/ornaments [shaped like/in the shape of] the sun and half-moon.” We do not know where “little suns and half-moon ornaments” were hung since they could conceivably be added to footwear, hands, bracelets, necklaces, headgear, clothing, or to all of these places. Archaeologists have found necklaces with these ornaments. If they are translated as items hanging on necklaces then they should not be tightly grouped with “anklets.”
\cont \u Verse 19\u*
\line \i Ntifoth\i* (“pendants,” combined by \a GNT\a* with saharonim in verse 18): The “pendants” probably refer to tear-drop or drip-shaped ornaments since the root word in Hebrew is used with liquids like honey and wine, and is not a general word for “hanging.” \a TOB\a* has a note saying “Literally \i drops\i*, most likely pearls.” These “pendants” could be worn on a necklace made with pretty stones or glass. \a FRCL\a* and \a NCV\a* use “earrings.”
\line \i Sheroth\i* (“bracelets,” “[ornaments] on their wrists”) For this Hebrew word, “bracelets” is not recommended as a translation. In later Hebrew, the word meant a neck-strap used for domesticated animals. It may be related to a word for “chain” and probably means “necklace” or “neck cord” here. If so, it would make a fitting pair with the bead-droplets immediately before it. Thus “beads and necklaces” or “droplets and neck cords” is preferred for the first two words in this verse.
\line \i R‘aloth\i* (“scarfs,” “veils”): The last item in this verse is less problematic. The Hebrew word \i r‘aloth\i* refers to cloth used to cover the face. \a NCV\a* and \a GNT\a* have “veils.” See \l target="REALIA:6.12">6.12 Veil\l*.
\cont \u Verse 20\u*
\line \i P’erim\i* (“headdresses,” “hats”): The word “headdresses” is a close approximation in English to the Hebrew word here. The word probably refers to head decorations, perhaps often with a flower motif, either as a hat, turban, or crown. \a NCV\a* has “scarves,” and \a REB\a* says “headbands.” General words for (fancy) hats or special sashes wrapped as headgear by women around their heads is good here, but note the “turbans” in verse 23. \a NJB\a* has “diadems,” the ornamental head cover worn by queens and princesses. See also \l target="REALIA:6.6">6.6 Waistband, sash, belt\l*.
\line \i Ts‘adoth\i* (“armlets,” combined by \a GNT\a* with the next three items as “the magic charms they wear on their arms and at their waists”): The “armlets,” which were metal bands of decoration worn on the arm, are known from \s H01000101000042\s* (see \l target="REALIA:10.5.2">10.5.2 Bracelet, armlet, anklet\l* below). These may have signaled persons belonging to royalty or the ruling class, according to some interpretations based on ancient pictures from the Assyrian court. The root of the Hebrew word \i ts‘adoth\i* refers to a “step, pace,” so some scholars have thought that these ornaments were originally anklets (\a NCV\a* “ankle chains”; similarly \a NJB\a*). However, “armlets” is recommended as less speculative than “anklets.” In Isaiah’s description here, they are women’s ornaments. \a FRCL\a* has “little chains.”
\line \i Qishurim\i* (“sashes”): The “sashes,” or girdles, refer to bindings used on outer garments. They could be decorated with beads. \a NCV\a* opts for a longer descriptive phrase with “cloth belts worn around their waists.” \a REB\a* has “necklaces.” (It may be worth mentioning that a translator should never list the same item twice within one inventory!) see also \l target="REALIA:6.6">6.6 Waistband, sash, belt\l*.
\line \i Batey nefesh\i* (“perfume boxes”): The Hebrew here is literally “life houses” and may refer to small cylinders that could hold written incantations. \a TOB\a* explains that they were to provide a magic protection to those wearing them, and gives \s H00902502901000\s* as a possible reference. This interpretation is recommended, and the translator should use “talismans” (\a NJPSV\a*) as a model, or follow the \a GNT\a*. \a FRCL\a* has a word that could be translated “magic medicine.” This item will form a semantic pair with the next one.
\line \i Lchashim\i* (“amulets”): The Hebrew here is literally “whispered charms” and may refer to any kind of little article that is thought to carry magic power. \a FRCL\a* has “good-luck charm.” The purpose of mentioning these items is not to condemn pagan magic directly but to expose the pride that is placed on wealth and power. So these amulets signify amoral, wealthy power.
\cont \u Verse 21\u*
\line \i Taba‘oth\i* (“signet rings,” “rings they wear on their fingers”): As the renderings of \a NRSV\a* and \a GNT\a* indicate, it is possible to understand these rings either as signet rings (\a NIV\a*, \a REB\a*, \a NJPSV\a*, \a NCV\a*) or simply as decorative jewelry (\a GECL\a*, \a SPCL\a*, \a NASB\a*, \a NJB\a*); see the discussion under \l target="REALIA:10.2">10.2 Seal, signet ring, ring\l*. The choice of the translator will be determined by considering Isaiah’s intended audience here, which is “the daughters of Zion” (\s H02300301600048\s*). Since it is unlikely that women wore “signet rings,” with the implication that they wielded authority, then “rings” or “finger rings” is the better rendering.
\line \i Nizmey ’af\i* (“nose rings,” “[rings] in their noses”): “Nose rings” are an ornament that seems to be associated with women (\s H00102404700044\s*; \s H02601601200006\s*; \s H02800201501000\s*). Men may have worn similar rings in their ears (\s H00103500401000\s*). Some of these “nose rings” and earrings were associated with pagan cults (\s H00103500201000 H00103500301000 H00103500401000\s*). In some cultures for women to wear “nose rings” would appear to be a strange custom. If a literal translation would cause too much of a distraction, a translator may generalize and speak of jewelry worn on the head as opposed to that worn elsewhere on the body. See \l target="REALIA:10.5.1">10.5.1 Earring, nose ring\l* below.
\cont \u Verse 22\u*
\line \i Machalatsoth\i* (“festal robes,” “fine robes”): The meaning of this Hebrew word is uncertain. It may be connected with the word for “waist.” Perhaps these garments were fine coats with sleeves. Other possible meanings are “skirts,” “slips,” “underwear,” and “loincloths” (suggested by Sheffer, page 546). However, these last meanings do not fit as well with the next two words. “Fancy coats” may be the most probable meaning here. \a REB\a* has “fine dresses” and \a NCV\a* “fine robes.” \a NJB\a* “party dresses” is an attempt to find a modern equivalent. See also \l target="REALIA:6.2">6.2 Outer garment, cloak, mantle, robe\l*.
\line \i Ma‘atafoth\i* (“mantles,” “gowns”): The “mantles” were probably outer garments that could be wrapped around the shoulders and over the head. Perhaps they were made of a heavier material than the next item. This is the only place where the word occurs in the Hebrew Bible. \a FRCL\a* has “capes.”
\line \i Mitpachoth\i* (“cloaks,” “cloaks”): The “cloaks” appear to be a specific covering worn by women. This Hebrew word also occurs in \s H00800301500010\s*. Women were able to cover their heads and shoulders with these garments. \a NJPSV\a* gives a good model for translating this word in English with “shawls,” which is a covering normally used by women. They were sometimes used for carrying possessions, as in the Ruth example. See also \l target="REALIA:6.2">6.2 Outer garment, cloak, mantle, robe\l*.
\line \i Charitim\i* (“handbags, purses”): The last item in this verse is slightly different from the garments mentioned here. The “handbags” were bags used for carrying money or other small items. Perhaps these “purses” were grouped with shawls because both could be used for carrying things. See \l target="REALIA:10.1">10.1 Bag, sack, money bag, purse\l*.
\cont \u Verse 23\u*
\line \i Gilyonim\i* (“garments of gauze,” “revealing garments”): This Hebrew word probably refers to a thin, fine piece of cloth that can be seen through, so \a GNT\a* has “\i revealing\i* garments.” Some scholars have suggested that the word refers to “mirrors” (\a NCV\a*, \a TOB\a*) that could be carried in the purses of the previous verse. However, “fine cloth” is more probable.
\line \i Sdinim\i* (“linen garments,” “linen handkerchiefs”): The “linen garments” were sheets of linen. They could be used to sit or recline on, or as curtains, or as clothing to wrap oneself in (“wrapper”). \a FRCL\a* has “fine blouses.” “Linen handkerchiefs” is another possibility if it can be understood as a piece of clothing. See also \l target="REALIA:6.3">6.3 Shirt, tunic\l*.
\line \i Tsnifoth\i* (“turbans,” “scarves”): This Hebrew word refers to women’s head coverings. The head covering may have been able to serve as a veil as well. \a FRCL\a* has “scarves.” One possible rendering is “fine clothes wound around the head,” unless such a description is too heavy or long-winded in the context of a description that aims at being comprehensive rather than precise and technical. See also \l target="REALIA:6.7">6.7 Headdress, turban, hat\l*.
\line \i Rdidim\i* (“veils,” “long veils they wear on their heads”): This Hebrew word probably refers to a veil of fine quality. It was able to cover the face. It probably refers to the same kind of veil as those mentioned in \s H00102406500054\s* and \s H00103801400022\s*, \s H00103801900014\s*, but it is a different word, most likely referring to a garment of finer quality. See also \l target="REALIA:6.12">6.12 Veil\l*.
\key 10.5.1
\title Earring, nose ring
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb נֶזֶם
\trl nezem
\ref H00102402200028 H00102403000014 H00102404700044 H00103500400032 H00203200200012 H00203200300014 H00203502200028 H00700802400024 H00700802400030 H00700802500028 H00700802600008 H01804201100086 H02001102200002 H02002501200002 H02300302100008 H02601601200006 H02800201500026
\heb עָגִיל
\trl ‘agil
\ref H00403105000030 H02601601200014
\grk ἐνώτιον
\trl enōtion
\ref L06801000400040
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0531_earrings_gold.jpg|col||Metropolitan Museum of Art|Gold earrings|10.0\fig* The earring was worn on the ear and the nose ring in the nose for decoration. They were small rings, usually made of silver or gold. They could have more or less elaborate decorative work attached to them.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew word \i nezem\i* refers to a ring that could be worn in the ear or in the nose. In either case, it was worn as decorative jewelry.
\line \fig |UBS-0037_nose_ring.jpg|col||© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart|Nose rings|10.0\fig* The Hebrew word \i ‘agil\i* in \s H02601601200006\s* clearly refers to an earring, and this is probably the case in \s H00403105000030\s* also.
\line \fig |KNW-0455_earring.png|col||Louise Bass © The British and Foreign Bible Society 1994|Woman wearing an earring|10.0\fig* The Greek word \i enōtion\i* in \s L06801000400040\s* specifically indicates a ring worn in the ear, not in the nose.
\key 10.5.2
\title Bracelet, armlet, anklet
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֶצְעָדָה
\trl ’ets‘adah
\ref H00403105000022 H01000101000042
\heb עֶכֶס
\trl ‘ekes
\ref H02300301800022
\heb צָמִיד
\trl tsamid
\ref H00102402200040 H00102403000022 H00102404700054 H00403105000026 H02601601100012 H02602304200038
\heb צְעָדָה
\trl ts‘adah
\ref H02300302000010
\grk χλιδών
\trl chlidōn
\ref L06801000400022 L07102102100016
\grk ψέλιον
\trl pselion
\ref L06801000400028
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0532_bracelets_gold.jpg|col||Walters Art Museum|Bracelets|10.0\fig* The bracelet/armlet was a piece of jewelry worn on the wrist/arm. It was round and made of metal.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The bracelet was worn on the wrist while the armlet was pushed up the arm, usually above the elbow. Where a distinction must be made between one part of the arm and another, the Hebrew word \i tsamid\i* in \s H02601601100012\s* may be translated “bracelets on your wrists.”
\line \s H00403105000022\s*: Where different words do not exist for a ring worn on the wrist and a ring worn on the upper arm, it is possible to use an inclusive term in this verse; for example, \a CEV\a* has “jewelry”.
\line Translators must be careful not to use a word that indicates an object worn on the arm but that is made of something other than metal. For example, \a CEV\a* has “arm-band” in \s H01000101000042\s*, but this could be misunderstood in modern English to mean an insignia made of cloth or plastic.
\line For the Hebrew words \i ‘ekes\i* and \i ts‘adah\i*, see the discussion on \s H02300301801000-H02300302301000\s* at \l target="REALIA:10.5">10.5 Jewelry, ornaments\l*.
\line In \s L06801000400028\s* the two Greek words \i chlidōn\i* and \i pselion\i* can both mean “bracelet“ (for the arm) and “anklet” (for the leg). Where two distinct words exist, they can both be used. It is also possible to say something like “decorative metal bands for the wrist and the ankle.”
\key 10.5.3
\title Hair decoration, tiara, ribbon
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk μίτρα
\trl mitra
\ref L06801000300064 L06801600800014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line The tiara was a decorative band, probably made of cloth, wrapped around the head or tied in the hair.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Almost all cultures know some kind of hair decoration worn by women. Normally it will be possible to use such a word. Translations vary for the Greek word \i mitra\i*. \a GNT\a* and \a ITCL\a* have “ribbon,” which is good. The word “turban” in \a NJB\a* may be accurate, but it may sound strange if a turban is normally considered a headdress for men. \a NAB\a* “fillet” is similar to “ribbon,” but this word is obscure in contemporary English. The word “tiara” in \a RSV\a* and \a NRSV\a* presents a nice picture of a woman beautifying her hair, which is the goal of the translator here.
\key 10.5.4
\title Necklace, chain, cord
\cont \u References:\u*
\arm הַמְנִיךְ
\trl hamnik
\ref A02700500700230 A02700500700240 A02700501600210 A02700501600220 A02700502900070 A02700502900080
\heb חָרוּז
\trl charuzim
\ref H02200101000018
\heb כּוּמָז
\trl kumaz
\ref H00203502200036 H00403105000034
\heb נְטִיפָה
\trl netifah
\ref H00700802600042 H02300301900004
\heb עֲנָק, ענק
\trl ‘anaq (noun or verb)
\ref H00700802600070 H01907300600004 H02000100900016 H02200400900026
\heb פָּתִיל
\trl pathil
\ref H00103801800026 H00103802500054
\heb רָבִיד
\trl ravid
\ref H00104104200044 H02601601100020
\heb שַׂהֲרוֹן
\trl saharonim
\ref H00700802600036 H02300301800034
\grk μανιάκης
\trl maniakēs
\ref L08100300600038
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line \fig |WEB-0533_necklace.jpg|col||© Wolfgang Sauber (Wikimedia Commons)|Necklaces|10.0\fig* The necklace was a string, band, cord, or chain worn around the neck for ornamentation. Often jewels or other ornaments were attached to it.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line \s H00104104200044 A02700500700240 A02700501600210 A02700502900070\s*: In these passages a chain of gold is given by a ruler to someone who has been promoted to a high position. The chain in both contexts was probably more substantial than a simple necklace, and it will be better to use a word meaning “chain” rather than one referring to a thin decorative necklace. However, it is important to include in the translation something indicating honor or high rank and not slavery. In some languages a word exists for a symbol of honor or high office that is worn around the neck. Where such a word does not exist or is obscure, the element of honor may be included by expanding the translation; for example, \a GNT\a* has “chain of honor” in \s A02700500700230\s*.
\line According to some commentators, the Aramaic word \i hamnik\i* in \s A02700500700240 A02700501600210 A02700502900070\s* does not actually refer to a chain but rather to a solid metal collar. \a NAB\a* has “collar.” In some languages a single verb can be used for wearing purple clothing and the golden collar as symbols of authority. But in others it will be more natural to use two separate verbs for “wearing” clothing and for “wearing” an ornament like a chain or collar around the neck.
\line \s H02200101000018\s*: The Hebrew word \i charuz\i* (plural, \i charuzim\i*) actually means a small bead or gem with a hole in it. When many of these were stung onto a string, they formed a necklace. Some translations render \i charuzim\i* as “necklaces” (\a NJB\a*, \a PV\a*), while others prefer to speak about the “jewels” (\a GNT\a*, \a NCV\a*) or “precious stones” that made up the necklaces. Others combine the two: \a RSV\a* “strings of jewels”; \a NASB\a* “strings of beads”; \a CEV\a* “necklace of precious stones”; and \a SPCL\a* “pearl necklaces.”
\line The meaning of the Hebrew word \i kumaz\i* (\s H00203502200036 H00403105000034\s*) is uncertain, but it clearly refers to some kind of jewelry. Most translations agree that it indicates something that was worn around the neck, whether “necklaces” (\a GNT\a*, \a GECL\a*) or “pendants” (\a REB\a*, \a NJPSV\a*).
\line \s H00103801800026 H00103802500054\s*: In these verses the Hebrew word \i pathil\i* probably refers to nothing more than a simple cord around the neck, used to hold the signet ring. \a CEV\a* is good with “cord around your neck” in \s H00103801800026\s*.
\line For the Hebrew words \i netifah\i* and \i saharonim\i*, see the discussion on \s H02300301801000-H02300302301000\s* under \l target="REALIA:10.5">10.5 Jewelry, ornaments\l*.
\key 10.6
\title Cosmetics
\index \l target="REALIA:10.6.1">10.6.1 Perfumes\l*
\line Oil: See \l target="REALIA:1.10.5">1.10.5 Anointing oil\l*; \l target="REALIA:1.15.1">1.15.1 Oil, ointment\l*; \l target="REALIA:9.3">9.3 Olive oil\l*.
\key 10.6.1
\title Perfumes
\index \l target="REALIA:10.6.1.1">10.6.1.1 Myrrh\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:10.6.1.2">10.6.1.2 Oil of nard\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb רקח, רֶקַח, רֹקַח, רַקָּח, רִקֻּחַ, מִרְקַחַת
\trl raqach (verb), reqach, roqach, riquach, mirqachath
\ref H00203002500016 H00203002500020 H00203002500014 H00203003500010 H00203003500014 H00203702900030 H00900801300012 H01300903000012 H01300903000016 H01401601400042 H01401601400046 H01600300800030 H02101000100012 H02200800200022 H02305700900022
\heb שֶׁמֶן
\trl shemen
\ref H01001400200048 H02002700900002 H02100700100008 H02100900800016 H02101000100010 H02200100300006 H02200100300010 H02200401000026 H02305700900016 H02306100300024 H02601600900030 H03300601500024
\grk ἤδυσμα
\trl ēdusma
\ref L06900401700020
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Perfumes were specially produced mixtures of pleasant-smelling spices usually added to an oil base. They were used to cover unpleasant smells such as human perspiration, decaying bodies, or even the bloody results of ritual slaughter.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The Hebrew verb \i raqach\i* means “to mix, compound,” while the Hebrew word \i shemen\i* means “oil.”
\key 10.6.1.1
\title Myrrh
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לֹט
\trl lot
\ref H00103702500050 H00104301100062
\heb מֹר
\trl mor
\ref H00203002300014 H01700201200070 H01904500900002 H02000701700006 H02200101300006 H02200300600022 H02200400600030 H02200401400022 H02200500100014 H02200500500020 H02200500500026 H02200501300022
\grk μυροβρεχής
\trl murobrechēs
\ref L07900400600036
\grk μύρον
\trl muron
\ref G04002600700012 G04002601200010 G04101400300036 G04101400400026 G04200703800062 G04200704600018 G04301100200016 G04301200300012 G04301200300062 G04301200500010 G06601801300016 L06801000300042 L07000200700008
\grk σμύρνα, σμυρνίζω
\trl smurna, smurnizō (verb)
\ref G04000201100060 G04101502300008 L07102401500020
\cont \u Description and usage:\u*
\line Myrrh was the aromatic resin of certain bushes. This resin was added to an oil base to make a perfume to put on the body. See also \l target="REALIA:4.8.3.1">4.8.3.1 Embalming oils\l*.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line The tree that produced the myrrh resin was not native to Israel, and the import of myrrh made it an expensive luxury. This should be borne in mind when translating \s H01700201200070 H01904500900002 H02000701700006 H02200101300006 G04000201100060\s*.
\line Most translators borrow a term for “myrrh.” In some passages translators may expand the translation to indicate the nature of the substance; compare \a GNT\a* at \s H01904500900002\s*, where it says “perfume of myrrh.” In many instances, particularly in the New Testament, they may use a general expression such as “ointment,” “aromatic oil,” or “perfume.” When the Greek word \i muron\i* means “perfume,” it may be rendered “sweet-smelling oil” or “fragrant oil.”
\key 10.6.1.2
\title Oil of nard
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb נֵרְדְּ
\trl nerd
\ref H02200101200014 H02200401300018 H02200401400002
\grk νάρδος
\trl nardos
\ref G04101400300038 G04301200300014
\cont \u Description:\u*
\line Oil of nard was an aromatic oil extracted from a plant called nard.
\line ———
\cont \u Translation:\u*
\line Translators normally borrow the term “nard” but use some type of classifier, for example, “perfume called nard” or “sweet-smelling substance, nard.” For other issues related to the above verses, see also \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.3">5.18.1.3 Alabaster jar, alabaster flask\l*.
\c 11
\key 11
\title Weights, Measures, and Money
\index \l target="REALIA:11.0">11.0 Introduction\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.1">11.1 Weights\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.2">11.2 Units that are both weights and monetary values\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3">11.3 Measures of volume\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.5">11.4 Measures of length\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.5">11.5 Measures of area\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.6">11.6 Money\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.7">11.7 Weights, Measures, and Money Bibliography\l*
\key 11.0
\title Introduction
\cont Weights of different periods and also measures of volume have been uncovered in various archaeological sites. The weights generally are made of stone, sometimes of metal. They are spherical in shape, and are identified by having their names engraved on them. The measures of volume are usually containers, stone or clay jars, with the name of the measure inscribed on them. Because of their rustic manufacture, they are not “accurate” or “just” in a precise modern sense. However, they served as normative standards in a given period and region, although they differed according to time and place. For this reason the equivalences in terms of modern weights and measures are only approximate.
\line Translators who make use of tables of equivalents from more than one reference book may be confused when they notice that different books sometimes give different values for the same biblical units. However, this only shows that there is some uncertainty about some of the units. In the case of these particular units, each translator will have to decide which value he will base his translation on. Here it is probably best to stick to what is recommended by one reliable reference book for the whole range of biblical weights and measures. (In most instances the variation between the values given in different books is not significant as far as the main meaning of the text is concerned.)
\line If a translation retains the original terms, then it should supply footnotes and/or tables so the reader can understand them. In common-language translations, where the terms are converted in the text into modern equivalents it may not be necessary to include a table of coins or weights and measures. This is true even of study editions based on a common-language translation. You will notice in the lists which follow that most weights, measures, and monetary units appear relatively few times in the Bible. Of the approximately forty-five items that are listed below, only five appear in more than ten places and only eight in more than five places. This means that most items can be annotated every time they appear, while those few items that occur more often can be discussed in a glossary.
\key 11.0.1
\title Rounding off
\cont Many biblical weights and measures are given in round figures or whole numbers. When they are converted to modern equivalents, the resulting figures will often have one or two decimal places. This can give the modern reader the impression of a measurement that is more precise than was actually the case. To avoid this, it is recommended that numbers be rounded off as much as possible to the same number of significant figures as was the case in the original text. The “significant” figures are the digits other than the place holding zeros in a given measurement; for example, if the original measurement is 40, it has one significant figure, that is, one digit followed by a zero in a two-digit number. If the conversion of this measurement results in a modern equivalent of 189, rounding off to one significant figure would yield 200, that is, one digit followed by zeros in a three-digit number. We may take an example from \s G04202401300030\s*, where the distance is given as 60 stadia in the Greek text. The number 60 has one significant figure. One stadion equals 607 feet, so 60 stadia are 6.9 miles. Rounding off 6.9 miles to one significant figure would mean a translation of “7 miles” (so \a RSV\a* \a GNT\a*).
\key 11.0.2
\title Symbolic numbers
\cont In several places in the book of Revelation, and perhaps elsewhere, measurements are given which probably have symbolic meaning. Since the numbers themselves are part of the message (and perhaps a more important part than the actual measurements), these numbers should not be obscured by converting them to modern equivalents. The following passages fall into this category and are discussed below: \s G06601402000040 G06601602100010 G06602101600042 G06602101700018\s*.
\line The treatment that follows does not pretend to be comprehensive nor even to take into consideration variations in values from one time period to another and from one location to another. The values suggested, however, should be sufficient to aid a translator to produce renderings that will give the readers a reasonable idea of size and volume.
\line In the discussions that follow, weights and measures are generally given in ascending order, from small to large. These discussions should be used together with the tables that appear below.
\key 11.1
\title Weights
\index \l target="REALIA:11.1.1">11.1.1 Gerah\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.1.2">11.1.2 Beqa\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.1.3">11.1.3 Pim\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.1.4">11.1.4 Peres, Parsin\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.1.5">11.1.5 Pound\l*
\cont The metric and imperial equivalents given in the tables are rounded-off approximations. While they should suffice for purposes of translation, they are not intended to present a high degree of mathematical precision.
\line \b Old Testament:\b*
\line Name: Talent (\i kikar\i*)
\line Equivalence: 60 minas
\line Metric: 34 kilograms
\line Imperial: 75 pounds
\line Name: Mina (\i maneh\i*, \i mna\i*)
\line Equivalence: 50 shekels
\line Metric: 0.6 kilogram
\line Imperial: 1.25 pounds
\line Name: Shekel (\i sheqel\i*)
\line Equivalence: -- -
\line Metric: 12 grams
\line Imperial: 0.4 ounce
\line Name: Pim (\i pim\i*)
\line Equivalence: 0.7 shekel
\line Metric: 8 grams
\line Imperial: 0.3 ounce
\line Name: Beqa (\i beqa‘\i*)
\line Equivalence: 0.5 shekel
\line Metric: 6 grams
\line Imperial: 0.2 ounce
\line Name: Gerah (\i gerah\i*)
\line Equivalence: 0.05 shekel
\line Metric: 0.6 gram
\line Imperial: 0.02 ounce
\line \b New Testament and Deuterocanon:\b*
\line Name: Talent (\i talanton\i*)
\line Equivalence: (See \l target="REALIA:11.6">11.6 Money\l*)
\line Name: Pound (\i litra\i*)
\line Equivalence: -- -
\line Metric: 327 grams
\line Imperial: 11.5 ounces
\key 11.1.1
\title Gerah
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גֵּרָה
\trl gerah
\ref H00203001300034 H00302702500020 H00400304700030 H00401801600034 H02604501200010
\cont In all of these references, the \i gerah\i* only appears as a definition of the shekel, of which it is 1/20; that is, the \i gerah\i* has no significance apart from the shekel. If the name “shekel” is retained in translation, then the name “gerah” may also be kept. If the word “shekel” is translated, it may still be possible to retain the word “gerah,” because you will just be saying it is 1/20 of the unit used for “shekel.”
\key 11.1.2
\title Beqa
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בֶּקַע
\trl beqa‘
\ref H00102402200032 H00203802600002
\cont In \s H00203802600002\s* a \i beqa‘\i* is defined as half a shekel. In \s H00102402200032\s* it is the weight of a gold nose ring. \a NRSV\a* just converts it to the shekel weight by saying “a gold nose-ring weighing a half shekel.” The \i beqa‘\i* equals 10 gerahs.
\key 11.1.3
\title Pim
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb פִּים
\trl pim
\ref H00901302100010
\line \fig |WEB-0716_pim.jpg|col||Funhistory (Wikimedia Commons)|Pim weight|11.0\fig* “The charge was a pim” (\i haptsirah fim\i*): The meaning of these two Hebrew words is highly conjectural. While most translators agree with \a RSV\a* that they indicate some unit of payment, others have thought that they refer to another kind of metal implement. However, the \a KJV\a* rendering “file” (which would hardly need sharpening but which could itself be used to sharpen things) is surely incorrect. Archaeologists in the land of Israel have found a number of small round stone objects, each weighing about 7.5 grams (¼ ounce; that is about ⅔ of a shekel) and inscribed with the word \i pim\i* (= \i fim\i*).
\key 11.1.4
\title Peres, Parsin
\cont \u References:\u*
\arm פְּרֵס
\trl peres
\ref A02700502500020 A02700502800002
\cont The basic meaning of the Aramaic word \i peres\i* (plural form \i parsin\i*) is “division,” “split,” “partition,” or “separation.” It seems in the context of \s A02700502501000-A02700502801000\s* to indicate either half a mina or half a shekel. However, this meaning is of little significance in the narrative and does not need to be reflected either in the translation or in a note. The first sentence of \a CEV\a* for these verses is a good model: “The words written there are \i mne’\i*, which means ‘numbered,’ \i teqel\i*, which means ‘weighed,’ and \i parsin\i*, which means ‘divided.’ ” To this \a CEV\a* adds the following footnote: “In the Aramaic text of verse 25, the words ‘mene, tekel, parsin,’ are used, and in verses 26–28 the words ‘mene, tekel, peres’ (the singular of ‘parsin’) are used. ‘Parsin’ means ‘divided,’ but ‘peres’ can mean either ‘divided’ or ‘Persia.’ ”
\key 11.1.5
\title Pound
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk λίτρα
\trl litra
\ref G04301200300010 G04301903900036
\cont \s G04301200300010\s*: In this verse the “pound” (\a RSV\a*; \i litra\i* in Greek) of costly ointment would have been kept in a relatively small container, something that would hold about a third of a kilogram. This corresponds to the volume of a small jar or tin can today. \a PV\a* says “half a liter.”
\line In focus here is not so much the amount of perfume but rather its high value. Translators should ensure that the amount of the ointment chosen to translate this verse would indeed be expensive (about a year’s wages; see the discussion under \i dēnarion\i* below, \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.6">11.6.2.6 Drachma\l*).
\line It may be most effective to substitute a container for the volume and begin this verse with “Mary took a bottle of very expensive perfume” (\a GW\a*).
\line \s G04301903900036\s*: \a RSV\a* understands a \i litra\i* to be equal to a pound, so at the end of this verse it has “about a hundred pounds’ weight.” This is misleading since the Roman \i litra\i* contained only about three quarters of a modern pound. For this reason many English translations say “about 75 pounds” (so \a NIV\a* \a NCV\a*). In the metric system this will be “about 30 kilos” (\a FRCL\a*).
\key 11.2
\title Units that are both weights and monetary values
\index \l target="REALIA:11.2.1">11.2.1 Shekel\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.2.2">11.2.2 Mina\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.2.3">11.2.3 Talent\l*
\key 11.2.1
\title Shekel
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שֶׁקֶל
\trl sheqel
\ref H00102301500012 H00102301600044 H00202103200020 H00203001300022 H00203001300026 H00203001300038 H00203001300044 H00203001500026 H00203002400012 H00203802400056 H00203802400060 H00203802500034 H00203802500038 H00203802600014 H00203802600018 H00203802900024 H00300501500052 H00300501500056 H00302700300038 H00302700300044 H00302700400018 H00302700500036 H00302700500048 H00302700600034 H00302700600050 H00302700700032 H00302700700044 H00302701600042 H00302702500012 H00302702500026 H00400304700010 H00400304700020 H00400304700034 H00400305000038 H00400701300028 H00400701300032 H00400701900030 H00400701900034 H00400702500026 H00400702500030 H00400703100026 H00400703100030 H00400703700026 H00400703700030 H00400704300026 H00400704300030 H00400704900026 H00400704900030 H00400705500026 H00400705500030 H00400706100026 H00400706100030 H00400706700026 H00400706700030 H00400707300026 H00400707300030 H00400707900026 H00400707900030 H00400708500048 H00400708600024 H00401801600022 H00401801600026 H00403105200036 H00600702100028 H00600702100042 H00900900800032 H00901700500034 H00901700700028 H01001402600054 H01002402400070 H01200700100034 H01200700100044 H01200701600030 H01200701600040 H01200701800032 H01200701800042 H01201502000040 H01302102500018 H01400300900012 H01600501500044 H01601003300020 H02403200900042 H02600401000016 H02604501200006 H02604501200014 H02604501200022 H02604501200030 H03000800500044
\arm תְּקֵל
\trl teqel
\ref A02700502500016 A02700502700002
\cont The Hebrew word \i sheqel\i* means “weight,” and the system of weights in ancient Israel was based on it.
\line According to Fry, we should treat the shekel according to three different time periods: (1) through the time of David, it was like the New Testament denarius, which equaled a day’s wage; (2) from the time of Solomon to the captivity, the shekel was 1/10 of the old value; (3) from the captivity onward there was again a devaluation, so a month’s wages was 20 shekels (equaling 1 daric). In the Old Testament where the word “shekel” refers to money, the passages can be divided as follows according to the meaning of “shekel”:
\line 1. One day’s wage equals one shekel: \s H00102301500012 H00102301600044 H00202103200020 H00403105200036 H00600702100028 H00600702100028 H00900900800032 H00901700500034 H00901700700028 H01001402600054 H01002402400070 H01302102500018\s*
\line 2. One day’s wage equals 10 shekels: \s H01200700100034 H01200700100034 H01200701600030 H01200701600030 H01200701800032 H01200701800032 H01201502000040 H01400300900012 H03000800500044\s*
\line 3. One day’s wage equals 20 shekels: \s H02403200900042 H02600401000016 H02604501200006 H02604501200006 H02604501200006 H02604501200006\s*
\line The word “shekel” refers to regular weight in \s H00102301500012 H00102301600044 H00202103200020\s* and in more than twenty other passages.
\line The word “shekel” refers to double weight (\i sheqel haqodesh\i*; literally “the holy shekel,” which is rendered “shekel of the sanctuary” by \a RSV\a*) in the following Old Testament passages: \s H00203001300022 H00203001300022 H00203001300022 H00203001300022 H00203001500026 H00203002400012 H00203802400056 H00203802400056 H00203802500034 H00203802500034 H00203802600014 H00203802600014 H00203802900024 H00300501500052 H00300501500052 H00302700300038 H00302700300038 H00302700400018 H00302700500036 H00302700500036 H00302700600034 H00302700600034 H00302700700032 H00302700700032 H00302701600042 H00302702500012 H00302702500012 H00400304700010 H00400304700010 H00400305000038 H00400701300028 H00400701300032 H00400701900030 H00400701900034 H00400702500026 H00400702500030 H00400703100026 H00400703100030 H00400703700026 H00400703700030 H00400704300026 H00400704300030 H00400704900026 H00400704900030 H00400705500026 H00400705500030 H00400706100026 H00400706100030 H00400706700026 H00400706700030 H00400707300026 H00400707300030 H00400707900026 H00400707900030 H00400708500048 H00400708600024 H00401801600022 H00401801600026\s*. There seems to have been a separate standard of weight used in the service of the Tabernacle. While its exact or even relative value is not given in Scripture, many scholars believe that it was double the weight of the shekel used in ordinary commerce. \a GNT\a* renders the literal expression “the shekel of the sanctuary” as “according to the official standard.” But it is probably better to add to this “. . . of the sanctuary” for the sake of clarity. Also, the religious component may have been significant in that some degree of consistency would have been used in such measures. Other ways of expressing the idea of a special weight/value used for religious purposes in a passage like \s H00203001300022\s* are “according to the official standards” (\a CEV\a*), “using the standard weight of the holy place” (\a GW\a*), and “according to the unit of weight which is in force in the sanctuary” (\a ITCL\a*).
\line For the Aramaic word \i teqel\i* in \s A02700502500016 A02700502700002\s*, see the discussion under \i peres\i* above, \l target="REALIA:11.1.4">11.1.4 Peres, Parsin\l*.
\key 11.2.2
\title Mina
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb מָנֶה
\trl maneh
\ref H01101001700016 H01500206900032 H01600707000034 H01600707100026 H02604501200034
\arm מְנֵא
\trl mne’
\ref A02700502500012 A02700502500014 A02700502600008
\grk μνᾶ
\trl mna
\ref G04201901300018 G04201901600016 G04201901600024 G04201901800014 G04201901800024 G04201902000018 G04201902400018 G04201902400030 G04201902500014 L07701402400028 L07701501800012 L07900100400080 L08100504400020 L08100504400028
\cont The above words refer to the mina. According to most authorities, the \i maneh\i* was equal to 50 shekels, and there were 60 minas in a talent. Some authorities, however, say there were 60 shekels in a mina and 50 minas in a talent (see \s H02604501200034\s*).
\line \s H01101001700016\s*: The weight of a gold shield is given as “three minas” (\a RSV\a*) in this verse. Most common-language translations have a modern weight equivalent, for example, “almost four pounds” (\a CEV\a*) and “almost two kilograms” (\a ITCL\a*).
\line \s H01500206900032 H01600707000034 H01600707100026\s*: Translators generally give the amounts here for the word \i maneh\i* in minas (with or without a note), or they give a modern weight equivalent. In \s H01500206900032\s* for the literal phrase “five thousand minas of silver” (\a RSV\a*), \a SPCL\a* is a bit heavy, writing out “two thousand seven hundred and fifty kilos of silver.” \a NCV\a* rounds off the figure to the same number of significant figures as the original text, saying “about 6000 pounds of silver.”
\line \s H02604501200034\s* defines one mina as 60 shekels. This is unusual in Scripture, and it may represent a purposefully higher “royal” figure.
\line \s G04201901300018 G04201901600016 G04201901600016 G04201901800014 G04201901800014 G04201902000018 G04201902400018 G04201902400018 G04201902500014\s*: The amount given to the servants in this parable almost certainly represents a sum of money and not a weight. The precise value of this money is not in focus here but rather what three of the servants did with what they received. It may be helpful to keep in mind that one \i mna\i* was approximately equal to the wages of a day laborer for four months. While the exact amount is not important, it is significant that they each received the same amount. \a CEV\a* seems to obscure this point by rendering the second clause in \s G04201901300018\s* as “gave each of them some money” (similarly \a REB\a*). Here the model of \a ITCL\a* is preferable: “he gave each of them the same amount of money.” \a NCV\a* renders \i mna\i* as “a coin,” but this is misleading since no country today has in circulation a coin of such high value. Its footnote does explain that it was a large sum of money, but inaccurately states the amount to be three months’ wages. \a GNT\a* “a gold coin” is only slightly better. Better still is “a large sum of money” (\a SPCL\a* \a ITCL\a*).
\line For the Aramaic word \i mne’\i* in \s A02700502500012 A02700502500014 A02700502600008\s*, see the discussion under \i peres\i* above, \l target="REALIA:11.1.4">11.1.4 Peres, Parsin\l*.
\key 11.2.3
\title Talent
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כִּכָּר
\trl kikar
\ref H00202503900002 H00203702400002 H00203802400044 H00203802500014 H00203802700008 H00203802700046 H00203802700048 H00203802900012 H01001203000022 H01100901400020 H01100902800026 H01101001000018 H01101001400036 H01101602400022 H01102003900090 H01200500500040 H01200502200050 H01200502300012 H01200502300024 H01201501900028 H01201801400062 H01201801400070 H01202303300046 H01202303300052 H01301900600032 H01302000200026 H01302201400020 H01302201400034 H01302900400006 H01302900400022 H01302900700018 H01302900700034 H01302900700052 H01302900700062 H01400300800050 H01400801800056 H01400900900018 H01400901300038 H01402500600022 H01402500900030 H01402700500044 H01403600300026 H01403600300032 H01500802600012 H01500802600032 H01500802600038 H01700300900024
\arm כַּכַּר
\trl kakar
\ref A01500702200006
\grk τάλαντον
\trl talanton
\ref G04001802400020 G04002501500012 G04002501600010 G04002502000012 G04002502000022 G04002502000030 G04002502000042 G04002502200014 G04002502200022 G04002502200034 G04002502400014 G04002502500012 G04002502800012 G04002502800026 L06700101400034 L06700402000014 L06900300900034 L06900400700038 L07701102800040 L07701301600010 L07701301900016 L07701503100016 L07701503100042 L07701503500042 L07800301100046 L07800400800014 L07800400800032 L07800402400042 L07800502100024 L07800801000024 L07800801100032 L08000401700026 L08100103400012 L08100103400020 L08100302100030 L08100405100020 L08100405200030 L08100801900066 L08100805600012 L08100805600024 L08100805600032
\grk ταλαντιαῖος
\trl talantiaios
\ref G06601602100010
\cont The above words refer to the talent. Basically the talent was the largest unit of weight in the ancient world, equal to about 34 kilograms (75 pounds). Later it was used as a monetary unit with a value that fluctuated, depending upon the particular monetary system that prevailed at a particular period of time. A silver talent was worth approximately 6000 denarii and a gold talent was worth at least thirty times that much.
\line There was no such coin as a talent, which had too high a value.
\line \s G04001802101000-G04001803501000\s*: In this parable the significance of the amount of the debts of the two servants is not in their precise value but rather in the huge difference between them. There seems to be a secondary significance to the size of the debt of the first servant, hinting at the great debt of sin that Jesus’ hearers have toward God. The amount of the large debt would be something like the salaries of 1,000 day laborers for 20 years. However, it would be awkward to try to include this information in the translation itself. The Greek text compares two different monetary instruments, the talent and the denarius. While the ancient hearer may have known that a talent was equal to 6000 denarii, this knowledge cannot be assumed for the modern reader. One effective way to emphasize the difference between the two debts may be to convert the 10,000 talents into denarii and render the last half of verse 24 as “one of them was brought in who owed him 60 million denarii.” This will then contrast with the 100 denarii in verse 28. This may be a problem in cultures where very large numbers are difficult to express. In such cultures translators may follow \a GNT\a* “millions of dollars . . . a few dollars” or \a PV\a* “millions of silver pieces . . . 100 pieces of silver.”
\line \s G04002501401000-G04002503001000\s*: The actual value of the talent in this parable is of secondary importance. It is of primary importance to retain the 5:2:1 ratio. Numerous ways have been found in translation to express the amount given to each servant. Here are a few examples for the first half of verse 15: “he handed five thousand coins to the first servant, two thousand to the second, and one thousand to the third” (\a CEV\a*); “He gave one man ten thousand dollars, another four thousand dollars, and another two thousand dollars” (\a GW\a*); “He gave one servant five bags of gold, another servant two bags of gold, and a third servant one bag of gold” (\a NCV\a*); and “to one he gave five thousand gold coins, to another he gave two thousand, and to another he gave one thousand” (\a GNT\a*).
\line Translations do not agree as to whether the master gave them gold or silver. While this makes considerable difference in the values, it does not affect the meaning of the text and so makes no difference to the translation. A particular metal should be included only if it is required by the language. The context in which this parable occurs is different from that in which the parallel in \s G04201901101000-G04201902701000\s* appears. Furthermore, Luke gives the amounts in minas while Matthew has talents, which were worth 60 times as much. While the translator does not need to find a precise modern currency equivalent, the amount chosen in Matthew should indicate that these were large sums of money.
\line \s G06601602100010\s*: In this verse many translations render the literal phrase “about a talent” as “about 40 kilograms” (\a FRCL\a*) or “about a hundred pounds” (\a NIV\a*). In languages that have a limited group of numbers it will be better to begin this verse with “Huge hailstones of tremendous weight [or, weighing as much as an adult person].” In fact, it will be quite adequate to follow the model of \a Phps\a* “Great hailstones like heavy weights” or \a GW\a* “Large, heavy hailstones.”
\key 11.3
\title Measures of volume
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1">11.3.1 Measures of volume in the Old Testament\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.2">11.3.2 Measures of volume in the New Testament and the Deuterocanon\l*
\cont \u References:\u*
\cont Estimates of volume vary in different authorities by a factor of two. In other words, according to some authorities the figures given above for Old Testament capacities should all be doubled.
\line \b Dry measure\b*
\line Name: Kor (\i kor\i*, \i koros\i*)
\line Equivalence: 10 ephahs
\line Metric: 220 liters
\line Imperial: 6 bushels
\line Name: Homer (\i chomer\i*)
\line Equivalence: 10 ephahs
\line Metric: 220 liters
\line Imperial: 6 bushels
\line Name: \i Artabē\i*
\line Equivalence: -- -
\line Metric: 50 liters
\line Imperial: 12.5 gallons
\line Name: Ephah (\i ’eyfah\i*)
\line Equivalence: -- -
\line Metric: 22 liters
\line Imperial: 0.6 bushels
\line Name: Seah (\i se’ah\i*, \i saton\i*)
\line Equivalence: 0.3 ephah
\line Metric: 7 liters
\line Imperial: 7 quarts
\line Name: Omer (\i ‘omer\i*)
\line Equivalence: 0.1 ephah
\line Metric: 2.2 liters
\line Imperial: 2.2 quarts
\line Name: Qab (\i qav\i*)
\line Equivalence: 0.05 ephah
\line Metric: 1.2 liters
\line Imperial: 1.2 quarts
\line Name: Choinix
\line Equivalence: -- -
\line Metric: 1 liter
\line Imperial: 1 quart
\line \b Liquid measure\b*
\line Name: Kor (\i kor\i*)
\line Equivalence: 10 baths
\line Metric: 220 liters
\line Imperial: 60 gallons
\line Name: \i Metrētēs\i*
\line Equivalence: -- -
\line Metric: 40 liters
\line Imperial: 10 gallons
\line Name: Bath (\i bath\i*, \i batos\i*)
\line Equivalence: -- -
\line Metric: 22 liters
\line Imperial: 6 gallons
\line Name: Hin (\i hin\i*)
\line Equivalence: 1/6 bath
\line Metric: 4 liters
\line Imperial: 4 quarts
\line Name: Log (\i log\i*)
\line Equivalence: 1/72 bath
\line Metric: 0.3 liter
\line Imperial: 0.3 quart
\key 11.3.1
\title Measures of volume in the Old Testament
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.1">11.3.1.1 Qab\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.2">11.3.1.2 Seah\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.3">11.3.1.3 Ephah\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.4">11.3.1.4 Homer\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.5">11.3.1.5 Kor\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.6">11.3.1.6 Omer\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.7">11.3.1.7 Log\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.8">11.3.1.8 Hin\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.9">11.3.1.9 Bath\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.10">11.3.1.10 Lethek\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.11">11.3.1.11 Shalish\l*
\cont Schneider has suggested substituting the names of known containers that contain approximately the volume or capacity indicated by the biblical name. Thus, for example, some cultures will have a special name for a basket or sack that holds about 25 liters (50 pounds) of grain, which is approximately equal to the \i ’eyfah\i*. It is recommended that translators investigate this possibility in their own setting. A word of caution, however, is in order. One should avoid words that are clearly anachronistic, words which indicate containers made of plastic or tin alloy. Thus, for example, in \s H00301401001000\s* the \i ’eyfah\i* of fine flour is to be mixed with a \i log\i* (about half a liter) of oil. It would be inappropriate to say “mixed with one can of oil,” although it would be possible to say “mixed with two cups of oil.” \fig |PTZ-0135_measures_of_volume.jpg|col||© Ray Pritz (UBS)|Measures of volume|11.0\fig*
\key 11.3.1.1
\title Qab
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קַב
\trl qav
\ref H01200602500042
\cont \s H01200602500042\s*: The one-fourth of a \i qav\i* here is equal to about half a liter. \a GNT\a* has “half a pound.” \a CEV\a* prefers to use a container, saying “a small bowl.” This will be a good solution in most cases.
\key 11.3.1.2
\title Seah
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb סְאָה
\trl s’ah
\ref H00101800600024 H00902501800040 H01101803200030 H01200700100028 H01200700100038 H01200701600024 H01200701600034 H01200701800026 H01200701800036
\cont \s H00101800600024\s*: Abraham tells Sarah to prepare “three seahs” of flour for the guests. What is important here is that this represents a relatively large amount of flour, perhaps indicating Abraham’s generosity toward his guests. A good model is \a CEV\a* “a large sack.”
\line \s H00902501800040\s*: Abigail prepares “five seahs” of roasted grain for David’s men. Some modern translations say “a bushel” (\a NCV\a*; \a GNT\a* is more generous with “two bushels) or “about forty liters” (\a SPCL\a*). It is effective to give the name of a container; thus \a CEV\a* and \a ITCL\a* have “a large sack.”
\line \s H01101803200030\s*: Elijah digs a trench around the altar, “large enough for two seahs of seed” (similarly \a NIV\a*). This is about 12 or 13 quarts, or about 11.5 liters, which is not a large amount. It has long been suggested that this speaks of the area that can be sown with this amount of seed, and in fact ancient Jewish authorities even calculated the area as 5,000 square cubits. If this is the intention, then it is clearly an exaggeration. Most translations give the idea that the volume of the trench was the same as that volume of seed, which would make a small and unimpressive trench. \a GECL\a*, however, says “so wide that it would have been possible to sow twelve kilos of seed in it.” \a GNT\a* changes the dry measure to a liquid one, saying “large enough to hold about four gallons of water.”
\line \s H01200700100028 H01200700100028 H01200701600024 H01200701600024 H01200701800026 H01200701800026\s*: The point of Elisha’s prophecy here is that prices will drop drastically and that what had been impossible to obtain will be plentiful and cheap. Here it is important that the amount to be paid seem like a very small amount considering what is being bought. However, this is the kind of thing which becomes quickly outdated in a translation. The translator might wish to add a qualifying phrase such as “XX will be sold for \i as little as\i* YY.” For the last half of \s H01200700100028\s*, \a CEV\a* provides a good model: “you will be able to buy a large sack of flour or two large sacks of barley for almost nothing.”
\key 11.3.1.3
\title Ephah
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֵיפָה
\trl ’eyfah
\ref H00201603600012 H00300501100044 H00300601300032 H00301903600010 H00400501500034 H00402800500008 H00502501400012 H00502501400016 H00502501500014 H00700601900018 H00800201700034 H00900102400022 H00901701700022 H02002001000008 H02002001000012 H02300501000024 H02604501000008 H02604501100004 H02604501100042 H02604501300016 H02604501300032 H02604502400006 H02604502400016 H02604502400036 H02604600500006 H02604600500038 H02604600700004 H02604600700014 H02604600700052 H02604601100024 H02604601100034 H02604601100064 H02604601400026 H03000800500036 H03300601000018 H03800500600018 H03800500700028 H03800500800024 H03800500900054 H03800501000028
\cont The \i ’eyfah\i* is the dry equivalent to the \i bath\i* liquid measure.
\line In six of the above passages (\s H00201603600012 H00300501100044 H00301402101000 H00400501500034 H00401500401000 H00402800500008\s*), the quantity mentioned is 1/10 of an \i ’eyfah\i*, which equals an \i ‘omer\i* (see \s H00201603600012\s*). In these passages it will be possible to use the same word that has been chosen to render \i ‘omer\i*.
\line \s H00301903600010\s*: This command to have just measures may need to be adjusted in some languages. It is not the absolute value of the \i ’eyfah\i* or the \i hin\i* which should be just, but rather the accurate capacity of the containers that are supposed to measure them. A merchant should not be doing business with a container that is supposed to contain an \i ’eyfah\i* but which actually holds less. It is possible to expand this to include enough extra information to give the reader understanding. Thus for the literal phrase “a just ephah, and a just hin” (\a RSV\a*), \a NCV\a* has “with your weighing baskets the right size and your jars holding the right amount of liquid.” This, however, may be too cumbersome. Perhaps best is \a CEV\a* with “don’t cheat when you . . . measure anything.”
\key 11.3.1.4
\title Homer
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb חֹמֶר
\trl chomer
\ref H00302701600034 H00401103200056 H02300501000020 H02604501100026 H02604501100038 H02604501100048 H02604501300020 H02604501300036 H02604501400036 H02604501400046 H02800300200018
\cont The derivation of the Hebrew word \i chomer\i* suggests that it originally indicated the quantity of grain which was carried by a donkey.
\line \s H00302701600034\s*: The amount of seed used to value a field here (50 shekels per \i chomer\i*) is the amount that it will yield, not the amount used to sow it. In other words, it is an estimate of the field’s worth, not its area.
\line \s H02300501000020\s*: The Hebrew text here compares two capacities of measure, the \i chomer\i* and the \i ’eyfah\i*, which was equal to one tenth of a \i chomer\i*. It is important to try to retain that the ratio of one unit of seed planted yields only one tenth of that unit in harvest. If this can be done, then the precise capacities of the \i chomer\i* and the \i ’eyfah\i* are less important. The point here is that harvest yields will be extremely poor. Most translations emphasize this by adding a word like “only,” “barely,” or “merely.”
\line \s H02604501100026 H02604501100026 H02604501100026 H02604501300020 H02604501300020 H02604501400036 H02604501400036\s*: This passage equates the ephah and the bath. Both are one-tenth of a homer. See also the comments under \i ’eyfah\i* above, \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.3">11.3.1.3 Ephah\l*.
\line \s H02800300200018\s*: The total amount paid by Hosea for his wife was not very large. It was somewhat less than a bride price (compare \s H00502202901000\s*) and similar to the price to be paid for a slave (compare \s H00103702801000 H00202103201000\s*). The mixture of silver and barley is unusual. The exact amount of barley cannot be known, because the text adds another Hebrew word, \i lethek\i*, the value of which is unknown. Some commentators and translations understand it to be half the volume of a \i chomer\i*, but this is only a guess. The Hebrew for the last part of this verse is literally “a homer of barley and a lethek of barley.”
\line Some translations follow the Septuagint, which has “a homer of barley and a wineskin of wine.”
\key 11.3.1.5
\title Kor
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb כֹּר
\trl kor
\ref H01100500200018 H01100500200026 H01100502500016 H01100502500030 H01400200900030 H01400200900040 H01402700500054 H02604501400028
\arm כֹּר
\trl kor
\ref A01500702200016
\cont According to \s H02604501400028\s*, the \i kor\i* is the same as the \i chomer\i*.
\line \s H01100502500016 H01100502500016 H01400200900030 H01400200900030\s*: The amount of oil which Solomon provides to Hiram is different by a factor of one hundred between these two verses. \s H01100502500016 H01100502500030\s* has “20 cors,” while the parallel text in \s H01400200900030 H01400200900030\s* has “20,000 baths.” \a HOTTP\a* accepts “twenty cors” as the best reading at \s H01100502500016 H01100502500030\s* and remarks that the translator should resist the temptation to harmonize the two texts. Not all commentators and translations agree with \a HOTTP\a*’s reading, however, and some prefer to accept the Septuagint’s “20,000 baths,” which brings the two texts into line.
\key 11.3.1.6
\title Omer
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb עֹמֶר
\trl ‘omer
\ref H00201601600026 H00201601800010 H00201602200026 H00201603200024 H00201603300028 H00201603600006
\cont In \s H00201601600026\s* the \i ‘omer\i* was the amount of manna to be gathered. It is expressed by many translations as “two quarts” (\a GNT\a*). Luther and \a GECL\a* prefer a container of appropriate size, saying “a jar full.” \s H00201603600006\s* defines an omer as 1/10 of an ephah.
\key 11.3.1.7
\title Log
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לֹג
\trl log
\ref H00301401000054 H00301401200034 H00301401500012 H00301402100060 H00301402400022
\cont The \i log\i* was the amount of oil to be mixed with offerings for cleansing lepers. It would be equal to about a measuring cup used in modern cooking recipes.
\key 11.3.1.8
\title Hin
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb הִין
\trl hin
\ref H00202904000020 H00202904000030 H00203002400024 H00301903600016 H00302301300044 H00401500400030 H00401500500016 H00401500600032 H00401500700016 H00401500900034 H00401501000018 H00402800500028 H00402800700010 H00402801400010 H00402801400026 H00402801400040 H02600401100016 H02604502400030 H02604600500032 H02604600700046 H02604601100058 H02604601400036
\cont The \i hin\i* was a liquid measure for wine and oil for the sacrifices and for mixing the incense to be used in the Tabernacle.
\line \s H00301903600016\s*: See the comments under \i ’eyfah\i* above, \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.3">11.3.1.3 Ephah\l*.
\line \s H02600401100016\s*: \a GW\a* and \a NCV\a* give the amount of water Ezekiel can drink as he acts out the siege as “two-thirds of a quart.” \a GNT\a* conveys the picture nicely with “two cups” (similarly \a CEV\a* “two large cups”).
\key 11.3.1.9
\title Bath
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb בַּת
\trl bath
\ref H01100702600026 H01100703800014 H01400200900050 H01400200900060 H01400400500026 H02300501000012 H02604501000014 H02604501100010 H02604501100030 H02604501400012 H02604501400022 H02604501400034 H02604501400044
\cont The \i bath\i* is the liquid equivalent to the \i ’eyfah\i* dry measure.
\line \s H01100702600026 H01400400500026\s*: In these verses the capacity of the bronze Sea is given according to the \i bath\i* measure. Since scholars do not agree on the size of the \i bath\i*, translations differ wildly on the capacity of the bronze Sea in \s H01100702600026\s*: 80,000 liters (\a FRCL\a*), 40,000 liters (\a GECL\a*), 11,000 gallons (\a CEV\a*), 10,000 gallons (\a GNT\a*), and so. It is to be noted that \s H01100702600026\s* gives the capacity as 2,000 baths, while \s H01400400500026\s* has 3,000 baths. Translators should not try to harmonize these figures. See also the discussion under \l target="REALIA:4.3.2">4.3.2 Temple: Sea, tank\l*.
\line \s H02300501000012\s*: See the comments under \i chomer\i* above, \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.4">11.3.1.4 Homer\l*.
\line \s H02604501000014 H02604501100010 H02604501100010 H02604501400012 H02604501400012 H02604501400012 H02604501400012\s*: This passage equates the ephah and the bath. They are both one-tenth of a homer.
\key 11.3.1.10
\title Lethek
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb לֵתֶךְ
\trl lethek
\ref H02800300200024
\cont See the discussion under \i chomer\i* above, \l target="REALIA:11.3.1.4">11.3.1.4 Homer\l*.
\key 11.3.1.11
\title Shalish
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb שָׁלִישׁ
\trl shalish
\ref H01908000600016 H02304001200032
\cont Many commentators understand the Hebrew word \i shalish\i* to refer not to a specific measure of volume but rather to some container. The word literally means “a third.”
\line \s H01908000600016\s*: Here \i shalish\i* may refer to a large drinking vessel. The point here is that the sorrow of God’s people is great, as indicated by the abundance of their tears. For the second line of this verse, \a GNT\a* has “a large cup of tears to drink,” while \a NIV\a* says “you have made them drink tears by the bowlful” (similarly \a CEV\a*). \a TOB\a* translates “a triple measure of tears to drink.”
\line \s H02304001200032\s*: Translations give a variety of interpretations to the word \i shalish\i* here, including “bucket” (\a CEV\a*), “cup” (\a GNT\a*), “bowl” (\a NCV\a*), and “basket” (\a NIV\a*). However, almost all agree in using some kind of container.
\key 11.3.2
\title Measures of volume in the New Testament and the Deuterocanon
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.2.1">11.3.2.1 Saton\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.2.2">11.3.2.2 Bath, Kor\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.2.3">11.3.2.3 Choinix\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.2.4">11.3.2.4 Metrētēs\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.3.2.5">11.3.2.5 Artabē\l*
\key 11.3.2.1
\title Saton
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk σάτον
\trl saton
\ref G04001303300036 G04201302100020
\cont \s G04001303300036\s*: The precise amount of flour is not important here, although the translation will want to indicate that it is a relatively large amount. Translators sometimes render “three measures” (\a RSV\a*) as “three containers” or as three of some well-known local equivalent measure, such as “three pans.” The other choice would be to use whatever the local way would be of speaking about approximately 50 pounds or 40 liters of flour; for example, \a GNT\a* has “a bushel.” Common-language translations tend to avoid using a specific volume. \a CEV\a* has “three big batches,” \a NCV\a* renders “a large tub,” and \a GW\a* and \a ITCL\a* say simply “a large amount.”
\key 11.3.2.2
\title Bath, Kor
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk βάτος
\trl batos
\ref G04201600600010
\grk κόρος
\trl koros
\ref G04201600700024 L08100802000012
\cont \s G04201600600010 G04201600700024\s*: Since the point of this parable is that the steward settled the bills for a lesser amount, the exact quantity of the \i batos\i* (equals the Old Testament \i bath\i*) and \i koros\i* (equals the Old Testament \i kor\i*) is not really in focus, except that the quantities in question are fairly large. \a RSV\a* simply renders both words as “measures,” which will adequately convey the idea. \i A Handbook on The Gospel of Luke\i* suggests that “one may adjust the renderings of ‘hundred’ and ‘fifty’ in such a way that the sum total approximately agrees with the original” (page 561). This seems unnecessarily cumbersome. (See also the comments of Louw and Nida, who say it is important to retain the possibly symbolic numerical values.) Common-language translations often render these words according to containers rather than according to specific volume. Thus \a GECL\a* \a DUCL\a* \a ITCL\a* have “barrels of [olive] oil” and “sacks of grain.” This will be the best solution in many cases.
\key 11.3.2.3
\title Choinix
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk χοῖνιξ
\trl choinix
\ref G06600600600022 G06600600600032
\cont \s G06600600600022 G06600600600022\s*: The \i choinix\i* was approximately equal to a liter or a quart, and it is possible to make a straight substitution without changing the numbers.
\key 11.3.2.4
\title \i Metrētēs\i*
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk μετρητής
\trl metrētēs
\ref G04300200600030 L07600100300046 L08100802000020
\cont \s G04300200600030\s*: The capacity of these stone jars is given as “between two and three measures,” that is, twenty to thirty gallons (about 80–120 liters). When expressing the capacity of these jars, it is important to indicate that they were large; it is less important to give precise capacities. \a GW\a* “18 to 27 gallons” is too precise. It is also possible to give an average volume rather than a range; for example, \a GECL\a* and \a PV\a* have “about a hundred liters.” See also the illustration and discussion at \l target="REALIA:5.18.1.1">5.18.1.1 Stone jar\l*.
\key 11.3.2.5
\title \i Artabē\i*
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ἀρτάβη
\trl artabē
\ref L07600100300032
\cont \s L07600100300032\s*: The \i artabē\i* was a Persian measure of volume equivalent to about 50 liters or 13 gallons. The text says the Babylonians were bringing twelve of these measures of flour every day to their idol Bel. This was a huge amount since each \i artabē\i* was equal to a large sack in volume. It is not necessary in translation to attempt to give a precise equivalent here. Where a roughly equivalent volume measure is known, it should be used; for example, \a RSV\a* \a GNT\a* \a NJB\a* say “twelve bushels,” and \a ITCL\a* has “twelve sacks.” Another possible rendering is “enough flour to feed several hundred people.”
\key 11.4
\title Measures of length
\cont \b Old Testament\b*
\line Name: Reed, rod (\i qaneh\i*)
\line Equivalence: 6 cubits
\line Metric: 3 meters
\line Imperial: 10 feet
\line Name: Cubit (\i ’amah\i*)
\line Equivalence: ——
\line Metric: 50 centimeters
\line Imperial: 18 inches
\line Name: Span (\i zereth\i*)
\line Equivalence: 0.5 cubit
\line Metric: 23 centimeters
\line Imperial: 9 inches
\line Name: Palm (\i tefach\i*)
\line Equivalence: 0.16 cubit
\line Metric: 8 centimeters
\line Imperial: 3 inches
\line Name: Finger (\i ’etsba‘\i*)
\line Equivalence: 0.04 cubit
\line Metric: 2 centimeters
\line Imperial: 0.75 inch
\line \b New Testament and Deuterocanon\b*
\line Name: Schoinos
\line Equivalence: 30 stadia
\line Metric: 5.6 kilometers
\line Imperial: 3.5 miles
\line Name: Mile (\i milion\i*)
\line Equivalence: 8 stadia
\line Metric: 1,480 meters
\line Imperial: 4,850 feet
\line Name: Sabbath day’s journey
\line Equivalence: 2,000 cubits
\line Metric: 1 kilometer
\line Imperial: 1,000 yards
