\key 11.4.1
\title Measures of length in the Old Testament
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.1.1">11.4.1.1 Finger\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.1.2">11.4.1.2 Palm\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.1.3">11.4.1.3 Span\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.1.4">11.4.1.4 Cubit\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.1.5">11.4.1.5 Gomed\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.1.6">11.4.1.6 Reed, rod\l*
\key 11.4.1.1
\title Finger
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֶצְבַּע
\trl ’etsba‘
\ref H02405202100044
\cont \s H02405202100044\s*: In this verse some common-language translations render the literal expression “four fingers” (\a RSV\a*) as “three inches” (\a GNT\a*), “seven centimeters” (\a SPCL\a*), “eight centimeters” (\a GECL\a* \a FRCL\a* \a DUCL\a*), or even “five centimeters” (Portuguese common language version). Older and more formal translations retain the “four fingers” of the original, and this is even done by some common-language versions (\a ITCL\a* \a NOB\a*). It seems likely that giving the thickness of the Temple columns as “four fingers” will communicate to the modern reader just as graphically as it did to the ancient one.
\key 11.4.1.2
\title Palm
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb טֶפַח
\trl tefach
\ref H01100702600006 H01400400500006
\heb טֹפַח
\trl tofach
\ref H00202502500010 H00203701200010 H02604000500050 H02604004300008 H02604301300024
\heb טַפְחָה
\trl tafchah
\ref H01903900600004
\cont The \i tefach\i*/\i tofach\i* is the width of the hand at the base of the fingers, not including the thumb.
\line \s H00202502500010 H00203701200010 H01100702600006 H01400400500006\s*: In many languages it will be possible to express these words as the Hebrew does, as the width of a hand. Otherwise a measurement such as “8 centimeters” (\a FRCL\a*) or “3 inches” (\a GNT\a*) will do. For some reason \a CEV\a* and \a NCV\a* have “three inches” in the Exodus references but “four inches” in 1 Kings and 2 Chronicles.
\line \s H02604000500050 H02604301300024\s*: Here the cubit is said to be longer by one \i tofach\i*. This is the measure used throughout chapters 40–48 of Ezekiel. The shorter cubit actually measured about 45 centimeters (18 inches), and this longer one would have been 53 centimeters (21 inches). Some translations try to reflect the difference. Many, however, will prefer to use a rounded-off value of 50 centimeters (18 inches) for both.
\line \s H01903900600004\s*: Here the word \i tefach\i* (\i tapchah\i*) is a symbolic figure indicating the shortness of life. This may be the basis for the statement of Jesus in \s G04000602701000\s*. See the discussion under \i pēchus\i* below.
\key 11.4.1.3
\title Span
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb זֶרֶת
\trl zereth
\ref H00202801600008 H00202801600014 H00203900900016 H00203900900022 H00901700400034 H02304001200020 H02604301300050
\cont With the fingers spread, the \i zereth\i* is the distance from the tip of the thumb to the tip of the little finger.
\line \s H02304001200020\s*: The picture here is of a person stretching out his fingers and using the distance between his thumb and little finger to measure the extent of the sky. For the second clause in this verse, \a GECL\a* has “Who can . . . determine the extent of the sky with the span of his hand.”
\key 11.4.1.4
\title Cubit
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אַמָּה
\trl ’amah
\ref H00100601500016 H00100601500026 H00100601500034 H00100601600016 H00100702000006 H00202501000012 H00202501000022 H00202501000032 H00202501700012 H00202501700022 H00202502300012 H00202502300018 H00202502300024 H00202600200022 H00202600200034 H00202600800018 H00202600800030 H00202601300006 H00202601300016 H00202601600004 H00202601600014 H00202601600022 H00202700100018 H00202700100026 H00202700100042 H00202700900040 H00202701200020 H00202701300020 H00202701400008 H00202701600016 H00202701800014 H00202701800032 H00203000200002 H00203000200008 H00203000200018 H00203600900022 H00203600900034 H00203601500018 H00203601500024 H00203602100004 H00203602100014 H00203602100022 H00203700100018 H00203700100028 H00203700100038 H00203700600012 H00203700600022 H00203701000016 H00203701000022 H00203701000028 H00203702500018 H00203702500024 H00203702500032 H00203800100020 H00203800100028 H00203800100038 H00203800900036 H00203801100016 H00203801200018 H00203801300014 H00203801400008 H00203801500038 H00203801800038 H00203801800052 H00401103100064 H00403500400034 H00403500500028 H00403500500044 H00403500500060 H00403500500076 H00500301100048 H00500301100056 H00500301100062 H00600300400022 H00901700400030 H01000202400034 H01000800100036 H01100600200024 H01100600200038 H01100600300020 H01100600300040 H01100600600020 H01100600600036 H01100600600052 H01100601000026 H01100601600010 H01100601700010 H01100602000014 H01100602000022 H01100602000030 H01100602300022 H01100602400006 H01100602400022 H01100602400036 H01100602500010 H01100602600018 H01100700200018 H01100700200026 H01100700200034 H01100700600016 H01100700600024 H01100701000018 H01100701000026 H01100701500020 H01100701500040 H01100701600028 H01100701600044 H01100701900028 H01100702300020 H01100702300042 H01100702300060 H01100702400026 H01100702700022 H01100702700042 H01100702700054 H01100703100024 H01100703100036 H01100703100044 H01100703200048 H01100703200056 H01100703500016 H01100703800032 H01201401300070 H01202501700006 H01202501700008 H01202501700038 H01301102300028 H01400300300026 H01400300300038 H01400300300046 H01400300400028 H01400300800028 H01400300800036 H01400301100012 H01400301100024 H01400301100048 H01400301200014 H01400301200038 H01400301300014 H01400301500018 H01400301500040 H01400400100012 H01400400100020 H01400400100028 H01400400200020 H01400400200042 H01400400200056 H01400400300026 H01400601300026 H01400601300034 H01400601300040 H01402502300066 H01600301300040 H01700501400026 H01700700900066 H02300600400006 H02405101300020 H02405202100012 H02405202100034 H02405202200024 H02604000500040 H02604000500046 H02604000700032 H02604000900016 H02604000900028 H02604001100018 H02604001100030 H02604001200014 H02604001200020 H02604001200038 H02604001200048 H02604001300032 H02604001400012 H02604001500038 H02604001900040 H02604002100056 H02604002100074 H02604002300050 H02604002500036 H02604002500050 H02604002700044 H02604002900060 H02604002900074 H02604003000018 H02604003000026 H02604003300062 H02604003300074 H02604003600032 H02604003600044 H02604004200020 H02604004200032 H02604004200044 H02604004700016 H02604004700024 H02604004800024 H02604004800034 H02604004800050 H02604004800060 H02604004900010 H02604004900020 H02604100100024 H02604100100036 H02604100200012 H02604100200024 H02604100200034 H02604100200048 H02604100200056 H02604100300022 H02604100300032 H02604100300044 H02604100400012 H02604100400020 H02604100500014 H02604100500026 H02604100800034 H02604100900024 H02604101000014 H02604101100050 H02604101200030 H02604101200042 H02604101200056 H02604101300016 H02604101300038 H02604101400026 H02604101500046 H02604102200010 H02604102200020 H02604200200008 H02604200200028 H02604200400016 H02604200400028 H02604200700044 H02604200800024 H02604200800040 H02604201600020 H02604301300016 H02604301300018 H02604301300020 H02604301300032 H02604301300036 H02604301400024 H02604301400030 H02604301400058 H02604301400066 H02604301500010 H02604301700042 H02604301700052 H02604500200032 H02604700300030 H03800500200034 H03800500200046
\cont The \i ’amah\i* is the distance from the tip of the elbow to the tip of the middle finger, that is, about 50 centimeters or 18 inches. There is also a longer cubit mentioned in Ezekiel (see \i tefach\i* above, \l target="REALIA:11.4.1.2">11.4.1.2 Span\l*).
\line \s H02604100800034\s*: The Hebrew text here speaks of an \i ’amah ’atsilah\i*. The word \i ’atsilah\i* is problematic, perhaps referring to a length, or perhaps having something to do with a foundation or a terrace. Translations generally treat it as a length, something that qualifies the length of a cubit: “a long cubit” (so \a RSV\a*). Others indicate this by giving a longer length for the rod than someone might expect, for example, “ten and one-half feet” (\a NCV\a*). If it is felt to be significant that a non-standard cubit is being used here, then this latter solution will be unacceptable.
\key 11.4.1.5
\title Gomed
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb גֹּמֶד
\trl gomed
\ref H00700301600020
\cont \s H00700301600020\s*: This single appearance of the \i gomed\i* gives us little to indicate its length. Many commentators and translations take it to be equal to a cubit. Since Ehud was able to hide the sword under his garment, it probably could not have been any longer than a cubit, and it may have been shorter. \a CEV\a* translates the Hebrew word \i cherev\i* (usually rendered “sword”) as “dagger,” thus indicating it was short, but leaves the phrase about its length untranslated. Another possible model is “a short . . . sword” (\a GECL\a*).
\key 11.4.1.6
\title Reed, rod
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קָנֶה
\trl qaneh
\ref H02604000300036 H02604000500032 H02604000500064 H02604000500072 H02604000600044 H02604000600058 H02604000700008 H02604000700016 H02604000700058 H02604000800020 H02604100800030 H02604201600012 H02604201600024 H02604201600028 H02604201700014 H02604201700018 H02604201800016 H02604201800020 H02604201900018 H02604201900022
\cont The \i qaneh\i* in Ezekiel was a measuring rod used to measure length. It had a fixed length of six cubits and a palm, that is, about 3.5 meters (11.5 feet). See also \l target="REALIA:1.8.6">1.8.6 Measuring rod, measuring line\l*, and \l target="FLORA:5.1.4">Reed\l* in \i Plants and Trees in the Bible\i*.
\key 11.4.2
\title Measures of length in the New Testament and the Deuterocanon
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.2.1">11.4.2.1 Pēchus\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.2.2">11.4.2.2 Fathom\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.2.3">11.4.2.3 Stadium, furlong\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.2.4">11.4.2.4 Sabbath day’s journey\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.2.5">11.4.2.5 Mile\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.2.6">11.4.2.6 Schoinos\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.4.2.7">11.4.2.7 Measuring rod\l*
\key 11.4.2.1
\title Pēchus
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk πῆχυς
\trl pēchus
\ref G04000602700024 G04201202500024 G04302100800036 G06602101700018 L06800100200024 L06800100200034 L06800100200050 L06800100200062 L06800100300020 L06800100300036 L06800100400020 L06800100400032 L07801300500016 L08100602400008 L08100602400014 L07400102400018
\cont The \i pēchus\i* is the New Testament equivalent of the cubit (\i ’amah\i* in Hebrew).
\line In most cases the translator will be able to avoid awkward fractions and decimal points for the \i pēchus\i* by using the formula, two cubits equal one meter or one yard.
\line \s G04000602700024 G04201202500024\s*: One problem of interpretation here is that the Greek word \i pēchus\i* is normally used of distance rather than of time. However, it may also be used of time, and that meaning is much more satisfactory in the present context. Moreover, the Greek word rendered “span of life” by \a RSV\a* is more frequently used as a measurement of time than height. Modern translations tend to accept the meaning of a measure of time. If span is used as a measurement of time, the use of the word \i pēchus\i* to qualify it would mean a brief span, whereas if it is used of a person’s height, it would be a significant amount (about half a meter or 18 inches). \a NAB\a* renders the last part of \s G04000602700024\s* as “add a moment to his life-span,” and \a GECL\a* has “lengthen his life only by one day.” Other possibilities are “add a little time to his life,” “live a little longer,” and “make his life last even a little longer.” Some translators will indicate a specific amount of time, such as “even one day” or “even one hour.”
\line \s G04302100800036\s*: The distance given here is approximately 100 meters or 100 yards. Translators will want to follow something like \a CEV\a* “only about a hundred yards from shore.”
\line \s G06602101700018\s*: The text gives a measurement of 144 cubits, that is, twelve times twelve. This seems to be a symbolic number, and many translations—among them common-language translations such as \a GW\a* \a NCV\a* \a ITCL\a* \a GECL\a*—choose to leave the number in the text. \a ITCL\a* also adds the metric equivalent in the text, saying “one hundred forty-four cubits (seventy meters).”
\line \a GNT\a* takes this measurement, 144 cubits (72 meters; 236 feet), to be the height of the wall (also \a NJB\a* \a REB\a* \a FRCL\a*, \a Phps\a*). It may, however, refer to its thickness (\a NIV\a* \a BRCL\a*). Some commentators make the point that, for a city that is 1,500 miles tall, a wall only 72 meters (236 feet) tall is so small that it seems foolish. But it is also pointed out that the wall, in this case, is not for the protection of the city (inasmuch as the gates stay open all the time) but for its demarcation. In any case, the notion of height is preferable to that of thickness. A translation should opt for one or the other; simply to say, as \a RSV\a* and others say, “a hundred and forty-four cubits” (or, “72 meters” or “236 feet”), without indicating that this is the height, does not qualify as a translation. An alternative translation model for the first half of this verse is “He also determined the height [or, thickness] of the wall [or, fence]. It was 72 meters [or, 236 feet].” For this verse see also \i A Handbook on The Revelation to John\i*, pages 306–307.
\key 11.4.2.2
\title Fathom
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ὀργυιά
\trl orguia
\ref G04402702800008 G04402702800026
\cont \s G04402702800008 G04402702800008\s*: The \i orguia\i* was traditionally the measure of a man’s outstretched arms from fingertip to fingertip. It was reckoned at approximately 6 feet or about 1.85 meters. It was used as a technical nautical term to measure the depth of water. Water depth was measured with rope with a weight on the end, and this measure possibly derives from the way of counting off the arm lengths of rope. The measurements mentioned in this verse are about 40 meters (130 feet) and about 30 meters (100 feet). Where a language has a unit of measure that is used specifically for water depth (like the English word “fathom”), it may be used here.
\key 11.4.2.3
\title Stadium, furlong
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk στάδιον
\trl stadion
\ref L07801100500034 L07801200900042 L07801201000008 L07801201600038 L07801201700008 L07801202900022
\grk στάδιος
\trl stadios
\ref G04001402400010 G04202401300030 G04300601900008 G04301101800020 G06601402000040 G06602101600042
\cont \s G04001402400010\s*: The Greek says that the boat was “many stadia” from land. It is not necessary to express this in any particular unit of measurement. \a GNT\a* “the boat was far out in the lake” is a good model. (Some Greek manuscripts have “in the middle of the lake” instead of “many stadia from the land.” In either case, neither reading gives a specific measurement; both merely state that the boat was now some distance from the shore, and therefore any phrase that conveys this information will be faithful to the intent of the text.)
\line \s G04202401300030\s*: The distance given here in the best manuscripts is “sixty stadia,” which is about 11 kilometers (7 miles). Some manuscripts have “one hundred sixty stadia,” but this reading cannot be correct. Other ways of expressing “sixty stadia” might be “two hour’s walk” (Leyden, Sranan, Timorese) and “two leagues” (Tzeltal, where “a league” is commonly explained as “one hour’s walk”).
\line \s G04300601900008\s*: English translations generally give “three or four miles” (\a RSV\a*). Where the metric system is used, you would say “five or six kilometers” (\a FRCL\a*).
\line \s G04301101800020\s*: In this verse translations generally have “about two miles” (\a RSV\a*) or “almost two miles.” Where the metric system is used, you would say “about three kilometers.” It would also be possible to say “about a half hour walk.”
\line \s G06601402000040 G06602101600042\s*: The numbers in these verses, 1,600 stadia and 12,000 stadia respectively, are probably symbolic and, as such, are more important than the exact distance they might represent. For this reason some translations prefer to retain the numbers and explain the distances in a note or in parentheses in the text. So, for example, \a ITCL\a* has “twelve thousand stadia (more than two thousand kilometers),” while \a NIV\a* says “12,000 stadia in length” and adds this footnote: “That is, about 1,400 miles (about 2,200 kilometers).”
\key 11.4.2.4
\title Sabbath day’s journey
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk σάββατον ἔχον ὁδόν
\trl sabbaton echon hodon
\ref G04400101200028
\cont \s G04400101200028\s*: Jewish sources approximately contemporary with the New Testament period defined “a Sabbath day’s journey” as 2,000 cubits, which is about one kilometer or 1,000 yards. Some translations express this as “about half a mile” (\a GNT\a*) or “about a kilometer” (\a PV\a*). \a ITCL\a* renders it in terms of the amount of walking time, “a half hour’s walk.” \a SPCL\a* expands it to “exactly that which the law permitted one to walk on the day of rest,” although this may be felt to be too cumbersome. Also, this rendering still does not tell the reader what distance was involved.
\key 11.4.2.5
\title Mile
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk μίλιον
\trl milion
\ref G04000504100010
\cont \s G04000504100010\s*: There are a number of ways in which the distances can be expressed here. Many translations have maintained the literal mile, even in situations where the metric system is employed. “One mile” was presumably the distance a Roman soldier could force a Jew to carry his equipment. What is important here is not the exact distance, but the relation between “one mile” and “two miles.” While this relation will be clear even in settings where miles are unknown, many translations choose to say “one kilometer” and “two kilometers” simply to avoid introducing the unknown word, “mile.”
\line Actually, it is possible to substitute any distance that takes about 15–20 minutes to walk, or even to express it in walking time; compare the Rincon Zapotec rendering for this verse: “If anyone forces you to carry his load for half an hour, go with this person for a whole hour.” In some cultures it may be natural to express the “mile” in terms of its original meaning in Latin, which is “a thousand paces.”
\key 11.4.2.6
\title Schoinos
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk σχοῖνος
\trl schoinos
\ref L07801100500034
\cont The \i schoinos\i* was a distance equal to thirty stadia, about 5.6 kilometers (3.5 miles). There is a textual problem in \s L07801100500034\s*, which seems to have read “five stadia,” which is much too close to Jerusalem. Already in ancient times the text was emended to read “five \i schoinos\i*.”
\key 11.4.2.7
\title Measuring rod
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk κάλαμος
\trl kalamos
\ref G06601100100008 G06602101500016 G06602101600038
\cont Like the \i qaneh\i* (see above), the \i kalamos\i* was a measuring rod. In Revelation its length is not given but only the lengths of the things it measures. See also \l target="REALIA:1.8.6">1.8.6 Measuring rod, measuring line\l*.
\key 11.5
\title Measure of area
\index \l target="REALIA:11.5.1">11.5.1 Pair\l*
\key 11.5.1
\title Pair
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb צֶמֶד
\trl tsemed
\ref H00901401400040 H02300501000006
\cont The Hebrew word \i tsemed\i* indicates a “pair” of oxen. In \s H02300501000006\s* it speaks of the area that two oxen could plow in a day. Some English translations try to employ an equivalent English word, although they cannot agree on just how big the area is. Thus \a RSV\a* has “ten acres” while \a GNT\a* has “five acres.” The important point here and in the continuation of the verse is that harvests will be extremely poor. Most translations convey this idea by adding a word like “only,” “barely,” or “merely.”
\line \s H00901401400040\s*: This is a corrupt text. If the word \i tsemed\i* is correct here, then it indicates the length of a plowed furrow, approximately 20–30 meters (65–100 feet); in other words, Jonathan and his servant killed the Philistine soldiers within about half that distance.
\key 11.6
\title Money
\cont The relative values of monetary units mentioned in the New Testament may best be understood in their relationship to the denarius, which was equivalent to one day’s wages for a common laborer:
\line Talent = 6,000 denarii; \s G04001802400020 G04002501500012 G04002501600010 G04002502000012 G04002502000022 G04002502000030 G04002502000042 G04002502200014 G04002502200022 G04002502200034 G04002502400014 G04002502500012 G04002502800012 G04002502800026\s*
\line Mina = 1,000 denarii; \s G04201901300018 G04201901600016 G04201901600024 G04201901800014 G04201901800024 G04201902000018 G04201902400018 G04201902400030 G04201902500014\s*
\line Stater = 4 denarii; \s G04001702700046\s*
\line Didrachma = 2 denarii; \s G04001702400018 G04001702400042\s*
\line Denarius (also Drachma) = ONE DAY’S WAGE; \s G04001802800030 G04002000200014 G04002000900020 G04002001000026 G04002001300024 G04002201900022 G04100603700030 G04101201500028 G04101400500016 G04200704100018 G04201003500016 G04201500800008 G04201500800018 G04201500900028 G04202002400006 G04300600700012 G04301200500018 G06600600600026 G06600600600036\s*
\line Assarion = 1/16 denarius; \s G04001002900008 G04201200600010\s*
\line Kodrantes = 1/64 denarius; \s G04000502600026 G04101204200022\s*
\line Lepton = 1/128 denarius; \s G04101204200014 G04201205900022 G04202100200016\s*
\cont For a general discussion of translating terms related to money, see \l target="REALIA:1.6.3">1.6.3 Money, coins\l*.
\line maneh: See \l target="REALIA:11.2.2">11.2.2 Mina\l*, “Mina.”
\line talanton: See \l target="REALIA:11.2.3">11.2.3 Talent\l*, “Talent.”
\line peres: See \l target="REALIA:11.1.4">11.1.4 Peres, Parsin\l*, “Peres, Parsin.”
\key 11.6.1
\title Qsitah
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb קְשִׂיטָה
\trl qsitah
\ref H00103301900038 H00602403200058 H01804201100078
\cont The precise meaning of the Hebrew word \i qsitah\i* is unknown. \a REB\a* takes it to mean “sheep,” but gives “piece[s] of money” as an alternate rendering. It is misleading with such obscure words to try to be too precise. Good models at \s H01804201100078\s* are “some silver” (\a CEV\a*), “a piece of silver” (\a NCV\a*), and perhaps “some money” (\a GNT\a*). In all three places where it occurs, it seems to be something that has a fairly significant value. The word “coin” is anachronistic in these three passages, and most translations have “piece[s] of silver.”
\key 11.6.2
\title Greek coins
\index \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.1">11.6.2.1 Assarion\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.2">11.6.2.2 Kodrantes\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.3">11.6.2.3 Lepton\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.4">11.6.2.4 Adarkon, darkmon\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.5">11.6.2.5 Denarius\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.6">11.6.2.6 Drachma\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.7">11.6.2.7 Didrachma\l*
\index \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.8">11.6.2.8 Stater\l*
\line argurion, see \l target="REALIA:1.6.3">1.6.3 Money, coins\l*.
\key 11.6.2.1
\title Assarion
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk ἀσσάριον
\trl assarion
\ref G04001002900008 G04201200600010
\cont The Greek words \i assarion\i*, \i kodrantēs\i* and \i lepton\i* (\l target="REALIA:11.6.2.2">11.6.2.2 Kodrantes\l* and \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.3">11.6.2.3 Lepton\l*) refer to small coins. Each of these words may be rendered “very small coin,” “coin with very little value,” or “money that was not worth very much.” Generally the same word or phrase may be used for all three, except in \s G04101204200022\s*, where two \i lepta\i* equal a \i kodrantēs\i*.
\line For the \i assarion\i*, translations generally choose a very low denomination coin in \s G04001002900008 G04201200600010\s*, for example, “a penny” (so \a RSV\a* \a GNT\a*). The meaning of Jesus’ saying is well conveyed also by \a PV\a*, which says “for almost nothing.”
\key 11.6.2.2
\title Kodrantes
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk κοδράντης
\trl kodrantēs
\ref G04000502600026 G04101204200022
\line Kodrantes: \fig |UBS-0038_kodrantes.jpg|col||© Kwo-Wei Peng (UBS)|Kodrantes|11.0\fig*
\line \s G04000502600026\s*: At the end of this verse most translations have something like “until you have paid the last penny” (\a NIV\a*). It is also possible to express this well without naming a specific coin; for example, \a NCV\a* and \a PV\a* say “until you have paid everything you owe.” Some scholars think it more likely, however, more likely that this clause means “until you have paid off all the money the judge fined you [or, said you must pay].” Compare \a GNT\a*, which reads “until you pay the last penny of your fine” (similarly \a GW\a*).
\line \s G04101204200022\s*: At the end of this verse the Greek says literally “two lepta, which are a kodrantes.” Many translations expand “two lepta” somewhat to “two small copper coins” (\a NCV\a*), and then indicate that they were worth very little by saying they were worth “a penny” (\a RSV\a*), “a few cents” (\a NCV\a*), “less than a cent” (\a GW\a*), “about a penny” (\a GNT\a*), or “of very low value” (\a SPCL\a*). \a ITCL\a* omits the second phrase, since the purpose of that phrase in the original text was to explain to Mark’s readers the value of the lesser known \i lepton\i*.
\key 11.6.2.3
\title Lepton
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk λεπτόν
\trl lepton
\ref G04101204200014 G04201205900022 G04202100200016
\cont See the comments under \i kodrantēs\i* above, \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.2">11.6.2.2 Kodrantes\l*.
\key 11.6.2.4
\title Adarkon, darkmon
\cont \u References:\u*
\heb אֲדַרְכּוֹן
\trl ’adarkon
\ref H01302900700026 H01500802700012
\heb דַּרְכְּמוֹנִים
\trl darkmonim
\ref H01500206900018 H01600706900036 H01600707000024 H01600707100016
\cont The \i ’adarkon\i*/\i darkmon\i* is a monetary unit of uncertain value.
\line According to some scholars, the \i ’adarkon\i* and the \i darkmon\i* are not the same coin, the former coin corresponding to the Persian daric and the latter one to the Greek drachma. In all of the passages listed above, however, it is possible that the reference is to a weight of gold and not to coins.
\line In \s H01302900700026\s* it does not seem necessary to retain the actual numbers nor to give the amounts with too much precision. \a GNT\a* provides a good model with “190 tons of gold, 380 tons of silver, 675 tons of bronze, and 3,750 tons of iron.” The mention of coins in this verse is anachronistic, as coins did not make their first appearance until several hundred years after the time of David. It is possible that the writer of Chronicles has converted the amount of gold into a monetary unit contemporary with the time of writing.
\key 11.6.2.5
\title Denarius
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk δηνάριον
\trl dēnarion
\ref G04001802800030 G04002000200014 G04002000900020 G04002001000026 G04002001300024 G04002201900022 G04100603700030 G04101201500028 G04101400500016 G04200704100018 G04201003500016 G04202002400006 G04300600700012 G04301200500018 G06600600600026 G06600600600036
\cont The denarius had the same value as the drachma
\line \fig |UBS-0001_denarius.jpg|col||© Kwo-Wei Peng (UBS)|Emperor Tiberius on a denarius|11.0\fig* Because of the recent rapid inflation in the world and the considerable loss of buying power of coinage metals such as gold, silver and copper in comparison to ancient times, a number of translators have attempted in some measure to relate coinage to buying power, or perhaps better, to earning power. Thus, rather than translating “denarius” by some specific amount in a modern currency, it may be equated to a day’s wage. For example, in \s G04100603700030\s* the literal expression “two hundred denarii” (\a RSV\a*) is sometimes rendered “the equivalent of 200 days’ wages” or even “eight months of a laborer’s wages.” This will be a good solution in most cases with a couple of exceptions: (1) There are some passages where converting to work days will be unwieldy; for example, in \s G04001802800030\s* the debt of the second servant is equivalent to about four months’ wages, which is a figure that people can grasp. However, the debt of the first servant was approximately equivalent to the wages of 1000 men for 20 years. It would be awkward to include this in translation. (2) There are still some cultures in the world where hiring day laborers is unknown because each person or family unit in the village does its own hunting and gathering or even farming. In such cultures “a day’s wage” may have little meaning.
\line When calculating the number of days’ wages, translators should not forget that, unlike other peoples in the ancient world, Jews did not work one day out of seven. Thus a work week consisted of six work days, and about 25 days made up one work month. The 100 denarii of \s G04001802800030\s* equaled four months’ salary and not three months, as stated in some common-language translations.
\key 11.6.2.6
\title Drachma
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk δραχμή
\trl drachmē
\ref G04201500800008 G04201500800018 G04201500900028 L06700501500018 L07800401900026 L07801002000036 L07801204300014 L07900302800040
\cont The drachma had the same value as the denarius, that is, a day’s wage. See the comments under \i dēnarion\i* above, \l target="REALIA:11.6.2.6">11.6.2.6 Drachma\l*.
\line \s G04201500800008 G04201500800008 G04201500900028\s*: While the amount the woman has lost here may not seem like a lot since it is only one day’s wage, it should not be represented in translation as insignificant. This would be against the whole point of the parable. The word “silver,” which appears in many translations (so \a RSV\a* \a GNT\a*), is only implied in the word “drachma” (which was a silver coin). Including this piece of information in translation can help to indicate that the coins were not of low value.
\key 11.6.2.7
\title Didrachma
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk δίδραχμον
\trl didrachmon
\ref G04001702400018 G04001702400042
\cont \s G04001702400018 G04001702400018\s*: Here the Greek word \i didrachma\i* (rendered “the half-shekel tax” in \a RSV\a*) refers to the tax which, according to \s H00203001301000\s*, was required of every male Jew from the age of twenty onward.
\line \fig |UBS-0002_didrachma.jpg|col||© Kwo-Wei Peng (UBS)|Tyrian half-shekel|11.0\fig* It is not the amount of the half-shekel tax that is really important in this verse, but rather the nature of it, as seen in \a GNT\a*, which says “the Temple tax.” Translators can say “the tax all the men [or, all Jewish men] paid for the Temple expenses” or “the tax paid to support the Temple.”
\line Some translators have wanted to give some indication of the amount of money here and have said “the tax of money of half a shekel” or even “the money called a half-shekel that people had to pay to the Temple.” It is also possible to indicate in a footnote that this was about half the wages a laborer would earn in a day. But this is marginal information and does not need to be specified in the text. Another rendering some have used is “the small amount of money people had to pay to support the Temple.” But translators should be careful not to make the expression too cumbersome. Nor should they give more emphasis to the amount of money than to its function. The Temple tax was paid once a year.
\key 11.6.2.8
\title Stater
\cont \u References:\u*
\grk στατήρ
\trl statēr
\ref G04001702700046
\cont The \i statēr\i* was a silver coin worth two \i didrachma\i* or approximately four denarii. In \s G04001702700046\s* it may be rendered “a coin.” A footnote might be added: “Literally, ‘a stater,’ a silver coin worth four drachmas, the exact amount needed for two people to pay the Temple tax.”
\key 11.7
